<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, May 8.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LIBERALS (Beijing) _ China's leaders are attempting to
rein in a growing and increasingly self-assertive liberal
intellectual movement, criticizing prominent academics in speeches,
forbidding newspapers from running their articles and punishing
publishers who have brought out their work. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-IMMIGRANTS (El Ejido, Spain) _ The life of immigrants in
this tense town in southern Spain throws light on Europe's perhaps
most pressing social problem: how to deal with a massive influx of
labor from other climes and continents. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The euro was supposed to unify the
economies of 11 European nations and be a symbol of stability to
rival the dollar, the yen and even the British pound. But so far it
has been a boon to the very currencies with which it was supposed
to compete. Now Americans brandishing dollars are finding bargains
from Amsterdam to Vienna. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PREEMIES (Undated) _ It has been more than 20 years since
doctors began saving extremely premature infants, and about a
decade since advances in neonatology vastly improved the survival
of babies of very low birth weight _ those weighing less than 1,500
grams, or 3 pounds 4 ounces. Thousands of these children are now
well into their school years. The conventional medical wisdom had
been that those who were not seriously disabled physically would
catch up to other youngsters by age 5. Many do. But as the first
large group of tiny babies grows up, new research is showing that
academic and behavioral problems often surface in the school years.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BOWLING-ALLEY (Los Angeles) _ For the last five years,
Jacqueline Sowell has loved to go to the Holiday Bowl, a faded
bowling alley on a faded street in a faded district of Los Angeles.
Walking into the Bowl renewed her faith. It showed her day after
day just how well people of diverse backgrounds and races can get
along. But early Saturday morning, after 42 years, the Holiday Bowl
was closed. And a few hours after the last balls thundered down the
lanes, a group of Sowell's neighbors, co-workers and friends were
standing outside, holding signs, declaring the Bowl ``A Landmark of
Diversity'' and urging the new owners and the city to ``Preserve
Not Destroy.'' By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-POLITICS (Washington) _ This week offered a stunning
contradiction in numbers: a 3.9 percent unemployment rate, the
lowest in 30 years, and two major national polls showing Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas leading Vice President Al Gore by 5
percentage points. To put that contrast in perspective, the last
time a president's party lost the White House in good times was
1920. So why isn't the booming economy blowing Bush away? By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-REPUBS (Salt Lake City) _ Utah is one of the most
Republican states in the country. But in Utah, there are
Republicans and there are Republicans. At the Republican state
party convention, even Sen. Orrin Hatch was greeted with a healthy
mix of boos and jeers. So was Gov. Michael Leavitt, who is running
for a third term against three challengers and failed to reach 60
percent in any of three ballots, putting him in a primary for the
first time since 1992. ``These conventions are the political
version of hazing,'' Leavitt said. ``You have to expect it as a
two-term incumbent.'' By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHEDULE _ There are fewer than 6,000 hours left in the
Clinton presidency, a dwindling block of time that many people want
to share. Putting together Clinton's schedule in these final months
is a delicate balancing act that involves squeezing together
fund-raising dinners, presidential speeches and photo ops with golf
games, foreign trips and overnight stays in Chappaqua, N.Y. By Marc
Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   SHALIKASHVILI-PROFILE _ Gen. John Shalikashvili, former chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, works on the administration's behalf
to lobby for arms control on the hill. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-CHECKIN (Undated) _ In a competition to attract the
business travelers who are responsible for a majority of the
carriers' revenue, major airlines are spending tens of millions of
dollars on new technology. They hope to whisk passengers through
terminals more quickly, redefining what industry executives glumly
call ``the airport experience.'' By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Now it is Microsoft's turn to
say what its future should be. On Wednesday, the software maker
must submit its reply to the government's proposal to split the
company in two and, at the prodding of a federal judge, offer its
own suggested remedies in the antitrust case. The company has
little choice but to engage in what it regards as the unpalatable
exercise of recommending sanctions against itself. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MEMS-INTERNET (Undated) _ Tiny machines known as MEMS, for
micro-electromechanical systems, have already made their way by the
millions into products like automotive air bags, ink jet printers
and disposable blood pressure analyzers. But this is the year that
MEMS seem poised for their first central role in computing and
communications. Various companies are introducing MEMS-based
information switches and other MEMS devices to help manage the
rapidly expanding networks of optical fiber cables that constitute
the backbone of the Internet. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LOVEBUG-FORD (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Perhaps no company was hit
harder by the virus known as the love bug than Ford Motor Co.
Starting at 6:45 Thursday morning, Ford systems experts shut down
the company's e-mail system, and they fought the bug until the
middle of Friday afternoon. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   TIMEWARNER-DISNEY-MEDIA (Undated) _ What the dispute between
Time Warner and Disney says about how the distribution of media is
controlled, and exactly what lies behind the fight. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMEWARNER-ASSESS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Anatomy of a public
relations disaster: How Time Warner miscalculated on the Disney
talks. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY-MAG-MEDIA (Undated) _ A look at Conde Nast's latest
launch: Lucky, a magazine about shopping that looks like a catalog
_ yet one more example of the lines being blurred between editorial
and advertising. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Unilever, a company known for its
household and personal care products, is starting a
multimillion-dollar campaign for a shampoo line. By Patricia
Winters Lauro
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Cisco is the undisputed leader in
Internet communications equipment and the No. 1 company in market
value. But in the new economy, few titans remain astride their
industry for long, and several newer communications equipment
companies have Cisco in their sights. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column: a new
``omnidirectional'' top made of small acrylic spheres spins even
though it has no pointed edge; a playhouse that resembles a
miniature church, with steeple, stained glass windows, pews and a
working sound system that plays hymns, wedding music and sermons;
and a vacuum cleaner attachment that filters tiny toys like Barbie
accessories and Lego pieces. By Teresa Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ A quarter of PR professionals say they
lie; on the other hand, they say, their clients also lie to them.
</P>
