<HEADLINE>
KIDD SLOWED BY BRYANT, ANKLE INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jason Kidd emerged from his shower, walked slowly
to his locker then turned and faced the music.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of reporters forming a circle around the Phoenix
Suns guard seemed appropriate. After all, Kidd was crowded, swarmed
and pressured for 39 minutes Sunday in the Lakers' 105-77 victory
over Phoenix in Game 1 of the Western Conference semifinals at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The postgame scene was just more of the same, only instead of
Kobe Bryant's slender body and long arms, Kidd was staring at
microphones and notepads.
</P>
<P>
   It was a forgettable game for Kidd, who finished with more
turnovers (five) than points (three) while making just 1 of 6
field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The game started badly when Kidd tweaked his right ankle coming
down awkwardly after a first-quarter layup - the same ankle he
fractured March 22 and that sidelined him until the Suns'
series-clinching victory over San Antonio in the first round five
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd played cautiously the rest of the way Sunday, afraid he
might make the injury worse, and that contributed to his
difficulties. He's at his best when he's free-wheeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to gain more confidence,'' Kidd said. ``This is
only my second game back so I'm going to be a little rusty, a
little uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   Players don't miss five weeks then come back sharp, especially
when the intensity kicks up a notch in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's struggles set the tone for the Suns, who turned the ball
over 23 times and shot 36.4 percent from the field. The Lakers made
Phoenix pay for the turnovers, burning the Suns for 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   They may play smarter, but will Kidd play with more confidence?
He laughed when he heard people say it looked as if he hadn't
missed a beat on his return against the Spurs, knowing full well
how absurd that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel a lot different on the court,'' Kidd said.
``The big thing is I have to gain confidence every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd played well against San Antonio, getting nine points, 10
assists, three steals and two rebounds. But he wasn't playing
against Bryant, who was voted to the NBA's All-Defensive first team
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, unsure how much he could push off his right foot,
struggled against Bryant's constant pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe is a great defender no doubt about that,'' Suns coach
Scott Skiles said. ``I thought Jason had great energy and he also
had some opportunities when he kicked (the ball) out. But guys
missed shots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
