</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DEFENSE STOPS SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anyone remember defense?
</P>
<P>
   The swatted jump shot, the leap into the passing lane, the hand
in the face? A few days ago, it all seemed so passe, so last
millennium, as the Lakers went fashionably offensive to beat the
shoot-happy Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But a new series brought the return of an old ally.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Suns, meet Laker defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took advantage of 23 Phoenix turnovers Sunday and
cashed them in for a 105-77 blowout in front of 18,997 at Staples
Center in Game 1 of the best-of-seven conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The victory came with all the usual, stylish accessories - 37
points from Shaquille O'Neal and 25 from Kobe Bryant - but on a day
when the Lakers sputtered early, their third-quarter suffocation of
the Suns' attack won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' said Bryant, who locked up Suns playmaker
Jason Kidd. ``I told Coach Frank (Hamblen) on the bench, I said,
`Damn, this looks good.' It gives us a chance to strap up.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked familiar, and should have. This was the way the Lakers
won most of their 67 games in the regular season, turning endless
deflections and rebounds into points. That was difficult in the
first round, when they had to simply outscore the Kings while
allowing an average of 96.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   The 77 points and 36.4 percent shooting by the Suns were more
reflective of the Lakers' personality this season under coach Phil
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of rewarding to have offense,'' Jackson said. ``It
lulls you into kind of a happy game, scoring, everybody's enjoying
it. It was a struggle out there for us in the first half, and to
actually shoot 43 percent and win by (28) points is really not
indicative of what the game is about.''
</P>
<P>
   From Jackson's perspective, Sunday's game also might be a lousy
barometer of what's to come in this series, which resumes with Game
2 on Wednesday at Staples.
</P>
<P>
   The teams stumbled to an 18-18 tie in the first quarter - the
Lakers perhaps fatigued from Friday's emotional clincher against
the Kings, the Suns apparently too relaxed after a four-day break.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I kind of had a hunch about it, neither team was able to
bring a best game to this opening game of this series,'' Jackson
said. ``That's more of a feel-out game, I think, rather than an
indicator of what this series is going to be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our players looked tired in the first half, but they
got a real good energy boost the third quarter, played a wonderful
third quarter. A.C. (Green) gave us a lift, and (Ron) Harper got a
couple steals and did some things good for us too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns never led after the midway point of the second quarter,
but the rout took longer to develop. Harper picked Penny Hardaway
to open the second half, leading to a Bryant fast-break layup and
three-point play, for a 49-41 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then an O'Neal block of Clifford Robinson. Then a Bryant steal
and a turnaround jumper in transition. Then another Harper steal,
off Rodney Rogers. Then another Bryant steal.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Suns had stopped giving away possessions, the
Lakers had built the lead to 72-56 - capped by O'Neal's backcourt
steal of Corie Blount's inbounds pass.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with four blocks, Bryant with three to go with
three steals.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway led the Suns with 25 points, but Phoenix never
recovered from the third-quarter assault and trailed by double
digits the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned up the defense a little bit to start the third
quarter, and we didn't handle it very well,'' said Suns coach Scott
Skiles. ``They scored 28 points off our turnovers. We scored 4 off
of theirs - there's the game right there. It's been one of our
weaknesses all year long. We haven't handled the ball well on the
break, and just handling and passing the ball from point A to point
B is one of our weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a fairly simple Laker game plan was hatched: stand between
point A and point B, wait for errant pass, cruise to easy basket.
It netted 14 steals, with a team-high four by Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the style that they play,'' Bryant said. ``They're so up
and down, they like to take risks, take chances, throw lobs. ... We
just wanted to help them out. Seriously, we just wanted to put a
little pressure on them. Not to the point where we're constantly
gambling, but just playing solid defense and see what we can come
up with.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal started slowly, missing 6 of his first 7 shots, but he
soon found an easy rhythm against the undersized Suns and made 14
of 21 the rest of the way. He also regained his free-throw touch,
making 7 of 10 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   No other Lakers scored in double figures, but no one needed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is definitely going to be the cornerstone for us,''
said Glen Rice. ``The defense has saved us many, many games. ...
You can best believe the game Wednesday night, they're not going to
turn the ball over that much. They're going to take much better
care of the ball, and they're going to come out and they're going
to be a different team Wednesday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
