<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-FASSERO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO IN A GOOD STRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ All of Jeff Fassero's pitches were working Sunday. He
was able to locate his fastball, slider, and splitter well,
surrendering no walks. So solid was the lefthander's outing, he did
something he hadn't done all season.
</P>
<P>
   He worked six innings in a start.
</P>
<P>
   Five innings has been a cinch for the nine-year veteran. Sunday
was his longest outing of the season, as he overcame a two-run
first to hold the Devil Rays to one run and six hits over the next
five frames.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he left in the sixth (his plea to manager Jimy
Williams to return for the seventh was turned down), Fassero had an
8-3 lead, and the Red Sox withstood Tampa Bay's four-run eighth to
preserve his third consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get stretched out a little bit. Six innings was
good today,'' said Fassero, who improved to 4-1 and has won three
straight for the first time since 1998, when he pitched for
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up nine hits and three earned runs, and added a
season-high six strikeouts. It marked the first time he pitched at
least six innings since Aug. 1 of last season, against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got past it; the thing I hated was seeing the bullpen get up
early in the game,'' Fassero said. ``It's not like I'm giving up
rockets or something like that. I got double plays when I needed
them, and as long as I don't walk guys I'm not going to get into
any trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Sunday's game, righthanded hitters were batting .400
against Fassero, the second-highest average against a starter in
the league (former Red Sox Ron Mahay, now with Oakland, is first).
</P>
<P>
   Fassero faced a mostly righthanded-hitting team Sunday, and got
in trouble from the outset. Gerald Williams led off with a single
and Miguel Cairo followed with a bunt single to the mound, then
reached second on a throwing error by Fassero, with Williams
advancing to third.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out Greg Vaughn, Fassero gave up a double to Jose
Canseco, scoring Williams and Cairo. But he got out of the inning
by retiring Fred McGriff and Vinny Castilla on grounders. In the
third, he gave up a single to McGriff that scored Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a single in each of the next three innings, but the
only Devil Ray who got past first was Cairo, who stole second and
third in the fifth. But he was stranded when Fassero struck out
Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some tough luck early,'' said catcher Jason Varitek
about Fassero. ``Those three runs were tough luck, they really
were. He made good pitches and stayed within himself from there. He
gave us a chance to get our bats going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could throw my slider for a strike when I needed to,''
Fassero said. ``I didn't try to overthrow anything, and I think
that helped, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that the Red Sox, who averaged 8.2 runs when
Fassero pitched, scored eight for him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've fallen into a good slot this year,'' said Fassero. ``We
score a lot of runs the day I go out there and pitch, and that
makes it easier to go out there every inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero worked five innings in each of his previous five starts.
In his only defeat, a 1-0 loss to Oakland April 17, he got one out
in the sixth. After a no-decision his first outing of the season,
he has worked on his mechanics and it is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the last start and this start, I've worked on keeping
my back leg straighter and trying to keep that downhill plane,''
said Fassero. ``I want to keep getting the ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a lot of grounders and they're not hitting the
ball exceptionally hard. That means I'm getting late movement at
the end of the pitch and I'm happy with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
