<HEADLINE>
RED SOX OFFENSE BUILDS POWERFULL CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Friday night they banged out 10 hits, including six for
extra bases. In Sunday's 9-7 win over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays at
Fenway Park, they had 12 hits, including three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The aberration came Saturday, when they could only come up with
three hits against Steve Trachsel in a 1-0 loss that ruined a
17-strikeout performance by Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will tell you their production Sunday was more
indicative of their skills and potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't hit on all cylinders yet,'' said Trot Nixon, who
blasted his fifth home run (his first at Fenway) into the
right-field stands in the third inning that was followed one out
later by a Troy O'Leary blast to the same vicinity. ``But we're not
far off. Troy had a great game, and Offie (Jose Offerman) is
starting to do the things he does best, which is getting on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Add the production of Carl Everett, who banged his 10th home run
of the season, a three-run shot to center in the fifth, and you
have a team that can produce runs in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary is the latest Red Sox to get as hot as the weather,
which turned summerlike over the weekend. The left fielder had his
first three-hit performance since an opening-week effort at Anaheim
by ripping his fifth homer of the season in the third and banging
two more hits.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to indicate the end to a mini-slump for the quiet,
shy outfielder who entered amid a 4-for-19 stretch when nothing
seemed to be falling for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy's a very good hitter,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``He
was before I got here. To me, he's going to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone did Sunday, with only shortstop Andy Sheets and
center fielder Darren Lewis going hitless.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox took note of the difference a day made. ``Everyone
hit the ball hard today,'' said Everett, who has been doing that
all season. ``Troy hit the ball hard, Trot hit it hard. It was
quite a difference from (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   The encouraging news for the Red Sox is that, as Nixon pointed
out, the players have not all hit their offensive stride at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our best hitters have not had the best of starts,''
said catcher Jason Varitek, who contributed two hits and a run
batted in. ``That's the encouraging part.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said maybe the arrival of warm weather means a change is
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just so frustrating,'' he said of Saturday's game. ``To
have a guy get 17 strikeouts and not win. (Saturday) we couldn't do
a thing, and today balls were flying left and right. I think once
things start to warm up, this club will start to hit and do some
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett says it doesn't matter where the power comes from,
whether it is from Offerman (who has had five hits in the last
three games) at the top of the lineup, or third baseman Wilton
Veras at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   And the center fielder doesn't care about numbers. ``I don't
think about stats at all,'' he said, although in three games as a
designated hitter this season he has five hits in 10 at-bats, with
three doubles, a home run, five runs scored, and eight runs batted
in. ``If they didn't put it in front of my face, I wouldn't know
what my stats are. Numbers don't tell the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they do, but Everett's point is that the number that
counts the most is games won, which they did twice in the
three-game series with Detroit and twice in the three-game series
with Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   He knows there will be times when all the Boston bats are
stopped like they were Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the way the Red Sox feel about themselves and what they have
shown in the first month suggest that games like Sunday's will be
more the rule than the exception.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
