<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION LIKE VIEW FROM THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After four years pursuing D.C. United, the Revolution
have finally overtaken the three-time MLS Cup champs _ at least
temporarily. And, instead of playing the role of the self-deluded
challenger, the Revolution are preparing for Saturday's visit to
Washington as the Eastern Division leader.
</P>
<P>
   The role reversal resulted from a drastic downturn in the D.C.
defense and some steady performances by the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams made a breakthrough Saturday. United took a 5-2
victory at Colorado, reconfirming the team's explosiveness but
doing little to dispatch doubts about the defense. D.C. could pull
into a tie for the division lead by winning in Miami Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, meanwhile, were sparked by Mauricio Ramos in a
2-1 win over San Jose, but possibly lost Leonel Alvarez (left
ankle) and Wolde Harris (shin) along with John Harkes (calf).
</P>
<P>
   The situation has reaffirmed some of coach Fernando Clavijo's
assessments of his team. But Clavijo is treading the line between
outright confidence and cautious optimism. Clavijo, in his first
season with New England, does not carry the baggage of coaching a
team that has never finished better than second-to-last place.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution have never been in first place two
months into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I didn't know that,'' Clavijo said Sunday.
``Everyone wants to be in first place every season. Unfortunately,
some teams have never achieved those goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``(D.C.) scored five goals on Colorado, which shows they have
the power to do it. They did not go from a great team to a bad team
overnight, but they were going through some hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well against them at home (a 2-1 overtime win April
15) and if we have everyone back we should be all right. They are
the defending champions and they think they need to rebound. We
need to hold our ground. And if everyone stays confident, plays
smart, and sacrifices for the good of the team, we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo hopes to continue with the 3-5-2 alignment that allowed
Ramos to explode against the Earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along I want to play a 3-5-2 formation,''
Clavijo said. ``We haven't been able to do it because we were
looking for a sweeper. But I am more comfortable now with Brian
Dunseth in back, along with Rusty Pierce and Ivan McKinley.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo is likely to stay with the formation against United.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say don't change something if it's working,'' Clavijo
said. ``When I thought about it before the San Jose game, I decided
why not try it? Yes, you could lose badly but you could also win
big.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mental part of the game is the most important thing. You
have to stay positive. No matter what happened in the past, there
is nothing we can do about it now. We control our own destiny. If
we are clicking on all cylinders, and we are healthy, and our minds
are in the game, this is one of the deepest teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rican midfielder William Sunsing was uninjured but his car
was totaled in an accident in New York Sunday . . . The Revolution
now have 38 3-point victories in 138 games. Their home record is
25-32-12 (102-100 goal differential); their road record is 13-47-9
(85-144).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
