<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     05-08 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIVING RICE'S ALLEY-OOP OOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most memorable vision of Glen Rice on Sunday
wasn't exactly one for the highlight file: Rice, tripping over the
Phoenix Suns' Shawn Marion while attempting a rare alley-oop dunk,
turning his left ankle in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The ball sailed harmlessly out of bounds on the unusual play.
And as the Lakers rolled to a 105-77 victory, Rice settled for a
quiet contribution of seven points and five rebounds. But he's
figuring on better opportunities as this best-of-seven series
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns eventually will need to send help toward the paint to
prevent another 37-point night from Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to make some adjustments,'' Rice said,
``and the minute they give me a little breathing room, I'm going to
have to make them pay.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't easy Sunday, with Marion draped over Rice for much
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're basically staying home on me, and any time I get a
little breathing room, it's probably going to be in the transition
offense,'' said Rice, the Lakers' third leading scorer and top 3-
point threat.
</P>
<P>
   With few perimeter opportunities, Rice went for the
unconventional (for him, anyway) - the alley-oop pass from Kobe
Bryant early in the third quarter. All it got him was a sprained
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, that's probably why you don't see me going for too
many,'' Rice said with a laugh. ``My ankle rolled over on me. All I
could do as I was falling is watch the ball sail out of bounds. ...
It's a little swollen now. It's a little sore. But we've got
(today) to get in there and get some treatment. I'm sure by
Wednesday, it'll be all better.''
</P>
<P>
   Role playing: Derek Fisher has been in and out of the rotation,
but he seems to have a clear-cut part in this series: defend Kevin
Johnson. As the Lakers' lone small, quick guard, Fisher spent much
of Game 1 moving on and off the floor when Johnson did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's a great player and always has been,'' said Fisher.
``Growing up in Little Rock (Ark.), Cal actually came down to
Little Rock and played one year. I must have been like 9 or 10
years old and remember seeing him play then. So he's been doing
this for a long time. At the same time, competing against him and
wanting to beat him as my opponent, but also respecting him and
learning from how he plays the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Slow start: The Lakers' shooting percentage of 43.5 was
deceiving, dragged down by a 5 for 23 first quarter. They traced
the slow start in part to the quick turnaround from Friday's Game 5
clincher against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was tough on us mentally making the adjustment to
now, OK, it's a new team, we have to play pick and roll a new way,
there are new matchups, you have to do things differently,'' Fisher
said. ``We didn't have shootaround this morning, so we didn't
really have a chance to get the legs going. I believe a lot of that
had to do with the slow start, especially shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant: ``Our legs were just a little heavy. I think the
(four) days off kind of helped (the Suns).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8610 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBERS DON'T ADD UP FOR PHOENIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Jell-O was jiggling, the butter was getting
hard, Game 1 was in the refrigerator for the Lakers. Because a
sellout crowd had turned up at the Staples Center and a network
television audience had tuned in, they played out the final three
quarters of their second-round playoff opener against Phoenix
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly didn't help Jason Kidd's surgically repaired ankle
and the Suns' collective psyche to sweat and stagger through 36
minutes more, just to wind up on the embarrassing end of the 105-77
final score.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Lakers' 28-point margin of victory, the game's most
telling numbers were contained in the first quarter statistics: The
Lakers shot 21.7 percent from the field, went more than eight
minutes before pulling down their first offensive rebound, had two
measly assists and looked up at the scoreboard after 12 minutes to
find the score knotted at 18.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. If the Suns can't carve out a lead on the
Lakers when Shaquille O'Neal is missing six of seven shots and Kobe
Bryant is misfiring on three of four attempts and ex-Laker Corie
Blount is controlling the defensive boards, then what does that say
about the Suns' chances of taking four of seven games in the
series?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, if you ask us.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been one thing if the Suns had come out and
wrapped up the Lakers shooters like leftovers in cellophane, and
that's what caused the cacophony of clanks. In fact, the Lakers
were suffocating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix coach Scott Skiles could have credited his starting
frontcourt of Shawn Marion, Cliff Robinson and Luc Longley for
shutting down O'Neal in the early going. Instead he opted for the
truth. O'Neal ``had some decent looks,'' Skiles said, ``and missed
them.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's missed shots were as contagious as a yawn. His
teammates saw his shots bounce off the rim and next thing they knew
they were reflexively misfiring too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed some easy shots,'' starting point guard Ron Harper
said. ``I know because I missed (four) of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers were just about Bryant's slashes and O'Neal's
slams, it might have been a long afternoon for Los Angeles. But the
Lakers are much more than they appear; behind that bewitching
offense is a blue-collar defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers clogged the Suns' passing lanes and forced 23
turnovers, off which they scored 28 points by Skiles' count.
</P>
<P>
   That's the game right there. That's going to be the series, too,
unless the Suns can find a way to do onto the Lakers as the Lakers
did onto them; that is, prevent the ball from getting inside to
O'Neal by pressuring the perimeter players into bad passes and bad
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Lakers were reading the Suns, they appeared to have
Phoenix's playbook down better than the Phoenix players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did an excellent job defensively, no doubt about that,''
said Bryant, adding, ``I love playing defense.''
</P>
<P>
   On this afternoon, it showed. The ball was like a yo-yo in
Bryant's hands; it kept finding its way back to him. He contributed
three steals and three blocked shots along with 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bryant is like a bird dog, sniffing out the
basketball on both ends of the court. The difference in Bryant last
season and now, said Blount, his former teammate, is that there
seems to be a method to Bryant's constant motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing I see changed in Kobe is he doesn't force a lot
of shots like he used to,'' Blount said. ``His shot selection is a
lot better and so is his control.''
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing is Bryant's mind moves as fast as his feet. He
caught Kidd limping in the second quarter and started driving on
him. It was as if Bryant was a Porsche and Kidd was parked on the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, playing in his second game since having his left ankle put
back together with screws, finished with three points and five
turnovers, the latter of which left more of an impression than his
seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was O'Neal, who made 14 of 21 shots over the final
three quarters to finish with a game-high 37 points. O'Neal and
Bryant buried the Suns. Resurrecting themselves in Wednesday's Game
2 isn't going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Bryant said. ``They have a choice to make. Do
they want to pack in the middle or do they want to double me on the
perimeter?. They can't do both.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns didn't do either on Sunday and they got burned. How
severely, we'll have to wait and see. From where we sat, it didn't
look good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-SHARKS-NOTES-TEX     05-08 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TRACEY MYERS AND JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Coming into Reunion Arena down 3-1 in a best-of-seven
series was tough enough for the San Jose Sharks. But their hopes
for continuing their season were hampered even more when they took
the ice without two of their top skaters.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Bryan Marchment and right winger Owen Nolan were
sidelined last night, and their absences were felt immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Marchment, who suffered a groin injury in Friday's game and
didn't make the trip, had been a crucial defender against the
Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk, who scored twice last night.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan's injury was a little more complicated. He was reported to
be suffering the ``flu'' when he was scratched prior to Game 5. But
after the Sharks were eliminated, Nolan admitted to having a lower
abdominal pull, which he suffered in Round 1's Game 7 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously losing Nolan was a huge loss,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said ``Our players commented that after games, they
noticed him wincing on the ice. That tells you that he had more
than a foot injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan had been pivotal on the Sharks' power plays and scored two
goals in the series.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose coach Darryl Sutter said the decision to scratch Nolan
was made last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we used it as an excuse at all,'' Sutter said
about losing the two players.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks players felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using that as an excuse,'' right winger Todd Harvey
said. ``We've got 20 guys in here that suited up tonight and
expected to win this. We didn't do the job. We didn't put the puck
in the net. Against a team like that, as soon as they get a lead,
it's tough to get goals.''  &QL; 
No early lead
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Sutter had stressed all series that his team had to score
first. But for the fifth consecutive game, the Stars lit the red
light first..
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to play against one of the best defensive teams in
the league when you're behind and playing catch up,'' center
Vincent Damphousse said. ``That was one of the big points that we
mentioned coming into this series, and we didn't do it. It was one
more aspect we weren't able to do. The first 10 minutes of any game
is always important, especially against Dallas. We had our chances.
We just couldn't get the lead.''  &QL; 
Finally, a goal
</P>
<P>
   For 2 1/2 periods, it looked as if the Sharks would leave town
0-for-Dallas last night. They lost all three games at Reunion
Arena, but avoided a third consecutive shutout when Patrick Marleau
scored] on the power play at 8:32 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks had 33 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of guys not score goals in the playoffs,'' Darryl
Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   The goalless streak looked as if it might end in the second
period, when the Sharks fired 13 shots at Stars goalie Ed Belfour.
Starting at the 8:17 mark of the second period, the Sharks put a
heavy attack on Belfour, but he squashed all comers.  &QL; 
Sharks don't feel power
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' only goal did come on a power play in the third
period, but they missed several opportunities on their first power
play in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks got off three good shots, but they weren't able to
penetrate Ed Belfour. They also came up empty on another power
play, late in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to put something by them in the series, and we
just didn't, and it cost us the series,'' winger Jeff Friesen said.
``We didn't quit, but we didn't get the big goals at the right time
of the game. It's just an opportunity that we let slip.''  &QL; 
Too many giveaways
</P>
<P>
   After reducing their giveaways to 15 in Game 4, the Sharks
served up 11 in a first period last night that proved to be their
undoing. A giveaway by Patrick Marleau in the Sharks' zone led to
Scott Thornton's goal at 13:34 to give the Stars a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ice was real bad,'' rookie defenseman Brad Stuart said.
``At the same time, when you know it's like that, you have to keep
it simple, and we didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jeff Norton had a close call later in the period when
his attempted pass from the Sharks' goal line deflected high off
Guy Carbonneau's stick, hit rookie defenseman Scott Hannan on the
back and nearly trickled into the goal.  &QL; 
Sundstrom a passenger
</P>
<P>
   Sharks winger Niklas Sundstrom did not have a good series. To
steal a favorite term of Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, Sundstrom was a
``passenger,'' a players who is around for the ride but doesn't
contribute much to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   For a team dying to find a goal scorer, Sundstrom, a third-line
winger, had one assist in the series, that came in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   He's not asked to be a major contributor of offense, but during
the season, the Sharks went 19-4-6 when he recorded a point.  &QL; 
Quick shave
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Sharks shaved their playoff facial hair immediately
after the game. Jeff Norton got rid of his goatee, and Scott Hannan
shaved off his side burns that had stretched to his jawbone.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
