mentioned coming into this series, and we didn't do it. It was one
more aspect we weren't able to do. The first 10 minutes of any game
is always important, especially against Dallas. We had our chances.
We just couldn't get the lead.''  &QL; 
Finally, a goal
</P>
<P>
   For 2 1/2 periods, it looked as if the Sharks would leave town
0-for-Dallas last night. They lost all three games at Reunion
Arena, but avoided a third consecutive shutout when Patrick Marleau
scored] on the power play at 8:32 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks had 33 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of guys not score goals in the playoffs,'' Darryl
Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   The goalless streak looked as if it might end in the second
period, when the Sharks fired 13 shots at Stars goalie Ed Belfour.
Starting at the 8:17 mark of the second period, the Sharks put a
heavy attack on Belfour, but he squashed all comers.  &QL; 
Sharks don't feel power
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' only goal did come on a power play in the third
period, but they missed several opportunities on their first power
play in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks got off three good shots, but they weren't able to
penetrate Ed Belfour. They also came up empty on another power
play, late in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to put something by them in the series, and we
just didn't, and it cost us the series,'' winger Jeff Friesen said.
``We didn't quit, but we didn't get the big goals at the right time
of the game. It's just an opportunity that we let slip.''  &QL; 
Too many giveaways
</P>
<P>
   After reducing their giveaways to 15 in Game 4, the Sharks
served up 11 in a first period last night that proved to be their
undoing. A giveaway by Patrick Marleau in the Sharks' zone led to
Scott Thornton's goal at 13:34 to give the Stars a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ice was real bad,'' rookie defenseman Brad Stuart said.
``At the same time, when you know it's like that, you have to keep
it simple, and we didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jeff Norton had a close call later in the period when
his attempted pass from the Sharks' goal line deflected high off
Guy Carbonneau's stick, hit rookie defenseman Scott Hannan on the
back and nearly trickled into the goal.  &QL; 
Sundstrom a passenger
</P>
<P>
   Sharks winger Niklas Sundstrom did not have a good series. To
steal a favorite term of Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, Sundstrom was a
``passenger,'' a players who is around for the ride but doesn't
contribute much to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   For a team dying to find a goal scorer, Sundstrom, a third-line
winger, had one assist in the series, that came in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   He's not asked to be a major contributor of offense, but during
the season, the Sharks went 19-4-6 when he recorded a point.  &QL; 
Quick shave
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Sharks shaved their playoff facial hair immediately
after the game. Jeff Norton got rid of his goatee, and Scott Hannan
shaved off his side burns that had stretched to his jawbone.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
