<HEADLINE>
HE'S SENDING A FRANK MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In case you were wondering, Frank Robinson says he
was never slapped with a fine or a suspension for getting into a
baseball brawl during his 21-year playing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never fined, never suspended,'' he repeated when asked during
halftime of Sunday's Lakers-Suns playoff game at Staples Center,
where he and his family sat in their usual baseline courtside
seats.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the sport's new big-shot suspension-giver-outer-guy
laughs when asked if all the heavy duty punishment he's been
dishing lately to big leaguers is payback for someone who once
wronged him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the case at all,'' said Robinson, who happens to be
third on the all-time list for being hit with a pitch at 198.
</P>
<P>
   OK, there was one time he thought about going out to the mound
as a member of the Cincinnati Reds, against San Francisco pitcher
Ron Herbel at Candlestick Park. But all the while, he was hoping
someone would stop him before he got there. Someone did.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one message the one-time Dodgers and Angels
outfielder wants to get across, it is that today's athletes need to
understand something basic. They're not entitled to go crazy when
someone invades their territory. It's part of the game. And the
managers a job he also once held have to be held accountable as
well.
</P>
<P>
   He compares baseball's problem in this area to the NBA, where
players ``jaw at people, go dunk on other players. In baseball, if
the pitcher throws inside, he's staring at the hitter, the hitter
will jaw back at him. That has to stop.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   -You gotta realize that Tommy Lasorda won't be doing any actual
managing when he's down under with the boys of Sydney, waving the
flag of the U-S-of-A. Press conferences, back-slapping and wearing
out the starting pitcher's arm are his forte.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be up to those who are selected as coaches to do the real
dirty work. ...
</P>
<P>
   -It shouldn't have taken a devoiding injury to Devo for Davey
Johnson to recognize Todd Hollandsworth's value as an everyday
player. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Wonder what Blackjack McDowell thinks of actor Jack Black doing
the Marvin Gaye classic ``Let's Get It On'' in the flick ``High
Fidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, it beats Mills Lane screaming it out. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Tiger Woods, who appears as himself this week at the Byron
Nelson Classic, did a very stand-up thing by disappearing for a
Nike commercial out of respect for the picketing Screen Actors
Guild.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who has made more than $3 mil in just eight Tour events
this year can afford to do it, sure. But The Tidy Bowl guy thanks
you for your support. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Pat Riley tells the New York Times he has sold six screenplays,
``to all of the studios,'' but none have been made into movies.
Yet.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is entitled ``The Seventh Game.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   -And you just know it'll be a Miami-Lakers final, something a
scriptwriter can't help but dream up. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Former NBA great Bill Russell, who got HBO to do a flattering
documentary on his career called ``My Way'' last month, is now
trying to motivate a book publisher to give him the cash to do a
motivational book. ...
</P>
<P>
   -One-time Sports Illustrated swimsuit model Carre Otis appears
in the June issue of Playboy. Without her swimsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, we see no difference. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Jenine Sahadi is one tough filly. ...
</P>
<P>
   -One theory as to why there seems to be more hit-and-run
incidents these days: After a wreck in a NASCAR event, you never
see both drivers pull off to the side and exchange insurance
information.
</P>
</TEXT>
