<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARKS KNEW WHAT TO DO, BUT COULDN'T DO IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Owen Nolan finally acknowledged that he never really
had the flu, and the Sharks confessed the Stars can be vulnerable
if you follow the correct formula.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these revelations came after last night's 4-1 Stars
victory that sent the eighth-seeded and once upstart Sharks home in
five games.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan did not play in the decisive game and told the waiting
world after the game that his mystery illness, which also forced
him out of Game 2, was a lower abdominal pull suffered in Game 7
against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with a lot of pain the last game. I emptied the
tank,'' the Sharks captain said of that wild affair that the Stars
won, 5-4. ``I had nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   And as far as this vulnerability thing regarding the Stars as
they prepare for a Western Conference finals rematch against the
Colorado Avalanche, well, the Sharks figured out what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get the lead going into the third period, they will
open up,'' Sharks center Vincent Damphousse said.
</P>
<P>
   How to do it is the Avalanche's riddle to solve now. The Sharks
certainly had no luck. They managed one lead this series, that
coming in Game 3 when they took a 2-1 lead into the third period
and made it stand.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Sharks goalie Steve Shields gave up the game's first
goal in the first period for the fifth consecutive game, enabling
the Stars to drop into their suffocating defensive system with only
half the first period expired.
</P>
<P>
   When Scott Thornton slid Stars goal No. 2 through Shields' legs
at the 13:34 mark of the first period, the Sharks were then simply
choked out of humid Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they have everyone playing on the same page, playing the
same way, buying into that program that \RStars coach Ken\S
Hitchcock has them playing, they are a tough team to play
against,'' Sharks veteran Ron Sutter said. ``You have to pay the
price and be accountable at paying that price to give yourself a
chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all 20 guys, not just three or four guys on every
shift, but all five guys together. No individual effort is going to
beat that team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche was almost certainly watching last night, watching
Ed Belfour stop 32 shots, 25 of 26 in the second and third periods.
The second period was the Sharks' to win. They outshot the Stars,
13-4, and applied heavy doses of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize how close we were,'' Sharks winger Jeff Friesen
said. ``If we had some guys step up and score some big goals, we
might be moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche, players such as Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic and the
recovering man on a mission, Ray Bourque, almost certainly took
note of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team that plays hard below the circles, that's got the
guys with the guts to do it, can create chances and score goals,''
Sutter said. ``They're the Stanley Cup champs, and I think it's
open. We felt it was open for any team.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps any team that can take a lead into the third period.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
