<SLUG> BC-HKN-REMATCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN FINALS A REMATCH OF '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Avalanche is coming.
</P>
<P>
   The highly anticipated matchup is here. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will meet the Colorado Avalanche with a berth in the
Stanley Cup Finals at stake. The NHL won't release the dates for
the series until at least today, which means the Western Conference
finals will start no earlier than Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stars fans can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Stars had even wrapped up their semifinal series with
a 4-1 victory against the San Jose Sharks last night, the Reunion
Arena crowd of 17,001 was chanting for the Avalanche. Stars players
were happy for a day off before preparation begins for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a serious series,'' Stars center Mike
Modano said. ``Everybody has been waiting for this matchup, a
rematch of last year. It's a great opportunity. You are eight wins
away from it, but we're going to have our hands full.''
</P>
<P>
   On their way to the Stanley Cup last season, the Stars defeated
the Avalanche in seven games in the Western Conference finals. With
apologies to the St. Louis Blues, who won the Presidents' Trophy as
the NHL's best regular-season team, the Stanley Cup still goes
through Dallas and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely two of the top teams. I don't know if it's
the two best teams,'' Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``At
this time of the year, everybody's here for a reason. But it's two
great teams in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado was only 30-27-10 before acquiring defenseman Ray
Bourque in a trade with Boston on March 6. The Avalanche is 20-4-1
since, including an 8-2 playoff record, although Bourque missed the
last two games of the semifinal series against the Detroit Red
Wings with an injured left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fooling ourselves,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``We're playing the hottest team in the National Hockey League. We
were chuckling a little bit because this is the first time in a
very long time that this team \RDallas\S has come in as an
underdog. But we all saw what they did to Detroit, and Detroit's a
hell of a hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 1-3-1 against Colorado this season, but they
still have their memories of their playoff series against them last
season. Dallas won the last two games in the seven-game series to
advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that they lost last year, they've got that
vengeance in their eyes,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``We
know they're going to come hard. But this team likes to play in
those games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
