<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8620 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS RUNNING ON CRUISE CONTROL WITH BELFOUR IN GEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In the end, the story of these two weeks among the
Sharks wasn't the coaches. It wasn't the sudden resuscitation of
Joe Nieuwendyk. It wasn't Owen Nolan's courageous play amid the,
uh, flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belfour was the story in the series,'' San Jose center Vincent
Damphousse correctly answered.
</P>
<P>
   In the NHL playoffs, it is written, a team is only as good as
its goaltender. And thus far, the defending champions have been
cruising because, indeed, Eddie Belfour has been the answer for
nearly every Stars question.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's second period acrobatics yesterday slammed the final
door on the Sharks. Jeered in San Jose, swaddled in adoration at
Reunion Arena, Belfour came close to pitching his third consecutive
home-ice shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the difference in the series had a lot to do with
Eddie's play,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said after the Stars' 4-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was outstanding, especially the game he played in the
second period today.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Stars clutching a 2-0 lead, Belfour withstood a wave of
Sharks chances, including one with Damphousse nearly parked in his
lap. Another save came with Belfour sprawled across the ice, and
still another came when he snared Jeff Friesen's one-on-one chance
with his mitt.
</P>
<P>
   When the visitors went to the second intermission still
scoreless and trailing 2-0, an air of festive inevitability began
to overtake Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cup stays here! Cup stays here!'' the crowd chanted.
</P>
<P>
   And with seven minutes left and the Stars lining up for a
face-off in their own end, the arena PA began to play the Jimi
Hendrix classic, ``Are You Experienced?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, so they are.
</P>
<P>
   No more so than Belfour, who has been there and _ at long last _
done that. Eddie himself gave a stock answer to the
post-Cup-confidence question yesterday, but in so many ways he's
been answering it all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think throughout the season, he's been our most consistent
over-achiever,'' general manager Bob Gainey said yesterday. ``I
think \RMike\S Modano came on at about the 60 percent point and
from there was like a snowball rolling downhill, whereas Eddie
started with game one and hasn't slipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is amazing, considering the, uh, distractions that Belfour
faced in March _ the alleged headlock on the hotel security guard,
the alleged spirited ride to the police station, and the alleged
charm that Eddie exhibited therein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him play this well,'' said the Sharks' Darryl
Sutter, who coached Belfour briefly in San Jose. ``But he plays so
much more in control now. You've all seen it. I think that's the
big secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, in this best-of-seven series cut short, Belfour
laughably outplayed his San Jose counterpart. Sharks goalie Steve
Shields seemed either asleep or oblivious to two of the Stars' four
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be rude, but as much as Belfour was the difference for
the Stars in this series, so, too, was Shields for his team _ in
all the wrong ways.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he felt the Stars were beatable, though, Shields
answered, ``I don't know what they were like in the playoffs last
year, but I feel like they were beatable this time. We played a
couple of one-goal games where, if we would have gotten a few more
breaks, we could have won those games and we would've been right
there with them.''
</P>
<P>
   See? He really was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   But the story was Belfour, Captain Headlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a continuation of what Ed did all year, with all
the injuries we've had,'' defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``He
played exceptional hockey last year when we won the Stanley Cup,
and he's carried it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best goalies in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The personally acclaimed best in the world, of course, comes up
next. Certain to be discussed in the coming days are the remarks
that Belfour made that reportedly rubbed the ermine fur of
Colorado's Patrick Roy the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like the challenge of playing against Patrick,''
Belfour said, simply.
</P>
<P>
   He knows _ from experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
