<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8621 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     05-08 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STRENGTHENS POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Somewhere in the Dirtbag locker room sits a
trash can full of baseball caps -- the team's cool gray-top,
black-billed caps, black caps with the white interlocked LB, black
caps with the logo in gold, and some sweat-soaked, funky smelling
practice caps that the Environment Protection Agency might consider
toxic.
</P>
<P>
   They reside in this bucket because 49ers baseball coach Dave
Snow felt the need to give his team a shake, and how better than to
deny them the privilege of wearing a Dirtbag cap? So before the
weekend series with Pacific began, he collected the headgear and
handed his players generic black hats.
</P>
<P>
   Did the psychological ploy work? Well, the Dirtbags beat Pacific
4-3 Sunday to sweep the series and strength its position for a Big
West title and NCAA tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning, catcher Bryan Kennedy stepped up with a
huge defensive play to save the win, the kind of play that has
always distinguished what Dirtbag baseball is about.
</P>
<P>
   But even after the sweep, Snow admits he still doesn't have a
feel for this team. He's had several teams in his dozen at Long
Beach develop a personality late in the season, but never this far
into the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirtbags are 29-20 overall and 16-8 in the Big West, a game
behind their primary rival, Fullerton. They have seven games left,
a Tuesday game at UCLA, a series at third-place Nevada (31-17,
15-9), and then the Titans at home to end the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our opportunities are ahead of us,'' Snow said. ``The whole
hat idea was to just try something different, to shake them up and
send a message. We needed something to rally around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a strange season. We haven't had that one
inspirational leader who's willing to take the team on his
shoulders and not let them bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's uncharacteristic of the teams we've had here. When we
hit our rough spot (this season), the players didn't take it as a
challenge to step up. They've let the setbacks and losses drag them
down. It's almost like we gave in to the adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been plenty of that. After winning 15 of 16 games to
improve to 16-4 and a No. 8 national ranking, the 49ers went 10-16
over their next 26 games, including a six-game losing streak, the
longest ever under Snow.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't won a mid-week non-conference win since mid-March,
suffering two losses to sub-.500 Northridge as well as Wednesday's
come-from-ahead 8-7 loss San Diego. They lost two of three to
Sacramento State in April, and followed two wins in three games
against Fullerton by blowing a three-game series to UCSB.
</P>
<P>
   How rare is that? UCSB had a grand total of five wins against
Snow in the previous 11 years. Twenty-two of the 49ers' 42 Big West
losses the previous six seasons had been claimed by two schools,
Fullerton and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Snow's teams have always been resilient. His '91 team staggered
down the stretch (5-6 in its last 11) but won its regional and
advanced to the College World Series. His 1993 team opened 12-12
but closed 26-5, then swept its regional and advanced to the World
Series. His 1995 team was 21-19-1 before winning 13 of their next
14 and coming one misplayed bunt in a regional final of another
World Series trip.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 team opened 6-10 then won 20 of 23 and took LSU to the
title game of a regional. His 1998 team went to the CWS, too. That
squad opened 2-8-1 then won 16 of 17. It had another 2-8 slump,
too, before 11 straight wins and a KO of No. 1-ranked Stanford in
the regional.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Kennedy, outfielder Chuck Lopez and pitchers Jason Berni
and Jeff Leuenberger were members of that '98 team. Kennedy says
the difference between that team and the 2000 team comes down to
the little things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled at times when I was a freshman, but not like
this,'' Kennedy said. ``You can't point to any one thing and say
`that's it,' other than a lot of the little things, like driving in
a runner from third with one out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The 49ers came into Sunday's game hitting .305, had a
respectable 4.36 earned run average, and was playing good defense,
highlighted by shortstop Bobby Crosby, who has made just three
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought: Maybe the pool of potential Dirtbags is
shallow. The nonchalance of pro athletes has infected younger
athletes and turned the ``team'' concept into an anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kennedy, responding in general to a broad question not
about his teammates: Being a Dirtbag is what I want to be. But I
think there are a lot of guys out there who are results driven.
When you come to Long Beach, coach stresses that you have to put
your own personality aside for the good of the team, because that's
what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow said his pool is still full. But it should be noted that
the 49ers have started three different players at third base this
season, and that last year's third baseman, Lou Dobbs, who hit .376
with 63 RBI, wasn't invited back.
</P>
<P>
   Snow prefers to look forward. Sunday, his team had eight hits
and four runs in the first four innings, but just two hit
thereafter. In Pacific's ninth, a bloop single, balk and sacrifice
put the game-tying run on third. The situation looked too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy raced up the third-base line to corral a wild throw
from Chuck Lopez after a fly out, keeping the Pacific on third, and
Crosby got a generous hop on a grounder off the mound for the
game's final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year, we talk about doing the things in the field
that represents Dirtbag baseball,'' said Snow of Kennedy's save.
``It's the kind of thing which gives character to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of thing which can earn them back their caps, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
