<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NIEUWENDYK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK SUPPLIES SPARK TO SECOND LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS_ Call the post office and milk carton manufacturers. The
search for Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk is over.
</P>
<P>
   He's alive and scoring, and looking more and more like the 1999
Conn Smythe Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring the first goal in last night's series-clinching
4-1 Stars victory against San Jose, Nieuwendyk has given the Stars
something that Western Conference finals opponent Colorado has: two
lines that are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe elevated his game,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said. ``We
talked before the series about them having two dominant centers,
and both of them showed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 4 at San Jose, however, it was one dominant center:
Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   His line, along with Brenden Morrow and Brett Hull, posted a
streak from Games 1 through 4 where it provided all the offense for
more than 148 minutes. After those games, Nieuwendyk was inundated
with questions about when he thought he was going to break out of a
slump that saw him score one goal in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you miss as much time as I did, you want to come back and
have everything be the same,'' said Nieuwendyk, who had injury
problems this season. ``The last little while I'm starting to feel
the intensity of it, getting involved more and just applying myself
a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   With two goals in the Game 4-victory, Nieuwendyk was back. In
Games 1 through 3, he had one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played very strong tonight,'' Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said. ``It adds a dimension that has only been
there sporadically.''
</P>
<P>
   The dimension is a second productive line. In Games 1 through 3,
the line of Nieuwendyk, Jamie Langenbrunner (who missed Game 3) and
Scott Thornton combined for two points.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to the past two games:
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk: Three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner: Three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton: One goal, two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We depended on Modano's line a lot since the beginning of the
playoffs,'' Thornton said. ``But, you need a supporting cast to win
in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   With Colorado and their center combination of Joe Sakic and
Peter Forsberg, who have combined for 16 points in the playoffs,
the Stars know that to advance to the Stanley Cup Finals, at least
two lines must be producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from \RModano\S, but the further you
go in the playoffs, if you only have one line going, I don't think
you're going to win,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``We
showed that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential problem for the Avalanche is, which line checks
which? Throw defensemen Adam Foote and Ray Bourque at Modano's line
or Nieuwendyk's line? If both are scoring, it can be like choosing
between jumping into a fire or a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think especially against Bourque and Foote, whoever
plays against those guys are going to have their hands full,''
Modano said. ``Hopefully our two lines can push them to the limits
and wear them down and cause them to decide which line they are
going to play against.''
</P>
<P>
   With Nieuwendyk scoring, the decision just got tougher.
</P>
<P>
   This is why one fan in last night's audience had the confidence
to carry a sign that read: ``He's back. I Nieuwy he would be''.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
