<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH MAKING THE MOST OF IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It might be a two-week hitch or a season in center
field, but Todd Hollandsworth is more concerned with the present
than the future.
</P>
<P>
   Playing center and batting leadoff for Devon White, who could
face surgery after tearing the rotator cuff in his left shoulder
Tuesday, Hollandsworth has done well with his new opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   After doing time on the disabled list in four of the past five
seasons, Hollandsworth is the healthy one now. And it shows.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over for White last Wednesday against Atlanta,
Hollandsworth has gone 7 for 17, including a leadoff home run
Sunday in the Dodgers' 14-8 loss to the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holly is a valuable player because he can do so much for us,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``We are encouraged that Devo
is getting better, but it is good to know we have someone of
Holly's skill to step in.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run was critical after the Astros jumped out to a four-
run lead in the top of the first. It also started a five-run inning
for the Dodgers against Houston right-hander Jose Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth came in batting .429 (6 for 14) against Lima, who
had dropped five straight. Hollandsworth also went 2 for 5 Friday
night against the Astros, including a game-winning RBI single in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Big Hurt: Houston outfielder Moises Alou is one of the game's
top players, when healthy. After missing most of last season with a
knee injury, Alou is back on the disabled list with a strained
right calf muscle. It is the eighth time in nine seasons that Alou
has been on the DL, totaling 65 weeks. His father Felipe, now the
manager at Montreal, went on the DL once in his 17-year career.
Moises is set to return Friday against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming: The Dodgers open a three-game series tonight against
the NL West-leading Diamondbacks, who have won five straight.
Former Dodgers right-hander Mike Morgan has taken over for injured
Matt Mantei as the Diamondbacks' closer. Morgan, a career starter,
has four saves, one more than he had in the first 17 years of his
career. Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley is 15 for 36 lifetime against
Morgan with four homers. ...
</P>
<P>
   Arizona CF Steve Finley is among the league leaders with 11 home
runs, and it's no fluke. The once light-hitting Finley, who has
three Gold Gloves, is now one of the NL's top offensive players.
From May 3, 1999, to last Tuesday, Finley has played 156 of
Arizona's 162 games and has a .281 average, 40 homers, 116 RBI, 112
runs scored, 31 doubles and 10 triples. ... Dodgers reserve
infielder Jose Vizcaino is 1 for 11 in his career against tonight's
starter, Omar Daal, a finesse pitcher, but 4 for 10 vs. fireballer
Randy Johnson, who will pitch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   More Big Unit: Johnson, who is 7-0 with an 0.93 ERA, tied a
major-league record with six victories in April. Last year, when
Johnson won the Cy Young Award, he did not get his sixth win until
May 30. He is on pace for 373 strikeouts, 58 walks and 152 hits
allowed in 287 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
