   QUEPASA (Phoenix) _ Arturo Jimenez is one of a growing number of
Hispanics defying the notion that they don't go online.``I use it
frequently for news, entertainment; for what's ever going on in the
Latin world,'' said Jimenez, 31, an account executive at Radio
Unica, a Spanish-language talk-radio station in Phoenix. A 1998
U.S. Department of Commerce study found that less than 13 percent
of Latino households had Internet access, compared with 30 percent
for Anglos. But in the past two years, the gap has narrowed as
increasing numbers of Latinos rush to get online, according to
Ekaterina Walsh, an analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge,
Mass. Walsh said 28 percent of the nation's 32 million Latinos are
online at home. By DANIEL GONZALEZ. Story will move in the ``A''
