<HEADER>
A8625 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX     05-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Beginning this morning, Colorado coach Bob Hartley will
say all the right things about playing the Stars. They're a good
team, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing he can say will say as much as the look on his face when
a camera caught him in the stands at Reunion Arena last night. He
was watching the Stars' 4-1 whipping of the San Jose Sharks in Game
5 that put the Stars in the Western Conference finals against the
Avalanche for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Hartley wasn't smiling. He looked like a man who had seen
something he didn't very much like. A flying Joe Nieuwendyk, a
stifling Stars defense and a focused Ed Belfour will do that to a
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think this is the best we've played all season,'' Stars
general manager Bob Gainey said after watching the Stars dispatch
the Sharks. ``We've got a lot of elements going right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Avalanche are good. They showed it by wrapping up the
Detroit Red Wings in five games on Friday night. The Stars aren't
so bad themselves. They showed that last night.
</P>
<P>
   They're about to find out how good _ playing an Avalanche team
that has won 22 of their past 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fooling ourselves. We're playing the hottest team in
the NHL,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We're chuckling a
little bit because for the first time in a very long time we're
coming in as an underdog. We saw what they did to Detroit, and
Detroit is a hell of a hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   If the rest of the Avalanche were indeed watching, the Stars
gave them something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   So the Avalanche rolls four lines, headlined by Peter Forsberg
and Joe Sakic? The Stars reminded us yesterday that they have four
as well. Last season's Conn Smythe winner, Nieuwendyk, scored the
first goal at 10:31 in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's back. He scored one goal and was on the ice for all
three others, including Scott Thornton's at 13:34 of the first
period. Not bad for a guy said to be struggling. He's a perfect
complement to Mike Modano, who has been playing like Conn Smythe
2000 since the playoffs began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going,'' Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner said of
Nieuwendyk. ``It just hasn't been going in the net for him. When it
doesn't go in the net for you, you start to second guess and you
maybe sit back a little bit. When that confidence comes back, you
start attacking like he has been.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Avs have a hot goalie in Patrick Roy, do they? Well, the
Stars have goalie Ed Belfour, who was every bit as good last night.
Belfour hadn't allowed a goal in 187 minutes, 25 seconds at Reunion
Arena until Sharks forward Patrick Marleau scored at 8:32 of the
third period. The Stars goalie finished with 32 saves, including 13
in the crucial second period where the Stars were outshot, 13-4.
</P>
<P>
   Reunion, coincidentally, is where Games 1 and 2 of the Western
Conference finals will be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with him for almost 10 years so I know how he can
play. When he starts the season, he wants to win the Stanley Cup,''
Stars center Guy Carbonneau said of Roy. ``Fortunately, we have a
guy like Eddie that is in that class and he wants to do the same
thing. So that's why I say it's going to be even better this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sharks coach Darryl Sutter: ``I've seen him play this well,
but he plays so much in control now. We've seen that the last two
years and that's the biggest difference.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Avs have a defense allowing 1.8 goals a game, do they?
Well, the Stars defense hasn't been playing so bad itself. If you
take out a meltdown Game 4, the Stars allowed the Sharks three
goals in the other four games against San Jose. They allowed four
goals at Reunion in the playoffs this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can play better defensively,'' Stars defenseman
Darryl Sydor said. ``I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Avs have an injured player coming back in defenseman Ray
Bourque? The Stars have two-time reigning Selke Trophy winner Jere
Lehtinen ready to go when the next round begins.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, whatever the Avs showed to prove they're ready for Stanley
by defeating Detroit, the Stars showed they can keep the Cup here
with their showing against the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't watched a second of it,'' Stars winger Brett Hull
said of Colorado's whooping of Detroit. ``I'm sure we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Strains of ``Hey, Hey Goodbye'' began echoing through Reunion
Arena when Hull scored on a 5-on-3 power play with better than 10
minutes remaining and Sylvain Cote added another score 41 seconds
later on the other power play. But Hull's and Cote's were just
finishing touches. The Stars put San Jose in the rear-view mirror
long before, in what was a seemingly easy romp over the Sharks. San
Jose was playing without their captain Owen Nolan (strained
abdominal muscle) and defenseman Bryan Marchment (strained groin).
</P>
<P>
   ``God, I'd like to know what easy is if you guys think that
was,'' Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk said. ``I thought it was
a pretty good battle out there.''
</P>
<P>
   What Matvichuk was trying to say _ and his teammates echoed _
was the Avs will be even more difficult to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a serious series,'' Modano said.
``Everybody has been waiting for this matchup.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
