<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     05-08 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SEE ONE GET AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Diamondbacks were waiting in Arizona, but the
Dodgers had to go extra innings Sunday night before starting their
longest trip of the season against the best team in their division.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been worth it if they had swept the Houston Astros
for the first time since 1994. Instead, after more than 4 hours of
double switches and pitching changes, the Dodgers were rocked for
seven runs in the 10th and now hit the road for 12 games in the
next two weeks after a 14-8 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been playing good baseball,'' said Shawn Green after
the second-place Dodgers lost for just the third time in their
10-game homestand. ``Tonight was frustrating, but we have to put it
behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big series coming up, and it would be nice to win a
few games and pick up some ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Few were left among the sellout crowd of 52,806 at Dodger
Stadium when closer Jeff Shaw hit Richard Hidalgo with the bases
loaded to force home the eventual winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer still could do the math on a lost weekend for Shaw, who
gave up five of the seven runs in the 10th even though the Astros
never really hit the ball hard. He blew a save Friday night by
allowing a ninth-inning home run but wound up with the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he was gone by the time former Dodger Roger Cedeno
capped the evening with a three-run homer against Alan Mills, the
club's fifth pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner (1-1) pitched 1 innings to earn the victory for
Houston. Jose Cabrera allowed an RBI single to Mark Grudzielanek in
the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw (2-2) took the loss, but he was not alone in his
frustration. The Dodgers overcame a 4-0 deficit in the first inning
but wound up blowing a 7-4 lead in the seventh. They left 10
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   For Houston, catcher Mike Meluskey had five hits. He entered the
game with just 12.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser also looked like he was headed for a big game. He
received a huge ovation when he came on to relieve struggling
starter Eric Gagne with two outs in the fourth. Hershiser pitched
well into the seventh in his longest relief appearance since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But after retiring the first two batters, he loaded the bases by
giving up two singles and hitting Craig Biggio with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Osuna, sidelined for most of the past two years with
elbow problems, came on for his first appearance since May 16,
1999, and promptly gave up a two-run single to Bill Spiers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the game began at 5 p.m., there were none of the
twilight horrors that usually bother hitters at that hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros jumped on Gagne for four runs in the first inning,
including back-to-back home runs by Ken Caminiti and Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   But Gagne, still winless in five starts this season, caught a
break. He was facing the Astros' Jose Lima, who entered the game
with five consecutive losses. Sunday, Lima, a 21-game winner last
year, gave up five runs in the first, although only two were
earned.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth opened the Dodgers first with a home run, but
most of the damage was self-inflicted by the Astros, who committed
three errors in the inning and four overall.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros and Mark Grudzielanek later added home runs to help
the Dodgers build the 7-4 lead, but Hershiser ran out of steam in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Dodgers boarded their charter for the
one-hour flight to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Their three-game series with the Diamondbacks features a
potentially epic matchup Wednesday between Kevin Brown and Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been overpowering since missing a month with a broken
right pinkie, but Johnson has been unhittable. After becoming just
the third pitcher to go 6-0 in the month of April, Johnson now is
7-0 with a 0.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The trip does not get any easier when the Dodgers head to St.
Louis for three games next weekend against the Central-leading
Cardinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
