A8641 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CALSTATE-PROGRAM-LADN     05-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALSTATE-PROGRAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST CENTRAL AMERICAN STUDIES PROGRAM OFFERED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California State University, Northridge, will open
the nation's first minor program in Central American studies
Monday, a natural for a campus that has the nation's largest number
of students with roots in that region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything from taking care of other people's
kids to sending probes to Mars,'' said program coordinator Roberto
Lovato, himself the son of a Salvadoran immigrant. ``We feel we're
changing the nature of what it means to be Latino in Southern
California.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1990 U.S. Census, about 310,000 Central
Americans live in Los Angeles. By 2010, Lovato estimates the number
will grow to 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Fernando Valley, the influx of Central Americans is
evident in restaurants along Van Nuys Boulevard that sell pita-like
(ital) pupusas (ital off) and in the emerging Salvadoran,
Guatemalan and Nicaraguan business communities. At CSUN, Central
Americans constitute about 6 percent of the school's nearly 28,000
students.
</P>
<P>
   As a new demographic snapshot develops of Central Americans in
the United States, students are demanding a program devoted to
their cultural experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a moment where blacks and Mexican-Americans were in
the 1960s,'' said Monica Novoa, 20, a member of CSUN's Central
American United Student Association. ``We're creating our own
space, politically. Before the program we didn't have a voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The minor program, which will offer about 300 students a full
courseload of classes starting in the fall semester, will explore
the Central American experience, including immigration to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lovato said the emergence of a new Central American middle class
in the San Fernando Valley goes hand-in-hand with the establishment
of the minor program. Carlos Alsaro, 27, of Tarzana is a member of
that growing middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Alsaro was 9 years old when his mother, frightened by El
Salvador's civil war, brought him and his older brother to the
Silver Lake district near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other inner-city Central Americans, Alsaro and
his brother were bused to Valley schools, which were less crowded
than their neighborhood campuses. Eventually, the family moved to
the Valley because it offered safer neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Now he and his brother, Jose, run Alsaro and Alsaro Insurance
Services on Victory Boulevard in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do identify as being from El Salvador but, as far as being
here, I look at it more as finding business opportunities and being
able to work with all communities,'' Alsaro said. ``My mind-set is
a little more roll-with-it, a little more multicultural.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the minor program, students will explore how Central
American immigrants, who bring memories of political unrest and
civil wars, influence Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Better known is how Southern California influences Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   Salvadoran immigrants, who make up the vast majority of Central
Americans in Los Angeles, send so much of their earnings to
relatives back home that the money accounts for an estimated 5
percent of El Salvador's gross national product, according to
various studies done by Southern California colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those kinds of distinctions of here and there are kind
of disappearing as we see people living a binational existence,''
said Jorge Garcia, dean of CSUN's College of Humanities and a
pioneer of its Chicano Studies program, the first of its kind when
it started in 1969. ``Borders don't mean what they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the experiences of Salvadorans, Nicaraguans and
other Central American immigrants are drastically different from
those of their Mexican neighbors. Most Salvadoran students at CSUN
and residents in the surrounding community recall stories of wars
fought less than a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   The different experiences jibe with what Lovato calls the one
constant that will be the program's first lesson: ``Being an
American has always been in flux,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
