<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-COOPER-HNS     05-08 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-COOPER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
In grade school, those ``How I Spent My Summer Vacation'' theme
papers were often tough to write but usually entertaining to read.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comets guard Cynthia Cooper, if asked to pen a piece about her
vacation from pro basketball over the past eight months, probably
could turn out something that would attract attention from the
editors of Conde Nast Traveller.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's journeys took her around the world, with stops in
Australia, Vietnam and Angola. It was a chance to forget about jump
shots, fast breaks and WNBA scoring titles and recharge her
batteries after enduring a year that included the deaths from
cancer of her mother and of former Comets teammate Kim Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The past nine months have) been very therapeutic in the sense
that I've busied myself to where I couldn't think about anything
but what I was doing,'' Cooper said. ``I don't know if that was
necessarily a good thing. But I feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken some steps in the grieving process. I've gotten
better. I feel like I've gotten better. I'm not out of the woods,
and it's not totally behind me. But I'm just feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike sponsored Cooper's trip to Australia and Vietnam, where she
and fellow Nike spokesman Carl Lewis got an up-close look at how
the company's shoes and clothes are manufactured. And Cooper also
was able to take several satellite tours and enjoy the beautiful
outlying areas of a country that has been closed to Americans for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing and fulfilling portion of Cooper's
offseason, however, was a trip to war-torn Angola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa was wonderful,'' Cooper said Sunday following practice
with the Comets at Westside Tennis Club. ``We went on a goodwill
mission. So we brought over some vitamins, toys, basketballs and
basketball goals. We visited orphanages and hospitals, pediatric
hospitals. It was sad, but it was also wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Angola, a country in southwest Africa gripped by the ravages of
civil war, extended through the Eduardo dos Santos Foundation an
invitation for a ``multisectional delegation'' from America. Cooper
and her group spent four days in Angola during February.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more emotional moments Cooper said she experienced
during her trip came during a stop at a pediatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one of the nurses in the hospital who came up to me
and said, `I really hate to see the women go through these type of
things,''' Cooper recalled. ``She said, `All we need is some
sheets, just some sheets.' I looked over to my business partner and
said, `You know what? If we don't do anything else, we're going to
send them some sheets.' It may be something very little, but it
means so much to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing firsthand the anguish that accompanies a life filled with
trouble and uncertainty left an indelible impression on Cooper, who
grew up in the poverty-ravaged Watts section of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first went (to Angola), it reminded me of Watts,''
Cooper said. ``It reminded me of my own neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have hungry children here in America. We don't have to go
all the way over to Africa to find homeless, hungry children or
people in need. But I also saw smiling children. I saw children who
were dying to take a picture (with her). Or they were diving in the
water laughing and having fun. I saw smiles on faces also. I didn't
just see sadness and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience over there was definitely sad in some cases.
Definitely, there is a need over there. But more than anything, it
was a positive experience and I definitely want to return. They
live in conditions we probably would not be able to survive in. But
they do it. And for that, I commend them.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the hospitals, Cooper's delegation stopped at
several educational facilities and other institutions geared toward
sports and athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no journey involving Cooper would be complete without
the Comets star sharing some of her knowledge of basketball and the
game of life.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's swing through Australia and Vietnam ended just before
she reported to the Comets' training camp. While she arrived back
in Houston perhaps a bit jet-lagged, it was an experience she will
always remember.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who has few peers on a basketball court, over the past
three years has become quite the businesswoman away from it. Her
companies and the services and products they provide are as varied
as the shots and moves that compose Cooper's basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Angola, Cooper promised continued support to the
people through any means her companies can provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do a lot of different things out there,'' she said.
``Just to be able to go over there and help in some way, in a small
way, it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
