<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LOCKERBIE-DEAL-BOS &LR;      05-08 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-DEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKERBIE VICTIMS' KIN FEAR DEAL WITH KHADAFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZEIST, Netherlands _ Citing the words of Moammar Khadafy
himself, some relatives of those killed on Pan Am Flight 103 are
charging that the American and British governments have secretly
gone along with a deal that gave the Libyan leader immunity from
prosecution in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives claim the promise of immunity was contained in a
Feb. 17, 1999, letter to Khadafy from UN Secretary General Kofi
Annan, which was instrumental in persuading Khadafy to surrender
the two suspects two months later to face trial.
</P>
<P>
   Annan and both governments deny that there was any deal to limit
the investigation to the two reputed Libyan intelligence agents,
Abdelbaset Ali Mohmed Megrahi and Al Amin Khalifa Fhima. But
Khadafy fueled suspicions on Tuesday, the eve of their trial here,
when he told a British television reporter that a deal had been
struck between him and Western officials.
</P>
<P>
   While not all, or even most, of the victims' relatives appear to
believe there was a deal, their suspicions and anger flared when
they learned that US State Department officials had visited Libya
at the end of March. The relatives and their supporters in Congress
see that trip as the first step toward lifting the 1981 ban that
bars Americans from traveling to Libya.
</P>
<P>
   More than 11 years after Pan Am Flight 103 exploded 6 miles
above Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259 passengers and crew on
board as well as 11 Lockerbie residents on the ground, the two men
accused of planting the bomb went on trial here last Wednesday at a
former US airbase. But even as they applauded the opening of a
trial they had fought long and hard for, some of the relatives said
they do not believe justice will be served.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a show trial,'' said Susan Cohen of New Jersey, whose
20-year-old daughter Theodora was one of dozens of college students
returning home who were killed in the explosion. ``A deal's been
made, and there's money to be made. People say Libya is a great
place to invest now. You don't have to be a genius to figure out
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Cohen and several others who lost loved ones, both
the British and American governments are anxious to allow business
to cash in on lucrative oil and aerospace markets in Libya.
</P>
<P>
   While Cohen and her husband Dan are the most outspoken, many
others are skeptical of State Department assurances that no deal
has been struck to grant Khadafy or other high-ranking Libyan
officials immunity if the evidence should point toward them.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, the Massachusetts Democrat who has
been the staunchest congressional supporter of the families, wrote
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, urging her to clarify what
Annan did or did not promise Khadafy in his letter.
</P>
<P>
   In a Feb. 8 reply, Albright acknowledged the existence of the
Annan letter but insisted that there was no deal. She said the
trial, being held before a Scottish court as part of the elaborate
compromise that led to the suspects' extradition, is not a show
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me assure you that there are no external or negotiated
limits to the authority of the Scottish prosecutors in the trial or
the lines of inquiry they can pursue,'' Albright wrote to Kennedy.
``The trial will be a genuine criminal proceeding, not a show trial
or an exercise in political propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, she said, ``will have free rein to do what is
necessary and appropriate in their judgment. They have full
latitude to pursue the evidence wherever it leads, including the
possible implication and prosecution of additional suspects
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But several other events have fanned the relatives' suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   In January, former chief prosecutor Lord Andrew Hardie abruptly
resigned, taking a seat on the Scottish High Court.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hardie who last year met with the families and promised
prosecutors would go wherever the evidence took them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen any document, nor would I have been party to
any document, that would inhibit me in the exercise of my duties,''
said Lord Hardie, adding that he had read Annan's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, the State Department abruptly classified the
Annan letter, which was not initially considered secret. That fact,
and the refusal of UN officials, the State Department, the British
Foreign Office, and Scottish prosecutors to release it, convinces
some families that authorities are hiding something. The Justice
Department, acting on behalf of the families, tried to force the
State Department to release the letter, but failed.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cohen and Rosemary Wolfe of Alexandria, Va., whose
20-year-old daughter, Miriam, was killed in the explosion, said
portions of the letter were read to them over the telephone earlier
last year by low-ranking State Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   Both said one sentence promised that the trial would not
``undermine the Libyan regime.'' Cohen said another State
Department official confirmed to her that promises were made to
Khadafy that, the official acknowledged, amounted to immunity.
Neither of the officials Cohen and Wolfe named could be reached for
comment last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also claims that Fred Eckhard, Annan's spokesman, read her
a portion of the letter over the phone which included the phrase,
``it is not our intent to undermine the Libyan regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that when she pressed him on the matter, he became
irritated and hung up on her.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in New York on Friday, Eckhard said the letter was
written to reassure Khadafy that ``the US and the UK would not pull
a trick on him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This line was not intended to constrain in any way the legal
process,'' he added. ``It will go where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   After the relatives started to complain about the Annan letter,
Cohen said, ``everybody clammed up. Now no one will talk to us and
tell us what is really going on.''
</P>
<P>
   So angry were the relatives' congressional supporters over the
State Department trip to Libya that archenemies Kennedy and Senator
Jesse Helms, along with Democrat Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey,
put aside their ideological differences to co-sponsor a resolution
attacking the visit. It was approved last month.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also called on President Clinton to consult Congress
before changing any policy toward Libya and for the White House to
disclose ``any assurances received by the Khadafy regime.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all of the relatives are worked up over the Annan
letter. Elizabeth Philipps, whose family was living in Newton,
Mass., at the time that her 20-year-old daughter, Sarah, was
killed, believes some relatives are spending too much time and
energy on the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Philipps said the families have no right to see the letter,
which she considers private, diplomatic correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking Nelson Mandela what he told Khadafy,'' she
said, referring to the former South African president's efforts to
get Khadafy to hand over the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
   More important, said Philipps, is making sure that Khadafy
complies with the conditions set out in UN resolutions, namely that
he cooperate fully with the trial, renounce terrorism, and
compensate the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   But Philipps said her husband shares the cynicism of other
families. Ervin Philipps, a Jew who spent the first six years of
his life fleeing the Nazis in Europe, ``finds it difficult to
believe in the genuineness of this process,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So cynical is Ervin Philipps, she said, that he would not join
her to observe the first few weeks of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels that there are so many opportunities for the
governments to control information,'' Elizabeth Philipps said. ``He
feels that if the British, Scottish, and Americans don't want
something to come out, it won't come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said she and other relatives would fight to see that the
investigation goes up the chain of command in Libya.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Cohen has already begun to despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khadafy said on TV the other day that he had won. In a ghastly
way, Khadafy is being more honest than our own government,'' said
Cohen Thursday, standing outside the courtroom because she could
not bear to hear grisly testimony describing how the bodies of
victims rained down on the little town of Lockerbie on the night of
Dec. 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're watching at this trial is political theater,'' said
Cohen. ``Our government is betraying us for oil. This is about
money, pure and simple. I think it's disgraceful that our
government has capitulated to terrorism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
