<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, May 14)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending April 29 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. WE'LL MEET AGAIN, by Mary Higgins Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $7.99.) A woman tries to free herself
</P>
<P>
   of people's suspicion that she murdered her
</P>
<P>
   husband.
</P>
<P>
   2. CARNAL INNOCENCE, by Nora Roberts. (Bantam, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A concert violinist visiting Innocence, Miss.,
</P>
<P>
   becomes enamored of a man suspected of being a serial
</P>
<P>
   killer.
</P>
<P>
   3. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager finds help and caring in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town.
</P>
<P>
   4. BLACK FRIDAY, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A secret militia lays siege
</P>
<P>
   to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   5. FORTUNE'S HAND, by Belva Plain. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young attorney's ideals are tested when he joins a
</P>
<P>
   prominent law firm.
</P>
<P>
   6. TOM CLANCY'S NET FORCE: Night Moves, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Computer terrorism in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   8. JOINING, by Johanna Lindsey. (Avon, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1214, an Englishwoman changes her feelings
</P>
<P>
   about her partner in an arranged marriage.
</P>
<P>
   9. ON MYSTIC LAKE, by Kristin Hannah. (Ballantine, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman who has been betrayed by her husband is reunited
</P>
<P>
   with her first love.
</P>
<P>
   10. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British boy, neglected
</P>
<P>
   by his relatives, finds his fortune attending a school
</P>
<P>
   for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) WORST FEARS REALIZED, by Stuart Woods. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) A police officer turned lawyer seeks a serial killer
</P>
<P>
   he once knew.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE BLUEST EYE, by Toni Morrison. (Plume, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of an 11-year-old black girl _ pregnant by her
</P>
<P>
   father _ who prays for blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   13. A NEW SONG, by Jan Karon. (Penguin, $12.95.) A
</P>
<P>
   clergyman and his wife move 600 miles, creating new
</P>
<P>
   friendships and maintaining old ones.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE DEVIL'S TEARDROP, by Jeffery Deaver. (Pocket Star,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) On Dec. 31, 1999, a diabolical scheme involving
</P>
<P>
   a robotic assassin threatens Washington.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) HUSH MONEY, by Robert B. Parker. (Berkley, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   The private eye Spenser encounters racial, sexual and
</P>
<P>
   academic politics when a black professor is implicated in
</P>
<P>
   a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   3. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $15.) A presentation of superstring
</P>
<P>
   theory, which attempts to mediate between
</P>
<P>
   quantum mechanics and general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   6. BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   An American remembers a spring and summer spent in the
</P>
<P>
   romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) SPONTANEOUS HEALING, by Andrew Weil. (Fawcett,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95; Ballantine, $7.99.) How the body heals itself. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) TRAVELING MERCIES, by Anne Lamott. (Anchor, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A chronicle of the author's journey toward faith.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) THE ONION'S FINEST NEWS REPORTING, edited by
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dikkers and Robert Siegel. (Three Rivers, $16.)
</P>
<P>
   A collection of humor pieces.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) REACHING TO HEAVEN, by James Van Praagh.
</P>
<P>
   (Signet, $7.50.) A ``renowned medium'' discusses
</P>
<P>
   death, the spirit world and reincarnation.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL III, compiled by
</P>
<P>
   Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   3. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways
</P>
<P>
   to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. ORGANIZING FROM THE INSIDE OUT, by Julie Morgenstern.
</P>
<P>
   (Owl/Holt, $14.) How to organize your home, your office
</P>
<P>
   and your life.
</P>
