<P>
   Three former judges, doing time at a federal prison in
</P>
<P>
   Florida, concoct a lucrative mail scam that goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE BLUEST EYE, by Toni Morrison. (Knopf, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of an 11-year-old black girl _ pregnant by
</P>
<P>
   her father _ who prays for her eyes to turn blue.
</P>
<P>
   8. BEOWULF, translated by Seamus Heaney. (Farrar, Straus
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Giroux, $25.) A new rendering of the Anglo-Saxon
</P>
<P>
   epic by a Nobel Prize-winning Irish poet.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE HEIR, by Johanna Lindsey. (Morrow, $24.) A young
</P>
<P>
   woman taking part in the coming-out season in London
</P>
<P>
   experiences a forbidden romance.
</P>
<P>
   10. RAVELSTEIN, by Saul Bellow. (Viking, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The life and death of a brilliant professor (modeled
</P>
<P>
   on Allan Bloom) who writes a best-selling book.
</P>
<P>
   11. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   12. HUGGER MUGGER, by Robert B. Parker. (Putnam, $23.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The private eye Spenser is hired to protect a 2-year-
</P>
<P>
   old colt who may be the next Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   13. DAUGHTER OF FORTUNE, by Isabel Allende. (HarperCollins,
</P>
<P>
   $26.) A young woman from a British colony in Chile joins
</P>
<P>
   the 1849 California gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   14. HORSE HEAVEN, by Jane Smiley. (Knopf, $26.)
</P>
<P>
   The world of horse racing, as seen from the varied
</P>
<P>
   perspectives of humans and thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   15. CAROLINA MOON, by Nora Roberts. (Putnam, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman returns to the town where she grew up and where
</P>
<P>
   her best friend was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom. (Doubleday,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of his weekly visits
</P>
<P>
   to his old college mentor, who was near death.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE CASE AGAINST HILLARY CLINTON, by Peggy Noonan.
</P>
<P>
   (ReganBooks/HarperCollins, $24.) A former Reagan
</P>
<P>
   speechwriter calls the first lady to account. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. THE MILLIONAIRE MIND, by Thomas J. Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrews McMeel, $26.95.) An analysis of the people
</P>
<P>
   who make up America's financial elite.
</P>
<P>
   4.(x) THE ROCK SAYS ..., by the Rock with Joe Layden.
</P>
<P>
   ReganBooks/HarperCollins, $26.) A memoir by a
</P>
<P>
   professional wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   5. TRUTH AT ANY COST, by Susan Schmidt and Michael
</P>
<P>
   Weisskopf. (HarperCollins, $26.) Two journalists
</P>
<P>
   examine Kenneth Starr's investigation of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   6. FAIR BALL, by Bob Costas. (Broadway, $21.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The sportscaster's critique of major-league baseball
</P>
<P>
   and his proposals for improving the game.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE MEASURE OF A MAN, by Sidney Poitier.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperSanFrancisco, $26.) The movie actor's spiritual
</P>
<P>
   autobiography.)
</P>
<P>
   8. CYBILL DISOBEDIENCE, by Cybill Shepherd with
</P>
<P>
   Aimee Lee Ball. (HarperCollins, $26.) A memoir by
</P>
<P>
   the film and television actress.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) 'TIS, by Frank McCourt. (Scribner, $26.) An Irish
</P>
<P>
   immigrant gets used to life in America: a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   10. A HEARTBREAKING WORK OF STAGGERING GENIUS, by
</P>
<P>
   Dave Eggers. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23.) A young
</P>
<P>
   man's account of raising his 8-year-old brother
</P>
<P>
   after their parents died just weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   11. JONBENET: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation,
</P>
<P>
   by Steve Thomas with Don Davis. (St. Martin's, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A former Boulder police detective who worked on the case
</P>
<P>
   presents his interpretation of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE ART OF HAPPINESS, by the Dalai Lama and
</P>
<P>
   Howard C. Cutler. (Riverhead, $22.95.) What Buddhism
</P>
<P>
   and common sense tell us about everyday problems.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   14. CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 1, by Neale Donald
</P>
<P>
   Walsch. (Putnam, $19.95.) The author addresses
</P>
<P>
   questions of good and evil, guilt and sin. (b)
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) THE TIPPING POINT, by Malcolm Gladwell.
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $24.95.) A journalist's study of
</P>
<P>
   social epidemics, otherwise known as fads.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. EATING WELL FOR OPTIMUM HEALTH, by Andrew Weil. (Knopf,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) A physician's guide to food, diet and nutrition. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. TEN THINGS I WISH I'D KNOWN _ BEFORE I WENT OUT INTO
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL WORLD, by Maria Shriver. (Warner, $19.95.) Life
</P>
<P>
   lessons from the anchorwoman. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. SOUL STORIES, by Gary Zukav. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $24.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways in which an understanding of the soul can transform
</P>
<P>
   one's life. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. WHO MOVED MY CHEESE? by Spencer Johnson. (Putnam,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) How to deal with changes at work and in life
</P>
<P>
   in general. (b)
</P>
