<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1356 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CELLPHONES-CRIME-RE     05-08 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CELLPHONES-CRIME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLULAR PHONES: THE WEAPON OF CHOICE FOR SELF-DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of cellular telephones, and you perhaps conjure up
thoughts of the man at the movie whose pocket starts ringing at a
gripping moment of drama, teen-agers chatting in front of their
school or the woman at the video store reading movie titles to her
jaded friend.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials in New York City had a different idea.
Responding to the killings of nine livery cabbies this year, they
announced that a program originally designed to distribute cell
phones to potential crime victims would be expanded to include the
drivers. The program, which was first devised for victims of
domestic violence, gave away 500 phones, all programmed to dial
911.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly viewed as a luxury item, these phones have become
commonplace in the last 15 years, and since the early 1990s they
have increasingly been regarded as an all-purpose cure-all for
individual safety. Today the notion of being wired in the
electronic age is shared not only by parent and child, but also by
salesman and client, cop and felon. Less certain is whether people
are really connected, really secure, or merely think they are.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, the Arizona Foundation for Women is sponsoring a
local drive to give cellular phones to victims of domestic abuse.
In Winthrop, Maine, police have programmed cell phones to dial 911
and the friends and relatives of women who have been attacked by
their spouses and companions. In 1994, the New York Police
Department gave phones to crime-watch volunteers in two dangerous
parks. ``We don't need knives and guns and Mace,'' Michael Julian,
the department's chief of personnel, said at the time. ``We need a
way to call for help.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maryland at College Park offers discounts to
students wanting to buy such phones. In part, the program was
established for the safety of the students, university officials
say. Parents also often give phones to children heading off to
college.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Davitt, a spokesman for the district attorney's office in
Brooklyn, where a recent rise in murders has been linked to
domestic violence, said such phones were not the answer to every
problem. But, Davitt added, ``For a victim, it removes the
isolation and the terror that often assists the perpetrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these crimes happen one on one,'' he added, ``but this
puts a kind of electronic third person in the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, more than 80 million Americans have purchased cell
phones. A recent federal report noted that the sense of security
offered by cell phones is a major factor in the accelerated growth
of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500,000 calls are placed to 911 and other emergency
numbers through cell phones each month in the United States,
according to industry reports. And nearly half the callers say they
have used the phones to report crime, car trouble, drunk drivers or
medical emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   But to Fernando A. Mateo, president of the New York state
Federation of Taxi Drivers, New York City's effort to get the
devices to each livery cab driver is an example of a good idea gone
too far and a waste of energy and resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have someone in the car with a gun to your head,''
Mateo said last week, ``for you to dial 911 and be able to speak
will be pretty tough. By the time the drivers finish answering all
the questions, they will be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, argue that the presence of cell phones in the
cabs might discourage criminals from singling out drivers, who are
being required to install bulletproof partitions that separate the
front seat of the car from the back.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal sociologist at San Diego State University, William C.
Kennedy, said perception in crime fighting is often as important as
reality, noting that cell phones make people feel safer _ whether
on highways and in alleys _ and may make criminals more hesitant to
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that once a crime is under way, the phones often do
little more than create ``a false impression of safety.'' Some
people ``say they would never walk down a certain street without
their cell phone,'' he said. ``Unless you are going to use it has a
hammer, it is probably not going to do you much good.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most criminals act quickly, preventing people from using their
phones to call for help, he said. The phones are most effectively
used to report crimes being committed against another person,
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   To many young people, a cellular phone is the latest high-tech
toy offering entree into the cool club, much like the beeper craze
of the last decade. But others see it is as essential for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Jaimie Kent, a 21-year-old Duke University junior from River
Vale, N.J., bought her cell phone about four years ago, around the
same time she received her driver's license. ``It was mainly a
safety thing _ just when I was driving on the highways by myself,''
Kent said in an interview last week. ``I could call if my car broke
down.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 3, 1999, while home on winter break, Kent was driving on
a rural road when, she said, she ``literally got a stomach flu that
came over me as I was driving home and I started to pull over to
stop, and I blacked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The next thing she remembered was the sound of tapping.
``Someone was knocking on my window, I woke up, and she was able to
use my cell phone to call my mom,'' Kent said. It took all the
strength she could muster, Kent added, to give her Good Samaritan
the telephone number to reach Kent's mother, who came to get her.
</P>
<P>
   Kent understands the limitations of her phone, she said. But
regardless of whether it will protect her from a criminal, she says
she sees it, in many ways, as her digital security blanket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8708 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-MEDIA-TECH-REVIEW-N     05-08 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEDIA-TECH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMMING THE FLOW OF FREE INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing like a blank screen to spark one's imagination.
It is the Rorschach test of the information age. And never more so
than last week, when the ABC channel on Time Warner cable systems
in seven markets went blank.
</P>
<P>
   ABC devotees in 3.5 million homes, confronted with a blue screen
and scrolling Time Warner propaganda, may have thought about the
celebrities they would not see. Marketers of satellite dishes
probably contemplated fatter sales figures. And federal lawmakers
and regulators could ponder how to prevent the gatekeepers of the
information castle from pulling up the drawbridge and leaving the
public outside.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, for those who have believed in
technology's implied promise of an information utopia, in which
people can see or hear or read whatever they want (and show or tell
or write whatever they want), it was an uncomfortable reminder: the
more information available, the more places in which it is
available, the more the logic of economics and egos will come into
play to restrict it.
</P>
<P>
   As Floyd Abrams, the noted First Amendment lawyer, said in a
speech to the Mercer Law School in Georgia in March,
``paradoxically, the effect of more information becoming more
available more quickly may be less information being made public at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the evidence for Abrams' paradox. Last week, to gain
leverage in its contract dispute over the terms under which it
could carry ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co., Time Warner
pulled the plug on ABC's signal.
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations _ Disney was seeking to make its Disney
Channel part of Time Warner's basic service and to get the cable
systems to carry its Toon Disney and Soap channels _ Disney
sometimes engaged in brinkmanship. In the Houston market, Disney
came within minutes of letting Time Warner's right to carry its
programming lapse. If it had done so, it would have pulled the plug
on itself.
</P>
<P>
   Disney was offering more programming (which in turn would bring
it more advertisements and more revenue). Time Warner's cable
system is capable of carrying scores of channels. But both media
giants, under the terms of the laws, regulations and contracts
governing their business, could serve as gatekeepers and black out
the signal. More information, or less? Or more information and more
choke points where it can be shut off?
</P>
<P>
   In other situations, the promise of open access to free
information has also produced a backlash:
</P>
<P>
   _ APBNews.com, a Web site specializing in covering crime stories
and the legal system, filed a Freedom of Information Act request
for all the financial disclosure statements filed by federal
judges. At first, the financial disclosure committee of the
Judicial Conference of the United States rejected the request,
citing judges' concerns that unstable or unsavory people could
obtain their addresses or the names of family members. In March,
the Judicial Conference ruled that the reports could not be
withheld ``simply because they are going to be placed on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Associated Press, Reuters and three other international
news agencies preparing to cover the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney
were asked in January if they would wait an hour before making
results available to commercial Web sites, including their own, and
if they would credit IBM and Swatch when reporting the results. The
AP argued that the results are raw data, not subject to copyright
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Servan-Schreiber, the director of communications and
new media for the International Olympic Committee, withdrew the
requests for the time being. He maintains that copyright
protections extend to ``the tabulation'' of results, if not the
results themselves. ``The agencies want to take the real-time
results and resend it, with no value added, to other Web sites _
and give us no compensation,'' he said. ``And those Web sites would
be competitive with our Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Association of Research Libraries and various teachers'
organizations are fighting legislation that would provide
electronic databases with copyright-like protections. Leslie
Harris, a lawyer who represents some teacher groups, said, ``You
want protections to encourage creation of intellectual property,
but you also want to encourage dissemination of information in a
free society.'' She added, ``As we migrate online, the traditional
ability of my clients to say, `Great article on Martin Luther King
Day; I'll make 15 copies for my class' may not be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, laws governing intellectual property and freedom
of information overlap with the laws governing information
distribution systems and the antitrust laws. Which is not
surprising, since a basic premise of the information age is that
information itself has economic value.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, it is a matter of civic interest if television viewers
are barred from receiving ABC News programming. The issue for the
Federal Communications Commission, though, was not the free flow of
information, but the fact that the plug was pulled during sweeps
month, when stations measure their audiences to determine what to
charge advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   If a city council wants to force a cable carrier to carry any
Internet service provider, it is a matter of business regulation.
(Federal judges in Oregon and Virginia have come to opposite
conclusions on the propriety of such actions.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it is a matter of copyright law if the
National Football League objects when a reporter from The St. Paul
Pioneer Press gives real-time coverage on a Vikings game via the
newspaper's Web site. And a matter of competition, since the NFL
also has its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article in Release 1.0, Esther Dyson's technology
newsletter, the Harvard law professor Lawrence Lessig said: ``The
original architecture of the Net gave great freedom to perfect
competition. But we're seeing an erosion of that freedom now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 0949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
