<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-AIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBEKI TEMPERS AIDS STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA _ Scorned internationally for his baffling response to
an epidemic that is ravaging the African continent, and his own
country, President Thabo Mbeki convened a conference of experts
worldwide to debate whether, in fact, the human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV, causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are faced with a catastrophe,'' Mbeki told scientists in an
opening address Saturday. ``You can't respond to a catastrophe
merely by saying, `I will do what is routine.' You respond to a
catastrophe in a way that recognizes the fact that you are facing a
catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mbeki, reaching beyond the routine has meant challenging the
applicability of Western anti-AIDS drugs to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   For critics, Mbeki's stance has amounted to delay and denial in
the face of an epidemic that has reached millions of adults across
much of southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the first day of debate, in a conference that
brought together some of the world's most respected AIDS
authorities, among them some with dissenting views on treatment,
participants voiced cautious optimism that a consensus was emerging
on the link between HIV and AIDS that would allow Mbeki a way out
of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disease has ever been so well understood. We have the
entire genetic code for this virus,'' said David Scondras, a former
Boston city councilman who took part. ``If this allows Mbeki to
move on, it will have been worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's response to the epidemic has set the tone across
southern Africa, the center of the AIDS pandemic. More than 2
million sub-Saharan Africans die each year of AIDS, the United
Nations says. In South Africa the virus infects 1,700 new people
each day. By December 2001, the UN estimates, Africa will have 13
million AIDS orphans.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Mbeki instructed every member of his Cabinet to
develop AIDS strategies and wore the AIDS ribbon conspicuously.
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki stunned even his own health minister in October,
announcing in a speech that AZT, one of the most commonly
prescribed anti-retroviral treatments worldwide, was too toxic for
his government to provide, despite findings from within his own
scientific community that it safely blocked transmission of HIV
from pregnant women to their unborn children.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Mbeki began courting a small and disparate
group of scientists who have rejected the mainstream scientific
view that HIV resulted in AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Defending that position in a letter to Western leaders last
month, Mbeki likened condemnation of that dissident view on AIDS
treatment to persecution by the Spanish Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The health minister, Manto Tshabalala-Msimang, said the purpose
of considering every viewpoint was to find the most suitable
response to the disease in Africa, where malnutrition and poverty
are rife.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics speculate that debates about toxicity and the workings
of HIV mask a different concern: the high cost of anti-AIDS drugs.
It costs abut $20,000 per year to treat one patient with AZT,
according to Scondras, a figure that is far beyond the reach of
African budgets.
</P>
<P>
   There were hints at the conference that the South African
government may be trying to move beyond the controversy it created.
Mbeki's speech, said Malegapuru Makgoba, head of South Africa's
Medical Research Council, included the president's clearest
acknowledgment yet of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki went to lengths to spell out government initiatives to
combat AIDS. Government papers issued to each participant,
meanwhile, dealt less with what causes AIDS than with how to stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the conference, which ended Sunday, considered
three areas of discussion: prevention, treatment, and how HIV
spreads in Africa. Over the next six weeks, the participants will
continue a discussion online, with a view to making policy
recommendations when they reconvene in early July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
