<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8715 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      05-08 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS BASK IN NETHERLANDS' THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM _ In Holland, old Canadian soldiers never die. They
just come back here every five years.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, 55 years after he helped liberate Amsterdam and the
rest of the Netherlands, Sam Shore, 79 years old, put on his old
brown uniform, pinned on his medals, and sat in the back of a
vintage Jeep with his old army buddy, Howard Lyons, to be driven
over the winding canals of this great Dutch city.
</P>
<P>
   Every five years, Shore, Lyons, and hundreds of other Canadian
veterans return for a parade on National Liberation Day in the
Netherlands. Dutch people line the streets and applaud as they pass
in open-top military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch shout ``Thank you!'' and step forward to shake the
Canadians' hands. Middle-aged and elderly women frequently step
from the curb to hand the veterans tulips, and sometimes to kiss
them. Even toddlers in strollers wave at the old men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dutch people are very gracious and very appreciative of
what we did,'' said Shore, whose father was the cousin of the
Boston Bruins hockey legend Eddie Shore. ``And we're very
appreciative of the reception they give us every five years. It's
important for us to come back here, especially for the young
people, so they'll remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Menno Nelis agrees with that. As the parade began, the
11-year-old boy climbed into the Jeep and sat between Shore and the
79-year-old Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We study the war in school,'' the boy said. ``I know what
these men did, and I am very thankful to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shore beamed at the boy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Canadian soldiers arrived in Amsterdam on May 5, 1945,
Shore's commanding officer in the Seaforth Highlanders regiment
ordered him to seize control of the telephone exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``A German general surrendered to me. I was just a buck
private,'' Shore said, shaking his head, still amazed at the
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Every May 4, the Dutch observe Memorial Day. At 8 p.m., church
bells toll and nearly everyone in the Netherlands stops to observe
two minutes of silence for those who died in World War II,
especially those who perished in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In Amersfoort, southeast of Amsterdam, an old man got off his
bicycle and bowed his head for two minutes Thursday night. His
image, framed in the fading light, was extraordinarily moving.
</P>
<P>
   On May 5, the anniversary of the liberation, the mood turns from
solemn to festive. But at the heart of everything is a respectful
commemoration of those who died, and of those who saved others from
dying.
</P>
<P>
   Memories are long in Holland, and often painful when it comes to
World War II. When war broke out, the Dutch declared their
neutrality, but the Germans invaded anyway. When the Dutch
resisted, the Germans bombed Rotterdam. The Netherlands quickly
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Though overwhelmed by the military power of the Third Reich, the
Dutch did not lie down. When the Nazis arrested 450 Jews in
Amsterdam in 1941, dockworkers went on strike. The sculptor Mari
Andriessen commemorates that stand with her famous ``Dokwerker
Monument,'' a revered memorial here on the Jonas Daniel
Meijerplein. At the Verzetsmuseum, the exploits of the Dutch
Resistance are accorded an honored place.
</P>
<P>
   By 1942, the Germans began deporting Holland's Jews to the
concentration camps. Many Jews tried to hide, and some were hidden
by ``righteous Gentiles,'' as they are known.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1942, Anne Frank, her family, and another family of
Dutch Jews hid in a small apartment behind a revolving bookcase at
the rear of a house at 263 Prinsengracht. Anne Frank was 13 when
she began writing her famous diary. She made her last entry in
August 1944, a few days before her family was arrested. She died
seven months later in the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp. Anne
Frankhuis, the museum dedicated to her memory, is also a place of
honor in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans punished the Dutch for their defiance, cutting off
food during 1944 and 1945. Thousands died in what the Dutch call
the ``Hunger Winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Verloop was a skinny, malnourished 13-year-old when the
Canadians rolled into Amsterdam. Every five years, Verloop turns
out to greet and thank his liberators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans had capitulated, but we hadn't seen any allied
troops until the Canadians arrived,'' he said, standing on the
Leidseplein as the old soldiers rode by. ``As a boy, I was so happy
when they came into Amsterdam because it was then that I realized I
would live.''
</P>
<P>
   Verloop said the small parade is something that most Dutch
people hold dear, but it is getting smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, because every five years there are fewer of them,''
he said. ``They're dying off.''
</P>
<P>
   In the back of their Jeep, Sam Shore and Howard Lyons both
acknowledged this could be their last reunion in Amsterdam. Shore
said he is at peace with himself and his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dutch teach their children about the war, about the
suffering and the sacrifice,'' Shore said.
</P>
<P>
   He looked down at 11-year-old Menno Nelis and put a comforting
arm around the boy. The boy smiled up at his 79-year-old hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried,'' the old soldier said, using his other arm
to wave to the crowd. ``We'll never forget these people. And
they'll never forget us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of the Globe's London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
