<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for love in all the wrong e-mail
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ You should never, never underestimate the
damage the words, ``I love you'' can do. Didn't your mama ever tell
you this? Didn't your roommate? Hasn't some bleary eyed guy on a
barstool who showed no evidence of having changed his clothes or
bathed for three days?
</P>
<P>
   How many times must experience prove this wisdom true?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, more than a million people all around the world
learned this harsh lesson anew. Everywhere in the global computing
village, computer systems, servers, individual hard drives and
Internet e-mail systems have been messed up and shut down. All
because of a virus _ a worm, actually; a visual basic script, if
you want to get technical _ carrying the alluring words
``ILOVEYOU'' squished together on its subject header.
</P>
<P>
   If you open this e-mail, you will find an attachment that seems
to be a mash note. It says ``LOVE-LETTER-FOR-YOU.TXT.VBS.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are using Microsoft Outlook and click on that attachment
_ as some 1.5 million people around the world have _ a tiny,
10-byte series of commands go to work corrupting Outlook, your
Internet browser and your operating system. It will peek into your
address book and send copies of itself to everyone listed there. It
will overwrite the picture and music files on your hard drive. It
will mess with the files that run Windows. It will change your
browser's start page. It will do everything but go into your
refrigerator, drink all the beer and leave the empties for someone
else to throw away.
</P>
<P>
   And this is happening because millions of people think somebody
out there loves them and is finally sharing those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   This is too sad. We are a planet of chumps.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this virus more insidious than its predecessors is
not only sophisticated programming, but good timing and
salesmanship. Past viruses had hokey and unconvincing headers. VERY
IMPORTANT MESSAGE!!! OPEN NOW! LOOK AT THIS! WIN BIG PRIZES! They
looked like junk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   This one, however, aims right at the heart. It exploits the
suspicion that somewhere out there, someone is pining for you. It
preys on the misapprehension that some past meaningless
conversation was actually a come-on. It practices on the deeply
held belief that since it's spring, new action is around the
corner. It exploits the arrogance of those who believe several
people are hot for them.
</P>
<P>
   And since the return address seems to be from someone who has
you in his or her address book, the illusion is even more
convincing. The poor sucker thinks: ``I knew she had it for me, but
why did she e-mail this as an attachment?'' A click of the mouse
and another fool's paradise is shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the unbelievable spread of the virus is that
few people believe virus warnings. The average e-mail inbox is
stuffed with unsolicited advertising, bad jokes, urban myths, and
bogus virus warnings. Roughly in that order. That means many people
who were warned weren't helped. They deleted the advice without
reading it.
</P>
<P>
   A planet of Internet users is looking for love in all the wrong
places. If the worm weren't so destructive _ damage estimates are
as high as $1 billion this would be funny. Or maybe reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   It seems some of the smartest and best-paid people around the
globe are not too sophisticated to avoid falling for The Old Fake
Love Note Trick. Sending a fake love note to engineer a comeuppance
is a prank so old it was shopworn when Shakespeare used it. And
used it and used it.
</P>
<P>
   The best pranks don't grow old, they just go global.
</P>
<P>
   The virus proves that even in our cynical age, many people scan
their e-mail expecting love notes. Stupid, but still sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the virus claims to be a joke in its heading.
That won't work. E-mail jokes are as common as anti-virus notices.
It doesn't use the magic words. We are willing to take dumb risks
for love. But not for jokes. Not generally.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
