<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children learn good behavior by parents' example
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The Miami Senior High School class of 1951
was the first to hold commencement ceremonies in the new Dade
County Auditorium. My boyfriend Jimmy picked me up in his '39
Mercury coupe. His cap and gown were in the back seat. I wore mine,
and as we headed east on Flagler Street, I swiveled the rear-view
mirror to fiddle with the tassle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it flat,'' Jimmy reminded me. ``Remember what we were
told in assembly.'' I remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mortarboards are to be worn flat _ level with the ground,''
the dean had pronounced. ``Graduation is a solemn ceremony and your
parents will be watching. Walk tall, be proud, and above all, don't
get cute with your cap. It was not designed to be cocked over one
ear or shoved onto the back of the head. It is to be worn with
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   All of us knew the textbook definition of that word. DIGNITY:
bearing, conduct, or speech indicative of self-respect or
appreciation of the formality or gravity of an occasion. But we
were still struggling with the concept.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, football games were not dignified occasions.
Miami's Orange Bowl rocked with our screams as we jumped up and
down, imploring the god of the spheroid to bless us with just one
more touchdown so we could leave arch-rival Lee of Jacksonville,
eating our dust.
</P>
<P>
   After-game ``stomps'' in the east patio were a semi-dignified
affair. When we weren't jitterbugging to Glenn Miller's ``String of
Pearls'' or slow-dancing to ``Moon Over Miami,'' we were drinking
Cokes and checking out the week's newest couples, and generally
goofing around.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers always erupted when the football players, freshly
showered and hyped from another win, strode in from the field
house. That was about as noisy as we got except for the time
somebody tossed Poo Poo Pollack into the tiled fountain in the
center of the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Formal dances and Wednesday morning assemblies called for all
the dignity a teenager could muster. The first because we were
dressed to within an inch of our lives, and the second because we
knew that if we acted up we'd soon be headed for the Dean's office
and kissing our backsides goodbye on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, though they might get goofy with us kids now and then,
mostly behaved with grown-up dignity. We thought it was because
they were ancient and too decrepit to whoop it up. Later, when we
reached that stage with kids of our own, we figured it out.
</P>
<P>
   Dignity is all tied up with self-respect and appropriate
behavior, the latter being the only manner in which folks can
survive in close proximity to one another without throttling the
neighbors over a too-loud stereo, or maiming the kid who
consistently tosses the morning paper behind the holly bush.
</P>
<P>
   My parents used their dignity to teach me values. Mother taught
me it wasn't seemly to pull my dress over my head every time the
kindergarten teacher fussed at me. In like manner, I never saw my
mother do it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Control that temper,'' my father warned, ``or you'll end up
making a fool of yourself every time.'' He set the example, and
eventually I caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the thou-shalt-nots accumulated, and though I
was often bored and frequently annoyed with the instruction, I
followed my parents' lead. It paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, although I'm not sure exactly when, I sprouted
dignity, and when the time came I was able to pass it along to my
son. He says it serves him well.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida's Broward county, the superintendent of schools is
gearing up for this year's graduation by instructing his principals
to have parents wishing tickets to the solemn ceremony sign a
pledge promising to behave themselves. No more noise toys or
airhorns. No more raucous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good start Mr. Supe, but while you're at it, why not ask
the parents to consider honoring their graduates by dressing for
the occasion? Red Dog tee-shirts and half-bared butts belong in
bars _ not at their kids' commencements.
</P>
<P>
   It just ain't dignified.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
