<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Gunning for the White House
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President George W. Bush will be the best buddy guns have had in
the White House in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   We have no less an authority for this intelligence than the
National Rifle Association, which is bragging on its candidate pal
and investing heavily in him and in, it hopes, a Republican
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush himself, this is an awkward moment. With most Americans
favoring the gun controls President Clinton has sought and Vice
President Gore proposes, Bush doesn't want to rasp entirely against
the grain of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But he sure as shootin' doesn't want to risk slowing the money
machine the NRA has cranked up on his behalf or risk giving pause
to the millions of voters the NRA is promising to turn out for him.
</P>
<P>
   So the Bush campaign, by way of trying to show that the
candidate isn't the gun lobby's boy toy, is both touting his
enthusiasm for the Second Amendment and emphasizing a couple of
rare points at which Bush strays from the gunners' party line. He
would raise the age for handgun buyers from 18 to 21 and would ban
imported, high-capacity ammunition magazines.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the lobby easily forgives such trifles,
understanding Bush's need to cling to at least one veil in public.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's sugar-daddy money, however, speaks louder than Bush's
claims to chastity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 and 2000, the NRA has given $537,500 in ``soft money''
to the GOP. Its ante in the 1996 cycle was just $87,725. No NRA
money in those years has gone to the Democratic Party, though some
has supported invidual Democrats. And NRA Executive Vice President
Wayne LaPierre Jr. recently pledged $250,000 more to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA knows what it is buying. Bush has been close to the
lobby for years.
</P>
<P>
   When he was elected governor, the NRA's magazine crowed, ``Gun
Owners Win Big.'' Bush has delivered the big goods the lobby wanted
-- legislation to legalize concealed firearms and a law barring
Texas cities from suing gun manufacturers, as 31 cities and
counties have done elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Congresses have delivered, too, and hoping Republicans will
retain control and Bush will be elected, the gun industry has
broken off settlement negotiations in those lawsuits. The industry
expects President Bush to enact a national ban on lawsuits against
it.
</P>
<P>
   There is testimony to go with money. The NRA's second-ranking
officer has said that with Bush ``we'll have ... a president where
we can work out of their office.''
</P>
<P>
   Kayne Robinson, NRA first vice president and chairman of the
Iowa Republican Party, added, ``If we win, we'll have a Supreme
Court that will back us to the hilt.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, far more to any candidacy than just one
issue, this one tops no list of voter concerns, and personalities
seem to drive elections more than issues anyway. But in a nation
that annually suffers a civil bloodbath like no other, it is a
queer politics that works to swing a whole election on behalf of
the main instrument of that slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
