r f BC-TECH-SAVVY0509-COX     05-08 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to remove Explorer 5.5
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I downloaded Explorer 5.5 and tried it. I no longer wish to use
it. Besides reformatting the hard drive, how do I get rid of it?
</P>
<P>
   _Jim Huntley, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Others are asking, too. Instead of listing the steps for
uninstalling Explorer 5.5 on a PC, we'll steer you to www.help.com.
Click the Internet Explorer link. You'll find a link to uninstall
using the Add/Remove program from your Control Panel. Microsoft's
Web site (www.microsoft.com) also tells how to use Add/Remove to
delete Explorer. Type Explorer 5.5 in the search bar. At the bottom
of the next page, click on ``Next 10 Results (11-20)  &QR;  &QR; '' link. See
``How to Uninstall Internet Explorer 5.5.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Installing an application can put files everywhere,
making the bits and pieces hard to find. Control panels,
extensions, preferences, etc., may have names you wouldn't
associate with the app.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Look for utilities to help uninstall unwanted apps or to
keep a hard drive lean and mean. For the PC, check out Uninstaller
from CyberMedia or CleanSweep Deluxe. And for our Mac loyalists,
Tri-Cleaner 2.02 or SpringCleaning from Aladdin Systems. There are
more. Do your homework.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I'm on Windows 95 and use Internet Explorer. I set Explorer to
reject cookies, but an annoying message keeps asking if I want to
allow them. I click ``No'' repeatedly. It's tiresome. Can you turn
it off? How do you reject cookies without getting a message?
</P>
<P>
   _Marie McIntyre, Monroe, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Browsers have preference settings to let you pick between
always accepting cookies, getting a prompt before accepting
cookies, or blocking them. (Newer browsers have more cookie control
options.) Perhaps your browser is set to prompt you, and that's why
it asks permission. Be aware, some sites won't let you visit if you
disable cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: What are cookies exactly? What they are NOT is edible. No
chocolate chips or sugary sprinkles. Cookies are saved to a text
file on your hard drive and contain information a Web site gathers
from you. They help the Web site recognize you the next time you
drop by. Cookies can save you from retyping a user ID or password,
and they remember on-line purchases. They also track surfing habits
and are used for marketing research.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Making Web life easier is one thing, but some think cookies
muck with your privacy. There are steps you can take if you have
privacy concerns or want to trash cookie clutter. You can delete
your cookie file. It's called cookies.txt on Windows and
MagicCookie on a Mac. Of course, your browser creates a new, empty
one each time.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Freeware and shareware are available to manage and filter
cookies, too. We came across Internet JunkBuster Proxy, Cookie
Crusher and Cookie Pal for the PC, and Cookie Monster, Cookie
Cutter and WebFree for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
