<SLUG> BC-ME2CAM0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Me2Cam forces children out of their seats to play games
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you're concerned with the amount of time your
child spends hunched over a mouse or joystick playing computer
games, you might want to take a look at the Me2Cam Virtual Game
System from Intel Play.
</P>
<P>
   To play games with the system, the child stands in front of the
Me2Cam, a small video camera mounted on top of the computer
monitor, and moves his or her body to control the action on the
screen. The Me2Cam picks up the image of the child and inserts the
moving picture into the animated game action.
</P>
<P>
   A snowboarding game, for instance, requires the child to shift
quickly from side to side to guide a snowboard downhill while
steering around some obstacles and jumping over others. A dancing
game encourages vigorous motion by playing the music faster and
faster as the player dances faster.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with the Me2Cam probably won't give a child as much
activity as playing outdoors, but it's a lot more physical than
most computer games.
</P>
<P>
   The Me2Cam game system features Universal Serial Bus (USB)
connectors, so if your computer is an older model that doesn't have
USB ports, you won't be able to use the system without
modifications.
</P>
<P>
   Set-up is easy. After the programming CD-ROM is inserted,
on-screen instructions lead you through the steps to optimize the
game's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Once the game is turned on and a player is selected, the system
is controlled entirely by body movements. A voice prompt tells the
player how to move to activate various modes of play; no reading is
required.
</P>
<P>
   The Me2Cam Virtual Game System is rated for children 4 years old
or older. The games are simple and easy to learn, but they may not
hold the interest of teens or young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Currently only one CD-ROM containing five games is available,
but Intel Play likely will offer more games in the future if the
system catches on. The video camera that comes with the system is
similar to cameras used for sending video snapshots online, but the
programming CD only includes software for using the camera with the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The system sells online at www.shopmattel.com for $69.95 and is
available at software and office supply merchandisers for about the
same price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
