<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY0509-COX     05-08 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net is revolutionary, but doesn't change life's basics
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You'd think, from reading the newspaper and listening
to the TV, that the Internet has changed everything. There are new
rules for marketers. The way we communicate with friends and
co-workers is changing. In short, the Internet has been a
combination of the hydrogen bomb, the Salk vaccine for polio and
Mother Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   The temptation with any important new technology is to stop
seeing shades of gray and to assume _ because it is new _ that
everything we knew up until then is wrong. So, depending on what
you do for a living, you may think that newspapers as we know them
will vanish, retail stores will become little more than kiosks
where you'll order things from the Internet, doctors will make
house calls by telecommunicating to your computer, and life will
become so virtual that it will be hard to tell if it's Uncle Fred
or Memorex.
</P>
<P>
   Look, the Internet is a big deal. It has changed things, but
it's shortsighted, naive and human to think it has somehow
short-circuited common sense. In fact, there's strong evidence for
the argument that _ now that the hysteria is dying some _ the old
rules haven't been suspended at all.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with e-commerce. Two years ago, you were being told
that starting any kind of a dot-com was like having a license to
print money. And the stock market and venture capitalists bore that
out. Twentysomethings started dot-coms right and left, became
millionaires, and their stunning successes indicated that commerce
was forever changed. Nowadays, you are seeing some of these
companies fall out of favor as Rule One of the marketplace begins
to reassert itself: Sooner or later you have to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the e-commerce boom, there were serious and dark
worries that the Internet would somehow destroy society _ with
mankind crawling back into caves, this time into electronic ones.
Instead of going out to eat, we'd munch cold pizza by the computer
monitor; instead of holding conversations with each other, we'd
have computer chats; and reality itself would blur as the
difference between a real person and a virtual human narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   But the last time I went to a restaurant, I had to wait for a
table. The last time I was at a movie, I saw real people holding
hands. The Internet has become _ as it should have _ just another
way to talk, another way to set a date for the movies. Sure, there
are people who live online, but before the Internet there were
people who lived on the phone. There have always been people who
overdo things, people who don't have healthy lives. It's possible
to get lost in a virtual world, but most of us are still doing fine
living our lives out where the sun shines.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. The Internet is a big deal, is changing
business and society, but _ as during the time of the advent of the
telephone network _ those changes are mostly taking place within
the framework of the world that already existed.
</P>
<P>
   Stop for a moment and tell me one brand new thing the Internet
has delivered. Maybe you download your music from the Internet now
instead of buying a CD.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you order the Fruit-of-the-Month Club from the Web page
instead of the catalog ... but the sounds are just as enticing, the
fruit just as sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Life goes on. You can tell me how the Internet has speeded up
things; you can explain how it has offered new avenues for
commerce, new ways to talk to each other, or how it has made the
world smaller and easier to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   But unless you have a brand-new notion that I haven't heard, I
don't expect to hear of any fundamental shift in life as we know
it.
</P>
<P>
   So if you've been worrying that you'd have to reinvent your
business or yourself, stop worrying. Life is still good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
