</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I took my kids to
<TEXT>
the Backstreet Boys concert. I paid for the tickets but told them
if they wanted a souvenir, they would have to use their allowances.
My daughter bought a necklace, and when she opened it the next day,
it was broken. Who can I contact for a replacement? My daughter is
counting on you!
<P>
   _ S. Sohns
</P>
<P>
   A: Send the necklace and a letter with contact information
explaining the problem to Winterland, Andrea Sitchon, 1951 Fairway
Drive, San Liandro, Calif. 94577. Every effort will be made to find
a replacement necklace.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for burgundy berets for a church youth group. Do
you know where I might find some?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Berets are not just for Basques anymore. From the French
resistance in World War II to followers of Che Guevara, the beret
has become a symbol of rebellion. Berets (cotton, wool, knitted _
even reversible faux animal print) are sold by Village Hat Shop at
www.villagehatshop.com (prices begin at $8.95).
</P>
<P>
   Q: My best friend is getting married in France, and neither one
of us knows local traditions. Her fiance' is from Malataverne,
north of Marseilles. What are the traditions of French weddings and
receptions?
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonja Wooten
</P>
<P>
   A: Bons souhaits! There are some bygone customs such as the
coupe de marriage, a double-handled marriage cup used for a toast,
as well as giving bridesmaids fans with mythological theme in Louis
XVI fashion. Another ancient tradition? Scatter laurel leaves
outside the church for luck. French Consulate press attache
Veronique Lhemann notes that in small French towns the couple has a
civil ceremony at the mayor's office. The wedding party then walks
to a church for a religious ceremony. That evening a large
all-night party is held complete with wine (vin d'honneur), food
and dancing. Lhemann remarks children traditionally attend the
French bride and groom, unlike the adult bridesmaids and groomsmen
in the United States. Q: We have an over-friendly bird that spends
hours each day flying directly into a window. The noise is heard
throughout the house. Can you help us save this bird and our
window?
</P>
<P>
   _ Felicity McKevitt
</P>
<P>
   A: This bird sees its own reflection and either thinks this
other bird is competition or a conceivable mate. Your bird is
defending territory or trying to meet a possible prom date. Cover
the window with cardboard to eliminate the reflection or place a
rubber snake or plastic owl on the ledge. In a week or so the bird
will have moved on to disturb another family.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard that shrinking heads involves hot sand, but I
cannot find anything on the process to confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   _ S. Davis
</P>
<P>
   A: Head shrinking is how a conquering tribesman converts the
power of his victim to himself. Currently outlawed, the practice is
historically connected to the Jivaro Indians. The victim's head is
removed and slit down the back to allow the skull to be removed.
The skin is shrunk by placing hot stones or sand in the cavity
until cool. Repeat. The head constricts as the material cools.
During the process, which takes several days, the skin is rubbed
with charcoal dust to keep the victim's avenging soul from
escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for soft winter- wheat flour; it is supposed to
make the lightest biscuits and scones due to its low protein
content.
</P>
<P>
   _ Juliette Miller
</P>
<P>
   A: You can order it from The White Lily Foods Company at (800)
264-5459. A five-pound bag is only $2, plus $5 for shipping. The
soft red winter wheat in this flour is lower in protein and gluten.
Gluten is the protein that makes cakes and biscuits softer and less
gummy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I swim almost every day. My swimsuits only last three months,
and they are getting more and more expensive. I have tried rinsing
in cold water and in a machine in cold on delicate. I have tried
washing by hand once a week with shampoo. My last suit I never
washed (ugh!!), and it still only lasted a few months. How can the
life of a woman's swimsuit be extended?
</P>
<P>
   _ Francine Rosenstein
</P>
<P>
   A: The durability of a swimsuit depends on fabric, not brand,
say the gurus at Speedo, (888) 4-SPEEDO.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion swimsuits, made of weaker fabrics, are for sunbathers,
not swimmers. Lycra suits are for competitive swimmers seeking
speed, not durability. Nylon is a strong fabric often chosen by
those in aggressive activities such as water polo. In chlorinated
water? A polyester suit may work best. Speedo carries a variety of
nylon and polyester suits. Swimsuit care? Rinse your suit
thoroughly with tap water. If a chlorine odor remains, use a little
Woolite. Dry flat. Do not use detergent. Place a towel between your
suit and rough surfaces to prolong suit life. Contact Jane Greig at
P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
