r l BC-NETWATCH0509-COX     05-08 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As download beat goes on, recording industry fights back
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The online music revolution will not be televised.
</P>
<P>
   It's being played out right now on the Web and in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As you read this, thousands, possibly millions, of college
students and other music lovers are downloading recorded music from
the Beatles to the Backstreet Boys from digital download sites such
as MP3.com, or using file-sharing software called Napster
(www.napster.com).
</P>
<P>
   Like Amazon.com, which scored its early success because it was
able to offer a variety of books that no brick-and-mortar store
could stock, the sheer volume of recorded music available on the
Internet is staggering. Digital download fans can pick and choose
and make their own personal music collections.
</P>
<P>
   And every last track, from every last artist, is free _ for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   One student recently told MTV she never buys music anymore, that
she and her roommate just download the songs they want from the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really knows what to do about this. Artists don't want to
alienate their fans, but they do want to make money.
</P>
<P>
   But while music junkies are loading up on their favorite tunes
from MP3.com or Napster, they are bypassing traditional methods of
buying music. They are clogging university networks uploading and
downloading songs. And even though bands like U2 seem to be in the
music business just to fight for human rights and world peace, at
the end of the day, they still want a paycheck. With the digital
download situation as it now stands, that could be endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the parties involved, the Recording Industry Association
of America is the most upset, the most vocal and the most
litigious. The RIAA filed lawsuits against both Napster and MP3.com
for copyright infringement. On April 28, it won a key victory when
a federal judge said MP3.com had violated industry copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is potentially disastrous for MP3.com. The RIAA is
asking for damages that could exceed $6 billion. The New York Post
reported last week that the RIAA is willing to settle with MP3.com
for a cool $100 million. Some reports indicate MP3.com isn't
willing to settle.
</P>
<P>
   But while MP3.com and Napster slug it out in court, users are
still downloading music in higher numbers every day. Lars Ulrich,
drummer for the heavy metal band Metallica, personally delivered a
list of 335,435 Napster users Metallica claims have illegally
obtained the band's music online.
</P>
<P>
   Artists and record companies call this pirating. Users call it
downloading.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Rosenbloum, an entertainment attorney and vice president
of business affairs for the Web site ArtistDirect (www.
artistdirect.com), says downloading even one song to play while
you're surfing the Web is a violation of fair-use laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four factors of fair use,'' Rosenbloum says. ``The
purpose of the work, the nature of the use, the amount of the work
that was taken and whether the use undermines the market for the
original. Whether (digital downloads) undermine the market for the
original is characterized as the most important factor in these
decisions, and its easy to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Napster,'' he continues. ``The ultimate goal of that
company is business. One day, there will be an advertising model.
Even though they don't post the files (Napster allows users to
share their digital files with other users who are logged on at the
same time), the creative works that are available would be worthy
of the highest degree of protection under copyright law. Most
people looking at this would say it very clearly undermines the
market potential for the original.''
</P>
<P>
   For the average, normally law-abiding computer user busy
downloading music, it's time to install that cable modem or
high-speed phone line and get moving if you want to get some free
tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbloum says the major recording labels are working out their
own plans to enter the fray. And once they get online, digital
music is going to cost you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you are going to start seeing over the next six
months is an increasing willingness on the part of the major labels
to compete with what's going on out there,'' Rosenbloum says. ``You
will see continued use of legislation and a combined effort by all
of the major labels to come up with a combined business model to
combat the illegal uses we are seeing now. ``
</P>
<P>
   Even though the RIAA is determined to take its case through the
legal system, Rosenbloum says he's not sure legislation is the
right way to attack this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an outspoken critic of legislation,'' he says. ``Often the
best solution to a conflict is by discussion, negotiation and
mediation. But sometimes legislation is your only option if one
side or the other won't compromise _ especially in this very
complicated area.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
