<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer users on high alert
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Computer systems around the world were attacked last
week by computer viruses, known as ``worms.'' The viruses, which
attacked Thursday and Friday, spread via e-mail and instant
messages in chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   When a computer user opened an infected e-mail and clicked on an
attachment, the virus was unleashed on the user's address books.
</P>
<P>
   The virus was programmed to mail itself to everyone in the
books. The virus also was programmed to attack photo and video
files in the user's computer.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that tens of millions of computers worldwide
were affected by the original bug that arrived Thursday with the
message ``ILoveYou.'' About five copycat viruses appeared on
Friday. Their subject lines claimed to be jokes or about a Mother's
Day gift.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users were told not to open the messages and to delete
them. Police, who believe the ``ILoveYou'' virus started in the
Philippines, were tracking a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   TOO MUCH OR TOO LITTLE RAIN CAUSE PROBLEMS IN ETHIOPIA
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal rains finally have come to the African nation of
Ethiopia. But the rains may do more harm than good for the starving
people of this poor country.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Ethiopia has been gripped by a
terrible drought. Little rain has fallen to nourish crops or
livestock. Thousands of animals and hundreds of people have died.
</P>
<P>
   Now rain is preventing aid agencies from sending in food to help
the starving people. Planes cannot land on the muddy runways and
trucks cannot travel on some muddy roads.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Ethiopian government asked for 836,800 tons of
emergency food to assist an estimated 7.7 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA'S SMOG RATE RISING
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is becoming more like Los Angeles _ and not just because
you're seeing more stars in town.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you might see fewer stars _ in the sky _ as Atlanta's
air becomes filled with more and more smog.
</P>
<P>
   A report by a Georgia Tech researcher shows that smog keeps
increasing in Atlanta and decreasing in Los Angeles. For years, Los
Angeles has had the nation's most polluted air. In Los Angeles, new
rules in the past several years have helped that city improve its
air quality.
</P>
<P>
   Smog is made up of pollutant gases, such as ozone, as well as
tiny particles of soot, dust and metals. Those materials mainly
come from car exhaust, coal-fired power plants and refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
