<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If impact printer makes you happy, just keep using it
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mail from the Windows refuseniks continues rolling in,
both the sweet and the surly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your attitude is typical for the crowd with more money than
sense,'' announces a fellow defending impact printers. He may be
right, but I have so little of either it's hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Panasonic dot-matrix (printer) works with Windows in about
70 percent of the things I need to do, even on graphics without
color. It's faster under DOS than Windows 98, even, and still
faster than Windows driving a HP Deskjet. Please give me a GOOD
reason for discarding it in favor of a slower, more expensive
printer for all my printing.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's that other 30 percent that goes unmentioned in
your diatribe. Further, I never suggested you discard anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you have a tech department to keep upgrading your
equipment and to sort out difficulties, so it costs you personally
little to play the `keep up with Joneses' game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not hardly, and I've never been able to keep up with the
Joneses. The Hatfields or the McCoys, perhaps, but not the Joneses.
And insofar as expense goes, I believe we paid about $550 for our
last dot-matrix printer. You can get an inkjet printer that does a
vastly superior job now for $150 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, inkjets are a lot more expensive to run, and if you
need to do a lot of printing, then a laser is the way to go. But if
you've got an impact printer that does what you need to do, then
far be it from me to suggest you trash it.
</P>
<P>
   Another, gentler fellow reports that ``My wife and adult kids
keep after me to get a new setup rather than just upgrade my old
box and to get the latest Microsoft programs. I don't need 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first computer was an Osborne which included SuperCalc,
WordStar and that big database. I now use Q&AMP;A and just keep
upgrading the spreadsheet and the word processor.''
</P>
<P>
   You mean Q&AMP;A is still around? A fine program it was (or is),
too. My first computer was a Morrow, which of course ran the same
miserable operating system as your Osborne _ CP/M. I've never felt
the same about spreadsheets since I found I couldn't get more than
about a dozen rows of eight cells each into its 64K memory.
</P>
<P>
   And you remember that wonderful Wordstar Catch-22? You'd be
typing along on the Great American Novel, tell it to save your
work, and if you had been careless about watching your floppy disk
space (no hard drives then) it would report there wasn't enough
room to save your work.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Put in a new disk, save to that. Oh, WordStar wouldn't let
you do that. You had to use the disk you'd been working with. You,
my friend, were out of space and out of luck, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate Microsoft because Windows will not allow me to put my
DOS menu program as the first screen when starting,'' this
gentleman continues.
</P>
<P>
   Now, really. That's like hating ``Frankenstein Meets the
Wolfman'' because Bela Lugosi wasn't in it, or loathing Dvorak's
9th Symphony because it doesn't sound like Beethoven's Sixth. Of
course it doesn't allow you to put your DOS menu in place of the
desktop. It's supposed to replace your DOS menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will use my old DOS WordStar to write most of the copy for
my Rotary Club's 144-page catalog for our upcoming Artists of
America Gala Sale and Exhibition,'' he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   You, sir, are hopeless. But I admire you, just as I have a
sneaking admiration for those hardy souls who not only still smoke,
but roll their own.
</P>
<P>
   From Denver comes a note from a fellow puzzled by the recent
report from a PFS Professional File user who said his current date
function now always produces something in the year 1900. His PFS,
he said, prefers the year '27, in an unspecified century.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Finally comes a kind gentleman offering relief to the fellow who
is using a Leading Edge word processing program and was trying to
find an old version of Word for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vandiver says he can probably help you. Get in touch with
him at 76350.1227(at)compuserve.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
