<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, May 9, 2000 are moving today
to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The Miami Senior High School
class of 1951 was the first to hold commencement ceremonies in the
new Dade County Auditorium. My boyfriend Jimmy picked me up in his
'39 Mercury coupe. His cap and gown were in the back seat. I wore
mine, and as we headed east on Flagler Street, I swiveled the
rear-view mirror to fiddle with the tassle.(Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ You should never, never
underestimate the damage the words, ``I love you'' can do. Didn't
your mama ever tell you this? Didn't your roommate? Hasn't some
bleary eyed guy on a barstool who showed no evidence of having
changed his clothes or bathed for three days? How many times must
experience prove this wisdom true? Last week, more than a million
people all around the world learned this harsh lesson anew.
Everywhere in the global computing village, computer systems,
servers, individual hard drives and Internet e-mail systems have
been messed up and shut down. All because of a virus _ a worm,
actually; a visual basic script, if you want to get technical _
carrying the alluring words ``ILOVEYOU'' squished together on its
subject header. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal). MOVED
</P>
