<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available Tuesday after 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH 0509 -- They've done it. They have finally done it.
They have come up with a gimmick to lure men into grocery shopping.
It's called shopping for groceries using Priceline.com, a kind of
win-win lottery that turns buying diapers into a game.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 3-column
color illustration of a man shopping in a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PRICLINE BOX _ A step-by-step guide to ordering groceries.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS _ New in stores this month is a compact stereo system
that can turn your television into a home theater system complete
with a DVD player, Dolby Digital surround sound speakers, a
subwoofer and a digital tuner. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) Art
includes a 1-column color photo of Sony Dream System.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ At the moment, some of the hottest sites on the Web
are auction sites that let you bid on anything from vintage china
and dolls to airline tickets and toothpaste. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GAME CORNER _ For gaming with kids, the original Croc was a fun
romp with lots of eye candy and a cute little backpack-wearing
crocodile. And though the sequel, Croc2, is fun, some unfortunate
changes have robbed the concept of a lot of its zip. (Staff, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes a 1-column color photo of video
game box.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ Viruses are the nuclear bombs of the Internet.
Just as real world bombs are more sophisticated with each new
generation _ computer viruses have moved from being an occasional
pest to stealthy and dangerous critters that can lay waste to your
computer. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1
column color sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   ME2CAM _ If you're concerned with the amount of time your child
spends hunched over a mouse or joystick playing computer games, you
might want to take a look at the Me2Cam Virtual Game System from
Intel Play. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). WITH GRAPHIC. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is James Cummings' gadgets column.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GEAR _ The latest in digital game gear. This week: Sharp
DV-L70U. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDGEAR _ Games for children. This week: Pokemon Stadium.
(Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GAMER _ Games for the console and desktop aimed at the
moderate to advanced gamer. This week: NHL Rock the Rink. (Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Commentary on the impact of the
Internet on our lives. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Mail from the Windows
refuseniks. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: The legality of
downloading recorded music. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Web sites
offering legal help. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SAVVY _ Question and answer column focusing on using
computers and other technology as tools to get jobs done.
(Cleere/Rudd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS _ CLEVELAND _ Daily coverage, as merits, of United
Methodist General Conference in Cleveland. Issues coming up this
week are same-sex blessing, a new TV ad campaign to rival the
Mormons, legislation apologizing for the denomination's past racism
and trying to raise a huge amount of money for historically black
Methodist colleges that include Clark Atlanta University, some
denominational reorganization, and possible resolutions on Elian
Gonzalez and gun control, to name a few. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-DONOR _ An Atlanta man will become a living organ donor
May 12, one of perhaps only a handful of people who've donated a
portion of their liver to a patient who is not a relative. Medical
technology has improved to the point where donations from living
donors are not only possible, but a much lower risk for the donor
and a much higher chance of success for the recipient. A look at
where the technology is and how it's being used. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-STATS _ Numbers of organs donated in 1989 and 1999 by
living and dead donors; numer of people on waiting lists
nationwide; numbers of people who died waiting in 1999. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-WEB _ How you sign up to be an organ donor; why you must
tell your family. Plus web sites for more information. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   THEPILL _ Forty years after oral contraceptives were first
introduced on May 9, 1960, more than 100 million women rely on
them, a study found. The report from he Johns Hopkins School of
Public Health found that the pill was the most popular
contraceptive method in 78 of 150 surveyed countries. Includes
percentage of women who use the pill by country. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN _ A computer-programmed morphine pump provides much greater
pain relief with far lower doses by sending morphine straight to
the central nervous system, and it eases fears of morphine
addiction by taking the patient's decisions out of the equation.
But Dr. Townsend Smith says it's like most other pain treatments in
that it's not helping as many patients as it could be. (Dayton
Daily News). 38. WITH PHOTOS and an ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PAIN-SIDE _ When patients with chronic pain can't find relief
from their physicians, a lot of them turn to alternative
practitioners. Besides highlighting conventional medicine's
limitations, the trend also puts patients at risk if they don't
tell their doctors about alternative therapies that could interact
badly with prescription drugs, university researchers said last
month. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-BEAUTY _ This year's best picture Oscar winner, ``American
Beauty'' arrives on video, (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 3.
</P>
<P>
   GLADIATOR _ With 'Gladiator' expected to pull in big bucks at
the box office, we compare Russell Crowe's new film to earlier big,
bloody sword epics ``Braveheart'' and ``Ben-Hur.'' (BLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   CD-HANSON _ A quick take on Hanson's new cd, the group's first
in three years. Like the single, it's titled ``This Time Around.''
(Harrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN _ Observations on the television industry from
a leading commentator. This week: Will ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire?'' start to cool with audiences? (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Three or four briefs of world and national news,
written for kids to understand. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
