   THEPILL _ Forty years after oral contraceptives were first
introduced on May 9, 1960, more than 100 million women rely on
them, a study found. The report from he Johns Hopkins School of
Public Health found that the pill was the most popular
contraceptive method in 78 of 150 surveyed countries. Includes
percentage of women who use the pill by country. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN _ A computer-programmed morphine pump provides much greater
pain relief with far lower doses by sending morphine straight to
the central nervous system, and it eases fears of morphine
addiction by taking the patient's decisions out of the equation.
But Dr. Townsend Smith says it's like most other pain treatments in
that it's not helping as many patients as it could be. (Dayton
Daily News). 38. WITH PHOTOS and an ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PAIN-SIDE _ When patients with chronic pain can't find relief
from their physicians, a lot of them turn to alternative
practitioners. Besides highlighting conventional medicine's
limitations, the trend also puts patients at risk if they don't
tell their doctors about alternative therapies that could interact
badly with prescription drugs, university researchers said last
month. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-BEAUTY _ This year's best picture Oscar winner, ``American
Beauty'' arrives on video, (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 3.
</P>
<P>
   GLADIATOR _ With 'Gladiator' expected to pull in big bucks at
the box office, we compare Russell Crowe's new film to earlier big,
bloody sword epics ``Braveheart'' and ``Ben-Hur.'' (BLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   CD-HANSON _ A quick take on Hanson's new cd, the group's first
in three years. Like the single, it's titled ``This Time Around.''
(Harrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN _ Observations on the television industry from
a leading commentator. This week: Will ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire?'' start to cool with audiences? (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
