<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0509     05-08 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0509-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game over? That's unlikely, even after `Millionaire' cools
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Red hot has to cool down eventually. Even the
sun could burn out in a billion years or so.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' is sure to cool down a lot
quicker, right? In fact, the hotter the show, the faster it cools.
Maybe. That seems logical, but logic doesn't always apply when it
comes to quirky pop culture explosions. Who knew wrestling would
bounce around the ring so long and the Ninja Turtles would go down
for the count in such short order?
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' has been setting ratings records since it
debuted as a summer experiment last year. Its popularity caught
everybody by surprise, including fashionable host Regis Philbin and
a gaggle of network executives. Now on ABC's schedule three times a
week, ``Millionaire'' is soaring. Last Monday's celebrity edition
raked in almost 40 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Can it stay sky-high, soar even higher, or has it peaked?
</P>
<P>
   ``The week by week ratings may be up or down, but it's still
routinely No. 1, 2 and 3,'' says Anne Elliot, vice president of
marketing and communications for Nielsen Media Research. ``It
rarely budges unless there's a really special episode of something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' has bumped it from the top, but that's been about the
only threat since January, when ``Millionaire'' graduated from
occasional special to full-time series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I have a hunch this red-hot hit won't sustain itself much
longer. I think people will get tired of watching ordinary folks
fret over questions that wouldn't win them a penny of Ben Stein's
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' isn't the first series to start at the top.
``ER'' debuted at No. 1, and six seasons later it's still the
highest-rated drama. So why am I suspicious of the game show's
potential? Well, a drama with a large ensemble cast and multiple
storylines is easier to sustain than a gimmicky contest. ``Mork &AMP;
Mindy,'' on the strength of the hysterically gimmicky Robin
Williams, also debuted at No. 1 and was a huge hit its first
season. But it started to fade the next year. That seems a more
likely trajectory for ``Millionaire,'' though it may not disappear
as quickly as it fades. It could linger for several seasons with
considerably cooler ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me (``Millionaire'') is an indicator of the new TV
environment, where all sorts of trial-and-error balloons are
floated,'' says Horace Newcomb, a University of Texas professor and
a leading authority on prime-time entertainment. ``It leapt up in
part ... because it was something that was new again. I think it
will cool off, but I also think it will stay on. Ten years ago a
show would have been canceled when it cooled, but now I think
there's a place for a show like this to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the increased choices and resulting fragmented
audience have created an environment in which shows don't have to
attract 40 million viewers a week to survive. They can easily get
by with half that.
</P>
<P>
   The cooling process for ``Millionaire'' could start this summer,
when CBS brings on ``Survivor,'' a game show that purports to be a
life-and-death contest with 16 participants living off the land
(and reportedly eating rats and worms) on a Malaysian island. If
nothing else, ``Survivor'' will steal a bit of the buzz from
``Millionaire.'' Fox's cheesy ``Greed'' and NBC's classier but dull
``21'' haven't made a dent in ``Millionaire,'' but they didn't
generate the hype ``Survivor'' is getting.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``Millionaire'' plummets by September or not, ABC, now
the highest-rated network, is thrilled with the show. Millions of
``Millionaire'' viewers have boosted ``The Practice'' from midway
down the Nielsen chart to No. 9 for the season, and the
weak-performing ``20/20 Downtown'' rose to last week's Top 10. Good
work, Reege.
</P>
<P>
   But by running a potentially fast-burning hit Sunday, Tuesday
and Thursday nights, the network may well have mortgaged its
future. ABC, which will unveil its fall lineup in a couple of
weeks, is considering only five sitcom pilots compared with 15 last
year. The network's eggs are lumped in one Regis-held basket.
</P>
<P>
   If I were the programming tsarina (and, as you know, that's my
true calling), I'd keep ``Millionaire'' as an ``event series'' to
run during sweeps, thus tempering the danger of quick burnout. I'd
look for new, innovative entertainment series to diversify. But
even though I'd keep ``Millionaire'' in a limited capacity, I
wouldn't watch it. I'd stick with the far more challenging ``Win
Ben Stein's Money.'' Less money but lots more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
