<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VEGETARIANS (San Francisco) _ Dressed in an oversized banana
suit, Rob Schaff spent Sunday afternoon playing tunes with titles
like ``I Got the Blues 'Cuz I Ain't Got No Greens,'' and ``I Left
My Lettuce Hearts in San Francisco.'' He blared out the moody
melodies as hundreds swarmed around tables sampling meat-free
morsels at VegFest 2000, a celebration organized in part by the San
Francisco Vegetarian Society to promote plant-based diets. And to
revel in plenty of puns. By ANATASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ Big bucks. Boardroom intrigue.
Back room political and publishing deals. The first week of former
political consultant Clint Reilly's antitrust suit to block Hearst
Corp. from buying the San Francisco Chronicle presented an
extraordinary inside look at the intertwined relationship between
the daily newspaper business and politics. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-COLUMN (White Sulphur Springs, W.Va.) _ Land Rover, the
British sport-utility-vehicle maker, has drawn a ``line in the
mud'' with the introduction of a new, entry-level model of its
Discovery II aimed at snagging some sales away from the popular
Jeep Grand Cherokee and other midsize SUVs. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS
III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SUBARU (Undated) _ Is it a car, or is it a sport-utility
with a trunk? That's the big question with the 2000 Subaru Legacy
Outback Sedan, a strange combination of vehicular concepts that
just might catch on with some consumers who have never seriously
considered buying one of those big trucklike things. By G. CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-TIRES (Undated) _ Tires are prone to going flat; all it
takes is a nail, screw or piece of debris to puncture the rubber
and let out the air. What if you could just keep on driving to a
repair shop, where the tire could be repaired safely while you
lounge in the waiting room? That is possible with the Goodyear Tire
Co.'s run-flat tire, known as the EMT _ short for
``extended-mobility tire.'' By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-INTERNET (San Francisco) _ Larry Ellison is breathing
life back into the network computer, reviving a stalled idea he
championed years ago. The Oracle Corp. chairman was expected to
announce Monday the creation of the New Internet Computer Co.,
which will be based in San Francisco and produce a $199 Internet
appliance dubbed the ``NIC.'' By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PAN-AM-GAMES (San Antonio) _ Organizers of San Antonio's bid for
the 2007 Pan American Games are ready to give a boost to the
Dominican Republic, which plays host to the event in 2003. Juan
Antonio Flores, executive director of the San Antonio bid team,
wants to do all he can to make certain the Games in Santo Domingo
rate as a success. By JERRY BRIGGS.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-PEGASUS (Louisville, Ky.) _ Just how many horses will
Fusaichi Pegasus face at the Preakness Stakes on May 20? That is
the question. After listening to the trainers talking about their
charges after the Kentucky Derby, the second leg of the 2000 Triple
Crown could have as few as four horses and most likely won't have
more than eight starters. By LEE SCHIEDE.
</P>
