<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-ADVISORY-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE ADVISORY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special Features. For
purchase information, see end of text.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for New America News Service stories
that are for release Fri., May 5, 2000, or anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA'S BLEAK FUTURE MINUS MEXICAN IMMIGRANTS. The supply of
willing Mexican imigris to the United States will shrink in coming
years. Within a decade, the number of Mexicans illegally entering
the United States will diminish to the point of endangering the
production of our food supply. How? Because illegal aliens
constitute the majority of workers who pick the crops. Columnist
Raoul Lowery Contreras writes that a surge in the Mexican economy,
combined with plunging birthrates and a slower population growth
are the cause. He argues for the creation of a viable guest-worker
program that will legalize people who are willing to come North for
better jobs and higher wages. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-DWINDLING-MEXICAN-IMMIGRANTS-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   SPINELESS HYPOCRITES ARE NOW SECURE WITH ALI. In this excerpt
from Emerge magazine, Terence Moore, a sports columnist at The
Atlantic Journal-Constitution, writes about the change in mood
toward Muhammad Ali. Moore recalls the unfair treatment Ali
received when he changed his name from Cassius Clay to his current
Islamic name, and the indignities Ali suffered when he refused to
be drafted on religious grounds. The columnist asks us to look at
the hypercritical divide between how we treat Ali now, and the way
we treated him then. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-MUHAMMAD-ALI-TURNCOATS-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   LURING LATINOS TO THE GOP FOLD. The term ``Hispanic Republican''
used to be an oxymoron, writes columnist James Garcia. But not
anymore. With national polls suggesting that George W. Bush could
win as much as 40 percent of the Hispanic vote in the presidential
election, Jose Rivera, chairman of the Republican National Hispanic
Assembly, predicts that the ranks of registered Republicans in the
Latino community will grow dramatically in the coming years. A
report. (slugged: BC-NEW-AMERICA-LURING-LATINOS-TO-GOP-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   THE DARK SIDE OF ANGEL ISLAND. A few moths ago, columnist Amy Wu
came across a book, originally published in 1980, titled ``Island:
Poetry and History of Chinese Immigrants on Angel Island.'' The
book is filled with poetry written by hundreds of Chinese
immigrants, who carved their prose into the walls of barracks at a
detention center on Angel Island. The island, which is north of San
Francisco and which has been called the Ellis Island of the West,
was once used as a place to detain nearly 200,000 Chinese between
the years of 1910 and 1940. In this poignant commentary, Wu
describes how the book spurred her to search for those ``ghosts who
penned the poetry.'' In doing so, she realized that what she was
really searching for was a better understanding of herself.
(slugged: BC-NEW-AMERICA-ANGEL-ISLAND-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
