<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-MUHAMMAD-ALI-TURNCOATS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPINELESS HYPOCRITES ARE NOW SECURE WITH ALI  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By TERENCE MOORE  
 &HT;    Of all the retrospectives in the weeks surrounding the turn of
the century, there is one that everybody missed: The Hypocrites of
the Century. Such a distinction goes to millions who suddenly are
wrapping their arms around Muhammad Ali to give him a sloppy hug
instead of a deadly choke.
 &HT;    Tributes to Ali are everywhere, and show no sign of ceasing in
the new millennium. The life story of the former heavyweight
champion was the subject of an ABC made-for-TV movie. A second Ali
movie is expected to air on FOX later this year. While many
publications declared Ali the greatest athlete of the past 100
years, ESPN ranked the former heavyweight champion in third place.
 &HT;    There also is the epidemic of glee that Ali creates whenever he
enters a room. Three times in the past two years, I've seen Ali
generate overflow crowds during his appearances. Some mugged with
Ali for snapshots. Others giggled while he kissed them or their
babies. All of these Ali worshippers were different sizes, colors
and religions. They continued a trend that began after Ali rose
from the Atlanta darkness to fight the Olympic flame in 1996. To
the masses, ``The Greatest'' officially became ``The Greatest Back
Then,'' and thus started an explosion of hypocrisy.
 &HT;    Not long ago, Ali was considered worse than the stuff that
fighters spit into containers between rounds, by many of the same
people who said they tingled after his last Olympic moment.
 &HT;    No, it was worse than that. When the former Cassius Clay became
a regular before cameras and microphones in the early '60s, his
critics began to set a foundation for more than two decades of
hatred for the guy. They didn't like his tongue. He couldn't keep
it from flapping, and they fumed even more when his words were a
combination of brash and prophecy. He predicted that he would shock
the world by whipping the invincible Sonny Liston for the
heavyweight title in 1964 _ and he did.
 &HT;    Shortly thereafter, despising Cassius Clay became a national
obsession when he said he wished to change his ``slave'' name to
Muhammad Ali, after his conversion to Islam. During the three years
that he successfully defended his title nine times after his name
change, The New York Times was among those refusing to call Ali
anything but Clay. Although Sugar Ray Robinson was Ali's boxing
idol, the relationship between the two became strained when
Robinson couldn't bring himself to call him Ali.
 &HT;    Therefore, it wasn't surprising that Ali heard howling from much
of the world after he strained his hernia before his scheduled
rematch with Liston in the winter of 1964. The fight was canceled,
but the howling around Ali continued. In fact, the howling
increased when Ali slammed a short right against Liston's temple
the following spring to end the fight in the first round. It was a
punch so quick and potent that it was nearly invisible to onlookers
as Liston slammed backward against the canvas.
 &HT;    A Rocky Marciano or a Joe Louis would have received praise in
the aftermath. Ali just received grief. That's because Ali was
accused of delivering a punch that never touched his suddenly
lambasted opponent, who was accused of throwing this fight, as well
as his first one against Ali, to get more money with a rematch. The
idea in the minds of his critics was to say nearly anything to
diminish Ali ... or Clay ... or simply ``that guy with the big
mouth.''
 &HT;    There also was the ugliness surrounding Ali's fight against
Ernie Terrell in February 1967. Since Terrell joined the others in
boycotting Ali's new name, Ali spent 15 rounds pounding his
opponent along the way to victory and snarling, ``What's my name?''
 &HT;    Then came the draft incident. In 1967, during the peak of the
Vietnam War, Ali refused to enter the U.S. Army for religious
reasons. A federal court followed the overall mood toward Ali by
delivering the stiffest possible sentence. He was fined $10,000 and
given a five-year prison term. He spent no time in prison after an
appeal, but the State Department revoked his passport. And boxing
commissions wouldn't sanction his fights. Ali was reinstated as a
boxer in 1970, and the U.S. Supreme Court overturned his conviction
in 1971.
 &HT;    He later had three classic wars with Joe Frazier. He also
survived a grueling match against George Foreman. Still, the prime
of Ali's career was snatched away by that federal court. By the
time Trevor Berbick embarrassed Ali into retirement in 1981, he was
finished in more ways than one. He had Parkinson's disease after
years of taking mighty lefts and rights from the Fraziers and the
Foremans.
 &HT;    Now, at 57, Ali rarely speaks in public. When he does, his words
are slurred. Only his hands shake more than his head. He's the
equivalent of a massive teddy bear. So many of those who absolutely
couldn't stand Ali in the past, can't get enough of him now. In
their minds, he can't hurt them anymore _ or they just feel guilty.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (TERENCE MOORE is a sports columnist at The Atlantic
Journal-Constitution.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Emerge magazine 
