</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-DWINDLING-MEXICAN-IMMIGRANTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S BLEAK FUTURE MINUS MEXICAN IMMIGRANTS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS  
 &HT;    They keep coming to the United States _ the men and women from
rural Mexico _ to work in the flower fields, nurseries, avocado
groves and sundry jobs throughout the country. There are an
estimated 2.5 million Mexicans working in the country. Soon,
however, fewer and fewer of them will be coming here to live and
work.
 &HT;    Wishful thinking? No. The supply of willing Mexican emigres to
the United States will shrink in coming years. Within a decade, the
number of Mexicans illegally entering the United States will
diminish to the point of endangering the production of our food
supply.
 &HT;    The steady decline can be attributed to a surge in the Mexican
economy, plunging birthrates and a slower population growth. Mexico
now generates about a million jobs a year, double the amount
available a decade ago.
 &HT;    In 1993, before the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA),
Mexico manufactured about 500,000 automobiles, with over 80 percent
geared for the domestic market. Last year, the number had grown to
1.5 million automobiles, with fewer than 500,000 for the Mexican
market and a million for export, mostly to the United States and
some to Brazil and other countries. It obviously takes more Mexican
autoworkers to build a million more cars than pre-NAFTA days.
 &HT;    The declining Mexico City birth rate is spreading to the rural
areas that have long supplied the young men who immigrated to The
North, El Norte. Statistics from 1996 show that the birth rate
among Mexican mothers was under three children, down from an
average of six births in 1994. This is the result of a 20-year-long
birth-control program hustled in every rural village by the Mexican
government.
 &HT;    Despite superficial opposition from the Catholic Church, the
government has persisted in promoting this program, and the country
will soon reap the double-edged rewards of a declining birth rate.
And Mexican women, who traditionally have not worked outside the
home, have entered the work force, which also contributes to the
drop in national fertility rates.
 &HT;    As Mexico's economy grows and modernizes, more and more jobs are
created. As the number of young people becomes smaller, an
unprecedented situation may come to pass: Mexico will have more
jobs than people. Consequently, wages will rise. Thus, the promise
of NAFTA is becoming real in Mexico. Mexicans will have all the
jobs they can fill in Mexico. They won't need to come here looking
for work. At least, that's the theory.
 &HT;    Mexican demographer Agustin Escobar says that for 15 years, the
number of working-age Mexicans entering the labor force has
remained steady. ``We needed emigration to help our people find
work,'' he says. ``But now we can see that the future is going to
be quite different from what we saw in the 1980s and 1990s.''
 &HT;    Escobar thinks that by 2010 the number of Mexican emigrants to
the United States will decrease to such an extent that it will pose
problems for the American economy _ specifically for California's
agricultural economy.
 &HT;    According to the U.S. Department of Labor, at least 52 percent
of farm workers in California may be illegal aliens. Farm owner
groups, however, think that the percentage might be as high as 80
percent. California depends on illegal-alien labor to pick almost
all crops in the most productive farmland in the country. If
illegals from Mexico aren't there to pick the crops, who will?
 &HT;    Jose Pescador Osuna, a deputy secretary in Mexico's Foreign
Ministry, says that in the next 15 years, Mexicans won't cross the
border just to get jobs. Rather, they will come here to get better
jobs, or to compete for higher wages. The NAFTA agreement contains
a provision to allow 60,000 North Americans per year to work in
Mexico and a similar number of Mexicans to come here every year to
work legally.
 &HT;    In the meantime, who will do the work in California, pack the
beef in Omaha, cut tobacco in Kentucky and pluck the chickens in
North Carolina?
 &HT;    Will we bring in Chinese, like we did to build the railroad? Or
will a new president construct a viable guest-worker program that
will legalize people who are willing to come North for better jobs
and higher wages?
 &HT;    Will a guest-worker program stop the hatred some Americans feel
against illegal aliens that permeates the so-called immigration
debate? No. But the work will get done, and everyone will benefit.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, an editorial board member of La Prensa
San Diego, hosts his own radio talk-show on KOGO in San Diego.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
