u k BC-NEW-AMERICA-ANGEL-ISL     05-08 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-ANGEL-ISLAND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DARK SIDE OF ANGEL ISLAND  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement
with New York Times Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of
text. 
 &HT;    
 By AMY WU 
 &HT;    A few moths ago, I came across a book, originally published in
1980, titled ``Island: Poetry and History of Chinese Immigrants on
Angel Island.'' The book is filled with poetry written by hundreds
of Chinese immigrants, who carved their prose into the walls of
barracks at a detention center on Angel Island.
 &HT;    Angel Island is north of San Francisco and has been called the
Ellis Island of the West.
 &HT;    Several prominent politicians _ including New York's Diane
Feinstein and Hawaii's Daniel Akaka _ have worked hard to preserve
the island, and Congress is looking to allot money for the creation
of an immigration museum.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Angel Island is rarely mentioned today. Few people
know what it is, where it is and what it once held. The island is
now a state park, and its beauty masks the hardship and shame of
its former purpose _ a place to detain nearly 200,000 Chinese
between the years of 1910 and 1940.
 &HT;    I searched for those nameless people who have passed through
this island, the ghosts who penned the poetry, and have realized
that, in part, I am searching for myself.
 &HT;    I have spent countless hours talking with Angel Island
survivors, whose shame has turned into anger. I chatted with a man
in his 80s, who spent three months there. He remembers having his
belongings locked in a warehouse, and seeing the dead bodies of men
who, in the depths of despair, hung themselves in the shower
stalls.
 &HT;    He recalls being grilled for nearly four hours by officers who
asked everything _ from the number of stairs in his house in China
to the number of windows in his cousin's house.
 &HT;    Since leaving the island, he went to Mississippi, where he spent
years working at a grocery store because he couldn't attend school.
In the 1930s, the Chinese were excluded from the white schools and
only the ``colored schools'' were open to the new immigrants.
 &HT;    ``That's unbelievable,'' I found myself repeating like a mantra.
 &HT;    The anger from the old man seems carved on his bones. He fought
in WWII, worked in a grocery, spent many years drawing for an ad
agency and is a law-abiding citizen. Yet he still feels the sting
of history.
 &HT;    I talked with other survivors, who said that even now they still
find it painful to talk about their experiences _ that it has
affected the way they see themselves, and that they do not want to
return to Angel Island to open old wounds.
 &HT;    The poetry of such people, who were locked in loneliness, shame
and uncertainty, still sits on the walls of the barracks, a searing
reminder of how far we have come and yet how far we have yet to go.
 &HT;    One of the poems reads: ``Bored and filled with a hundred
feelings, I am imprisoned in the building. Seeing the surroundings
stirs one who is sad. How can one stop the tears? I recall the ship
starting off for the land of America. Looking back, the moon has
repeated a cycle.''
 &HT;    Recently, I chatted with a 74-year-old woman named Li-king, an
outgoing, extremely optimistic woman, who talked for hours about
her experiences on the island. For much of her adult life she kept
it a secret, and then one day she decided to share her experiences
with her grandchildren, since they are part of their roots.
 &HT;    She spent four hours talking with a producer for ``The American
Tapestry,'' a documentary about the beauty of diversity in America.
 &HT;    ``I thought my story should be told because the younger
generation knows nothing about what the older generation had to go
through,'' she said.
 &HT;    As a first-generation Chinese-American, I will never truly
understand the pain experienced by those who passed through Angel
Island. However, I do think it is important to reopen this chapter
in the history of Asian people.
 &HT;    Only by looking back can we move forward.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Amy Wu is a free-lance writer who spent three years as a
journalist in Hong Kong.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 2000 Amy Wu 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC; 
