<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8771 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r a BC-NEW-AMERICA-LURING-LA     05-08 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-LURING-LATINOS-TO-GOP-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURING LATINOS TO THE GOP FOLD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES E. GARCIA  
 &HT;    The term ``Hispanic Republican'' used to be an oxymoron. Not
anymore, according to Jose Rivera, chairman of the Republican
National Hispanic Assembly (RNHA).
 &HT;    With national polls suggesting that George W. Bush could win as
much as 40 percent of the Hispanic vote in the presidential
election, Rivera predicts that the ranks of registered Republicans
in the Latino community will grow dramatically in the coming years.
 &HT;    Rivera has reason to be upbeat. RNHA's membership has almost
tripled since 1997, increasing from 7,000 to more than 20,000. And
RNHA chapters have started popping up in some unlikely places, such
as Arkansas, Mississippi, Nebraska and the state of Washington.
 &HT;    The demographic trend among Hispanics, soon to be the nation's
largest minority group, also includes a fast-growing
entrepreneurial class with a penchant for limited government and
lower taxes.
 &HT;    Largely funded by the Republican National Committee, Rivera's
group, which was founded in the '70s, is part of a new outreach
effort by the GOP. The party says it's spending about $10 million
in a national ad campaign aimed at recruiting Hispanic voters.
 &HT;    GOP spokeswoman Leslie Sanchez calls the party's effort its
first-ever, comprehensive political marketing strategy``meant to
persuade Latinos that the GOP shares its views.''
 &HT;    ``We have had the right message for many years, we've just had
the wrong messengers,'' says Tomas Bilbao, RNHA's deputy director
and, at the age of 21, one of the party's newest messengers.
 &HT;    Bilbao is talking about former California Gov. Pete Wilson, who
helped pass Proposition 187. critics say Proposition 187, which
most California Latinos strongly opposed, inspired a wave of
anti-Latino sentiment in Congress and across the country.
 &HT;    But times have changed. The Republicans still control Congress,
but worried about losing the Latino vote the GOP has softened its
stance on issues such as welfare and immigration reform. And the
party's collective persona has also been reshaped. Bilbao points to
a new crop of Republican messengers, including Bush and his former
challenger, Sen. John McCain.
 &HT;    The challenge, Rivera says, is to get the word out to the
Hispanic community _ a job made easier since more Latino
Republicans are getting elected to public office. For instance,
Rep. Henry Bonilla is a rising Republican star in Congress and a
major player in Bush's presidential campaign.
 &HT;    In California, Gloria Matta Tuchman, who helped pass that
state's controversial bilingual education reform initiative, is
running for Congress in the fall against two-term incumbent
Democrat Loretta Sanchez. And Texas Railroad Commissioner Tony
Garza could end up in a cabinet post in a Bush administration.
 &HT;    One of RNHA's main goals in the coming months is to boost Latino
representation at the Republican National Convention, which will be
held in Philadelphia in July. The Democrats have already upped the
ante by appointing Lydia Camarillo as CEO of the Democratic
National Convention. Camarillo has pledged to recruit a staff of
employees and volunteers ``that looks like America.''
 &HT;    ``If the Republican Party intends to be the home of Latinos in
the new millennium, it is essential that we are given the
opportunity to represent our interests at the convention,'' Rivera
said recently. ``Not to do so would hurt the convention, the
presidential candidate and the party.''
 &HT;    To spread the word about its activities, RNHA publishes a weekly
electronic newsletter, which the group also posts on its Web site,
www.rnha.org. Not surprisingly, articles about Democratic missteps
are easy fodder for the e-letter.
 &HT;    But the e-letter also has a lighter side. In a recent issue, it
lampooned Gore in its list of predictions for the Academy Awards.
The award for Best Performance in a Foreign Film went to Gore ``for
his role as a deity at the Hsi Lai Buddhist Temple.''
 &HT;    But the serious business of recruiting Latinos to the GOP
promises to keep Rivera and company busy. Rivera admits it won't be
easy. The Clinton-Gore ticket captured the Latino vote in 1996,
with more than 70 percent of Latinos voting for Clinton. Likewise,
Gore made a strong showing among Latinos in California and New York
in the March 7 primary.
 &HT;    Still, Bush has a strong Latino following in his home state of
Texas and in Florida, where his brother Jeb Bush is governor. And a
national poll conducted earlier this year by the Tarrance Group
showed Bush leading Gore among Latino voters. Observers say the
candidates are likely to split the Latino vote in November, but no
one can predict by how much.
 &HT;    For his part, Bilbao says he is not surprised by the GOP's
growing support among Hispanics and predicts even better times
ahead.
 &HT;    ``We're the party of conservative values, education, limited
government and limited taxes. As a Hispanic, those are values that
are dear to me,'' he said. ``Our message has always been the
same.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James E. Garcia is editor-in-chief of Politico magazine, a
monthly publication covering U.S. Latino politics. E-mail
Politico1 aol.com or visit www.politicomagazine.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James E. Garcia 
