w e BC-TRACEY-ULLMAN-IN-SMAL     05-08 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACEY-ULLMAN-IN-SMALL-TIME-CROOKS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACEY ULLMAN TRIES A NEW IDENTITY: MOVIE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Tracey Ullman with Hugh Grant in a scene
from ``Small Time Crooks.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Tracey Ullman's entourage takes up less room than those of most
Hollywood stars.
 &HT;    Actually, they're all her. A hairy New York cabbie opens the
door to her hotel room. A screaming Ricky Martin fan materializes
moments later. And scary Beverly Hills attorney Sydney Kross
practically drips sarcasm as he picks at the fruit plate.
 &HT;    Five minutes into a conversation with the 41-year-old British
comedian, and you've met a parade of people of every race, creed,
gender and sexual preference. But they have one thing in common:
They're all hilarious.
 &HT;    So much for Jerry Lewis' recent comment that women can't be
funny.
 &HT;    ``That comment would hurt if it came from anyone I thought was
funny,'' Ullman says, snapping into her real persona. ``Frankly, I
was burning up when I heard that comment. My first reaction was,
`Why did you say that, you old fool? What about Gilda Radner? What
about Lucille Ball? What about me?'''
 &HT;    Yes, what about her? Ullman burst onto the American comedy scene
13 years ago with her critically acclaimed television series, ``The
Tracey Ullman Show'' (1987-1990), and nowadays has a hit HBO comedy
series, ``Tracey Takes On.''
 &HT;    And now she's starring opposite Woody Allen in the
rags-to-riches story ``Small Time Crooks,'' opening May 19. Ullman
plays Allen's wife, who gets entangled in his scheme to tunnel into
a bank and rob the place.
 &HT;    For years, Ullman recalls, she longed to work with Allen.
 &HT;    ``I remember sitting in my hot tub in America when I was
pregnant and whining to my husband, `Should I stay in America? I
miss London,''' she says. ``But then what changed things for me is
that I watched `Broadway Danny Rose' (1984), and it was so terrific
that I thought I should stay in America just so I could work with
Woody Allen.''
 &HT;    Never one to sit and wait, Ullman immediately took pen in hand.
 &HT;    ``For years I wrote Woody silly letters,'' the comedian says.
``I said things like, `Dear Woody. You use Mia Farrow all the time.
Isn't it time for a change? Let Mia sit in my hot tub and I'll come
to New York and be in your movies.'
 &HT;    ``I honestly thought he would read these lunatic notes and say,
`You know, that's a good idea.'''
 &HT;    For his own part, Allen says in a separate interview, he was
simply confused.
 &HT;    ``She wrote me all these letters, and frankly I never heard of
her,'' Allen recalls. ``Eventually Tracey sent me a tape of her
performances. She was great _ I even went around telling my
friends, `You've got to see this woman. She's amazing.'''
 &HT;    When he was casting ``Bullets Over Broadway'' (1994), Allen gave
Ullman a small role.
 &HT;    ``The previous day I had been asked to do a Christmas special in
Montreal with the Olsen twins,'' she recalls. ``Bless them, they
are sweet little girls. But it wasn't my cup of tea.
 &HT;    ``Plus, I had to ask questions such as, `When are the Olsen
twins going to be nude in Playboy? It might not be good for me to
be associated with them.'''
 &HT;    Ullman landed a bigger part in Allen's ``Everyone Says I Love
You'' (1996), complete with a song-and-dance number. But when the
movie ran 20 minutes too long, the filmmaker was forced to cut out
her role entirely.
 &HT;    ``I had to explain to her that it had nothing to do with her
performance,'' Allen says. ``It was my bad writing.''
 &HT;    When he gave her a co-starring role in ``Small Time Crooks,''
Allen says, he was less worried about her performance than about
his own.
 &HT;    ``Frankly, I was intimidated,'' he admits. ``She's a comic
genius.''
 &HT;    That comic flair was cultivated during a rough childhood spent
in the posh area of Slough, near London, in the 1960s. Her father
died from a heart ailment when Tracey was 6, and Ullman used to try
to distract her mother from her worries by staging nightly shows in
her bedroom.
 &HT;    ``Those were sad years,'' Ullman says. ``I would try to do
anything to cheer up my mum. I would put on her negligees and strut
around the room _ nothing was off limits to make her smile.''
 &HT;    A natural mimic, Ullman won a scholarship to a professional
children's school in London, but she soon realized that
conventional show business was not for her.
 &HT;    ``I hated every minute of it,'' she says, grimacing. ``The other
girls were there because their mothers wanted to make them little,
annoying, blonde stars of toilet-paper commercials. I would sit in
the bathroom at school, smoke and make fun of all the other
girls.''
 &HT;    At 16 Ullman left school to become a dancer, then took a shot at
a singing career. Her first album, ``You Broke My Heart in 17
Places,'' went gold and produced four Top 10 singles in England.
 &HT;    But her heart wasn't in music, and she soon turned to the
theater and, in turn, television work for the BBC. That's where she
met her husband, British television producer Allan McKeown, a
former hairdresser who co-created her early BBC series and also
helms her current HBO show, ``Tracey Takes On,'' as well as helping
raise their two children, Mabel and John.
 &HT;    Defining her unique show-business niche hasn't been easy, Ullman
admits.
 &HT;    ``It is tougher for girls to be funny,'' she says. ``I'm lucky
because I find humor in situations. But I never wanted to be a
stand-up comic _ I could never be one of those girls who gets up in
front of a mike and talks about her Tampax ... I don't get why
female stand-ups feel they have to talk about sex and be bawdy and
brash.''
 &HT;    Women are also harder to make jokes about, she says, because
they're more likely to take offense.
 &HT;    ``Once I did this talk show with supermodel Christie Brinkley,
and I went up to her and said, `It's amazing _ I always heard you
were pretty,''' Ullman recalls. ``She almost burst into tears.
 &HT;    ``It was a joke,'' she says defensively.
 &HT;    ``You have to do selective bitchery,'' the comedian adds.
``There is some bitchery we don't want to say openly, because we
don't want to damage our careers.'''
 &HT;    At the same time, she's adamant in insisting that no topic is
too sensitive to joke about.
 &HT;    ``Everything is comic fodder,'' Ullman says. ``I take on some
serious issues, and I find the humor in them. The poignant/funny
pieces are the ones I like the most. Once I did this skit on gay
golfers kissing _ I thought it broke a bit of ground.''
 &HT;    Ullman is even willing to bite the hand that feeds her, taking
off on two of the top-rated shows on HBO, for which she will soon
begin taping new episodes of her series, ``Tracey Takes On.''
 &HT;    She lapses into a dead-on impression of ``Sex and the City's''
Sarah Jessica Parker.
 &HT;    ``Yes,'' she burbles, ``let's talk orgasms!''
 &HT;    To riff on the grueling prison drama ``Oz,'' she assumes the
voice of a blase Noo Yawk television critic.
 &HT;    ``It's a great show,'' she says with a theatrical sigh, ``but
how many gang rapes can you see in two hours?''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
