<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-AMY-SMART-IN-ROAD-TRI     05-08 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMY-SMART-IN-ROAD-TRIP-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMY SMART: BAD GIRLS HAVE MORE FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Amy Smart in a scene from ``Road
Trip.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF and MELANIE SEYMOUR  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Amy Smart made a name for herself by playing good girls in
``Varsity Blues'' (1999) and ``Outside Providence'' (1999), but
nowadays she's doing even better being bad.
 &HT;    The 24-year-old blonde with an infectious smile and an easy
laugh can currently be seen on the hit television series
``Felicity'' as Noel's new love who gets pregnant by another guy.
She recently played a second-rate model caught up in drugs and cult
religion in the NBC miniseries ``The '70s,'' and her next
big-screen appearance _ in ``Road Trip,'' opening May 19 _ is as a
girl who likes to videotape her sex life.
 &HT;    Some may recall seeing her in a more risque role in ``Varsity
Blues,'' but they're wrong.
 &HT;    ``People still think I'm the one who had sex with a guy and lots
of whipped cream,'' she says. ``That girl was actually my friend
Ali Larter. Maybe it has something to do with the fact that we're
both blonde.''
 &HT;    ``Road Trip'' gives Smart her first topless scene, opposite
hunky Breckin Meyer.
 &HT;    ``I'd never done nudity before, so I was a little nervous,'' she
admits. ``Then the director, Todd Phillips, told me that he would
never forget watching Phoebe Cates drop her top in `Fast Times At
Ridgemont High' (1982). He said it changed his life.''
 &HT;    She pauses and giggles.
 &HT;    ``I guess that made me feel better.''
 &HT;    Smart did check with her mother first, she adds.
 &HT;    ``She said, `If you think it's the right choice, then you should
do it,''' the actress recalls. ``I was just so glad she didn't
become overprotective.''
 &HT;    ``Road Trip'' is a teen comedy of errors which casts Meyer as
Josh, a college student who's cheating on his significant other
with Beth (Smart). The videotape of their amorous encounter is
accidentally mailed to his girlfriend at her Texas college, so Josh
and a few buddies hit the road to the Lone Star State, determined
to intercept the incriminating tape.
 &HT;    Co-starring as Meyer's bizarre roommate is the wildly
unpredictable MTV comic Tom Green.
 &HT;    ``We didn't know what to expect from Tom,'' Smart says. ``We
were all a little nervous that he might be trying to pull some gags
on us during a scene. But he was really very nice and low-key.
 &HT;    ``But after the camera stopped rolling,'' she adds with a grin,
``he'd get a little crazy.''
 &HT;    Most of the rest of the ``Road Trip'' cast are male, but Smart
says that wasn't a problem.
 &HT;    ``Fortunately, there weren't any big egos,'' she says. ``I felt
completely at home, because growing up I was sort of a tomboy. I
was the one skating with the boys. I even played Little League with
them. I was the only girl on the team, and they called me `Smarty
Pants.' So I've never had any trouble getting along with a bunch of
guys.''
 &HT;    She may be a budding movie star with two hits behind her, but
Smart says that so far it's television that has given her whatever
recognition she enjoys.
 &HT;    ``I get recognized a lot for `Felicity,''' she says. ``I guess
people sort of get hooked on their favorite series and watch them
religiously. When fans of `Felicity' see me, it's like they know
me.''
 &HT;    Her character on ``Felicity'' has forced Smart to deal with the
issue of teen-age pregnancy, which she says has been a real
eye-opener.
 &HT;    ``I met some single young women who kept their babies,'' the
actress says. ``I used to wonder how they could make that kind of
mistake and get pregnant. Now I'm much more forgiving, because I
realize the love they feel for that child. I have a lot more
compassion, which was a huge learning lesson in itself.''
 &HT;    So was playing a pregnant character.
 &HT;    ``I had to put on this pregnant suit,'' she says. ``Just looking
down at my big belly was wild and kind of exciting. I want to have
kids eventually, and so I'd go, `Wow, this is what I'd look
like.'''
 &HT;    Smart and her brother, Adam, had a thoroughly conventional
upbringing in Topanga Canyon, Calif.
 &HT;    ``I was actually very shy,'' she recalls. ``I was always
watching one of my friends, Vinessa Shaw, who started acting when
she was very young and, ironically, got the good-girl role in `The
'70s.' First I studied ballet, and when I danced on stage I loved
the attention. Then I finally took the leap and enrolled in an
acting class, and I was hooked.''
 &HT;    Her first career opportunity, however, came as a model.
 &HT;    ``Vinessa Shaw suggested me as a replacement in a photo shoot,''
she says, ``and I got the job. Suddenly I was getting assignments
to travel to places like Italy, France, Mexico and Tahiti. I wasn't
a cover girl, but I was able to pay for my first car and my first
apartment.
 &HT;    ``I never worried about getting pigeonholed as a model,'' she
adds, ``because I wasn't getting that much attention.''
 &HT;    Smart made her acting debut in a small part in an MTV ``Rock the
Vote'' promo, and went on to minor roles in ``Starship Troopers''
(1997) and ``The Last Time I Committed Suicide'' (1997). Then came
``Varsity Blues,'' and the wheels of celebrity began to turn.
 &HT;    ``I'm still close to my parents,'' she says, ``and they help
keep me grounded. But they get a kick out of what I'm doing. For
instance, NBC put a huge `'70s' billboard on a building in Burbank.
It was almost six stories high. My father called me up and said, `I
brought my camera to work. Let's have lunch and take a few
pictures.'
 &HT;    ``He was posing me in front of this billboard with a picture of
me on it,'' the actress recalls, laughing. ``It was so sweet.''
 &HT;    Another grounding influence in Smart's life is her boyfriend,
actor Branden Williams.
 &HT;    ``We've been together for a long time,'' she says. ``It's nice
to be with somebody who understands this business. If you don't, I
think you could become incredibly insecure in a relationship with
an actor.''
 &HT;    Actually, Smart adds, despite the cliche of the neurotic
actress, she considers herself perfectly secure.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes you just have to take charge,'' Smart says. ``I
remember that, when I was doing `Felicity,' it looked like it would
conflict with `The '70s.' I really wanted the chance to play this
wild party girl on the miniseries, but I also knew that getting
pregnant on `Felicity' was something I had to do.
 &HT;    ``Finally I called up J.J. Abrams, the `Felicity' producer, and
I told him I really wanted to do both and I needed him to help
me,'' she recalls. ``That little phone call kept me on the show. I
realized how important it was to speak up and not get caught in
having an agent or somebody else speak for you. I charged ahead,
and I got what I wanted.
 &HT;    ``The other thing I've learned,'' she adds, ``is how the best
people, especially some of the legends, are really just people. You
have this larger-than-life image of them, and then you realize that
they're not trying to be that way.
 &HT;    ``It actually brings up my own confidence,'' Smart says. ``You
realize they're just people, too. And if they can do it, maybe you
can, too.
 &HT;    ``So why not reach for the stars?''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf and Melanie Seymour are Hollywood-based free-lance
writers.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Road Trip,'' consult the
official Web site at www.roadtrip-itsgood.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
