<HEADER>
A8784 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-MALCOLM-IN-THE-MIDDLE     05-08 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOLM-IN-THE-MIDDLE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKIE MUNIZ: LITTLE MAN IN THE MIDDLE OF A GREAT BIG HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Frankie Muniz in a scene from ``Malcolm
in the Middle.'') 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before May 28. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This past year has been a blur for Frankie Muniz.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old actor has gone from virtual obscurity to stardom
as the title character of the season's biggest breakout comedy,
``Malcolm in the Middle.'' And Muniz is enjoying his rocket ride to
fame, with one small exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't skateboard any more,'' he says with a rueful regret
that would befit any teen-ager. ``Although I did get hurt a couple
times _ I used to do a lot of extreme stuff. I have to be a bit
more careful now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox Broadcasting insists on it, in fact _ the network counts
Muniz as one of its most valuable assets. Since its January
premiere, ``Malcolm'' has become a Sunday-night habit for many
viewers who either identify with the dysfunctional family depicted
therein or at least love to laugh at their foibles.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm's family doesn't have a last name, they're not animated,
the parents aren't divorced and, most notably, the series has
managed to be anything but predictable. In short, it's ``The Wonder
Years'' filtered through ``Mad TV,'' and the public can't get
enough.
</P>
<P>
   In person, Muniz dispels the myths about child actors: instead
of being a petulant, snotty brat, he's charming, self-effacing and
friendly. Even more refreshing, in a business in which the Olsen
twins have acted like corporate traders since they could toddle,
Muniz actually acts his age.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he complaining about the added responsibilities that
accompany his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love acting, so whatever comes with it, I'll do,'' he says.
``It's really fun for me. I don't mind traveling all over, living
in a hotel, because I get to meet so many new people. It's just a
lot of fun for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun is only beginning. In addition to his newfound fame as
Malcolm, Muniz got a big-screen boost with this spring's
family-themed feature ``My Dog Skip,'' in which he co-stars with
Kevin Bacon. And he's recently started shooting a new film,
``Deuces Are Wild,'' in Los Angeles, alongside Matt Dillon and
Deborah Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I'm doing a cartoon for Nickelodeon called `The Very
Odd Parents,''' Muniz adds, ``and I'm doing a charity event for
Baskin-Robbins.''
</P>
<P>
   Between all of this, Muniz must find time for school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm home-schooled now,'' he says, ``but when I was in regular
school I was always a little ahead in my stuff, and my teachers
would always have to give me extra work, because I would get done
with my math and everything really quickly. So when I was in first
grade, I was doing fourth-grade work.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't mistake him for Malcolm, the television genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a genius,'' Muniz says patiently, ``but just a little
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   He never had the trouble that Malcolm does with other children
taunting him about his brains _ though he admits that his
blossoming career has brought problems of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this kid who, it seems every time he sees me, someone
is always asking about the show or about acting and stuff,'' he
says, ``so he's always like, ``Is that all you talk about?''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's a little weird,'' Muniz says. ``But really, before
this show, I never told anyone about my acting. They would just see
it on TV and come up to me, `Were you on that? That's really cool.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But now everyone has seen the show, so they all come up to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the show took off, Muniz, his mother and his 15-year-old
sister have moved from New Jersey to Los Angeles, where the young
star keeps himself busy on his time off by exploring the area's
endless array of golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually play golf,'' he says. ``I've played since I was 5.
My grandpa taught me, and I can now beat him. I have a 13
handicap.''
</P>
<P>
   He also spends time with his ``Malcolm'' castmates, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do hang out together,'' he says. ``We're always in school
together, and then when you're done with school we play football
and just hang out, or play basketball on the set.''
</P>
<P>
   From all reports that set is one of the most laid-back in Los
Angeles, which is saying quite a lot. Bryan Cranston, who plays
Hal, the boys' oddball father, seconds the motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real normal kids,'' he says in a separate interview.
``Which is great from my standpoint, because they're not so
callused and business-savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 7-year-old daughter myself,'' he adds, ``and she is
crazy about the boys. Crazy about them.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not the only one. ``Malcolm'' has proven to be a ratings
powerhouse for the troubled Fox network, and there are already a
multitude of devoted fan sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz is elated about the show's success, but like many actors
before him is perplexed by his fans, who seem to think that Muniz
is Malcolm and vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the confusion may be his own fault, he admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to sound real weird, but I hadn't read the
script when I first auditioned, so I was just myself saying
Malcolm's words,'' he recalls. ``I just went in and did how I would
do it if it was me. So I guess I am who I play.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has grown into his character, Muniz has become more aware
of their differences than of their similarities, and he's no longer
sure that he'd even want to hang out with Malcolm himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be friends with him ... like half and half,'' the
young actor says thoughtfully. ``He is like me a little bit, but I
really wouldn't want to be with him because he is always angry.
He's always so mad at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad temper notwithstanding, it looks like Muniz is stuck with
Malcolm for the foreseeable future. The little guy is still
settling into his role as television's top kid, but the actor who
plays him is slowly getting used to those surreal moments that seem
to keep popping up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so weird,'' he says, shaking his head. ``Last year I was
watching the Nickelodeon Kids Choice Awards, and this year I'm
co-hosting. It's just so weird and awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based correspondent for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Malcolm in the Middle,''
consult the Fox Broadcasting Web site at www.fox.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
