w e BC-BARRY-WILLIAMS-ON-GRO     05-08 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRY-WILLIAMS-ON-GROWING-UP-BRADY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO BRADY: BARRY WILLIAMS REVISITS HIS YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Barry Williams on the set of ``Growing
Up Brady.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It was another Brady moment in a life bursting with Brady
moments.
 &HT;    There stood Barry Williams, who portrayed the ever-wholesome
Greg Brady in ``The Brady Bunch'' and its assorted spinoffs,
watching as actor Adam Brody played Williams playing Greg in a
scene for ``Growing Up Brady.''
 &HT;    Based on Williams' memoirs about his days as a Brady, ``Growing
Up Brady'' will air May 21 on NBC.
 &HT;    ``I think surreal might describe it,'' Williams says. ``There
was an element of deja vu. There were moments when it was plain old
uncomfortable. I felt exposed _ you had 100 people on a soundstage,
dissecting my life, my memories, my dialogue.
 &HT;    ``I'd be standing right there, thinking, `No, Barry wouldn't do
that. Wait a minute, let me tell you what to do,''' he says.
``There had to be a bit of compromise, because the actor playing me
had to interpret the dialogue for himself. I think believable is
better even than accurate.''
 &HT;    Williams, who served as the television movie's co-executive
producer and appears briefly as himself, explains that the story is
told in flashbacks and covers his five years making ``The Brady
Bunch,'' his relationship with co-star Maureen McCormick (Kaley
Cuoco) and the battles between Robert Reed (Daniel Hugh Kelly),
producer Sherwood Schwartz (Michael Tucker) and Paramount Pictures
over money and the quality of the scripts.
 &HT;    Most important, ``Growing Up Brady'' examines the impact of the
show on its six young cast members.
 &HT;    ``It gives you a real clear feeling for the environment of
growing up as pretty normal kids in pretty unusual circumstances,''
Williams says by telephone from his production offices in New York.
``You've got a bunch of kids dealing with all the hype, intensity,
challenges and rewards of being under the microscope as a result of
being on a show, making records, touring, making personal
appearances, being isolated from our friends and counting on one
another.
 &HT;    ``The telemovie, as opposed to my book, shows all of that,
rather than putting it only into words,'' he says. ``The telemovie
has a completely different arc than the book. It's got a beginning,
middle and an end, while the book goes chapter by chapter.''
 &HT;    Nobody, of course, ever foresaw that ``The Brady Bunch,'' which
ran from 1969 to 1974, would endure as it has. It was a sweet,
corny show that never quite went away. Much like ``Star Trek,''
``The Brady Bunch'' entered the realm of phenomenon only after its
cancellation, riding an unending afterlife of reruns.
 &HT;    Soon enough, there was a ``Brady Bunch'' variety hour, then
several reunion telemovies and two short-lived ``Brady'' series.
Then came two feature films, ``The Brady Bunch Movie'' (1995) and
``A Very Brady Sequel'' (1996). Even now, ``Brady'' fever runs so
high that Fox has whipped together its own Brady telemovie, ``The
Brady Bunch _ The Final Years,'' and scheduled it for May 16, a
week before ``Growing Up Brady.''
 &HT;    Exactly why ``The Brady Bunch'' emerged as an icon _ and why it
remains one _ is as much a mystery today as it was 10, 20 or 30
years ago.
 &HT;    ``There are probably 1,000 answers, and I'm certainly no
authority on it,'' says Williams, who is now 45 and a newlywed who
lives with his wife in Connecticut. ``I can tell you what people
tell me, and that is they appreciate the show for not being
preachy.
 &HT;    ``They like the little messages in each show,'' he says. ``They
like that the family communicates, that they get along, that the
parents get along with each other and the kids, and that the kids,
if they have an argument, talk and work things out.
 &HT;    ``There's also an identifiability factor,'' Williams adds,
``because there are boys and girls, and there's a youngest kid, a
middle kid and an oldest kid. Even now, adults can say, `Oh yeah, I
had braces' or `I remember when I got my first pair of glasses.'
 &HT;    ``It could also be the supergroovy fashion statements we made
every week,'' he says with a laugh.
 &HT;    ``All in all, everybody understands that there is no family like
the Bradys, but it is an ideal that just hasn't gone out of
fashion,'' he concludes. ``I'm thrilled that kids today appreciate
the show, and I've got 5- and 6-year-olds coming up to me and
asking for autographs, sometimes for themselves and sometimes for
their parents.
 &HT;    ``What's amusing to me,'' Williams adds, ``is that kids think
they've discovered this new show. And what I find poignant is that
parents tell me that watching `The Brady Bunch' is one of the few
activities they can do together and actually enjoy with their
kids.''
 &HT;    Prior to ``The Brady Bunch,'' Williams was a busy child actor in
Hollywood. He appeared as a boy dying of leukemia on ``Marcus
Welby, M.D.'' and as a young king in a ``Mission: Impossible''
episode. He played brainy boys and kids who talked back.
 &HT;    And then came Greg.
 &HT;    ``I've lived life with `The Brady Bunch' in it, and I'm happy
with my life,'' the actor says. ``But there is a true curiosity on
my part about what it would have been like not to have been
associated and identified with one project so strongly.
 &HT;    ``It would have been fine that I played Greg,'' he says, ``but
the show never left the air. It's been on for 30 years, and that's
a lot of reinforcement.
 &HT;    ``The whole typecasting phenomenon is interesting,'' he says
thoughtfully, ``and it's something I've come to learn a little bit
about. All actors who come on the scene get associated with the
role that made them famous. Sean Connery has a tremendous body of
work, but don't you think of Bond when you think of Sean Connery?
Michael Landon did `Little House' and `Highway to Heaven,' but to a
lot of people he was always Little Joe from `Bonanza.'
 &HT;    ``Look at what Sally Field had to overcome,'' Williams says.
``Sylvester Stallone is an interesting case. He came on the scene
as Rocky and he tried everything, comedies and even musicals, but
people just didn't get him in those other roles. You can't do
anything about typecasting, unless you do something bigger than
that which you became first known for.''
 &HT;    Williams has yet to land a part that will do for him what
``Norma Rae'' (1979) did for Field or ``First Blood'' (1982) did
for Stallone, but he isn't complaining. A couple of years ago he
starred in the national tour of ``City of Angels'' and, more
recently, he released ``The Return of Johnny Bravo,'' a CD of pop
songs which is available through his official Web site,
barrywilliams.com.
 &HT;    ``Here's the thing,'' he says. ``I'm proud of `The Brady Bunch.'
I embrace it. I feel fortunate that I have had a career outside it,
that I've done one-man shows and many musicals, and that I've
performed on Broadway, in Las Vegas, all over the country.
 &HT;    ``So I don't feel threatened by the show,'' Williams concludes.
``People love it, and for that I'm very grateful. It's part of who
I am as a person and as an entertainer.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
