<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETARIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HERBIVORES CELEBRATE THE JOYS OF SHUNNING FLESH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRACISCO _ Dressed in an oversized banana suit, Rob Schaff
spent Sunday afternoon playing tunes with titles like ``I Got the
Blues `Cuz I Ain't Got No Greens,'' and ``I Left My Lettuce Hearts
in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   He blared out the moody melodies as hundreds swarmed around
tables sampling meat-free morsels at VegFest 2000, a celebration
organized in part by the San Francisco Vegetarian Society to
promote plant-based diets. And to revel in plenty of puns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be known for being too serious because this is such a
serious issue,'' said Nancy Loewen, a Vegetarian Society board
member who has not eaten any meat, poultry, fish or dairy products
for nearly a decade. ``What we really want is to just give people
information, education and inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouquets of smiling, cartoon-faced Mylar balloons shaped like
bell peppers, tomatoes and celery stalks bobbed above vendors
pitching products with names like Un-Chicken, Tofurkey Jerky and
even one called ``Veat.''
</P>
<P>
   After eating a tan-colored cube of Veat from a toothpick, Laura
Bilodeau declared it delicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tastes a lot like chicken,'' said Bilodeau, a
self-described ``major carnivore.'' ``They did a good job of faking
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal fitness coach, Veat fan and sample-server Christopher
Todd said he fell in love with the flavor after his first bite of a
faux salmon filet about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm getting goose-bumps just thinking about it,'' he
said, pointing to his forearm. ``This is my buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd even composed a poem about his favorite product, which is
posted on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But for vegetarian Esta Lewin, the texture was almost too close
to the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little too meat-like for me,'' said Lewin, who lives
in South Lake Tahoe and came to San Francisco for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, I used to travel for recreation, now I travel to
eat,'' she said, explaining that her menu options are often limited
in her hometown because there are far fewer vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the San Francisco area has one of the largest
concentrations of vegetarians and vegans in the country, organizer
Loewen said the group hopes even more will join the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second consecutive year the Vegetarian Society has
sponsored such an event. Last year's ``Joy of Soy'' gathering at
Fort Mason was tightly focused on the vegetarian staple. About 500
people attended, Loewen said.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers decided to broaden the emphasis this year to include
all kinds of products - though many of those featured did contain
some form of soy.
</P>
<P>
   Loewen, who is also a nurse, said the health benefits are
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty to 70 percent of chronic illnesses in the United States
are diet-related, including heart disease, many types of cancer,
osteoporosis, arthritis and diabetes are just a few,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal is putting to rest the perception that vegetarian
diets are boring and bland.
</P>
<P>
   Vegan restaurateur Ann Wheat of Millennium wowed the crowd with
gourmet plantain tortes and cabbage-shiitake spring rolls.
</P>
<P>
   There were many variations of vegetable- and soy-based
``burgers'' and even soy-based corn dogs served with sweet and
spicy mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most popular were the chewy vegan cookies and brownies
from the Oakland-based company called NoCookie. The secret recipe
ingredient: prunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what keeps them moist,'' boasted the vendor.
</P>
<P>
   While most of those ``vegging out'' at the food festival are
already devout vegetarians, some, like Ed Lomasney, said they were
there to learn more about going meat-free and to try various
meat-free recipes by attending informational lectures by
dietitians, chefs and organics experts, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, I never met a vegetarian I didn't like,'' Lomasney
joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
