NYT-05-08-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-CRITERION-BOS &LR;      05-08 1560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CRITERION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM SCHOOL IN A CAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sandwiched between a Japanese restaurant and an Irish
bar on 52d street near Third Avenue is the modest brick home of two
companies developing the future of home entertainment _ Janus Films
and the Criterion Collection. A pair of posters frame the lobby. On
one side there is Orson Welles as the enigmatic Harry Lime in ``The
Third Man,'' while on the other Erich von Stroheim fixes his
eternal gaze out from Jean Renoir's ``Grand Illusion.'' It's a
small building consisting of two floors and an assortment of
offices and work spaces. Yet, on these few thousand square feet, a
handful of employees is producing as much work on as many films as
Louis B. Mayer created on his miles of backlot in MGM's heyday.
</P>
<P>
   Criterion obtains the rights to films, searches for the best
available components, runs them through a complex series of
computerized and digitized operations, adds supplementary
commentary tracks and creates, essentially, an entertaining film
school in a can.
</P>
<P>
   First the numbers: Nearly 4 million DVD players were sold in
1999, up from 350,000 in 1997, according to the trade publication
Video Business. According to the Video Software Dealers
Association, the number of PCs equipped with DVD drives has will
rise from 12 million in 1999 to an estimated 32 million by the end
of this year. There are now nearly 6,000 titles available and the
DVD Entertainment Group, a consortium of DVD providers, estimates
that number will rise to 8,500 by the end of the year. Homes with
DVD players bought 21 discs last year, three times more than the
1997 VHS numbers when that format was at its economic peak.
</P>
<P>
   The plants where the DVDs are pressed can't keep up with the
demand. An estimated 45 million discs _ at prices averaging about
$20 _ were sold last year. Nearly 30 million already have been
shipped to retailers this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent issue of Variety, the studios
earned $9.5 billion from domestic home entertainment (VHS, DVD,
Pay-Per-View) last year _ triple what they made from theatrical
rentals.
</P>
<P>
   There's gold in DVDs, and Criterion is just one of dozens of
companies planning to cash in.
</P>
<P>
   While the inside of Criterion, with imposing stacks of audio and
video components, makes it look like a souped-up version of the Bat
Cave, it has its roots in the scratchy black-and-white 16mm
art-film library of Janus Films.
</P>
<P>
   Criterion president Peter Becker, a graduate of Milton Academy
and Harvard '87, and his partner, Jonathan Turrell, whose fathers
were partners in Janus Films, are carrying the family tradition to
the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you've got an electronics engineering degree, it's
difficult to understand how the colorful lights intersect with the
cables and monitors and how the computer modules work together, but
one thing is certain _ the results are astounding.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Anderson, the director of DVD development, who started as a
Criterion intern six years ago after graduating from the University
of Colorado film school, explains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Putting pieces together &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically start the production process by searching for the
best available film elements,'' he said, while working his way
through the labyrinthine complex. ``We piece together sections of
negative with chunks of release prints that we find sometimes at
the major studios in Los Angeles or in film archives in Europe.
While we usually start at the studios, they are usually not the
best places to find material. Sometimes the studios don't even know
what they own.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the pre-home-video movie moguls believed films were
perishable commodities _ destined for a few days or weeks in
theaters. Now, with so many ancillary markets, movies have become
completely recyclable.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson opens the door to a small room where David Lean's
``Brief Encounter'' (1945) is playing on a monitor. The
black-and-white cinematography sparkles, and the soundtrack,
featuring Rachmaninoff's Second Piano Concerto, has never sounded
crisper.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says it's often easier working on vintage films because
the camera was kept much steadier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They concentrated much more on the acting,'' he says, as
Trevor Howard stares longingly at Celia Johnson. ``They weren't as
interested in a showy style. We try to assemble the closest thing
to a camera negative. Then we begin a video-grade restoration. The
process picks up every flaw. If the camera jiggles a little bit it
gets picked up. They were much steadier in the old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, Will Salas and Benjamin Rabitor are working on a
restoration of ``The Blob,'' a 1958 horror film starring Steve
McQueen and featuring a title song composed by Burt Bacharach. It's
a print that looks as if it's been run through too many drive-in
projectors. At the time, ``The Blob'' symbolized the Red Menace
threatening small-town America, with its ever-growing, red oozing
mass. But at the moment, Salas and Rabitor are not interested in
the figurative. They're trying to remove more than 30 years of
dirt, scratches, and other examples of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Rabitor, seated at the monitor, hits a few computer keys and a
thin red box imprisons a particularly ornery scratch. He strikes
annother key and the scratch disappears. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Creating missing frames &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer's sometimes too smart,'' says Salas. ``If you let
it have its own way it reads everything with a slightly gray tinge.
But what's amazing is that if there's a frame completely missing,
the computer reads the preceding frame and the following frame and
creates the missing frame based on that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston-born Michael W. Wiese, who supervises the audio elements,
is in New York for some discussions on upcoming titles, but he does
most of his work from his home in Sante Fe, where he's currently
editing down six hours of commentary from Jimmy Cliff on ``The
Harder They Come'' for its DVD release sometime later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some DVD producers just let the subjects talk over the film
extemporaneously,'' says Weise, who's wearing a Boston Bruins cap.
He prefers to edit the commentary. ``You can't expect people to be
witty and sharp and intelligent speaking into a microphone for an
hour and a half or two. It usually doesn't work. At least for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from matching a director or star's observations to the
footage, Weise, a former musician, is also responsible for
eliminating annoying noises on the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start by eliminating the clicks and ticks and crackles,'' he
says. ``Then, the tiny hums and minor sounds. Then they put it
through a Dolby digital process that sometimes exposes new problems
we hadn't heard before. It's very time-consuming. You've got to be
very careful going through all the levels of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the technical renovations, Criterion prides itself on
its ability to attract the film's creators to talk about the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on the three-disc set of `Brazil,' '' says Anderson.
``and Terry Gilliam was very active in the whole process.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Brazil'' resurrected &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil'' is a magnificent case in point for the power of DVD
to resurrect a director's version of a movie. In 1985, Gilliam
delivered a bleak, futuristic comedy to Universal Studios. They
rejected it and ordered it recut without Gilliam's consent. Through
the intercession of Criterion, Gilliam restructured his original
film and viewers can now see the 142-minute film as he intended.
Not only that, the set also includes the 94-minute cut version
(which bears little relation to Gilliam's), a 30-minute on-the-set
documentary featuring Gilliam, star Jonathan Pryce, and
screenwriter Tom Stoppard, among others; Jack Matthews's
documentary on the battle over control of the movie; a production
notebook with Stoppard and cowriter Charles McKeown discussing the
script's evolution through three treatments and three drafts, and a
remarkable audio track where Gilliam's commentary details the
destruction of his idiosyncratic vision by bureaucratic marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get Peter Weir to talk about his early work on
`Picnic at Hanging Rock,' '' says Anderson. ``Weir told me that the
film is about the impossibility of knowing for certain what
happens. He declined to do a commentary track we respect his
position. Our goal is to present the film the way the filmmaker
wants it presented.''
</P>
<P>
   While Criterion owns most of the Ingmar Bergman titles, the
Swedish director also has declined several invitations to
participate in the process. But that doesn't affect the
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a film like `The Virgin Spring,' it's important to
preserve the quality and integrity Bergman expected,'' states Steve
Riforgiato, vice president of sales and marketing for Home Vision,
the distributor of home video for Janus Films and Criterion. ``Our
viewers no longer hope for the best, they anticipate it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest was always in the films and not in the means of
transmission,'' says William Becker, Criterion president Peter
Becker's father and one of the original partners in Janus Films
back when founder Cy Harvey ran it out of the back offices of the
Brattle Theatre in Cambridge, Mass. ``But I must say this is very
impressive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
