<HEADLINE>
AGGRESSIVE SAVING SHOULD KEEP PROGRAM ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Due to being married to a drug addict and all of the
accompanying financial problems, I have contributed to my
retirement savings erratically; some years the maximum, some years
nothing. I am now divorced (with two children and no child support)
and am attempting to catch up and save regularly. How close am I to
being on track? I plan to establish Roth IRAs each year in the
future. My 401(k) plan now has a new option to invest in Franklin
Small Cap Growth fund. Should I put some into that one?
</P>
<P>
   L.W., Escondido, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you maintain your aggressive saving pace, you'll be in
great shape. A lot of people your age are just starting to get
serious about retirement saving, and few have savings targets as
high as yours. I suspect experience has taught you something about
discipline, and the most important thing for you to do _ even if it
requires slightly reducing your savings level _ is to get into a
saving groove that will break the irregular pattern of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some projections (I did not include the bank savings in these
tallies, and I assume you are making the same proportional 401(k)
contributions from your bonuses as from your base salary):
</P>
<P>
   If you achieve 10 percent average returns from the total
portfolio and maintain the contributions at current levels, you
would have $2,153,415 at age 60, and $3,631,413 at 65. If you
maintain your savings level as a percentage of earnings, the totals
would increase significantly as your earnings increase.
</P>
<P>
   Those additions could be important, because if inflation runs at
an average 3.5 percent for 26 years, the accumulation at age 60
would be the equivalent of a little more than $875,000 in today's
dollars. The projected accumulation for age 65 would be the
equivalent of a little less than $1.5 million in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the lower level, you certainly would have enough to
maintain your current life style _ which I tally as your earnings
less the amount you are now contributing to your retirement savings
_ plus leave yourself a good deal of money to invest to offset the
inflation that is likely to come after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   I have no major problem with your portfolio as it now stands,
but I am unenthusiastic about that $1,000 in Van Eck Global Hard
Assets, a natural resources fund with heavy participation in the
precious metals area. As that fund's 8.61 percent five-year record
shows, such funds tend to produce only mediocre long-term results,
although short-term they can be spectacular. My suggestion would be
to swap that position for the new offering, Franklin Small-Cap
Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   You might also consider substituting an overseas fund for Janus
Worldwide, provided one is available. As a way to participate in
overseas markets, Janus Worldwide is less than perfect, since about
30 percent of its portfolio consists of large-cap US stocks _
precisely what you are already holding in the Standard and Poor's
Index fund. But if there is no purely international fund available,
I wouldn't worry about it. Janus Worldwide has an excellent record,
so you could just tally your exposure to the overseas markets as 70
percent of whatever the Janus Worldwide position is, and add 30
percent to your large-cap domestic position when judging the
balance of your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I suggest you use your plan to fully fund Roth IRA
accounts in future years to branch out into some more aggressive
elements for your portfolio. Since the after-tax money that goes
into a Roth account will produce tax-free earnings, the Roth
accounts are where you want to make your most aggressive market
plays. I suggest you use this to establish positions in some sector
funds. For example, I'd begin with Vanguard Health Care fund,
following the next year with Fidelity Select Computer fund. Then
reassess your position, maybe repeating the same pattern in years
three and four.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps by that time some of the froth will have gone out of
Internet stocks, and there might be an offering in that arena that
offers prospects of some big winnings (and some spectacular flops
at this stage). Such investments are riskier than the funds you now
hold, but all of them are in markets with enormous upside
potential. And even though you feel that you haven't made a lot of
progress at age 34 (although I disagree) you're still more than 25
years away from the usual retirement age. Such funds will in all
likelihood provide a bumpy road, but over that very long time frame
they should reward you handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been with the MFS fund family for six years but would
like to get more dividends. For 1999, I got only about $14,000 from
my IRA portfolio. I also am drawing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   J.R., Dana Point, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a fairly tough call. You have a substantial amount in
higher-yielding bond funds: the MFS High Income and the MFS
Strategic Income funds. Transferring from the MFS Government
Security fund to one of those, or to a similar higher-yielding
fund, would increase risk. And moving out of MFS Massachusetts
Investors Trust, your only stock fund, would eliminate the one
element of the portfolio that should keep it growing and
accordingly would offer you some protection against inflation. But
its yield, 0.2 percent, is nearly negligible.
</P>
<P>
   I'd suggest one of two courses:
</P>
<P>
   Cut the Massachusetts Investors position to an even $100,000,
putting the proceeds into the High Income fund, which would net you
an additional $1,787 annually in income.
</P>
<P>
   Or, look to the solid longer-term results of Massachusetts
Investors and decide you could safely withdraw $2,000 a year from
that position, calculating that over time a 1.6 percent annual
withdrawal rate should not seriously dampen the position's ability
to protect you against future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   I'd take the second course.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel you would need still more income, you could probably
draw more from that position, but I would draw the line at about
$3,500, or roughly 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it a great risk to roll over our $210,000 in IRAs into an
IRA annuity? The offer, from an insurance company, is 7.65 percent
interest the first year and 6.25 percent in the remaining five
years.
</P>
<P>
   V.H., Chatanooga, Tenn. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The rate being offered is well below what you can get with
CDs. Entering this week, the nation's best rate for five-year CDs
of $100,000 or more was 7.46 percent. Put your IRAs into such CDs,
at the end of the five years you'd have $304,549. If you take the
annuity offer, you would have $290,786 by the end of the fifth
year, and $309,459 at the end of the sixth year. Thus you would
have to achieve only 1.6 percent interest returns in the sixth year
for the CD to tie the annuity. The odds are overwhelming that you
will do a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures, of course, do not reflect the mandatory minimum
withdrawals you will be required to take, but even if those were
calculated, the best bank rate is superior to what this annuity
offers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
