<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP LOOKS FOR RECONCILIATION WITH MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As George W. Bush and John McCain prepare to meet Tuesday for
the first time since the primaries ended, uncertainty about the
warmth of their tete-a-tete dogs the presumptive Republican nominee
and potentially imperils his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Will Bush be greeted with enthusiasm, as his campaign hopes, or
will McCain continue to treat him with the cool hostility that has
marked their relationship since the South Carolina primary?
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems clear: Both sides agree there will be no
endorsement for the television cameras immediately following the
get-together in Pittsburgh, expected to last an hour. Bush campaign
officials, however, are hoping that the promise of a prime-time
role at the Republican convention in Philadelphia this summer will
nudge McCain along on the path toward reconciliation. And McCain is
expected to endorse Bush's candidacy eventually.
</P>
<P>
   The two camps have been engaged in a delicate dance for weeks.
Aides to Bush called the meeting crucial toward helping the Texas
governor attract independent voters and beat Vice President Al Gore
in November. However, McCain aides have maintained a studied
take-it-or-leave-it indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how many people care about politics right now
anyway,'' said John Weaver, McCain's political director. ``Although
people who committed to John are looking for a signal about where
he is headed and how enthusiastic he will be about the governor. .
. . These initial discussions will help indicate how enthusiastic
he will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and advisers to Bush warned that McCain's conduct will
have as much bearing on his own presidential ambitions as it will
on Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McCain has any political future, how he handles this is
going to have a lot to say about what future he has,'' said Will
Abbott, a former political director for Bush's father during the
1988 New Hampshire primary. ``If he's an impudent child he has no
future in the Republican Party, and if he's a mature senior member
of the party, he has another crack at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates and campaign staffs have nursed bruised feelings
since dropping all pretense of friendliness following McCain's
lopsided victory in New Hampshire. In South Carolina, the religious
right massed against McCain, passing along rumors of drug addiction
by his wife, a black child in their family, adultery, and an
illegitimate child. Bush ran television ads questioning McCain's
commitment to funding breast cancer research even as McCain's own
sister battles the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, McCain's campaign issued a ``Catholic voter
alert,'' phone calls to Catholic voters telling them of Bush's
visit to Bob Jones University in South Carolina, where students are
prohibited from interracial dating and the pope has been compared
to Satan.
</P>
<P>
   Since McCain dropped out of the race, tensions escalated as Bush
said he had learned nothing from McCain and would change nothing
about his own positions based on McCain's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the Bush campaign considered jobs for a few
members of McCain's team, they were met with total rejection. Even
McCain's bus driver on the ``Straight Talk Express'' refused to
work for Bush despite strong wooing. McCain aides strongly
discouraged the driver, Greg Price, from jumping ship because of
the symbolism his departure would provide. Price is expected to
drive McCain to the Republican convention this summer instead.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush and McCain get together they are expected to talk
about Social Security, education, health care, the military, and
campaign finance reform. McCain's role at the convention will be on
the table, too, and Bush is expected to sound him out about running
for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, has strenuously rejected that idea and is
expected to brush the governor back if the topic is raised.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers are likely to analyze every syllable uttered
by the politicians as they emerge from their meeting, looking for
hidden messages and nuances. And there's no real agreement on
whether strong backing from McCain will bring along his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's support really isn't transferable,'' said John J.
Pitney, a political scientist at Claremont McKenna College in
California. ``People aren't going to switch their November
preferences based on what John McCain says unless he decides to
become a problem and start criticizing Bush openly.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell M. West, a political science professor at Brown
University, said that while most voters have moved on since the
primaries, a small segment intend to take their cue from McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has incredible credibility among a certain set of
voters, namely independent swing voters, and they are the voters
Bush needs if he's going to win,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Abbott, a Bush supporter, said the tenor and texture
of McCain's words at this meeting are critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure John McCain would be greatly distressed if George
Bush didn't win the election,'' Abbott said. ``And that's why
anything less than an enthusiastic endorsement would hurt the
party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
