<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORKER MARKS ITS 75TH, WITH STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New Yorker threw itself a 75th birthday bash over
the weekend and danced fancy all over town.
</P>
<P>
   From Greenwich Village north to Times Square and beyond, it
strutted its stable of writers and poets and cartoonists for
audiences in love with the magazine and the idea of it.
</P>
<P>
   They came from British Columbia and North Carolina and the West
80s and Soho to hear Salman Rushdie and Zadie Smith, the way kids
from the Bay Shore of Long Island line up for Springsteen at the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The large names were here, save V.S. Naipaul, who was lost to
illness, and John Updike, who was holed up in his lair on the North
Shore of Boston, churning out his 600 words a day. The list
dazzled: William Trevor, Muriel Spark, Edna O'Brien, Julian Barnes,
Rushdie and Smith, Richard Ford, E. Annie Proulx, Alice Munro,
Stephen King, Jhumpa Lahiri, Tobias Wolff, Cynthia Ozick, Sherman
Alexie, T. Coraghessan Boyle, Nick Hornby.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just Friday night, when the Yankees beat the
Orioles in a roller coaster up in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Reading The New Yorker tea leaves has long been a pursuit
rivaled perhaps by Cold War Kremlinology. The practice has been
feverish this birthday year, as readers ponder questions like:
</P>
<P>
   Has editor David Remnick brought the magazine back to the center
after a spell out on the warning track under Tina Brown?
</P>
<P>
   Are the cartoons still funny?
</P>
<P>
   Is it a bad thing that John McPhee no longer writes 80,000 words
on the history of the Ping-Pong ball?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, no, and no.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares? More interesting was the speculation about the
audiences this weekend. Would they be a hoary bunch pining for a
literary Camelot where people still drink gin and where station
wagons still come with real wood paneling? Would they be gaunt New
York Review of Books types in Birkenstocks? Village people in
fuschia with lip rings? Banana Republic SUV jockeys?
</P>
<P>
   They were, in their splendor, all of the above. Friday night,
when the fiction blitz lit up the city at 8 p.m. in 13 different
spots at once, legations of Prozac Nation in reading glasses were
overwhelmed by strange and wondrous urban creatures in Doc Martens
and dreadlocks who floated through the first tropical night of the
year like lightning bugs. Score one for youth.
</P>
<P>
   The arteries hardened on Saturday, when the theater critic John
Lahr talked in the hush of the Morgan Library about Noel Coward to
a crowd whose average age was 60, by his own estimate. And over on
Seventh Avenue, Adam Gopnik spoke about the magazine's most
brilliant artist, Saul Steinberg, to an audience with a 50-year
spread. (Gopnik reported that Steinberg once had told him, ``First
grade is a shock from which we never recover.'')
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was a smorgasbord or a nightmare, depending on your
energy level. Charles Gates interviewed UN Secretary General Kofi
Annan, Calvin Trillin waxed on about humor, Remnick queried Paul
Simon about songwriting, outlaw singer/songwriter Steve Earle
played some new tunes. Then there were the panels _ on the
Internet, presidential politics, medicine, journalism, and young
writers.
</P>
<P>
   The options were as exhausting as was the logistical challenge
of trying to get to them, on a day of steamy temperatures and
Midtown gridlock from the throngs paying their respects to the late
Cardinal John O'Connor, who lay in state at St. Patrick's
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this chaos, the ill-fated New Yorker bus tour of
Manhattan's landmark buildings, led by the architecture critic Paul
Goldberger, departed its perch by Saks Fifth Avenue, a festival
sponsor that featured blow-ups of New Yorker cartoons in its
windows.
</P>
<P>
   This jaunt was not for the faint of heart. The double-decker bus
secured by the magazine had itsy-bitsy windows and no air
conditioning. The heat inside surely rivaled the innards of a
Sherman tank in a firefight with Rommel somewhere near Tobruk.
</P>
<P>
   And with the roof squarely in place, riders could gaze at the
first five stories of the skyscrapers whose hallowed spires
Goldberger described in detail _ while the vehicle remained stuck
in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   It was about this time that the birthday bash acquired the feel
of a forced march. Springtime in New York be damned, cabs suddenly
looked swell and a nap better than sex. Culture can be a brutal
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who could get a ticket rallied that evening for the
humor review at Town Hall. Playwright Wendy Wasserstein adapted
some of the wittiest writing from the magazine's 75 years. Swoosie
Kurtz, Alec Baldwin, Buck Henry, and Christopher Durang then read
the material with panache on stage. Some of it flopped, but most
was priceless.
</P>
<P>
   There was James Thurber's ``Mr. Preble Gets Rid of His Wife'' _
(``Let's go down to the cellar.''); Robert Benchley's
``Questionnaire'' _ (``What are English actors saying?''); Andy
Borowitz's ``Emily Dickinson: The Jerk of Amherst'' _ (``Writing
poetry beats stealing cars.''). Ian Frazier envisioned Samuel
Beckett as an airplane pilot _ (``You are now free to move about
the cabin and hang yourselves.'')
</P>
<P>
   The events continued like rolling thunder Sunday, when the
brunches took place. There were eight of them, on subjects ranging
from cartoons to war, from jazz to crime. The cartoon gang, led by
Robert Mankoff and Roz Chast, assembled in the cafe on the eighth
floor of Saks Fifth Avenue, which offered a fabulous view of the
secret gardens of Rockefeller Center high above street level.
</P>
<P>
   All moaned good-naturedly about the magazine fact-checkers,
famous for their diligence with cartoons as well as text. Charles
Barsotti recalled being queried if a hot dog has 17 grams of fat in
it after one of his offerings included a wiener.
</P>
<P>
   The cartoonists finally provided faces to go with their storied
names. They also provided the delicious thrill of walking across
the ground floor of the store on a Sunday morning, when it is
closed to the public and free of all those women of a certain age
spritzing perfume atomizers at you like ray guns.
</P>
<P>
   By the the end of the weekend, it was clear that the hagiography
around the ancien regime under the late William Shawn, the
secretive mandarin who edited the magazine for more than three
decades, is fading. Which is fine with Remnick, who became the
editor of the magazine at the absurdly young age of 39 less than
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Yorker is not a museum, and I am not a curator,'' he
said last week in his office on the 20th floor of the Conde Nast
Building. Remnick pointed to the photos on the wall of his office
of two dead New Yorker icons, A.J. Liebling and Joseph Mitchell,
and said, ``I worshiped them, but they're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, will be the readership frozen in the same amber. The
demographics demand an infusion of young New Yorker readers. ``I am
not an ancient,'' he said, stating the obvious. It is no surprise
that Remnick publishes young authors like Jhumpa Lahiri and Zadie
Smith and pays close attention to popular music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Yorker was great on Vietnam,'' he noted. ``But it
missed the Beatles. It missed rock and roll for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet such lapses won't happen on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   If Shawn was a god to many, he was a martinet to others.
Rushdie, for one, does not miss his magazine for an obvious reason.
``I couldn't get published in The New Yorker of Mr. Shawn,'' he
said Friday night at the Public Theater. Shawn rejected Rushdie's
first story, he recalled, saying, ``We don't publish pastiches.''
</P>
<P>
   But such eddies are lost in the broad flow of The New Yorker's
history. Rushdie is now part of the family, whose breadth and
vitality were evident along with its genealogy. If the bash was
uneven and solipsistic, it was nonetheless unlike anything else in
recent memory in this city. To paraphrase the PBS fund-raising
television spot, if not The New Yorker, who?
</P>
<P>
   The festival closed with a dozen of the magazine's finest poets
reading from their works in Bryant Park, behind the New York Public
Library. The lawn was full of hundreds of listeners who withstood
the fetid late-afternoon air to hear the likes of Philip Levine,
Charles Simic, and Louise Gluck read to the city. The turnout was
grand for the hometown magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The only missing element was the French aerialist who was to
have walked on a high wire above the crowd. But city officials
denied The New Yorker the necessary permit. The cowards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
