<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEYTON-PLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS AFTER ``PEYTON PLACE,'' CAMDEN, MAINE CELEBRATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, Maine _ When Barbara Dyer heard in 1957 that the film
version of ``Peyton Place'' was going to be shot in Camden, alarm
bells rang in her head.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the quaint New England town of Woodstock, Vt., had
coldly refused to associate itself with Grace Metalious' scandalous
novel. The quaint Maine towns of Wiscasset, Skowhegan and
Waterville were abuzz, weighing the promised income against the
danger of moral decay. Even the newspaper editor in Lewiston, a
town not quaint enough to make the director's short list, offered
his lofty two cents: ``We somewhat doubt,'' he wrote, ``if even the
broad-minded people of any Maine town would want it known as the
vicarious locale of such purposeless goings-on.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyer, who had read three pages of the novel before putting it
down in shock and disgust, heard the news and saw only disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   So it is ironic that, at the age of 75 and now the town
historian, Dyer helps to celebrate ``Peyton Place'' in a spirit of
playful 1950s nostalgia. Last weekend, as part of a film festival
on the theme ``Small Towns, Steamy Movies,'' Camden hosted fans of
the seminal small-town melodrama, walking them through Allison
McKenzie's sexual awakening, Selena Cross's pregnancy by her
stepfather and Betty Anderson's tenure as a parking lot siren. Dyer
is the first to admit it: Episodes that, in 1957, seemed to drill
into the marrow of human decency now seem almost quaint.
</P>
<P>
   But time has not entirely softened the story of ``Peyton
Place.'' Behind the weekend fun was the grim true experience of
Metalious, whose life was wrecked by the book she wrote. A lifelong
New Hampshirite from a poor Franco-American family, Metalious
declared war on Yankee New England with her first novel. The sex
scenes that titillated a nation were only the most obvious
transgression; behind every door in her fictional town lay an ugly
secret _ whether it be ethnic hatred, Doc Swain's abortion
services, the town fathers' desire to wipe poor families off the
map, or the everyday malice leveled at individuals who broke the
community's rules.
</P>
<P>
   Metalious's portrait of small-town life gave New England the
treatment usually reserved for the South. ``To the tourists,''
Metalious told one reporter, ``these towns look as peaceful as a
picture postcard, but if you go beneath the picture it's like
turning over a rock with your foot. All kinds of strange things
crawl out.''
</P>
<P>
   Words like that did not go unpunished. As ``Peyton Place'' broke
records in the publishing world _ it sat at No. 1 on the New York
Times's best-seller list for 59 weeks _ New England reviewers,
librarians and schoolteachers vilified Metalious and her book.
Camden's library did not stock ``Peyton Place'' when Mike Robson
decided to film the movie there; neither did the library in
Gilmanton, N.H., where Metalious lived, until Barbara Walters
donated one on a visit.
</P>
<P>
   But what got to Metalious was the personal snubbing, said Ardis
Cameron, a University of Southern Maine professor who uses ``Peyton
Place'' to teach social commentary in her New England Studies
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like she had an `A' on her,'' said Melissa Preston, 44,
who grew up in Gilmanton and now works at the Chamber of Commerce
in Camden. ``In New England, you shun something that is morally
wrong in your eyes. It affects your family to be seen with that
person.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was with Metalious, who was 32 when ``Peyton Place'' was
published: She was shunned, according to her friends and
biographers, as painfully as any character in her book. In
Gilmanton, people ostracized her children and crossed the street to
avoid her, said her then-husband, George Metalious. Once, flush
with her new success, Metalious invited all the town's citizens to
stay with her at the Plaza in New York, and none of them accepted,
Cameron said. When the film ``Peyton Place'' premiered in Camden to
great fanfare, Maine resident Bette Davis was on hand, but
Metalious was not.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked Metalious about it, she said she was not
invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people thought Grace was a trashy person,'' said Emily
Toth, a professor at Louisiana State University who published
``Inside Peyton Place,'' a biography of Metalious, in 1981. ``I
remember sitting in a library in Laconia and local citizens would
say things like, `If you found out the truth about her it would
really curl your hair.' There was a way in which they were still
mad at her.''
</P>
<P>
   In her peculiar isolation, Metalious began to drink heavily.
Near the end, she ate almost nothing but big salads at night time,
Toth said.
</P>
<P>
   Metalious died of cirrhosis of the liver in 1964, at age 39,
seven years after her blockbuster success. According to Frances
Hugelman, 84, who lives in Metalious's old house, there was a
sincere attempt by some citizens of Gilmanton to prevent her being
buried in the town cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   When tourists asked to see Metalious's grave, Preston recalled,
townspeople ``wouldn't even show them where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But the events in Camden have a gentle, nostalgic tone, geared
less toward revisionist historians than film buffs such as Frank
Anzalone.
</P>
<P>
   For Anzalone, a Philadelphia stage director who was a boy when
the movie was released, the lush technicolor and hectic embraces of
``Peyton Place'' preserve the delicious appeal of the forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about an innocent time, and about sex being verboten,''
he said. ``There's a fascination with that, because we've certainly
gone the other route. If you look around, there is no innocence
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie that came out of Camden was far less disturbing than
Metalious's book, substituting a miscarriage for Selena Cross's
abortion, excising racist and ethnic ugliness and toning down a
host of seething sexual issues involving parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s television series ``Peyton Place'' was even more
benign, removing Selena Cross and Doc Swain from the scene
altogether. When the Camden Herald's editors defended their stance
in favor of allowing the filming, they made it clear that they had
little respect for the novel: ``It is a sorry day,'' they wrote,
``when the people of a state as steeped in freedom as Vermont or
the editors as conscientious as the (Lewiston) Sun argue against
the making of a movie because the book it is based on is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The gamble paid off for Camden, a sparkling coastal town where
the balance had been shifting from industry to tourism for many
years. Although Camden had long drawn wealthy summer people, the
movie's lush scenery helped establish ``leaf-peeping'' as a
middle-class pastime, said Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, fans of the movie trickled in, and it became
clear that Camden's potential scandal had grown into a legitimate
tourist attraction culminating in the weekend festival, which was
complete with a re-creation of Allison McKenzie's Prom Night and
appearances by two of the film's actors.
</P>
<P>
   But New Englanders are still prepared to debate whether
Metalious drew an accurate picture of small-town life. One elderly
resident recalled moving to Camden a few years after the film came
out and expressing disgust at the film's depiction of a town full
of malicious gossip and dark secrets. Overhearing her comment, an
elegant older neighbor took her aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear, talk to me after you've lived here long enough to
know your neighbors a little better,'' she said. ``We'll see what
you think then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
