<HEADER>
A8882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-DONS-BOS &LR;      05-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LEGENDARY ACADEMICS, UP CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE DONS 
Mentors, Eccentrics and Geniuses 
By Noel Annan. University of Chicago Press. 357 pp. Illustrated.
$30. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before there were playing fields at Eton, the British had
raised insiderdom to an art form. In the last century, it had few
finer practitioners than Noel Annan, who died in February at age
83. An insider's insider, he was to the British Establishment what
Olivier and Richardson were to the West End.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of King's College, Cambridge, Annan was a
military-intelligence officer during World War II. He returned to
King's as a fellow, then provost. He later was provost at
University College, London, then became vice chancellor of the
University of London. He was president of the London Library and
served on the boards of the British Museum, National Gallery, and
Royal Opera. Annan also chaired the government committee on the
future of broadcasting that led to the creation of Britain's
Channel 4. For these and numerous other accomplishments, he was
made an officer of the Order of the British Empire, and a Labour
government (Annan wasn't a complete insider) elevated him to the
House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   His academic specialty was intellectual history. Such books as
his study of Leslie Stephen, the 19th-century man of letters who
was Virginia Woolf's father, and ``Our Age,'' Annan's magisterial
examination of the cultural impact of the generation that came of
age between the two world wars, combine a wonderfully vigorous
prose style with a dauntingly encyclopedic knowledge. Not only did
Annan know everyone that mattered (or so it could seem to readers
of his many New York Review of Books articles, wherein his dropping
of names was simply the pursuit of footnoting by other means). He
could also give the impression of knowing everything that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to conceive of anyone better situated to write a book
like ``The Dons,'' Annan's highly affectionate yet by no means
worshipful look at some of the more remarkable academic personages
to distinguish _ and sometimes dumbfound _ Oxford and Cambridge
over the past two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Annan makes no claim to be comprehensive. These are simply the
men _ and a few women _ who seem to him representative,
particularly interesting, or (in several instances) of whom he was
personally fond. Some are famous, such as John Henry Newman;
Benjamin Jowett, the translator of Plato; or the physicists J. J.
Thomson and Ernest Rutherford. Others claim a narrower renown, such
as Maurice Bowra and Isaiah Berlin. A few would seem to be included
as much for their oddities as anything else. There is, for example,
the Cambridge historian Oscar Browning, who upon seeing the
incumbent poet laureate eagerly introduced himself: ``Hello
Tennyson. I'm Browning.'' (Lord Alfred replied, ``No, you're
not.'') Or there was the Cambridge classicist of whom a college
master complained, ``What time he can spare from the adornment of
his person he devotes to the neglect of his duties.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that it cherishes eccentricity and abounds in Oxbridge
gossip, ``The Dons'' is at heart a deeply serious book, one
dedicated to a conception of learning and culture that is at once
increasingly rare (on both sides of the Atlantic) yet very far from
being outmoded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities,'' Annan writes, ``should hold up for admiration
the intellectual life. The most precious gift they have to offer is
to live and work among books or in laboratories and to enable the
young to see those rare scholars who have put on one side the world
of material success, both in and outside the university, in order
to study with single-minded devotion some topic because that above
all seems important to them. A university is dead if the dons
cannot in some way communicate to the students the struggle _ and
the disappointments as well as the triumphs in that struggle _ to
produce out of the chaos of human experience some grain of order
won by the intellect. That is the end to which all the arrangements
of the university should be directed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dons'' concludes with Annan's celebrated 1956 essay, ``The
Intellectual Aristocracy,'' a fitting coda to a book from a man who
so clearly belonged at the fore of any such body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1342EDT &QL; 
