<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SILENCE-BOS &LR;      05-08 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SILENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FABLE OF LUTENIST STRIKES A HOLLOW NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AMY GRAVES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MUSIC AND SILENCE 
By Rose Tremain 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 485 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year is 1629, the hero plays the lute in the royal orchestra
of King Christian IV of Denmark, and the plot is simple: He's about
to fall in love. Will he get the girl?
</P>
<P>
   You have to wait almost 400 pages to find out, and what happens
in between doesn't fit neatly into any category. Billed as
historical fiction, Rose Tremain's ``Music and Silence'' is
anything but.
</P>
<P>
   It's a romance novel that happens to be set in a long-ago time.
Or it's fable _ a sad king struggles to save his country from debt
and himself from his adulterous second wife; the lutenist loves a
young girl who's lost her chief protector with the death of her
mother; and a countess's husband goes mad trying to remember a song
he's heard only in his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Fables are supposed to teach us something. The book promises
enlightenment early on: As one attendant to King Christian's wife
tells another, ``a fable can awaken the mind to the truth of what
it perceives in the daily world.'' Tremain offers us familiar fairy
tales about growing up and making your way in the world; her story
of the boy made king before he's old enough to assume power is
engaging, if a little old hat.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, though, it's a false hope. This book teaches us
little beyond the value of plot. The characters are flat and their
actions predictable. If you read on, it's to see how Tremain works
it all out. With few exceptions, the characters are either entirely
good or entirely wicked. The wicked ones are amusing; the good ones
are pathetic and boring.
</P>
<P>
   Take the lutenist, Peter Claire. His angelic good looks and
perfect playing are dull enough. On top of this, the reader must
struggle with incredulity: One minute he's recovering from the loss
of a lover, the Italian-born Countess O'Fingal, and the next he's
in thrall to Emilia, a motherless child he's just met who proves
the opposite of the brave, mature countess in every way.
</P>
<P>
   Growing old is no fun in ``Music and Silence.'' The most nuanced
character, King Christian, starts out as a boy who sees the world
``not as it was, but as his mind reconstituted it,'' a brave and
benevolent soul who puts a forger to work as a royal printer,
rather than sentencing him to death, out of admiration for his
skill. From this promising start he's reduced to begging gold from
his mother to finance work on a silver mine in Norway, so he can
save Denmark from financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest women in the book _ the countess and the king's
second wife, Kirsten _ never get what they want, though Tremain
seems determined to pair everyone else off. Kirsten is the one
truly memorable character, if only because she's painted in
hilarious extremes, especially in her journal entries, which are
peppered with unnecessary capitalization and passages betraying her
complete lack of self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   She's punished for her sins. Not only divorced by the king,
she's abandoned by everyone except her servants: ``I find myself in
a house of Shadows with only the Furniture to talk to, but even
this . . . seems to have risen up against me. Worst and rudest of
these Things are the Mirrors on the walls. Whenver I pass by one,
it contrives to Distort me, so that instead of seeing myself as I
am . . . what I am shown is a Scowling and Plump Object that I do
not recognize at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tremain has written at least one highly praised work of
historical fiction, ``Restoration,'' about Charles II and the
return of royal rule to England. ``Music and Silence'' does not
measure up to that standard. It offers much drama and stunning
cruelty, but little insight into the human condition of any time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1343EDT &QL; 
