<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     05-08 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITNEY'S THE SALON TALK OF THE TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My daughter wanted to know if it was true that Whitney Houston
is addicted to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   I told her I didn't know, but I hope not.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the look of concern on her face as she asked the
question, it occurred to me how involved we can become in the lives
of people we only read about in newspaper headlines, see on
television and in the movies, or in magazine photographs.
</P>
<P>
   We talk about them as if they were our best friends or next-door
neighbors or both. We laugh at them and with them. We criticize
them and we mourn when they die.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Vivian Thorne, owner of Vivian's Healthy Hair, during
a recent conversation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whitney had put the old boy out so when he went on Jay Leno,
she called up Jay Leno and told him to put Bobby (Brown) on the
phone. Girl, Whitney told Bobby to come on back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughter filled the salon and everybody in the know _ that
wouldn't include me _ knew the punch line: Brown (Houston's
husband) had the goods on Whitney, Vivian said, and she wanted to
keep him quiet.
</P>
<P>
   I won't say what the goods are for two reasons: They're too
risque and it wouldn't be right to spread rumors or allegations
that very well may be false.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it's Saturday morning and Vivian is on a roll even
though she passes on the doughnuts and coffee she's doling out to
her sleepy clients.
</P>
<P>
   She moves breathlessly from Whitney to Luther Vandross back to
Whitney to Oprah _ laughter spewing from every other word _ until I
finally ask Vivian, ``Where do you get all that stuff? The National
Inquirer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, that's salon talk,'' she says, as if that makes it more
credible.
</P>
<P>
   While ``salon talk'' isn't necessarily based in fact, it
occurred to me much later how easily it is passed on as such.
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, salon talk is a substitute for the
conversations we used to have over the backyard fence, when life
was simpler and we had time to stop and talk, share recipes,
discuss what the children were doing, find out who'd given birth,
who died or who just got married.
</P>
<P>
   And when you're in the salon _ unless you're dozing under a hot
dryer _ that's what you do. The magazines and books are in your lap
only as props. After all, not everyone _ especially the few with
the Bibles and motivational books _ want it known that they'd
willingly participate in idle gossip, which is what salon talk
amounts to most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to say this is all bad. Sometimes we actually talk
about things that are important, in which case salon talk becomes a
way to exhale, to unwind and unload about work, the children, the
husband and life in general.
</P>
<P>
   That itself makes salon talk not just important but necessary.
It's like therapy without the big bill, confession without the
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   I don't feel like a moral failure for listening, for instance,
to unsubstantiated allegations about Whitney Houston or about
Luther Vandross' lifestyle. I don't feel as though I am backsliding
because I find the comedy in it all strangely uplifting.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's nothing funny about some of the gossip we
hear about celebrities _ who they're sleeping with, who they marry,
and their personal habits. But it occurred to me that a reason our
lives seem so entangled with theirs is that they have ascended to a
place we'd like to be but will never reach, and because they
reflect the dark places in our own lives.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
