<HEADER>
A8887 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-BALKANS-BOS &LR;      05-08 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-BALKANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BARD IN THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE FOSTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Two weeks before previews, Slobodan Unkovski
doesn't know how he's going to end ``The Winter's Tale,'' which he
is directing for the American Repertory Theatre. It doesn't concern
him much; he's used to working this way. And it doesn't seem to
concern the actors, who have learned to love his intuitive,
collaborative style and trust that he _ and they _ will work it
out.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why Unkovski might be a little uneasy over the
ending. ``The Winter's Tale,'' one of Shakespeare's last works, is
a play both beautiful and difficult. It's usually viewed as a tale
of reconciliation after a raft of tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   What happens is this: When King Leontes gets suddenly and wildly
jealous over the attention his wife, Hermione, is paying to their
guest, his best friend, Polixenes, it sets in motion a series of
terrible events. Going from zero in nothing flat, he sends
Hermione, who is pregnant, to prison. Then he orders their newborn
daughter to be taken into exile and abandoned. His young son dies.
And just at the point where he finds out he's wrong, he's told that
Hermione is dead. He spends the next 16 years paying for his
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Even though at the end he is restored to his daughter and,
seemingly magically, to his wife, how do you get a truly happy
resolution out of all that tragedy? Is a modern audience going to
believe that a woman will easily forgive a man whose jealousy
wreaked such havoc with her life? Can this marriage be saved? That
is the problem this director is trying to solve.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare is terse with the details: There is a reference to
Hermione embracing her husband. Other than that, it's not clear.
And Unkovski is mulling over what to make of that. ``At the end,
the short speech of the queen doesn't mention the king, just her
daughter. And Leontes just says, `Let's go, we have to talk.'
There's no real happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   He sits at a gateleg table in ART's apartment in Harvard Square
and mulls over the problem. ``I'm not going to help the people
forgive him and forget the mistake that he did at the beginning of
the play. At the end of the play, there will probably not be a
reconciliation. There are so many dead people, so many shadows and
ghosts onstage. There's no way of having a new beginning. The
things that happen are so terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirjana Jokovic, who plays Hermione, says the actors spent some
time talking about the question of forgiveness. ``I think
Hermione's always being pictured as an idealistic woman who is
capable of forgiving everything. But I think in our case, it's
about trying to face another reality: Is it too late for
forgiveness? What would forgiveness bring?
</P>
<P>
   ``Did she forgive Leontes? I don't think so. I don't think she
has anger and bitterness toward him, it's more of a question of her
being noble . . . and living with that curse of what happened to
her.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
What colors his outlook &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That the production is taking such a dark view may have
something to do with the fact that Unkovski is from Macedonia, one
of the republics of the former Yugoslavia. It was one of the
countries to which hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians fled
when expelled from Kosovo by the Serbs. His wife, a psychologist,
treated many of the refugees, as well as the Macedonians who opened
their homes to them. While this play is not being actively seen
through the lens of that strife, he says it no doubt colors his
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my plays connect with my life,'' he says. ``It's not just
a professional execution of a play. In the last 10 years, my work,
especially my work in the US, has been about trying to articulate a
silent scream about the Balkans.'' He staged ``Peer Gynt'' at the
beginning of the Slovenian war in 1991. His production of Dejan
Dukovski's ``The Powder Keg'' (``the first real excellent analysis
of the developing atrocities in the former Yugoslavia,'' he says)
toured to more than 30 theaters across Europe. And from 1996 to
1998, he took time out from directing to be Macedonia's minister of
culture. Currently he is professor of drama at the University of
Skopje in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   While Jokovic is also from the former Yugoslavia, and the set
director, Meta Hocevar, is from Slovenia, Unkovski gently
pooh-poohs the notion that they are a troika intent on stamping a
uniquely Balkan perspective on the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mirjana has acted nine years in the States. And Slovenia is
more likely to be part of Europe soon. I am the only one who is
coming from the Balkans. But I feel myself to be something of a
citizen of the world. I live and work there, but feel that
Macedonian culture gave so much to the world over the centuries
that it is more important than the terrible things that happened in
the Balkans in the last 50-100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Unkovski came to the United States in 1987 as a visiting
Fulbright Scholar at the City University of New York. He last
worked for ART 10 years ago when he directed ``The Caucasian Chalk
Circle.'' He's been in touch with artistic director Robert Brustein
ever since. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Like coming home'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent a letter (to Brustein) proposing a play for the next
season, to be taken from a novel, (MIT professor and playwright)
Alan Lightman's `Einstein's Dreams.' Bob said he already had the
season and suggested I do ``Winter's Tale.'' So I read the play
again. I thought I could find a good approach and sent them some
ideas. They liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   So after 10 years, he's back in Cambridge again. ``It was like
coming home. It's really beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the serious wrestling over the meaning of the play,
there's a sense of lightness and expansiveness in a rehearsal that
the actors say is typical of the whole process. In the church
basement that the company uses as a rehearsal space, a trio of
actors exits running giddily and whipping each other around in a
line. Karen MacDonald, who plays Paulina, starts a speech straight
and then throws in a Texas accent for the last line. Thomas Derrah,
who plays the pickpocket Autolycus, in the comedic section (yes,
there is funny stuff in this play!), merely has to walk across the
stage in a floppy beige coat and he gets snickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unka (the cast's nickname for Unkovski) likes to have fun in
rehearsals; that's rare. He likes people to enjoy themselves,''
says John Douglas Thompson, who plays Polixenes, the boyhood friend
of Leontes, and the king of Bohemia. ``What's unique about him is
everything doesn't need to be dark. He makes it possible to have
fun with the play and experience it to its fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Woronicz, who plays Leontes, concurs: ``We're working very
loose, we throw things out in terms of his ideas, use lots of
imagination. He has a lovely sense of humor and encourages us to
look at things differently.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Opposite kingdoms &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While much may be in flux up until previews start on May 12, one
thing that is established is that the two kingdoms in the play,
Sicilia and Bohemia, are diametrically opposed to each other in
mood and style.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sicilian side will be something very cold, rigid, with
sudden emotions,'' explains Unkovski. ``It will be based on some
kind of lost rationality. Sicilia, of course, is Sicily. But
Bohemia in the script doesn't match up to any particular country
nearby that has a coastline. So it's a made-up place. It will be
some place like North Africa, Morocco, different in culture and
habits. Bohemia will be something very warm, cool (as in hip, not
temperature), relaxed, and it will be based mostly on emotions:
love, joy, happinesss. So you'll have collisions between two
different worlds.
</P>
<P>
   The costumes will reflect this division: Those for Sicilia are
dark and confining, Bohemia's are light and fluid. And while
Unkovski steers clear of describing the sets (to not spoil the
surprise), in rehearsal the actors in a Bohemia scene were walking
on swaths of brilliantly colored fabric streaming across the long
room.
</P>
<P>
   A page from Bohemia makes a whooping cry as he enters. He sounds
like Tarzan. But Woronicz advised a reporter to not think that's
cast in stone. All is subject to change, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Is that true about the ending as well? Sure, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be about forgiveness by the time the play goes up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
