<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-STAIN-BOS &LR;      05-08 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST ROTH HERO UNDONE BY FREEDOM, IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE HUMAN STAIN 
By Philip Roth. Houghton Mifflin. 361 pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 40-year probe of the national psyche, Philip Roth has
hardly been bashful about putting his own consciousness under
scrutiny. Manic-expressive and sometimes dazzling to a fault, the
man has taken us on whirlwind expeditions through sex, death,
politics, and morality _ delivering, while he was at it, the modern
Jewish condition as well as half the continent of human neurosis.
Irony has been his cover but truth has been his point; revelation,
it seems, is a dish best served bittersweet. Toward this
not-always-noble end, he has let his alter ego, Nathan Zuckerman,
take most of the heat. If America itself, in all its vastness,
power, and madness, has been Roth's Lear, then Zuckerman,
insistently, has got to play the Fool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Stain'' is the end of a thematically linked trilogy
that began with the powerhouse beauty of ``American Pastoral,''
then stumbled badly through the vitriolic detours of ``I Married a
Communist.'' This last installment rights the edifice again, for
Roth has taken the classical underpinnings of ``American Pastoral''
and given us their shadowy counterpart _ a tragedy with shades of
Euripides and Shakespeare, set in the pseudo-pastoral confines of a
liberal arts college in the Berkshires. By rendering the downfall
of a good man _ a life cut short by hubris, secrecy, and human
folly _ Roth has given us a story of ancient dimension. By calling
his campus Athena College and by making his Delphic Oracle a saucy
little deconstructionist named Delphine Roux, he has made it,
inimitably, a modern novel of wickedly Rothian proportion.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the comic cruelty of, say, ``Sabbath's
Theatre,'' where Roth seemed to delight in Rabelaisian perils; nor
is Zuckerman off on one of his solipsistic footraces. Instead ``The
Human Stain'' is the sad and complex tale of Coleman Silk, an aged
classicist, and the choices he made and the ones he didn't _ the
road map of regret and indecision waiting for everyone who lives
long enough to earn the courage of hindsight. After devoting most
of his adult life to Sophocles and Homer _ to teaching half-formed
innocents that the world is full of strife, betrayal, beauty, and
murder _ Silk finds himself the fall guy in a classroom
misunderstanding of ludicrous proportion. Casting about for a
couple of absent students at the beginning of term, he refers to
them, in the ghostly sense, as ``spooks'' _ only later discovering,
upon being charged with making a racial slur, that the students are
black.
</P>
<P>
   This mare's nest sets the stage for Silk's estrangement and
eventual undoing; the young professors that he, as faculty dean,
had hired to upgrade Athena are of little use or loyalty when it
comes to defending the old (read: white male) guard, and he leaves
the college in an outrage. When Zuckerman meets him in summer 1998,
Coleman has been retired without honor for two years; he has buried
his wife, Iris (a casualty, he believes, of the scandal), and is
living in isolation in the old farmhouse in Western Massachusetts
where they raised four children. Well, near isolation: At 71,
virile and furious and still shadow-boxing with the specters of his
decline, he has taken up with a 34-year-old woman, Faunia Farley,
who works at Athena as a janitor, a woman apparently illiterate and
with a horrendous history of abuse and bad luck. When she and
Coleman find each other, it is a connection of immediacy and
honesty: They are neither one worried, at this point in life, about
what they have to lose.
</P>
<P>
   And Zuckerman, our town crier, is the equally isolated
neighbor-author whom Coleman befriends _ the wide-angle lens
through which we will view this story of the Professor Unbound.
We're introduced to Coleman and his past as one of the first Jews
invited into the patrician realm of classical studies; he has come
to Athena by way of NYU (and East Orange, N.J.) and breathed a
formidable new vitality into the college. Through a series of
crosscutting narratives and perspectives, the story of Coleman's
early years unfolds: the girls he loved and the boxing career he
barely sidestepped; the father who gave him perfect diction and
what he called ``the language of Chaucer, Shakespeare, and
Dickens.'' The child of humble roots _ his father an optician who
failed in the Depression, then a dining-car waiter; his mother a
nurse _ Coleman began a path of upward and outward mobility like
those of a million midcentury sons and daughters trying to make
their way in the world. But his own journey away from the past, his
effort to be ``just on his own and free,'' had a singular grief and
treachery at its center. And no amount of classical understanding _
of a life spent with the great tragedies of literature _ has been
able to lessen the wrenching effects of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Stain'' draws its title from an observation by
Faunia, whose weary rejection of bourgeois civilization has not
kept her from understanding one of Coleman's precious truths: that
humanity leaves its mark (of rage, desire, or both) on everything
in its wake, whether you see it as an imprint or a scar. It also
alludes to the central tragedy of this novel, which I've been loath
to reveal but which every other reviewer in America seems hellbent
on disclosing. Suffice it to say that Roth has invented a story of
exquisite personal suffering that resonates with the larger
upheavals of history _ where the sins of the children, it turns
out, are visited on generations before and since (see accompanying
story).
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Faunia had seen her share of trouble before Coleman
arrived, the most recent miseries inflicted by her former husband,
Les Farley, who came back after his second tour in Vietnam poised
far more for violence than for domesticity. Carrying here all the
rage of Achilles with precious little of the spoils, Farley is a
triumph of a creation, and it's testament to Roth's empathic skills
that the author was able to envision him. Now a heat-seeking
missile, Farley is reduced to the quivering sum of his fears in a
Chinese restaurant _ an agonizing scene of sauteed pork and
post-traumatic stress disorder and simply magnificent realism. In a
novel laden with depth of character and narrative insights, Roth
has managed to make a terrifying, hardly heroic man far less
terrifying than what befell him.
</P>
<P>
   Having stumbled upon a splendid lot of characters, all with
their own driving mysteries, Zuckerman has the good sense to stay
out of their way, but for a few stretches of long-winded
pontification. He is instead the melancholy vast intelligence and
narrative momentum of this story, which belongs to the tragic cast
upon the stage, their sorrows inevitably linked, then revealed, in
death. There are typically Rothian etchings along the way: that
Delphic theorist, clutching her Julia Kristeva and hiding her
all-too-human yearnings; Coleman's sister, Ernestine, who shows up
near the end of the novel to bestow it with grace. And there's a
laconic moment of stunning tenderness in a foxtrot on the porch of
Coleman's home _ Coleman and Zuckerman! _ which paves the way for
the unstrained mercy that must accompany this story. Finally, there
is Coleman Silk himself _ the confused and heartsore counterpart to
the Swede of ``American Pastoral,'' each man following out his
story of serendipity, private agony, and doom. Each man something
more, too: a wounded summation of all the deceits, love songs, and
little murders that make up the great American mythology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SIDEBAR: THE PLOT THICKENS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The great secret Coleman Silk has spent a lifetime protecting is
that he is a light-skinned black passing as a Jew. Roth's unveiling
of this central mystery _ why Coleman made the choice and what it
cost him _ is extraordinary, both in its eloquent comprehension of
the act and in its structural grace within the novel. Growing up as
a firecracker-talented black kid (and high school valedictorian) in
a predominantly Jewish neighborhood in the 1940s, Coleman slips
sideways into this dangerous territory of Self sacrifice: First he
is mistaken for being Jewish; then, upon the death of his father
(and his subsequent encounters, as a young man, with a racist
society), he dares to glance toward that unknown territory where
all things seem possible. Barely shy of his 18th birthday, he lies
about his age on a Navy enlistment form _ and then realizes that,
with the mark of a pen, he can change his race as well. By the time
he emerges in the free-form Greenwich Village of the postwar years,
the lie is set. And Coleman is carrying a concealed weapon that
will protect and threaten him for the rest of his days.
</P>
<P>
   It has been tempting for some to draw a parallel between Roth's
subject and the late New York Times critic Anatole Broyard, whose
bohemian life in mid-century New York mirrored some of Coleman's
here. But the comparison, which packages an age-old story in an au
courant frame, only goes so far. While Roth has made Coleman's
heartrending duplicity the subtle center of his novel, it is not
simply a story about passing. Instead it traces one of the great,
treacherous undercurrents of American literature: The same idea of
reinvention that drove Dreiser's Clyde Griffith and Fitzgerald's
Jay Gatsby. And like Gatsby's Nick Carraway, like Ahab's Ishmael,
Zuckerman alone has lived to tell the tale: ``I did no more than
find a friend,'' he tells us near the beginning of his story, ``and
all the world's malice came rushing in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
