<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PEOPLE SPEAK, AND THEY ACTUALLY AGREE WITH ME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not used to this. To praise, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   My mail, e-mail and phone messages usually run overwhelmingly in
favor of the widespread point of view that I'm an idiot. Some of
these messages are so mean and obscene that I can't even get all
the way through them without hitting the delete key or tossing them
into the trash.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my surprise at the favorable reaction to last week's
column praising the government for snatching EliAn Gonzalez from
his Miami relatives and reuniting him with his father. No kidding,
folks _ positive responses to that column vastly outnumbered the
critical messages.
</P>
<P>
   A quick tally of the first surge of phone calls, in fact, came
out 23-2 in my favor.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few highlights from the voice mail:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful. You said what I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My sentiments exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Cuban-American, and I live in Arlington, Texas. That
was a great article.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts completely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you run for political office, I'll vote for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The last one was scary, wasn't it? That reader's vote would
surely be the only one I'd get if I ran for office.
</P>
<P>
   Even I wouldn't vote for me.
</P>
<P>
   I appreciate the thought, though. When you spend a sizable chunk
of your day listening to people tell you how wrong you are, it's a
nice change of pace to suddenly get a truckload of ``atta boys.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt, of course, that my opinion on the Elian deal
just happened to be approximately the same as that held by a large
majority of Americans. Public-opinion polls suggest that anywhere
from 60 to 70 percent of the public has endorsed Attorney General
Janet Reno's decision to grab Elian by force and return him to his
Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time somebody gave Janet Reno the credit she
deserves in placing Elian back in his father's arms where he
belongs,'' wrote one e-mailer. ``I was beginning to think that the
Cubans in Miami had their own laws and were exempt from U.S.
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for my continued sense of humility, there were
dissenters. Frankly, I'd be distressed if I ever received a batch
of letters that didn't include at least a modicum of hate mail. I
would worry that my legions of detractors had stopped reading.
</P>
<P>
   One of the angrier responses came from a reader who apparently
took exception to my characterization of Elian's Miami relatives in
general as ``lunatic uncles and cousins'' and to Marisleysis
Gonzalez in particular as ``dangerously unstable.'' An excerpt:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your racism and xenophobia is evident ... since you have to
resort to petty insults to the latino community to make your
opinion known. Your kind of hatred died out a long time ago,
usually in the crosshairs of a Marine infantryman on D-Day ... did
you also cheer when the protesters at Kent State were mowed down?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not exactly sure what D-Day and Kent State have to do with
Elian Gonzalez, but the reader's objection to my opinion is duly
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader took issue with my description of the relatives
as ``kidnappers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Miami family was `kidnappers' as you so claim, why
weren't they arrested? Is it because of the kindness of Janet Reno?
Uh-huh. If you actually believe in the legality of the search and
arrest warrant produced ... to conduct this armed raid, I've got
some oceanfront property in Arizona I'd like to sell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I've been to Arizona _ I spent a month in Phoenix one
week _ and I wouldn't be interested in property there even if this
e-mailer could magically deliver an oceanfront lot. But I agree
with him on one thing: Why weren't the Miami relatives arrested?
They were holding the kid illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Reno knew she'd have her hands full just defending
the raid to her critics without putting herself in the position of
explaining why a hysterical Marisleysis was hauled off in
handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the reader who accused me of subscribing to
``that old saw _ the end justifies the means.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't everyone?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
