<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-PIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT BIG SALESPERSON IS WATCHING YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Willy Loman never had it so good.
</P>
<P>
   Five decades after Arthur Miller eulogized a salesman's life,
modern-day seller John Bacon keeps a crush of appointments,
callbacks, and drop-ins at arm's length, thanks to a laptop
computer and GoldMine 4.0 software. While crisscrossing half a
dozen states in a Dodge Caravan, Bacon uses the software to keep
appointments, record customer preferences, and track inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lost without it,'' says Bacon, the regional sales
manager for a pharmaceutical company.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to manage a gaggle of clients, though, to benefit
from personal information managers (PIMs) such as GoldMine.
Millions of people use them along with _ or in place of _
old-fashioned calendars and date books to organize their personal
lives.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that the software is affordable and widely available,
running as low as $30 in many places.
</P>
<P>
   Still, free is better.
</P>
<P>
   That's where online calendars enter the picture. These
on-the-house imitations of PIMs first appeared on the Web scene a
little more than a year ago, providing basic PIM functions as well
as access to local movie times, cultural and sporting events, TV
schedules, and other events about town.
</P>
<P>
   The catch? Most keep track of your schedule so they can sell you
things tied to your to-do list. They make money, in other words, by
shepherding you to online ticket vendors and providing cards for
upcoming holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The aggravation isn't worth the benefit for most folks.
</P>
<P>
   But not all sites are created equal. A handful differentiate
themselves by throwing in nice extras, and a glorious few are
designed with the investor in mind. With the aid of Bacon's expert
eye as both an investor and a PIM aficionado, here are a handful of
the most popular sites.
</P>
<P>
   The salesman's analysis: All are worth more than the price of
admission (zilch), but he won't be giving up GoldMine any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   --www.when.com _ When.com is unabashedly commercial, which is
not surprising given its parentage (the site is a division of
America Online). Virtually anything with a possible sales tie-in is
listed, from sports to Stravinski.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the calendar will search and automatically list
career fairs, cultural events, wine tastings, and movie openings
around town if you like. It will even keep you up to date on your
favorite TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its most redeeming quality is its ``Finance Channel,''
which consists of a schedule of earnings announcements, public
offerings, and stock splits of companies you select.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of companies is limited, and the rest of when.com
seems aimed at the pop-culture crowd. And the site doesn't do much
beyond the calendar, which puts it at a disadvantage when compared
to other offerings.
</P>
<P>
   --http://calendar.msn.com _ MSN Calendar looks and works much
like when.com's, but that's just the beginning this time around.
</P>
<P>
   This agenda keeper also ties into a search engine, e-mail,
online buying service, and MSN, with all its news and chat
capabilities. For investors, the cherry on top is the calendar's
click-through connection to MSN Money Central, one of the better
finance sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that the calendar doesn't interact directly with
Money Central. So there's no way to have the calendar itself alert
you to earnings announcements or important business news.
</P>
<P>
   --www.smartmoney.com/si/tools/calendar _ SmartMoney.com is an
investment site first and foremost. In addition to its calendar
service, the site offers portfolio tracking, market news, brokerage
information, sector news, investment charts, and chat areas. All
are robust.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar is noteworthy in its own right, though.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to keeping track of your comings and goings, it can
be set to track economic data, from the consumer price index to
regional Federal Reserve Board reports. It will send you e-mail
reminders before and after the announcements, as well as show up on
your grid of events.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar also notes corporate earnings announcements, if you
like, along with stock splits, dividend payouts, company meetings,
conference calls, and analysts' upgrades or downgrades.
</P>
<P>
   --http://calendar.yahoo.com _ Like SmartMoney.com, Yahoo
Calendar is one piece of a larger puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   On top of its well-known Internet search engine, Yahoo also
offers a free address book, auction service, e-mail account, chat
rooms and, importantly, finance-specific area
(http://finance.yahoo.com). The latter includes news on US and
world markets, investment research, an Investment Challenge game,
tax and insurance areas, message boards, and an economic calendar
similar to SmartMoney.com's.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the calendar and address book makes Yahoo
more like a traditional PIM than its brethren, and its finance
offerings are nearly as extensive as those on SmartMoney.com. Plus,
as an added bonus, Yahoo calendar synchronizes with traditional
PIMs and some palm-top computers easily, so you don't necessarily
have to ditch one for the other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1350EDT &QL; 
