<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-MCCAIN? LET'S HOPE IT'S TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-awaited, much-anticipated, big-deal meeting between
George W. Bush and John McCain is scheduled for Tuesday in
Pittsburgh, according to news reports, and Bush-backers everywhere
are eagerly awaiting the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Will George and John bury the hatchet and stand happily united
against Al Gore and the Democrats in the fall election? Will the
former rivals plot out common ground on previously rancorous issues
such as tax cuts and campaign finance reform?
</P>
<P>
   And don't overlook the big one: Will Bush ask McCain to be his
running mate?
</P>
<P>
   McCain has consistently said that he wants no part of the vice
presidential nomination, but it is an established fact that the
Arizona senator does not always say what he means. If you don't
believe it, just look at his recent back flip on the Confederate
flag controversy in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet the farm that McCain will decline if Bush offers the
No. 2 spot on the GOP ticket. For one thing, McCain is _ or claims
to be _ a dutifully loyal Republican; if Bush tells him that the
party needs him, McCain will be hard-pressed to say, ``No,
thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   For another, McCain might just figure that serving as vice
president _ or even serving as second banana on a losing ticket _
will set him up perfectly for a future run at the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   But even if we assume that McCain would be receptive to a vice
presidential offer from Bush, there is another question that must
be asked: Why in the world would Bush make the offer?
</P>
<P>
   McCain prides himself on his independence, his willingness to
take issue with or flat-out defy his party and its leaders on a
variety of issues. That's good for a legislator; it's bad for a
vice president or a candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Look, folks, running mates don't have to agree on every issue,
and the VP candidate doesn't have to slavishly say, ``Ditto,'' to
every pronouncement by the guy who tops the ticket. But it is
absolutely imperative that No. 2 understands and accepts his role _
and his role precludes any words or deeds that undermine the
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans need look no further back in history than 1996 to
see what can happen when the candidate for vice president is
someone who is incompatible with the presidential candidate in
terms of philosophy and/or personality.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole chose Jack Kemp as a running mate because Kemp was a
big name in Republican circles, retained some nonpartisan celebrity
status as a onetime football star, and commanded considerable
admiration among economic conservatives. But Kemp disagreed with
Dole on a number of basic issues, harbored no apparent loyalty to
the presidential candidate and clearly believed from the start that
he was second in command on a sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp was right about the ticket's nonexistent chances of
dislodging Bill Clinton and Al Gore from the White House. But
wouldn't you think he could have faked a little enthusiasm _ just
to bolster Republican morale, if nothing else?
</P>
<P>
   Dole would have been better off with no running mate at all.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the much-discussed idea of a Bush-McCain
ticket _ the much-discussed and terrible idea of a Bush-McCain
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of self-absorbed egomania, Kemp is a third-stringer
compared to McCain. Where politics and public policy are concerned,
McCain has one overriding priority, and it isn't campaign finance
reform _ it's John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gets along with just about everybody, but McCain seems to
get along with almost no one. We're talking about a man who snarled
at the perfectly pleasant and totally harmless Maria Shriver on
live television, for crying out loud.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Bush needs as he embarks on a tough presidential
campaign _ and, later, the challenge of the presidency _ is to be
saddled with a cantankerous vice president who feels no allegiance
to Bush or his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Bush knows all this. Surely the talk about McCain as a
running mate is just talk and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Surely.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
