<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATHIE LEE'S WOE-IS-ME MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Kathie Lee Gifford. ``People will not let us heal; they
have to pick the scab,'' she complained to Diane Sawyer on ``20/20
Downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it occurred to her that if she bandaged the scab, maybe
people would stop picking at it? Better yet, she should bandage her
mouth, permanently. The woman is insufferable. Will she ever shut
up about her pain and her heartbreak after the much publicized
infidelity of her husband, Frank? Evidently not _ or not as long as
she thinks she can wring another nickel out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee's appearance on ``20/20 Downtown'' Thursday night was
as much infomercial as interview. Sawyer didn't miss an opportunity
to plug Kathie Lee's new CD, a collection of songs about _ what
else? _ Kathie Lee's pain and heartbreak. There were musical
interludes from the album, including a song about, as Sawyer put
it, ``surviving the unbearable.'' Like a good pitchwoman, Sawyer
noted that Dolly Parton had sung the song with Kathie Lee at the
recent Dove Awards. All that was missing was an 800 number across
the bottom of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Sawyer turned to Frank and said, ``You've heard
the album.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet he has. OK, he cheated on her. Still, it's impossible
not to feel a little sorry for him, one of the great heroes of
American sport, publicly undone by his own urges, then publicly
humiliated by his third _ or is it his fourth? _ wife. It might
almost be a classic tragedy, if he had a brain. He sat there
looking like a ventriloquist's dummy as Kathie Lee compared their
post-scandal lovemaking to having a colonoscopy: ``It's not easy,
but you're supposed to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. And she wonders why people won't leave them alone.
</P>
<P>
   It was gratifying to see that Frank hasn't been totally
emasculated. He faced up to his sin like a man. ``I was stupid,''
he told Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He revealed that he had considered suicide in the wake of the
tabloid story about his interlude with the other woman. ``I thought
seriously about how easy it would be to take my little Mercedes
convertible and stick it in the abutment.''
</P>
<P>
   He decided to stick it out instead. The marriage, that is. He
stayed. They prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed in Scripture and we stayed in bed,'' said Kathie
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that part,'' said Frank, a little too eagerly, I
thought, considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Will their marriage last forever? Sawyer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of forever, if you think about it,''
reflected the 69-year-old studmuffin, the man Kathie Lee used to
call her Love Machine. Those were the days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running out of time and running out of wives,'' Kathie
Lee put in perkily.
</P>
<P>
   She said she's fallen in love with Frank all over again. But
even if she hadn't been able to bring herself to forgive him, she
would have stayed in the marriage. She told Sawyer, ``I remember
saying to myself, even if it means I stay married to somebody I am
no longer in love with, I will still do it for my children's
sake.''
</P>
<P>
   She also stayed for the sake of her weaker sisters. ``For every
woman that's ever fallen apart,'' she said, ``let one woman be
strong to show we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee. Martyr. Patron of self-promotion. Now at a record
store near you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
