<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! ``Adrenaline Drive'' Lightweight Japanese comedy with a
take-the-money-and-run plot. A young corporate nerd and a shy nurse
happen upon mob money, then flee, hoping the mob won't happen upon
them. We've been here before, too often. This one seems powered by
Redi-Whip _ not by, well, adrenaline. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Bossa Nova'' Warmly beguiling romantic comedy, with Rio de
Janeiro and a bossa nova soundtrack supplying some of the charm.
Most of the rest is supplied by Amy Irving's widowed
English-language instructor and Antonio Fagundes's dapper
gentlemanly charmer, one of her pupils. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Committed'' This one proves that Heather Graham can carry
a comedy even when it stops carrying itself. As a dishy,
saucer-eyed wife, she tracks her unworthy husband from SoHo to El
Paso when he flies the coop. The film bogs down there, but she
doesn't; Patricia Velasquez and Casey Affleck supply some help as
goofy pilgrims of love. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(FL) !! 1/2 ``I Dreamed of Africa'' Kim Basinger stars in a true
story of a European woman who made a new life for herself and her
young son in Kenya. Grandly dramatic things happened to this brave
spirit, and the visuals are stunning. But the film never really
penetrates its characters' exteriors, or translates their story
into a cohesive, compelling whole. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Gladiator'' It's just as solemn as Hollywood's old
sword-and-sandal epics, but more jolting in its fight scenes.
Russell Crowe is commanding as a fictional Roman general betrayed,
sold into slavery, then hacking his way back with venegeance on his
mind. But the film, while high-impact, is too cynical not to seem
more than a merger between Hollywood and the World Wrestling
Foundation. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!! ``Up at the Villa'' Stylish period romance built around W.
Somerset Maugham's novella about the idle classes in Tuscany on the
eve of World War II. No tea, no Mussolini, but handsomely inflected
performances from Kristin Scott Thomas as an impoverished widow,
Sean Penn as a rakish ne'er-do-well, and Anne Bancroft as a shrewd
American-born principessa. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``The Virgin Suicides'' Sofia Coppola's impressive debut
film uses the suicides of five teenage sisters as a dreamy,
fabulist evocation of adolescence, with everything heightened and
much remaining mysterious. Kirsten Dunst is the standout as the
most ephemeral and provocative sister. James Woods and Kathleen
Turner are too sad to be funny as the rigid parents who repress
them into disaster. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
