<HEADER>
A8902 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      05-08 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH FLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cape Cod waterfront property was selling for $2.3 million.
The buyer paid cash. Not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see people who aren't stretching to pay one or two million
for a house,'' says Paul Grover at Kinlin Grover GMAC Real Estate
in Osterville. He notes that Cape waterfront land is higher than
it's ever been, with places going for $5 million. But that's cheap
compared to Palm Beach, where oceanfront sells for $15 million to
$20 million. Everything is relative.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these people who can write a check for a view? A person
with a mortgage and no view, or someone who can't even find an
affordable rental, easily works up an aggressive stereotype of a
young dot.com-er who thinks money grows on computer terminals. And
realtors do see a lot of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to see a guy in jeans and know he was a college
student looking for an apartment,'' says Joe Palermino, managing
partner of Cabot &AMP; Co. ``Now he's got a half million to put down on
an $800,000 condo.'' Cabot has had four all-cash buyers in the past
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with cash walk into a place, look around, and say,
`Yep, this is it. Oh, by the way, how much is it?' '' notes Michael
Foley, manager of Boston Realty Works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in business 30 years and have never seen anything
like it is now,'' says Janet Hansen, who manages the Boston offices
of DeWolfe Cos. She's noticed cash purchases increasing over the
past five years. ``I see a lot of women with huge sums of money,
and not because they just got divorced. I just had a woman walk in
and buy a $457,000 condo for her daughter _ an undergraduate!''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much money a person has, or how little, the
purchase of a home is almost always emotional _ probably the most
emotional investment a human being can make. And as crazy as this
economy is, it's not spawning the speculative real estate market of
the 1980s. Today's buyer usually buys to live there, to enjoy, and
to connect with some basic psychological stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 60 years old, and still following my mother's advice,''
says the Massachusetts venture capitalist who paid cash for the
$2.3 million Cape waterfront. ``My mother was a real estate broker
and she said you should always pay cash for the land.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to tear down ``a ramshackle cottage'' and build a
house, which he will finance with a mortgage. It will be his
permanent residence. He also has a condo on the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   He has owned several Cape properties and generally pays cash for
whatever he buys or builds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a background where I had no money. My parents were
hard-working middle-class people, products of the Depression. Their
parents lost their homes. So I'm happy to forgo the tax break for
the comfort of knowing there's no risk of my missing a payment. If
I suffer a setback of some kind I won't owe a lender. Even though
my net worth is in the millions, I always worry about losing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many buyers today, he was in a bidding war, but won because
his competition was a developer and the sellers didn't want their
land subdivided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been in the family for generations. That's what I want
_ I want the property to go to my children.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cambridge architect wasn't so lucky last year when she offered
just under $500,000 in cash from investments for a tiny
1,200-square-foot house on a 7,000-square-foot lot in her city. The
seller wanted no conditions on the sale. When the architect asked
that the land be surveyed because she couldn't tell where the
property line ended, she lost out. She offered more money, but no
deal. She cried _ still no deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd looked for two years,'' she said, noting that she wanted
a small place to renovate and expand so she could show prospective
clients her work. She and her husband, a college professor, and
daughter love Cambridge. They like city walking. They want
bookstores. Call it a need for intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   She has since found another place but still reads the ads _ it's
an addiction of sorts. Her favorite was the two-family house with
termites and no bathrooms. Asking price: $600,000. It sold.
</P>
<P>
   And somebody loves it. Maybe somebody's mother does, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
