<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-CUBA-EMBARGO-BOS &LR;      05-08 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-EMBARGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA EMBARGO MAY EXPIRE OF WEAKNESS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the dust from the Elian Gonzalez saga settles, one unintended
but welcome consequence is emerging: the likelihood that the United
States will reconsider its policy toward Cuba _ especially the
embargo that has been in place since shortly after Fidel Castro
took power in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone considers that good news. For the Cuban-American
National Foundation, the powerful lobbying group for the exile
community, any step toward trade with Cuba is perceived as a
softening of opposition to the longest-running tyrant in the
Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban-American community has taken a beating for its support
of Elian's Miami relatives. The public perception of it has been
driven by stereotypes of Hispanics as hysterical and irrational.
Yet however misguided and legally uninformed the exile community
has been, it has acted on passion and principle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one likely consequence of the Elian episode will be to
dilute both the exiles' voice and their influence in favor of
traditional US-Cuban policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the Cuban-American community has been a
determining factor in keeping the embargo in place, and I think
their capital at the political level has diminished because of the
Elian thing,'' said Lisandro Perez, director of the Cuban Research
Center at Florida International University.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are tending to believe less what Cuban exiles
have to say,'' Perez continued. ``They put all their eggs in this
one basket, in this cause they never could have won either
politically or in terms of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the political impetus to end the embargo may be fresh,
the action itself is long overdue. As Castro maintains his iron
grip after 41 years, some facts have become increasingly
indisputable.
</P>
<P>
   First, the embargo is not going to dislodge Fidel. Second, the
embargo primarily serves to impoverish the poor people of Cuba,
adding to the burden of those who are already deprived of civil
liberties and political rights as well.
</P>
<P>
   Third, and most important, the embargo is the greatest
propaganda tool Castro has at his disposal. It legitimizes his
false rhetoric of victimization, enables him to present himself as
a champion of the people he has oppressed, and strengthens his hold
on the Cuban economy, his chief tool for rewarding his friends and
punishing his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the embargo, once an article of faith among exile
activists, has been showing signs of weakness for some time. Even
among the huge, 800,000-strong exile community in Miami there has
been growing frustration that it has failed as a means of
punishment. Elsewhere, given the United States' willingness to
trade with equally oppressive governments _ most notably China _ it
has come to be regarded as a hypocritical Cold War anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo began for legitimate reasons. After taking power,
Castro nationalized all US property on the island. More
importantly, in the context of the time, he vowed to export
communism throughout Latin America, and to build closer ties to the
Soviet Union. At that time, the US government thought the embargo
might bring a quick end to this upstart pest in its backyard.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a miscalculation. By the end of the Cuban Missile
Crisis in 1962 _ which followed the fiasco at the Bay of Pigs _ it
was clear that the embargo would not be the tool to sweep Castro
from power. Even as exiles began pouring into Florida by the
thousands, much of the embargo's original rationale was fading.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Castro's threats to export ``armed struggle''
never amounted to much. In the 1970s, the official position was
that the embargo could not be lifted until Castro ended efforts to
export revolution and severed military ties with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the Soviet Union fell apart, and the United
States began moving toward normal relations with many other former
enemies, including Russia, the embargo had taken on a different
flavor. For exiles, even those who acknowledged its practical
ineffectiveness, it had come to symbolize resistance to the Castro
regime and its human rights abuses. Meanwhile, for Castro himself,
it had become an easy excuse for every failure of his ruinous
economy. The embargo had become an issue where extremes met.
</P>
<P>
   Characterizing the view of the Cuban exile community, not his
own position, Perez explained: ``If it were lifted, it would be
recognition of the legitimization of the Castro government. Castro
would have `won'. You have to understand the embargo in terms of
symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   International support for the embargo, once widespread, withered
long ago _ leaving the United States as the only country pursuing
economic isolation as its foreign policy toward Havana.
</P>
<P>
   More recent, supposedly tougher, measures have failed even more
dramatically. The Cuba Democracy Act of 1992 _ which stiffened our
embargo just as other countries were lifting theirs entirely _ has
done none of the things its advocates said it would do. At the time
of passage, its chief sponsor, US Senator Robert Torricelli, a New
Jersey Democrat, bragged that the Castro regime would fall within
months.
</P>
<P>
   Barring the unforeseen, when Bill Clinton leaves office, Fidel
Castro will have outlasted his eighth US president.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the divide between Cuba and the United States is
beginning to erode. In recent years travel restrictions have eased,
and the two governments have cooperated on environmental and
anti-drug efforts. At the same time, Washington has allowed the
sale of certain medical and farming supplies to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will soon consider a proposal that goes a considerable
step further, exempting all food and medicine from the embargo.
There is also a move afoot to ease restrictions on exiles returning
to Cuba to visit families.
</P>
<P>
   Recent years have also brought some measures to open up the
Cuban economy. Castro now allows private enterprise in some limited
forms, such as farmers' markets and small businesses. The US dollar
has become coveted currency. The loss of the Soviet Union as a
national bank has been largely offset by increased tourism, much of
it from Americans who enter through third countries.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of isolationism, of which embargoes are a part, is a
sorry one. Withdrawing from countries and isolating them only
tightens the grip of leaders like Castro. A unilateral embargo
makes even less sense, serving in this case only to assuage the
bruised consciences of those who wrestle with the guilt of having
``lost the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Cuban-Americans suggest that lifting the embargo could
perhaps be tied to internal changes in Cuba, such as freeing
political prisoners or relaxing restrictions on a free press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Castro was willing to allow a general amnesty of political
prisoners, if he would allow the people to be able to express
themselves without repression, if he would allow the opposition
groups to be legalized _ which now he does not _ and if he would
allow supervised free elections, I think everybody would work
together to get rid of the embargo and I think the Cuban people
would benefit,'' said Ramon Saul Sanchez of the Democracy Movement,
an anti-Castro advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   That is far too much to hope for while Castro remains in power.
But economic improvements always weaken repressive regimes, and
that alone may be reason enough to lift this symbolic gesture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
