<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-08 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUB SETS EXAMPLE FOR GORE ON HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my favorite morsels of Tom Menino wisdom involves big
issues that politicians steer clear of, the ones that everybody
talks about except their ``leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't say anything because they don't know what to do,''
says Boston's mayor. ``And so they hope that by ducking completely,
the public's attention will go to other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The best example right now is housing.
</P>
<P>
   Go anywhere in the country and housing is Topic B if it isn't
Topic A. Price, location, availability. One of the few unfortunate
side effects of an unprecedented run of prosperity has been its
impact on the supply and price of dwelling units; in the world
where normal people live, the impact borders on the catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   As Senator John Kerry said in a speech in Boston last year, ``A
child cannot learn if he has to attend three or four schools in a
single year, if his family moves from relative to relative to
friend to friend because his parents can't afford the rent.''
</P>
<P>
   When $1,500 for a couple of bedrooms in a city or nearby suburb
is a bargain, hard work no longer translates into decent housing.
In Massachusetts, Kerry notes, it takes a hundred hours at the
minimum wage to afford a typical rental; worse, in Boston, the
figure is 135 hours at three times the minimum. And for elderly
citizens trying to squeeze into what there is of assisted housing,
there are more than eight people in line for each unit.
</P>
<P>
   More often, local governments struggle mightily just to keep the
situation from getting worse as federal subsidies expire and other
gentrification pressures intensify.
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential campaign slowly takes shape, housing is
still a stepchild. Given other priorities _ across-the-board income
tax cuts, Social Security privatization, ``Star Wars'' _ there is
no room, much less interest, in George W. Bush's constellation for
this issue, with the sole exception of a few symbolic gestures in
support of homeownership.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is more of a question mark. As a Democrat who relied big
time on urban voters in nailing his nomination victory early, he
has no excuse taking so long to address housing issues. But Mayor
Menino and other major urban figures have prodded and cajoled, and
there have been signs in the last few weeks that the vice
president's Nashville-based operation is ready to try its hand.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason is that economic prosperity will add tens of
billions of dollars to the budget surpluses of the next few years.
And housing has gotten the shortest end of the budgetary stick
during the Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is willing to wake up, Menino and Kerry are in
especially good positions to offer assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Under Menino, Boston is unusual in its record of direct
investment in housing. This year the city will spend $26 million of
its own funds from the sale of surplus properties on housing
production, and last year the number of new housing starts exceeded
2,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   Along with several of his colleagues, Menino believes that the
national tax reform of 14 years ago went too far in cracking down
on real estate shelters. He favors _ and so should Gore _ letting
apartment buildings for low- and moderate-income renters be
eligible for accelerated depreciation schedules. Commercial real
estate can ebb and flow with market forces, but affordable housing
needs and would greatly benefit from special tax treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, meanwhile, has proposed giving affordable housing
production the same kind of dedicated revenue stream that supports
highway and airport development _ in short, a trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the credit programs of the Federal Housing
Administration and the Government National Mortgage Association
generate earnings of $2 billion annually. That money now goes into
the government's pool of general revenues; Kerry proposes that it
go instead into a trust fund for the expansion of affordable
housing production operating through the states and the multitude
of private and nonprofit groups that already exists.
</P>
<P>
   His only string, to oversimplify, would require of recipients
that they make the kinds of vigorous local efforts that Boston
already does.
</P>
<P>
   The housing near-crisis did not happen overnight or by accident.
It was the conscious decimation of a national effort by Ronald
Reagan and George W.'s father. Twenty years ago the country was
turning out nearly 130,000 units of affordable housing a year; by
the 1990s, the slashing of federal efforts had cut that figure by
well over half.
</P>
<P>
   It can rise again, and in this economy it would be almost
criminal if the opportunity were lost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
