<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTS IN COMPUTER VIRUS CASE DETAINED IN PHILIPPINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ Authorities took a man into custody Monday
and demanded the surrender of a woman in connection with the ``love
bug'' virus that has disabled computer programs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects, apparently both bank employees, live in an
apartment where authorities believe a computer owned by the woman
was the source of the virus. They apparently located the source by
tracing a telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   A warrant was issued in the name of the woman, Irene de Guzman,
23. If she is responsible for the virus, this would be a very rare
case in which a woman is implicated in computer vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they had reached her by telephone and she had
promised to surrender in the company of a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The officials did not characterize the detentions as arrests,
however, and said the suspects were not necessarily the creators of
the virus, which could have been the work of anyone using the
computer. They said there might be additional suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only the computer used to launch the virus that was
traced, but anybody could use that computer,'' said an official of
the National Bureau of Investigation. ``The difference is that the
person we have identified is the registered owner of that
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   After three days of rumors and delays, agents late Monday moved
in on a three-story house in the lower-middle-class Manila
neighborhood of Pandacan. When the man, whom they named as Reomel
Ramones, 27, arrived after work, they ``invited'' him, in
handcuffs, for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   They seized 17 items including telephones, wires, computer disks
and computer magazines, according to a local official, Gil Alnas.
He said a computer was not found in the apartment, which could mean
authorities might not be able to look for evidence on the hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Local radio reports quoted Ramones as denying involvement with
the virus, and his relatives suggested the real culprit could be
the woman's sister, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which apparently originated through two e-mail
addresses in the Philippines, is one of the fastest-spreading and
most destructive acts of computer vandalism on record.
</P>
<P>
   By inviting recipients to open an attachment with the subject
line ``ILOVEYOU,'' it has infected some 45 million users in at
least 20 countries and has invaded systems in the Pentagon and the
British Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Several variations have followed, two of them masked as e-mail
jokes and one as a receipt for a Mother's Day gift. Operating as a
sort of poisoned chain letter, when opened the messages destroy
graphics and other saved files.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts quickly identified the Philippines as the
likely source of the infection. Reports emerged several days ago
that the suspect was a man living in the Pandacan neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators here first said they could not find a judge to
issue a warrant over the weekend, and then they said they could not
find a law under which to make out a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no law on this, so we are looking for a law,'' said
Federico Opinion, chief of the National Bureau of Investigation,
earlier Monday. The warrant was finally issued under the Access
Device Act, which governs the use of codes, account numbers and
passwords. It provides for a maximum punishment of 20 years in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   According to one report, de Guzman or other suspects could be
charged with committing fraud using a telephone. Officials have 36
hours to bring charges against detainees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, investigators said, charges could be brought in the
United States because the virus caused damage there. The FBI has
been assisting investigators in the Philippines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Computer experts said the delays may have allowed the suspects
to destroy evidence and could make prosecution more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation here that the virus _ technically a
``worm'' that eats its way into programs _ was created primarily as
a scam to get Internet access rather than as an attempt to cause
widespread havoc.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was complicated by the fact that the
programmer of the virus apparently used a prepaid Internet account.
Such accounts are common here and issue temporary user names and
passwords. Temporary names are often difficult to trace.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation included evidence from Access Net, one of
several Internet service providers in the Philippines believed to
have been used by the programmer. The chief operating officer of
Access Net, Jose Carlotta, said he had given extensive e-mail logs
to government officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
