<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ORACLE FOUNDER INTRODUCES NETWORK COMUTER, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Larry Ellison is breathing life back into the
network computer, reviving a stalled idea he championed years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Oracle Corp. chairman was expected to announce Monday the
creation of the New Internet Computer Co., which will be based in
San Francisco and produce a $199 Internet appliance dubbed the
``NIC.''
</P>
<P>
   The network computer will allow users to surf the Internet,
check e-mail, run software applications and perform other basic
computing functions without the benefit of an individual hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the NIC will deliver those services across a network,
using a Linux operating system stored on a CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   Former Examiner columnist and ABC-TV technology correspondent
Gina Smith is the company's co-founder and CEO. Although Oracle
Corp. does not own the NIC Co., Ellison is the primary investor.
</P>
<P>
   The world was expected to got its first look at the NIC on
Monday morning in Dallas, where Ellison, Smith and Gen. Colin L.
Powell announced plans to donate ``thousands'' of NICs to schools
around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Independent School District will be the first
recipient of the free NICs, with announcements of future donation
sites coming soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed by the offerings currently in the
marketplace, so we designed and built our own,'' said Ellison in a
statement. ``We were looking for an inexpensive yet reliable way of
connecting everyone, especially teachers and schoolchildren, to the
Internet as part of Oracle's efforts to bridge the digital
divide.''
</P>
<P>
   The donation is part of ``Oracle's Promise,'' an ongoing
philanthropic program to place thousands of computers in schools
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``At $199, the NIC is less expensive than the cheapest PC, but
it is every bit as Internet capable,'' said Smith, who recently
left a job at CNET in The City to co-found the NIC Co. with
Ellison, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It supports popular plug-ins - meaning the NIC can view any
site a PC can. It has all the functionality of a PC with none of
the hassles.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison had introduced the idea of a network computer nearly
five years ago, championing the advantages of centralized storage
in the office. Although Oracle subsidiary Network Computer Inc. did
market a network computer for a short time, the product failed to
capture a significant portion of the lucrative commercial computing
market.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the formation of the NIC Co., Ellison and Smith will
set their sights on the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Network Computers (NCs) are computing devices which cost much
less than traditional PCs to buy and maintain,'' said Michael
Salort, a spokesman for the NIC Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one needs the fast, hard-drive heavy PCs anymore. It's
overkill,'' he said. ``Most people would not be able to tell the
difference in the speed of a top-end computer vs. a low-end
computer. People are paying through the nose for not only
purchasing devices up front, but also for maintaining them,
upgrading them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-08 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAND ROVER SOFTENS ELITE IMAGE, AND PRICES, TO EXPAND SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS, W.Va. _ Land Rover, the British
sport-utility-vehicle maker, drew a ``line in the mud'' last week
with the introduction of a new, entry-level model of its Discovery
II aimed at snagging some sales away from the popular Jeep Grand
Cherokee and other midsize SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   In the rugged setting of the Land Rover Driving School in the
heart of West Virginia's Appalachian Mountains, Discovery model
manager Kim McCullough showed off the V-8 powered $33,350 Discovery
II SD alongside a comparably priced six-cylinder Grand Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   She then watched as Land Rover driving instructors compared the
off-road capabilities of the two vehicles along a steep, muddy
demonstration course on the hunting grounds of the Greenbrier
resort, which is home to the driving school.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery II seemed to easily outperform the Grand Cherokee
on the slippery course, smoothly moving up and down the hills and
through deep ruts.
</P>
<P>
   But then, off-road prowess has always been Land Rover's forte;
the company's longtime role has been to provide the Brits with
capable but refined vehicles to traverse the wilderness areas of
their once-vast worldwide empire.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its tenure in the U.S. market, however _ since the
company arrived on these shores in 1987 _ Land Rover has been only
an upscale marketer of the elite, full-size Range Rover SUV,
designed for affluent consumers. Those vehicles now are priced from
the upper $50,000s to beyond $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   With the original Discovery model, introduced in the mid-1990s
with a beginning price in the middle $30,000s, Land Rover has
attempted to become more of a mass-marketer and compete against
high-end models of other popular midsize SUVs, such as the Grand
Cherokee, Mercedes-Benz M-class and Ford Explorer Limited.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. sales of the Discovery II _ a slightly
redesigned model _ increased more than 50 percent to 21,937,
accounting for about 40 percent of the brand's worldwide sales,
McCullough said.
</P>
<P>
   But to Land Rover, that's not good enough. Because of Land
Rover's perception among consumers that it offers only expensive
vehicles to elite buyers, ``We're not even getting on people's
shopping lists when they're considering vehicles like the Grand
Cherokee,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover is hoping to change that with the lower price of the
entry-level Discovery II, down from $34,150 last year. Not only has
the price been lowered, but content has been added, too.
</P>
<P>
   A faux-leather interior called Duragrain replaces the previous
cloth seats. And power seats have replaced manual seats up front.
The comparably priced Grand Cherokee has cloth seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we sell just one Discovery for every 11 Grand
Cherokees sold, and we think we can get that to two or maybe even
three,'' McCullough said. ``In fact, if we get it to three, I can
retire.''
</P>
<P>
   To help get its message across to U.S. consumers, Land Rover
last month fired its previous advertising agency and signed up
Austin, Texas-based GSD&AMP;M, the longtime agency for Southwest
Airlines and the state of Texas' tourism promotions.
</P>
<P>
   New GSD&AMP;M ads to promote the Land Rover brand will appear within
the next few days, said Jim Selwa, Land Rover's vice president for
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real excited about this new campaign and this new
agency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just how successful can Land Rover be with this new push into
the world of mass marketing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to ask them in England for a firm number, but I
believe they can turn out 150,000 Discovery II units a year if we
need them to,'' said Land Rover North America President Howard
Mosher, who also was on hand for the rollout of the lower-priced
Discovery model.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never maxed them out at the plant yet,'' he said. But he
also hinted that such a condition might be advantageous for Land
Rover as it prepares to be taken over by Ford Motor Co. Such
success might keep Ford from taking too active a role in managing
Land Rover.
</P>
<P>
   Ford last month announced that it would purchase the profitable
Land Rover operation from German parent BMW, and the takeover is
expected to be finalized by the end of June, Mosher said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why Land Rover officials were careful not to
mention the Ford Explorer _ which also is priced comparably to the
Discovery II _ in their ``line in the mud'' declaration of war
against the top-sellers in the midsize SUV class.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer is the best-selling passenger vehicle in the
nation, and it has been almost from its introduction in 1990.
Worldwide sales total nearly 500,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
