<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-SUBARU-HNS &LR;      05-08 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SUBARU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUBARU ZOOMS AHEAD WITH HYBRID SUV-SEDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it a car, or is it a sport-utility with a trunk?
</P>
<P>
   That's the big question with the 2000 Subaru Legacy Outback
Sedan, a strange combination of vehicular concepts that just might
catch on with some consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A bunch of you out there have watched the growing sport-utility
vehicle craze from a detached point of view, and have never
seriously considered buying one of those big trucklike things.
</P>
<P>
   But then, perhaps on some occasions you just might like to have
a vehicle that can boldly go where your average family car has
never gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Outback Sedan, a cross between the very nice midsize
Legacy sedan and the beefy Legacy Outback wagon, the one that has
been touted in innumerable television commercials by Paul Hogan,
the Down Under comedian who starred in the Crocodile Dundee movies.
</P>
<P>
   Although I found that I liked this vehicle quite a lot, I must
take issue with one claim Subaru makes in its marketing literature:
The company bills this as ``the world's first sport-utility
sedan.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   American Motors Corp., the former Jeep company, made one in the
1980s called the AMC Eagle, which looked a lot like the Legacy
Outback but wasn't built nearly as well. A few of the old Eagles
are still around; I see one now and then.
</P>
<P>
   What these cars had in common was their high profile (for better
ground clearance) and four-wheel drive. But the Outback Sedan is
much more refined. Inside, it's more like a luxury car than a
sport-utility. It has Subaru's patented full-time all-wheel-drive
system, which makes for outstanding traction on all kinds of
terrain in all types of weather.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, people in places like Texas seldom have a need for
all-wheel drive in their daily commutes, but think about the
possibilities. The Outback Sedan probably would never get stuck in
the sand on Padre Island (well, never say never). And with its high
ground clearance _ 7.3 inches _ which approaches that of some
popular sport-utilities, it could clear some not-too-high rocks on
some desert back trails in Big Bend National Park.
</P>
<P>
   For ski trips to Colorado, it would be great _ nothing short of
a blizzard could stop it.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you're not planning a lot of off-the-beaten-track
excursions, it's still a great everyday car for those of you who
want a car and not one of those big SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not cheap, but it costs a lot less than comparably priced
midsize sport-utilities, so that could be a consideration for some
consumers. Base price of the Outback Sedan is $25,895 (plus $495
transportation), but it comes almost fully equipped for that money.
Our test model had only one option, a $260 subwoofer amplifier for
the audio system. That brought the total sticker to $26,650, about
$10,000 less than a well-equipped Toyota 4Runner or similar SUV.
</P>
<P>
   This essentially is a version of Subaru's flagship Legacy sedan,
which has been completely updated for 2000. It was so nice that I
felt as though I were in a much more expensive car.
</P>
<P>
   It came with leather interior, power moon roof,
AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc stereo with six speakers,
power-everything, heated exterior mirrors and front seats, front
and side air bags for the front-seat occupants, four-wheel antilock
disc brakes, keyless entry, six-way power driver's seat, halogen
fog lights, air-conditioning, cruise control and lots more.
</P>
<P>
   Standard is a smooth four-speed automatic transmission; no
manual transmission is available.
</P>
<P>
   The transmission links to the all-wheel-drive system, which
includes a viscous limited-slip rear differential for even better
foul-weather and off-road traction.
</P>
<P>
   The system automatically distributes power to all four wheels as
needed to maintain traction, with no driver input required. It can
vary the amount of power sent to each wheel at all speeds.
</P>
<P>
   This system isn't designed for serious off-roading; it has no
low-range gearing for the steep inclines, and the ground clearance
isn't enough to overcome the kinds of terrain you would find on
routes such as the famous Rubicon Trail in California's Sierra
Nevada range. But it has ample traction for dirt roads that you
wouldn't want to take the average family sedan on.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Outback comes with Subaru's 2.5 liter, 16-valve,
single-overhead-cam four-cylinder boxer engine that produces 165
horsepower and 166 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Although I found the car a bit sluggish on initial starts
because of a lack of serious low-end torque, it performs well at
highway speeds. It's easy to get it going way over the speed limit
on the freeways. Top speed is well over 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Ride comfort is much better than you would find in even the
cushiest of truck-based sport-utilities, so if that is a
consideration but you still need foul-weather and off-road
capabilities, this might be the vehicle for you.
</P>
<P>
   Road handling is much better than that of the average SUV, too _
steering response is crisp, with no disturbing body lean in tight
curves, thanks to the Outback Sedan's comparatively lower center of
gravity. It's no sports car, but it doesn't drive like a pickup,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Five adults can fit inside _ two in the comfy front bucket seats
and three on the rear bench _ but like most cars in the midsize
segment, two would be more comfortable. The trunk has 12.4 cubic
feet of space for luggage and stuff, not huge, but adequate for
most needs.
</P>
<P>
   Competing cars, according to Subaru, include the Audi A4, Honda
Accord EX, Mazda 626, Mitsubishi Galant, Nissan Maxima, Oldsmobile
Intrigue and Toyota Camry. Of those, only Audi has all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features include automatic-off headlights, dual
power mirrors, 16-inch alloy wheels with splash guards,
windshield-wiper de-icers, heavy-duty raised independent
suspension, front and rear stabilizer bars, daytime running lights,
power rack and pinion steering and a five-year/60,000 mile
powertrain warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is one of the Outback Sedan's greatest advantages
over the average sport-utility. EPA ratings are 22 miles per gallon
in the city and 27 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 16.9 gallons
of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
