<P>
   &UR; NORTH CAROLINA GOVERNOR'S RACE TESTS BUSH AND GORE, TOO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOV-RACE-N.CAROLINA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Over the past three decades, the Republican ticket
has carried North Carolina in every presidential election except
one _ in 1976, when Jimmy Carter of neighboring Georgia won. In
that same period, however, Jim Hunt, a Democrat, won four elections
for governor. Under the state constitution, Hunt cannot seek a
third consecutive term as governor this year. His absence from the
ballot has touched off spirited races for both the Democratic and
Republican nominations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: North Carolina Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARENTING, THE CLINTON WAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTONIAN-PARENTING-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Having put in a magnificent performance as a
stand-up comic at last weekend's White House correspondents'
dinner, President Bill Clinton was back on deadly serious form on
May 2, tackling two of America's most worrying problems: the glass
ceiling that prevents parents from rising to the top at work, and
the difficulty of raising teenagers. All those honest folk who once
had to choose between climbing the greasy pole or weaning their
daughters off Black Sabbath will now be able to get the best of
both worlds _ and sue if anybody tries to stop them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SMOOTH-SAILING ECONOMY BOOSTS LUXURY BOAT SALES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEKKIE-YACHTS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, MD. _ Is the high-tech party over, as Nasdaq bucks
and slides? Not if messing about in boats is any indication. Over
the past two years, yachting and power-boating have taken off in a
big way, particularly among the techies of the Pacific Northwest.
Total sales in the American recreational boating market were up
more than 19 percent in 1999. The link between boating and
confidence in laptop land appears to be a strong one. Despite the
travails of Nasdaq, larger purchases are still holding up; when the
high-tech admirals start leaving their vessels at the pier, it may
be time to bail out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOZAMBIQUE NEEDS _ AND DESERVES _ REBUILDING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REBUILD-MOZAMBIQUE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XAI-XAI _ Two months after horrifically devastating flood waters
destroyed a large part of the country, Mozambique is asking for
$450 million to rebuild roads, homes and lives. The government held
a joint summit with aid agencies in Rome on May 3 and 4 to extract
pledges of outside help while memories are fresh. It will be money
well spent. Helped by the donations already received, Mozambicans
have been working hard to rebuild their battered country. A
generous injection of charitable liquidity could well restore it
rapidly to health. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OLD MEDIA, NEW ECONOMY: TECHNOLOGY MAGAZINES ARE BOOMING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HITECH-MAGAZINES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All the talk in technology publishing is of the
``thud factor.'' Subscribers are said to prefer computer magazines
that make a loud slap when they hit the desk. If that is true,
American readers are certainly getting what they want. The
technology magazine business is booming _ a twist of irony, really,
given the ``paperless'' society that technology was supposed to
have spawned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LA VIDA BROKA: SOUTH AMERICA'S STRUGGLING AIRLINES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATIN-AIRLINES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAO PAULO _ The skies over South America are going to get
emptier. Several of the continent's airlines are experiencing
severe economic turbulance. Can they stay aloft? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCE AND ECONOMICS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASDAQ: TODAY AMERICA, TOMORROW THE WORLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASDAQ-GOES-GLOBAL-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the condemned home of sleazy stockbroking
practices to the shining temple of cutting-edge technology-company
shares in only five years, Nasdaq's image has undergone quite a
transformation. Now the world's second-biggest stock market is
rapidly taking its technology gospel to the far corners of the
earth. On May 3, it took a giant step towards its goal of creating
the ``first global digital stock market.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONGOLIA SEEKS FOREIGN INVESTORS WILLING TO BANK ON IT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BANK-OF-MONGOLIA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ULAN BATOR _ For the ten years since the end of communism in
Mongolia, the banking system has inflicted more costs than benefits
upon the economy. Yet now a political consensus has emerged to get
the state out of banking, bring foreigners in, and improve
supervision. That should lay the foundations for serious economic
growth. This ex-vassal of the Soviet Union might yet have one of
the best banking systems in developing Asia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAMING OF THE SHREWD: HEDGE FUNDS CAPITULATE TO CHANGING
MARKETS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOROS-FOLDS-850&AMP;add-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I am very happy to pull my money out of the
market,'' says George Soros, a hedge-fund investor who has won fame
and notoriety in equal measure. A a lifetime in the markets, Soros
has made his biggest, and possibly last, investment decision: that
he does not understand what is going on. &QL;
</P>
