<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TONY-NOMINEES-530&AMP;ADD     05-08 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-NOMINEES-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY PRODUCTIONS RECEIVE TONY NOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A struggling new musical, ``The Wild Party,''
received seven Tony nominations, a mother and daughter were pitted
against one another in a leading-actress category and two actors
who alternate roles in ``True West'' wound up as competitors when
the Tony Award nominations were announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 30, ``The Wild Party'' _ which opened to mixed
reviews last month _ was selling at 50 percent capacity. Had it not
been nominated for best musical, some people in the theater
industry expected it to close. Monday's nominations, however _ only
one less than the acclaimed revival of ``The Music Man'' _ give
``The Wild Party'' a new lease on life, at least until the awards
are announced on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Michael John LaChiusa, who, with George C. Wolfe, wrote ``The
Wild Party'' and also wrote ``Marie Christine,'' which closed
earlier this year, had a big day Monday. Both of his shows received
nominations for best book of a musical and best original score
despite the fact that they have not been hits.
</P>
<P>
   The nominations also pointed up the growing gray area in
defining a musical because the three shows nominated along with
``The Wild Party'' for best musical defy conventional definitions.
``Contact'' is a dance play performed to recorded music, whose
eligibility has prompted protest from the musicians union; ``James
Joyce's The Dead'' is a play with parlor songs that recently closed
on Broadway; and ``Swing!'' is a dance show.
</P>
<P>
   The races that promise to be particularly close are best play,
best revival of a musical and best performance by a leading actor
in a play.
</P>
<P>
   In the best play category, the acclaimed production of Michael
Frayn's ``Copenhagen'' will compete against ``Dirty Blonde'' by
Claudia Shear, ``True West'' by Sam Shepard _ which successfully
lobbied for consideration as a new play although it was previously
produced off-Broadway _ and ``The Ride Down Mount Morgan'' by
Arthur Miller, which recently earned attention after its star,
Patrick Stewart, complained from the stage about what he considered
inadequate promotion by the producers, the Schubert Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart himself was not nominated.
</P>
<P>
   The race for musical revival has heated up since ``The Music
Man'' opened on April 27, creating head-to-head competition with
``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which opened in the fall. The two musicals are
competing for awards for best performance by a leading actor in a
musical _ Brian Stokes Mitchell for ``Kiss Me, Kate'' versus Craig
Bierko for ``The Music Man'' _ and for best performance by a
leading actress in a musical _ Rebecca Luker for ``The Music Man''
versus Marin Mazzie for ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition for best actor is complicated by the fact that
Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly have both been nominated
for performances in ``True West'' despite efforts by the play's
producers to have the actors, who alternate roles every three
performances, be considered jointly as one candidate. The two
actors are up against Gabriel Byrne, who received strong reviews
for ``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' Stephen Dillane for ``The Real
Thing'' and David Suchet for ``Amadeus.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A number of shows will compete against themselves in various
categories. For best performance by a featured actress in a
musical, for example, Laura Benanti and Ann Hampton Callaway were
nominated from ``Swing!'' and Deborah Yates and Karen Ziemba were
nominated from ``Contact.'' Also in that category was Eartha Kitt,
nominated for ``The Wild Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kevin Chamberlain and Bob Stillman of ``Dirty
Blonde'' will compete against each other for best performance by a
featured actor in a play.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stroman will compete against herself for best direction of
a musical and best choreography, having been nominated for both
``Contact'' and ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The director Michael Blakemore also received two nominations,
though in different categories _ one for ``Kiss Me, Kate'' and one
for ``Copenhagen.'' The last time this happened was 10 years ago,
when Blakemore was nominated for his direction of the musical
``City of Angels'' and of the play ``Lettice and Loveage.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Harris, nominated for ``Waiting in the Wings,'' will
compete against her daughter, Jennifer Ehle, nominated for ``The
Real Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two musicals that have closed each received five nominations:
``James Joyce's The Dead'' and ``Marie Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the shows seemingly slighted by the awards was ``Aida,''
which was not nominated for best musical, although Elton John was
nominated for the score and the show received three other
nominations (for its star, Heather Headley, and for scenic design
and lighting design). Julie Taymor's ``The Green Bird'' received
only two nominations _ one for best costume design (Constance
Hoffman) and one for best performance by a featured actor in a play
(Derek Smith).
</P>
<P>
   The first hour of the Tony Awards will be broadcast on PBS by
Thirteen/WNET in the New York metropolitan region beginning at 8
p.m. on June 4. The remaining two hours will be broadcast live on
CBS from Radio City Music Hall with Rosie O'Donnell as host.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
