<P>
   VIEQUES-PROFILE (New York) _ A profile of Juan A. Figueroa, head
of the Puerto Rican Legal Defense and Education Fund and a leader
of the U.S. resistance to the U.S. Navy exercises in Vieques. By
Jan Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   SF-FAT-BIAS (San Francisco) _ The city of San Francisco has
outlawed discrimination against people who are overweight, joining
a very small but growing list of places that outlaw discrimination
based on appearance. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   NM-LOSALAMOS-FIRE (Dateline to kum) _ Forest fires threaten the
Los Alamos lab. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BUSH (Pittsburgh, Pa.) _ After three months of antagonism
in the primaries and two months of post-primary tension, Gov.
George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain will meet on Tuesday. By Peter
Marks.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (New York) _ Al Gore's day; he attends the cardinal's
funeral. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-ONLINE (Detroit) _ Automakers have long been aware of the
long waits encountered by buyers who order vehicles online. But now
they are striving to speed things up, partly because the Internet
makes it possible and partly because their control over the sales
process is threatened by online car-buying services. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila) _ Developing: Investigators in the
Philippines have arrested Reomel Ramones, 27, and are seeking Irene
de Guzman, 23, in connection with the creation of the ``I love
you'' virus. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND (San Francisco) _ Today the fight is over
digital music, but tomorrow the legal battle over copying
information via the Internet is certain to shift to video and
software. At stake in the coming information war is the power and
perhaps the very business of some of the world's largest media
companies. The software underlying the ability to copy information
via the Internet is evolving rapidly, setting the stage for a much
larger confrontation over the ability to freely and almost
instantly copy any kind of digital information -- music, video,
software or documents -- to any location on the globe. And the new
technology will make it more difficult, perhaps impossible, to stop
the worldwide sharing of data. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   GM-APPOINT (Detroit) _ General Motors names a French woman as
its new director of design. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-JAPAN-INTERNET (Tokyo) _ NTT Communications Corp. of Japan
will buy the 90 percent of the U.S. Internet provider Verio Inc.
that it does not already own for $5.5 billion. The deal is NTT's
first major international expansion and will allow it to run other
companies' Internet sites in the United States. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   AD-AGENCY-MERGER (London) _ Publicis says it will not make a new
bid for Young &AMP; Rubicam. Developing. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
