<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CHATTANOOGA-TRAVEL-LI     05-08 2647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHATTANOOGA-TRAVEL-LIFEBEAT-ART-1343&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FAMILY FUN,CHUG DOWN TO CHATTANOOGA
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    ART ADV: (Photos of Chattanooga available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    Terese Loeb Kreuzer has written about England, Scotland, France,
Italy, Poland, Guatemala, China and the Caribbean as well as about
many places in the United States.
 &HT;    
 By TERESE LOEB KREUZER 
 c.2000 Terese Loeb Kreuzer
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<P>
   When you go to Chattanooga, make sure that you're there on a
Friday night. Cross the Tennessee River and head up Signal Mountain
until you get to the Walden Ridge Civic Center, a white wooden
building that looks like it might once have been a church or a
schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, you'll find a large room decorated with American flags
and faded photographs. On a sultry night, ceiling fans stir the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Around 400 people assemble here every week at 8 p.m. to listen
to amateur bass, banjo, fiddle and guitar players trot out old
favorites like ``The Wabash Cannonball'' and ``Smoky Mountain
Blues'' interspersed with cornpone patter and nostalgic
reminiscence about favorite players who have passed on. This is the
Mountain Opry _ ``free, authentic and wholesome,'' according to a
brochure that continues, ``Everyone is welcomed including the aged,
children, dogs, cats, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   They're all here, some of them eating popcorn and hot dogs,
which can be purchased on the premises. Alcoholic beverages and
smoking are prohibited. The proceedings are over by 11 p.m.,
probably so the kids can get to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga is a great place for a family vacation. For a
relatively small city (population 152,000), it offers a lot to do.
The city straddles the Tennessee River and is surrounded by
mountains, most prominently Lookout Mountain, the local landmark.
</P>
<P>
   While noted for its industry, it also has forests, caves,
waterfalls and flower-strewn meadows in and near the city. An
eight-mile-long path for walkers, joggers and bicyclists runs along
the river. Eventually, it will be 20 miles long and will stretch
between Chickamauga Dam and what is called the Grand Canyon of the
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of Chattanooga is the largest fresh water aquarium
in the world. The intersecting triangles of its distinctive roof
dominate the skyline. The 7-year-old aquarium is credited with
spurring a renaissance in downtown Chattanooga, which, like many
American cities, had deteriorated as people moved to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   A plaza in front of the aquarium is a setting for concerts and
other community events and nearby streets are once again bustling.
Dozens of stores and restaurants plus two new movie theatres have
opened in the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   More than a million visitors a year have ascended the aquarium's
narrow escalator _ accompanied by the sound of a mountain stream _
to find themselves in a re-creation of an Appalachian cove forest
complete with live trees, flowers and native birds. Trout swim in a
mountain pool while river otter frolic nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Other naturalistic exhibits introduce visitors to the Tennessee
River, to other major rivers of the world and to the Mississippi
delta.
</P>
<P>
   There are around 9,000 animals on display including the
ever-popular American alligator, a giant catfish who weighs in at
62 pounds and some six-foot-long arapaima from the Amazon that are
still growing. Apparently they get excited easily and have been
known to jump out of their tanks. The kids might enjoy that.
</P>
<P>
   The newest exhibit at the aquarium, ``Venom Striking Beauties,''
which features poisonous frogs, toads, snakes and the like, is also
sure to please the younger set.
</P>
<P>
   While life is usually relatively placid in the tanks despite the
presence of predators and prey, you never know what's going to
happen. The tanks are monitored 24 hours a day from a control room
equipped with computers and alarms.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, during an open house for the 350 volunteers who
help keep the aquarium going, someone noticed that the fish in one
tank were going belly up. Fortunately, because of the party, the
aquarium was fully staffed so a dead fish was rushed up to the
laboratory, dissected and examined under a microscope. The
diagnosis was too much oxygen in the water. The situation was
immediately corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in another tank, a stingray was giving birth. Her
babies, born live, fluttered around her while some of the larger,
predatory fish hovered nearby, sensing the presence of some tasty
morsels. While some volunteers hastily suited up to go in and
rescue the babies, the rest of the staff watched anxiously, unsure
of whether the rescue would come in time. It did. It's all in a
day's work at the aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chattanooga institution, the Houston Museum of
Decorative Arts, is surely one of the most unusual museums in the
world. The collection of priceless china, antique art glass, early
American pressed glass and antique furniture was assembled by Anna
Safley Houston, who was as famous for her eccentricity as for her
encyclopedic knowledge of antiques.
</P>
<P>
   She was born into a poor family in Arkansas in 1876, and was
married at least nine, and possibly as many as 12 times. She spent
her last years living in an unheated barn surrounded by her
collection, devoting all of her money and strength to acquiring
more so that she could fulfill her cherished dream of creating a
museum.
</P>
<P>
   Children are admitted here, but you might enjoy yourself more if
you send them elsewhere while you wander through room after room of
glass and china.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty in and around Chattanooga to interest the history
buff, including two major Civil War battlefields. Chattanooga's
strategic location on the Tennessee River and prominence as a
railroad hub made the city important to both North and South.
</P>
<P>
   On September 19 and 20, 1863, the Federal Army of the Cumberland
faced the Confederate Army of Tennessee in the forests and
farmlands now known as the Chickamauga Battlefield. The Union
forces were defeated and retreated to Chattanooga, where they were
beseiged for almost two months. With food almost completely
depleted, the seige was lifted in November by troops led by newly
appointed Gen. Ulysses S. Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The battle of Chattanooga, sometimes called the Battle Above the
Clouds because much of it took place at the top of Lookout
Mountain, is considered one of the turning points in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Kids may come away with a better understanding of the enormity
of this war which, in Tennessee, a border state, pitted brother
against brother and neighbor against neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   In the battles of Chickamauga and Chattanooga alone, 5,000
people died and 42,000 were wounded or reported missing. To put
that in perspective, the population of Chattanooga at that time was
2,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   The haunting whistle of a steam locomotive and the rhythmic
clack of iron wheels on iron rails are more cheerful legacies of
the past. The Tennessee Valley Railroad, which runs two-hour-long
excursions between East Chattanooga and Chattanooga, is the largest
operating historic railroad in the South. An intriguing roundtable
enables engineers to turn hulking black locomotives around for a
return trip.
</P>
<P>
   For a different kind of historic ride, try the recently
refurbished antique carousel from Atlanta that was installed at the
north end of the Walnut Street Bridge, in itself an attraction for
both tourists and residents. The bridge is more than a 100 years
old and is the longest pedestrian bridge in the world. If you're
agile, you can join local rock climbers, who scale its sturdy stone
pilings.
</P>
<P>
   After so much sightseeing, the family may want a good meal. Try
Mount Vernon, a one-story clapboard roadside restaurant famous for
its pies. For many years, they were baked by a tiny, gray-haired
lady named ``Mama'' Ida Kate Davis. Mama Kate's best seller, the
amarillo pie, is not for someone on a diet. A thin, buttery crust
is topped with an almond-flavored custard and a thick layer of
whipped cream with almonds sprinkled on top.
</P>
<P>
   This, or one of her other pies (pecan, bavarian fudge or
``goober'') should give everyone enough fuel for another day of
family fun in Chattanooga. With so much to do, including hang
gliding and whitewater rafting, a few extra calories shouldn't
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHATTANOOGA: THINGS TO DO AND PLACES TO STAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THINGS TO DO: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain Opry is on Fairmount Road, two miles past the
shopping center. Free music from 8 p.m. to 11 p.m. every Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets can be purchased daily from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. for the
Tennessee Aquarium at One Broad Street. Adults: $11.95, children
(3-12) $6.50 and children under 3, free. A package that includes
admission to the aquarium and the IMAX 3D theater across the street
costs $16.95 for adults and $9.95 for children 3-12, with children
under 3, free. Closed Thanksgiving and Christmas. Extended summer
hours. For more information, call (423) 265-0695 or (800) 262-0695.
</P>
<P>
   The Creative Discovery Museum offers hands-on art and science
exhibits for kids. Open daily from Memorial Day to Labor Day, 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. and Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.,
Sundays, noon to 5 p.m. the rest of the year. Admission, $7.95 for
adults, $4.95 for children 2-12. Under 2, free.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Museum of Decorative Arts at 201 High St. is open
daily from April 1 through November 1. The hours are Monday through
Saturday, 9:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. and noon to 4:00 p.m. on Sunday.
The museum is closed on Sunday from November through March. Special
exhibits. For more information, call (423) 267-7176.
</P>
<P>
   The Chickamauga and Chattanooga National Military Park, the
largest and oldest in the United States, is open during the spring,
fall and winter from 8:00 a.m. to 4:45 p.m. with extended hours
from Memorial Day through Labor Day. Admission, $2. A multimedia
program costs $3 for adults, $1.50 for seniors, and $1.50 for
children from 6 to 16. Part of the battlefield is in Tennessee with
the rest in Georgia. Call (706) 866-9241 or (423) 821-7786 for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL EVENTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The annual Riverbend festival(June 9-17) brings crowds to Ross'
Landing (near the aquarium) for music, food and art displays. A
Children's Village offers special activities for children. Hours:
5:30 to midnight. For more information, call (423) 756-2211.
</P>
<P>
   On June 24, the third annual Sculpture Symposium takes place in
the Bluff View Art District, with indoor and outdoor sculpture
exhibits and presentations by the artists. Hours: 10 a.m. to 9 p.m.
For more information, call (423) 265-5033, ext. 489.
</P>
<P>
   On September 16 and 17, the 137th anniversary of the battle of
Chickamauga will be commemorated with special talks, tours,
exhibits and living history demonstrations on the battlefield.
Hours: 8 a.m. to 4:45 p.m. Call (706)-866-9241 for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton County Fair takes place on September 23-24 with
crafts, music, blue ribbon competitions and agricultural exhibits.
Chester Frost Park. Call (423) 842-0049 or (423) 209-6030. October
7-8 brings the Celebration of Fine Crafts to Ross' Landing. For
more information call (615) 665-0502. Oktoberfest is celebrated in
the Bluff View Art District with authentic German food and
beverages, music and art. This is accompanied by an outdoor art
market displaying the work of local artists. Call (423) 267-7353 or
(800) 374-2923 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Valley Railroad, the largest operating historic
railroad in the South, offers excursions of varying lengths and
prices through Chattanooga and North Georgia. A highlight of the
season (which extends from April through December) takes place in
October and early November: the day-long, steam-powered ``Annual
Autumn Leaf Specials'' to Summerville, Ga. Passengers lunch in the
dining car of the train.($67 for adults.) In addition, the regular
schedule features a steam locomotive pulling four or five historic
railroad cars with up to six round-trips daily between East
Chattanooga and Grand Junction. The two-hour round-trip, which
includes time in the station watching the locomotive change
directions on a large turntable, costs $9.50 for adults and $4.50
for children 3 to 12. For more information, call (423) 894-8028.
</P>
<P>
   Also in October, the annual Fall Color Cruise and Folk Festival
takes visitors through the Grand Canyon of the Tennessee River to
view over 300 different kinds of trees at the height of the color
changes. The festival, which is held at the Shellmound Recreation
Area at Nickajack Dam near Jasper, Tenn., includes Southern cooking
and traditional, country and gospel music. For more information,
call (423) 892-0223.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information on other activities, contact the
Chattanooga Area Convention and Visitors Bureau, 2 Broad Street,
Chattanooga, Tenn. 37402 or call (423) 756-8687 or (800) 322-3344.
The Webs site is www.chattanoogafun.com
 &UR; PLACES TO STAY: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga's former railway terminal has been converted into a
Holiday Inn with 31 acres of formal gardens, shops and displays of
historic railroad cars including the famous Chattanooga Choo Choo
of the 1941 Glenn Miller song. Though most rooms are more
conventional, accommodations include restored railroad sleeping
cars. Rooms range from $69 to $175 a night, with packages
available. Write to 1400 Market St., Chattanooga, Tenn. 37402 or
call (423) 266-5000 or (800) 872-2529 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chattanooga has numerous hotels and bed and
breakfasts. Among them, the Thompson House in the Bluff View Art
District, (built in 1908 by a former mayor of Chattanooga) has two
suites each with several rooms, fold-out sofa beds, and fully
equipped kitchens. Rates range from $225 to $250 a night for the
suites. Smaller, less expensive accommodations are also available
in the Bluff View's three bed and breakfasts. Call (423) 265-5033
for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLACES TO EAT: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Southside Grill at 14th and Cowart streets is excellent and
family friendly. Located in a refurbished turn-of-the-century
warehouse, this superb restaurant serves gourmet food with a solid
French base and Southern overtones (for instance, appetizers
include fried green tomatoes and smoked catfish in addition to
grilled portobello mushrooms). It's expensive (dinner entrees hover
around $20,) but worth it. Kids who eschew quail breasts and rabbit
might enjoy lamb chops, steak or chicken, which are also on the
menu. Call (423) 266-9211.
</P>
<P>
   For less expensive, family-style cooking, try Mount Vernon at
3509 Broad St. where entrees cost around $12 and include seafood,
pasta, steak and chicken. Mount Vernon is open Monday through
Friday from 11 a.m. to 10 p.m. and on Saturdays from 4:40 p.m. to
10 p.m. For more information, call (423) 266-6591.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
