<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8992 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MOTHERSDAY-HEALTH-ACT     05-08 2656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERSDAY-HEALTH-ACTIVISM-LIFEBEAT-1275&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERS AND OTHERS FIGHTS ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH RISKS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 By DIANE DI COSTANZO 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1989, actress Meryl Streep gathered a group of parents in her
rural Connecticut home to discuss their shared concern about the
effects of pesticides on their children's health. Streep had in her
hand a report issued by the Natural Resources Defense Council
titled ``Intolerable Risk: Pesticides in Our Children's Food.''
</P>
<P>
   It revealed that a chemical called Alar was so commonly sprayed
on apple crops that it represented the No. 1 cancer risk for kids.
Since Alar seeped through the peel to the fruit's flesh, neither
peeled apples nor apple juice were safe.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the elevated risk was due to a kind of oversight: When
regulations were set to limit pesticide residue in food, the body
(and consumption patterns) of an adult male were considered.
Because no adjustment of these levels was made to safeguard a much
smaller and developing body, children over the course of their
growing years were ingesting ``intolerable'' amounts of the toxin,
the report warned. (Indeed, seven years later, a federal act would
rule that the Environmental Protection Agency, when considering
questionable chemicals, must divide the level considered safe for
adults by 10 to arrive at one safe for children.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the moms present at that meeting in Streep's kitchen was
Wendy Gordon, her friend and the mother of two boys. A staff member
of the National Resources Defense Council, Gordon knew about the
toxic effects of pesticides on the body. She also knew that
granting consumers the right to know what's in their food was part
of what parents should fight for.
</P>
<P>
   From this kitchen-table meeting, Mothers &AMP; Others for a Livable
Planet was born. This nonprofit organization is dedicated to
untangling environmental issues so the average consumer can make
eco-sound decisions for her family, both in her home and at the
store. The underlying message is simple: environmental activism
begins at home with small, but significant choices that are made
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to know is essential to all of us as consumers, and
it is at the heart of Mothers &AMP; Others' mission,'' says Gordon, who
served as executive director of the organization for its first 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against Alar was a baptism by fire for the tiny but
determined group of parents. Although not by design, Streep, Gordon
and their gang had taken on an 800-pound gorilla as their first
adversary. Alar was manufactured by Uniroyal, a multinational
corporation disinclined to withdraw a profitable chemical from the
market.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, ``60 Minutes'' broadcast a damning report about
Alar that prompted the apple industry _ and a faction of the press
_ to turn against the protesters, branding them ``Chicken Little
environmentalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits were filed, the Supreme Court was called into judgment
and _ in the midst of the circus _ Uniroyal stopped selling Alar.
In 1990, the EPA banned the substance. Alar, of course, wasn't the
only bad apple in the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Mothers &AMP; Others is voicing its concerns about PVC _ a
compound used to make products such as shower curtains, mini-blinds
and flooring. Dioxin, a carcinogen, is produced during its
manufacturing process.
</P>
<P>
   Alerting members about the hazards of PVC, the organization's
Web site (www.mothers.org) also provides a list of manufacturers
responsible for bringing the substance into your home, along with a
sample letter to send to them protesting its use. Consumer pressure
does work, Mothers &AMP; Others contends: Companies such as Simple
Green, Kiss My Face and the Planters Co. have phased out use of PVC
bottles in response to shoppers' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives like these are at the core of the group's ongoing
``Shoppers Campaign,'' dedicated to educating consumers about
what's in their food and how to speak out against the bad stuff.
The biggest battle raging today concerns genetically modified
organisms that are produced when DNA, pesticides and/or herbicides
are spliced into seeds used by farmers to increase crop yields.
</P>
<P>
   As with Alar, GMOs flood into supermarkets inadequately tested
and unlabeled _ and Mothers &AMP; Others has organized an attack: It
has spoken out against genetic engineering at Food &AMP; Drug
Administration hearings; it provides education on its Web site and
in its monthly newsletter, the ``Green Guide''; and it encourages
members to write to the CEOs of such corporations as Nestle USA, to
protest the use of GMOS.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the Eco-Info phone line rings constantly in the
Mothers &AMP; Others New York City office. Although the 11-year-old
organization's membership has swelled to 30,000 nationwide (and
comprises not only mothers but also fathers, grandparents and
single people), a real live person still answers calls, fielding
questions from members on topics as diverse as baby-bottle choices
to levels of lead in mini-blinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of carpet calls,'' says executive director
Elisabeth Marx, when asked to name a major area of consumer
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We help keep parents calm,'' says Mindy Pennybacker, editor of
the ``Green Guide.'' ``A mother might call because her
mother-in-law used a commercial carpet shampoo to clean up a spill
while baby-sitting and the child had been playing on the carpet for
hours. We'd ascertain that her child is symptom-free, then assure
her that it's really a cumulative exposure to household toxins that
poses health risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Marx acknowledges that most parents get involved with Mothers &AMP;
Others out of a kind of self-interest: A recent poll shows that 98
percent of the members feel that their personal health and the
environment are closely linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``One mother might look at her toddler walking for the first
time across her spring lawn and think, 'Lawn chemicals cannot be
good for him,''' explains Marx. There is a natural ripple effect
from one issue to the next, she says, citing a mother who might be
in the process of washing organic salad greens in a sink she just
scrubbed with a chemical disinfectant _ which prompts her to ask
about a different way to clean sinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all start with what's at hand,'' Marx says philosophically.
Indeed, the organization is only too happy to encourage baby steps
toward clean-and-green living _ otherwise the conversion effort is
so monumental that few people will actually succeed.
</P>
<P>
   As a Mothers &AMP; Others member, Haylee Messing, a New Jersey
mother of two, appreciates this accommodation, noting that when she
first bought organic food, she purchased only enough for her kids'
meals, which was all her budget could withstand at the time. ``Once
one change became a habit, I added another,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members might not start by writing to the FDA,'' Marx says.
``They might not think of themselves as 'political.' So they can go
about making their personal choices, and that's a good thing. But
in order for real change to happen, we all need to express our
preferences to the stores we patronize and the companies we
support.''
</P>
<P>
   A reasonable first step: Take two extra minutes in the produce
aisle to find the manager or the store owner and request that he
stock organic fruits and vegetables. You might also ask questions
about fruit that's unlabeled: Where is it from? If it was not
locally grown, is it possible to get produce from regional farmers?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Marx says, our buying patterns do reveal our values.
But a faster way to express what we want is to communicate via fax,
mail and e-mail to food processors and to our governmental leaders.
And Mothers &AMP; Others is equipped to aid in this process _ and
amplify members' voices _ in every way.
</P>
<P>
   THE TOP 10 FOODS TO BUY ORGANIC
</P>
<P>
   Most of us can't shop all organic all the time. But some
conventionally grown and processed foods tend to have higher levels
of toxins than others do, and those toxins have a greater effect on
a child's small body. Plus, the average youngster tends to eat more
fruits, vegetables and dairy products than the average adult does.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these Mothers &AMP; Others guidelines also apply to
adults _ who should opt for organic coffee and meat whenever
possible, too.
</P>
<P>
   1. BABY FOOD: In 1995, the Environmental Working Group tested
eight baby foods made by the leading manufacturers. Some 16
pesticides were found in more than half of the samples. Commercial
organic baby foods include Earth's Best, Well-Fed Baby and Gerber's
Tender Harvest _ or make your own by cooking and pureeing organic
food.
</P>
<P>
   2. RICE: Because rice allergies are practically nonexistent,
this cereal grass is a primary ingredient in baby food. Pesticide
use on rice fields in California's Sacramento River Valley, one
major growing region, has been so heavy that it has contaminated
groundwater there.
</P>
<P>
   3. STRAWBERRIES: These fruits are the single most
pesticide-laden produce item in the United States, according to a
1995 Environmental Working Group study. In addition, strawberries
and other produce bought out-of-season are likely to be imported,
often from countries with even less-stringent pesticide
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   4. GRAINS: The USDA recommends six to 11 servings of grains a
day. But in 1994, the FDA found illegally high pesticide residue in
a year's worth of oat-based Cheerios. And two years later, the FDA
found residue from at least one pesticide in 91 percent of wheat
samples tested. Serve a healthy variety of organic offerings,
including millet, quinoa, barley, couscous, amaranth and spelt.
</P>
<P>
   5. DAIRY PRODUCTS: Milk comprises nearly a quarter of the
non-nursing infant's diet, but many dairies inject their cows with
recombinant bovine growth hormone to boost milk production.
Organic-milk dairies don't use hormones or antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   6. CORN: Processed foods made with corn _ cornbread, tortilla
chips and popcorn _ were among the top 15 foods likely to expose
children to an unsafe dose of organophosphate residue, according to
a 1998 report by the Environmental Working Group.
</P>
<P>
   7. BANANAS: Often the first fruit offered to babies, bananas are
produced using the pesticides benomyl (linked to birth defects) and
chlorpyrifos (a neurotoxin). In Costa Rica, a major exporter, only
5 percent of farmland grows bananas, but that small number accounts
for 35 percent of the country's pesticide consumption.
</P>
<P>
   8. GREEN BEANS: In 1992-93, contamination with pesticides
illegal in the United States was found in 7.4 percent of green
beans imported from Mexico. The EWG's tests found three pesticides
in conventional green-bean baby-food samples.
</P>
<P>
   9. PEACHES: A recent FDA study found that 5 percent of the peach
crop in the United States was contaminated with excessive amounts
of pesticides. Peaches lead the EWG's list of foods likely to
create unsafe organophosphate exposure.
</P>
<P>
   10. APPLES: This fruit ranks second on the EWG list for
organophosphate residue and baby-food apple juice also made the top
15. Look for organic apples and those from crops grown utilizing
integrated pest management.
</P>
<P>
   MERYL STREEP TALKS ABOUT WHY SHE IS AN ENVIRONMENTAL ACTIVIST
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, when the pesticide Alar was being used to spray apples,
Meryl Streep had three children who were, as she says, ``mainlining
apple juice.'' She had cause for concern: Alar had been cited as
the No. 1 risk factor for cancer among children. Streep acted
locally, gathering friends to discuss the problem, and then
globally, co-founding Mothers &AMP; Others.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, ``Healthy Living'' spoke with the Academy
Award-winning actress and mother of four about environmental
activism on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Were you always attuned to nature?
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, actually, I grew up in New Jersey. (Laughter) As a
girl, I remember following the fogger trucks on my bike. They were
emitting these clouds of DDT _ I remember thinking it smelled so
sweet. I'm horrified to think of that now. In college in the '70s,
I was impressed by reports about dangerous levels of pollutants in
our air and water. But it wasn't until I had my first child that my
environmental concern crystallized.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, when our son was born, we (Streep and sculptor husband,
Donald Gummer) were living in Chinatown (in Manhattan) in an
apartment with intermittent heat and a hot plate for cooking. But
when we had money to spare we'd send a check to the Natural
Resources Defense Council. With a baby at home, I was suddenly
concerned with what my son breathed, ate, drank. Before, when we
were living paycheck to paycheck, the future was always next week.
Suddenly, I was committed to the future in a way I hadn't been
before.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did the Alar issue mobilize the mothers you knew?
</P>
<P>
   A. We all had young children and we were all browbeating them to
eat fruits and vegetables. But we weren't washing the food as
assiduously as we might have. Then it became clear that Alar can't
be washed off _ it penetrates to the flesh of the apple _ and that
it was highly toxic. We weren't scientists. But we knew that it
could not be good for our children.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're very focused on your family.
</P>
<P>
   A. Every single choice I've made in my career I've based on my
concerns as a parent. What is satisfying about the Mothers &AMP; Others
work is that people really heard us _ people who were feeding
children. And eventually, together, we created a demand for organic
foods, a market that's been growing by 20 percent every year. That
carries a lot of weight with companies making decisions about how
to grow and process food. ``The dollar drives the dream,'' as they
say.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does Mothers &AMP; Others help you make decisions in your own
home?
</P>
<P>
   A. I rely on the ``Green Guide'' a lot. Because household
cleansers are among the most toxic substances we willingly bring
into our homes, I clean with a mix of white vinegar and baking soda
_ it's cheap, it's nontoxic and it smells really good. I'm also
involved with a community supported agriculture group that delivers
organically grown vegetables once a week. I have three teen-age
daughters, and I'm concerned about the levels of dioxin produced
when tampons are bleached. This is just one example of how
environmental choices can affect us in a very intimate way.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you get your kids to be eco-conscious?
</P>
<P>
   A. We can only set an example. I have been a mother long enough
to know that even though most of what I offer is atmospheric, if
they're breathing, some of it will go in. There were times, I
admit, when they were a little reluctant to accede to my wishes,
but I trust that they are thoughtful about these things.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does environmentalism mean to you?
</P>
<P>
   A. Acting on behalf of the environment is about all the little
decisions we make every day. It's not separate from living; it is
living.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane di Costanzo writes for ``Country Living's Healthy
Living'' magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
