<SLUG> BC-TECHNOLOGY-DVD-LIFEBEAT-686-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO DVD OR NOT TO DVD: EXPERTS SAY THERE'S NO QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Jennifer Keeney writes for ``Smart Money.''
 By JENNIFER KEENEY 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   If you still haven't replaced your old VCR with a DVD player,
then you don't know what you're missing. Besides a much sharper
picture and ultra-crisp sound, DVD offers features such as multiple
viewing angles, zoom and scan, and, in some cases, interviews,
deleted scenes and other insider information on your favorite
flicks. Most important, DVDs show a movie the way the director
meant for you to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Watch ``The Graduate'' on DVD, for example, and _ unlike on VHS
_ you'll get a full view of Anne Bancroft seducing Dustin Hoffman.
Plus, you can use a DVD player to play your audio CDs.
</P>
<P>
   After a blowout Christmas season, most manufacturers have
stepped up production of new models with even more bells and
whistles. As it turns out, though, your choice of a DVD player is
simpler than it seems.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, you need to look at what kind of entertainment
system you have (or would like to have). Here's why: DVDs use
particular sound formats _ Dolby Digital is the most universal _ to
give movies their lifelike quality. To extract this sound from your
DVD movies, a decoder is required. You have to decide whether to
get a player with a built-in decoder (which adds about $100 to the
price) or to rely on a separate audio receiver to supply the
decoder.
</P>
<P>
   If you simply want to hook up the DVD player to your television
for better sound and picture quality, then the built-in decoder
will do the trick. However, if you intend to put together any type
of component home-theater system, you are better off putting $100
toward a high-quality receiver, if your stereo system doesn't
already have one. Not only will the sound quality be better, but
you will also have the flexibility to add new digital components to
your setup down the line.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing to consider when shopping is whether your player
has the right outputs _ the connections to your television or
receiver. The most important two to look for are S-video and
component video, both of which will sharpen your picture.
(Component video is the more important, but they usually come as a
package.) And make sure that your television's inputs are
compatible with the DVD player's outputs.
</P>
<P>
   So which player should you buy? If you're in the market for a
basic model, we like the ultra-reliable Panasonic DVD-RV30 ($300),
which has a component-video output for high- resolution color and a
``cinema mode'' that reduces glare and sharpens details.
</P>
<P>
   With just a simple receiver and two speakers (rather than six),
this machine will also give you virtual surround-sound.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you'd like to build something of a powerful home theater
but don't want to spend several thousand dollars on a piece of
consumer electronics. In that case, consider the Sony DVPS7700
($999). Its best feature: two separate lasers _ one for compact
discs and one for DVDs _ so you'll get maximum performance when you
play either.
</P>
<P>
   Sony also introduced a new product this spring: an all-in-one
system for those who don't want to build a component system from
scratch. The Sony DAV-S300 provides a lot of bang for its $599
price tag: It's a DVD player and receiver in one box, so you can
also listen to the radio in full surround-sound. And it comes with
six speakers to maximize the Dolby sound. (This is the only product
we've selected that has a digital decoder built in.)
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to turn your living room into a virtual Imax theater?
Then you might want to pony up $2,495 for the California Audio Labs
CL-2500. It's designed for the aficionado who plans to invest in
other components, such as a six-speaker system and a big-screen
television, in order to maximize the player's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Watch a DVD on this system and you will be able to discern the
stitching in an actor's cashmere sweater and hear grains of sand
hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a good reason to go with a less expensive
model, consider the fact that recordable DVD players are on the
way, meaning that you might not want to make a serious investment
right now. Pioneer was the first to launch such a product; on sale
right now only in Japan, it will be available in the U.S. this fall
and will sell for about $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
