<HEADER>
A8994 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-COLLECTIBLES-DINNERWA     05-08 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTIBLES-DINNERWARE-LIFEBEAT-ART-935&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE PASTEL-COLORED BONBONS, VINTAGE LU-RAY DINNERWARE IS SWEET 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  ART ADV: (Photos of Lu-Ray
dinnerware are available in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez
at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Kathy and Bill Meehan, authors of the ``Collector's Guide to
Lu-Ray Pastels,'' write for ``Country Living'' magazine.
 &HT;    
 By KATHY &AMP; BILL MEEHAN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Set your table with jewels. That's what a 1940s brochure for the
Taylor, Smith &AMP; Taylor Co. (TS&AMP;T) invited homemakers to do with the
firm's softly hued dinnerware line _ Lu-Ray Pastels. Introduced in
1938, the East Liverpool, Ohio, firm marketed Lu-Ray as an
alternative to the bold ``fiesta'' colors then popular in
``modern'' dinnerware.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half century later, the Art Deco-inspired plates,
platters, pitchers, tumblers and teacups still catch collectors'
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lu-Ray Pastels have simple designs and cheerful colors, but
there's more to it than that,'' say Michael Fiur and Jerry
Lombardi, whose 250-piece collection fills the kitchen of their
late-1800s farmhouse in New York's Hudson River Valley. ``The look
is retro, yet it has stood the test of time. A table set entirely
with Lu-Ray is classy, but the pieces were introduced as a
moderately priced pattern meant for the everyday working person.
These inherent contradictions appeal to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Named for the colorful caverns in Luray, Va., Lu-Ray Pastels
were originally produced in four colors: Windsor Blue, Sharon Pink,
Surf Green and a butterfly yellow called Persian Cream.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth color, Chatham Gray, was added to the line in 1949 but
didn't prove as popular with homemakers as the original four.
Chatham Gray was discontinued in 1955; the rarity of pieces in this
color have bolstered their desirability among today's collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the early 20th century's elaborate dining rituals,
TS&AMP;T produced 29 pieces in the original Lu-Ray line, including not
only the basic plates, bowls and cups, but a wide variety of
specialized serving pieces, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The line's immediate success encouraged the manufacturer to add
new pieces every year through 1942, including a tiny bud vase and
urn in 1939, a covered muffin plate in 1940, a set of four nesting
mixing bowls in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Following World War II, however, Americans yearned for
simplicity in food preparation and presentation, so most of
Lu-Ray's elegant but nonessential serving pieces were discontinued
by 1947. As with Chatham Gray items, the rarity of serving pieces
produced for a limited time have made them particularly desirable
with collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Lu-Ray Pastels remained one of America's most popular dinnerware
patterns through the early 1960s (production ceased in 1961). After
that time, piles of the colorful pieces were discarded, often
viewed simply as unfashionable ``old dishes.'' This unfortunate
turn, coupled with 60 years of repeated use and the inevitable
breakage, has dramatically decreased the supply of Lu-Ray. Because
of the pattern's revived popularity with collectors over the past
few years, the hunt for quality Lu-Ray Pastels _ especially certain
rare designs _ has become more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we began collecting four years ago, it was fairly easy to
find inexpensive pieces in small antiques shops around the
country,'' says Fiur, who works in New York City as a producer for
Radio City Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Fiur frequently crisscrosses the United States while producing
such events as the Radio City Christmas Spectacular and the Super
Bowl Halftime Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spotted our first piece of Lu-Ray _ a Surf Green chop
plate, a large circular plate _ in Cat House Antiques in High
Falls, N.Y. I don't remember what we paid for it at the time, and
we had no way of knowing that it would inspire more collecting. We
just loved the color and the shape.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Fiur, rare pieces have become more difficult to
find, and prices have risen by roughly 20 percent to 40 percent in
recent years. ``Dinner plates used to start at about $8 each,'' he
recalls. ``Now it's more like $12.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor affecting the market is online auction sites.
``Online auctions have been both good and bad for Lu-Ray
collectors,'' says Lombardi, owner of Simply Grand Catering in New
York City. ``Through sites like e-Bay, you can sometimes locate
hard-to-find pieces that might have taken you years to find
otherwise. On the other hand, prices tend to run quite high. Rare
pieces can reach several hundred dollars each. We've found that
prices on e-Bay are about 50 to 100 percent higher than what you'd
pay for similar pieces in an antiques shop.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those collectors who savor the joy of a patient pursuit,
there is still plenty of Lu-Ray to be found. Searching for these
pastel beauties, whether online or at antiques stores and flea
markets, can become an open-ended Easter egg hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common pieces can still be found for $10 to $15, and rare
pieces even appear from time to time in unexpected places, but
those can often cost $100 to $200,'' Lombardi points out. ``It's
still possible to amass a wonderful collection, and the pieces look
particularly great when they're displayed in large numbers, but it
has definitely become more of a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fiur and Lombardi have gone to great lengths to create
a suitable setting for their own sizable _ and ever-expanding _
collection. Soft-yellow walls complement Lu-Ray's pastel shades,
custom-made open shelving and glass-doored cabinetry beautifully
showcase stacks of plates and rows of platters, and period Lu-Ray
advertisements have been framed and hung on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly antiquing trips keep the collection growing. ``Sometimes
we pass on a piece now, but not often. Rare pieces with small chips
can be displayed with the chip facing the wall and duplicates of
common items come in handy if something breaks,'' Fiur says. ``In
all these years, our interest has certainly not waned.''
 &UR; LU-RAY LITERATURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 1938 trade-show advertisement sponsored by the Taylor, Smith &AMP;
Taylor Co. of East Liverpool, Ohio, features a group of businessmen
discussing the firm's newest dinnerware line, Lu-Ray Pastels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have a real volume winner in Lu-Ray,'' one says
to another. ``They must have,'' he responds, ``judging by the talk
that's going around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``TS&AMP;T. was famous for creating an aura of anticipation before
introducing a new line,'' says New Jersey Lu-Ray expert Bill
Meehan. Store displays, illustrated brochures and company
literature often utilized equally intriguing jargon.
</P>
<P>
   According to Meehan, Lu-Ray enthusiasts often buy advertising
items to round out their collections. ``Brochures that include
costs are especially fun to have on hand for reference,'' he says.
``There are prices like 45 cents for a teacup, 65 cents for a
10-inch plate and $1.50 for a covered sugar bowl. If the original
makers could see what these pieces are selling for today _ $10,
$50, $100, and more _ they probably wouldn't believe it!''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Lu-Ray literature is difficult to find, and examples
that turn up at flea markets and ephemera fairs often sell for $100
or more, depending on age, condition and graphics. Quality copies
are sometimes offered by dealers for significantly less than the
originals.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
