<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, May 9:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VINLAND (L'Anse Aux Meadows, Newfoundland) _ At the northern
tip of Newfoundland is what archaeologists agree is the first and
still only authentic site of Viking settlement in North America,
500 years before the voyages of Columbus. Ruins of eight houses and
workshops, some of their thick walls and pitched roofs meticulously
restored, will be a focus for this year's millennial commemoration
of all things Viking. Excavations here have not only confirmed
elements of truth in the sagas of the seafaring adventurers from
Scandinavia, they have also inspired new scholarship revising the
legendary image of the Vikings. By John Noble Wilford. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT28 sent on 04/27, and a map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Forty
years ago a social and medical revolution was set off: the Pill was
born. And as people were to learn later, it had a number of side
effects, good and bad, as well as helping kick off a sexual
revolution, freeing women of the confines of other generations.
Since its introduction, an estimated 468 million American women
have taken the pill. Today more than 16 million American women are
on it, making it the most popular contraceptive technique outside
of sterilization. By Jane E. Brody. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JEWS-DIASPORA (Undated) _ Following the trail left in the Y
chromosome, geneticists chart the Jewish diaspora. By Nicholas
Wade. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Undated) _ The government consortium decoding the
human genome announces that it has sequenced its second chromosome,
No. 21, which is linked to Down's syndrome. The chromosome turns
out to contain surprisingly few genes. By Nicholas Wade. (600
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEWZEALAND-ECOLOGY (Undated) _ Authorities in New Zealand
continue to strive mightily to keep out invasive species with the
potential to destroy the prisitine ecological balance of that
island nation. By Alan Coukell. (975 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA (Washington) _ NASA engineers and experts on spacecraft
design talk about new ideas for yet faster, cheaper, better space
exploration. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIGHTMAN-PHYSICS (Undated) _ A physicist-turned-writer looks
back on what he misses about science: the purity. Theoretical
physicists, and many other kinds of scientists, work in a world of
the mind. It is a mathematical world without bodies, without
people, without the vagaries of human emotion. By Alan Lightman.
(1025 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MILKYWAY-COLLIDE (Undated) _ Andromeda and the Milky Way are
speeding toward each other at more than a quarter-million miles per
hour. In three billion years, the two galaxies may slam together
head-on. By Kenneth Chang. (790 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Items about Arctic and Antarctic species
being ever so similar; the effects of El Nino; blister beetles'
remarkable survival techniques. By Herny Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ULTRASOUND (Undated) _ Since the '70s, ultrasound has grown
up. Rather than simply glancing at the fetus, doctors today take a
series of measurements: the length of the fetus; the length of the
thigh bone; and the circumferences of the head and abdomen. They
check the four chambers of the heart and the structures of the
kidney and bladder. And now ultrasound is on the verge of yet
another revolution. The latest gadgets, though far from standard
use, create three-dimensional images of the fetus and may be used
to peer deep within the fetal brain, identifying fine points of the
developing anatomy never seen before. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
(1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AMNIOCENTESIS (Undated) _ Women share the joys and sorrows
of amniocentesis, as compiled by in interviews for a book by Dr.
Renna Rapp. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROSTATE-TREATMENT (Undated) _ Like Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, 180,000 American men will suddenly learn that they have
prostate cancer this year, and what makes their decisions so
difficult is that doctors do not know which treatment is most
effective. Better information about survival and side effects may
come from studies in Canada, Sweden and the United States, but not
for several years. Until then, patients must rely on limited
information. Not surprisingly, wide variations in practice occur.
By Lawrence K. Altman. (1320 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTOR-TRAINING (Undated) _ The pressures of efficiency and
profits are ruining the environment of the teaching hospital. The
bottom line: doctors in training to longer have the time to
contemplate and think through their decisions. And that may mean a
new generation of physicians unable or unwilling to challenge
conventional wisdom or go beyond the standardized prescribed course
of treatment. By David A. Shaywitz, M.D. and Dennis A. Ausiello,
M.D. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on helth and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A study that looked at almost 13,000 people over six years
found that those who were most prone to anger were about 2.5 times
as likely to have heart attacks or sudden cardiac deaths than their
calmer counterparts. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Most Americans still don't eat the 5 daily servings of fruits
and vegetables so widely recommended, a new study shows. (290
words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Oxidants may actually have value in repairing diseases to
heart vessels. (240 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Now, experts say, the crucial number in a blood pressure
reading is the systolic pressure, the top one, not the bottom. (300
words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Ulcerative colitis, a serious disease in which the lining of
the colon and rectum become inflamed causing severe pain, appears
to be worsened by long-term stress, a new study has found. (150
words0
</P>
