<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OCONNOR-ART-370&AMP;ADD-N     05-08 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-ART-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH AND POLITICAL LEADERS HONOR O'CONNOR AT MASS  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the sounds of choral hymns rose toward church
spires, Roman Catholic leaders draped in white robes slowly filed
through the portals of St. Patrick's Cathedral Monday afternoon to
commence the elaborate funeral Mass of Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders began their short march after 1 p.m. on the
sweltering streets in front of the cathedral in Midtown Manhattan,
where hundreds of worshippers, some tearful, had gathered since the
morning Mass. The solemn procession then turned into the cool
recesses of the cathedral, where the cardinal's body rested in his
wooden coffin, awaiting this final congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners from around the world gathered before the gilded altar
to pay their final respects to the most influential Roman Catholic
leader in America.
</P>
<P>
   Before the funeral began, church officials estimated that about
3,500 people would pack the cathedral for the invitation-only
ceremony. They included President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, former President George Bush, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and more than 100 bishops, archbishops
and cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   State and city leaders also attended, including Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, former Mayor Edward Koch and New York state Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal, who died on May 3 at the age of 80, was the eighth
man to lead the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York. For 16
years he led one of the most diverse Catholic constituencies in the
world. But for the last eight months, O'Connor's health flagged as
he struggled with brain cancer. This year, he missed his first
Easter Mass since ascending to his position.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely expected that Pope John Paul II will appoint Bishop
Edward M. Egan of Bridgeport, Conn., to the empty post, perhaps as
early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The successor is expected to be as vocal a champion of Catholic
tenets as was O'Connor. He tried to influence some of the most
controversial social issues of the day, speaking out against
abortion and holding a firm line on church teachings regarding
homosexuality and the ordination of women. Such stringent views won
him many admirers in the church but also inspired critics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the Mass began, the cardinal's closed coffin rested in
the center aisle near the altar, bathed in light streaming through
stained glass windows. The cathedral portals were opened to allow
hundreds of priests, nuns, deacons, representatives of lay orders
and leaders of other religions to enter the cathedral. Many of the
priests helping to celebrate the Mass wore the archdiocesan
chasuble, a sleeveless outer vestment, designed for Pope John Paul
II's tour of the New York area in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishops followed the first marchers in the procession. Those
bringing up the rear were among the highest-ranking officials of
the Roman Catholic Church. They included two cardinals from the
Vatican and 13 from the United States and four other countries. All
wore crimson skullcaps identifying them as cardinals, white
vestments symbolizing the resurrection and the miters that church
princes have long worn.
</P>
<P>
   The rituals ushering O'Connor into the afterlife have evolved
for centuries, since cardinals were likened to princes and popes
were regarded as monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve other Catholic leaders have been entombed in the crypt at
St. Patrick's Cathedral, beginning with Cardinal John Hughes. The
same ritual was followed for all of them: the coffin was carried
past the altar, down a short marble staircase and through the
bronze doors below the sacristy. There, according to Catholic
beliefs, the bodies were to be hidden forever from human eyes while
the spirits ascended to their appointment with God.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday morning, hundreds of worshippers came to the
cathedral hoping to catch a final glimpse of the cardinal before he
was laid to rest. But after the 8 a.m. Mass ended, church officials
unexpectedly ushered everyone outside to allow Secret Service
agents to conduct a security sweep before President Clinton
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Those who had come for later ceremonies were barred from
entering. Some worshippers prayed on the cathedral steps while
others stood outside the doors as policemen politely turned people
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was the cardinal for all the people, not for the
politicians or the Secret Service,'' said Faith Mavretich, 40, who
had come with her 10-year-old daughter, Jennie. ``You could get
angry, but I don't think Cardinal O'Connor would get angry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
