<P>
   TONY-NOMINEES (New York) _ In the Tony Award nominations, a
struggling new musical, ``The Wild Party,'' won seven nominations
and a mother and daughter were pitted against one another in the
leading actress category. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-MUSIC (Vienna) _ In this land of musical effervescence
and, lately, political uproar, a silence spoke louder than either
after an account of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony by Sir Simon Rattle
and the Vienna Philharmonic at the quarry of a former concentration
camp in Mauthausen, Austria. By James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   NY-AUCTION (New York) _ On the auction of Impressionist works at
Christies. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WAGNER-RING (New York) _ A Critic's Notebook: No ``Ring'' cycle
guarantees customer satisfaction. Wagner's four-evening, weeklong
operatic monster, known officially as ``Der Ring des Niebelungen,''
has too many spiritual and physical moving parts to inspire
consensus. Barter and negotiation occupy the minds and hearts of
every audience member: what must I surrender to gain what I most
value? The trades are not easily made. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-BOOK-REVIEW (Undted) _ ``Half a Heart,'' by Rosellen Brown
(Farrar, Straus, Giroux). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
