<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9037 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-08 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL TRUTHS ARE SELF-EVIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the end of the recent legislative session, Arizona became
first state in the nation to require grade-school children to
recite the passage from the Declaration of Independence beginning,
``We hold these truths to be self-evident, that all men are created
equal.''
</P>
<P>
   We did it, apparently, to keep the little brats from whining
about the fact lawmakers have done nothing for them. It's there in
black and white. All men are created equal. Nothing about children.
Deal with it, kiddies.
</P>
<P>
   The passage continues:
</P>
<P>
   ``That they (all men) are endowed by their creator with certain
unalienable rights. That among these are life, liberty, and the
pursuit of happiness. That to secure these rights, governments are
instituted among men, deriving their just powers from the consent
of the governed . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation requiring Arizona's kids to repeat these words
each day was called ``a huge victory for future generations of
children in Arizona'' by Len Munsil of the Center for Arizona
Policy, an organization that prides itself on standing up for the
Declaration's values _ as long as the liberty you pursue in life
doesn't involve any actual happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Munsil told me it was vital to make kids recite the passage in
order to ``reinforce the most important principles'' of our
country.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Munsil and his organization and their allies lobby
the legislature to preserve unenforced Arizona laws that make a
crime of co-habitation (which is popular among senior citizens
hoping to keep their benefits) as well as certain activities
engaged in by adults within the privacy of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   As Munsil so delicately put it earlier this year, ``Is it really
necessary for the Legislature to spend its time giving the state of
Arizona's stamp of approval to cheating on your spouse, shacking up
and anal intercourse?''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Arizona policy also would like to prohibit anyone
in the state from wagering a few bucks on the state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   It would like to make it impossible for anyone to purchase a
girlie magazine or rent a naughty movie from the video store.
</P>
<P>
   It wants laws on the books making it more difficult to get a
divorce, apparently believing it's better for children to live with
unhappily married parents than happily divorced ones.
</P>
<P>
   It's against any kind of state-subsidized day-care for poor
families but is more than willing to give special ``education tax
credits'' to parents wealthy enough to afford the price of private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Munsil's vision of a more perfect America, a woman who had an
abortion would be charged with murder, as would her doctor and any
accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   All this, it seems, will come to pass eventually if we first
have our children recite like robots an otherwise lovely passage
from one of the world's great documents.
</P>
<P>
   This same type of mindless memorization _ without any thought to
what the words on the page actually stand for _ was tried when some
of us were kids. The plan worked spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   Because of it, you and I and just about every thief, con man and
murderer in the nation's prison system can successfully recite the
Pledge of Allegiance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
