<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-08 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSING THE BORDER TO ABSURDITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd think a nice retired couple
</P>
<P>
   like Rocky and Midge Wahl would have learned long ago that being
an honest, taxpaying citizen doesn't give you the right to
disregard U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we were thinking,'' Rocky told me.
</P>
<P>
   The Wahls brazenly violated long-standing U.S. immigration
practices and conspired to transport a young Mexican couple across
the international border _ legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured the best way to get this done was to go completely
by the book,'' Rocky said, pausing while we had a good laugh
together.
</P>
<P>
   The Wahls divide their time between Arizona, Washington state
and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, in Mazatlan, they met a young Mexican teenager named
Oscar. The Wahls and Oscar became friends, visiting his home and
meeting his family. They've dined together, gone to sporting events
and traveled some in Mexico. Oscar now is in his 20s and married to
Lorena.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Wahls invited Oscar and Lorena to accompany them
from Arizona to Washington. The plan was to take 25 days and visit
the West from the Grand Canyon to Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The Wahls planned to pay for all their friends' expenses. They
helped the couple acquire Mexican passports, then paid for Oscar
and Lorena to travel from Mazatlan to Hermosillo so they could
apply for U.S. visas at the consulate there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent all manner of documentation to the consulate,'' Rocky
said. ``We informed them we were paying for the trip and made a
personal guarantee that Oscar and Lorena would return to Mexico. We
thought that would have more than satisfied American officials.''
</P>
<P>
   A vice consul in Hermosillo looked through all of the Wahls'
paperwork, complimented them on their thoroughness and generosity _
then denied the visas. The Wahls were told that because Oscar and
Lorena don't own a home or a car, they couldn't be trusted to
return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very large and close family down there,'' Rocky
said. ``Oscar has a good job (at a hotel). Neither one has a desire
to live here. We told them (consulate officials) all this. For some
reason, that wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Morisseau at the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City told me the
embassy alone processes 2 million visa requests a year. Consulates
across Mexico process thousands more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final decision is the consul's,'' Morisseau said. Oscar
and Lorena can apply again in a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wahls went so far as to offer a sizable bond they were
willing to forfeit if their friends didn't go home. That, too,
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can walk out of my door in Redmond (Wash.) and see illegal
immigrants working in orchards,'' Rocky said.
</P>
<P>
   If Oscar and Lorena had wanted to pick fruit rather than have
lunch in the Space Needle, Wahl figures they'd have had no trouble
at all.
</P>
<P>
   The government did offer a compromise, it turns out. The Wahls
were told that their net worth, along with the other information
they provided, qualified them to sponsor Oscar and Lorena for
permanent resident status in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Just not for a visit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
