<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: V-E bonfire ''twas a glorious
sight'
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Lois Oller Nasados
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   It was V-E Day _ Victory in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler's forces had surrendered, and those of us kids who
watched Saturday movie newsreels knew it was only a matter of time
before Japan would give up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Why wait? We were ready for a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the war practically over, but my father would be
coming home from the Navy. I was certain it would be any day now.
</P>
<P>
   Since we couldn't have fireworks because of the wartime
shortages, the most excitement we could envision was a huge
bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Where? Well, in the middle of the street, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone big enough to pull a wagon or carry an armload of
newspapers was recruited to gather materials.
</P>
<P>
   We went from neighbor to neighbor collecting the newspapers they
had been saving for the Victory Paper Drive held each month by the
local public schools to help the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   A few stubborn souls held out, claiming the United States might
need their papers to finish the job of winning the war in the
Pacific. But most folks were ready to celebrate with us.
</P>
<P>
   At this point an ad hoc committee of parents stepped in. After
assuring us they wouldn't spoil our fun, they put two older boys in
charge of the building the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   The ``little kids'' -- though none of us admitted to being in
that category _ were sent to watch from the porches with parents
and grandparents. The ``big kids'' -- everybody else _ could stand
as close as the curb.
</P>
<P>
   To quote my Irish grandfather, ``'Twas a glorious sight.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bonfire that blazed long past our usual bedtimes,
two things stand out in my memory.
</P>
<P>
   My mother worried that my father, stationed on a repair ship
based at San Diego, might still be sent to the Pacific war zone.
The war with Japan must be ended quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as important in her mind was the problem of continued
rationing and food shortages. Would she be able to buy enough sugar
and real butter to bake Daddy his favorite cake to welcome him
home?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, my father came safely home, greeted by three excited
children, each with a different story about the Great V-E Bonfire,
and by a beaming wife _ and yes, with a real cake, complete with
chocolate frosting.
</P>
<P>
   (Lois Oller Nasados lives in Gladewater, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
