<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9054 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-TIRES-HNS &LR;      05-08 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-TIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW TIRES MAY MAKE JACKS A THING OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not the kind of situation anyone wants to experience:
Changing a tire on a dark freeway in the middle of the night, with
cars buzzing by inches away at 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But it has happened to many of us. Tires are prone to going
flat; all it takes is a nail, screw or piece of debris to puncture
the rubber and let out the air.
</P>
<P>
   What if you could just keep on driving to a repair shop, where
the tire could be repaired safely while you lounge in the waiting
room?
</P>
<P>
   It's possible with an innovation in technology introduced to the
U.S. market in 1993 on the Chevrolet Corvette sports car: the
Goodyear Tire Co.'s run-flat tire, known as the EMT (short for
``extended-mobility tire'').
</P>
<P>
   With the model in use on the Corvette, the driver can keep going
even if all of the air escapes from the tire. And it isn't
necessary to stop at the nearest service station or tire shop; the
Corvette run-flat tires can be run up to 200 miles at 55 mph,
according to engineers from Akron, Ohio-based Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, we've driven 1,000 miles on one of these tires with a
2 1/2-inch hole in it, without a problem,'' said Bill Egan,
Goodyear's chief engineer for advanced product design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run-flat is the best technology so far that keeps you from
having to stop and change a tire,'' he said. ``It's so good, that
the two cars that come from the manufacturer with these tires _ the
Corvette and the Plymouth Prowler _ don't even come with a spare
tire. It can fail only from the standpoint of running it too far
and too fast; but even then, the failure is not catastrophic. You
don't want to drive very fast very far, because the tire gets hot
very fast with no air in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet began offering the Goodyear EMT as an option on
Corvettes in 1993, but when the fifth-generation 'Vette debuted in
1997, the tires were made standard, and the spare tire and jack
were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Goodyear introduced a line of Aquatred EMT run-flat
tires for vehicles other than the Corvette and the Prowler. They
don't have quite the range as a flat Corvette tire, but they will
go up to 50 miles at 55 mph with no problem, Egan said.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight sizes available to fit most popular sedans from
the midsize Ford Taurus, Honda Accord and Toyota Camry to the
high-end full-size cars such as the Buick Park Avenue and the
Cadillac Seville.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of the tires is a rigid sidewall that supports the
weight of the vehicle even if all of the air is gone. Goodyear uses
a special computer-designed steel thread in the tires to give it
the added strength.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the tires are available only for cars; they aren't
considered strong enough to support the weight of pickups, vans and
sport-utility vehicles, Egan said.
</P>
<P>
   For the cars that can use them, the new tires aren't cheap, and
there is a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Besides paying $120 to $150 apiece for the tires, each consumer
must also buy a low-air-pressure warning system that is installed
in each wheel to alert the driver if one of the tires loses its
air, Goodyear officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That system can cost up to $400 per car. But for now, in an
effort to get more people to buy these new tires, the company is
offering the pressure-warning system free, said Bob Toth,
Goodyear's marketing manager for consumer auto tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is that the tire performs so well when it loses air
that we can't leave it to the driver to determine when it has lost
air,'' he said. ``We require that you outfit your car with the
low-pressure warning system.''
</P>
<P>
   That system is rather high-tech itself: It consists of a
pressure gauge hooked to a miniature radio transmitter fitted into
each wheel. When the air pressure falls below 20 pounds, the
transmitter sends a signal to a dashboard-mounted receiver that
warns the driver that there is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the transmitters has its own lithium-ion battery that is
designed to last at least as long as the tire, Egan said. To
conserve battery power, the devices shut themselves off after the
car has stopped for a few minutes, and they turn themselves back on
when the wheels start spinning again.
</P>
<P>
   In the Corvette and Prowler, the system is installed when the
vehicles come down the assembly line, and the warning receiver is
integrated into the instrument panel.
</P>
<P>
   But with after-sale installations, the receiver might not be the
most aesthetically pleasing piece of equipment in the car's cabin,
Toth said. It has to be attached to the dashboard or hung from a
sun visor, and it is usually plugged into the cigarette lighter
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the issues we still have to overcome,'' he
said. ``They just aren't very pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   That technology is evolving, though, and soon the
pressure-warning systems should be less obtrusive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, most people will be driving on run-flat tires _
either Goodyear's or comparable tires developed by other
manufacturers, such as Michelin's new PAX run-flats _ tire experts
predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I want these tires on the cars my wife and
daughters are driving,'' Toth said. ``It's just not safe to get out
of the car and change a tire these days.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are some other solutions to that problem, however. Several
tire manufacturers, including Uniroyal, are selling self-sealing
tires, which come with a soft compound inside that works
automatically to seal the tire in the event of a minor puncture,
such as from a small nail or screw. They can't handle really large
punctures, however.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the market are puncture sealants that can be injected
into a flat tire through the air valve. These are readily available
at most auto parts stores.
</P>
<P>
   But they work ``just about 10 percent of the time, and they will
void the manufacturer's warranty on the tire,'' Egan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are water-based, some solvent-based. And some are not
very friendly to have running inside the tire. The chemicals in
them can attack the tire and make it fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear is now marketing a puncture-resistant tire for some
sport-utility vehicles, perfect for off-road use such as on the
famous Rubicon Trail in California, Goodyear spokesman Dave Wilkins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, run-flat tires are available for many passenger cars
on the road today, and customers are embracing them even though
they do cost more and come with the complication of the
pressure-warning system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
