<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-YOUNG-VOTERS-COX     05-08 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-VOTERS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Young voters, students sometimes feel unwelcome
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Montgomery
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Melissa Fried of Washington Township, Ohio, .
knows she looks young, even for an 18-year-old, but she didn't
expect her youthfulness to be such a burden when she went to vote
this year in Ohio's presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Poll workers ``really questioned'' her about her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three times they asked me how old I was and I kept telling
them,'' Fried said. ``They said, `Well, what year were you born?' I
mean, why would I lie about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, they huffed impatiently because she didn't know
how to use the key-punch voting system.
</P>
<P>
   The workers may only have been being vigilant, protecting the
integrity of the election rolls, but the result made Fried feel
unwelcome as she cast her first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be a nice experience, but the whole
time I felt like I wasn't good enough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom pegs apathy as the leading cause of dismal
turnout among potential voters between the ages of 18 and 34, but
some election experts and activists say the problem is deeper than
that.
</P>
<P>
   From obstinate election officials to registration laws that
don't take into account the mobility of the young, the U.S.
electoral system offers more obstacles than incentives, say
advocates who are trying to reverse the decline in participation
among young Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes those obstacles seem deliberate. For instance,
Michigan put a new law into effect last month requiring the home
address on a voter's registration card to match his or her driver
license. For college students who typically move annually the new
law means they'll have to get a new driver's license each year if
they want to vote in local elections where they go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's aimed specifically at preventing students from voting,''
said Michael Delli Carpini, who as head of Policy and Programs for
the Pew Charitable Trusts has funneled grant money into many youth
voting initiatives. ``I think that's a great example of the system
actually working against young people voting.''
</P>
<P>
   A Michigan state legislator who introduced the bill called it a
``common sense'' law to ensure that people vote where they really
live, but youth voting advocates say it's designed to make voting
more difficult for people whose voting habits may be harder to
predict. Six university student groups joined the Michigan ACLU in
filing a legal challenge to the new law, but last month a federal
judge rejected their request for an injunction to block the law
from being enforced. The judge said the inconvenience of renewing a
license wasn't an unreasonable burden on voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really frustrating,'' said Windi Yager, 20, a junior at
Central Michigan University, who as a member of the school's
student government has been involved in voter registration drives
on campus. Yager said she has left her parents' address on her
driver's license for simplicity, so that such things as health
insurance and financial records don't get tangled by her constant
relocating.
</P>
<P>
   But Yager has a 12-month lease in Mount Pleasant, and that's
where she recently completed the Census form that will help Mount
Pleasant's local elected officials get their proper share of
federal money for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Yager said she simply wants to vote on the local issues that
effect her directly. Voting absentee in her home town of
Beavertown, Mich., isn't a good option. ``Why would I want to vote
in Beavertown?'' she said. ``I live in Mount Pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   She said in the months before the new law went into effect, her
campus was shot through with rumors that changing a driver's
license address could cost students everything from health
insurance to financial aid to scholarships. She said most of the
rumors couldn't be confirmed one way or another because
</P>
<P>
   policies vary from one institution to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't really involved in voting and I was just a regular
student here, I'd be extremely deterred from voting if I thought
something in my records might get messed up by changing my
address,'' she said. ``Society doesn't put a lot of pressure on
young people to vote, so anything that discourages it ....''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of mobility looms large among young Americans. In a
Census study in 1998, about 25 percent of Americans 35 or younger
said they had moved in the last year, but that percentage dropped
to about 7 percent for those 45 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very, very mobile generation,'' said Russ Freyman,
director of Neglection 2000, a youth voter project. ``And that
flies in the face of registration requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   That conflict flared earlier this year in New Hampshire, which
is one of the few states that permits same-day voter registration.
On the day of that state's first-in-the-nation primary in February,
hundreds of University of New Hampshire students flocked to the
town's polling place for a get-out-the-vote rally by the Bill
Bradley presidential campaign and a group called Youthvote 2000.
But when the students arrived they were greeted by poll workers who
so vehemently questioned the students' claims of residency some
simply gave up, according to a rally organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire Attorney General's Office conducted an
investigation, but no action was taken because students filed no
formal complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent a letter reminding our communities that have
universities that they need to allow the students to register,''
said New Hampshire Assistant Attorney General Anne Edwards, ``that
a dorm address is good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this leads Ohio Secretary of State J. Kenneth Blackwell
to conclude it's unfair to simply label young voters as
disinterested or apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do think it's unfair,'' said Blackwell, whose office
handles elections in Ohio. ``Younger people are further down the
political food chain so it's easier to dump on them and say they're
apathetic than it is to look in the mirror at what we're doing to
help them become voters.''
</P>
<P>
   What would help young people become voters?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can break that down into two words,'' Blackwell said.
``Adult example.''
</P>
<P>
   He said dwindling turnout among all Americans makes it even more
difficult to draw younger people into the process. As the Pew
Trust's Delli Carpini said: ``Young people reflect us better than
we'd like them to.''
</P>
<P>
   And Blackwell, himself a campaign veteran who has run on state
and local ballots for years, said not everyone in the political
arena is eager to reverse the trend in youth voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are whole legions of campaign professionals, and some
weird pundits, that have made megabucks on low voter turnout
elections,'' Blackwell said. ``Do I think we have a whole class of
election professionals who prefer a smaller, more manageable
turnout? Yes, and that's a big part of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without sinister motive, some say campaigns are
perpetuating a chicken-and-egg problem: The campaigns don't target
young people because they don't vote, but then young people don't
vote because the campaigns haven't targeted them. Or perhaps it's
the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Neglection 2000, a project run by the young voting
group Third Millennium, tried to chronicle the dilemma by studying
the use of campaign commercials in the heat of the presidential
primary earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Studying media markets in four cities from Dec. 1, 1999 through
the decisive March 7 primary, Neglection 2000 used marketing
demographics and concluded that the presidential campaigns seldom
ran their television ads on shows or during viewing hours when
young voters were likely to see them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the study found that only 36 presidential campaign
ads ran during the popular young people's show Friends, compared
with 651 ads during the ``older leaning'' Today.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to Neglection 2000, was that only 17
percent of those between the ages of 18 and 34 remembered a
campaign commercial, but for those over age 50 the percentage
jumped to 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For Nan Whaley, the youth coordinator for the Montgomery County
Democratic Party, none of this is surprising. At 24, she still
believes young people have to take more responsibility for becoming
engaged in voting, but she said the system needs to bend a bit to
help make that easier.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for instance, the University of Dayton is likely to
become one of the rare college campuses with a polling place on its
grounds. The Montgomery County Board of Elections still is
reviewing the details of how the new precinct would be drawn, but
approval is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a polling place on campus took years. To split a
precinct, state law requires 1,000 new and active voters to be
counted in an existing precinct, but that's hard to do in a college
neighborhood when people are moving out every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us five years,'' said Whaley, who began working on the
project when she was a freshman at the school. ``The board of
elections people didn't really believe this ever would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With a polling place on campus, Whaley is convinced UD will
dramatically raise its voter participation rate among students
simply because voting will be so much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Yager, the frustrated junior at Central Michigan University,
admits it may sound like the height of laziness to say voting
should be made easy. But, she counters, at least it shouldn't be
made hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it just sounds like little things,'' she said, ``but if
you take all the little things and put them together it becomes a
big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
