 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-DEAL (Zeist, Netherlands) _ Now that the Lockerbie
trial is under way, questions are arising about the deal that
persuaded Libya to turn over the suspects for trial. There are
hints in documents and elsewhere that the price Moamar Khadafy
exacted was an agreement by the United States and Britain that they
would not pursue anyone higher up in the operation. By Kevin
Cullen. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDS (Johannesburg) _ After months of strange talk on
AIDS, indulging discredited theories and speculating about the
toxicity of AZT, South African President Thabo Mbeki brings a panel
of scientists together to consider the epidemic in Africa. By Kurt
Shillinger. 690 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Amsterdam) _ When Canadian soldiers liberated
the Netherlands from Nazi oppression in 1945, the Dutch never
forgot. By Kevin Cullen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MCCAIN (Undated) _ As George W. Bush and John McCain
prepare to meet for the first time since the primaries, uncertainty
about the warmth of their tete-a-tete dogs the presumptive
Republican nominee and potentially imperils his candidacy. By Jill
Zuckman. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CITIZENS-ARMED (Undated) _ Twice in the past few weeks we've
seen news stories about apparently sane people in relatively safe
areas packing a loaded gun. Why do citizens feel they must be armed
to be safe when the crime rate is the lowest it's been in 30 years?
By Scot Lehigh. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   PEYTON-PLACE (Camden, Maine) _ As part of a film festival called
``Small Towns, Steamy Movies,'' Camden hosts fans of ``Peyton
Place,'' the seminal small-town melodrama. Behind the campy fun is
the grim true-life experience of author Grace Metalious. By Ellen
Barry. 1380 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORKER (New York) _ The New Yorker throws a 75th birthday
bash, strutting its stable of writers and poets and cartoonists for
audiences in love with the magazine and the idea of it. By Sam
Allis. 1470 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-EMBARGO (Undated) _ Now that the Elian flap has calmed
down, it's time to begin dismantling the embargo that's at the root
of much of the United States' battle with Cuba. By Adrian Walker.
1350 words.
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) -- Who's against racial preferences?
Almost everyone. By Jeff Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Despite falling behind in some polls,
Vice President Al Gore could still become president _ especially if
he gets a little more help from conservative Republicans. By Robert
A. Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Undated) _ The housing near-crisis did not
happen overnight or by accident. It was the conscious decimation of
a national effort by Ronald Reagan and George W.'s father. By
Thomas Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Kathie Lee's woe-is-me marketing. By
Diane White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
