   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-STAIN (Undated) _ In his 40-year probe of the national
psyche, Philip Roth has hardly been bashful about putting his own
consciousness under scrutiny. By Gail Caldwell. 1680 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-END-OF-DAY (Undated) _ George V. Higgins' ``At End of Day''
is a terrific and topical book that takes off from headlines. By
Richard Dyer. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-DONS (Undated) _ Long before there were playing fields at
Eton, the British had raised insiderdom to an art form. In the last
century, it had few finer practitioners than Noel Annan, who died
in February at age 83. By Mark Feeney. 760 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SILENCE (Undated) _ Billed as historical fiction, Rose
Tremain's ``Music and Silence'' is anything but. By Amy Graves.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SINGLES (Undated) _ A major shift is under way in pop
music: With technologies that enable consumers to create their own
``greatest hits,'' the single is back. By Joan Anderman. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CRITERION (New York) _ With DVDs, Criterion company has
been restoring classics, adding commentary and scenes, to make a
film school in a box. By Michael Blowen. 1630 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GUIDE (Undated) _ Globe critics review current movies.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-VIDEOS (Undated) _ Good and bad in video films. By Globe
staff.
</P>
<P>
   STAGE-BALKANS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ A Macedonian is directing
``The Winter's Tale,'' as he has in most of his work lately, with
the recent fighting in mind. By Catherine Foster. 1450 words.
</P>
