<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9064 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PAIN-COX     05-08 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reports find patients' needs misunderstood
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Physicians need to be more sensitive to their
patients' pain and more receptive to using both opiates and
alternative therapies, a Gallup survey and two research studies
have shown in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Stenning already knew that.
</P>
<P>
   For 55 years, he has battled spinal pain from a World War II
injury through surgeries and spinal fusion, from local hospitals to
the Mayo Clinic, using leg braces and crutches but never escaping
the pain that both wore him out and kept him awake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pretty much decided I'd had it with doctors and surgeons
and what have you,'' Stenning says, but when his wife, Anne, read
something about a pain seminar two years ago, ``I decided to take
one more crack at it.''
</P>
<P>
   That seminar at Miami Valley Hospital led to surgery in October
in which a morphine pump was implanted in his abdomen and connected
to his spinal fluid.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-programmed pump provides much greater relief with
far lower doses by sending morphine straight to the central nervous
system, and it eases fears of morphine addiction by taking the
patient's decisions out of the equation. But even though all the
public hospitals in Montgomery County perform the procedure, Dr.
Townsend Smith says it's like most other pain treatments in that
it's not helping as many patients as it could.
</P>
<P>
   People suffer unnecessarily across the pain spectrum, from
aggravating to debilitating, largely because they don't know they
have a choice. As the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
said Thursday in an arthritis report, available methods for
treating pain and educating patients are underused. The problem is
compounded by misconceptions among health professionals and
government regulators about both pain itself and the opioid
pain-killing drugs that include morphine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very big scare in most physicians' minds about
prescribing opioids for chronic pain problems,'' says Smith,
associate director of Miami Valley Hospital's Pain Center. Doing so
invites heavy government scrutiny and requires voluminous record
keeping, all with the doctor's license at stake. But there are
situations, says Smith, where no alternative pain management
exists.
</P>
<P>
   Even physicians tend to overestimate the risk of addiction,
according to University of Wisconsin Medical School findings
published April 5 in The Journal of the American Medical
Association. The report said medical opioids' share of all
drug-abuse cases decreased from 5.1 percent to 3.8 percent from
1990 to 1996, and previous research has shown such addiction is
rare among patients who never were addicted to anything else.
</P>
<P>
   About three of every seven American adults _ 42 percent _
experience pain daily, according to the Gallup survey of 2,002
adults for the Arthritis Foundation and several other
organizations. Opiates aren't appropriate for all of them, but some
treatment is called for when the same percentage, or 83 million
Americans, say pain ``frequently affects their participation in
some activities.'' The survey's margin for error was plus or minus
2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthritis and other types of pain significantly impact the
lives of most Americans, but many aren't comfortable taking the
first step to find relief _ talking to their doctor,'' says Dr.
Jack Klippel, medical director of the Arthritis Foundation, which
launched a ``Speaking of Pain'' program last month in hopes of
making the subject more prominent.
</P>
<P>
   It's telling, then, that one of the things Stenning, 75, found
most impressive about Smith was, ``He's a listener.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the roughly half of adults who see doctors for pain
treatment, the Arthritis Foundation survey says barely two-fifths
of them ``believe their doctor completely understands how their
pain makes them feel.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason pain is undertreated, Stenning says. Very few
doctors ``understand that kind of pain because they've never
experienced it.'' He recalls with contempt a military doctor who
was so insensitive to an amputee's ``phantom limb'' pain that he
opened his empty hand and said, ``Here are some phantom pills for
your phantom pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In Stenning's case, pain came from bending, sitting ``for any
length of time,'' turning the wrong way in bed, really just being
alive. Sometimes it was nerve pain shooting across his back or down
a leg. Sometimes it felt as if ``someone had put a knife in the
middle of my spine and was turning it.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much he could do ``without the pain becoming an
all-encompassing reality in my system.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialists are learning more techniques to fight pain all the
time, Smith says. The World Congress on Pain two years ago
recommended an ``analgesic ladder'' starting with nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory drugs such as aspirin and progressing to such
milder opioid pills as codeine, then to stronger opioids in
morphine's class and finally to the heavy artillery of corrective
surgery, intravenous opioids, microwave therapy and epidural nerve
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those options, 80 percent of respondents in the Gallup
survey called pain an unavoidable result of aging, 60 percent said
it is ``just something you have to live with'' and 28 percent
didn't believe there was ``any real solution'' for pain. Older
Americans are more likely to suffer pain regularly, certainly, but
even in the 18-to-34 age group, two-thirds of those polled reported
pain at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are starting to understand that at some point, pain
goes from being merely a symptom to being a disease process,''
Smith says. ``There are studies showing changes in the nerves
themselves as a result of a chronic, painful stimulus.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain complicates cancer treatment, for example, by robbing
patients of appetites and therefore nutrients, and of energy and
therefore exercise and social contacts. Cancer patients account for
about one-quarter of the 26 pumps Smith has installed in his three
years at Miami Valley, says Randy Lakes, his registered nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see more of them,'' Lakes says. ``Cancer patients
really respond well and often return to a practically normal
lifestyle. These people typically outlive their prognosis.''
</P>
<P>
   Back pain is the most common problem Smith treats with the pump.
It's often a vicious cycle, Smith says, because surgery to repair
back pain leads naturally to scar tissue that can cause worse back
pain. The pump also can be filled with Baclofen, a strong muscle
relaxant to relieve spasticity in some quadriplegics and people
with multiple sclerosis or cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   The morphine pump is a treatment of last resort, Smith says, for
the 5 percent to 10 percent of pain patients who can't be relieved
otherwise. Prospective patients are first screened psychologically
and hospitalized for three days to simulate the pump with an IV
drip.
</P>
<P>
   The pump, about the size of a hockey puck, is placed in the
abdomen with a catheter going to the intrathecal fluid around the
spinal cord. ``That is where we have the highest concentration of
receptors for pain,'' Smith says, ``so we can get better results
with a much lower dose of medication, sometimes one-300th of what
we were giving orally.''
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of decrease in his own opioids, Stenning says the
medication no longer clouds his concentration as it occasionally
did before. He still has some pain. ``It's not a cure-all,'' he
says. But the pain no longer overshadows everything else. He no
longer wakes up in agony two or three times a night.
</P>
<P>
   The pump can be refilled by injection and reprogrammed by radio
waves, but its batteries need to be replaced surgically every five
to seven years. It also has the advantage for doctors of not
requiring repeated large prescriptions for opioids.
</P>
<P>
   Other physicians often refer patients to Smith, says Lakes,
``because they don't want to prescribe narcotics themselves.'' But
Lakes says Ohio's State Medical Board makes no allowances for a
pain-treatment specialty when it monitors a doctor's prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in addition to governmental fear of addiction, Congress is
considering legislation to further impede pain medication as a
means of discouraging physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be looking to utilize these medications in the
appropriate situations regardless of personal feelings,'' Smith
says. In other words, stop considering anything else but the
patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife used to say, `Your face is full of pain,''' Stenning
says. ``That doesn't happen anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact for the Arthritis Foundation for the booklet Speaking
of Pain: How to Talk with Your Doctor about Pain, sponsored by drug
manufacturer Merck &AMP; Co., by calling the AF Information Line at
(800) 283-7800 or on the Web at www.arthritis.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Kevin Lamb at 225-2129 or e-mail at
kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
