<HEADER>
A9084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MOMS-MARCH09-COX     05-08 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMS-MARCH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEARS FOR CHILDREN INSPIRED MANY TO JOIN ANTI-GUN MARCH
 &HT;    820&AMP;adds. With MOMS-GOALS.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Parenting in America has come to this: Before
letting their children play at a friend's home, mothers routinely
ask if there's a gun in the house and, if so, whether it has been
safely locked away.
</P>
<P>
   Caren(cq) Appel started inquiring after her 9-year-old daughter,
Molly, was visiting a pal in an Atlanta suburb and the friend's
5-year-old brother walked in with a parent's firearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my 6-year-old goes to play with a friend, one of the
questions I ask is if they have a gun,'' said Margaret Erickson of
Austin, Texas, who has two sons, Michael, 6, and Christopher Robin,
3.
</P>
<P>
   Before dropping off her 4-year-old son on a play date, ``I have
to ask if they keep a gun in their home,'' agreed Valerie Hartman
Levy, another Atlanta mom. ``Children can't get into a bottle of
Tylenol because of the safety cap, but they could easily pull the
trigger of a loaded gun. That doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   On Mother's Day, these women will join a predicted 100,000
marchers in the nation's capital on a quest for ``sensible''
legislation to help ensure safer childhoods for their sons and
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of thousands of mothers also assembling in 20
other cities, including Atlanta and Austin, organizers believe this
``Million Mom March'' will be the largest rally ever for gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   Foreshocks are already being felt in the capital. Activists on
both sides of the gun issue are advertising heavily, including a
``Put Safe Kids First'' print and TV campaign by the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by marching moms, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., will
introduce legislation Tuesday to require that all future gun sales
be recorded and gun owners be licensed. On Friday, President
Clinton is scheduled to meet at the White House with mothers
seeking new gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Million Mom March has inspired a counter-demonstration
in the capital called the Armed Informed Mothers' March. Sponsored
by Second Amendment Sisters Inc., a self-described ``grassroots
self-defense and safety-education advocacy group'' based in Dallas,
this march is to highlight people whose lives have been saved by
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said the keynote speaker will be Texas state Rep.
Suzanna Gratia-Hupp. She was a patron in a Kileen, Texas, cafeteria
in 1991 when a man killed 21 people in a shooting spree. The
victims included Gratia-Hupp's parents. Had she been armed, she has
said, she could have stopped the killer.
</P>
<P>
   At the Million Moms March on Sunday, TV talk show host Rosie
O'Donnell will emcee a rally on the National Mall between the
Capitol and Washington Monument. Rosanne Cash and Patty Smyth will
sing. Speakers will include Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose
husband was killed in a 1993 shooting on the Long Island Rail Road,
and several mothers whose children were killed in gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started in my family room and has grown to a mantra
across the nation,'' said Donna Dees-Thomases, the New Jersey mom
who conceived the march. ``There is nothing more powerful than a
mother's drive to protect her children.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months since Dees-Thomases asked the National Park
Service for a permit to stage a march on May 14, the mothers'
crusade has gathered force in PTAs and play groups and car pools
and neighborhoods across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers received a $300,000 grant from the Funders'
Collective for Gun Violence Prevention and are selling T-shirts for
$25 to help raise the $1.6 million needed to finance the event. The
group's Internet site attracts about 50,000 hits a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is purely a grassroots movement,'' said David Bernstein
of Handgun Control Inc., a Washington advocacy group that supports
the march. ``It was started by mothers who are sick and tired of
gun violence in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband saw it on the Web,'' said Michelle Boeckman of
Austin. Since then, the Washington march has turned into a Boeckman
family gathering. Jim and Michelle Boeckman and their 3-year-old
daughter, Taylor, are coming from Texas. Jim Boeckman's parents are
coming from Missouri, and two brothers and their pregnant wives
will also be there, along with Taylor's 3-year-old cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make a statement,'' Michelle Boeckman said in
explaining the trip. ``It's crazy that we have so many guns out
there. ... Guns aren't the most important things in the country.
People are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about it, I knew that I had to get involved,''
said Appel, who lives outside Atlanta in eastern Cobb County and
described herself as a ``mom at home with three children.'' In
addition to Molly, there's Rebecca, 7, and Michael, 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really concerned for my children's safety,'' she said.
Recalling how children roamed safely and freely in her childhood
neighborhood, she lamented the ``locked environment'' that is now
necessary for children to grow up safely.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the march came last August as Dees-Thomases was
watching TV in her family vacation house on Fire Island, N.Y. Her
husband was away on business and her daughters, Lili, 6, and
Phoebe, 4, were asleep. A part-time publicist for CBS-TV's ``The
Late Show with David Letterman,'' Dees-Thomases was channel-surfing
in search of her boss when she happened onto a news show about the
shooting at a Jewish community center in California.
</P>
<P>
   Her own children attend such a center, so the issue of gun
control suddenly grew personal. The following week, she jotted down
the words ``Million Mom March,'' registered a Web site and filed
for a parade permit for Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   But this organizer was considerably better connected than the
typical suburban mom. A former journalist, Dees-Thomases was the
publicist for Dan Rather and the CBS Evening News from 1987 to
1993. Her husband, Jeffrey Thomases, is the brother of Susan
Thomases, a close friend of first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The march got a national publicity boost when O'Donnell agreed
to emcee the Washington rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``These 'Million Moms' are an inspiration. And as a mother, this
is a personal issue,'' O'Donnell explained. ``The gun-control issue
is of vital interest to me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Marchers stressed their mainstream views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the right to bear arms and in the Constitution,''
said Erickson, who said she has many friends who hunt and have
taught gun responsibility to their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also know some people who shoot squirrels with assault
guns. That's not really hunting,'' she said. ``I think we can have
some rules (controlling guns) that make it safer for children.''
</P>
<P>
   The gun control issue suddenly became personal for Hartman Levy
several years ago when she and her husband, Jeff Levy, were robbed
while coming home from a dinner party in the Atlanta neighborhood
of Ansley Park. ``I had a gun put to my face,'' she recalled. Her
husband was ``beaten up.'' She described the assailants as two
armed ``young kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, people asked if she hadn't wished that she had been
armed, Hartman Levy said. ``I believe that if I had had a gun, I
would be dead. It would have escalated until I was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband and 4-year-old son will be marching in Atlanta on
Sunday, while the trip to Washington is her Mother's Day present.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take a stand as a family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.millionmommarch.com, www.sas-aim.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
