<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9088 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      05-08 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   North and South Meet
</P>
<P>
   North is north, and south is south, and never the twain shall
meet. That (with apologies to Rudyard Kipling) has been the general
thinking about species isolation in Arctic and Antarctic waters. A
cold-water-loving species in the north is separated from the same
species in the south by thousands of miles of warmer ocean, and
thus might be expected to evolve differently.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study by scientists in Britain has shown that for
several plankton species, at least, that is not the case. Studying
three types of foraminifera, single-celled organisms that make up
much of the world's plankton, the scientists have discovered that
northern and southern specimens of the same species display some
identical genetic variation.
</P>
<P>
   This, the researchers write in Nature, is evidence that the
creatures somehow stay in touch enough to allow for genetic mixing.
</P>
<P>
   Different species of forams, as the organisms are known, show a
distinct preference for warm- or cold-water zones. These zones were
essentially established 8 million to 16 million years ago, so the
cold-water species in north and south should have had plenty of
time to develop genetic differences. But the researchers, studying
ribosomal DNA, found the same DNA sequences in both Arctic and
Antarctic populations of the same species.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how this mixing might occur is unclear. But the
researchers suggest that because the forams would be unlikely to
survive transit across warmer surface waters, the organisms might
be being submerged to deeper, cooler levels for their travels
through the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino's Effects
</P>
<P>
   Even a warm-water organism can run into trouble sometimes, if
the water gets too hot. That's apparently what happened off Belize
during the El Nino winter of 1997-98. The dominant coral species in
the central lagoon of Belize was almost completely destroyed as
water temperatures reached 90 degrees, the highest sea surface
temperature ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   When corals are stressed by high temperatures or other
environmental conditions, they expel the symbiotic algae that are
the source of most of their food. If the algae do not return, the
corals can die. The phenomenon is known as coral bleaching because
the loss of the photosynthesizing algae makes the corals appear
white.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Dauphin Island Sea Lab in Alabama studied the
destruction in Belize caused by the heat, which has been attributed
both to El Nino and global warming. Until now, the researchers
wrote in Nature, coral reefs in the Caribbean that had been
bleached eventually recovered. The Belize case, they say, is the
first in which coral mortality has passed the point of no return.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also took core samples from the reef and
determined that nothing like the bleaching had occurred in Belize's
lagoonal reefs in at least 3,000 years. Their results, they say,
show that concerns about the impact of climate change on reef
ecosystems is justified.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky Survival Technique
</P>
<P>
   Birds do it, bees do it. The larvae of blister beetles don't do
it, but, being parasites, they are glad that others do
(particularly the bees).
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at San Francisco State University have discovered a
remarkable way in which blister beetle larvae get into the nests of
bees, allowing them to survive in harsh desert conditions like
those in the Mojave in California. The larvae, known as
triungulins, clump together into a mass that makes a male bee
swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the researchers report in Nature, a male bee
mistakes a clump of triungulins for a female bee (using both visual
and olfactory cues), and tries to mate with it. The triungulins
respond by latching onto the male. Then, when the male eventually
finds and mates with a real female, the triungulins are transferred
to the female, who carries them to the nest. There they grow fat
and happy, living on pollen provided by the bees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
