<HEADER>
A9089 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      05-08 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Minn., N.C., Miss., Ohio)   (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAUSE AND EFFECT: When Anger Sets Off Heart Attacks
</P>
<P>
   An outburst of anger sometimes prompts the plaintive response,
``Don't have a heart attack!'' There may be something to that
advice, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   A study that looked at almost 13,000 people over six years found
that those who were most prone to anger were about 2.5 times as
likely to have heart attacks or sudden cardiac deaths as their
calmer counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who experience frequent and intense anger may benefit
by learning to identify triggers of their anger,'' said the lead
author of the study, Dr. Janice Williams, who was an epidemiologist
at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill when the
research was done.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers followed the medical histories of people who
appeared free of heart disease in four communities: Washington
County, Md., suburban Minneapolis, Forsyth County, N.C., and
Jackson, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The subjects, chosen randomly, were given a 10-item
questionnaire known as the Speilberger Trait Anger Scale, which
assigns a score of 1 to 40, depending on the level of anger a
person reports. The average was 16, and about 8 percent were rated
as having high levels of anger (most were younger, less educated
men who were more likely to drink and smoke).
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the study, 256 people in the group had heart
attacks. Those who were the most prone to anger were 2.69 times as
likely to have them as those with the lowest scores. Those with
moderate scores were 35 percent more likely to have heart attacks
than those with the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the increased risk did not hold true for people
with high blood pressure, who were already at higher risk. The
researchers are not sure why this is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perplexing,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION: Americans Still Pass Up the Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables and fruit still have not caught on with the public,
despite the health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than one-fourth of Americans eat the five daily servings
of fruit and vegetables recommended by federal health officials and
the National Cancer Institute, a survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   The report, published in a recent issue of The American Journal
of Public Health, found that some progress had been made in the
period studied, 1990 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year, only 19 percent of Americans reported eating
five servings a day; in the last, 22.7 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   But most of that improvement, the researchers said, took place
place before 1994, and a leveling off has since occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted in 16 states, involved telephone calls to
up to 32,000 people a year. They were asked six questions,
including how often they drank juice or ate fruit. They were also
asked how often they ate potatoes (French fries and potato chips
did not count).
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed were also asked about exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The highest proportion of people who met the dietary
recommendations were men and women 65 and older, whites, college
graduates and people who exercised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although progress from 1990 to 1994 was encouraging,'' the
report said, the survey suggested that further efforts were needed,
especially among inactive and obese people.
</P>
<P>
   REACTIONS: A Good Word for the Maligned Oxidant
</P>
<P>
   The much-reviled oxidant, also known as the free radical, has a
new defender.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical, which occurs naturally in the body, has long been
linked to cancer and other illnesses. And antioxidants, including
those found in high concentrations in fruits like the pomegranate,
have been assumed to be of potential value.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by researchers at Ohio State University finds that
when it comes to heart disease, at least, the oxidant has had a bum
rap. Dr. Pascal Goldschmidt, director of the university's heart and
lung institute, says oxidants actually appear to play a vital
repair role in repairing blood-vessel damage that can lead to heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   When wounds occur in the walls of blood vessels _ as happens,
for example, when cholesterol builds up _ endothelial cells nearby
produce more oxidants than their counterparts do elsewhere in the
body, Dr. Leni Moldovan and Goldschmidt reported in a recent issue
of the journal Circulation Research.
</P>
<P>
   Although the free radicals do kill healthy cells, the
researchers said, they appear to be necessary if new endothelial
cells are to come in and fill the hole caused by the wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can look at oxidants as not just being the bad guys, but
sometimes playing a positive role,'' Goldschmidt said. A goal,
researchers said, should be to develop drugs that stop the damage
the oxidants cause, but let them do their repairs.
</P>
<P>
   STANDARDS: On Pressure Scale, Heeding the Top Line
</P>
<P>
   For years, it has seemed almost axiomatic: to know if someone
has high blood pressure, just look at the figure for their
diastolic pressure (the ``80,'' for example, in 120/80.) The upper,
or systolic, figure, was practically ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, federal health officials said last week, is that
this belief, common among many doctors, is wrong _ dangerously so,
in many cases. Systolic blood pressure, health officials said, is a
reliable general sign of hypertension and as people get to middle
age and beyond, it is the best reliable indicator.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health have issued a formal clinical
advisory to doctors suggesting that they focus on systolic pressure
in older adults. And it plans to conduct a broad public education
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the health institutes issued guidelines recommending
that both systolic and diastolic blood pressure be used to diagnose
hypertension in patients of all ages. But since then, federal
officials said, studies have shown that the key figure for patients
who are middle-aged or older is the systolic figure.
</P>
<P>
   Significant evidence of the value of systolic pressure, for
example, came from recent results in the Framingham Heart Study,
which has followed the health of thousands of people in the Boston
area for 50 years. Still, Dr. Daniel Levy, director of the
Framingham study, said in an interview that there had been no one
finding that changed medical thinking about how to diagnose high
blood pressure, but rather a growing body of evidence that in the
end seemed incontrovertible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Systolic hypertension is a major health threat, especially for
older Americans,'' Dr. Claude Lenfant, director of the National
Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, said in announcing the clinical
advisory.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines recommend that blood pressure for people of
all ages be kept below 140/90 (130/85 for hypertensives with
diabetes, and as low as possible for people with heart of kidney
failure).
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK: Painful Colon Disease Is Linked to Stress
</P>
<P>
   Ulcerative colitis, a serious disease in which the lining of the
colon and rectum become inflamed causing severe pain, appears to be
worsened by long-term stress, a new study has found.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have long theorized that stress can play a role in the
disease, but have never been able to prove it, said the
researchers, writing in the May issue of The American Journal of
Gastroenterology.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, they said, was that past research looked at
short-term stress, with the expectation that a flare-up would be
seen within a month of two. Instead, the researchers concluded,
after examining 62 patients in Italy for six years, it is
longer-term stress, measuring as long as two years, that seems to
play a role.
</P>
<P>
   They emphasized, though, that stress was only one factor and
that no one really could explain the course of the chronic disease,
which goes in and out of remission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
