<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yellow Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Q. I see yellow tomatoes, among other exotic types, at vegetable
stores. Do they differ in nutritional value from red tomatoes?
</P>
<P>
   A. Like all vegetables, tomatoes differ somewhat in nutritional
value from variety to variety, and even from season to season; for
example, the U.S. Department of Agriculture lists different average
nutrient contents for tomatoes harvested from November to May and
for those from June to October.
</P>
<P>
   Many food values are comparable for red and yellow tomatoes, or
are a tradeoff. For example, the amino acids are found in similar
smidgens. The precursor of vitamin A called beta carotene is found
in valuable amounts in red and yellow tomatoes and in many other
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Both colors have vitamin C, though a red tomato has about three
times as much. Minerals are similar, though a yellow tomato is
higher in sodium. Yellow tomatoes have more niacin and folate, red
tomatoes have more vitamin B6 and pantothenic acid, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one significant nutrient, reported in some studies
to be a powerful antioxidant that may help prevent cancer, that is
found in red tomatoes but not in others: lycopene. Lycopene, which
is also converted in the body to vitamin A, is the very thing that
makes red tomatoes red. The redder the tomato, the more lycopene,
and no lycopene at all is to be found in green or yellow tomatoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9093 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DOCTOR-TRAINING-N     05-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCTOR-TRAINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEMISE OF REFLECTIVE DOCTORING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By DAVID A. SHAYWITZ, M.D. and DENNIS A. AUSIELLO, M.D.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals, the hospitals responsible for the education
of tomorrow's physicians, are now engaged in a struggle for
survival. Their unprecedented fiscal strain stems both from the
reluctance of HMOs and insurance companies to contribute
financially to clinical training and from recent reductions in
federal support.
</P>
<P>
   These new pressures have created a frenetic environment that
challenges patients and makes it difficult to turn out innovative
doctors who will question accepted doctrine, seek new knowledge and
establish higher standards of care for the next generation of
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the responsibility to train doctors seemed a
natural extension of a teaching hospital's basic commitment to
providing patients with quality care. For patients, the obligation
to be examined by a succession of physicians _ an experience
neither efficient nor universally appreciated _ generally was
offset by the reassurance from such a thorough evaluation, and the
promise of collective wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   For doctors in training, the process brought close connections
with patients and a more sophisticated understanding of the
underlying diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of such reflective doctors on medical progress would
be difficult to overstate. The discovery that stomach ulcers can be
caused by bacterial infection, the use of steroids to treat
rheumatoid arthritis, the identification of Lyme disease, all are
important medical advances that resulted from doctors' efforts to
understand the problems of their own patients.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the focus of clinical training has
changed drastically, as efficiency has become increasingly
important. In some ways, this new emphasis has served patients
well. Doctors are more rigorously guided by scientific evidence and
flow-charts articulating the best ways to manage common diseases.
</P>
<P>
   This growing awareness of a standard of care means that
physicians are more likely to apply successful strategies quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But our daily experience suggests that in the current
preoccupation with speed, something vital to medical education has
been lost. The damage to the new generation of doctors can be seen
perhaps most visibly in the much-publicized atrophy of their
essential skills: the ability to perform a basic physical exam, for
example, as several recent studies have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Young doctors also find they have little time with patients. The
deeply personal relationships they had long anticipated seem to
have devolved into brief, emotionally detached encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, what may turn out to be the most significant casualty of
the modern training experience is also the least obvious: the
gradual disappearance of time to think, in an expansive fashion,
about an individual patient. Traditionally, such reflective
thinking has been a hallmark of teaching hospitals. It was why
doctors came to train and why patients came for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs and insurance companies tend to focus on the bottom line
and have placed intense financial pressure on teaching hospitals
and their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, even the most insightful and compassionate
academic doctors feel increasingly compelled to evaluate and treat
patients with reflexive speed.
</P>
<P>
   This matters because medicine is more than simply the
compassionate (and now, efficient) application of received wisdom;
it is also the challenging of old customs, and the development of
new insights. It is critical to recognize that an academic
clinician is both a provider, whose goal is to assimilate and then
thoughtfully apply a given set of information, and a medical
scientist who questions traditional dogma.
</P>
<P>
   This creativity crunch has appeared just as medicine sits poised
to benefit from major advances in molecular biology and computer
technology. Desperately required now are more ``clinical
champions,'' passionate physicians who have the expertise,
imagination and perseverance necessary to ensure that this
scientific progress finds expression in the care and treatment of
patients.
</P>
<P>
   We must encourage doctors in training to ask fresh, penetrating
questions, to wonder about underlying biological mechanisms, to
consider alternative therapeutic approaches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
