<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     05-08 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: THE PILL AT 40: NEW USES FOR A DRUG THAT CHANGED
SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty years ago Tuesday, the Food and Drug Administration
approved a medication that set off a medical and social revolution.
The medication was an oral contraceptive called Enovid, introduced
in 1960 by Searle to a nation of women increasingly eager for
greater certainty in preventing unwanted pregnancies. Though few
realized it then, ``the Pill,'' as it came to be called, has turned
out to have a number of ancillary health benefits as well as some
serious side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The pill was developed by Dr. Gregory Pincus and Dr. John Rock.
Rock, then a devout Roman Catholic, had hoped in vain that his
church would accept it as a ``natural'' means of birth control,
although many Catholic women adopted it despite papal
proscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The pill arrived at a time when abortion was illegal everywhere
in the United States and when growing numbers of young women were
striving to liberate themselves from the social trappings of
premarital chastity and vocational suppression.
</P>
<P>
   It took just five years for the pill to become the leading
reversible contraceptive method in the United States. Since its
introduction, an estimated 468 million American women have taken
the pill. Today more than 16 million American women are on the
pill, making it the most popular contraceptive technique outside of
sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   By blocking ovulation, the synthetic hormones in the birth
control pill, when taken properly, proved to be better than 99
percent effective in preventing pregnancy. Only surgical
sterilization could match that, and sterilization is not an option
for women who may want to have children one day.
</P>
<P>
   Diaphragms and condoms, which had to be used at the time of
intercourse, took their toll on spontaneity and romance and did not
offer enough contraceptive security for women seeking to complete
their educations and establish careers before starting families.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the pill gave women a highly effective
reversible method of contraception that was completely divorced
from the sex act.
</P>
<P>
   But also for the first time, millions of young, healthy women
were taking a potent drug every day, raising legitimate concerns
about drug-induced health risks of potentially epidemic
proportions. All drugs, including those sold over the counter, have
side effects. And, as predicted, serious, even fatal, complications
did occur among users of oral contraceptives, especially among
women who smoked or were over 35 and those who used the early
high-dose pills.
</P>
<P>
   These problems prompted a host of warnings and stimulated
research that resulted in safer products containing far smaller
hormone doses, less than one-hundredth the amount of estrogen in
the original pill.
</P>
<P>
   All the oral contraceptives work by suppressing the pituitary
hormones that prompt the ovaries to release eggs ripe for
fertilization. Most products contain synthetic versions of both
estrogen and progesterone. The so-called minipills contain just
synthetic progesterone (progestin). Although the minipill is
slightly less effective than the combination pills, it can be used
by women, like those who are breast-feeding, who cannot take
estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   In both versions, the hormones are taken daily for 21 days,
usually starting from the first day of a woman's menstrual cycle,
then stopped to allow the built-up tissue lining the uterus to be
shed as menstruation.
</P>
<P>
   Women can now choose from among 59 different products, all
variations on the original theme. The types of synthetic estrogen
and progestin, the dosages and the design of dispensing packets
vary, and some products include seven dummy pills in addition to
the 21 active ones to help women remember to take a pill each day.
In 1984 Ortho Pharmaceuticals was the first to introduce a
triphasic version of the pill, which provides three different
hormone levels in the course of the month, more closely mimicking a
woman's natural hormone cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The pill in its current formulations is a remarkably safe drug,
and the overwhelming majority of women who take it experience
neither minor side effects like breakthrough bleeding or serious
health damage. Still, the pill today is sold with an insert
mandated by the FDA and filled with more facts, figures and
warnings than most women would want to know but should know if they
wish to avoid becoming a statistic.
</P>
<P>
   Blood clots, which can result in heart attacks, strokes,
thrombophlebitis, pulmonary embolism or vision-impairing eye
damage, are the most common serious side effect and are most likely
to occur in women who smoke and in older women. A smoker in her
middle to late 20s is seven times as likely to die as a nonsmoker
from pill-related clots, and the older the woman, the more smoking
increases her risk if she also takes the pill. Women who have
already had a clot-related disorder are advised not to take the
pill.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, women over 40 were told to avoid the pill
because of clot-associated risks. Then, in 1989 an advisory
committee of the FDA noted that if a woman over 40 was healthy and
did not smoke, the pill's benefits probably outweighed possible
risks, assuming she used the lowest-dose pill that was effective.
</P>
<P>
   But women who have had cancers of the breast, lining of the
uterus (endometrium), cervix or vagina are advised not to take the
pill, since it is possible that the hormones it contains could
stimulate the growth of such cancers.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s and mid-'70s, two cancer scares temporarily
curbed enthusiasm for the pill, but neither scare turned out to
have relevance to women using pills then on the market. While there
is at present no clear evidence that the pill increases a woman's
risk of developing breast cancer, women taking the pill who have
strong family histories of breast cancer or those who have had
breast nodules or abnormal mammograms should be monitored closely
by a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Every user of the pill should be told that it does not protect
against any sexually transmitted disease, including infection by
HIV. When there is a risk of such an illness, a condom should also
be used in every sexual encounter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to avoiding the risks associated with an ill-timed
or unwanted pregnancy, the pill has proved to have a number of
other benefits. For women whose menstrual cycles are irregular, the
pill provides predictability. For those who bleed heavily, it
reduces menstrual flow and consequently the risk of becoming
anemic. Menstrual cramps and other menstrual symptoms tend to be
lessened by the pill and, by minimizing menstrual flow, the pill
also diminishes the risk of developing endometriosis and can
sometimes reverse this disorder as well.
</P>
<P>
   The hormones in the pill cause a thickening of the cervical
mucus, providing something of a barrier to infectious organisms. As
a result, women on the pill have a reduced risk of developing
pelvic inflammatory disease, which can damage the tubes and cause
infertility.
</P>
<P>
   The pill also provides some protection against cancers of the
endometrium and ovaries. Taking the pill for as little as a year or
two significantly diminishes a woman's risk of developing ovarian
cancer. Noncancerous breast cysts are less frequent among pill
takers. And one product, Ortho Tri-Cyclen, has received FDA
approval to treat moderate cystic acne in women 15 or older who
desire contraception and who have not been helped by topical acne
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Although the pill blocks the monthly release of eggs, it does
not delay menopause. As Dr. Sharon Winer, an
obstetrician-gynecologist and reproductive endocrinologist at the
University of Southern California explained, ``A woman's eggs get
old and die off even if they are not released, so menopause occurs
on schedule.'' But the pill is increasingly being recommended for
women approaching menopause whose own estrogen levels are dropping
but who still face a risk of becoming pregnant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
