<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9101 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-NASA-ART-2NDTAKE-     05-08 0222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NASA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LAUREL, Md.: he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spear agreed with some of the criticism, saying that people who
took short cuts or ``dumb risks'' under the guise of ``faster,
better, cheaper'' were not properly following the concept. ``There
has to be some flexibility and the ability to adjust goals if
things don't go as planned,'' he said, ``If you are working under a
fixed cost and schedule, for instance, you have to be able to
change the scope of the mission, perhaps leaving an experiment or
something off to compensate.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the meeting said that even without formal
policies to cut costs, there was pressure worldwide to find ways
drive down the price of space exploration. The European Space
Agency (ESA), a consortium of 15 countries, is planning to dispatch
a mission called Mars Express that would orbit the planet's poles
in 2003 and send down a small lander to examine soil composition.
</P>
<P>
   While ESA has never adopted the `faster, better, cheaper''
mantra, there has considerable pressure to cut mission costs in
recent years, said Gordon P. Whitcomb of the European consortium.
In a new approach, the Mars mission will use technology developed
for previous projects and turn over much of the project management
to contractors working under the supervision of a reduced ESA
project team.
</P>
</TEXT>
