<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9103 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ULTRASOUND-ART-NY     05-08 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ULTRASOUND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCES, AND ANGST, IN A NEW ERA OF ULTRASOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RANDI HUTTER EPSTEIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, obstetricians listened for the reassuring
sound of a fetal heartbeat and felt a woman's abdomen to monitor
fetal growth and position. It was, in essence, educated guesswork,
trying to visualize the unborn baby without ever really seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, obstetricians started to see it all. New
kinds of ultrasound machines revolutionized prenatal monitoring.
For the first time, physicians, mothers, and fathers could look at
the fetus' beating heart and squiggling hands and feet. Expectant
parents left the doctor's office with goodie bags, envelopes filled
with early baby photos.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, ultrasound has grown up. Rather than simply
glancing at the fetus, doctors today take a series of measurements:
the length of the fetus; the length of the thigh bone; and the
circumferences of the head and abdomen. They check the four
chambers of the heart and the structures of the kidney and bladder.
</P>
<P>
   And now ultrasound is on the verge of yet another revolution.
The latest gadgets, though far from standard use, create
three-dimensional images of the fetus and may be used to peer deep
within the fetal brain, identifying fine points of the developing
anatomy never seen before. Another type of ultrasound, Doppler, is
being used to monitor blood flow of fetal organs, helping doctors
check not just structure, but function of organs.
</P>
<P>
   And yet another new ultrasound technique, one that measures the
fluid in a fetus' neck, is now being studied. Many experts think
it, when combined with analyses of blood tests and maternal age,
might eventually reduce number of screenings by amniocentesis and
chorionic villus sampling, two definitive yet slightly risky
procedures, in detecting birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``With any new technology there are growing pains, but once we
overcome them we will see that the uses of ultrasound will grow
exponentially,'' said Dr. John Hobbins, director of obstetrics at
the University of Colorado Health Science Center in Denver. ``Soon
we will be using ultrasound to assess normality, not just identify
abnormalities. These new technologies are allowing us to see the
whole deal _ what the baby looks like, how it is behaving, and how
the organs are functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   But as ultrasound has grown up and come to rival amniocentesis,
it is raising new questions about how much information expectant
parents really want, and whether all those using ultrasound really
know what the new images mean.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest findings is a bright spot on the heart that
has been tied to an increased risk of Down syndrome, Hobbins said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that ``if you use a high-frequency transducer,
with a little imagination you can find a bright spot in every fetal
heart,'' Hobbins said. ``So what do you tell a patient? I tell
patients that I've seen a bright spot and we are not sure what it
means, though some studies have shown an association to Down
syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   An article in January in The Journal of Ultrasound in Medicine
highlights the angst that the new technology can bring: ``From my
vantage point, the identification of these `abnormalities' in
low-risk women has crossed the line of `more harm than good,'''
wrote Dr. Roy Filly, professor of radiology at the University of
California at San Francisco School of Medicine. ``We put at least
10 percent of all pregnant women with perfectly normal fetuses
through a great deal of worry,'' he concluded in his essay,
``Obstetrical Sonography: The Best Way to Terrify a Pregnant
Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first trimester, the ultrasound scan is now typically
used to determine fetal age by measuring crown-rump (head to
bottom) length and head circumference. In the second trimester,
doctors measure abdominal circumference, and check the chambers of
the heart, the kidneys and bladder to spot defects and monitor
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Another standard measurement is femur, or thigh bone, length.
Between 17 and 19 weeks of gestation, an abnormally short femur may
suggest Down syndrome, said Dr. Lawrence Platt, chairman of
obstetrics and gynecology at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But ultrasound is already moving beyond such measurements. One,
now being tested in two trials in the United States, is performed
between the 10th and 13th weeks of pregnancy and, when combined
with blood tests and assessment of the mother's age, is aimed at
determining a woman's odds of having a baby with Down syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The new technique measures a fluid-filled area behind the neck,
known as nuchal translucency. Fetuses with birth defects often have
extra fluid in this area between the 10th and 14th weeks of
gestation, said Dr. Kypros Nicolaides, a professor of fetal
medicine at Kings College Hospital in London, who developed the new
method.
</P>
<P>
   The blood test measures two hormones: beta-HCG (the same
substance measured in pregnancy tests) and PAPP-A, or
pregnancy-associated placental protein. For still unknown reasons,
abnormally high levels of HCG and low levels of PAPP-A in the first
trimester have been linked to Down syndrome. Already a British
study of 120,000 women found the method was 85 percent accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Such tests are still quite different from diagnostic tests like
amniocentesis and chorionic villus sampling (CVS) _ in which a
sample of fetal cells is examined with a microscope and offer
definitive answers. But roughly one woman in every 200 to 300
miscarries after amniocentesis. The risk is slightly higher for
CVS.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Leyden, a 38-year-old mother of two from Philadelphia, for
one, was determined to avoid amniocentesis in her second pregnancy.
In her first pregnancy, a blood test falsely suggested a birth
defect so her doctors recommended amniocentesis, which found the
fetus to be normal. This time she elected to participate in one of
the trials evaluating the new first-trimester ultrasound test. She
knew the test would not yield conclusive information but hedged her
bets that the results would be more accurate than the blood test
she had had before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The procedure was painless,'' Leyden said, referring to the
ultrasound. ``It was wonderful to see the baby at 14 weeks. I knew
there were no definitive answers, but every indication showed the
baby was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyden said her own mother feels fortunate she gave birth in the
days before the information explosion because, she told her
daughter, ``it's driving you girls crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if studies prove the first-trimester ultrasound test is
effective, many women may still decide to go right to amniocentesis
or CVS. ``It's an individual and personal decision that patients
will have to decide for themselves,'' said Dr. Michael Mennuti,
chairman of obstetrics and gynecology at the University of
Pennsylvania Health System in Philadelphia. ``For some women the
anxiety of possibly getting a `high risk' result and then having
amniocentesis is not worth it. They would rather go directly for
the invasive, definitive test. For other women the reassuring
information of a screening test is good enough and they are happy
to avoid the definitive test because of the low risk of
miscarriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Socza, a 36-year-old television producer in Los Angeles,
was one who jumped at the chance to participate in the screening
trial. ``The last thing I wanted was amniocentesis. I didn't want
to be one of the statistics when the test didn't work out, plus a
needle going through your abdomen seemed so intrusive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the screening test, if it is proved effective,
may pinpoint young women at risk who would never have considered
amniocentesis. About 80 percent of Down syndrome babies are born to
women younger than 35. That is because even though the individual
risk is lower, the vast majority of babies, healthy and unhealthy,
are born to younger women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some women who are intimidated by the
choices and find it confusing,'' said Dr. Ronald Wapner, the
director of maternal fetal medicine and of reproductive genetics at
Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia, and a researcher in
one of the trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of women are very happy to have choices and take
control over their pregnancy,'' he said. ``They are difficult
decisions. But the most important thing to remember is that no
matter how a woman decides, most likely everything will be fine.
The odds are in her favor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
