<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MILKYWAY-COLLIDE-     05-08 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MILKYWAY-COLLIDE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD-ON COLLISION IN THE MAKING IS SEEN ON THE GALACTIC HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Mass., Calif.) (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphics
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within the constellation Andromeda is a dull, fuzzy patch of
light.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Great Andromeda galaxy, spiral in shape and similar
to Earth's own Milky Way galaxy, at 14 billion billion miles, the
farthest object one can see with the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   It is getting closer.
</P>
<P>
   Like the headlight of a distant, oncoming car, this little patch
of light will slowly brighten and sharpen over the eons. Andromeda
and the Milky Way are speeding toward each other at more than
250,000 mph. In 3 billion years, the two galaxies may slam together
head-on.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have known for decades that Andromeda is headed this
way, though they still cannot say whether the two are destined to
collide or merely to speed past, narrowly missing each other.
</P>
<P>
   But, if their paths are to cross, computer simulations now
provide a preview of that celestial crash.
</P>
<P>
   Using the latest, biggest, fastest computer at the San Diego
Supercomputer Center, Dr. Lars E. Hernquist, a professor of
astronomy at Harvard University, and Dr. John J. Dubinski, an
assistant professor of astronomy at the University of Toronto,
calculated the motions of 107 million particles representing the
contents of the two galaxies to obtain the most detailed look yet
at their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a collision where it's mostly head-on, but it's
slightly offset,'' Hernquist said.
</P>
<P>
   Given that outer space is mostly empty, individual stars would
very rarely, if ever, run into one another, the astronomers say,
and the hundreds of billions of stars in the two galaxies would
continue to burn, unaffected by the merger.
</P>
<P>
   But gravitational forces would radically shuffle around the
stars' locations.
</P>
<P>
   As the two initially graze past each other, the gravitational
forces pull off strands of stars into ``tidal tails,'' ripping
apart the galaxies' pinwheel shapes and casting tens of billions of
stars into the dark, intergalactic void.
</P>
<P>
   About two billion years later, the Andromeda and the Milky Way
merge into one larger, mangled blob.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't look like a spiral galaxy anymore,'' Hernquist
said.
</P>
<P>
   While supercomputers are needed for the details, the basic
physics of how tidal tails form is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of the phenomenon is almost kinematic,'' said Dr.
Alar Toomre, professor of applied mathematics at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``clumsy calculations'' he performed in the 1970s produced
tidal tails, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the gravitational pull of the Moon creates tides in
Earth's oceans, the pull of one galaxy on the other would lead to
bulges of stars on the near and the far sides of each galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Because the galaxy rotates, ``the far side gets swung and slung
into something that looks like a comma,'' Toomre said. ``This
comma, after a while, goes flying off into space,'' producing the
tail, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed simulations could help astronomers figure out
whether the football-shape elliptical galaxies they observe are the
result of spiral galaxies that have collided and combined. Some
elliptical galaxies have streams of stars orbiting around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might suggest perhaps these elliptical galaxies are a
more evolved version of what we're seeing at the end of the
simulation,'' Hernquist said.
</P>
<P>
   The simulations could also lead to better understandings of the
halos of ``dark matter'' that encircle the visible parts of the
galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone left on Earth three billion years from now, the night
sky would become almost totally black if the sun were one of the
stars cast out into the void.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have this dark sky with very few stars,'' Dubinski
said. ``Maybe none.''
</P>
<P>
   If the sun and Earth were pushed in the other direction, toward
the center of the merging pair, the view would brighten
considerably. When galaxies collide, hydrogen gas left over from
the formation of the galaxies is sometimes pushed toward the
center, sparking a new epoch of star-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you slam that much gas together, you can ignite these
starbursts,'' Dubinski said. With more stars, there would be more
supernovas, the explosive deaths of the largest stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are these celestial fireworks that will be going off for
tens of millions of years,'' Dubinski said. ``It would be much
brighter than a full Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   A supernova too close, however, could kill off any remaining
life on Earth, though the end of the world would be nearing in any
case. By the time the two galaxies complete their merger about five
billion years from now, the sun will have burned out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
