 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, May 9. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ At least four people
were killed Monday after shooting erupted in Sierra Leone's capital
as U.N. peacekeepers struggled to maintain control in the West
African nation. Witnesses said at least four people were killed
outside the rebel leader Faday Sankoh's house after his supporters
fired into a crowd of protesters who had marched on it to demand
peace. (Summary from wires.) By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-TRADE (Washington) _ After a bill-signing ceremony in the
Oval Office last month, President Clinton sidled up to an unlikely
ally in his fight to pass a decisive trade bill with China, the
administration's top foreign policy goal. ``We talked about what
each of us has to do and we gave each other some advice,'' said
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip and one of
Clinton's most vitriolic critics on Capitol Hill, who refused to
discuss the details of the conversation. With the crucial vote just
over two weeks away, DeLay, who led the charge to impeach Clinton,
now finds himself in the improbable role of the president's chief
water-carrier and potential legacy-builder in an all-out battle to
grant China permanent normal trading privileges. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ After the cross-border violence
late last week, Israel is speeding up its preparations to withdraw
troops from southern Lebanon in case Prime Minister Ehud Barak
decides to redeploy them before his self-imposed July 7 deadline.
Senior military officials believe that they will be pulling out
under fire, and several think that they may as well withdraw as
soon as possible and cut the losses they could sustain over the
next two months. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-RATES (Undated) _ For the first time, the nation's falling
murder rate, which had been centered in many big cities, is being
led by suburbs, small towns and rural areas. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR (New York) _ Cardinal John O'Connor's life was
celebrated at a funeral Mass on Monday marked by pageantry, prayer,
hope and an outpouring of love for the man who served the
archdiocese's 2.4 million Catholics for 16 years. A massive funeral
procession of 800, including priests, 120 bishops and 15 cardinals,
wound its way through the great bronze doors of St. Patrick's
Cathedral where an estimated 3,500 invited mourners gathered,
including President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
(Summary from wires.) By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   SF-FAT-BIAS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco is joining only two
other cities and the state of Michigan in outlawing discrmination
against people because of their personal appearance. Passage of the
legislation in San Francisco comes after a local health club ran
this ad: ``When the aliens come, they'll take the fat people
first.'' The campaign created a huge outcry among overweight
people, many of whom pressed for the law. Other cities with similar
ordinances include Santa Cruz, which is not a surrpise, and
Washington, D.C., which has had such a law on the books since the
1970s, and has, according to officials there, invoked it often in
job discrimination cases. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BUSH (Pittsburgh) _ Will they embrace as friends or
briskly shake hands as adversaries? Will the cameras record smiles
of warmth, or ice? Will the loser deliver some qualified pledge of
support for the winner, offer more lavish words of praise or
perhaps utter something close to the e-word? If politics is often
about appearances, the eagerly anticipated meeting here on Tuesday
between Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona is being scrutinized as closely by the political and media
elites as Egyptologists might pore over the Rosetta Stone. In their
first face-to-face encounter since Bush trounced McCain in the
primaries on Super Tuesday, March 7, the governor and senator are
getting together at Bush's invitation for private fence-mending,
public picture-taking and the expectation in the Bush camp that
McCain would eventually make some kind of formal endorsement. By
Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AD-AGENCY-MERGER (London) _ Young &AMP; Rubicam, one of the last
major independent advertising agencies on Madison Avenue, agreed
Monday to be acquired by its London-based rival, WPP Group, for
$5.7 billion in the largest deal in advertising industry history.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND (San Francisco) _ Today it is music, but
tomorrow the legal battle over copying information and sharing it
via the Internet is virtually certain to shift to video and
software. While the rock group Metallica is pursuing an Internet
service that it says is facilitating illegal copying of the band's
recordings, the software for reproducing and disseminating
information is evolving rapidly. As a result, a more dramatic
confrontation may be looming over the ability to copy any kind of
digital information _ music, video, software or documents _ freely
and almost instantly, to any location on the globe. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila, Philippines) _ Authorities on Monday
named a man and a woman, apparently both bank employees, as
suspects in the unleashing of a malicious computer program that has
disabled computer systems around the world. They took the man into
custody and demanded the surrender of the woman. The two suspects
live in an apartment where authorities said they had found a
computer, owned by the woman, that they identified as the source of
the infectious program, apparently by tracing a telephone line. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JEWS-DIASPORA (Undated) _ With a new technique based on the
male or Y chromosome, biologists have traced the diaspora of Jewish
populations from the dispersals that began in 586 B.C. to the
modern communities of Europe and the Middle East. The analysis
provides genetic witness that these communities have, to a
remarkable extent, retained their biological identity separate from
their host populations, evidence of relatively little intermarriage
or conversion into Judaism over the centuries. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-AUCTION (Undated) _ On April 28, a California man who uses
the handle ``golfpoorly'' put a half dozen items up for sale on
eBay, the online auction company. Along with an unopened roll of
twine, a never inflated basketball, a Mexican voodoo mask, a
Netgear network card and a pewter frame, he offered a ``great big
wild abstract painting'' that he said was bought years ago at a
garage sale in Berkeley and has a small hole inflicted by a son
wielding a bicycle. He asked for bids to open at a quarter. On
Monday bids for that painting, which may be a 1952 work by Richard
Diebenkorn, were up to $135,605. If the sale, which ends Monday
night, goes through, and if the painting is genuine, it would be
not only a stunning and serendipitous investment for ``golfpoorly''
but also probably the second-highest price paid online for a work
of art. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   TONY-NOMINEES (New York) _ A struggling new musical, ``The Wild
Party,'' received seven nominations, including one for best
musical; a mother and daughter were pitted against each other in a
leading-actress category; and two actors who alternate roles in
``True West'' wound up as competitors when the Tony Award
nominations were announced Monday. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
