<HEADER>
A9134 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l BC-FAIRCHILD-COLOR-THERA     05-08 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-COLOR-THERAPY-BUSINESS-SUBSTITUTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE COLORS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RACHEL MARLOWE  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Late last year, every wrist in Los Angeles, New York and London
seemed to be sporting at least one colorful powerbead bracelet, if
not an armful.
</P>
<P>
   Pink, rumored to attract love, was the most popular, followed
closely by green (for money) and orange (for joy). The wearers must
have been getting results, because the hottest accessory to have on
your arm right now is your very own color therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Color therapy is based on the theory that colors bring about
emotional reactions and can correct energy imbalances. Aleta St.
James, an ``emotional healer'' and ``success coach,'' has used the
practice for 27 years to heal emotional blocks and balance the
body's seven chakras. Patients include designer Todd Oldham and
model Carolyn Murphy, who says, ``Aleta helped me become a better
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I use my intuition with my patients to find out where the
trauma is,'' St. James explains. ``If, for example, it's in the
heart, I put my hands there. I shoot the healing color into them _
in this case green for acceptance and love _ like a laser beam out
of my hands, eyes and heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan E. Moses, an L.A.-based naturopath and self-styled
``minister of health'' takes a slightly different approach, using
color in conjunction with Chinese medicine to balance the body's
yin and yang and ``restore personal power.''
</P>
<P>
   To determine which parts of the color spectrum his patients need
more (or less) of, he asks them to say their name while looking at
five different colors _ yellow, red, green, blue and gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever color they show a loss of energy in front of is their
deficient color,'' he says. ``It's usually their favorite, and
that's why _ because they need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood screenwriter Rick Krause is a convert to Moses'
technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I have excessive heat,'' Krause says. ``That means I
have too much red and I have to stay away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   After his consultation with Moses, Krause went out and bought a
new blue carpet and a blue bedspread.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm wearing a blue sweater right now,'' he says. ``What
he's done has worked for me. I get more done, I function on a
higher level and it's doubled my energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Color therapy may seem like a New Age fad, but in fact it's one
of the oldest practices around, dating back to Ancient Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not an exact science. Different cultures have
different traditions, and there's plenty of room for
interpretation. Seeing red might anger a bull, for example, but it
increases egg laying in chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Westerners believe blue to be an appetite suppressant, while
Chinese medicine prescribes blue for weight gain. Green may be the
traditional color of envy, but feng shui recommends wearing green
underwear to secure a raise at work.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such contradictions, it's an area that has become
red-hot in the beauty and alternative healing industries. Of
course, adding a new dimension to the use of color is a no-brainer
for cosmetics companies, who have been quick to explore the new
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Philosophy started early with its Rainbow Kit, a color therapy
bubble bath launched four years ago. According to creator Christina
Carlino, sales are at a higher level now than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like feng shui, color therapy is becoming very popular because
people are starting to think in terms of energy,'' says Christina
Bornstein (aka Tina) of Tony &AMP; Tina, which has based its makeup
line on the vibrational therapy of color and is currently
researching a book on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands are great places to receive and transmit energy, so nail
polish is a good way to wear color.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony &AMP; Tina nail polishes are named after the vibes they
supposedly emit: clarification (yellow), courage (deep red), solace
(pink).
</P>
<P>
   Even the usually sensible Elizabeth Arden has joined the party,
prescribing plum lipstick for passion and neutral for serenity.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're brave enough to self-administer a dose of color
healing, you can try Color Therapy from Rainbow Inc., which has
everything from rose-tinted spectacles for a bit of Tibetan color
visualization to color music CDs featuring compositions based on
the harmonic relationship between color and notes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, medical studies have begun to show a
scientific basis for color therapies. The American Journal of
Psychology found that using red and green light to treat depression
reduced symptoms by 20 percent after two hours, and a 1997 study by
The Biology of the Neonate journal reported that three hours of
blue-light phototherapy eliminated jaundice in five out of 10
babies studied (the other five experienced moderate relief with
green-light phototherapy).
</P>
<P>
   And in opthamology, color is a widely accepted method of
treatment. Optometrist Joseph Shapiro of Manhattan's Unlimited
Vision employs Syntonic therapy, a method developed in the 1930s by
Dr. Riley Spitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syntonic therapy is color therapy for visual imbalances _ such
as eye-muscle problems, lazy eyes and tunnel vision,'' Shapiro
explains, ``I cure my own migraines by thinking of a color in the
blue-violet range.''
</P>
<P>
   But doctors warn against making too many claims for color
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no controlled studies on the relationship
between color and healing,'' says Stephen Josephson, a clinical
psychologist who teaches at Cornell and Columbia. ``I accept that
pinks and reds stimulate the sympathetic nervous system, blue and
green are relaxing, and yellow can enhance concentration. I'm sure
that studies in the future will show that we're affected by
everything from humidity to the moon to light _ but as a field,
color therapy is unexplored territory.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing, however, is clear: Certain colors do make us feel
better. And that's enough to keep a lot of people thinking pink, or
yellow or green.
</P>
<P>
   ``If color gets us moving into a positive state of mind quickly,
then that's great,'' St. James says. ``Sometimes, you just don't
have time to meditate.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rachel Marlowe is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
