<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9148 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-KENNYROGERS-COMEBACK-     05-08 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNYROGERS-COMEBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS STILL BELIEVE IN KENNY ROGERS, WHO'S BACK ATOP COUNTRY CHARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listening to Kenny Rogers is like eating your mom's meatloaf. He
is country music's comfort food: You know what you're going to get
every time, and you know you're going to like it.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the most adventurous meal you've ever had, but it
will fill the tummy and maybe even trigger a childhood/better days
flashback or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't surprise you,'' says Neil Pond, editor of Country
Weekly. ``He's exactly who you think he is. He does what he does
well. I think that line in ``The Gambler'' is really true _ he does
know when to hold 'em and when to fold 'em, and right now he's
holding two big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hits _ the hugely popular ``Buy Me a Rose'' and, before
that, ``The Greatest,'' both from his latest CD, ``She Rides Wild
Horses'' _ have meant a career resurgence of major proportions for
the 61-year-old Houston native who, between 1977 and 1981, was
perhaps the world's most popular male singer.
</P>
<P>
   Long pegged as a musician whose most successful days were behind
him, Rogers has roared back into the mainstream country fray.
Currently at No. 2 on the country singles chart, ``Rose'' is
Rogers' first Top 10 single since ``The Vows Go Unbroken'' hit No.
8 in late 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses'' has sold more than 500,000 copies and peaked at No. 6
on the Billboard country charts; it's currently at No. 11, which
means it's outselling Alan Jackson, Kenny Chesney, LeAnn Rimes and
Reba McEntire.
</P>
<P>
   Penned by Don Schlitz, the man who wrote ``The Gambler,'' ``The
Greatest'' tells the story of a little boy in love with baseball
and the simple joy in believing in himself. It's a cute, sweet
song, one that has received airplay in some ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Rose,'' the CD's second single, has garnered more
interest. The message is pure romantic sentimentality: A wife is
frustrated by her hardworking husband forgetting to do the little
things: buying her a rose, calling from work, opening the door for
her. At the end, the narrative shifts from third to first person
and Rogers, with backing vocals from Alison Krauss and Billy Dean,
promises to do better. ``I'm gonna make things right for the rest
of your life,'' he sings, to the collective sighs of women across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really touched a nerve _ it's made people stop and
listen,'' says Linda O'Brian, music director of KSCS/96.3 FM in
Dallas-Fort Worth. ``You get a lot of men dedicating it to their
wives. They'll say, `She's at home with my two little kids and I
was just thinking of her.' It just nails 'em. It's a very sweet
song, especially if you've been married awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's WSIX/97.9 FM, like KSCS, has ``Rose'' in heavy
rotation, which means both stations played it about 40 times last
week. O'Brian and WSIX program director Mike Moore agree that the
song is requested by younger, as well as older, people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear stories from listeners,'' Moore says. ``We get calls
from wives who say, `I wish my husband would talk that way' and
calls from husbands who say, `You know, maybe I don't do enough of
the little things for my wife.' We have heard people say it's
helped them reassess their marriages and why they got together in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   With covers of Sarah McLachlan's ``I Will Remember You'' and ``I
Can't Make You Love Me'' (a hit for Bonnie Raitt several years
ago), ``Horses'' definitely has its eye on giving Rogers more of a
contemporary sheen.
</P>
<P>
   But it's done so well precisely because it sounds so much like
old Kenny Rogers: the mellow voice and tempo, bed of acoustic
guitar, solid pop hooks and hopeful messages of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This caught a lot of people by surprise,'' says Smokey Rivers,
assistant program director for KPLX/99.5 FM in Dallas-Fort Worth.
``The guy has a track record and he just pops up once in a while,
hits one out of the park. This is a pop song but if you think back
to the '80s, with songs by Anne Murray and others, we haven't had a
lot of those recently, those real nice ballads.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this way, Rogers' age actually helps him: From his cover
of ``Ruby, Don't Take Your Love to Town'' to ``Islands in the
Stream'' to ``The Gambler,'' his songs were never told from a cocky
kid's point of view. Which means, Pond says, that people feel like
he's an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel like they've grown up with him,'' Pond says. ``He
sings about grown-up topics, and because he's not new and hip and
edgy, he appeals to a settled, more mature crowd, people over 40
who have been bounced around a bit. There's a quality to his fame
and his voice that suggest he's been around the block in love and
life.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's definitely true. Rogers grew up poor in a housing
project, and by age 25 had been married three times. (In 1997, he
married wife No. 5, Wanda, an Atlanta waitress almost exactly half
his age whom he had met in the early '90s.)
</P>
<P>
   He worked with a variety of groups and first found fame in 1968
as part of the First Edition with ``Just Dropped In (To See What
Condition My Condition Was In).'' There would be several more hits
before his 1977 career-making hit ``Lucille,'' which was followed
closely by ``Daytime Friends,'' ``Sweet Music Man,'' ``Love or
Something Like It,'' ``She Believes in Me,'' ``The Gambler,''
``Coward of the County,'' ``Don't Fall in Love With a Dreamer,''
``Love the World Away'' and ``Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1981, Rogers was the most popular artist in country, a
successful TV actor with the CBS movie ``The Gambler,'' a regular
multiple-category winner at the American Music Awards, and very
rich.
</P>
<P>
   The hits never really dried up altogether, but Rogers settled
into a comfortable middle-of-the-road type of stardom, lending his
name to a chain of chicken restaurants, doing TV specials and
movies, touring and releasing several books of photography.
</P>
<P>
   There were also few odd moments along the way. These include
three high-profile liposuction surgeries and, more troubling, the
1992-'93 sex-line scandal: Three women accused Rogers of coaxing
them into high jinks on a private 800 number.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers never denied the conversations, saying at the time that
he was simply disappointed that private conversations between
consenting adults had become public, and the women's case was
tossed.
</P>
<P>
   He recently told London's Daily Telegraph that at the time, he
was going through ``a serious midlife crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had this cloud of guilt over me from that day forward,
and I hate it. ... It was stupid,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But Moore says that many people in the country community think
Rogers handled the sex-line incident well in that he 'fessed up to
some of the allegations and admitted he shouldn't have done what he
did.
</P>
<P>
   And neither this _ nor the well-publicized liposuction
surgeries, nor the cheesiness of the TV movies _ has hurt him with
the fans. If anything, his trials and tribulations and occasional
missteps have made him seem more human, more real.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sentimental, and he's been very public about his weight
and his sex life _ he went on TV and said he did it, and America
got over it very quickly,'' Moore says. ``There's a candor to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also see him singing into his old age, like Frank
Sinatra. Right now, everything's coming together for him. His
career path and his age seem to have led him to this place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839 or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
