<SLUG> BC-HOMER-SLUGFEST-BASEBALL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOH! ANOTHER RECORD YEAR FOR `BACK-BACK-BACK-BACK!'S  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``s'' sports news
files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hits just keep on coming. Baseball is in the
middle of a festival of firepower, a home-run heat wave, and it
shows no sign of ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off on a record pace again for dingers, dongs and
back-back-back backs,'' wrote Sports Illustrated's Leight
Montville. ``The ball is juiced, the strike zone is about the size
of a sheet of Xerox paper, the fences in the new parks are as close
as the kitchen telephone. Everyone is hitting home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 season, when Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa punched their
way through the long-standing record of 62 runs in a season,
galvanized the country. But the totals keep climbing.
</P>
<P>
   There were 931 home runs in April, a record for the month and
nearly 200 more than last April. There were 980 last May, the most
ever in one month, but there is still plenty of the season left,
and the balls keep flying into the bright summer skies.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport that is almost a branch of numerology, the shift has
been catalogued in minute detail. There were 5,528 HRs last year,
an average of 2.3 per game; this year that average is running at
2.6 per game.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1968, there was an average of 1.38 homers per game. The
records keep falling: last month, 57 homers were shot in one day.
</P>
<P>
   All of this ought to bring joy, one would have thought; there
are few finer things than hearing the bat make contact and then
tracing the ball's arc on its way into the stands, watching the
fans scramble for it.
</P>
<P>
   But the home-run bonanza has longtime fans uneasy, and the
commentators are worried. Baseball (like cricket) is not, to the
cognescenti, a matter of smacking the ball around the park: it is a
game of subtlety, tension, strategy and timing.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball commissioner, Bud Selig, has been publicly sanguine
about the change, which is reshaping the game before his very eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just see how this plays out,'' he said last month. ``Of
course we have concerns,'' he told the Associated Press. ``We
always have concerns. But at this stage we're just sitting back and
monitoring.''
</P>
<P>
   He has hired two scientists to look at the balls, but that seems
unlikely to yield anything much.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't entirely clear why the runs are stacking up, though
some guesses can be hazarded. The ball parks are getting smaller as
more intimate, old-style stadiums come back into fashion. Then
again, some people believe that the wood used in manufacturing the
bats could make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The increased number of teams with expansion may be a factor _
some wonder if there are enough talented pitchers to go around, in
effect _ but it seems more likely that the reasons lie at the other
end of the ball's arc.
</P>
<P>
   The hitters have gotten stronger and better, and that isn't just
evolution. In some cases, the use of dietary supplements and other
chemicals has helped: McGwire admitted to taking androstenedione,
though he later stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strikes me as non-cyclical is that hitters have an
incentive to bulk up _ more weight-training and dietary supplements
_ and there's not a corresponding advantage available to
pitchers,'' said Steve Hirdt of Elias Sports Bureau. ``It doesn't
help them to get much bigger and they can't be throwing
year-round.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been one concrete result from the hitfest, though,
which is clearly negative and a cause for concern. As the balls
come hurtling back, pitchers are getting hit _ some have suffered
broken bones _ and they are getting frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a nasty series of violent incidents as
pitchers have thrown beamers straight at hitters and, on occasion,
punches have been thrown, culminating in a series of brawls between
the Detroit Tigers and the Chicago White Sox last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good time for pitchers, there's no doubt,'' the
Dodgers' Kevin Brown said. ``There are a lot of ways to get hurt
out there, the way the ball's flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that the game's top tier are winding up the runs to
bring back the fans. If that is true, it is not working. The sport
has not benefited from the batting bonanza in terms of bums on
seats: indeed fan attendance has never recovered from the 1994
labor problems which killed that year's World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices have pushed up, so the bank accounts are looking
comfortable in any case.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, as with military technology, things usually
shift between the defensive and the offensive. Just as barbed wire
and machine guns could stop massed infantry, so tanks later
outflanked the static style of warfare that was dominant during the
First World War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the pitcher's mound was reduced and it may be that the
sport's hierarchy decides the advantage has shifted too far. Until
then, the records will tumble. &QL; 
