<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SPLIT-UP MEANS MACRO EXPENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Do you think if the Justice Department gets its
way and breaks up Microsoft into separate companies, we'll have
another fiasco like when they broke up Ma Bell? Remember when you
could call one number for service and get help? Now you don't know
who or where to call for your telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   _ All Broken Up
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ALL: It's an unsettling picture all right: Bill Gates
giving you a call just as you sit down to dinner, trying to
convince you to switch operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else the government touches, you can be certain
the Microsoft decision will make life more confusing and expensive.
The latest scheme would break Microsoft into competing companies,
one selling Windows and another selling applications programs, such
as Word or Excel. Great. It's hard enough getting all that stuff to
work together now. I can't wait until the software engineers stop
talking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I just got an old computer from work, a Dell
486/66. I am going to give it to my sister to use as a word
processor. The problem is that it's password-protected. Please help
us, Doc. You never know. My sister might go nuts and want me to buy
her a real computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sister's Keeper
</P>
<P>
   DEAR KEEPER: What do I tell you people about never throwing away
the manuals? Nobody ever pays attention.
</P>
<P>
   Power-on passwords are generally a dumb idea, not because you'll
inevitably forget the secret word, but because they're so easy to
defeat. You should go to support.dell.com for the specific
instructions for your model, but it'll likely be one of two
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   On some models, you can unplug the internal battery for a couple
of minutes, then hook everything back up. The chip that keeps track
of your system specs _ and the password _ will have lost its
memory. Did I mention you should run the setup program first so you
can record the settings? Whoops.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility involves removing a jumper from the
motherboard, firing up the computer, shutting it down, then
replacing the jumper. Please don't just go pulling jumpers at
random. Find the right one in your documentation or on the Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   And, this may seem a little too obvious, but did you ask whoever
had the computer before what the password is? I guess that makes
too much sense, unless you don't want anybody to know you took home
office equipment. Ohhhhh! I get it now. My lips are sealed.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I would like to know if you can set the
computer to turn on at a set time. I work the night shift and would
like to come home and have the machine up and running waiting for
me.
</P>
<P>
   _ No Time to Lose
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NO TIME: Well, I think that's just plain loony. Unless you
can have it make a martini at the same time, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Plug a power strip into one of those timers that don't fool
burglars while you're on vacation. Just make sure it can handle the
wattage. The lawyers made me say that in case your house burns
down.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I think your column is strictly to satisfy your
overrated ego.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disenchanted
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DIS: And it took you this long to figure that out? Say,
were you by any chance the one playing the banjo in
``Deliverance''?
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay's ego isn't overrated. He is. Write him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In the nonvirtual world, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems managerf for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
