<HEADLINE>
EVEN FOR DIE-HARD FAN, COULD AN ALL-HOCKEY TOUR BE TOO MUCH OF A
GOOD THING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, Horst Wallman and his family enjoy a traditional
sort of vacation _ sunning themselves on the shores of the
Mediterranean. But one week a year for the past eight, Horst, a
strapping insurance salesman with white-blond hair and an earring,
ventures across the Atlantic from his home in Germany. Here, he
travels by bus from city to North American city, from arena to
arena, gorging himself on professional hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Horst tells me this as we walk from our downtown hotel through a
chilling March mist to the Molson Centre, the cavernous new arena
that is home to the Montreal Canadiens of the National Hockey
League. Horst watches NHL hockey two nights a week in Germany via
satellite dish, he says. The three or four months a year without
hockey are bad for him, causing symptoms of withdrawal. That sort
of obsession is why he comes each year to North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends think I'm crazy,'' Horst says, smiling proudly in
the rain.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't. I know there is a subspecies of humans for whom
hockey is embedded deep in the DNA, because, I, too, am one of
them. So are the nine others who have joined Horst and me on a
strange, weeklong odyssey across eastern Canada and the
Northeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   We will travel by plush tour bus, sometimes for six hours at a
stretch, from the Canadian capital of Ottawa to Montreal, from
Montreal south across the U.S. border to Boston, Boston to New
Jersey via New York City, then back to Montreal. A few hours of
sightseeing will be built into each day. In Boston, for instance, I
will stumble across the grave of Paul Revere. In each city, our
hotels are the finest, the sort of places where bellboys wear caps
and uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   But a great hockey buffet is our purpose, our reward. Each
night, we have splendid seats for a total of five NHL games
involving eight different teams. Each of us has paid about $1,500
(not including airfare) to a Canadian tour group for the privilege.
For me, this trip is work; an editor made me do it. As much as I
love hockey, spending this kind of money for so much hockey seemed
a little excessive.
</P>
<P>
   But something tells me that Horst thinks it's a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE: OTTAWA: A steady drizzle falls the day I land in Ottawa
and though the snow is gone, it is Canadian cold. The route
downtown from the airport traces the Rideau Canal, upon which
locals ice skate to work in the winter. I wonder if they bring
pucks and practice stick-handling along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Our hotel is the Chateau Laurier, an old, castlelike edifice
where the Canadian prime minister lived in the 1930s. With a few
hours until our tour group is to meet, I borrow an umbrella from
the hotel concierge and walk over a bridge and up a hill to the
Parliament building of Canada, a magnificent, century-old edifice.
I pass a huge statue of Queen Elizabeth II on horseback, doubting,
somehow, that Her Majesty still rides. The gothic Peace Tower of
the Parliament building rises majestically into the afternoon murk.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pleasing whiff of nostalgia about all this. I grew up
playing hockey in a small town in northern Minnesota, closer to
Canada than almost anyplace else. I once knew more about Prime
Minister Pierre Trudeau than I did about President Jimmy Carter.
Bob and Doug McKenzie, the beer-swilling hosers from television's
``The Great White North,'' were friends of mine. (Well, not really,
but I went to college with plenty of Canadians just like them.) But
after moving to Texas in 1982, Canada seemed on another continent,
and now I am very happy to be back.
</P>
<P>
   Our tour group convenes in the lobby of our hotel a short time
later. We have been brought together by Roadtrips, a Winnipeg,
Manitoba, tour company. Roadtrips was the brainchild of a man named
David Guenther, who led spring break tours while still in college.
That led to golf weekends, then hockey tours. In business since
1992, Roadtrips is the leader in hockey adventures like ours. But
with the explosion in this kind of travel _ at least half-a-dozen
companies specialize in sports-oriented trips _ the company now
offers trips built around everything from the World Series to
NASCAR races.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa, I expect to meet fat cats with nothing better to do
with their time and money, but as far as I can tell, no member of
our group is rich. Instead the group includes a young couple from
Denver, season ticket holders to games of the Colorado Avalanche;
two brothers and a sister from a small town in Minnesota; a young
woman who is an accountant in upstate New York; a retired mechanic
in the Canadian Air Force from Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Gwen Goryl and her husband, Walt. Gwen grew up in
England, where she played field hockey, taking considerable delight
in whacking her opponents across the ankles with her stick.
Naturally, then, she took passionately to ice hockey when she moved
to the United States in 1961. She settled in New England,
surrounded by fans of the Boston Bruins, so Gwen adopted the
Philadelphia Flyers, just to be contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when we meet, Gwen, a tiny, fiery woman with short blond
hair, is wearing an oversized Flyers jersey. Gwen tells me that she
and her husband, a mild-mannered ex-policeman, joined our hockey
tour from their retirement home near Orlando, Fla., where Gwen
watches several hockey games on television each week. Walt says he
knows better than to disturb his wife while she watches hockey.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
