<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND     05-08 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL BATTLE OVER COPYING ON THE WEB SURE TO MOVE BEYOND MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today it is music, but tomorrow the legal battle over copying
information and sharing it via the Internet is virtually certain to
shift to video and software.
</P>
<P>
   While the rock group Metallica is pursuing an Internet service
that it says is facilitating illegal copying of the band's
recordings, the software for reproducing and disseminating
information is evolving rapidly. As a result, a more dramatic
confrontation may be looming over the ability to copy any kind of
digital information _ music, video, software or documents _ freely
and almost instantly, to any location on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America and two musical
acts have sued a Silicon Valley software developer, Napster Inc.,
in an effort to stop computer users from illegally posting and
copying songs over the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other, more powerful software programs are
being created and distributed that will make it far more difficult,
and perhaps impossible, to stop the worldwide sharing of programs,
files or recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The groups and companies pursuing the new technologies _
programs that in effect create vast digital libraries spread across
potentially hundreds of thousands of large and small computers _
range from iMesh, an Israeli start-up company that aspires to
become an international commercial digital distribution system, to
a small group of free software developers intent on building a
global network of computers impervious to censorship.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of these programmers say they have deliberately
set themselves on a collision course with the world's intellectual
property laws and express the hope that the outcome of the clash
over digital copyrights will be a world in which all information is
freely shared. In any case, the new programs have the potential to
change the basic terms of the discussion about intellectual
property.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Clarke, a 23-year-old Irish programmer, is finishing a
program called Freenet that is intended to make it possible to
share any kind of information anonymously while rendering it
virtually impossible to remove the information from the Internet
once it is placed there.
</P>
<P>
   The first version of Freenet was posted on the World Wide Web in
March. Clarke, who lives in London and is employed as a programmer
by a small electronic commerce firm, said last week in a telephone
interview that there had been more than 15,000 downloads of the
early versions of his product, indicating that hundreds or perhaps
thousands of network servers on the World Wide Web were already
running the program.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is confident that corporations trying to develop
complex technologies to encrypt information or otherwise halt the
free sharing of computer data will ultimately fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two words for these companies: Give up,'' he said.
``There is no way they are going to stop these technologies. They
are trying to plug holes in a dam that is about to burst.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude, plus the fact that millions of users have come to
rely on easy access to digital information via the Internet,
suggests that the issue may quickly outstrip the current debate
over copyright infringement between the recording industry
association and a variety of Internet music distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no shortage of gray hairs from worrying about these
programs,'' said Talal Shamoon, a Silicon Valley executive who
heads the Secure Digital Music Initiative, a technology and
entertainment industry working group.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts believe that the intellectual property laws
are being used in an effort to grapple with technologies they were
never intended to address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copyright law is not the right tool in the case of many of the
new technologies,'' said Pamela Samuelson, a digital technology and
copyright expert at the School of Law at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``The question will quickly become whether
other governments have reasons to try to regulate these new systems
or whether the U.S. government has the ability to regulate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, law enforcement officials are only beginning to wrestle
with the implications of new technologies that will permit the
anonymous, instant, global distribution of information of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously looking at all of these,'' said Christopher
Painter, deputy chief of the Justice Department's computer crime
and intellectual property section. ``It makes our job more
difficult and makes it harder to find the people who are
perpetrating crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Freenet, which Clarke conceived while he was an undergraduate at
the University of Edinburgh, is intended to function without any
centralized control point. ``Freenet is a near-perfect anarchy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet digital distribution program, Gnutella, created
by software developers at America Online's Nullsoft subsidiary, has
the same distribution approach employed by Freenet, meaning there
is no central directory of what information the system contains.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Napster, which is limited to digital music files,
Gnutella makes it possible to distribute video, software and text
documents as well.
</P>
<P>
   America Online declared Gnutella an ``unauthorized freelance
project'' in March, just hours after it was made available on the
Internet. But since it was developed under an ``open source''
programming approach, independent programmers have continued to
refine Gnutella even though the project was officially canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer industry executives contend that if the recording
industry's suit against Napster succeeds, it will simply lead
digital music enthusiasts to use alternatives, like Gnutella and
Freenet, which are even less open to copyright enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``So are all the musicians and record companies going to
continue their suits against Napster?'' a Gnutella user who
identified himself as Panicst8 wrote in a recent network posting.
``It seems kind of pointless or have they just not figured out yet
that Gnutella is about 10,000 times more effective at locating what
you want?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Freenet goes several steps beyond Gnutella in an effort to
protect the anonymity of those who publish or copy information
electronically. It encrypts the piece of data and scrambles the key
to its location within the system. That means not even the
operators of individual servers know whether something is on their
disks. And Freenet incorporates a digital ``immune system'' that
responds to any effort to determine the location of a piece of
information by spreading the information to other nodes of the
network.
</P>
<P>
   Freenet relies on a system of volunteers who run the program on
network computers, or servers, Clarke said, and it will even be
difficult for the operators of individual servers, or ``nodes,'' to
determine which computer holds any particular file.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Freenet will move information over the Internet in
such a way that the most popular data is also the most widely
distributed. In the future, he said, if a piece of information that
is popular in one country, like Britain, becomes popular in another
country, like the United States, the information will be relocated
to use the Internet more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this whole thing catches on, I think that people will look
back in 20 to 40 years and look at the idea that you can own
information in the same way as gold or real estate in the same way
we look at witch burning today,'' Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
   For technologists like Shamoon, systems like Freenet present a
challenge, but not an insurmountable one. In addition to his
industry role with the Secure Digital Music Initiative, Shamoon is
senior vice president for media at the InterTrust Technologies
Corp., a Silicon Valley company that builds systems for protecting
intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   He cites the possibility of the transmission of viruses and
other harmful programs as being one of the obvious risks inherent
in communities where no basis for trust exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a trust standpoint, the current generation of tools such
as Gnutella and Freenet is a nightmare for the same reason that
badly constructed social communities are a nightmare,'' Shamoon
said. The recording industry will survive, he argues, if it is able
to offer its users new things of value.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of dangers here,'' he said. ``But as a
society, we're very adept at adapting to compensate for these
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
