<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-HOCKEYODYSSEY-2ndTake     05-08 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEYODYSSEY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: watches hockey. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We pile onto our tour bus and arrive at the arena to watch the
Ottawa Senators and Philadelphia Flyers warm up. At first,
Philadelphia clearly dominates, peppering shots at the Ottawa
goaltender, Tom Barrasso, who flops around on the ice like a walrus
at Sea World. But Philadelphia leads by only one goal as the game
enters the final period. Then the Flyers' goalie, an aging fellow
named John Vanbiesbrouck, allows an easy game-tying goal. The
Flyers eventually lose, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the bus after the game, I notice Gwen staring out the
window, her face pinched into a tight frown. I am tempted to hurl
some gentle ribbing in her direction, but she anticipates me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't even start,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DAY TWO: MONTREAL: At times over the week, we watch movies
(''The Waterboy,'' ``The Mummy'') to pass time on the road. But
mostly we sleep, or look out the windows, or talk hockey. I mean
really talk hockey, down to the ridiculous minutia common to, say,
fantasy baseball league owners. This is how Jeff Wills and I occupy
most of the two-hour bus ride from Ottawa to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff is the tour guide for Roadtrips. He is a smart, happy young
guy who left his small hometown in northern Ontario to get a
business degree. But his years as a hockey player and die-hard
hockey fan are probably more important credentials for his current
job.
</P>
<P>
   As we discuss the NHL playoffs, bus driver Brian Beaucamp calls
out over his shoulder, ``Get out your passports, we're leaving the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Brian was only kidding. We were merely crossing the
provincial boundary from Ontario into Quebec. Quebec only wishes it
were a separate country, a country where the people would speak
only French. For generations, Quebecers have fought the pollution
of their culture by English-speakers. I think this a bit quaint,
tantamount to Cajuns wanting to secede from Louisiana. But in
Quebec, blood has been spilled over the issue. As we near Montreal,
I strain to recall my two years of high school French 25 years ago.
I remember how to count to 10, and say, ``merci beaucoup.'' I doubt
that will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   But at our hotel, when the bellboy says ``Bonjour,'' I say
``Bonjour'' in reply, feeling quite cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   After check-in, our group walks a few blocks to the Molson
Centre, where a pert guide named Denise gives us a tour of the
arena in heavily-accented English. This is sacred ground for a
hockey fan, because the Montreal Canadiens are this country's
equivalent of the New York Yankees, winners of 24 Stanley Cups.
Denise leads us to the team's Hall of Fame, a hushed, dimly lit
place that contains the busts of legends like Bernie ``Boom Boom''
Geofrion; Maurice ``The Rocket'' Richard; Jacques Plante and Jean
Beliveau, names that would mean nothing to the average Texan. But
these are hockey's Ruths, its Gehrigs, its DiMaggios.
</P>
<P>
   I am stirred to be reminded how integral hockey is to the
Northern culture, a ritual passed down over many generations. In
Texas, by comparison, despite the success of the Stars, hockey
still seems like a novelty, entertainment a notch or two above pro
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   With a few hours to kill, I walk the bustling, rain-slickened
streets of downtown Montreal. All the women look like Celine Dion,
who was born here. All the men look like Celine's middle-aged
husband, Rene Angelil. This is a city of great cathedrals and Old
World charm, but also of the boutiques, bookstores and strip joints
that crowd each other along St. Catherines Avenue. I turn from St.
Catherines onto Crescent Street, pass the Hard Rock Cafe, and step
into a Russian restaurant that offers wild boar, which I had never
eaten. (I have now. It tastes like roast beef.)
</P>
<P>
   The Molson Centre is packed for the game between the Canadiens
and Boston Bruins. I have a spectacular seat, center ice about 10
rows up. Three young men sit next to me during the game, jabbering
in French and getting very drunk. In front of us sits a row of
brave supporters of the Bruins, dressed in the jackets and jerseys
of the opposition. Among them is a middle-aged man with a
salt-and-pepper pompadour and a nasty overbite.
</P>
<P>
   After each goal by the Canadiens, one of the drunk guys next to
me ruthlessly taunts the Boston fan, screaming in French and
putting his fingers to his mouth, imitating walrus tusks.
</P>
<P>
   This is terribly bad form, I think. Yet I'm happy when the
Canadiens score in the last minute to win the game. Thousands of
French-speaking men and women pour happily from the arena into a
frigid night, just as they have here for a century, and walking
with them, I feel a part of something old, something substantial.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DAY THREE: BOSTON: Somewhere in upstate New York, Jeff Wills
tells me about a man and woman who met during last year's East
Coast NHL tour. One thing led to another. When they returned to
their respective homes in Canada, they tried a long-distance
romance, but it ended after a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found out hockey was all they had in common,'' Jeff says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else is there?'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   We pass Fenway Park and unload at our hotel in the Back Bay
section of Boston, a city I've never seen. I'm told the arena is a
long walk across downtown, so I set out down Boylston Street,
passing the enormous Boston Public Library and churches dating to
Colonial times. The late afternoon is bright and warm, and several
young people toss a Frisbee on Boston Common, a massive green-space
reminiscent of New York's Central Park. On the other side of the
Common, tucked into the shadows of several brownstone buildings, is
a tiny cemetery. Tablet-sized gravestones tilt precariously in the
Old Granary Burial Ground, as if a strong wind would blow them over
altogether. Much of the writing on the headstones has eroded in the
330 years since the first person was buried here, but I manage to
find Paul Revere's resting place, and the graves of Ben Franklin's
parents. The body of John Hancock is here, too, buried near four
victims of the Boston Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
