<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9155 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-HOCKEYODYSSEY-3rdTake     05-08 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEYODYSSEY-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: the Boston Massacre. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston is like that, a history lesson on every corner, and I
begin to resent the approach of tonight's hockey game, which
intrudes on my time for sightseeing. I stand beneath the balcony of
the Old State House, where the Declaration of Independence was
first read, and pass the Old South Meeting House where Benjamin
Franklin was baptized.
</P>
<P>
   At the arena, I burn up a roll of film taking ice-level
photographs of the St. Louis Blues warming up, hoping to prove to
my son that I am not making this up. The Blues defeat the Bruins in
a close game. As I file out of the arena, I realize an NHL game
every night in an interesting new city is beginning to seem normal.
On my long hike back to the hotel, the dome of the Massachusetts
State House blazes over the darkened Boston Common. Later, I learn
the dome was cast by Paul Revere.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DAY FOUR: NEW YORK/NEW JERSEY: Our bus motors past Yankee
Stadium, then churns down Second Avenue through the bustling
streets of Harlem, then to Mid-town. As we step out in front of
Madison Square Garden, Walt Goryl goes to find a hot dog from a
sidewalk vendor, for this seems the thing to do in New York. The
faces of the Heglund siblings from Minnesota betray a mixture of
incredulity and terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people and tall buildings make me dizzy,'' says Leslie
Heglund, a legal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Our now-weary group shuffles along a guided,
behind-the-scenes-tour of Madison Square Garden, and the Heglunds
snap some photos when the Empire State Building appears through a
window. I find the Garden tour unspectacular. For me, the highlight
is a size-18 basketball shoe left in a locker room by one of the
New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's back on the bus, through the Lincoln Tunnel to a
barren expanse of New Jersey _ tonight's destination. The arena of
the New Jersey Devils is located here, for some reason, and as we
drive to the game, we see the lights of Manhattan teasing us to the
East. I wish I was in Times Square, not in another arena, which,
unlike baseball parks, all look more or less the same on the
inside. The Devils trounce the Atlanta Thrashers as we watch. Maybe
my mother was right. There can be too much of a good thing. Even
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DAY FIVE: MONTREAL: The most satisfying moments of the trip come
on the last day. In the afternoon, after we cross the St. Lawrence
River back into Montreal, I stroll around Old Montreal, its narrow
streets and spectacularly old buildings. I step inside the Notre
Dame Basilica, the massive, neo-gothic church where hundreds of
votive candles flicker, where the wall behind the altar is
illuminated a brilliant blue, where stained-glass windows depict
moments of Montreal's religious history dating to the 1600s. I
eavesdrop on a tour leader, who says Celine Dion was married here.
</P>
<P>
   At the Molson Centre, a plump lady sings the American national
anthem, then ``O Canada,'' before the Canadiens game with the
Buffalo Sabres. The Canadiens must win this game to make the
playoffs, and the buildup has continued in the newspapers and bars
all week. As the respective anthems are finished, I think I have
never heard a hockey venue as loud as this one. All the ghosts of
Montreal's hockey past seem to be lurking.
</P>
<P>
   But another legend plays tonight for the Sabres. He is Dominik
Hasek, the goaltender called the Dominator, who rejects one
Canadiens shot after another. When Buffalo scores to take the lead,
a stout older man who has been up and down in his seat the entire
game says something to me in French. I dig deep into my memories of
high school language class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Je ne parle pas francais, monsieur,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   So he speaks to me in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want the Canadiens to win?'' he asks me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I need to leave and go to the bar,'' he says. ``Every
time I sit here, the Canadiens lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He shuffles past me and storms out of the arena.
</P>
<P>
   But Hasek is impenetrable, and the Canadiens lose anyway. The
crowd shuffles into the cold Canadian night, quietly, as if after a
funeral. I share their dour mood, but for a different reason. Their
team won't make the playoffs, but my hockey buffet is over, and I
have plenty of room for dessert. I'm with Horst. At $1,500, this
trip was a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Madigan is a writer for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call him at (817) 390-7544, or e-mail:
tmadigan(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
