<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-NOMINEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY NOMINATIONS MIRROR A SMALL WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Photos showing scenes from several of the nominated plays
are available for download from either the Wieck Photo Database in
Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A struggling new musical, ``The Wild Party,''
received seven nominations, including one for best musical; a
mother and daughter were pitted against each other in a
leading-actress category; and two actors who alternate roles in
``True West'' wound up competitors when the Tony Award nominations
were announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days ago, ``The Wild Party,'' which opened last month to
mixed reviews after a version by the Manhattan Theater Club ended
its run, was selling at just 50 percent capacity. Some people
expected it to close if it was not nominated for best musical. But
its seven nominations, only one less than for the acclaimed revival
of ``The Music Man,'' have given it a new lease on life, at least
until the awards are announced on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really fabulous,'' said George Wolfe, the director and
a co-producer of ``The Wild Party,'' who wrote the musical with
Michael John LaChiusa. ``It's the Broadway community embracing new
work.''
</P>
<P>
   LaChiusa, who also wrote ``Marie Christine,'' had a big day
Monday, with both of his shows drawing nominations for best book
for a musical and best original score, although neither has been a
hit. ``Marie Christine'' closed in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me Kate'' led the nominations, announced at Sardi's
restaurant, with 12 nods in categories from best musical revival to
best orchestration.
</P>
<P>
   The Tony nominations pointed up the increasingly gray area of
what constitutes a new musical these days, given that the three
shows nominated with ``Wild Party'' in the best musical category
defy conventional definitions. They are ``Contact,'' a dance play
performed to recorded music whose eligibility has prompted protest
from the musicians union, Local 802; ``James Joyce's `The Dead,'''
a play with parlor songs that recently closed; and ``Swing!,'' a
dance show. ``Aida,'' a more traditional musical, was not nominated
for best musical, although it received five other nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The races that promise to be particularly close are for best
play, best revival of a musical and best performance by a leading
actor in a play. In the best play category, the acclaimed
production of Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen'' will compete with
``Dirty Blonde'' by Claudia Shear; Sam Shepard's ``True West,''
which successfully lobbied for consideration as a new play although
it was previously produced off Broadway in 1980 and 1982; and ``The
Ride Down Mount Morgan'' by Arthur Miller, which recently earned
attention when its star, Patrick Stewart, complained from the stage
about what he considered inadequate promotion by its producers, the
Shubert Organization. Stewart was not nominated.
</P>
<P>
   The race for musical revival has heated up since ``The Music
Man'' opened on April 27, creating head-to-head competition with
``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which opened in the fall. The two musicals are
also vying for awards for best performance by a leading actor in a
musical (Brian Stokes Mitchell for ``Kiss Me, Kate'' and Craig
Bierko for ``The Music Man'') and for best performance by a leading
actress in a musical (Rebecca Luker for ``The Music Man'' versus
Marin Mazzie for ``Kiss Me, Kate'').
</P>
<P>
   The competition for best actor is complicated by the nominations
of both Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly for their
performances in ``True West,'' despite efforts by the play's
producers to have the actors, who alternate roles every three
performances, considered jointly as one candidate. The two actors
are up against Gabriel Byrne for ``A Moon for the Misbegotten;''
Stephen Dillane for ``The Real Thing''; and David Suchet for
``Amadeus,'' all of whom received strong reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's nominations for the Tony Awards, which are presented by
the American Theater Wing and the League of American Theaters and
Producers, found some shows competing against themselves. For best
performance by a featured actress in a musical, for example, Laura
Benanti and Ann Hampton Callaway were nominated from ``Swing!,''
and Deborah Yates and Karen Ziemba were nominated from ``Contact.''
Also in that category was Eartha Kitt, nominated for ``The Wild
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kevin Chamberlain and Bob Stillman of ``Dirty
Blonde'' are competing against each other for best performance by a
featured actor in a play.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stroman will be competing against herself for best
direction of a musical and for best choreography, having been
nominated in both categories for both ``Contact'' and ``The Music
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The director Michael Blakemore also received two nominations,
though in different categories, one for ``Kiss Me, Kate'' and one
for ``Copenhagen.'' The last time this happened was 10 years ago,
also to Blakemore, although he won for neither his direction of the
musical ``City of Angels'' nor of the play ``Lettice and Lovage.''
</P>
<P>
   For best actress in a play, Rosemary Harris, nominated for
``Waiting in the Wings,'' is competing with her daughter, Jennifer
Ehle, nominated for ``The Real Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two musicals that have closed each received five nominations:
``James Joyce's `The Dead''' and ``Marie Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John was nominated for the ``Aida'' score and the show
received three other nominations (for its star, Heather Headley,
and for Bob Crowley for its scenery and for Natasha Katz for
lighting ). Julie Taymor's ``The Green Bird'' received only two
nominations, one for best costumes (Constance Hoffman) and one for
best performance by a featured actor in a play (Derek Smith).
</P>
<P>
   The first hour of design and creative awards will be broadcast
on PBS on June 4 at 8 p.m. The remaining two hours will be
broadcast on CBS from Radio City Music Hall with Rosie O'Donnell as
host.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
