<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-NYTSF     05-08 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: MUST-HAVE TRAVEL GUIDES FOR SPRING 2000  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE! -----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The Internet has spawned dozens of travel sites, but that hasn't
diminished the ambitions of book publishers. Just witness the
hundreds of new travel guides that have arrived in time for the
summer travel season. Here's a selection.
 &HT;    Lonely Planet, long the bible for backpackers, has covered two
of the most popular destinations in the United States. ``Las
Vegas,'' by Scott Doggett (Lonely Planet, 2000; $15.95), has tips
on how to play the ``Great Room-Rate Game'' and get a better deal
at hotels. There's advice on choosing the best of the legendary
hotel buffets. And there are reviews of every major show, from the
illusionists Siegfried &AMP; Roy (``the hottest ticket in town'') to
``Mystere,'' which features Cirque du Soleil performers. If the
guide saves readers a few extra bucks for the blackjack table, it's
probably worth buying.
 &HT;    Hawaii is the other destination that Lonely Planet is focusing
on. ``Oahu,'' by Ned Friary and Glenda Bendure (Lonely Planet,
2000; $14.95), evaluates the hotels and restaurants on Waikiki, but
also opens up the rest of this oft-overlooked island for visitors.
 &HT;    The hidden side of Hawaii is also the subject of ``Diving &AMP;
Snorkeling in Hawaii,'' by Casey &AMP; Astrid Witte Mahaney (Lonely
Planet, 2000; $17.95), which covers all the islands.
 &HT;    Fodor's ``Around Los Angeles with Kids'' by Lisa Oppenheimer
(Fodor's, 2000; $10), and ``Around New York City with Kids,'' by
Mindy Bailin (Fodor's 2000; $10), are pocket-sized guides that fit
perfectly in a glove compartment, purse or backpack.
 &HT;    Each one features 68 activities for parents and kids and is
written by a local parent. The organization is terrific: no more
than two pages per activity, suggestions for ``Kid-Friendly Eats''
and enough facts to keep short attention spans intrigued. There are
similar guides for Chicago, San Francisco and Washington D.C.
 &HT;    ``Rome &AMP; the Heart of Italy,'' by Dana Facaros and Michael Pauls
(Cadogan, 2000; $17.95), devotes barely two well-chosen pages to
Roman hotels; double that for restaurants. But it does what Cadogan
guides do best: It provides a real sense of history, written in a
highly readable style.
 &HT;    This is the guide to take along while wandering through the
Forum and the Coliseum during this Jubilee Year. It also covers the
surrounding area of Abruzzo, Lazio and Molise for those who want to
venture a bit farther.
 &HT;    Dorling Kindersley Travel Planners are something new from the
publishers who brought out the much-acclaimed Eyewitness Travel
Guides. They come in a cardboard folder and include a heavily
detailed and annotated map as well as a slim ``Index-Gazetteer &AMP;
Survival Guide.''
 &HT;    The maps include notations of major sights, city highlights,
walks and entertainment venues. The idea, presumably, is that after
reading about a destination in an Eyewitness guide, all one really
needs are these detailed destination maps. They're priced at $9.95,
and they currently include such destinations as ``Florida,''
``Great Britain &AMP; Ireland'' and ``Spain.''
 &HT;    For those who really like to travel light, Cognoscenti MapGuides
are the size of a folded road map, with a detailed street map on
one side and essential information on hotels, restaurants,
nightlife and entertainment elsewhere.
 &HT;    The ``Cognoscenti New York City'' (Cognoscenti, 2000; $7.95) has
broken down restaurant and hotel suggestions by neighborhood. It
mentions Caffe Regio for authentic espresso in the Village and
Sylvia's Soul Food Restaurant as a Harlem landmark. It also gives
capsule descriptions for the best museums in New York, from the
Pierpont Morgan Library to the Frick Collection.
 &HT;    In truth, there's enough information here to keep a visitor
happy for a very long weekend. And best of all, the weight is
negligible. Other cities covered include London, Paris, Rome and
Washington D.C.
 &HT;    Signpost Guides is a new series from Thomas Cook Publishing that
refer to themselves as a ``Driving Guide for the Independent
Traveler.'' That they are, with detailed maps and ratings for
beaches, architecture, scenery and children's activities, along
with loads of colorful photographs. There are just enough
recommendations for accommodation and dining in each area.
 &HT;    The writing tends to be informed and gently opinionated. If
there's a criticism to be levied, it's that the guides tend to
spread themselves a little too thin when covering larger areas such
as British Columbia, California or New England.
 &HT;    The regional guides, such as ``Catalonia and the Spanish
Pyrenees,'' by Tony Kelly (Thomas Cook Publishing/Globe Pequot
Press, 2000; $22.95) and ``The Dordogne and Western France,'' by
Eric and Ruth Bailey (Thomas Cook Publishing/Globe Pequot Press,
2000; $22.95) are the standouts in the series.
 &HT;    Mountain Bike America is another new series, this one from
Outside America and Globe Pequot Press. These guides are aimed at
both beginners and true devotees of the sport. They're written by
local cyclists, with very detailed maps, difficulty ratings and
photographs to get even the most sedentary riders jazzed.
 &HT;    ``Mountain Bike America Colorado,'' by Stephen Hlawaty (Outside
America/ Globe Pequot, 2000; $17.95), comes in at 433 pages, with
49 well-mapped trail rides and, best of all, ``The Great Escape:
Telluride to Moab Hut to Hut.'' This seven-day trip from Colorado
to Utah might be considered the Holy Grail for mountain bikers.
 &HT;    Other guides in this series focus on Boston, New
Hampshire/Maine, Moab and Philadelphia. So saddle up.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
