<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: MULTIGENERATIONAL TRAVEL ADVENTURES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE -----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ADELE MALOTT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    When Perry G. headed to sea with his teen-age daughter and
70-something parents in tow, he wondered what had possessed him to
think that four people who have nothing in common except familial
genes and a bit of history could enjoy each other's company during
a weeklong cruise.
 &HT;    Although the personalities involved ranged from Type-A adult to
teen-age cynic, the quartet's patience and creativity helped make
the trip memorable.
 &HT;    Today's family travel options feature cruise-ship quarters,
hotel suites, tot-size meals, budget-stretching ticket options and
kid-proof adventures, such as white-water rafting for all ages.
 &HT;    Some locations cater to trouble-free family reunions. Some trips
are crafted especially for grandparents and their grandchildren who
live far apart and who use summer vacations to keep in touch. And
the family-travel business is booming _ nearly half the adults in
the United States took at least one child on a trip in the past
five years, and 16 percent brought their grandchildren.
 &HT;    Like Perry G., the Shaver family also booked a cruise. Two
mature travelers and their granddaughter explored the Pacific from
Tahiti to Los Angeles aboard the Golden Princess (800-774-6237 or
www.princess.com) with stops at locations such as Bora-Bora,
Moorea, Papeete and Honolulu. As the Shavers describe it, ``Our
10-year-old, who tended to confuse Tahiti with Tasmania, became an
expert on South Pacific geography.''
 &HT;    Between stops, the Shavers made use of many of the ship's
services, including Kidville, the ship's youth center that is
staffed by counselors and that operates from 9 a.m. to midnight
daily, and a full-scale, no-charge laundromat. Princess has added a
Junior Cruiser menu in their ship's 24-hour restaurants.
 &HT;    The Beasly family, whose four generations range in age from 3 to
83, traveled throughout the American West for 10 days on a reunion
trip that was developed for them by Maupintour's Special Groups
Department (800-255-4266 or www.maupintour.com). The Beaslys met in
Salt Lake City and moved from one national park or monument to the
next _ from Yellowstone to Mt. Rushmore, with its lighting show,
and then on to Cody, Wyo., for the rodeo and a float trip on the
Shoshone River.
 &HT;    For several years, Warren River Expeditions (800-765-0421 or
www.raftidaho.com) has offered a one-week trip on the Salmon River
exclusively for grandparents and their grandchildren. Other
outfitters in Idaho offer trips that range in length from three
hours on the Boise River to multiday expeditions on the Salmon
River.
 &HT;    One of the most popular places for intergenerational travel is
in and around Orlando, Fla., which is home to Walt Disney World.
There, Holiday Inn SunSpree Resort (800-366-6299 or
www.kidsuites.com) in Lake Buena Vista pioneered its Kidsuites, an
idea now adopted by other hotels. Kidsuites give kids their own
space, their own entertainment and their own beds in rooms that
reflect different fun themes, such as outer space, magic castles,
forts and tree houses. The play area sleeps two to four children
and comes equipped with its own TV, VCR and Nintendo.
 &HT;    With so many choices for multigenerational travel, it's best to
consult a travel professional who can find a trip that matches you
family's interests or who will create a trip just for your group.
Who knows _ as your adventure comes to close, you may hear your
little ones express their delight in the same way the Shavers'
10-year-old grandchild did: ``This trip has been fabulous, and a
lot of other words I can't spell. I will remember it my whole
entire life.''
 &HT;    WARNING: When traveling with your grandchildren, don't forget to
take proper legal documents that will allow you to deal with any
unexpected medical problems and that prove you have the parents'
permission to have the children in your custody.
 &HT;    Here are some ideas for summer travels with your grandkids.
 &HT;    
 VAIL GRANDKID PACKAGE  
 &HT;    The Sonnenalp Resort of Vail is offering a Summer 2000
Grandparent-Child package from June 15 to 24 that includes five
nights' lodging, a fondue dinner at the Swiss Chalet, a Bully Ranch
dinner, daily breakfasts and ``fun coupons.'' The coupons may be
redeemed for activities such as river rafting, jeep tours, guided
fishing excursions and horse-trail rides.
 &HT;    Or adults in need of a well-deserved ``timeout'' can use a
coupon for selected spa treatments while their children amuse
themselves by joining one of the free KidVentures programs, from
panning for gold, to alpine sliding, to hiking or swimming.
 &HT;    The package is priced at $2,675 for two grandparents and one
child age 12 or younger, provided the child stays in the
grandparents' room. The package is also available from April 23 to
June 15 and from Sept. 24 to Nov. 22 for the lower price of $1,809.
 &HT;    For more information, call (800) 654-8312, or visit
www.sonnenalp.com on the Web.
 &HT;    
 ALABAMA SPACE CAMP  
 &HT;    Space Camp in Huntsville, Ala., is a five-day program in which
``cadets'' engage in activities related to space science, from
flying a multi-axis trainer to guiding a shuttle into space.
 &HT;    For grandparents who want to explore Alabama on their own for a
few days, Space Camp (800-637-7223) offers hands-on programs for
youngsters _ $699 for children ages 9 to 11; $799 for those ages 12
to 14. There are also grandparent- or parent-child weekends for
$658 per pair, provided the child is between the ages of 7 and 11.
 &HT;    Space-camp programs run every weekend in spring and summer and
during selected weekends during the fall and winter.
 &HT;    
 EUROPEAN GRANDTRAVEL  
 &HT;    Grandtravel, a tour company that specializes in
intergenerational tours, will showcase the history and tradition of
London and the artistry and elegance of Paris in a 10-day, two-city
tour that combines learning and fun. Six departures are scheduled
starting June 20.
 &HT;    The tour begins in London, and then moves to Paris via the
high-speed Eurostar train. The cost: $5,360 per adult, $5,175 per
child. Grandtravel programs are developed by teams of teachers,
leisure counselors and psychologists and include counseling for
participants prior to departures.
 &HT;    Another tour _ a 15-day exploration of the French countryside,
from Paris to Nice _ departs June 16 and July 7. The former is for
children ages 12 to 17, the latter for children of all ages. The
cost: $7,695 for adults, $7,590 for children.
 &HT;    For more information, call (800) 247-7651, or visit
www.grandtravel.com on the Web.
 &HT;    
 CAMP SNOOPY KIDS  
 &HT;    Radisson Resort at Knott's Berry Farm has a package that is sure
to enthrall the kids _ a night in an elaborate Peanuts-themed
double room, along with breakfast, full day admission to the park
and amenities, such as vouchers for in-park Snoopy Kids Meals and
snacks. The $249 rate (tax excluded) is for two adults and two
children under 12. For more information, call (800) 333-3333, or
visit www.radisson.com on the Web. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on The WAY TO
GO! travel package and other features. &QL;
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
