<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The temperature in New York City soared past 90 degrees Monday
for the second consecutive day as sunshine and breezes from the
west brought midsummer heat to the region. The unseasonable warmth
will persist Tuesday as daytime readings near record levels.
Noticeably cooler conditions will cover eastern New England as a
front slipping south from Canada delivers chillier air.
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms will erupt in the middle Mississippi Valley
and southwestern lakes as a jet stream disturbance intercepts a
flow of humid air from the Gulf States. The storms will produce
heavy rain, hail and isolated tornados. The risk for flooding will
be heightened in areas recently affected by heavy rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   Cool and unsettled weather will cover the Northwest while the
Southwest deserts stay sunny and hot.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WILD FLUCTUATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend the temperature in Boston fluctuated wildly as the
city teetered between midsummer heat and the chill of early spring.
On Saturday, the temperature tumbled from a midnight reading of 70
degrees to the lower 50s in the afternoon as ocean-chilled air
arrived from the east. On Sunday, the temperature jumped from 68 to
89 degrees between 2 and 4 p.m. The 21-degree climb occurred as a
strengthening wind from the west sent the ocean-chilled air back to
sea. Tuesday, a front will waver across eastern New England,
setting the stage for another rapid temperature change in Boston. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
