u e BC-NIRELAND-LIBEL-TRIAL-     05-08 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-LIBEL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER PROTESTANTS WAGE A LIBEL SUIT IN WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
  By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington is the odd arena for a $100 million libel trial in
which two car dealers from Northern Ireland are challenging a small
Colorado publisher and an author who accused them of participation
in a secret ruling committee of Protestant terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the dispute is Sean McPhilemy's book
``Committee: Political Assassination in Northern Ireland,''
published in 1998 by Roberts Rinehart. British publishers, who
operate under much tougher libel laws than those in the United
States, declined to issue the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Committee'' grew out of a 1991 British documentary
produced by McPhilemy, who says that an influential group of about
60 middle-class Protestant business professionals in County Armagh
forged links in the 1980s with British special police forces and
Unionist paramilitary group, bankrolling a terrorist campaign that
led to nearly 60 killings of Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers David and Albert Wesley Prentice are among the
businessmen cited by McPhilemy. They are pressing their libel claim
against McPhilemy and Roberts Rinehart, a press near Boulder,
Colo., that says it has stopped publishing new books partly because
of trouble obtaining loans with a lawsuit clouding its future.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in Washington because McPhilemy heavily
promoted the book there, said William W. Taylor, the attorney for
the businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   The Prentice brothers and their relatives are expected to
testify. So is McPhilemy, who lives in England, and Frederick R.
Rinehart, a founder of the press and the scion of an old-line New
York publishing family that once was part of Holt, Rinehart &AMP;
Winston.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is expected to start Tuesday in the trial, which
is being heard by Washington Superior Court Judge Geoffrey Alprin.
The witness lists for both sides indicate that the jury may soon be
presented with a crash course in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   McPhilemy's defense lawyers have listed 40 witnesses, among them
Harold Evans, the former Random House publisher and former editor
of The Sunday Times of London, and Colin Wallace, the former press
officer for the British army in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The witness list for the Prentice brothers includes some 40
names, including David Trimble, the leader of the Ulster Unionist
party in Northern Ireland, who testified earlier this year in a
libel case in London arising from the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, McPhilemy won a libel suit that he filed against
The Sunday Times of London for describing his documentary on a
secret ruling committee as a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   For his documentary and book McPhilemy relied heavily on
information provided by a Unionist supporter, James Alfred Sands,
who was the only direct witness to provide the producers with taped
descriptions of the committee's structure, meeting locations and
members.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Sands has changed his statements several times,
recanting and then reversing himself. He has told journalists that
he would testify in the libel trial, but it is unclear whether
either side will risk calling him.
</P>
<P>
   McPhilemy's lawyers said that they intended to argue that the
author balanced his portrayal of the Prentices by including a
blanket denial from everyone accused of committee involvement,
along with information about a Royal Ulster Constabulary
investigation that absolved them. Sands will also figure in the
defense because the lawyers contend that the paperback version of
the book appeared after Sands disavowed his recantation and offered
fresh details about the Prentices last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't envy the jury on this case,'' said Jack Holland, the
author of five books about Northern Ireland and a correspondent for
The Irish Echo, the New York-based weekly. Holland elicited Sands'
most recent comments, in which he said he offered information to
McPhilemy as a joke. ``It's going to be hard for anyone to sort out
the tangled history. Plus the interpretation of that tangled
history is going to be warped by political agendas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
