<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAN-AM-GAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN ANTONIO LOOKS TO HELP DOMINICAN REPUBLIC; WIN PAN AMERICAN
GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JERRY BRIGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Organizers of San Antonio's bid for the 2007 Pan
American Games are ready to give a boost to the Dominican Republic,
which plays host to the event in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Flores, executive director of the San Antonio bid
team, wants to do all he can to make certain the Games in Santo
Domingo rate as a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for them to be as successful as they can be,''
Flores said. ``If they don't reach their potential, then it can't
be as great a hemispheric occasion as we want it to be for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores plans to explore ways to provide assistance to the
Dominican Republic, which was ravaged by Hurricane Georges in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he believes it might be possible to solicit U.S.
companies that could advise Dominican officials on
telecommunications, public safety or on the effort to organize
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity between nations in the Western Hemisphere, Flores
said, is the ``buzzword'' after the Pan American Sports
Organization (PASO) meetings in Costa Rica last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're laying out strategy for continued contact with (PASO
officials) and identifying programs for solidarity with other
nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flores and Susan Blackwood, executive director of the San
Antonio Sports Foundation, will attend meetings of national sports
officials in Brazil at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings of the Association of National Olympic Committees
will convene in Rio de Janeiro the week of May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Rio de Janeiro and San Antonio have been announced as bidders
for the 2007 Games. Guadalajara, Mexico, one of the finalists for
2003, also is widely believed to be interested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
