<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9185 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-KIDS-VOTE-HNS &LR;      05-08 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-VOTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KIDS TO GET CHANCE FOR MOCK BALLOTING IN THIS FALL'S ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new group called Youth-e-Vote announced Monday
that it will offer schoolchildren across the country a chance to
take part in online mock balloting for president, governor and
members of Congress this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is more important to our system of government than the
active and informed participation of today's youth,'' said Joseph
Mohen, chief executive officer of election.com, a Garden City,
N.Y.-based online voting company that is providing its technology
free of charge to the youth-vote project.
</P>
<P>
   ``By exposing students to the political process at a young age
Youth-e-Vote (will help) turn the tide of the so-called voter
apathy in this country,'' Mohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Youth-e-Vote will mail all U.S. schools information seeking to
encourage them to register for the student vote on its Web site,
www.youthevote.net. The group is also trying to provide Internet
access for schools currently without online capabilities so their
students can vote.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters will ballot on the Youth-e-Vote Web site between Oct.
23 and Nov. 2. Results will be available the day voting ends. Every
registered school will provide pupils with passwords to ensure one
vote per student.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinating the youth-vote effort is Doug Bailey, founder and
publisher of the political newsletter Hotline and president of the
Freedomchannel.com political Web site. ``We will work as hard as we
know how for geographic, income and ethnic balance among
participating schools,'' Bailey said. ``No school that wants in
will be left out.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes the online vote will encourage more young
people to become interested in politics and that the students who
vote online will urge their parents to vote in the real election.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 presidential election about half of all registered
voters went to the polls, and fewer than a third of citizens aged
18 to 24 voted.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey cautioned that the children's vote should not be used to
predict the outcome of the real election.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Jarvis, a communications professor at George Washington
University here, said the youth vote will provide a good test for
online balloting because the so-called ``digital divide'' between
the wealthy and the poor in terms of access to technology is
smaller among young people than among older groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis heads Youth-e-Vote's efforts to connect more schools to
the Internet by soliciting donations of money and computers from
local companies.
</P>
<P>
   She said that because youngsters are less likely than older
people to be afraid of new technology, the students will more
comfortable voting online.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
