<P>
   He said he hopes the online vote will encourage more young
people to become interested in politics and that the students who
vote online will urge their parents to vote in the real election.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 presidential election about half of all registered
voters went to the polls, and fewer than a third of citizens aged
18 to 24 voted.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey cautioned that the children's vote should not be used to
predict the outcome of the real election.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Jarvis, a communications professor at George Washington
University here, said the youth vote will provide a good test for
online balloting because the so-called ``digital divide'' between
the wealthy and the poor in terms of access to technology is
smaller among young people than among older groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis heads Youth-e-Vote's efforts to connect more schools to
the Internet by soliciting donations of money and computers from
local companies.
</P>
<P>
   She said that because youngsters are less likely than older
people to be afraid of new technology, the students will more
comfortable voting online.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
