<P>
   SCIATLANTA-TV _ Eastman Kodak Co., the world's largest
photography company, said it will work with Scientific-Atlanta Inc.
to develop a system of displaying photographs on television sets
without using a computer. The system will incorporate
Scientific-Atlanta's Explorer set-top box that lets viewers connect
to the Internet through their TV sets. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   LODGIAN _ It's looks like William Yung and his Edgecliff
Holdings aren't going anywhere anytime soon. The Kentucky-based
holding company continues on its quest to acquire Lodgian, a hotel
company. Yung recently filed a letter with the SEC in which he asks
other shareholders to support a proposal to add at least three new
members to the board. Yung wants a seat on the board with two of
his supporters. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED _ Plaintiffs are rejecting Lockheed's settlement and
plan to a class-action lawsuit against the company and, possibly,
the union for systematic racial and sexual discrimination.
Meanwhile, the federal Office of Contract Compliance is
investigating the bias charges through extensive interviews at the
plant. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
