A9191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-SPOT-BJT09-COXUPDATE     05-08 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, May 9, 2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: BIG-GAME-MAIN, BIG-GAME-RICH, BIG-GAME-SHY
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MOMS-MARCH _ WASHINGTON _ Parenting in America has come to this:
Before letting their kids play at a friend's home, mothers
routinely ask if there's a gun in the house and, if so, whether it
has been safely locked away. Caren Appel started inquiring after
her 9-year-old daughter, Molly, was visiting a pal in an Atlanta
suburb and the friend's 5-year-old brother walked in with a
parent's gun. On Mother's Day, Appel will join a predicted 100,000
marchers in the nation's capital on a quest for ``sensible''
gun-control legislation. With hundreds of thousands of mothers also
assembling in 20 other cities, organizers believe this ``Million
Mom March'' will be the largest rally ever for gun control. (Dart,
Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MOMS-GOALS. _ Goals of the Million Moms March. (Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DISBAR _ ATLANTA _ President Clinton says he didn't give
``false'' testimony in the Paula Jones case, only misleading
testimony. And it's not enough to get him disbarred, the president
is arguing before the Arkansas Supreme Court Professional Conduct
Committee. The committee could move to disbar the president at its
next meeting on May 18. If it disbars him, Clinton would become the
first sitting president to have that ignominous distinction. The
president's defense was disclosed today by the Atlanta-based
Southeastern Legal Foundation, which first filed motions for
disbarment. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: File photos of Southeastern Legal Foundation president
Matthew Glavin and Lynn Hogue, the GSU professor who filed the
complaint, are available.
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-MEDIA _ ATLANTA _ Assessment of the media crush for
Thursday coverage of the Elian Gonzalez hearing. No cameras allowed
in the courtroom, but you can bet there will be loads outside. And
it is possible Atlanta police may be putting the satellite trucks
on the wrong side of the building for stand-ups in front of the
imposing stone entrance that reflects the courthouse stereotype.
Also wondering whether the morning talk shows may originate from
here. (tentative) (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCFLAG _ Advancer on Tuesday's debate in the South Carolina
House on flying the Confederate flag over the capitol. (Manuel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS _ CLEVELAND _ Daily coverage, as merits, of United
Methodist General Conference in Cleveland. Issues coming up this
week are same-sex blessing, a new TV ad campaign to rival the
Mormons, legislation apologizing for the denomination's past racism
and trying to raise a huge amount of money for historically black
Methodist colleges that include Clark Atlanta University, some
denominational reorganization, and possible resolutions on Elian
Gonzalez and gun control, to name a few. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   SKYWAY-ANNIV _ The 20th anniversary of the collapse of the
Sunshine Skyway bridge over Tampa Bay is May 9. We revisit the
tragedy, find out what harbor pilot John E. Lerro is doing now,
talk to a couple of South Florida survivors, changes to the bridge
and changes in piloting certification. (Hartnett, Palm Beach Post).
42. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-GAME-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ Flurry of tix buying leading up to
Tuesday's pick. Will include sales last week, volume Monday, adding
of staff at convenience stores, etc. Mantius and buros feeding.
(Chapman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BIG-GAME-RICH _ ATLANTA _ Who gets rich on the lottery?
Certainly, the winner, but there who are the winners on other
levels? Are there bonuses for Rebecca Paul? Does the contribution
go up for schools? How about the sales outlets, which make 5 cents
on every dollar? (Scheider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BIG-GAME-SHY _ What if you DID win. Advice from accountants and
lawyers. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH - Texas Gov. George W. Bush works on improving relations
with a group and a man who could prove pivotal to his presidential
ambitions. Three months after insulting some Catholics by speaking
at Bob Jones University, Bush on Monday re-arranged his schedule so
he could attend Cardinal O'Connor's funeral. On Tuesday, he meets
with former foe John McCain. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
20-25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-VOTERS _ Conventional wisdom pegs apathy as the leading
cause of dismal turnout among potential voters between the ages of
18 and 34, but some election experts and activists say the problem
is deeper than that. From obstinate election officials to
registration laws that don't take into account the mobility of the
young, the U.S. electoral system offers more obstacles than
incentives, say advocates who are trying to reverse the decline in
participation among young Americans. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
