<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-420&AMP;AD     05-08 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL ACCELERATES PREPARATIONS TO WITHDRAW FROM LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After the cross-border violence late last week,
Israel is speeding up its preparations to withdraw troops from
southern Lebanon in case Prime Minister Ehud Barak decides to do so
before his self-imposed July 7 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Senior military officials expect to be pulling out under fire,
and several have indicated that they may as well withdraw as soon
as possible and cut the losses they could sustain over the next two
months.
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli soldier and two Lebanese civilians were killed in
intensified fighting last week.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and his advisers dropped hints Monday, not for the first
time, that the withdrawal date could be advanced, perhaps doing so
as a way to pressure Lebanon into helping curb the violence or into
negotiating a withdrawal arrangement. A precipitous withdrawal
could plunge southern Lebanon into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The hints could also be aimed at Syria _ an 11th-hour prod to
remind the Syrians, whose forces control Lebanon, that they are
running out of time to resume peace talks before a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could be straightforward expressions of intention. But
for the moment, Barak has indicated that he wants to conduct the
withdrawal under the auspices of the United Nations, with full
international support. And that would make it less likely that
Israel could pull out before July _ though still possible.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials already consider time very short to obtain
Security Council approval for a plan, organize the nations that
would contribute peacekeeping forces and make practical
arrangements by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been grappling with U.N. requirements for the
withdrawal that have provoked intense internal debate in the
military and government. The major issue is a U.N. demand that the
Israel-backed South Lebanese army be dismantled when the withdrawal
takes place, and that the Khiam Prison, run by the militia and
assailed by international human rights groups, be shut down and its
detainees released.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Antoine Lahad, the commander of the Lebanese militia, asked
the Lebanese government Monday to grant blanket amnesty to his
officers and soldiers, who are considered traitors and face harsh
prison terms or death sentences. Lahad has maintained that without
pardons, his men will choose to stay and fight rather than
emigrate.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official said the government may seek U.N.
intervention on behalf of the militia members, suggesting that
persuading Lebanon to revoke their sentences would make it easier
to disarm them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Israeli newspaper Maariv reported Monday that the Israeli
army is already scaling back its transfer of arms and ammunitions
to the South Lebanese army and that it is considering collecting
heavy armaments like tanks, ammunition and armored personnel
carriers. Ephaim Sneeh, the deputy defense minister, said the
militia forces would need to retain some weapons to defend
themselves after the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   While Israel is anticipating that U.N. peacekeeping forces will
help quell violence after the pullout, it is especially anxious for
help from the United Nations during the withdrawal itself. The
United Nations will be called on to certify that Israel has indeed
withdrawn from Lebanese territory as promised. That will be
important for Israel, which is expected to assert, and seek
international backing for its assertion, that guerrilla forces can
no longer legitimize violent attacks on its northern border.
</P>
<P>
   The certification will be conditioned on Israel's full
withdrawal and its compliance with all demands, like dismantling
the Lebanese militia and closing the Khiam prison.
</P>
<P>
   Barak showed his inclination to accede to international
specifications when he quelled internal debate on two points.
Military officials were pressing to keep some outposts directly
over the border after the withdrawal, and idea that he, a former
general, squelched. And he also quieted disgruntlement about
letting an outside force delineate the border line to be used.
</P>
<P>
   Many Arab leaders are poised to suspect that Israel will not
comply fully.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's foreign minister, Amr Moussa, expressed concerns Monday
that the Israeli withdrawal would not be complete ``on land, sea
and air.''
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether Israel fully withdraws, U.N. officials will
use a 1923, internationally recognized line between Israel and
Lebanon, with mutually agreed upon amendments. Terje Roed-Larsen, a
U.N. peace envoy who is in the region to make preparations for the
withdrawal, said he has encountered ``no fundamental disagreement''
over this line.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lebanese prime minister, Selim al-Hoss, did tell Larsen
that it considers a piece of territory on the edge of the Golan
Heights to be Lebanese as well. That demand could cause problems,
because if the border is disputed then the completion of the
withdrawal will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell if this is worrisome,'' a U.N. official
said, but the issue will have to be resolved in the next couple of
weeks so the plan can be approved.
</P>
</TEXT>
