<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-PEGASUS-HNS &LR;      05-08 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEGASUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEW WILLING TO TAKE THE PEGASUS CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LEE SCHIEDE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Just how many horses will Fusaichi Pegasus
face at the Preakness Stakes on May 20? That is the question.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to the trainers Sunday morning talking about
their charges, the second leg of the 2000 Triple Crown could have
as few as four horses and most likely won't have more than eight
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Already ruled out of the race are runner-up Aptitude, China
Visit, Curule, Deputy Warlock, The Deputy, Commendable, Ronton and
Graeme Hall.
</P>
<P>
   On the fence at this time are third-place finisher Impeachment,
More Than Ready, Wheelaway, Captain Steve, War Chant, Trippi,
Exchange Rate, Anees and Hal's Hope.
</P>
<P>
   That means of the 19 starters in Saturday's 126th Kentucky
Derby, just Captain Steve and High Yield have made plans to ship to
Pimlico Race Course. They will join Red Bullet, who skipped the
Derby after being defeated by Fusaichi Pegasus at the Wood
Memorial, as this year's Triple Crown threat's chief competition.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, if trainer Neil Drysdale ships Fusaichi
Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fine this morning,'' Drysdale said. ``Somebody dropped
something and he bounced, so he was nice and bright this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see how he comes out of this race first before we
go on to the next. As you well know, they're fragile animals and
sometimes things look easy and sometimes something shows up in the
wash. So, literally, we'll just go one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step for everyone campaigning 3-year-old thoroughbreds
is to decide just how many times they want to face the dominating
performances that Fusaichi Pegasus, purchased in July 1998 by
Japanese businessman Fusao Sekiguchi for $4 million, has come up
with his last three times out.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's cruise through the pack to a 11/2-length
victory over Aptitude, Fusaichi Pegasus destroyed the field in the
final 1/8-mile at the Wood, showing that the California-trained
horse can handle the tracks on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bode well for the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with Fusaichi Pegasus,'' said High Yield's
trainer D. Wayne Lukas. ``All the fears about him were put to rest
when he went over there and did what he had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good one. When he's good, he's good. I'm hoping that he
isn't good every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenine Sahadi, who trains The Deputy, made it clear that her
colt was due for some serious rest and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will go back to California on Monday, and I am going to
give him a month to kick back,'' she said. ``He is fine this
morning; he ate his dinner last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``His temperature was normal, and he scoped clean after the
race. I don't have any excuses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
