<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER-08-COX     05-08 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER-08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Big Bush-McCain summit day
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain says he wants to learn more about George W. Bush's
reform plans when they meet Tuesday in Pittsburgh for the first
time since Bush knocked McCain out of the race back in March.
``He's said he's a reformer with results,'' McCain told the
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette. ``That's his slogan. I'd like to know what
those are and how I can be helpful in achieving a reform agenda.''
Bush, in New York today for Cardinal John O'Connor's funeral, said
of the meeting with McCain: ``I'm confident we'll have a
conversation that will cover a lot of subjects, none more important
than reform _ reform of our Social Security system. ... ``I don't
anticipate any changes on his part or my part, but there's a lot of
area for us on which to agree, and I look forward to having that
discussion.'' McCain said he'd urge Bush to appoint retired Gen.
Colin Powell as secretary of state. He also said he wouldn't
necessarily refuse a Cabinet position himself, such as secretary of
defense.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET JITTERS AND SOCIAL SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore raised alarms about George W. Bush's Social Security
plan even before Bush described it, saying it would be ``bad for
American families and bad for our economy'' because retirement
money would be exposed to a fickle stock market. Addressing
publishers in New York, where he was attending Cardinal John
O'Connor's funeral, Gore also asserted more broadly that Bush would
subject the nation to ``short-term irresponsible decisions'' on
many issues, including the budget, taxes, education, the
environment and guns. Because of the funeral, Bush postponed plans
to unveil a Social Security initiative that would allow Americans
to invest part of their payroll taxes in the stock market in
pursuit of higher returns. Gore instead would use interest savings
from paying down the national debt to shore up the Social Security
system through 2054.
</P>
<P>
   AND YOU THOUGHT PRIMARY SEASON WAS OVER
</P>
<P>
   Two top Republicans will battle it out Tuesday for a chance to
replace the only Democrat in Nebraska's congressional delegation,
Sen. Bob Kerrey. Attorney General Don Stenberg and Secretary of
State Scott Moore are expected to lead the four-candidate GOP
primary race. The winner is likely to take on ex-Gov. Ben Nelson,
who faces only token opposition in the Democratic contest. In other
races Tuesday, former Nebraska Cornhusker football coach Tom
Osborne, probably the the most popular person in the football-crazy
state, is running for the House as a Republican. And in West
Virginia, Republican Gov. Cecil Underwood faces a painting
contractor, a housewife and an unemployed construction worker in
the GOP primary. Underwood, 77, was so confident that he did not
campaign and plans to spend election night watching a minor league
baseball game. Oh yes, there also are now-meaningless presidential
primaries in both states.
</P>
<P>
   SO HAVE YOUR PHOTO ID HANDY AND SMILE SWEETLY
</P>
<P>
   Low voter turnout among young people could be more than just
apathy, Cox' Scott Montgomery reports. Melissa Fried of Washington
Township, Ohio, knows she looks young, even for an 18-year-old, but
she didn't expect her youthfulness to be such a burden when she
went to vote in the Ohio primary this year. Poll workers ``really
questioned'' her about her age. ``Three times they asked me how old
I was and I kept telling them,'' Fried said. Then, she said, they
huffed impatiently because she didn't know how to use the key-punch
voting system. The workers may only have been being vigilant,
protecting the integrity of the election rolls, but the result made
Fried feel unwelcome as she cast her first ballot: ``I thought it
was going to be a nice experience, but the whole time I felt like I
wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   WORD IMPERFECT PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has never been considered much of a wordsmith,
but bit by bit he's developing a political dictionary all his own.
For example, when Al Gore distorts Bush's record and proposals, at
least as Bush sees it, Gore is not ``lying.'' Bush never uses that
word. Rather, Gore is behaving in a ``disappointing'' manner. And
while Bush says he'll soon identify numerous ways in which the
government can save money, none of these plans will be ``cuts'';
they will be ``savings'' that make the government more
``efficient'' _ kinder, gentler terms. Bush fully acknowledges he's
playing this word game, and this unspoken but unmistakable
admission has precipitated endless rounds of semantic jousting
between him and reporters, who are constantly trying to get him to
say what he clearly means.
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI PACS MOSTLY FOR HIM
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki is continuing to raise money through
two political action committees that he set up outside New York to
enhance his national profile. The stated purpose of those PACs,
which bear the name ``21st Century Freedom,'' is to help Republican
candidates around the country who share his views. But campaign
records show that most of the total of $892,573 raised so far has
been used to benefit Pataki by building new political alliances and
subsidizing an increasingly expensive political apparatus that
helped him win two terms as governor. The out-of-state PACs _ one
was formed under federal law, and the other in Virginia, where
there are no limits on contribution amounts _ have channeled
$67,433 to state and federal races outside New York. Yet they have
paid at least $126,944 to Pataki's pollster, $118,046 to his
political consultants, and another $190,653 to a half-dozen
campaign aides who are or have been on his payroll for years.
</P>
<P>
   ROBB-ALLEN SHOOTOUT SHAPES UP IN VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   For Virginia Democrats, Sen. Charles Robb is the last man
standing. For Republicans, he's the one obstacle to dominating
every statewide elected office and government institution. Now, as
Robb seeks a third term, he faces an all-out blitz from ex-Gov.
George Allen in a contest that seems certain to make Robb's
bruising battle against Oliver North six years ago look like a
cakewalk in comparison. By the end of March, Allen had raised $5.2
million in direct campaign contributions to Robb's $2.8 million. If
Robb is worried, he hasn't shown it. Often stiff and awkward in his
25 years as a politician, the ex-Marine and son-in-law of President
Johnson appears relaxed and confident, and with reason. He, after
all, has never lost an election, even when at an overwhelming
financial disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   OH, THAT'S RIGHT, ANYONE CAN SEE IT
</P>
<P>
   So where did Handgun Control Inc. get that video footage used in
a new TV ad showing a National Rifle Association official bragging
that George W. Bush is in the gun lobby's pocket and if he becomes
president the NRA would practically be working out of the White
House? U.S. News &AMP; World Report reports that it was taped by an NRA
member who got the brilliant idea of posting it on the Internet,
thinking it would propel members to Bush. Instead, supporters of Al
Gore and the anti-gun group ``just stumbled across it'' and
downloaded it for their own use.
</P>
<P>
   STAND BY YOUR MAN _ BUT SOMEWHERE ELSE
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani's personal problems keep stealing the spotlight in
his Senate race. The New York Post reported that Giuliani's wife,
Donna Hanover, angered Roman Catholic Church officials by holding a
press conference about her troubled marriage just outside St.
Patrick's Cathedral as Cardinal John O'Connor lay in state inside.
Though Giuliani's relationship with ``very good friend'' Judith
Nathan came out of the shadows last week, Hanover told reporters,
``This marriage and this man have been very precious to me.'' But
others thought Hanover's comments intruded on a tribute to another
man who was quite precious to many. ``You don't call a press
conference at a wake,'' one church official was quoted as saying.
``It's grossly inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
