<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SALE OF NEWSPAPER BECOMES BIG NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Big bucks. Boardroom intrigue. Back room
political and publishing deals.
</P>
<P>
   The first week of former political consultant Clint Reilly's
antitrust suit to block Hearst Corp. from buying the San Francisco
Chronicle presented an extraordinary inside look at the intertwined
relationship between the daily newspaper business and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The trial continues Tuesday before U.S. District Judge Vaughn R.
Walker. Some of the alleged machinations _ including San Francisco
Examiner Publisher Tim White's testimony that he offered Brown
favorable editorials in return for his support _ have stunned media
professionals and the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reilly's lawsuit has certainly exposed the plumbing of San
Francisco politics and publishing,'' said Richard DeLeon, chairman
of the history department at San Francisco State University. ``It's
kind of sobering.''
</P>
<P>
   And this week's likely witnesses may break more sheetrock:
Reilly, who spent about $4 million of his own money on his 1999 bid
to be mayor and then tried to buy The San Francisco Examiner; Ted
Fang, publisher of the free San Francisco Independent, who backed
Mayor Willie Brown and won a deal to buy The Examiner; and Hearst
Corp. President Frank Bennack, who faces questioning about what he
knew of White's politicking.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer, contends the machinations are
part of Hearst's attempt to illegally gain a newspaper monopoly.
However, legal experts say the case hinges largely on less dramatic
factors like antitrust law, newspaper economics and how the judge
defines newspaper competition.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that Hearst's plans to buy the Chronicle for
$660 million and sell its San Francisco Examiner to the Fang family
will give Hearst an illegal newspaper monopoly in San Francisco
that will reduce the number of news sources and views and raise
advertising and subscription rates.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly claims Hearst's plan to give the Fangs a $66 million
subsidy to offset publishing costs is a ``sham'' because it would
cost more to run a viable competitor, and thus a Fang Examiner is
doomed to fail. Reilly's own bid requested a larger subsidy,
according to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, the Chronicle and the Fangs have denied Reilly's claims.
And the U.S. Justice Department concluded Hearst's plans will
result in economic competition between newspapers in San Francisco
for the first time in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are control of San Francisco's newspapers, and whether
Hearst will own the Chronicle, which has the prime morning position
in one of the nation's most lucrative media markets.
</P>
<P>
   So far, each trial day has brought another surprise, making the
future of the city's newspapers national news:
</P>
<P>
   Monday: White testified that he offered the mayor favorable
treatment in his paper's editorial pages in return for Brown's
support of Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle. For his part, the
mayor lobbied White to drop a separate business suit between Hearst
and his allies the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: Hearst put White on leave and said it would investigate
whether he breached journalistic ethics. John B. Sias, president of
Chronicle Publishing, admitted that contrary to his sworn
declaration, he didn't know The Examiner's and the Chronicle's
respective operating costs,and joked that he had been exposed as a
``perjurer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: Hearst Senior Vice President James Asher testified
that Ted Fang could personally earn a $500,000 salary and a
$500,000 bonus as part of the subsidy Hearst agreed to pay the
Fangs to take The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Asher testified that the Fangs' offer to use their
political clout to help win local support for the Chronicle
purchase was ``a consideration'' _ although a ``minor'' one _ in
Hearst's agreeing to the Fang deal.
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Asher testified that Hearst got ``intelligence'' about
the discussions on the Chronicle sale within the Chronicle
Publishing Co.'s board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disclosures are eye opening,'' said Stephen Barnett, a
professor at UC-Berkeley's Boalt Hall School of Law, ``but their
relationship to the law that the court has to apply isn't clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented trial will determine the future of San
Francisco's daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the afternoon Examiner and the morning Chronicle
have had a joint operating agreement, an exemption from antitrust
law under which they share printing, circulation and marketing and
all revenue. After paying costs of the combined operations they
split profits, and each paper pays the costs of its independent
editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements are allowed under the 1970 Newspaper Preservation
Act, which is meant to keep alive newspapers that might otherwise
fail so communities could benefit from competing sources of news
and editorials.
</P>
<P>
   At one point about 25 cities had joint operating agreements, but
now San Francisco's is one of a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, a few suits unsuccessfully claimed the
agreements violated antitrust laws. But Reilly's suit has resulted
in the nation's first trial over the break-up of a joint operating
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer, claims Hearst ``abused'' its
position in the joint operating agreement to get an unfair
advantage in buying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto says the terms of Hearst's sale of The Examiner to the
Fangs are designed to doom it and leave Hearst's Chronicle the only
paper in town.
</P>
<P>
   He also argues that Hearst's plans violate antitrust laws and
the Newspaper Preservation Act. He contends that _ in return for a
profitable exemption from antitrust laws _ the act imposes a
special duty to keep papers in print.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer, has argued that the Newspaper
Preservation Act does not apply to the dissolution of joint
operating agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Halling's key defense is that The Examiner is a failing
newspaper and could not survive outside its profit-splitting
agreement with the larger Chronicle. There can be no antitrust
violation, he says, if the business to be closed would have failed
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto sought to show that Hearst believed it could compete as
an independent paper, and that shutting The Examiner to buy the
Chronicle was an antitrust violation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of last week's testimony concerned whether The Examiner is
failing.
</P>
<P>
   White testified that in recent years Hearst has made a profit
from The Examiner under its joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, for example, after both The Examiner and the Chronicle
paid their joint costs, they split the remaining $80 million in
revenue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst took its half and paid the costs of The Examiner's 200 or
so editorial staff and was left with $23 million in profit, White
testified.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Hearst's profit was $20.5 million, he added, and Hearst
has projected profits of $21 million in 2000, $22.8 million in
2001; $23.3 million in 2002; and $25 million in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But Hearst has said in court that, outside of the agreement, The
Examiner would not be able to compete against the Chronicle, whose
465,535 daily circulation is more than four times The Examiner's
108,968.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of newspaper revenue comes from advertising,
and advertising is based on circulation, according to undisputed
court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   White, who came to The Examiner from Hearst's Albany Times Union
in 1999, testified that Hearst sought to make the Chronicle owners
think that after the joint operating agreement expired in 2005
Hearst would make The Examiner a morning paper competing directly
with the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   White said that in April 1999 he told Chronicle President Sias,
``It's our intent to stay and publish independent of the agency.''
</P>
<P>
   But White testified that scenario was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe that we could go head to head,'' said White,
noting there has been a steady decline in the number of smaller
metropolitan papers around the country. ``I had little confidence
that we'd be able to deliver on that threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, he said, was to convince the Chronicle's owners they
faced a costly newspaper war and were better off selling to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Alioto injected corporate intrigue into the trial
when he introduced an e-mail suggesting back-channel communications
between Chronicle Publishing Co. and Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   The June 22, 1999, e-mail said Richard Rosenberg, a member of
the Chronicle board of directors, had divulged the company's
internal boardroom discussions about plans to sell the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail said he passed the information on to Steven B. Falk,
head of the San Francisco Newspaper Agency, which handles joint
operations for the Chronicle and The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Falk then gave the information to George Irish, head of Hearst's
newspaper division.
</P>
<P>
   Irish fired off the e-mail to Bennack, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve told me that Rosenberg opined that if we waited until
the end of the process, they may find themselves flush with cash
and decide to keep the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick told Steve that there is still a great deal of long
standing dislike of Hearst among some of the (Chronicle)
shareholders, and a strong offer up front could lead to their
acceptance without the longer process,'' Irish wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand Friday, Hearst Senior Vice President Asher
testified that the e-mail was ``intelligence'' that Hearst
considered in submitting its bid for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto suggested that Rosenberg acted unethically in leaking
inside information, but Asher said he'd had no thought of that at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg, who at the time was on the board of directors of Bank
of America, could not be reached for comment Saturday. Falk said
Saturday that he never spoke to Rosenberg about it and that a
Chronicle executive had given him the information. ``My assumption
was that they wanted to get the message through me to Hearst,''
Falk said.
</P>
<P>
   But the testimony that sparked the most controversy last week
was White's Monday statement that at an Aug. 30, 1999, lunch he had
offered Brown editorial support in exchange for Brown backing
Hearst's effort to buy the Chronicle. The Fangs and local
politicians - including Brown - had opposed Hearst's initial plans
to buy the Chronicle and possibly close The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was then running for re-election as mayor against Reilly,
and had complained about The Examiner's coverage of his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto asked White: ``Is it not correct that you were in fact
intending to convey to Mayor Brown that his support for Hearst's
proposed acquisition of the Chronicle would result in more
favorable treatment for him in Examiner,`` a trial transcript
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said White.
</P>
<P>
   White then clarified: ``That wouldn't affect the journalism
side. It would affect the editorial side. In the editorials.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hearst issued a statement in which White said he had
been ``tired and confused'' during his testimony. Examiner
Executive Editor Phil Bronstein, who was also at the lunch,
insisted there were no negotiations of press coverage of kind.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto countered that White gave similar testimony to the
Justice Department in December.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto contended that Hearst was making White a scapegoat, and
that other Hearst executives, including Irish and Bennack, had
known of White's statements _ Hearst spokeswoman Debra Shriver and
Halling denied that.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, news of White's testimony triggered a storm of
reaction in newspapers, radio and television. In their own front
page message to readers, The Examiner staff condemned any trading
of editorial support for political favors, and in a petition 80
Chronicle staffers called on Hearst to treat White fairly but fully
investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto has contended that White's comments to Brown are part of
Hearst's alleged maneuvering to acquire an illegal monopoly.
Halling has denied that, saying the local politics are irrelevant
to antitrust law that will decide the case. Walker has said he is
considering the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this trial has done is show a lot of people the inner
workings of the mainstream media,'' said David Lee, a San Francisco
media consultant and executive director of the Chinese American
Voters Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue that all San Franciscans are concerned about,
that our newspapers are independent from the business part of the
operation,'' Lee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
