<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     05-08 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAME GOES OUT FOR BIG JIM COURIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Courier peered into the Centre Court crowd, found the face
of his mother, Linda, and screeched joyously: ``Me? In a Wimbledon
final?''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last place he expected to be: ``Grass and I haven't
gotten along too well.'' But the man multitudes of French admirers
called ``Beeg Jeem'' had beaten two-time champ Stefan Edberg, whose
fondness for the green stuff exceeded a cow's. Even though Courier
then lost the 1993 title bout narrowly, in four tough sets to his
pal, Pete Sampras, who would become Mr. Wimbledon, he had joined a
select handful of tennis players (12) to grace all four major
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Man, did he grace them _ in a way Rocky Marciano graced title
fights: hyper-combatively, slugging away until his opponent
dropped. For as long as it took.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano retired unbeaten as heavyweight champion. James Spencer
Courier retired Monday as an ex-world champ himself, having stood
boisterously at No. 1 in 1992. The two of them beat everyone who
counted during their time. If Rocky was the Brockton Blockbuster,
Jim was the Dade City Destroyer, also a product of a blue-collar
town, his in central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no nostalgia,'' he said over the phone from his
Orlando home. ``Deep down I knew it was time to go. I've got great
memories, of course. The greatest, I guess, was beating Andre
(Agassi) to win the French in 1991.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first of his four major titles that guarantee him
an alcove in the International Tennis Hall of Fame at Newport,
R.I., in five or so years. He repeated at the French in 1992, lost
his crown in the finale to Sergi Bruguera the following year, the
lone American male to shoot for the title three straight years in
that traditional trap for his countrymen, the clay pit named Roland
Garros.
</P>
<P>
   Although the few Yanks who won there never said as much as one
important French word (``merci'') in accepting the prize, Courier
wowed all Gaul by making his thank-you speeches in French. It
helped to have had a French girlfriend. But it was also a mark of
his curiosity, an active mind he displayed in trying to immerse
himself in the various cultures on the planetary tour. Airport,
hotel, and courts are the grand-tour destinations of the usual
players. Courier liked to wander the towns, absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave a lot, all of myself in playing tennis, but I got as
much from the game, the opportunities, as I gave,'' he said. ``I
lost matches, sure, but I never felt regrets about any of them, and
that I hadn't given everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It feels good to leave all-square. That's obvious in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Courier added Australian titles in 1992-93, beating Edberg both
times, but lost to the Swede in the 1991 US Open final. Six major
finals _ four titles. Altogether, 23 triumphs in 36 finals.
</P>
<P>
   He's the first to signal the inevitable breakup of that old gang
of his, the finest crop of American men ever. It includes Agassi,
Sampras, Michael Chang _ 23 majors among the four _ plus Todd
Martin and MaliVai Washington, who reached major finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't go on much longer,'' said Courier. ``I hope Americans
appreciate the guys the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier's hair and intensity matched the crimson courts of
Roland Garros, where he made his first breakthrough, ranked No. 47
while stunning No. 5 Agassi in the third round. They'd sparred
hundreds of times as boarders at Nick Bollettieri's finishing
school at Bradenton, Fla. But Bollettieri had indicated that Agassi
was his star pupil, and Courier's reaction was crimson, too, as it
often was in quick-tempered early days. Feeling slighted, he fled
Bollettieri and was the champ two years later, embracing his
initial major a year before Agassi got his.
</P>
<P>
   Although the brawny Courier will be only 30 in August, he has
``given it all at the office. I felt my enthusiasm waning.''
Courier's physical demands on himself set him apart as a demolition
derbyist in short pants and white cap. Making virtually every
stroke a Sunday punch, he intimidated with relentless groundies and
withering returns. A lefthanded-hitting shortstop as a kid, he
powered his two-fisted backhand with a baseball swing. One of the
great shots of the '90s was his backside boogie: the quick shuffle
to the left to deliver a demoralizing inside-out forehand. It took
him to the top, and kept him among the elite for a long time. But
he wore down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally knew it at San Jose in February,'' he said. ``I was
in the semis against Flip (Mark Philippoussis), which should have
been great. But I was having a miserable time. I wasn't excited. So
that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbreviating this, his 12th professional year, Courier has made
more than $14 million in prize money, plus plenty in endorsements.
He could have continued playing his way out of the range of soup
kitchens, but, ``It wouldn't have been fun, so what's the point?''
He was always true to himself and the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My old coach, Jose Higueras, sums up the feeling in a
sentence: `The day you wake up in the morning and don't want to get
better, it's time to quit.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The flame probably went out after his brilliant revival in the
3-2 US Davis Cup victory over Britain a year ago as he beat Tim
Henman and Greg Rusedski, both much higher-ranked, in five-set
thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   A ``big disappointment'' then was his inability to reach that
altitude again three months later at Longwood in the Cup
quarterfinal, losing to Aussie Pat Rafter in straight sets on
opening day. That made the 4-1 US defeat a certainty. Shortly
thereafter, in the same court, Courier presented further evidence
of deterioration and decline, unable to break serve in a 6-4, 6-4
beating by Sargis Sargsian in the first round of the US Pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out happily,'' he said. ``My passion now is music,
playing (drums and guitar), singing, and writing songs. I'll be
back at Wimbledon, in a TV booth, for TBS. One of my songs is
called `Letting Go.' Appropriate, huh? But it's not about tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was a fun day at Wimbledon. Me? In a Wimbledon
final? I feel the same way about my career. Me? Making it in this
game? It's what I always wanted when I went to Bollettieri's at 13.
We all had our eyes on it, and I feel grateful to have got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeg Jeem gave us a magnifique ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
