<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTOFPACKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRET TO PACKING? SMALL SUITCASES HOLD FEWER WORRIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by PACKING-GIZMOS and PACKING-RESOURCES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Packing a suitcase should be the easiest part of planning a
trip, a piece of cake compared with things like finding a cheap
flight or a decent hotel that's located near the things you want to
see.
</P>
<P>
   So how come I can survive 10 days in Mexico with a backpack and
a coin purse, but a three-day trip to Houston requires a giant
wheeled suitcase and an entire bag devoted to shoes? Why can I fly
to Italy with three changes of clothing and a raincoat, but when I
drive to Missouri for a long weekend with my family, the whole
trunk of the car gets filled with things I just can't live without?
</P>
<P>
   With a weekend trip to New Orleans looming _ the kind of trip
for which I traditionally end up lugging along a steamer trunk full
of junk _ I panicked. This time, I wanted to pack smart, to travel
lightly. So I went to a few packing experts _ yes, this is now a
viable job description _ to find out what I've been doing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Secretly, I also hoped they'd come to my house and pack for me.
But I'd settle for them wading through the wealth of books, videos,
Web sites, seminars, and gizmos and gadgets that supposedly make
your luggage hold more and your clothes less wrinkled, and telling
me what really worked.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out mine is a common problem; people most often overpack
on short trips, when they are less disciplined and plan poorly,
says Mona Williams of The Container Store.
</P>
<P>
   And overpacking ``is related directly to security,'' says Anne
McAlpin, who oversees a packing empire that includes books,
seminars and videos, and who has been called the world's best
packer by no less than Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think, `Maybe I need this, maybe I need that, what's going
to happen with the weather.' And the next thing you know, you're
taking all these things.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlpin, and everyone else consulted, insists you don't have to
spend a load of money on fancy gadgets or luggage. (Though, of
course, they're all running businesses; each pushed a favorite item
or two.)
</P>
<P>
   First, they counseled, make a written list. Not the night before
you leave, but a few days ahead, says Rita Mathis, a merchandise
manager for Voyagers, The Travel Store in Fort Worth. Mathis is all
for making an obsessive-compulsive kind of list, figuring out
exactly what you're going to do and then matching your outfits to
that list. Maybe even make it into a little chart. If you don't
know when you're going to wear it, it doesn't go along. And if you
need something new, you have time to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The chart-making seems a little extreme, but I go along with it.
Taking cues from McAlpin, I limit myself to two pairs of shoes
(three is her absolute limit, no matter where or for how long
you're going) and a limited color scheme. (Everything goes with
black.) I even check with the hotels to see if they provide hair
dryers, irons and certain toiletries. (They did. Big space-saving
move.)
</P>
<P>
   Following Mathis' lead, I cross a few things off, realizing I
don't really need a long black skirt or a sweat shirt in humid New
Orleans. And I write myself a note to buy a white sweater in the
next three days. (Which, however, I completely forgot about until I
got to the airport. Whoops.)
</P>
<P>
   The game plan continues. I get an early start on packing, piling
clothes in the spare bedroom two days early, and even putting them
in the suitcase the evening before the flight. Plenty of room.
Checking things off the list, I feel smug; this is going smoothly.
(But then, at the last minute, seeing that I had extra room, I
tossed in an extra dress and an extra silk T-shirt. Neither of
which I ended up wearing. Sensing a pattern here?)
</P>
<P>
   The suitcase also holds a few of the secret weapons recommended
by the experts: A roll of duct tape, for emergency repairs. (Never
used it.) A cadre of plastic zippered bags, for storage and
laundry. (Very useful.) A couple of Shout stain-removal pads for
unexpected spills. (I didn't remember I had them, but they would
have been useful if I had.)
</P>
<P>
   The final results? I get everything crammed into the smallest of
my rolling bags, one that can easily be carried aboard most
flights. You're supposed to take only what you can carry yourself,
so this is a very good thing. I was more comfortable, having only
one small bag to schlep through the airport.
</P>
<P>
   As for clothes, I brought plenty, just the wrong ones _ which
wasn't the experts' fault but mine, for not watching The Weather
Channel. I wished I'd listened to them and brought more jewelry, to
add variety to my same-old outfits. I also wished for another pair
of shoes. (But I've always wanted that.)
</P>
<P>
   But actually, it's not the tips and the gizmos and the packing
techniques that I'll remember before my next trip; it's these words
from McAlpin, the kind of sound bite that landed her on Oprah's
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get away from it all,'' McAlpin says, ``don't
take it all with you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
