<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS ARKANSAS PANEL NOT TO RESCIND HIS LAW LICENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has pleaded with an Arkansas
disciplinary panel not to take away his law license, arguing that
he has been a good public servant and insisting again that he did
not technically lie before a federal judge, according to court
papers filed by his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In an 80-page brief, backed by hundreds of pages of exhibits,
Clinton and his lawyers provided the first glimpse of how they will
argue that he is still fit to practice law even though he was found
in contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   In the brief, Clinton maintains that his answers under oath in
the presence of a federal judge denying a sexual relationship with
Monica Lewinsky were technically accurate. Much of the brief, in
fact, is an effort to press yet again his claim that he was
truthful in saying he had not engaged in sexual relations with
Lewinsky because the oral sex in which they engaged did not fit the
definition of sexual relations that had been approved by the judge
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said in the brief that his more than 20
years of public service should persuade the panel to be lenient and
not impose any sanction more harsh than a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee on Professional Conduct of the Arkansas Supreme
Court is set to decide as early as this month whether to discipline
Clinton by revoking or suspending his license or imposing a lesser
penalty, such as issuing a letter of reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's brief in the disciplinary case was not disclosed but
portions of it were reproduced in the opposing brief filed by the
Southeastern Legal Foundation, a conservative group based in
Atlanta that has been pressing Arkansas to revoke Clinton's license
to practice law.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Glavin, the director of the Southeastern Legal
Foundation, said he was disclosing his organization's brief and
urged Clinton and his lawyers to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But David Kendall, Clinton's lawyer, declined to do so Monday.
Kendall did not take issue with Glavin's account of the Clinton
brief but in a statement he criticized Glavin and his organization
for releasing their brief, asserting the action was part of a
long-running partisan campaign against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Foundation isn't interested in issues relating to Arkansas
lawyers and legal services,'' he said. ``It's just interested in
attacking the president any way it can.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Richard Mellon Scaife has given the Foundation
money and that Kenneth Starr has helped raise funds for it. Scaife,
a reclusive billionaire, has donated millions of dollars to
anti-Clinton causes; Starr was, until last fall, the Whitewater
prosecutor whose report of Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky
resulted in the impeachment of Clinton by the House in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The disciplinary case involves Clinton's statements under oath
on Jan. 17, 1998, when he gave a deposition in the sexual
misconduct lawsuit brought against him by Paula Jones. In the
presence of U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright, who was
presiding over the civil lawsuit, Clinton said he had never engaged
in a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and he denied that he had
ever been alone with her but for a fleeting moment.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton acknowledged in August 1998 that he had had an
``improper'' physical relationship with Lewinsky, Wright ruled that
his behavior constituted contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   She said that ``the president deliberately violated this court's
discovery orders, thereby undermining the integrity of the judicial
system, and that sanctions must be imposed to redress the
president's misconduct and to deter others who might consider
emulating the president's misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavin said that the bar's disciplinary rules do not require
that Clinton lied, only that he was purposely deceptive. He said
that the president has already admitted to that by saying that he
misled the public and authorities with his comments about his
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to take away the president's license to practice law
has run a course similar to other Clinton problems like Jones'
lawsuit; the president and his lawyers hope to treat the matter as
inconsequential but it does not go away and only grows in
importance because of the existence of a dogged opponent who has
turned the matter into a legal issue.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall had asked the disciplinary committee in March to
postpone its consideration of the case until after Clinton left
office, but the committee rejected that proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
