<SLUG> BC-GM-AUTO-230&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM HIRES STAR RENAULT DESIGNER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors, which has struggled for years to make
its cars less boring, announced on Monday that it had hired a star
designer who helped transform Renault from an also-ran in the
European auto industry into one of the industry's most feared
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Asensio, 37, is widely thought to be the most important
influence in three of Renault's biggest hits of the 1990s: the
small, quirky Scenic minivan and the Clio and Twingo small cars.
The Scenic in particular restored Renault's lost luster as an
innovative automaker, becoming the best-selling vehicle in Britain.
Scenic is the first non-British automobile to achieve the top
ranking there.
</P>
<P>
   Asensio has been the director of medium car design and the
third-ranking designer over all at Renault. She was considered the
heir apparent to run Renault's design department someday. At GM,
she will hold a new position as director of advanced automobile
design, overseeing the eight brand design managers who come up with
future models for various GM divisions like Cadillac, Chevrolet and
Buick.
</P>
<P>
   She will report to Wayne Cherry, GM's vice president for design,
and will be the highest-ranking woman ever in GM's design
department. But she will rank lower than Jerry Palmer, GM's
executive director of design, who also reports to Cherry and who
oversees design changes to models currently in production.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whether Asensio can breathe life into GM's designs will depend
on further progress in changes already underway. The company's
leaders were so intent on restoring its financial stability in the
early and mid-1990s that they tended to choose cautious designs
that were supported by large committees of designers relying on
extensive market research. But GM has begun experimenting recently,
and has committed itself to building six of the nine well-received
concept vehicles shown at the Detroit and New York auto shows this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry said he admired Renault's aggressive designs. ``The thing
I appreciate about Renault's style is they've taken risks, and most
designers admire that,'' he said. ``They've dared to bring out some
different vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   GM wants to show similar imagination, Cherry said, adding that,
``there's a renewed emphasis here from top management on design.''
</P>
<P>
   Asensio became well known in design circles at a young age. She
graduated at the top of her class from France's top design school,
said Carl L. Olsen, a former design director at Citroen who was one
of the school's outside examiners. ``It was obvious immediately
that she had a very exciting career in front of her,'' Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of Asensio's designs at Renault has been the
efficient use of space inside vehicles. The Scenic, which is not
sold in the United States, is roomy on the inside but shorter than
American minivans, which allows for easier parking on crowded
European streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to have a minimum amount of space on the road
and a maximum amount of space in the car,'' she said in a telephone
interview today from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Asensio said she knew what it meant to move from Paris to
Detroit. She studied here for a year in 1987 at the Center for
Creative Studies, one of the world's top automotive design schools,
and returned for a year in 1990 when Renault and Chrysler
collaborated on a sport utility vehicle design that never went into
production. She designed the first Scenic right after her return to
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Detroit, I know it's very different than Paris but the
GM offer is very interesting to me,'' she said, adding that she had
been fascinated when GM showed its latest concept vehicles at the
Geneva auto show in March. ``I'm more interested in the job than in
the town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
