<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACKING-GIZMOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHEAD OF THE PACK: HOW THREE METHODS RATE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies ART OF PACKING) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are the newest packing gizmos worth the money? We road-tested
two products _ and an old standby _ on a recent three-night trip.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Creek Pack-It Folder
</P>
<P>
   Cost: Medium size, $25.
</P>
<P>
   What it's for: Saving space, producing less-wrinkled clothing.
</P>
<P>
   How it's supposed to work: You fold garments around a stiff
packing sleeve, which you then remove; clothes look the way they do
when they've been folded at the dry cleaner's. You then stack the
folded garments in the canvas bag and fasten the Velcro-equipped
sides tightly around them, producing one neat package of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   How it worked: Once I got the hang of how to fold items, it was
easy to pack the folder. (After you've done a couple of garments,
you don't really need the stiff sleeve.) My 18-inch-size folder was
supposed to hold 12 garments. I put in two sweater sets, two pairs
of pants, and a man's dress shirt and tie, and it could easily have
held several additional items. The package fit neatly into a small
rolling suitcase, and after a day of travel, most of the garments
were less wrinkled than if I'd just packed them any old way.
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: On a short trip, when I was living out of a suitcase,
the folder sometimes seemed like more trouble than it was worth, as
you had to unpack the whole thing to reach a single item. But the
device did keep things neat and would be especially useful on a
longer trip; I'll definitely use one again.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Space Bag Travel Genie
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $9.99 for a set of two medium and one large.
</P>
<P>
   What it's for: Saving space.
</P>
<P>
   How it's supposed to work: These plastic bags, with a zippered
seal on one end and an air-release valve on the other, are supposed
to squeeze excess air out of garments, enabling you to pack up to
75 percent more. You load items into the bag, zip it shut, and then
slowly roll it together, pushing the air out through the valve.
</P>
<P>
   How it worked: I used one of the smaller bags for a single
polyester crepe dress; the bag compressed the dress to next to
nothing, but when I unpacked it, it was so wrinkled that ironing
seemed like a lost cause. On the way home, a pair of dress pants
and a silk T-shirt rolled into a thin package about the size of a
legal pad. Eight hours later, they were very wrinkled, but they
needed to be dry cleaned anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Good for dirty laundry or maybe a big fluffy sweater or
parka, but regular clothes get far too wrinkled to make it worth
the effort. I'd take it only on a long trip on which I expected to
fill my luggage with souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Plastic zippered storage bags, quart- or gallon-size
</P>
<P>
   Cost: About $2 for a box of 20.
</P>
<P>
   What it's for: Storage.
</P>
<P>
   How it's supposed to work: Um, for storing food. But in the past
few years, I've used them for shoes, toiletries, wet swimsuits,
delicate souvenirs, dirty laundry, used film, stacks of receipts
and snacks for the plane ride.
</P>
<P>
   How it worked: I filled two with potentially leaky toiletries,
then took another couple for laundry or in case one of the bags
tore. (One did.) This little precaution averted a major mess: I
didn't sufficiently tighten the lid on a bottle of hair goop, but
the sticky leakage stayed confined to the bag rather than ruining
my clothes. Another bag kept my dusty walking shoes from getting
dust all over everything else. Also, the leftover bags held dirty
laundry nicely, though without the space-saving feature of the more
expensive travel bags.
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: Won't leave home without 'em.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
