<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSTAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSIONARY TELLS TALE OF CHECHNYA CAPTIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Herb Gregg carries inside his pocket a small, white candle,
pressed flat and tucked inside a pouch.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sole reminder that he keeps with him of his nearly
eight months of captivity in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   This memento isn't about his captors' daily arguments over
whether he should live or die.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about the beatings and the isolation in a dim room the
size of an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about the right finger that was chopped off and mailed
to his missionary organization with a videotape demanding $3
million in ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The candle is about the changes that God made in the life of the
man from Mesa and about the hope he said he found in the midst of a
terrifying ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   In his daughter's comfortable home in Mesa, 53-year-old Gregg
looks nothing like the thin, shaggy-haired, bearded man who stepped
off a plane in Moscow nearly a year ago, after Russian Interior
Ministry troops freed him from Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   His brownish hair is cut short. His clothes are clean and
pressed. The smile, though, is the same one he flashed then when
asked what would he say to his captors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That God really loves them,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   He prays for the men who forced him into a car on Nov. 11, 1998,
on his way home from a youth basketball game in Dagestan, in the
southern part of Russia. He and his wife, Linda, taught English at
the university there as missionaries with the Evangelical Alliance
Mission, based in Wheaton, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just young men, a lot of them the age of my son. I
could see them trapped in this terrible darkness . . . trapped more
than I was,'' Gregg said this week. Until recently, he had declined
interview requests since his June 29 release.
</P>
<P>
   Only God, in his mysterious ways, knows why he was captured and
why he was spared, Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   He has theories: He and his wife have more work to do; God
wanted to show people that he still performs miracles.
</P>
<P>
   But, mostly, Gregg believes that the experience was about the
changes in his spiritual life, represented by the candle.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the middle of his captivity, he was given a few matches
and the candle to light briefly while he ate.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when he was sure he was going to the killing camp for
hostages whose ransoms went unpaid, he prepared. He put the
precious candle in his pocket, along with matches and some
bandages, torn from the lining of a coat.
</P>
<P>
   But they never came for him.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the candle in his pocket changed. It flattened, in
the same way Gregg's ego and pride were flattened, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a still person. For 33 years, I've been running around
all over the world. So God stopped me in my tracks, and the Holy
Spirit started pinpointing (areas of sin). . . . He gave me a
revival in that little washroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg described himself as an intense man and an impatient one,
driven to do the next thing and reach the next goal. The man who
returned home is more gentle, patient and kind, more appreciative
of ordinary things.
</P>
<P>
   Before reuniting with him, Linda Gregg, 52, worried about her
husband's mental state. She knew that some prisoners of war, for
example, never recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked into his eyes, I saw peace and joy and love,''
she said. ``I think it's a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The main goal in taking Gregg hostage was to get ransom money to
buy weapons to fight the Russian government. Gregg knew his mission
agency's policy: No ransoms will be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he asked God that the ransom would be paid, that he would
be released, that his hand would not be cut off and that he would
not be sent to the death camp.
</P>
<P>
   He also prayed for his family, especially his grandson, Caleb,
who was born with Fanconi anemia, a rare and fatal genetic
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his captivity, he received no news from his family.
He said he didn't know whether Caleb was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Coming home to his family, holding his grandson again, learning
that his daughter was pregnant with twins _ girls now 3 months old
_ is hard to describe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like it's too good to be true. It's like coming
into a dream from a nightmare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said he worked with a trauma counselor but hasn't had
nightmares or flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   He and Linda have spent the year resting, recovering and
visiting churches in the Valley and in the United States where
congregations prayed for him. They stayed with their married
daughter in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   In late August, the Greggs will go to another dangerous country
to teach English, to make friends and to share about the love of
Jesus, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The needs are too great, and the eternal aspect is too
important, to just sit around and not go,'' he said. ``If you
really believe what Scripture says, you share it.''
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare, it's 3-year-old Caleb's life that is on their
minds. A bone marrow transplant could lengthen his life, but
there's no family match.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is happiness, said their daughter, Amy Glover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start to see every day as a gift,'' she said. ``We see
Caleb's life as a gift. We see my dad's life as a gift. When you
can do that, you can really rise above in a healthy way, not in a
way you are pretending things don't hurt, but you can face it and
still have joy and peace in your heart. We have learned to be so
thankful for one another.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kelly.Ettenborough(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-7728. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
