<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-RESCUE-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN PLEDGES TROOPS TO SECURE SIERRA LEONE AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With: SIERRA-LEONE and SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain said Monday that it was sending at least 700
troops to Sierra Leone to secure the airport so that Europeans
there could safely leave. Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said the
British soldiers were not going as ``combat troops,'' but he did
not rule out their assisting the U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Parliament, Cook said, ``We must not allow a few
thousand rebels to prevent the end to violence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the British takeover of the airport would also allow the
United Nations to bring in reinforcements for its peacekeeping
force, which is 3,000 short of its mandated strength of 11,000.
</P>
<P>
   Iain Duncan Smith, the shadow defense secretary for the
Conservatives, said he supported the action, but he added: ``The
concern I would have is that it is clear in their mandate that they
are there to get the British nationals out, but not to get sucked
into a civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Geoffrey Hoon said the relatively large number
of troops was necessary to ensure that the British force would be
able to operate in such a chaotic situation. ``We have to make sure
they have the resources to protect themselves as well as those they
are seeking to evacuate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair's chief spokesman, Alastair Campbell,
declined to discuss how long the troops would remain and whether
they would have a broader mission than just holding the airport and
getting people out of the country safely. ``I'm not going to
predict all eventualities,'' he said. ``We have a very difficult
and worsening situation and British forces have been sent for a
very specific purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Office on Monday ordered the estimated 500 Britons
living in Sierra Leone to leave the embattled country, where about
300 U.N. troops have been taken hostage by rebels and another 200
are missing as a fragile peace breaks down. Cook told Parliament
that the rebels and their leader, Foday Sankoh, bear full
responsibility for the current outbreak of violence.
</P>
<P>
   He said Britain would evacuate an additional 250 Europeans and
50 citizens of commonwealth nations. The British High Commission in
Freetown was giving people instructions on how to proceed, though
it was not clear when the actual departures would start. ``Our
immediate advice to British residents in Freetown is to stay
indoors,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   An advance force of 250 British paratroopers crossed into the
country from Senegal on Monday and another 200 were flying there
from Brize Norton Air Force Base in Oxfordshire. The Royal Navy's
helicopter-carrier Ocean, the frigate Chatham and three support
vessels will arrive near West Africa, off the coast of Sierra
Leone, early next week, Cook said. All told, as many as 1,600
troops would ultimately be involved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cook said that reasons for keeping the British troops there
would be reviewed daily, but he did not put any time limit on their
stay. ``We will weigh the value of its presence against the
security and safety of those who are in it,'' he told Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Maude, the shadow foreign secretary, pressed Cook to say
that the army had only the one mandate of ``getting British
nationals out.'' He brought forth a testy response from Cook by
asserting that ``the sorry tale of Sierra Leone shows that, with
the best will in the world, there are limits to what can be done by
the United Nations attempting to keep the peace that has never been
properly struck.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook countered: ``It does seem to me that the message that
should go out from this House is not one that we are about to
accept the collapse of the U.N. operation, or, between the lines,
that we might be secretly gratified to see the collapse of the U.N.
operation. We are all wanting to work to make a success of that
European operation and will take every possible step that we can,
as Britain, to do so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
