<HEADER>
A9262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      05-08 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEETHOVEN AND KADDISH ECHO THROUGH A NAZI CAMP SITE
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAUTHAUSEN, Austria _ In this land of musical effervescence and,
lately, political uproar, silence spoke louder than either after an
account of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony by Sir Simon Rattle and the
Vienna Philharmonic on Sunday evening. The performance, at which
the audience had been asked not to applaud, took place at the
quarry of a former Nazi camp here, 120 miles east of Vienna. And
although it had been in planning stages for four years, mostly
without opposition, it recently became a hot issue.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the idea said it trivialized an infamous
slaughterhouse of the Holocaust. Others labeled the Philharmonic's
action merely as ineffectual given the rise of Joerg Haider and his
pugnacious right-wing Freedom Party. And the strongest opposition
came from survivors of the Mauthausen camp and its dozens of
satellites throughout Austria, and those who claimed to speak for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to keep it a holy place,'' said Leon Zelman, 73, the
director of the Jewish Welcome Service of Vienna, which helps
refugees revisit Austria. Zelman, a survivor himself, hatched the
notion of such a concert in 1995 to call attention to a part of
Austrian history too often studiously ignored, in hopes that the
effort would serve as a bridge to a more enlightened future.
</P>
<P>
   The quarry looks even today like the unholiest of holy places.
At one end a curving stone staircase, broad, rough and steep, rises
186 steps. Prisoners were endlessly forced to lug heavy stones up
the steps, sometimes only to be arbitrarily pushed back down to
their deaths. Their captors possessed a hellish repertory of lethal
means: gas, gunshots, medical ``experiments,'' overwork,
undernourishment. In all some 105,000 died at Mauthausen: Jews,
non-Jews from all over Eastern Europe and elsewhere, homosexuals,
Communists, ``antisocials.''
</P>
<P>
   Any concerned parties who stayed away from the music on
principle should know, at least, that there was nothing of the
circus about it. It began with addresses: by Elisabeth Orth, an
Austrian actress who was the host of the evening, which was
broadcast live in major cities and slightly delayed on national
television; by Thomas Klestil, the president of Austria, and Franz
Fischler, a member of the European Commission, who had signed on as
patrons; by proxy from the Holocaust survivor and author Elie
Wiesel, who canceled his plans to attend as a protest against
Haider; and by Hellsberg.
</P>
<P>
   The evening continued with Jewish prayers of mourning: Kaddish,
recited by Paul Chaim Eisenberg, the chief rabbi of Vienna; and
``El Moleh Rachamim,'' sung by Samuel Barzilai, the chief cantor,
accompanied by members of the Vienna Philharmonic and the Wiener
Singverein.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the very presence of the Vienna Philharmonic, with its
own dark history, on such an occasion was a problem for some. ``The
Philharmonic is part of the history of Austria,'' Zelman
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Just how integral a part is made clear with the coincidental
publication in the United States of ``Alma Rose: Vienna to
Auschwitz,'' by Richard Newman, Canadian music critic. The
protagonist, it may be recalled from Fania Fenelon's book,
``Playing for Time,'' became the leader of a women's orchestra in
Auschwitz-Birkenau, where she died at 37, probably from botulism.
</P>
<P>
   The book also tells the story of her father, who had been a
revered concertmaster of the Vienna Philharmonic for 57 years
before being unceremoniously dismissed with the other Jewish
players on the day of the Austrian Anschluss in 1938. By the end of
the war 50 percent of the members of the orchestra were Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Zelman's close friendship with members of the
orchestra, including Resel and Hellsberg, that gave shape to the
idea in the first place. And Zelman argues forcibly that the sins
of the fathers should not be visited on the present players.
</P>
<P>
   Hellsberg, who is also the orchestra's archivist and the author
of an unsparing history, ``Demokratie der Koenige'' (``Democracy of
Kings''), expanded on the evening's basic purpose in his address.
``We wished to think of those members of the Philharmonic who were
victims of the Nazis,'' he said. ``They were our predecessors,
royal and imperial court musicians, highly decorated professors and
teachers at the academy, highly respected artists who were
humiliated, driven to death or murdered. We want to pay our
respects to them by performing a work that they often performed
under the leading conductors of their times.''
</P>
<P>
   And that work, Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, was the final bone of
contention, chiefly because of its use of Schiller's ``Ode to Joy''
in the finale. The planners fastened chiefly on the text's
visionary passages, like ``Alle Menschen werden Brueder'' (``All
men become brothers''). But yes, there was joy: even if, for
Beethoven, a joy hard won, as Sir Simon, the conductor, pointed out
at the news conference, elaborating on his description in a printed
statement of the work's journey from ``deepest darkness to
fellowship, generosity and light.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it was done outdoors and rather crudely amplified, and
because of all the emotional and even moral overtones accruing in
the quarry, it was easier to evaluate the run-up performance of the
work on Sunday morning, at the orchestra's splendid home in the
Musikverein. Sir Simon led a dynamic performance, and the amateur
Singverein improbably matched the orchestra at every turn. The
performance swept all before it.
</P>
<P>
   At the evening performance the audience of 11,000 was asked to
refrain from applause, and against all odds it did. The silence was
overwhelmingly eloquent, showing respect and awe for the occasion.
Even the birds in the surrounding trees, which had been singing
their own joyous songs throughout, were quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Candles, which had been distributed to all, were lighted
onstage, and in the audience, where many had already been
illuminated during the anthem to brotherhood. The stage emptied in
sustained silence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
