r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-08 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1-2-3, WHAT WERE THEY FIGHTIN' FOR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names are cataloged alphabetically according to conflict. I
click on the heading for the Vietnam War, scroll down the long list
and stop at random. The name on the computer screen is Donald W.
Evans Jr.
</P>
<P>
   That's your answer.
</P>
<P>
   All this week, the 25th anniversary of the fall of Saigon,
newspapers and TV programs will be filled with writers, politicians
and historians trying to explain to us what the war in Southeast
Asia was all about.
</P>
<P>
   It was all about Donald W. Evans Jr.
</P>
<P>
   According to the information accompanying his Medal of Honor
citation, Evans was a 23-year-old specialist fourth class in the
U.S. Army. A medic. The army's Center for Military History
maintains a Web site (www.army.mil/ &QL; 
cmh-pg/moh1.htm) that lists the full texts of all the Medal of
Honor citations.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,400 of the medals have been awarded, beginning with
the Civil War. Nineteen individuals have earned two, and 574 were
awarded posthumously. What the recipients did is summed up in a
single long paragraph, not often well-written, occasionally
ungrammatical, consistently too terse and cliche-ridden.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' citation describes his actions on Jan. 27, 1967, at a
place called Tri Tam. It reads in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``He left his position of relative safety with his platoon which
had not yet been committed to the battle to answer the calls for
medical aid from the wounded men of another platoon which was
heavily engaged with the enemy force. Dashing across 100 meters of
open area through a withering hail of enemy fire and exploding
grenades, he administered lifesaving treatment to 1 individual and
continued to expose himself to the deadly enemy fire as he moved to
treat each of the other wounded men and to offer them
encouragement. Realizing that the wounds of 1 man required
immediate attention, Sp4c. Evans dragged the injured soldier back
across the dangerous fire-swept area to a secure position from
which he could be further evacuated. Miraculously escaping the
enemy fusillade, Sp4c. Evans returned to the forward location. As
he continued the treatment of the wounded, he was struck by
fragments from an enemy grenade. Despite his serious and painful
injury he succeeded in evacuating another wounded comrade, rejoined
his platoon as it was committed to battle and was soon treating
other wounded soldiers. As he evacuated another wounded man across
the fire covered field, he was severely wounded. Continuing to
refuse medical attention and ignoring advice to remain behind, he
managed with his waning strength to move yet another wounded
comrade across the dangerous open area to safety. Disregarding his
painful wounds and seriously weakened from profuse bleeding, he
continued his lifesaving aid and was killed while treating another
wounded comrade.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 239 Medals of Honor awarded in Vietnam. You can read
one citation a day for the rest of the year and know what the war
was all about. Forget the politicians and the historians and the
hacks like me. Remember what poet W.H. Auden said:
</P>
<P>
   ``To save your world, you asked this man to die/
</P>
<P>
   ``Would this man, could he see you now, ask why?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
