<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HEART-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-08 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HALF A HEART': UNCERTAIN PATH TO REUNION FOR MOTHER AND DAUGHTER
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end of review)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rosellen Brown has long been interested in that place where
private concerns intersect with public values, where the personal
and the political collide. In ``Civil Wars'' (1984) she depicted
the disintegration of a marriage against the backdrop of the civil
rights movement. In ``Before and After'' (1992) she examined the
fallout from a terrible crime on a family and the community it
belongs to. And in her latest novel, ``Half a Heart,'' she looks at
the ways in which race affects a woman's relationship with the
half-black daughter she hasn't seen in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are moments in ``Half a Heart'' where Brown's
gift for rendering her characters' inner lives shines through, the
novel feels far more programmatic than her earlier books, as though
she were struggling to execute a paint-by-numbers picture of an
unfamiliar subject. Its plot too often wobbles into the
predictable; its characters too often behave like stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, we learn, Brown's heroine, Miriam Vener, was a
civil rights advocate who moved to Mississippi, had an affair with
a black teacher and allowed him to take custody of their baby
daughter, Veronica. Since then Miriam has retreated into the
monied, bourgeois world of her youth. She is now married to a
wealthy doctor, has three lovely children and lives in an opulent
house in a gracious Houston suburb where her neighbors have no idea
of her secret past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her friends were given no way to suspect that her children
were replacement children,'' Brown writes, ``her life a replacement
life, her love a replacement love. Sometimes she felt as though she
lived beside a graveyard that she circled the long way around,
holding her breath, to avoid walking through it.''
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with this novel is that Brown never makes
Miriam's long-ago decision to abandon Veronica remotely plausible.
Why would Miriam _ who, we are repeatedly told, is a fiercely
liberal-minded woman _ assent to her former boyfriend's argument
that she would have difficulty, as a white woman, raising a child
of mixed race? Why did she make no effort to retain custody of
Veronica or reach a joint-custody agreement? Why did she allow 17
years to pass before making an effort to get in touch with Veronica
or see how she was doing? Why, given her and her husband's enormous
financial resources, did she make no effort to see whether Veronica
needed help paying for school?
</P>
<P>
   Though she makes vague allusions to Miriam's passivity and shame
over having an out-of-wedlock child, Brown does not provide a
persuasive explanation for her heroine's curious behavior. As a
result Miriam comes across as a curiously hardhearted woman: a wimp
when it comes to fighting for the child she says she loves, a
hypocrite when it comes to matters of race.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam's behavior, once she has reacquainted herself with
Veronica, is equally difficult to understand. Brown writes that she
feels ``a kind of liquid joy flooding her veins'' at the prospect
of getting Veronica to press charges against a police officer for
sexual harassment even though a lawyer tells her that the case is
unwinnable, even though Veronica herself worries that such charges
would expose her to terrible humiliation. For Miriam, apparently,
it is simply a chance to relive the civil rights actions she
participated in as a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   As for Veronica, she is often as unsympathetic as her mother.
She has decided to accept Miriam's overtures because she sees her
as ``a cash cow'' who can bankroll her college education and acting
ambitions. She just has to work ``her way around to getting her
hands on the keys to the safe,'' even if that means having to
accept a hug here and there. She sees Miriam, so eager to
re-establish a mother-daughter bond, as ``desperation on toast.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly a compelling story might be told about two such
difficult women trying to come to terms with each other, but Brown
repeatedly subverts the emotional through-line of her narrative by
setting up sentimental confrontations in which her characters
discuss the color of their skin. They consequently seem less like
individuals reacting to the social pressures of the world around
them than race-obsessed people parroting racial cliches.
</P>
<P>
   When Veronica tells her father that she wants to go to Stanford,
he asks her why she wants to go to ``White Folks' Heaven.'' When
Veronica goes on a date with a white boy, she turns to him and
says, ``So what can you tell me about black life in this wonderful
country?'' And when one of Miriam's old friends from the civil
rights days meets Veronica, she thinks, ``It was such a relief to
see her brown-sugar skin'' in Miriam's house. ``It was home.''
</P>
<P>
   While passages devoted to the characters' daily routines are
energized by the sort of emotional detail that distinguished
Brown's earlier books, this novel frequently lapses into
embarrassingly flabby romance novel prose. Of Miriam's anger, Brown
writes, it ``was building its bonfires on all sides of her, fed by
the past, fed by the present, and there was no place in it finally,
thank God, for tears.'' And of Miriam's grief after abandoning
Veronica, ``She was metal, she was stone, not wood, not anything
that had ever breathed or grown or leafed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Such prose is uncharacteristic of the usually meticulous Brown,
just as this novel feels like an uncharacteristic lapse in her
career, a story told more as a melodramatic made-for-television
movie than a heartfelt work of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HALF A HEART'
</P>
<P>
   By Rosellen Brown
</P>
<P>
   402 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
