<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-KOSOVO-NYT     05-08 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE MARK EMBASSY BOMBING ANNIVERSARY WITH LOOK TO FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ One year ago Monday, university students were hurling
bricks at the U.S. Embassy in a rage over the NATO bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade that killed three and injured 20. Now,
they spent a balmy Monday attending classes or playing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government, which last year railed against American
perfidy and imperialist ambitions, commemorated the bombing in a
low-key manner, as well. A government spokesman restated China's
position that the American explanation that the attack resulted
from targeting errors remains inadequate. An editorial in the
People's Daily called on Chinese to channel their continued anger
into strengthening the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese say they still believe the bombing had to have been
intentional, meant to warn or punish China, and resentment
persists. But now, the government and people want most to see the
China trade bill pass Congress this month, solidifying economic
ties by ending the annual review of China's trade status and
insuring that American companies benefit from the United
States-China trade agreement that was negotiated in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities do not want to goad the United States before the
vote on the disputed legislation to grant China permanent trade
privileges, and passed the word that demonstrations would not be in
order.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with students at People's University here Monday
found no sentiment for renewed rock throwing in any case, but
instead an appreciation of the political divisions in the United
States over China and serious concern about the trade vote.
</P>
<P>
   Zhou Jiubo, 21, who is studying management, was at the U.S.
Embassy in May heaving bricks. ``We were all hot-headed and
angry,'' he recalled. ``But now we've taken to heart the
government's advice to study hard and make China strong. We need to
make our country stronger so it won't be subject to bullying any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhao Bingling, 22, a law student, said, ``We haven't forgotten
about the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   What now worries her more, she said, is the congressional trade
vote, which many here see as a litmus test of American attitudes.
If the bill is defeated, she said, ``I think there will be a very
strong reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People would see that as a slap in the face for China, showing
that Americans despise our country,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese-American relations are improving, but have not recovered
to where they were before the NATO attack and the anti-American
outpouring that followed in several Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
   An unrealistic euphoria about a possible ``strategic
partnership'' had gripped some officials on both sides after
President Clinton's visit in 1998, when he bantered with President
Jiang Zemin and became a hero to many Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   China's adamant opposition to the NATO campaign in Kosovo,
coupled with the embassy bombing, led to feelings of betrayal, and
Chinese strategists focused more sharply on the chances of future
conflict with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the American side, too, the events were sobering reminders of
the many enduring differences, whether over America's military role
in Asia or human rights, that insure a rocky relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Clinton administration moved quickly to mend ties,
and the Chinese, as soon as wounded pride would allow, reopened
their doors to American officials. Late last year, they made
sweeping trade concessions in a deal to secure American support for
China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   And Beijing and Washington reached agreements to compensate for
the Chinese victims and property damage in the embassy bombing, as
well as for damage to American diplomatic missions in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the bombing, Chinese experts gave more attention to the
potential for confrontation in the Sino-American relationship,''
said Yang Mingjie, a foreign policy expert at the Chinese Institute
of Contemporary International Relations, a government research
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Chinese national strategy is still to promote economic
development, and I don't think the government wants to change
policy and portray the United States as a potential enemy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The commentary Monday in the People's Daily, the prime
mouthpiece of the governing Communist Party, praised the Chinese
people for their unity in the face of ``hegemonism'' by an unnamed
superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this contest between justice and evil and between truth and
power politics, we launched a firm struggle and won a major
victory,'' it said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inadvertently, the article displayed the contradictions
that face the Communist leaders as they simultaneously condemn
``Westernization'' and urge greater openness to the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hostile international forces are redoubling their pressures on
us, undertaking to Westernize and divide us,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   But it then added, ``Reform and opening up remain the key to
building a strong and prosperous country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
