<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-08 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: PROTESTANT OPTIMISM
</P>
<P>
   A key Protestant politician predicted that the Ulster Unionist
Party would accept the Irish Republican Army's offer to open its
secret arms arsenal to international inspection as a basis for
agreeing to re-enter the Northern Ireland home rule government with
Sinn Fein, the IRA's political allies. John Taylor, the unionists'
deputy leader, said the IRA's announcement opened the way for
resuming the Belfast government by May 22.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MAYOR SWORN IN
</P>
<P>
   Ken Livingstone, the leftist gadfly who won the race for
London's first elected mayor despite Prime Minister Tony Blair's
efforts to block his candidacy, was sworn into office without
ceremony. Livingstone said he intended to cooperate with the
national government but warned he might go to court to get greater
subsidies for the city's beleaguered subway system and block
Blair's plan for its partial privatization.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY: STRIKE TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Groups representing unions and employers held their first
meetings seeking to end a six-day national strike that has closed
hotels, stopped construction projects, shut down gas and oil
terminals and starved foreign car makers of parts. The walkout,
which has idled 86,000 workers, seeks higher wages and a quicker
introduction of a fifth week of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: 2 MORE HELD IN BOMBINGS
</P>
<P>
   Two more suspected Breton separatists are being held for
questioning in the bombings of two McDonald's restaurants in
Brittany, the police announced, bringing to five the total of
suspects in custody. A McDonald's employee was killed in the April
19 bombing. More than 1,000 demonstrators met in Rennes, the
leading city in Brittany, to condemn violence as a way to defend
the Breton language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA: RUSSIAN BOMBER LOST
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials say a bomber was lost in bad weather
over southern Chechnya and may have been shot down. Pro-Chechen
Internet sites _ often unreliable _ said the plane was downed by a
shoulder-fired antiaircraft missile, and displayed photographs of
what was said to be part of an aircraft wing. Russian officials,
seeking to shield the crew, refused to say where the plane went
down; the Chechens said a hunt for the ``pilot-terrorist'' was
under way.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PALESTINIANS WOUNDED
</P>
<P>
   Israeli troops clashed with Palestinians in the West Bank who
were rallying to demand the release of 1,650 prisoners. Israeli
soldiers shot and wounded six Palestinians with rubber-coated
bullets during clashes with stone-throwers.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: BARAK BACKTRACKS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak angered Palestinians by saying he is
likely to delay handing over the three Palestinian villages near
Jerusalem he was set to give them as a ``down payment'' on a future
territorial transfer. His statements soured negotiations, which
will be suspended Tuesday and Wednesday for Israeli Memorial Day
and Independence Day. Dennis Ross, the American envoy, is returning
to Washington with a muted report: much work remains, but he sees
``potential for progress.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CHIAPAS KILLINGS
</P>
<P>
   In a new surge of violence that has claimed 16 lives in Chiapas
state since February, three villagers were killed and three wounded
by four gunmen in an Indian township. The attack, attributed by
officials to a land dispute, came soon after the first visit to the
township by Bishop Felipe Arizmendi after he took over the
turbulent diocese last week. The township, Chenalho, was the site
of the December 1997 massacre of 45 Indians.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MAYORAL PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   About 150,000 supporters of Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, the
leading candidate for mayor of Mexico City, rallied to protest
efforts by President Ernesto Zedillo's party and two others to use
residency rules to exclude Lopez Obrador from the race. An April
poll by the newspaper Reforma showed Lopez Obrador was 11
percentage points ahead of his nearest rival.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: BOUCHARD GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Quebec's premier, Lucien Bouchard, emerged from a convention of
his Parti Quebecois with a strengthened mandate as party leader,
winning votes from 91 percent of the 2,000 delegates. With a poll
last week indicating that only 43 percent of Quebecers want to
secede, Bouchard said he would promote the economic benefits of
independence. Bouchard, whose term expires in 2003, repeated his
pledge to hold a vote on independence.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: TALKS RESUME
</P>
<P>
   Delegations from the Taliban militia and the opposition army of
Ahmad Shah Massoud have resumed peace talks in Saudi Arabia.
Similar talks in March produced no results. Last year, peace talks
preceded a huge Taliban offensive.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SMUGGLING ALERT
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and Afghanistan have agreed to talks about smuggling, a
matter of discord between the two friendly governments. Gen.
Pervaiz Musharraf, Pakistan's military leader, has vowed to stop
the trucks and busloads of smuggled goods that enter Pakistan each
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
