<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, May 9 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ As he scrambled on several
fronts to stave off the collapse of the U.N. peacekeeping mission
in Sierra Leone, Secretary General Kofi Annan met here Monday with
the Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who indicated afterwards
that the United States might help transport reinforcements to the
unstable West African country. ``We are looking at ways we can be
supportive,'' Albright told reporters after their meeting. Asked
whether that would include contributing to a rapid reaction force,
the secretary of state said, ``We are looking at how to provide
logistical support.'' By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR (New York) _ As the sounds of choral hymns rose toward
church spires, Roman Catholic leaders draped in white robes slowly
filed through the portals of St. Patrick's Cathedral on Monday
afternoon to commence the elaborate funeral Mass of Cardinal John
O'Connor. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: The early version has moved; will be updated)
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila, Philippines) _ Authorities on Monday
named a man and a woman, apparently both bank employees, as
suspects in the unleashing of a malicious computer program that has
disabled computer systems around the world. They took the man into
custody and demanded the surrender of the woman. The two suspects
live in an apartment where authorities said they had found a
computer, owned by the woman, that they identified as the source of
the infectious program, apparently by tracing a telephone line. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: The early version has moved; will be updated)
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-AUCTION (Undated) _ On April 28, a California man who uses
the handle ``golfpoorly'' put a half dozen items up for sale on
eBay, the online auction company. Along with an unopened roll of
twine, a never inflated basketball, a Mexican voodoo mask, a
Netgear network card and a pewter frame, he offered a ``great big
wild abstract painting'' that he said was bought years ago at a
garage sale in Berkeley and has a small hole inflicted by a son
wielding a bicycle. He asked for bids to open at a quarter. On
Monday bids for that painting, which may be a 1952 work by Richard
Diebenkorn, were up to $135,605. If the sale, which ends Monday
night, goes through, and if the painting is genuine, it would be
not only a stunning and serendipitous investment for ``golfpoorly''
but also probably the second-highest price paid online for a work
of art. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-TRADE (Washington) _ After a bill-signing ceremony in the
Oval Office last month, President Clinton sidled up to an unlikely
ally in his fight to pass a decisive trade bill with China, the
administration's top foreign policy goal. ``We talked about what
each of us has to do and we gave each other some advice,'' said
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip and one of
Clinton's most vitriolic critics on Capitol Hill, who refused to
discuss the details of the conversation. With the crucial vote just
over two weeks away, DeLay, who led the charge to impeach Clinton,
now finds himself in the improbable role of the president's chief
water-carrier and potential legacy-builder in an all-out battle to
grant China permanent normal trading privileges. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
</TEXT>
