<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9276 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WORKOUT-PILATES-TEX     05-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKOUT-PILATES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILATES METHOD FOR THOSE LOOKING FOR CONTROLLED FORM OF EXERCISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dancers do it.
</P>
<P>
   But they're not the only ones _ not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilates Method comprises more than 500 specifically designed
low-impact, controlled movements that engage body and mind in
creating more flexibility, better balance and greater strength.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Glover credits Pilates (pronounced puh-LAH-teez) with
correcting a painful misalignment in his left hip resulting from a
childhood accident. He is the financial backer of a new Pilates
studio in Hollywood. Other Pilates devotees from the rich and
famous set include Dustin Hoffman, Drew Barrymore, Madonna, Monica,
Melanie Griffith and Jodie Foster.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that started strong on both coasts and is now
gaining converts in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Pilates' movements stretch and strengthen muscles to promote
complete body conditioning and balance. Emphasis is on
concentration; smooth, controlled movements; correct body
alignment; and proper breathing, says Zoe Stein Pierce, a Fort
Worth dancer and certified Pilates instructor at Dancescape Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Pilates works on the deep muscles of the abdomen, lower back and
buttocks, ``the powerhouse'' of the body, in Pilates jargon. These
strong muscles, centered in the middle of the body, enable the rest
of the body to move freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilates starts in your middle, where everything connects, and
works its way out,'' says Stein Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to mat or floor exercises, Pilates includes work on
some jungle-gym-type equipment with springs and belts and stirrups
and bars that provide the extra resistance or added momentum
necessary to get the most out of a particular movement.
</P>
<P>
   With names like the Universal Reformer, the Cadillac, the Small
Barrel and the Wundachair, Pilates equipment can be a little
intimidating, and in fact should not be used without specific
instructions, Stein Pierce says.
</P>
<P>
   Named for Joseph Pilates, the German gymnast who developed the
exercises before moving to New York City in 1926, Pilates became
the best-kept secret of graceful dancers with perfect posture in
the 1930s and '40s. George Balanchine and Martha Graham frequented
his studio and sent their students to Pilates.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is still popular with ballet dancers, for both
training and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Harris, 25, wanted to dance the lead in the Houston
Ballet's performance of ``Sleeping Beauty'' at Bass Performance
Hall last May. She wanted it more than anything in the world _
almost.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was 16 when she left her home in Arlington to enroll in
the Houston Ballet Academy. She was 23 when she was promoted to
soloist for the company's 1997-'98 season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, she was a star when the company was
preparing to go on tour with ``Sleeping Beauty'' _ but she was a
star whose right knee hurt so badly she couldn't always walk on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was heartbreaking,'' Harris says. ``I wanted to dance
Aurora here at home so badly. It was my dream, and it was coming
true, but I had been struggling with my knee all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more than I wanted to dance the lead in ``Sleeping
Beauty,'' I wanted to be able to walk when I'm 60.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris underwent two knee surgeries and months of rehabilitation
centered around Pilates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilates was part of my training with the Houston Ballet
Academy,'' says Harris. ``They have a huge Pilates studio right
there at the school. So I had been doing Pilates for years. I
sought out Pilates to help me rehabilitate after my surgery last
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris is in Pilates training at Dancescape, with plans to
obtain certification as an instructor through the PhysicalMind
Institute in Santa Fe, N.M. It is one of several organizations that
certify Pilates teachers. Another is the Pilates Studio Worldwide,
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a feel-good class,'' says Pam Heston, directing a
small group of students, including Harris, recently at Dancescape.
``Don't make it work.... It should be so easy. You don't hold
positions, like in yoga; you move through them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilates is also especially appealing to baby boomers who may
also be doing aerobic exercise and weight training and just want to
get their bodies more flexible and not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general population ranges from their early 20s to about
65,'' says Karen Camelet, who teaches Pilates about 25 hours a week
at No Quitters Personalized Training in Fort Worth. She also dances
for the Bruce Wood Dance Company and works with young dancers at
Gayle Corkery School of Ballet to help them develop stronger, more
graceful bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilates is so popular right now, and the kids love it,'' she
says. ``People are always coming up to ask me about it after they
read an article with some movie star talking about it in ``Vogue''
or some other magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilates just makes me feel really strong _ strong from my
core,'' Camelet says. ``I get injured less and know more about how
my body works and how much I can push myself.''
</P>
<P>
   David Estes is a Fort Worth chiropractor who practices Pilates
and likens it to the wellness branch of chiropractic medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilates helps individuals correct a lot of the same problems I
see in my treatment,'' Estes says. ``Exercise can be crazy. The
only thing the average person gets from exercise is to strengthen
his or her imbalances. Pilates is a deliberate, healthy way to move
through space, rather than a clumsy, unhealthy way that's likely to
injure you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for everything. Bad backs and sore necks are caused
by bad fronts. If you don't have integrity in your abdominal
muscles, it will hurt sooner or later in your back. Human beings
are not meant to sit all day. We should be moving all the time,
every day, in a wide range of motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People today stay in one spot and do one type of motion all
day. We should be in constant motion,'' Estes says. Research for
this story provided by Shannon Canard of the ``Star-Telegram''
reference library.dozens of books and videos and at least two Web
sites: www.bodymind.net and www.stottconditioning.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
