u w BC-MEDICAL-ERRORS-HNS &LR;      05-08 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-ERRORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEATHS DUE TO MEDICAL ERRORS MAY BE MORE WIDESPREAD THAN
ESTIMATED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A widely publicized report saying that as many as
98,000 people die each year in the United States from medical
errors is conservative, and the number is probably much larger than
that, one of the study's authors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate by the Institute of Medicine (IOM) is low because
it looked only at deaths of patients at hospitals, said author
Janet M. Corrigan, IOM's director of health care services. The
Institute is a private, nonprofit organization that provides health
policy advice under a congressional charter to the National Academy
of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan told reporters at a Capitol Hill briefing Monday that
the study did not look at medical-error deaths at nursing homes,
emergency rooms or in doctors' offices. The mortality estimates are
low also, she said, because most of the information was based on
medical record reviews. ``Medical errors are a problem that has
been hidden,'' Corrigan added.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine's November report estimated that
medical errors cause 44,000 to 98,000 deaths every year in American
hospitals. Newspapers across the country headlined the story, and
the study spurred many hearings and briefings in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan said lawmakers should create a national center for
patient safety costing $30 million to $35 million a year for the
first few years and $100 million annually after that. The center
would collect data on medical errors and measures to prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   She said current private-sector efforts to stop medical errors
``don't go far enough and don't have broad-based support.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan also said medical providers need to computerize patient
information since computers can catch human errors, especially in
medications. ``It's hard to justify an industry that still writes
all kinds of information on paper,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frances M. Murphy, acting deputy secretary for health policy
and management at the Department of Veterans Affairs, said a
department pilot program in patient safety in Topeka, Kan., has cut
errors in giving medications to patients by two thirds this year.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said patients in the program wore wrist bands with bar
codes _ such those used on supermarket items _ with medical
staffers checking the patients' codes against bar codes on
medications to ensure that drugs were administered correctly and
didn't cause adverse interactions with other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Carmela Coyle, senior vice president for policy at the American
Hospital Association, which represents 5,000 hospitals, said
Congress should create an environment ``so doctors and nurses
(would feel) comfortable to come forward to report medical errors''
without fear of reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle suggested that lawmakers should take steps to encourage
voluntary medical-error reporting for the less serious mistakes to
prevent them from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   If medical providers fear legal action by revealing errors,
``people won't come forward,'' she said. ``At the core of any
successful reporting system is confidentiality for the caregiver,
the patient and the hospital. She said Congress must prevent
``fishing expeditions'' by malpractice lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle suggested that reporting be made mandatory in cases where
patients are ``seriously and permanently'' harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestions came in a panel discussion sponsored by the
Alliance for Health Reform, a nonprofit, nonpartisan group, and the
Commonwealth Fund, a philanthropic group that focuses on health
care. Sens. John D. Rockerfeller, D-W.Va., who chairs the alliance
and Bill Frist, R-Tenn., who is its vice-chairman, presided over
the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Frist predicted that ``there will be legislation (passed) in
some shape or form on the next several months ''
</P>
<P>
   But Rockefeller said in an interview later that Congress should
not move quickly. ``This is the kind of issue that is best
ingested, and then there is a little reflux and a little more
ingestion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
