</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC BEACH VOLLEYBALL SITE IN SYDNEY DRAWS PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Noisy critics of the Sydney Olympics kicked
sand in the eyes of the organizers Monday in a beach protest staged
to attract television coverage and force concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators won network news play here and elsewhere
around the country, but did not win a retreat by officials from a
decision to stage Olympic volleyball at Bondi Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi, a Sydney suburban surf center which is an Australian icon
and tourist favorite, is scheduled to be the location for the beach
volleyball competition. Monday morning, it was the scene of six
hours of political theater about a minor sport that rarely rates
attention.
</P>
<P>
   From dawn about 100 residents opposed to digging up their
neighborhood beach scuffled on the sand with 200 police trying to
keep order with a minimum of headlines while shielding 200 workers
starting foundations for a 10,000-seat arena. That construction
requires shifting about 6,000 tons of sand, excavations that worry
environmentalists and surfers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the police also deployed two motorboats, a helicopter
and 10 mounted officers, but employed minimal force in moving
activists who buried themselves to the neck in the sand before a
stalled bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to charge the 25 protesters they briefly detained,
instead driving them a few miles away before they were released.
</P>
<P>
   The protest group, Bondi Olympic Watch, includes environmental
activists, local retailers, young surfers and aging beach regulars
who swim, sunbathe, fly kites and jog year round at the mile-wide
Pacific bay five miles east of downtown Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The group's spokesman, Lenny Kovner, 53, a theater director and
television writer, and a former volleyball player, said 400
opponents of the volleyball competition have signed pledges of
civil disobedience to stop or stall construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not against the Olympics or volleyball, but we oppose
taking much of our beach away for five months for a 10-day event,
which will leave the community nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Building the $7 million arena will entail driving 360 steel
pylons 20 feet into the fine white sand to support 50-feet high
bleachers. Surrounding the framework will be hundreds of 30-foot
long plastic tubes, each filled with about 100 tons of sand to keep
high tides from eroding the foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the demonstrators claim erection of the temporary
volleyball center, to be dismantled in October, will damage the
beach, reduce public access by half and disrupt trade and
transportation for months in an already crowded precinct, where
about 20,000 people live within a few blocks of the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager of Olympic site operations, John Quayle,
said, ``Some disturbance is to be expected with any Olympic
facility.'' He promises ``the least possible impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The site manager, Jackie Murdoch, said that Bondi will get a
$600,000 improvement of its beach-front community center from the
Olympic budget.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters say firm guarantees of repair of any
environmental damage and major financing for new cultural
facilities would satisfy most complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi residents, vowing to continue opposition, have scheduled a
recruiting rally for May 14, when construction pauses and the beach
is busy with weekend crowds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1905EDT &QL; 
