<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-INSIDE-STORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   This is another installment in a period communique to editors
who receive The New York Times News Service. If you have seen
earlier copies, you know what it is all about, and I recommend you
save yourself time and skip to the first subhed.
</P>
<P>
   For editors who missed earlier explanations, here it is:
</P>
<P>
   As executive editor of this wire service, I want to make contact
with the people who read and use what we produce. So I am sending
this periodic newsletter to give editors occasional glimpses inside
The Times, illuminating who we are, how we think and why we do what
we do. I hope wire editors will pass this along to managing
editors, executive editors, department heads _ anybody who might be
interested.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE FIELD  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEWCOMER IN RUSSIA: Patrick E. Tyler, a distinguished foreign
correspondent whose byline was out of the paper for more than a
year while he mastered a new language, is now in The Times' Moscow
bureau. Before his crash course in Russian, Pat was in China, in
the Beijing bureau.
</P>
<P>
   VETERAN IN CHINA: Craig S. Smith is now the Times correspondent
in Shanghai. Formerly with The Wall Street Journal reporting from
the same city, he succeeds Seth Faison, who has taken a leave from
The Times to write a book.
</P>
<P>
   SPANNING TWO CONTINENTS: Anthony DePalma has undertaken a novel
new assignment for the business desk. He is the hemispheric
business correspondent, charged with illuminating the growing
economic relationships that stretch from Canada to Patagonia. Tony
is now based in the New York office, returning from Toronto where
he had covered Canada for several years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE HOUSE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AN AWARD: The Times has a staff award in memory of Nathaniel
Nash, the correspondent who died in a plane crash in Croatia four
years ago _ the same crash that killed the U.S. trade
representative, Ron Brown. The award is given to a reporter ``who
excels in business or economic news, nationally or abroad, just as
Nahaniel did.'' This year's recipient is Steve Lohr, a senior
writer for the Business Day section who has been a foreign
correspondent, beat reporter, editor, technology writer and much
more. For nearly two years, his name been one of the reporters
assigned full time to the Microsoft cae, and he is often the one
who performs the high wire act of writing the news analysis sidebar
on deadline.
</P>
<P>
   A PROMOTION: The Times's design director, Tom Bodkin, has been
added to the newspaper's masthead as an assistant managing editor.
Joe Lelyveld, the executive editor, said Tom's elevation was in
recognition of his work in leading the paper through a series of
perilous transitions. As custodian of the look of The Times, he
brightened and modernized the paper's appearance over a period of
years, and finally, three years ago, he guided the paper through
its transition to color. Editors who read the ASNE's publication
The American Editor may have noticed Tom's essay in the last issue,
in which he discussed his ideas on newspaper design.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence M. Paul
</P>
<P>
   Executive Editor
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: lmpaul(at)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   (As I have noted in previous installments of The Inside Story,
although my formal name is Laurence, just about everybody knows me
as Lad, a nickname my grandfather gave me when I was one. I invite
you to know me that way, too.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
