<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEMS (Austin, Texas) _ The once-mighty Texas Democratic
Party, whose fabled leaders Lyndon B. Johnson and Sam Rayburn once
dominated not just the state but the nation, has fallen on very
hard times. Of today's 29 officials elected statewide in Texas,
none are Democrats. And much to the chagrin of the Democratic state
chairwoman, Molly Beth Malcolm, several Democratic legislators are
out campaigning with none other than George W. Bush, the
second-term Republican governor and soon-to-be GOP presidential
nominee. Few people in Texas would argue that Democrats are
powerless or obsolete, particularly since the party still controls
the congressional delegation and the Texas House of
Representatives. But Democrats here are consumed by a parochial,
less glamorous agenda, such as legislative races and preparing for
the 2002 gubernatorial race. And few elected Democrats are willing
to make trouble for their popular governor. By Jim Yardley. (1650
words)
</P>
</TEXT>
