<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, May 9. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
AOLSENIORS (Undated) - Phoenix tops the list of the 10 most
``senior wired'' cities in the nation, according to new survey by
America Online. Phoenicians age 55 and over spend an average 22
hours a week online, compared to seven hours a week by the average
user, said AOL, the world's largest internet provider. About 93
percent in the AOL survey said they go online to e-mail children,
grandchildren and friends. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the
`A` and `L` categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Bernard Adelmo Ortiz sat before a
bouquet of TV microphones that had been placed at the table
specially for him, and smiled. This was his moment, his dream come
true. For the woman Ortiz has stalked for years and is accused of
stalking again _ singer Linda Ronstadt _ it must have been a
nightmare. By EJ MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOSTAGE (Mesa, Ariz.) - Herb Gregg, the Mesa, Ariz.-based Christian
missionary who was kidnapped and held by Chechen rebels for eight
months, gives his first long interview since his release on June
29, 1999. He talks about the experience of being held hostage, the
torture, how God changed him, the love for his family and his plans
to go back overseas and work as a missionary. By KELLY
ETTENBOROUGH. Story moved in the ``A'' category.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
