<HEADER>
A9309 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HANSON-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      05-08 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANSON-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME AROUND, NO MORE MMMBOP ON HANSON ALBUM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead, blame Hanson for the teen-dominated state of the Top
40.
</P>
<P>
   When the towheaded trio from Tulsa burst on a scene choked with
woe-is-me grunge and I-can't-stand-myself alternative rock three
years ago, only one member of the band was old enough to drive.
</P>
<P>
   That initial Hanson single, the infectious ``MMMBop,'' changed
everything, stealing the spotlight from rock cynicism and
refocusing it on youthful, optimistic hitmakers like the Spice
Girls and Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since 1997, the charts have been overcome by the
likes of `N Sync, Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, Westlife and
the rest. And Hanson, which on May 9 releases its long-anticipated
new album, ``This Time Around,'' was the catalyst for that
bubblegum youthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a lot has changed,'' admits singer-keyboardist Taylor
Hanson, 16. ``There's been a dramatic change in the climate of the
music scene. There's not a whole lot we did to adapt, but we're
aware of it. When (Hanson's debut disc) 'Middle of Nowhere' came
out, grunge was thriving and then all the other groups came
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22 million Americans aged 13 to 19 reportedly have
disposable income to the tune of $140 billion a year and their
choices in music, film and TV clearly reflect a desire to see
people their own age in the spotlight. And their tastes are
notoriously fickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think we're going to see first-week numbers
like we do with 'N Sync and the Backstreet Boys,'' predicts Anita
Bond, manager of Tower in Sherman Oaks. ``I think the young girls
that liked Hanson back in the 'MMMBop' days have moved on. It might
have a respectable first week, but I don't know about the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Hanson brothers _ Isaac, Taylor and Zac _
realize many of their first fans have probably switched allegiances
to some of the newer teen groups. But instead of hiring a fashion
coordinator and choreographer in order to compete with the 'N Syncs
of the world, the home-schooled trio set out to make a
classic-rock-tinged new record that seems to clear a path to an
older audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good rock record,'' said Bob Bell, senior rock buyer
for the Wherehouse Music chain. ``It's not necessarily a teen or
Top 40 record. But it's a hard one to predict because Hanson isn't
in the same genre with 'N Sync and Backstreet. They were a very
unique phenomenon. There really wasn't any other band like them. I
certainly hope and expect they built enough of a fan base that the
new album will do well.''
</P>
<P>
   While Taylor Hanson concedes the band's early fans have grown,
``In an ideal world, the fans grow and evolve at the same rate as
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson's success came after years playing the county fair
circuit as a family act singing doo-wop to prerecorded tapes. Under
the guidance of their father, Walker, the siblings broadened their
horizons, traveling to Austin's South By Southwest music conference
to perform a cappella for whomever would listen.
</P>
<P>
   During the next two years, Mercury Records took notice, sending
the boys to Hollywood to craft ``Middle of Nowhere'' with producing
team the Dust Brothers (Beck, Beastie Boys) and professional
songwriters like Barry Mann, Cynthia Weil and Desmond Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``MMMBop,'' which evoked comparisons to the Jackson 5, quickly
went to No. 1 in 22 countries and was named single of the year in
the prestigious 1997 Village Voice poll. It had been seven years
since New Kids on the Block peaked in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is always changing,'' drummer Zac, 14, said. ``What's
kind of funny is when the first record came out, Hanson was softer
than what was out there. And now our new record is harder than
what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Recorded in Los Angeles, ``This Time Around'' (Island) shows
Hanson has become a credible rock 'n' roll band still able to crank
out great singles like the album's piano-driven title track.
Taylor, in particular, has matured into a convincing blues-rock
singer while guests on the leaner, harder-edged disc include Beck
turntablist DJ Swamp, most recently seen on the wheels of steel at
the Greek Theatre last weekend, John Popper (of Blues Traveler),
Sly &AMP; the Family Stone's Rose Stone and Texan teen guitar slinger
Jonny Lang.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that like real musicians are going to go nuts for this
record,'' trumpets Lyor Cohen, president of the Island/Def Jam
Music Group. ``The striking thing is how great the songs are and
how naturally the guys have matured.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson appears May 9 on CBS' ``Rosie O'Donnell Show'' and May 10
on MTV's ``Total Request Live.'' The trio will go on tour at the
end of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we've grown up a bit probably makes it easier for
some people to accept us,'' Taylor says. ``I think it bothered some
people that here were three really young guys making this good,
real music.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now becomes: Is there room at the inn for a young
band that sounds nothing like Backstreet or Aguilera and a bit like
a more restrained Black Crowes?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a place for everything,'' Taylor said. ``The teen
stuff is not music we listen to, but obviously lots of people do.
But who knows what the next big thing will be _
reggae/jazz/slamgrass?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the music scene that's changed, either. Hanson's
voices are lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time goes by,'' Zac said. ``There's been some physical
changes, sure. But the band itself hasn't changed. You can see a
natural evolution in the music. We're still writing about the same
things.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Middle of Nowhere'' sold more than 8 million copies
worldwide, three Hanson albums were released over two years: a
holiday disc (``Snowed In''), a rarities collection (``3 Car
Garage'') and a live album (``Life From Albertane''). All were seen
as filler until ``This Time Around'' could be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a conscious decision to let all the attention die
away,'' Taylor said of the delay. ``What happened was we went on
tour in the summer of '98, and that pushed the record back. We had
a real longing to play. We'd been missing being in a band and
playing shows with all the media attention that was going on. Then
there was a year of writing songs, demoing them and meeting with
producers. Before all of this, we were just three guys in a band.
Now we have fans all over the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
