<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WAVING THE STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy National Teacher Day! There's still time, people, to send
your children's instructor a little remembrance _ a box of cookies,
a nice book, some Microsoft stock you aren't using anymore.
Meanwhile let's take a moment to discuss the ever-soaring state of
Standards in Education.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Higher Standards require well-qualified teachers, and
it is for this reason that 39 states have adopted basic skills
tests for new faculty. Unfortunately, 36 of these states waive said
test when they're short on staff, leaving a certain number of
students in the hands of educators who have not necessarily proven
their ability to name the days of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you may find it strange that individuals who cannot pass
a basic skills test would go into teaching in the first place.
Perhaps they were lured by the opportunity, offered in many
overcrowded districts, to eat lunch at 10 o'clock in the morning.
Perhaps they felt peculiarly suited to a career where salaries
begin, on average, at $8,000 a year less than other professions and
end, on average, at $24,000 less.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we have not seen so much political commitment to
better schools since the 1988 campaign, when George Bush and
Michael Dukakis each announced he intended to become the
``education president.'' The golden age of pedagogy that everyone
expected to flow from this contest somehow failed to arrive. Now Al
Gore and George W. Bush trade assault e-mail on the subject every
single day. Bush cannot talk enough about the way he's improved the
schools in Texas. He is particularly voluble about having ended
social promotion, about how he insisted that no Texas child go from
the third grade to the fourth until he or she could read at grade
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have high standards,'' he told a county
Republican gathering a while back, using a Bushian gesture that
indicates the height he had in mind was about five feet.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the first kids who will ever be affected by that
policy are currently in kindergarten. This is the classic political
approach to the setting of standards on any topic. You want to be
strict about the required levels of achievement, but loose about
the timetable. The ideal due date, in fact, is the year after
whoever sets the standards leaves office. If Bush is lucky, by the
time Texas third graders start getting held back, he'll be in
Washington preparing for his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing the things you can accomplish with long-term
projections. Residents here in New York have already been informed
that come 2004, the state debt will suddenly shrink to manageable
proportions and our high school seniors will be able to pass
challenging tests in math, english, science, history and global
studies in order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   In the bad old days, New York reserved what we call Regents
exams mainly for students who planned to go to college. But now
we're going to test everybody _ the special ed students, the kids
who arrived last week from Guatemala. And why not? Every child is
important, and just because he or she is going to school in double
shifts or studying science in a laboratory that was built when
Teddy Roosevelt was a teen doesn't mean we don't care enough to
demand the very best.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is necessarily as crazy as it seems. Some school
officials seem to be setting themselves up for a standards debacle
in hopes that when the great disaster finally occurs and kids start
failing in droves, an outraged public will ante up the money for
smaller classes, better-paid teachers, newer buildings, etc. The
only problem with this theory is that a whole generation of
students will wind up being used for cannon fodder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's worried about the kids caught in the middle,''
says Abigail Thernstrom of the Massachusetts state board of
education.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to Bush, Texas is actually making an attempt to set
the bar higher without whopping it over the heads of the children
who happen to get caught in the transition. This year the teachers
started getting additional training, and the students' skills are
being tested regularly so those who start to fall behind can get
special tutoring. A timetable that actually prepares kids for the
standards they're supposed to meet is definitely not silly.
</P>
<P>
   Bragging about it as if anything has actually happened, however,
is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
