<HEADER>
A9331 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH09-COX     05-08 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush attends O'Conner's funeral; meets with McCain
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probable GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush is on a two-day
mission to get right with an important voting bloc and a former foe
who may be able to sway another important voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush was among the high-profile mourners at
Manhattan's St. Patrick's Cathedral for the funeral of Cardinal
John O'Connor, the Catholic leader to whom Bush made amends after
speaking at Bob Jones University, a school with anti-Catholic
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Today in Pittsburgh, Bush meets privately with former foe John
McCain, the senator with whom Bush exchanged harsh words _
including some sparked by the Bob Jones speech _ during the primary
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the reclamation project,'' said University of
Texas government professor Bruce Buchanan, a close observer of the
Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cancelled a planned Monday speech on Social Security policy
in order to join the 3,500 invited guests at O'Connor's funeral.
Buchanan said it was a significant move by Bush, who has been
criticized for skipping events such as meetings of Hispanic
journalists and African-American mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's funeral was a can't-miss event for Bush, according to
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is justifiably worried about sending signals to
Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral, former Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn noted the
political upside of mixing church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to be associated with the hierarchy of the Catholic
Church is one way to ingratiate yourself with the Catholic people
across the country,'' said Flynn, now the U.S. ambassador to the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Catholic University political scientist John K.
White said Bush saw a good opportunity and seized it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to represent himself as a different kind of candidate
than the person he represented himself as during the primary
season,'' said White. ``It's very obvious that Catholics are going
to play a crucial role in the election. For him not to come to the
funeral would have been a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In late February, Bush used a letter to O'Connor to try to undo
damage done to his campaign as a result of the speech at Bob Jones
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``On reflection, I should have been more clear in disassociating
myself from anti-Catholic sentiments and racial prejudice,'' Bush
told O'Connor. ``It was a missed opportunity, causing needless
offenses, which I deeply regret.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain used Bush's speech at Bob Jones to try to turn Catholic
voters against Bush. It worked in Michigan, where McCain took a
crucial win that sent shivers of doubt through some Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush, who is counting on Catholic votes as part of
his victory formula, praised O'Connor as ``a man who stood for the
disadvantaged and the impoverished, and he was a strong voice for
life in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the only Catholic in the presidential race filed
for ballot status in Texas. Former Republican Pat Buchanan
submitted petitions with 129,000 signatures. To qualify as an
independent candidate, Buchanan needed signatures of 56,116
registered voters who did not cast ballots in the March primaries
or April runoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Secretary of State's Office will now review the
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who said there is little significant difference
between Bush and Gore, also is seeking the Reform Party's
presidential nomination. The party has until May 30 to come up with
the 37,380 signatures to get its candidates on the Texas ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh today, Bush and McCain will huddle privately for
the first time since the Texas governor clinched the nomination in
March. During primary season, Bush blasted McCain as ``a man that
says one thing and does another, a person who says he will run a
positive campaign then approves the scripts of anti-Catholic
bigotry in a state like Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush had only nice things to say about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to talking to John about education and campaign
funding reform,'' he added. ``I don't anticipate any changes on his
part or my part, but there's a lot of area for us on which to agree
and I look forward to having that discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Monday he's got an agenda in mind for today's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's said he's a reformer with results,'' McCain said.
``That's his slogan. I'd like to know what those are and how I can
be helpful in achieving a reform agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more things that we agree on than we disagree on,
and I believe he would be a good president of the United States,''
McCain said. ``There is no point in me looking back in rancor or
anger or bitterness in the campaign. It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he will issue a ``strong statement'' in support of
Bush, and will reiterate his lack of interest in being his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, did open the door to a cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference would be to remain in the Senate,'' he said.
``But you can't say I would refuse to serve in one of those
capacities. It's not the same as vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
