u i BC-LEONE-UNREST-BOS &LR;      05-08 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEONE-UNREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN WEIGHS RETURNING NIGERIAN PEACEKEEPERS TO SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four people were killed in rekindled violence in
Sierra Leone's capital Monday as UN diplomats considered handing
their crumbling peacekeeping operation back to a Nigerian-led
regional force that left the West African country last week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, US military helicopters began evacuating some of
the 170 American civilians who want to leave the nation. British
forces were doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having discussions with the Nigerians, as are others,
to see how we can resolve the situation,'' said Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, following a meeting here with UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan. Giving the operation back to troops from a West
African regional group was among those ``questions that are in the
process of being discussed,'' Albright said, although Washington
later announced it would fly another 700 Bangladeshi UN
peacekeepers into the region, but it was not clear if they would
set foot in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's departure of the Nigerian-led regional peacekeepers
and their replacement by 8,700 poorly equipped UN counterparts led
within days to renewed fighting by the Revolutionary United Front
rebels and the capture of 500 UN troops, who have been held hostage
for several days. One UN soldier has been killed, and the UN Monday
evacuated 266 members of a 321-member civilian staff.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuations gave greater credence to speculation that the
United Nations may again pull out its peacekeepers in the face of a
crisis, as it did in Somalia in 1993 and one year later in Rwanda,
just before the murders of hundreds of thousands in tribal
violence. Sierra Leone's surging rebels killed thousands and
chopped off the limbs of thousands more before a cease-fire
temporarily halted an eight-year civil war in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The UN troops in Sierra Leone have been criticized by the host
government for not fighting back when attacked by the rebels. By
contrast, the Nigerian troops fought the rebels for several years,
sustaining many casualties and recapturing Freetown from the rebels
in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of UN peacekeepers surrounding the home of rebel leader
Foday Sankoh Monday did little to prevent the clashes there that
led to the protesters' deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said at least four people were killed outside Sankoh's
home after his men fired into a crowd of thousands of peace
demonstrators who had been hurling rocks at Sankoh's house. The gun
battle pitted Sankoh supporters against loyalists of one or more
rival factions, including one led by ex-military ruler Johnny Paul
Koroma, who has called for his men to rearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sustained shooting was also reported in other parts of the
city,'' said UN spokesman Fred Eckhard while in Freetown, armed
gangs were seen roaming the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Okabe, a UN spokeswoman, said she spoke with an American
newspaper correspondent on the scene who had a gun put to her head
by a rebel after two protesters fell dead at her feet. Corinna
Schuler, a Johannesburg-based journalist for The Christian Science
Monitor, was rescued only when a Nigerian peacekeeper paid off her
attacker, said Okabe.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by a joint UN-rebel team to reach the captured UN
soldiers have failed because of fighting near the town of Makeni,
said Eckhard. The rebels have made no demands and set no conditions
for the hostages' release and continue to deny _ despite visual
evidence from UN helicopters to the contrary _ that the
peacekeepers are being held, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Okabe said a UN helicopter on Sunday trying to resupply a group
of Kenyan peacekeepers in Makeni was shot at by rifle-toting rebels
and was forced to make an emergency landing when its fuel tank was
struck.
</P>
<P>
   The UN High Commissioner of Refugees reported Monday refugees
were being prevented from fleeing across border by rebels. Only 149
known to have fled so far, the UN refugee group said.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said diplomatic efforts were continuing to find a
solution to the crisis. A summit meeting of Western African leaders
from Liberia, Sierra Leone, Guinea and Mali is set for Tuesday in
Conkary, the Guinean capital. Libyan leader Moammar Khadafy has
also interceded on the UN's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   If diplomacy fails, Eckhard said, the Security Council faced a
decision to allow UN peacekeepers to fight the rebels or be pulled
out of the country as peacekeepers were in Somalia and Rwanda
during the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The UN peacekeepers are charged with protecting civilians and
the government ``but they do not want to be seen fighting side by
side with the government against rebel forces,'' said Eckhard.
Peacekeeping becomes untenable when neutrality is lost, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council met Monday, but a British diplomat said
withdrawal was not discussed. ``But fighting was, and this could be
done by the West African regional force,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, the former colonial power, has sent 700-800 troops to
evacuate European nationals, and took control of Freetown's airport
Monday night, the diplomat said. She said British troops would stay
only long enough to get the Europeans out.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said Britain has not offered its troops to either free
the UN hostages or to support its peacekeeping mission. ``We can't
be sending British gunboats to fight a civil war,'' the British
official told the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, nevertheless, repeated his call for a rapid reaction
force to be sent to the country. His request last week for such a
force was rejected by Britain and France. ``There are only a few
countries that have such a capability,'' Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the collapse of the cease-fire, the UN peacekeepers had
intended to oversee disarmament and demobilization of both sides,
as well as elections next year, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
