<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SRI-LANKA-1STLD-WRITE     05-08 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRI-LANKA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT REJECTS CEASE-FIRE OFFER BY REBELS IN SRI LANKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: SUBS to update with new 2nd graf; alters content of
president's statement in 3rd graf.) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ Though it is on the defensive militarily,
the Sri Lankan government on Monday night firmly rejected a
separatist Tamil group's offer of a cease-fire in exchange for the
government's promise to withdraw tens of thousands of its troops
from the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The government's director of information, Ariya Rubasinghe,
confirmed that the government had no intention of pulling out of
the small peninsula at the country's northern tip.
</P>
<P>
   President Chandrika Kumaratunga, who survived an assassination
attempt by a separatist suicide bomber, did not refer to the
cease-fire offer in a nationally televised address, but said the
government would stay and fight the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. The rebel group is notorious for its suicide attacks and has
been labeled a terrorist organization by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The eye patch that had covered Kumaratunga's eye, injured in the
December assassination attempt, was gone tonight when she declared
in Sinhalese, ``We shall leave no room for the LTTE to again fasten
their fascist grip on half a million Tamil people in Jaffna.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kumaratunga's decision was a risky one. The Tigers have been
on a successful military march to reclaim Jaffna, the cultural
capital of the Hindu Tamil-dominated north in this majority
Buddhist Sinhalese nation. For the first time in the 18-year-old
civil war _ which has claimed more than 60,000 lives in a country
with a population no larger than New York State's _ the rebels
control Elephant Pass, which an opposition leader has called the
doorway to the fortress of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the government has controlled Jaffna, but for five
years before that the Tigers, who seek a separate Tamil homeland,
ran what was essentially a small state there.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Pass is a narrow strip of land connecting the mainland
to the peninsula and the site of one of the most heavily fortified
military bases in the country. On April 22, with military moves
like those of a conventional army, the rebels took the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government banned political rallies and union
strikes and tightened a vise of press censorship in what it said
was an effort to protect national security, but that the opposition
said was an attempt by the government to hide the government's own
failings.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers said in a statement from their London office on
Monday that they were willing to observe a cease-fire once the
government surrenders Jaffna, which the rebels said could open the
way to peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam wishes to state that it
is prepared to declare a temporary cease fire suspending all armed
hostilities against the Sri Lankan armed forces to facilitate the
beleaguered government troops to be evacuated safely from the
Jaffna peninsula,'' the group's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of a large force of demoralized government troops' being
trapped on the Jaffna peninsula and hostage to the Tigers have led
some here to hope that India, the region's great power, would
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   India's prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, met with the
leaders of 20 political parties on Monday to discuss the conflict
in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   India has a much larger Tamil population than Sri Lanka in the
politically potent southern state of Tamil Nadu. And India
supported Sri Lankan Tamil militants, including the Tigers, in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But India has to worry about stirring nationalist feeling among
its own Tamil citizens. And both Sri Lanka and India have an
interest in holding together their ethnically and religiously
diverse nations.
</P>
<P>
   So India ruled out military intervention, though it was not
clear that it would refuse to help evacuate troops. In the late
1980s, India lost more than 1,000 troops on a long peacekeeping
mission in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The parliamentary affairs minister, Pramod Mahajan, said after
the meeting that India would only consider mediating between the
Tigers and the Sri Lankan government if both sides wanted Indian
help.
</P>
<P>
   The role of mediator had fallen earlier this year to Norway, one
of the nations the Tigers had deemed an acceptable intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   The Sri Lankan political opposition leader, Ranil
Wickremesinghe, said in an interview tonight that he believed that
Norway and India might work together to try to broker a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter feuding between Kumaratunga and Wickremesinghe, who
heads the United National Party, has been an important element in a
failed attempt to get a peace plan through Parliament. The
opposition had opposed the government's attempt to change the
Constitution to give the Tamils greater autonomy in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Kumaratunga and Wickremesinghe have been having their
own peace talks, but any agreement they reach may be overtaken by
military developments that _ up to now _ are tilting in the Tigers'
favor.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
