<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LEWIS-VERDICT-BOS &LR;      05-08 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-VERDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DECIDES IN FAVOR OF DOCTOR IN REGGIE LEWIS RETRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bringing to an end a bitter, divisive saga that
stretched over two trials in two years, a jury has agreed that the
death of Celtics captain Reggie Lewis on a basketball court nearly
seven years ago was not caused by the negligence of his
cardiologist, who had confidently proclaimed that the 27-year-old
did not have a life-threatening heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   The requisite 13 of 16 jurors reached their verdict swiftly
within 30 minutes of being told Monday by Judge Thayer
Fremont-Smith that the lawyers in the case -- intent on avoiding
another mistrial -- would accept a verdict if only 12 could agree.
</P>
<P>
   When the jurors returned to the courtroom shortly before 10 a.m.
they had reached a decision: 13 in favor of Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge
Jr. and 3 against, a slight but significant shift from the 12-4
deadlock reported to the court on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors spent more than 20 hours deliberating before reaching
their decision, which came shortly after they began a fifth day of
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion to one of the city's highest-profile medical
malpractice lawsuits -- which drew in sports, medical and legal
sectors and fueled persistent public debate -- was oddly
anti-climactic.
</P>
<P>
   With neither Mudge nor Donna Harris-Lewis, Lewis's widow, in the
courtroom, the scene was subdued, the rawest emotion exhibited by a
female juror who wept as the verdict was announced. Mudge's lawyers
shared congratulatory hand shakes and pats on the back, while
lawyers for Harris-Lewis were expressionless.
</P>
<P>
   The low-key finale was in stark contrast to the first trial last
year, when Mudge and his wife, surrounded by jubilant friends and
family, let out a celebratory cheer as they descended a courthouse
elevator after the jury reported that it was hopelessly deadlocked
and the judge declared a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   Even the spectator gallery -- which last year swarmed with
supporters from both sides -- Monday was filled mainly with
reporters and a clutch of lawyers waiting to begin a new case in
the same courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   At Harris-Lewis's home, police had posted no-parking signs and
stretched yellow tape across her driveway to keep the media away.
Mudge, who is director of cardiac transplantation at Brigham and
Women's Hospital, could not be reached at work and did not return a
message left at his home.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Harris-Lewis's attorney, Neil Rossman, held out
the possibility of an appeal, all indications -- including public
comments by Rossman -- were that the case had finally come to a
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously very disappointed, but I tried the best case I
could try,'' Rossman said. ``I do want to say that we got a fair
trial...and I don't think if we tried the case again we could try a
better case. ... The jury just didn't see it our way.''
</P>
<P>
   In defeat, Rossman nonetheless savored some measure of victory,
principally the ruling by Fremont-Smith that jurors could not
consider evidence of Lewis's alleged cocaine use as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The judge made the ruling after Mudge testified that he did not
change his treatment plan after Lewis allegedly admitted to him
that he had used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got cocaine out of the case once and for all,'' Rossman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Harris-Lewis was handling news of the verdict, Rossman
said she was ``very disappointed, but I guess it's time to move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's lead attorney, William J. Dailey Jr., called the verdict
``a just result.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're very pleased with the verdict,'' said Dailey.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Mudge has fared professionally throughout the case,
Dailey noted that his cardiology practice is ``busier than ever,''
but added, ``To say that a case like this was not personally
traumatic to a physician would not be true.''
</P>
<P>
   On whether there were ever settlement discussions, Dailey said,
``There was talk about possibly trying to resolve it, but it never
came to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis sued Mudge and three other cardiologists for
malpractice in May 1996, just months before the litigation would
have been barred by the state's three-year statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other defendants, Drs. Peter L. Friedman and Mark A.
Creager, were cleared of negligence in the first trial last year.
The fourth defendant, Dr. John D. Rutherford, now in practice in
Texas, settled out of court with Harris-Lewis for $500,000 on the
day that jury selection began in the first trial.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Harris-Lewis's suit spurred furious debate about
her motives. Supporters hailed her as a grieving spouse determined
to clear her husband's name, which had been publicly linked to
cocaine use -- which can cause lasting heart damage -- after he
died. Critics labeled her a greedy widow intent on making money off
her husband's death, and willing to sacrifice his reputation in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Harris-Lewis, who staunchly denies that her
husband used drugs, said the suit was motivated by a 1995 Wall
Street Journal story suggesting that cocaine played a role in her
husband's death, and by Mudge's subsequent contention that Lewis,
two weeks before his death, had admitted using cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, widely regarded before his death as one of the nation's
rising basketball stars, first drew the concern of doctors when he
collapsed in the Boston Garden during a playoff game on April 29,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Lewis, a National Basketball Association
All-Star, was admitted for tests at New England Baptist Hospital,
where a team of prominent physicians from across the city -- dubbed
the ``Dream Team'' -- concluded that he had a serious heart problem
that could end his basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a bizarre turn of events three days later, Lewis left
the Baptist against medical advice in the middle of the night and
transferred to the Brigham under Mudge's care.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days later, Mudge announced at a press conference that
Lewis suffered only from a benign fainting disorder and would be
able to play basketball again. Eleven weeks later, on July 27,
1993, Lewis collapsed and died while shooting baskets at Brandeis
University, stunning the city and leaving behind a pregnant wife
and year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy found no evidence of drugs in Lewis's system, and his
death certificate listed adenovirus, a relatively minor virus
spread by coughing and sneezing, as the cause of scarring found in
his heart.
</P>
<P>
   In her suit, Harris-Lewis accused Mudge of failing to diagnose
her husband with an arrhythmia, an uncontrolled fluttering of the
heart that can cause death.
</P>
<P>
   But Mudge testified that he was considering a second diagnosis
of an arrhythmia. And his lawyers argued that Lewis contributed to
his own death by failing to take his medication regularly and
violating Mudge's orders not to exercise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
