<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. House debates flag's fate today
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old Confederacy will rally in Columbia today. At stake is
whether its battle flag will continue to wave over the copper-clad
dome of the South Carolina Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Generals will wear battle regalia, belles will sashay in hoop
skirts and soldiers will don gray woolen uniforms, if protests
since January are any predictor. They'll sing ``Dixie'' and wave
blood-red banners marked by sea-blue X's with 13 stars, for the 11
states that seceded from the Union and two that didn't officially
secede but sent many troops to the Confederate side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll certainly be well-represented,'' said R.G.
Wilson of Easely, S.C., lieutenant commander-in-chief of the Sons
of Confederate Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they'll gather for the drama that will unravel inside the
cool granite walls of the Capitol, still marred outside by
Sherman's cannon fire 135 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime past 1 p.m. today, the South Carolina House will begin
debating a bill that would remove the controversial battle flag
from the Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of lowering the flag _ especially at the hands of a
tourism boycott launched by the NAACP _ sends shudders through
ancestors of the Confederacy, who revere the battle emblem as a
stout symbol of Southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there would be significant impact in all areas of the
country that have any kind of Southern monuments or historical
display of Confederate battle flags,'' Wilson said Monday. ``There
would be an intense effort on the part of these NAACP-types and
those one-world-view types to eradicate those symbols of our
Southern heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   If the flag falls in South Carolina, Georgia becomes the next
target; like Mississippi, the Peach State weaves the Confederate
battle emblem into its state flag.
</P>
<P>
   As House debate begins, there's no consensus about what to do.
The banner has flown over the Capitol dome since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Democratic-run Senate sent the
Republican-controlled House a compromise bill that would remove the
battle flag from atop the Capitol dome. The Senate proposes flying
a similarly designed battle flag _ square instead of rectangular _
at the Confederate Soldiers Monument on the Capitol's prominent
north lawn.
</P>
<P>
   However, House Democrats, especially members of the black
caucus, reject that idea because it hangs the banner at one of the
most visible places in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Republicans refuse to support a Democratic
amendment that would remove the dome's banner and replace it at the
Confederate monument with a bronze likeness of the battle flag. A
memorial with no flying flag is a major obstacle for some
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders say today likely will be spent finding traction
for a plan acceptable to all sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any proposal out there right now that will
receive a majority vote,'' House Speaker David Wilkins
(R-Greenville) said Monday. ``Right now, the most viable plan, the
plan that has the best chance of ultimately succeeding, is the
Senate bill, the soldiers monument.'' Like Wilkins, House Minority
Leader Gilda Cobb-Hunter (D-Orangeburg) says a resolution could be
struck before the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is ready to end it, regardless of their position,''
Cobb-Hunter said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) O N T H E W E B : Flag history:
www.confederateflags.org/
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina legislature: www.leginfo.state.sc.us/
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) O N T H E W E B : Flag history:
www.confederateflags.org/
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina legislature: www.leginfo.state.sc.us/
</P>
