<HEADER>
A9339 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MEDICAL-DEVICES-BOS &LR;      05-08 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-DEVICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL DEVICE MAKERS, REGULATORS SEE IMPROVING RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ The uneasy relationship between the medical
device industry and its regulators is improving. But both sides
acknowledge &UR;  &LR; they still have a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to give us kudos, but everything ends up as
criticism,'' said Dr. Linda Suydam, the US Food and Drug
Administration's senior associate commissioner, who outlined some
of the structural changes for future agency and industry
interactions.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke Monday at the fourth annual conference of the
Massachusetts Medical Device Industry Council at the Westin hotel
here. Also speaking was Dr. Hugh Hill, director of the coverage and
analysis group at the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA),
which determines whether new products approved by the FDA are
effective and should be covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Suydam said the FDA has streamlined the approval process for
medical devices by permitting outside groups to help the agency
approve the products. The FDA also has an ombudsman to settle
issues between companies and the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But some Bay State device companies insist the approval process
is still marred by too much bureacracy and the FDA staff is either
not adquately equipped or trained to handle certain issues required
for agency approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think FDA has changed, but the approvals could be still be
done more effecively,'' said Thomas J. Sommer, executive director
of the state's 200-member medical device industry known as
MassMEDIC.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the biotechnology and pharmaceutical industries, which
nearly three years ago agreed to pay higher fees to the US Food and
Drug Administration to streamline the drug approval processes, the
medical device makers balked at hefty users fees. One result: drug
makers, once the FDA's loudest critics, are now among its boosters,
citing approvals have been shortened from three years to about a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Device companies argue they shouldn't be compared to the
drug-makers, since their products have short development life
cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Once products are approved by the FDA, medical device companies
complain HCFA is very slow in giving their approval. Several
executives said that, without HCFA approval, it is hard to sell
products that don't have insurance reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said HCFA is in the process of developing new guidelines
and procedures for device reimbursement that will be announced
shortly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
