A9340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLINTON-DISBAR-COX     05-08 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISBAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton foes reveal disbarment filings
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton admits he gave misleading testimony that was
morally wrong in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. But his
testimony was not ``false'' and his actions do not justify
disbarring him from the practice of law, according to defense court
filings made public Monday by a group trying to have the
president's law license revoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple moral truth (is) that his behavior in this matter
was wrong,'' Clinton's lawyers said in motions filed before the
Arkansas Supreme Court Committee on Professional Conduct. ``He
misled his wife, his friends and our nation about the nature of his
relationship with (Monica) Lewinsky.'' Lewinsky has admitted having
a sexual relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asserts his testimony was not ``false,'' only
intentionally misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Clinton's defense were made public Monday by the
Atlanta-based Southeastern Legal Foundation, which first filed a
complaint seeking to make Clinton the first sitting president to be
disbarred. The president's 80-page response to the Arkansas
committee has not been made public, but the foundation's reply to
Clinton's filing disclosed some of the president's defense. The
foundation released its filing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, strongly criticized the Atlanta
legal group Monday, saying it is not interested in issues related
to Arkansas lawyers and legal services. ``It's just interested in
attacking the president in any way it can,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   By disclosing some of Clinton's defense, Kendall said, the
foundation has engaged in ``just another part of the long-running
partisan mudslinging against the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also noted that former independent counsel Kenneth Starr
has helped the foundation raise money. Starr spoke at a foundation
event April 29 at the Cobb Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation President Matthew Glavin said Clinton's lawyers are
arguing against disbarment and suggest that a sanction ``no harsher
and perhaps more lenient than a letter of reprimand would be
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   In its court filing, the foundation noted that Arkansas rules
require lawyers in public office to maintain higher ethical
standards than other attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is no ordinary Arkansas lawyer,'' the foundation
said. ``It is especially important, in order to retain public
respect for the law and the courts, for lawyers holding public
office to avoid misconduct ... which would draw the law and lawyers
into disrepute.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing Clinton's response, the foundation said the president
``spends the bulk of his 80-page brief attempting to show that his
testimony was not `false,' as he defines that term.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas committee could consider disbarment proceedings
against Clinton at its May 18 meeting. It is considering two
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Legal Foundation, which filed its complaint in
September 1998, said Clinton should be disbarred because he lied
under oath and obstructed justice in the Paula Jones lawsuit. The
Arkansas committee also is considering a contempt citation issued
against the president by U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright,
who presided over the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's defense, his lawyers told the committee that
Clinton does not admit to giving ``false'' testimony during his
deposition in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's answers (were) ... an attempt to avoid a
flat-out admission that (Clinton and Lewinsky) were alone
together,'' the president's response said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also asserted that his testimony about his relations
with Lewinsky was immaterial and did no harm to the sexual
harassment lawsuit filed by Jones. Even if it did harm to the
lawsuit, the case was settled and Jones was compensated, Clinton's
filing said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
