<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA   SEEKS IMPROVED TRADE WITH NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you naturally think of Silicon Valley when someone
mentions the Internet, you're just who Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien wants to set straight.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like Nova Scotia to pop to mind. For information
technology? How about New Brunswick?
</P>
<P>
   Chretien, accompanied by executives from 40 companies in Eastern
Canada, was in Boston Sunday and Monday to try to convince New
England business owners and venture capitalists that Canada is not
just about salmon, oil, and timber anymore.
</P>
<P>
   While Canadian government officials have visited New England
frequently in recent years, it was the first time that Chretien had
led a regional trade mission. He was joined by the premiers of four
Atlantic provinces: New Brunswick, Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, and
Prince Edward Island.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to more than 500 business men and women at the Park
Plaza Hotel, Chretien's message was simple: Invest in Canada's
Atlantic provinces, where universities are graduating thousands of
new-economy workers and where doing business could soon cost less
than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is America's biggest trading partner. The relationship
between the two countries overshadows all others in the world, with
more than $1 billion worth of goods and services crossing the
border every day. But this business is far more important to
Canada, where US trade accounts for one-third of its gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   A small fraction of the goods are traded between the Atlantic
provinces and the New England states, about $3.3 billion worth in
1999. But most of the products imported by New England _ natural
resources such as fish, timber, and energy _ fall into the
old-economy category.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien argued that his country offers more, particularly in
the area of technology. Canada is hiring 2,000 new research chairs
at its public universities over the next five years, is the first
major country to connect all of its schools and libraries to the
Internet, and has the world's most advanced coast-to-coast
fiber-optic network, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with this innovative spirit, the prime minister promised
Canada will cut corporate taxes to make it a cheaper place to set
up shop.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Clancy, Canada's consul general in the region, said she is
concerned that with unemployment so low in New England,
electronics-savvy college graduates will start crossing the border
in droves.
</P>
<P>
   New Brunswick, for example, has 10 percent unemployment, and
10,000 men and women in their 20s left the province over the 10
years that ended in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes to convince US companies to build new plants to the
north. A trade group, Team Canada Atlantic, has also begun a pilot
project in Boston and Dallas to find out how best to ``brand''
Canada to attract American interest.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Hooper, a partner at the Boston venture capital firm
Advent International, said Canada has a lot of work to do. While
Toronto is known for its technology companies, ``I can't think of a
single technology company in the Maritimes to begin with,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses tend to invest based on the cluster theory, she said.
In other words, they gravitate to cities with good technological
universities and start-up companies with good management track
records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
