<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BIG-GAME-SHY-COX     05-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-GAME-SHY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius and Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not long after Katheryn and Paul Lowry of Norcross,
Ga., became the first Big Game winners of the millennium, people
with hard-luck tales began lining up to ask for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman wrote to say that she figured we would be buying new
vehicles, so could we please have your old ones?'' Ms. Lowry
recalled Monday. ``We didn't respond to any of the letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Those letters _ along with the FedEx packages and phone calls
from stockbrokers and investment advisors _ surely can be traced to
the press conference the Lowrys agreed to attend after they won the
$46 million Big Game drawing in the final hour of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had wanted to keep it as private as possible,'' Mrs. Lowery
said, who spent some of Monday washing the windows in her home.
``The lottery explained that they thought it would hold down the
media calling. We figured we'd do it and get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Most jackpot winners sense a direct tie between media exposure
and the number of people who will offer to help you spend your
money. Some winners have been extraordinarily shy in front of press
conference lights and expectant microphones. A few have refused to
attend press conferences at all.
</P>
<P>
   One pervious Big Game winner said it's best to avoid media
attention at all costs after collecting your winnings. But Georgia
Lottery CEO Rebecca Paul noted that lottery must _ when asked _
reveal the name and hometown of Big Game winners, though not their
address of phone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a $5 million jackpot, we don't do publicity if (the
winner) doesn't want it,'' Paul said. ``But even if John Smith who
lives in Atlanta wins the $325 million jackpot, one of you (in the
media) will find him and be on his doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we say to the winners is _ and I believe this _ it's
better to get it all done at once in a controlled setting rather
than have CNN parked in your driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   That take-your-medicine approach has worked out for the Lowrys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had only a few (media) calls since the press
conference,'' Ms. Lowry said. ``People have respected our privacy.
We have not been hounded.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lowrys still live in their three-bedroom home in Norcross
and never felt the need to change their listed telephone number.
Mrs. Lowry, 61, quit her job as a loan processor for a mortgage
company to join her husband in retirement. They plan to build a
summer cabin in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did buy new cars,'' she said. ``Nothing fancy, no Mercedes,
BMWs or Jaguars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lowrys opted to take their winnings in the form of a lump
sum cash payment of $22 million. They received an ``after-tax''
check for $14.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   That still leaves quite a nest egg for the couple, their six
kids and 15 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Even before they received their check, the Lowrys turned to a
CPA she'd worked with for years. He helped them with tax and estate
planning and screened investment brokers who wanted to make sales
pitches. They also hired an attorney, who taught them more about
trust funds and powers of attorney. They rewrote their wills.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband was a comptroller at a car dealership,'' Mrs. Lowry
said. ``I'd worked in financial services. We weren't ignorant of
what we needed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice for (for the next Big Game winner) is take your
time. There's no rush. You've got to do some planning.''
</P>
<P>
   If you win the lottery, here's some on advice on what to do
next:
</P>
<P>
   _ Find an accountant and an estate planning lawyer you are sure
you can trust.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you take you winnings in the form of 26 annual annuity
payments, consider whether you'd be better off to take the cash
option instead. Under a new law, you have 60 days from the date of
the drawing to ``cash out.'' (If you select the cash option at
first, you can't switch to an annuity.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the accountant or the lawyer to screen consultants, stock
brokers and others who will approach you with ideas for how to
invest your money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Renew your will and get serious about estate planning. (If you
take the annuity and die before annual payments cease, the balance
becomes part of your state and is mostly taxable. But your estate
probably won't have the cash to pay the tax due).
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep a low profile. The more you speak up on television or get
quoted in the newspaper, the more you can expect to be solicited
for a piece of your winnings.
</P>
<P>
   _ If solicitations are a problem, change your phone number or
get an unlisted number.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
