<HEADER>
A9347 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CARDINAL-FUNERAL-BOS &LR;      05-08 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINAL-FUNERAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL EULOGIZED IN FUNERAL RITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He liked to think of himself as a simple priest, and
in the end, his life was celebrated with the same funeral rite
accorded every Catholic, rich or poor, powerful or powerless.
</P>
<P>
   But that Rite of Christian Burial was accompanied by a degree of
pomp unusual even for princes of the church, a tribute to the
extraordinary visibility Cardinal John O'Connor enjoyed throughout
his 16 years as archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours Monday, the most powerful political combatants
in the United States _ President Bill Clinton and former President
George Bush, Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani
_ put aside their rivalries to join more than 3,000 Catholic clergy
and laity at St. Patrick's Cathedral in paying their respects to
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   In a spontaneous expression of appreciation reminiscent of the
cheers given O'Connor when he would complete celebrating solemn
Masses, the crowd packed into the cathedral burst into applause as
O'Connor left the sanctuary for the last time, his gleaming
mahogany casket escorted by his siblings and fellow cardinals
around the cathedral's aisles and down the marble steps into the
crypt beneath the sacristy where the bodies of archbishops of New
York are entombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our brother John has gone to his rest in the peace of
Christ,'' said Auxiliary Bishop Robert A. Brucato, the
administrator of the archdiocese of New York until Pope John Paul
II names a replacement, which could be Tuesday. ``Earth to earth,
ashes to ashes, dust to dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Bernard F. Law of Boston led the church elite in
celebrating O'Connor's life with a homily that provoked a
remarkable standing ovation when Law said, ``what a great legacy he
has left us in his constant reminder that the church must be
unambiguously pro-life.'' The sustained ovation, which appeared to
originate with a group of priests and then slowly to work its way
through the cathedral, clearly discomfited some of the elected
officials, some of whom support abortion rights and reluctantly
stood with the crowd but did not join in the applause.
</P>
<P>
   The 2 1/2-hour funeral capped five days of public mourning for
O'Connor, who died last Wednesday at the age of 80 after a long
battle against brain cancer. An estimated 150,000 people streamed
through the cathedral over the weekend, attending Masses and vigils
and filing silently by O'Connor's body.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral was open only to those who had obtained tickets, and
hundreds of people gathered on the steamy streets outside the
cathedral to participate as best they could. Streets running
alongside the cathedral were barricaded and law enforcement
officers patrolled inside and outside the cathedral because of the
number of dignitaries in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers and firefighters also packed the pews and joined
the procession into the church, in recognition of O'Connor's strong
ties to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best friend we had,'' said Sgt. Louis Rinaldi of
the Amtrak police force.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral, parts of which were planned by O'Connor himself,
acknowleged in several ways the cardinal's particular priorities.
The first reading, from the book of Wisdom, was given by a nun from
the Sisters of Life, an order O'Connor founded which has a mission
of opposing abortion and euthanasia. A second reading, from the
letter of Paul to the Colossians, was read from the Braille by a
visually impaired woman, because O'Connor had emphasized reaching
out to those who are disabled.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor spent much of his life as a priest working as a
military chaplain, and the funeral, like the daily Mass he
celebrated at St. Patrick's, ran with military precision.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance procession, led by a crossbearer and a thurifer
carrying incense, was packed with deacons, priests, bishops, honor
guards and others. The procession lasted nearly 40 minutes, as the
church dignitaries filed slowly down the center aisle, many pausing
to touch or kiss the casket shrouded in a white pall and topped
with an open Bible and a crucifix.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1:58 p.m., everyone had entered the church, allowing
Vatican Secretary of State Angelo Soldano, the emissary of Pope
John Paul II and the principal celebrant of the Mass, to greet the
crowd and begin the Mass for ``this kind churchman'' promptly as
scheduled at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic funerals do not feature eulogies, so Law sought in his
homily to use the gospel reading, about Jesus's last supper, as an
illustration of O'Connor's faith in the Eucharist and desire to
harness that faith to speak out on church teachings. Law, who was a
close friend of O'Connor and was at his deathbed last week,
recalled that even as O'Connor ceased being able to read or
converse, he could still recite from memory the Eucharistic prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Law acknowledged O'Connor's New York-style personality, saying
``God gifted him with a keen and subtle intellect, an uncommon
rhetorical skill, a knack for the dramatic gesture, a sharp wit and
an outrageous sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   But Law said O'Connor's reputation was built on his use of those
skills as a fierce advocate for life _ an advocacy that endeared
him to some and drew him criticism from others. Law, like the
Catholic church generally, used the word ``life'' broadly, to
encompass O'Connor's opposition to abortion, euthanasia and capital
punishment and as well as his support for the rights of workers and
for international peace.
</P>
<P>
   Law suggested that O'Connor's own decisions, in allowing his
brain cancer to run its course, was a testament to the church's
teachings on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he was dying last Wednesday, as a result of a disease with
terrible consequences, he bore witness one last time to the moral
evil of euthanasia and physician-assisted suicide,'' Law said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He preached most powerfully by his example the necessity of
seeing in every human being, from the first moment of conception to
the last momnet of natural death and every moment in between,
particularly the poor, the sick and the forgotten, the image of a
God to be loved and to be served.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
