<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9349 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LEWIS-MALPRACTICE-BOS     05-08 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-MALPRACTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING MALPRACTICE SUITS A CHALLENGE, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's a daunting statistic: Of all the medical
malpractice lawsuits that go to trial, 94 percent are won by
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, as a jury returned a favorable verdict for Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., concluding that the cardiologist was not
negligent in his care and treatment of the late Reggie Lewis, the
statistic seemed to hold true once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a plaintiff's point of view, medical malpractice cases
are the most difficult to win,'' said Boston attorney Andrew C.
Meyer Jr., who frequently represents plaintiffs in medical
malpractice cases.
</P>
<P>
   Even Neil Rossman, the lawyer for Donna Harris-Lewis, Lewis's
widow, acknowledged the challenge of convincing a jury that a
doctor provided substandard care. In comments to reporters after
Monday's verdict, Rossman said trying the case had been ``like
trying to push a boulder up a hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, plaintiffs who sue doctors face a rather high bar when
it comes to convincing a jury that a doctor was negligent.
</P>
<P>
   In medical malpractice cases, jurors are told that it is not
enough to find simply that a doctor made a mistake; they must find
that the care deviated from ``acceptable standards of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   And many attorneys say that conclusion can be difficult to reach
when a panel of jurors -- few, if any, with medical degrees -- are
asked to evaluate testimony that delves into complex, confusing
medical issues.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the mix expert witnesses who frequently offer conflicting
testimony and a jury's task becomes even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In Mudge's case, for example, his lawyers brought in numerous
consulting physicians who supported Mudge's diagnosis, including
two cardiologists who were cleared of negligence in the first
trial. Rossman, meanwhile, put several witnesses on the stand who
criticized Mudge's care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors are always capable of bringing in colleagues to defend
their conduct under almost any circumstances,'' said Meyer, ``and
that makes it very difficult for a jury to determine if a doctor is
negligent.''
</P>
<P>
   Many malpractice attorneys also say that juries tend to be
reluctant to deliver verdicts against doctors, particularly in a
place like Boston, where the city's medical community is held in
particularly high regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the medicine is so far above them, and they're hearing
differing opinions about what was done right and what was done
wrong,'' Meyer said, ``how can jurors possibly come to the
conclusion that a doctor's conduct was below the standard of
care?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to that question is that jurors often can't.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 94 percent figure -- which represents only medical
malpractice cases that go to trial -- tells only part of the story.
Roughly half of all medical malpractice lawsuits nationally are
settled before trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that it's very difficult for plaintiffs to win
medical malpractices cases at trial,'' Boston attorney James P.
McCarthy said. ``But a substantial percentage of cases settle prior
to trial through mediation, sometimes with very substantial
multi-million-dollar settlements.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical malpractice cases most likely to yield a verdict on
a plaintiff's behalf are those that a jury can understand without
medical evidence, such as operating on the wrong leg, giving
extreme overdoses of medications, and other kinds of outrageous
conduct, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Mudge, on the other hand, ``was a very
sophisticated diagnosis and an extremely complex case,'' McCarthy
said. ``And juries tend to give benefit of doubt to doctors in
those cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LOCKHEED-COX     05-08 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed workers to file suit
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of black workers has rejected Lockheed Martin's
overtures to settle their discrimination complaints, making a
high-profile court clash likely for the aerospace manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Workers Against Discrimination, a group of current and former
workers, has scheduled a news conference for today outside Lockheed
Martin Aeronautics Company in Marietta to announce plans for a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys Alexander, Hezekiah Sistrunk, an Atlanta class-action
expert, and Johnnie Cochran, the nationally renowned lawyer, expect
to file suit this week asking a court to certify them to represent
black workers at Lockheed plants nationwide in a racial
discrimination class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit will target both Lockheed and the workers' union,
said Josie Alexander, an attorney for the workers. Alexander said
that the union betrays them by giving lukewarm help in pursuing
complaints about discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   A ``good ol' boy culture'' exists in both management and in the
International Association of Machinists &AMP; Aerospace Workers,
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a minimum the union has acquiesced in the discrimination
and has failed to assist and to adequately represent the
grievances,'' Alexander said. ``Race is a criteria that is used by
Lockheed to eliminate African-Americans. They are not promoted at
the same rate or under the same circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gable, vice president of the union's Local Lodge No. 709,
has said previously that the discrimination complaints would not go
through the union because they didn't involve its contract with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Lockheed, Cobb County's largest private employer,
said the company made a good-faith settlement offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly have worked hard at trying to reach an agreeable
situation,'' said Terry Graham, executive vice president and chief
operating officer. ``Our job is to generate the kind of culture
that is conducive to everyone in the workplace, and I think we have
that kind of culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Xxxxg xxxxg xxxxg
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
