<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LODIGAN-COX     05-08 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LODIGAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shareholder to build support to buy Lodigan
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Battle lines are deepening between Lodgian Inc. and one of its
largest shareholders over continued efforts to buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, William
J. Yung, president of Kentucky-based Edgecliff Holdings Inc., which
owns 11 percent of Lodgian's stock, has asked fellow shareholders
to support his effort to elect up to three nominees to the board of
directors at the next annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Those nominees ``are expected to strongly advocate the sale of
the company to the highest bidder, whether to us or to any
competing bidder,'' Yung said in the filing last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the company's largest stockholder, we have grown
increasingly dissatisfied with the company's performance over the
past year,'' Yung said in the filing. ``Although we have made
repeated overtures to acquire the company in a transaction that
would give stockholders an opportunity to recognize a substantial
premium on their shares, the company has consistently rejected our
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Lodgian Chief Executive Robert S. Cole said Yung is ``doing what
he thinks is the right tactic. ... There's no surprise, this is old
news.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has not set a date for its annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC letter also asks shareholder support for a proposal to
prevent the board from adopting bylaw amendments that would impair
an effort to buy the company. Edgecliff has sued Lodgian in a
Delaware court seeking to clear the way to elect three board
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that he is pursing any and all remedies to obtain
board seats,'' said Paul D. Puryear, an analyst with Raymond James
in St. Petersburg, Fla. ``This is just another step in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgecliff, controlled by Yung, has made two proposals to acquire
Lodgian. Lodgian's board has hired Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to
review alternatives, including a possible sale. The company is also
in the process of selling some hotels to reduce debt.
</P>
<P>
   Lodgian owns and operates about 127 hotels in several states and
Canada. Lodgian is a major franchisee of Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts and
Marriott International chains.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2006EDT &QL; 
