<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SCIATLANTA-TV-COX     05-08 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIATLANTA-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta plans TV photos
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine sitting in your living room looking at the latest batch
of family photos. But there's not a photo album in sight. Just a
digital image on the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   Norcross-based Scientific-Atlanta and Eastman Kodak, the world's
largest photography company, agreed Monday to develop a system for
displaying photographs on television sets without using a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Cable subscribers will be able to share photos with distant
family and friends, transporting them over the cable network to a
secure Web server where they can be viewed by computer users and
cable subscribers alike. While personal computers are routinely
used to share digital images, the idea of using the family TV is
brand new.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for the service in Atlanta, at least for now.
MediaOne, Atlanta's major cable TV provider, does not use
Scientific-Atlanta cable boxes, according to spokesman Reg Griffin.
However, Kodak says the deal is nonexclusive, and similar deals
probably will be struck with other set-top box manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Any cable subscriber with a Scientific-Atlanta digital broadband
Explorer box will be able to send pictures from a digital camera
directly to a distant computer on the cable network through a
connection in the cable box. Louise Wasilewski, Scientific-Atlanta
director of business development, said about 1.5 million Explorer
boxes are in use. However, she said the actual market is 30 million
homes _ that's the number of homes located in areas served by cable
systems using Scientific-Atlanta equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak and Scientific-Atlanta expect to make money from service
fees, photofinishing and advertising sales. No fee structure has
been set yet. Scientific-Atlanta makes broadband access equipment
that has allowed cable operators to deliver more channels and
provide digital services such as this one.
</P>
<P>
   Wasilewski says the company will begin trials with Kodak this
fall to make sure the digital photo system works smoothly before
it's rolled out to cable systems across the country. No sites have
been set for the test.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Brumlow, director of worldwide business development for
Kodak, says that the cable-photo arrangement will bring digital
images back into the living room for people to share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits the paradigm of memories and families,'' he said.
``There are people using digital image services, and they want to
send those pictures to Mom. Mom may not have a PC, but she does
have a digital cable modem. That's a great value proposition,'' he
said. ``It really grows the market for digital cameras, since all
you have to do is plug the camera into the cable box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers really want to participate in the sharing and
posting of their own photographs,'' said Jupiter Communications
analyst Lydia Loizides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Photos are an extremely personal and expressive way for people
to share memories, especially as we bring the Internet into it,''
she said. ``It's a very quick and effortless way to store images.
It's a few steps up from the shoebox. In practical terms for
longevity _ film and negatives are fragile and this is a way for
people to store their photos long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Loizides says the advent of broadband has little to do with the
growing demand for posting pictures to the Web or the TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the ice cream on the cake,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fulfills an intangible need to create, to share and to
publish. Grandma in Utah will wait 20 minutes to see a picture of
the precious grandbaby's first birthday. It's the definition of
compelling content.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
