<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-KILLER (Houston) _ Attorneys for railroad-riding
drifter Angel Maturino Resendiz acknowledge that he was responsible
for nine murders in three states and entered a plea of innocent by
reason of insanity. Maturino Resendiz is charged with the December
1998 rape-slaying of a Houston physician, Dr. Claudia Benton.
Prosecutors have said they will seek the death penalty. By LISA
TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   CHROMOSOME-MAPPING (Undated) _ In an achievement that could help
develop treatments for a host of illnesses, scientists have mapped
chromosome 21, the smallest human chromosome and the one associated
with Down syndrome, epilepsy, Lou Gehrig's disease and Alzheimer's.
It is the second human chromosome to be fully deciphered;
chromosome 22 was mapped last fall. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-SALARY (Houston)_ After being recruited by such big-time
districts as New York and Los Angeles, Houston Superintendent Rod
Paige has been given a big-time raise. Paige's new salary of
$275,000, which takes effect July 1, is believed to be the highest
of any superintendent in the nation. By MELANIE MARKLEY.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-ERRORS (Washington) _ In the wake of congressional
hearings on a disturbing report that up to 98,000 people die every
year in U.S. hospitals because of medical errors, government,
business and health experts assess what is being done to solve the
problem and what more needs to be done. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN-TEXAS (AUSTIN) _ Reform Party presidential hopeful Pat
Buchanan files petitions to get his candidacy on the Texas ballot,
which would further solidify his grip on the front-runner status
for the party nomination. Buchanan would be the only Reform Party
candidate to qualify for the ballot in Texas by today's deadline,
replicating his earlier successes in Utah and South Dakota. By
JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-VOTE (Washington) _ A new group called Youth-e-Vote
announces it will offer schoolchildren across the country a chance
to vote for president, governor and members of Congress in online
mock balloting this fall. Officials say they expect about 10
million of the nation's 53 million students to vote in what the
organizers hope will be a huge electronic civics lesson. By AUSTIN
ZALKIN. Story also will be filed in the WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'')
category. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS NEWS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NBA-ROOKIE (Houston) _ Steve Francis of the Houston Rockets will
be named co-Rookie of the Year later this week along with Elton
Brand of the Chicago Bulls. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   BLINEBURY-COLUMN (Undated) _ A look at Steve Francis and the NBA
Rookie of the year award. By FRAN BLINEBURY.
</P>
<P>
   ASTROS-ROCKIES (Houston) _ Returning home after their longest
road trip of the season, the Houston Astros play host to the
Colorado Rockies in the opener of a three-game series at Enron
Field. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   ROBERTSON-COLUMN (Houston) _ A look at the Astros-Rockies game.
By DALE ROBERTSON.
</P>
