<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-SHAARA-AZR &LR;      05-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAARA-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-SHAARA-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    JEFF SHAARA PICKS UP FATHER'S PEN (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, no matter where you hide, destiny finds you.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Jeff Shaara, who was a rare-coin dealer when his father
died in 1988. Though his dad had written a Pulitzer Prize-winning
book on the Civil War ((beginitalic)The Killer Angels(enditalic)),
Jeff had never shown any interest in writing.
</P>
<P>
   That would soon change.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Michael Shaara's death, the popularity of
historical fiction was surging, fueled by Ken Burns' sweeping
documentary (beginitalic)The Civil War(enditalic)(beginitalic).
(enditalic)In 1993, (beginitalic)The Killer Angels (enditalic)was
made into the Turner film (beginitalic)Gettysburg(enditalic), and
the movie's director suggested that Jeff find someone to write a
sequel and a prequel.
</P>
<P>
   He found someone all right - himself. Two bestsellers later,
Jeff Shaara is still surprised at his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people asked me, how did I get the courage to sit
down and write,'' said Shaara, who will be in Phoenix on May 17 to
promote his new novel, (beginitalic)Gone For Soldiers(enditalic).
``It really didn't take courage, because I had no expectations
{hellip} that any publisher would take this.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaara knows he'll be known as the son of Michael Shaara, whose
book was recognized as a masterpiece when it was published in 1974
but never enjoyed commercial success. Jeff said his first two
books, (beginitalic)Gods and Generals (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)The Last Full Measure, (enditalic)both of which are
headed to the big screen, were simply the continuation of his
father's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was writing (beginitalic)Gods and Generals (enditalic)I
showed the manuscript to my sister, and she said, `This is being
written by the ghost of Michael Shaara,''' Jeff said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's proud when people compare his style to his father's
but that he never set out to imitate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that works,'' Shaara said. ``Then it becomes all
style and no substance. {hellip} The voice has to come from
somewhere else. I think, certainly, I've been influenced by my
father's style, there's no doubt about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it a great compliment when somebody tells me they
see similarities in my style and my father's.''
</P>
<P>
   To produce the Shaara brand of historical fiction, both Jeff and
his dad put the reader into the minds of historical figures,
re-creating conversations during key meetings and battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hearing their thoughts and hearing their words,''
Shaara said. ``By definition, that's fiction. There was nobody
walking around behind these guys with a pad and paper writing down
everything they said.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some have criticized the re-creation technique, Jeff said
all the work is based on months of research. Shaara pored over
memoirs and eyewitness accounts to re-create history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those meetings are real. {hellip} Any of the commanders in the
book could have said any of the words that I'm putting in their
mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   In what many see as a break with his father, Shaara's new book
is not about the Civil War. Instead, he chose the Mexican-American
War, in which future Civil War commanders like Ulysses S. Grant,
Robert E. Lee and Thomas ``Stonewall'' Jackson first learned the
art of combat. At that time, the two future Confederate generals
were fighting in the same uniform as Grant under the same Union
flag.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, (beginitalic)Gone for Soldiers
(enditalic)(named for a verse in the Pete Seeger song
(beginitalic)Where Have All the Flowers Gone?(enditalic)) is the
story of two opposing generals, War of 1812 hero Winfield Scott of
the United States and Mexico's Antonio Lopez de Santa Ana.
</P>
<P>
   To get inside their heads, Shaara found Scott's unpublished
memoirs at West Point and consulted Santa Ana's memoirs, which were
recently translated into English.
</P>
<P>
   Shaara said the Mexican-American War (1846-48) often is
overlooked. Though it allowed the United States to acquire most of
what is now Arizona, New Mexico and California, its short duration
and proximity to the Civil War make it a footnote in most history
books.
</P>
<P>
   There are also strong parallels with Vietnam, Shaara notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was seen as a bully's war, (that) basically we were going
down there to grab land,'' Shaara said. ``The themes are similar.
You have this big muscular country going down and beating on these
little guys. You had a lot of that in Vietnam. There was also the
sense that the soldiers were unappreciated back home.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Bill.Muller(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8178.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)
</P>
