<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, May 9. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ As he scrambled on several
fronts to stave off the collapse of the U.N. peacekeeping mission
in Sierra Leone, Secretary-General Kofi Annan met here with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who indicated afterward that
the United States might help transport reinforcements to the
unstable West African country. By Christopher S. Wren. (We plan to
move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars, map inside.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to UN-CONGO.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila, Philippines) _ Philippine law
enforcement agents stage a raid on a Manila apartment from which
they said a malicious computer program was unleashed last week,
disrupting computer systems around the world. They took one
resident into custody and ordered his roommate, a woman, to turn
herself in. The authorities apparently traced a telephone line to
the apartment. By Seth Mydans. (Eds.: an early version of this
story has moved; a 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead 4-column photo reefer to:
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR (New York) _ Cardinal John Joseph O'Connor, the eighth
archbishop of New York, whose wit and uncompromising eloquence made
him the Vatican's most visible leader in the United States, is
entombed beneath the altar of St. Patrick's Cathedral after a
ceremony almost ethereal in its pageantry and music. By Diana Jean
Schemo. (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; a
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-TRADE (Washington) _ After a bill-signing ceremony in the
Oval Office last month, President Clinton sidled up to an unlikely
ally in his fight to pass a decisive trade bill with China, the
administration's top foreign policy goal. ``We talked about what
each of us has to do and we gave each other some advice,'' said
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip and one of
Clinton's most vitriolic critics on Capitol Hill. With the crucial
vote just over two weeks away, DeLay finds himself in the
improbable role of the president's chief water-carrier and
potential legacy-builder in an all-out battle to grant China
permanent normal trading privileges. By Eric Schmitt. (Scheduled to
move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo reefer to:
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-AUCTION (Undated) _ On April 28, a California man who uses
the handle ``golfpoorly'' put a half-dozen items up for sale on
eBay, the online auction company. Along with an unopened roll of
twine, a never inflated basketball, a Mexican voodoo mask, a
Netgear network card and a pewter frame, he offered a ``great big
wild abstract painting.'' He asked for bids to open at a quarter.
On Monday bids for that painting, which may be a 1952 work by
Richard Diebenkorn, were up to $135,605. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRON-POLICY (Washington) _ The Clinton administration is
preparing to release a major environmental initiative. By Douglas
Jehl. (Scheduled to move by 9:15 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECT (Mexico City) _ By all accounts, this year's
presidential race is the fairest and most open Mexico has ever
seen. Voting conditions have never seemed more fair, but questions
are still being raised about the July 2 presidential election. By
Sam Dillon and Julia Preston. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to inside Business story:
</P>
<P>
   AD-AGENCY-MERGER _ Young &AMP; Rubicam, a Madison Avenue icon that
gave the world the Jell-O jingle and the numbered Excedrin
headaches, ends 77 years of independence by agreeing to a $5.7
billion takeover from London-based rival WPP Group, the largest
deal in the history of the advertising industry. By Andrew Ross
Sorkin. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars inside.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE (Washington) _ President Clinton has pleaded
with an Arkansas disciplinary panel not to take away his law
license, arguing that he has been a good public servant and
insisting again that he did not technically lie before a federal
judge, according to court papers filed by his opponents. By Neil A.
Lewis. (The story has moved in ``w'' news file.) 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JEWS-DIASPORA (Undated) _ Following the trail left in the Y
chromosome, geneticists chart the Jewish diaspora. By Nicholas
Wade. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   TONY-NOMINEES (New York) _ In the Tony Award nominations, a
struggling new musical, ``The Wild Party,'' won seven nominations
and a mother and daughter were pitted against one another in the
leading actress category. By Robin Pogrebin. (The story has moved
in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
