<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BIZMAGS-COX     05-08 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cisco chief executive No. 1 in Worth's annual ranking
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco Systems and its chief executive, John Chambers, are
rapidly replacing Microsoft and Chairman Bill Gates on the covers
of America's business press.
</P>
<P>
   Worth (May) says Chambers was the ``clear choice'' as No. 1 CEO
atop its annual list of the 50 best chief executives. He already
has created more wealth than investor Warren Buffett and will
likely surpass Gates this year, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers' portrait also adorns the cover of Fortune (May 22),
whose editor at large, Andy Serwer, says Chambers put together a
``corporate machine'' that enabled Cisco to create more than $400
billion in shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Barron's (May 8-12) to throw cold water on Cisco,
which it describes as ``the most successful company in the hottest
sector of the Internet economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barron's also calls it ``a modern house of cards'' whose
policy of growth by acquisition ``carries with it the seeds of
self-destruction'' by constantly bidding the price of its targets
higher and higher.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, two Georgia CEOs are on Worth's Top 50 list:
Arthur Blank of Home Depot at No. 8 and James Kelly of United
Parcel Service at No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Where the whammy is
</P>
<P>
   The premier edition of Fortune's new e-magazine _ eCompany Now
(June) _ offers advice on ``the people you need to see in Atlanta''
to get things done.
</P>
<P>
   Dean of the ``new economy'' is John Imlay, 63, who saved
Management Science America and sold it to Dun &AMP; Bradstreet in 1990.
More than 50 MSA employes have become CEOs of other firms.
</P>
<P>
   The others are attorney John Yates, 43, a partner at Morris
Manning and Martin; Bert Ellis, 46, founder of the Internet
services firm iXL Enterprises; Jeff Arnold, 30, whose WebMD was
merged into Healtheon in a $5.5 billion deal; venture capitalist
Alan Taetle, 36, of Noro-Moseley Partners; and Jeff Levy, 36, who
hosts prospective entrepreneurs at his incubator firm, eHatchery,
twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   The case for a crash
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing 100 years of data, two authors think there's a
67 percent chance of a stock market crash in the coming year, says
Business Week (May 15).
</P>
<P>
   According to London economic consultant Andrew Smithers and
Cambridge University professor Stephen Wright, the stock market
value of all U.S. companies has stretched far beyond the fair value
of the companies' net assets. When that has happened in the past
(Wall Street, 1929; Tokyo, 1989), they said stock prices snapped
with terrible consequences in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   What should investors do with their money? ``Put it into cash,''
they advise.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is out with a summer special, a ``Best of the Web''
edition that lists hundreds of computer sites for investors,
consumers and executives.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Investor (June) says ``old economy'' stocks are not
the safe haven panicky investors think they are. The theory:
Technology stocks will do better because that's where real economic
growth is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
