<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-DELAY-TRADE-NYT &LR;      05-08 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRADE BILL BRINGS TOGETHER TWO UNLIKELY ALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a bill-signing ceremony at the White House a
few weeks ago, President Clinton pulled aside an unlikely ally in
his fight to win approval for a decisive trade measure with China,
the administration's top foreign policy goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about what each of us has to do and we gave each
other some advice,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House
majority whip and perhaps Clinton's most venomous critic on Capitol
Hill, who refused to divulge details of the private chat in his
rare visit to the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   With the crucial vote just two weeks away, DeLay, who led the
charge to impeach Clinton, now finds himself in the improbable role
of the president's chief water-carrier and potential legacy-builder
in an all-out battle to grant China permanent normal trading
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   If the China measure succeeds, and right now the vote is too
close to call, it will be largely with the support of Republicans,
who are expected to deliver about 150 of the 218 votes needed to
pass it. The measure would allow American companies to benefit
fully from a market-opening accord that paves the way for China to
enter the World Trade Organization. Approval by the Senate appears
more certain.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Clinton needs DeLay, who as the chief Republican vote
counter, brings the power of his vaunted House whip operation as
well as his own widely acclaimed _ and feared _ brass-knuckle
tactics that have earned him the nickname ``The Hammer.'' (``If we
get within four or five votes, we can break some arms on the
floor,'' said one of DeLay's advisers.)
</P>
<P>
   DeLay insists his personal distaste for Clinton, whom he
criticized recently as ``lacking the necessary moral authority to
protect U.S. interests in the world,'' is not clouding his
professional task at hand: rounding up votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a fundamental disagreement with this president about
how he's done his job, but when he's doing something I think is
important I'm going to support him, because he doesn't do it very
often,'' DeLay said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay has even gone out of his way to praise the president's
efforts to rally support for the measure. DeLay's chief of staff,
Susan B. Hirschmann, consults regularly with the chief White House
lobbyist, Charles M. Brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a good job, and the president's done a very good
job,'' DeLay said. ``He's done exactly what a president should do
in getting his points across.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-DeLay connection is just one of the odd alignments
spawned from the fight, which has labor unions and conservative
religious groups opposing the measure and soybean farmers and
high-tech executives backing it.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the measure grew on Monday. Alan Greenspan, chairman
of the Federal Reserve, publicly endorsed it. Three former
presidents, Gerald R. Ford, Jimmy Carter and George Bush, issued a
letter coordinated by the White House warning that defeat ``would
be read in China as a vote for confrontation and as an argument for
hunkering down, instead of continuing to reach out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some colleagues say DeLay is singing the White House's praises
through clenched teeth, and is consoling himself that helping to
hand Clinton a crowning legislative triumph will cheer the
pro-Republican business community and undermine Beijing's communist
government.
</P>
<P>
   If it is strange to see DeLay and Clinton teaming up, it is
equally strange for the third-ranking House Republican to support a
measure that China passionately wants.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a fierce anti-communist, is the chief author of the
Taiwan Security Enhancement Act, a bill the House passed this year
to strengthen military ties between Taiwan and the Pentagon, which
Beijing strongly opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was DeLay's encounter last spring with China's
ambassador, Li Zhao Xing, offstage at NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him: `Don't take the weakness of this American
president as the weakness of the American people,' '' DeLay
recounted recently to a group of Washington Post reporters and
editors. ``He looked at me kind of funny, so I pulled him real
close, nose to nose, and I repeated it, very slowly. He just turned
and kind of walked off.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the studio, DeLay said the ambassador stopped
criticizing the United States and ``scooted off'' when the lawmaker
walked up. ``It shows you that if you stand up to a bully, then you
control the bully,'' DeLay said. ``If you kowtow to the bully, the
bully will run your life forever. And that's the way I see these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese Embassy official said the ambassador had no idea who
DeLay was, and until he read about the incident, thought he had
been accosted by an ordinary American. The two men met later to
discuss the China trade bill, and there were ``no hard feelings,''
the embassy aide said.
</P>
<P>
   So why does DeLay support a measure that his Moral Enemies No. 1
and No. 2 crave so badly? ``Exporting American values undermines
the communist regime in China,'' DeLay explained in the interview.
``Free-market principles, entrepreneurship, the Internet, all these
institutions reflect American values. I see it as a beginning of
the end of communism.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said he also distinguishes the Beijing government from
ordinary Chinese people. ``They have tasted the sweet taste of
freedom and they're not going to give it back,'' DeLay said in a
speech last week.
</P>
<P>
   But corporate lobbyists have always viewed DeLay's commitment to
trade with China with some suspicion. In a speech on March 16,
DeLay underscored his support for normalizing trade relations with
China, but he also warned that the status might be revoked if trade
ever strengthened the Beijing government rather than weakened it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should never be fooled into cheering higher profits while
Communist China harnesses that prosperity to construct an arsenal
of tyranny,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why many business lobbyists who have met DeLay recently
have been struck by his fervor. ``This man sounded like a true
believer,'' said one leading lobbyist. ``He talked about kicking
butt.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, DeLay and his vote-counters, as well as other top
Republican supporters outside the whip team like Rep. David Dreier
of California, will try to get a firm head count among their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been longing for an opportunity to work with the
president on something other than one of his scandals,'' Rep. Todd
Tiahrt, a Kansas Republican on the whip team who backs the measure,
said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   For now, DeLay is silent on any predictions _ saying only that
the next two weeks ``will be very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the whip of the House,'' DeLay said. ``It's my
responsibility to get the votes to achieve our agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
