<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEGAN-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-KEEGAN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    COULD ARIZONA'S LISA GRAHAM KEEGAN CUT IT AS EDUCATION
SECRETARY(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: moving in ``A'' and ``K'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KELLY PEARCE(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Todd Bankofier, vice president of the Arizona Board of
Education, jokingly referred to her as ``Secretary Keegan'' during
a recent board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``Secretary,'' as in Secretary of Education Lisa Graham
Keegan of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Some think it has a certain ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   Two influential magazine columnists, including George Will in
(beginitalic)Newsweek(enditalic), have mentioned Keegan, the
state's superintendent of public instruction, as a possible U.S.
Education secretary if George W. Bush is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Few now think the suggestion is far-fetched. In fact, all this
talk about Keegan's candidacy has Arizona folks wondering: Is she
qualified?
</P>
<P>
   The nation's top education post, now inhabited by Richard Riley,
is massive. The U.S. Education secretary is in charge of 175
programs and a $38 billion budget. The federal government pumps
money into such areas as bilingual education, lunches for
low-income students and classroom technology.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan-watchers have mixed views on whether she's ready to
ascend to the federal level. The complicated, well-spoken and
intelligent woman who moved to the state's top education job in
1994 after dabbling in politics in the Legislature has many allies
- and just as many detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Some like Keegan's stance on state testing and the fact that she
so quickly attached Arizona's Instrument to Measure Standards to a
high school diploma. They applaud her for cultivating charter
schools, which are publicly and privately funded schools that are
meant to inspire competition and encourage district schools to do a
better job.
</P>
<P>
   And they say she could take her successes in Arizona onto the
national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, say Keegan's alternative education system is
weakening public education rather trying to fix the problems from
within. They say she isolates those whom her state job is designed
to support, mainly teachers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   And all of this is happening as Arizona continues to land at the
bottom nationally when it comes to its high dropout rate, low
teacher salaries and per-pupil funding.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan is flattered by what she calls all of the ``pundits'
stuff.'' Her staff members were quick to fax the
(beginitalic)Newsweek(enditalic) column to local media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of a fifth-grade son and second-grade daughter at
Kiva Elementary School in the Scottsdale Unified School District
acknowledges that she's not loved by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   She's willing to admit that the education system has flaws.
That's the only way to begin the process of change, Keegan said.
But that type of attitude has a tendency to offend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fuzzy about opinions,'' Keegan said. ``You have to be
critical of the way things are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it bothers her when folks charge that she's trying to
dismantle public education. Just because she supports private
schools doesn't mean she's anti-public education, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My definition of public education is education that's
supported by the public, by which the child benefits,'' Keegan
said. ``So much of public education is private enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Love her or not, folks agree that Keegan has demonstrated
nimbleness and political savvy in recent months, gliding
effortlessly from Sen. John McCain's camp, where she spent at least
a week on the campaign trail, into the good graces of Bush after
McCain dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret she's hungry for a job in Washington, D.C., a
city she frequents. In 1994, she founded the Education Leaders
Council, a group of reform-minded education chiefs in eight states.
</P>
<P>
   Her national speaking engagements run from Harvard University to
the National Press Club to, most recently, a weekly gathering of
Republican senators. She's also been to Argentina twice to talk
about charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   While state Sen. Chris Cummiskey, D-central Phoenix, may not
agree with Keegan's support of vouchers and other conservative
ideas, he does admit she possesses attributes that make her a good
candidate for U.S. Education secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very articulate and good at expressing her perspective
on education,'' he said. ``She's willing to have a thoughtful
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the talk about Keegan, it may be premature to start
taking her national press notices too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Bush campaign officials are mum on the matter,
saying it's premature until the Republican National Convention
rolls around this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no list at this point,'' spokesman Scott McClellan
said. ``The governor will think about that in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan, who is 40 years old and has lived in the state since she
was 3, doesn't spend much time dwelling on her critics. She is
spending her time working on ideas for her job description, should
she find herself in the Bush Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan said she would revise the way federal money goes to the
