<HEADER>
A9366 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      05-08 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' and ``L'' CATEGORIES) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   ``PLAIN TRUTH''
</P>
<P>
   By Jodi Picoult
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Picoult's latest novel reads like a cross between the Harrison
Ford movie ``Witness ``and Scott Turow's novel ``Presumed
Innocent,'' with a dose of television's ``The Practice'' thrown in
to spice up the legal dilemmas. An Amish teenager named Katie
Fisher is accused of murdering her newborn child after hiding her
pregnancy from her parents and her Amish boyfriend (he's not the
father). Philadelphia lawyer Ellie Hathaway takes her case and
moves in with Katie's family for the duration of the trial, giving
Picoult the descriptive fodder of Amish life (especially
interesting is her portrayal of the austere Aaron Fisher, Katie's
father). When Ellie's old flame, a psychiatrist, comes to evaluate
Katie, he stays on for another romantic go-round with Ellie. It's
all appealing, suspenseful reading, despite unbelievable courtroom
antics and a final scene that is meant as a surprise but reads like
an afterthought. Picoult, who lived among the Amish to research her
book, portrays them unsentimentally but compassionately. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   THE ONION'S FINEST NEWS REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   (Three Rivers, $16)
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to ``The Onion,'' that shameless parody of print
journalism, to badmouth Special Olympians, to suggest that we
prefer Oprah's Book Club because the Drew Carey Book Club is too
challenging, to publish a guest column by JonBenet Ramsey. In other
news, we learn that Mother Teresa was sent to hell in a ``wacky
afterlife mix-up,'' that nine people were drawn and quartered at a
Renaissance Fair, that a new study proves human babies are not
inquisitive but are ``actually extraordinarily stupid.'' Last year
some very serious people published very serious books about the
major events of the 19th century, but ``The Onion'' came along and
aced them all with ``Our Dumb Century: 100 Years of Headlines From
America's Finest News Source.'' Is this book as funny as that one?
No, but it's close enough if you observe the ground rules: Always
remember that nothing is sacred (hence the photo of Christopher
Reeve and his chair bolted to the top of the Washington Monument),
and good taste is checked at the door.
</P>
<P>
   NEWJACK
</P>
<P>
   By Ted Conover
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Someone should write a book about Ted Conover - or maybe, in a
strange way, he has done it himself many times. His work is
sometimes called ``participatory journalism,'' but that, especially
in this case, seems inadequate to describe it. He has ridden trains
with hoboes in one book (''Rolling Nowhere''), travelled with
illegal aliens in another (''Coy(beginitalic)o(enditalic)tes'') and
mixed with Aspen's elite in ``Whiteout.'' But nothing engages
Conover's imagination like a prison. He tried to get into one as a
journalist, but was turned down, so he went in as a recruit and
spent a year as a corrections officer in Sing Sing, one of the
nation's most troubled maximum-security prisons (the title of his
book is the term for a novice officer). This is his fascinating
look at a disturbing place - every day, he writes, ``your stomach
lets you know, just before the shift starts, what it thinks of this
job'' - and the men who coexist there. It's a revealing book by one
of the most daring and compassionate journalists working today.
</P>
<P>
   KATIE.COM
</P>
<P>
   By Katherine Tarbox
</P>
<P>
   (Dutton, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you may be bored hearing so much about my hair, but
this is what matters when you are 13,'' writes Tarbox. ``Besides,
my hair was the only part of my body that I liked.'' The portrait
Tarbox paints of herself as a Connecticut 13-year-old is indeed
boring, and full of an adolescent's obsession with her flaws. and
her family's shortcomings. It might all be depressingly average,
except for one thing. In a teen chat room on American Online,
Tarbox met a boy named Mark, who was friendly and made good
conversation. They kept in touch, and their friendship began to
seem like destiny. Eventually he flew to Texas to meet her when she
was in Dallas for a swim meet, but there is nothing romantic about
what happened between them in his hotel room. Katie narrowly
escaped disaster, and, after learning from police that Mark was 41,
she and her mother pressed charges against him. This is a story
every parent should read, a cautionary tale about the importance of
love and, more importantly, vigilance. There's nothing boring about
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
