<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9371 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CD-HANSON09-COX     05-08 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-HANSON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hanson leaves boy-band days in the dust
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't call them a boy band.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Hanson has in common with the Backstreet Boys, 'N
Sync and their ilk is frequent appearances in Tiger Beat magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hanson didn't ask to be idolized by teenage girls,
and the trio's major-label debut album, ``Middle of Nowhere,''
sounded nothing like the music of contemporary boy bands, either.
This follow-up finds them moving even further from boy-band
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The young Oklahoma-born siblings took three years to follow up
the success of ``Middle of Nowhere'' and its hit single,
``MMMBop.'' A lot happens in a teenager's life in three years.
Isaac, Taylor and Zac Hanson and their fans have changed since
1997, and you have to wonder whether they've grown together or
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Time Around'' makes it clear that Hanson has grown in the
direction of 1970s FM-radio rock.
</P>
<P>
   Album opener ``You Never Know'' and first single ``This Time
Around'' wouldn't have sounded out of place between Stories'
``Brother Louie'' and Billy Preston's ``Will It Go 'Round in
Circles'' on the radio in 1973. Make no mistake, though, they would
have been just as massive as those two were. Hooks are timeless,
and Hanson fills these songs with more than you'll find in your
average bait shop.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the catchy tunes, Hanson's most obvious claim to
greatness is in the throat of Taylor Hanson. He has a classic rock
'n' roll voice. He growls, sneers and croons with the confidence of
someone far beyond his 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   A distinctive vocalist, no choreography, instruments played by
the people pictured on the cover, and no one trying to prove their
street cred. Doesn't sound much like a boy band, does it?
</P>
<P>
   ``This Time Around''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson. Island. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : For more information about Hanson:
www.hansonline.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GLADIATOR09-COX     05-08 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADIATOR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Gladiator' vs. 'Braveheart' vs. 'Ben-Hur'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moviegoers haven't savored a sword orgy like Russell Crowe's new
flick since Charlton Heston rocked
</P>
<P>
   the Circus Maximus 41 years ago _ unless you want to count Mel
Gibson's Oscar-winning Highlands hellcat. Here, we compare the
newcomer with two of the better-known of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   'Gladiator'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Circa: 2000 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Muscle: Russell Crowe, as unjustly booted Roman general
Maximus turned gladiator, out for revenge against a sniveling
emperor. Crowe just ... won't ... stop.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Villain: A pouty Joaquin Phoenix as the aptly named Emperor
Commodus. He has icky feelings for his sister.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brutality: The Colosseum, WWF-style. Bloody beheadings, garish
dismemberments, full-body torchings, crashing chariots, repeated
arrow stickings, suffocation, sword throwing, horse stompings,
crucifixions, tiger gutting, gooey wound pus.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best scene: The movie's punishing opening: a long, orderly and
brutal assault by Romans against a horde of dirt-caked Germans. At
times it approaches the devastating beginning of ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Domestic box office: $32.7 million _ in one weekend.
</P>
<P>
   'Braveheart'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Circa: 1995 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Muscle: Mel Gibson, as kilted 13th-century Scotsman William
Wallace, out for revenge against the bloody Brits. Gibson sometimes
just ... looks ... crazy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Villain: An ice-cold Patrick McGoohan as big fat liar King
Edward I. He's conniving, vindictive and unfeeling. And he coughs a
lot, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brutality: Double doses of neck slicing, broadsword
beheadings, multiple losses of legs, lance skewerings, sword
throwing, rain of arrows (one in upper cheek, one in lower cheek),
attempted rape, hot oil dousings, full-body torchings, mallet
mauling, hero slow torture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best scene: If you're a girl: an older Mel gives his love the
pressed flower she handed him as a child. If you're a guy: an even
older Mel breaks into a room on horseback and, with ball and chain,
gives a Scottish traitor a punitive whack in the head.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Domestic box office: $75.6 million. (Worldwide: $204 million.)
</P>
<P>
   'Ben-Hur'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Circa: 1959 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Muscle: Charlton Heston, as the determined Egyptian leader
turned Hebrew slave ... oops, sorry ... the determined Jewish
prince Judah Ben-Hur turned ship slave turned gladiator turned
miracle witness out for revenge against a scheming old Roman pal.
Heston's overacting just ... won't ... stop.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Villain: Stephen Boyd, with the pretty-boy strut, as the
merciless Messala. He puts Judah's mom and sis into a deep, dark
prison, and they become lepers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brutality: Galley slaves chained to a sinking ship, whippings,
horse tramplings, chariot crashes, sword stabbings, lance
shish-kebabbing, facial fire. And the crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best scene: The chariot race. Nobody's ever done it better.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Domestic box office: $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
