<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sneak peek at Disney's `Dinosaur'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dinosaurs were supposed to have disappeared millions of years
ago, but the big guys keep coming back. Sparked by ``Jurassic
Park'' in 1993, interest in the leaping lizards is soaring again. A
recent Discovery Channel program, ``Walking With Dinosaurs,''
attracted nearly 11 million viewers _ a record for a cable
documentary. And now Disney is following in the giant footsteps of
T. rex with ``Dinosaur,'' a $200 million, digitally produced
animated movie, which is scheduled to open in theaters May 19.
Newsweek ($3.50) gives readers a sneak peek at the first film from
Disney's new digital animation studio and traces the evolution of
computerized special effects. Thanks to improved computer graphics,
the magazine reports, these prehistoric creatures will be the most
realistic yet.
</P>
<P>
   An accompanying article updates the latest scientific findings,
including information about the recent discovery in South America
of the world's largest meat-eating dinosaurs. A replica of one of
those huge carnivores will be exhibited this summer at the Fernbank
Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ups and downs: In its third annual issue of ``Most Overrated
and Underrated,'' American Heritage ($4.95) decides that Franklin
D. Roosevelt, Barbra Streisand, Amelia Earhart and Sitting Bull
have been overpraised. So have ``Gone With the Wind,''
``Moby-Dick'' and the vodka martini. As for the underrated, the
magazine's experts list aviatrix Harriet Quimby, who flew solo
across the English Channel in 1912, Ronald Reagan, Bing Crosby and
the Sazerac cocktail, a cognac concoction with bitters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bugged: Time ($3.50) devotes its cover story to the fallout
from last week's ``Love Bug'' virus, which wreaked havoc with
e-mail, affected tens of millions of computers and caused as much
as $10 billion in lost work hours. ``Without architectural
improvements, we will see this again,'' says Jeff Carpenter of
CERT, a federally funded group that investigates Internet security
crises.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these guys who spread computer viruses and hack into
highly sensitive systems? Jon Katz, author of the book ``Geeks!,''
says they're ``gifted, alienated kids _ powerless in their real
adolescent lives _ who couldn't resist the temptation to make
themselves, even briefly, more powerful than they ever imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the magazine, a must-read is Garrison Keillor's
essay on ``The Mysteries of Prom Night.'' Parents shouldn't worry
about their kids staying out late and breeding, Keillor writes;
this generation intends to enjoy themselves and not marry until
they're 35. ``They know the grief that children can cause, having
so recently caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mysteries of the Taliban: In a fascinating article in The New
Yorker ($3), William T. Vollman visits Afghanistan to report on the
effect the military triumph of the Taliban has had on the country.
The streets are safer, Vollman writes, but at a high price. Many
are willing to tolerate a certain amount of fundamentalism _
including the beating of women and the banning of certain music _
for stability. Just to talk to an Afghan woman, Vollman had to get
permission from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick calories: Fast food is convenient, but it's often not
healthy. Men's Fitness ($3.99) offers a handy guide through the
calorie-laden minefield of burgers and shakes. Best bets include
the grilled chicken burrito at Taco Bell (390 calories), the
grilled chicken sandwich at Wendy's (310 calories) and the Veggie
Delite sandwich at Subway (232 calories). Dieters are urged to
avoid McDonald's Big Xtra with cheese (810 calories). You want
fries with that?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
