<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Living donors transforming transplant surgery
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The medical status of ``expired'' once was the major
requirement for an organ donation.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   As waiting lists for organs tripled in the past decade, and
transplant science took quantum technological leaps, healthy and
helpful relatives, friends and even strangers began volunteering in
record numbers to give away an organ.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, so many individuals are willingly undergoing risky
operations to give up vital parts while alive, they could soon
outnumber the people who donate their organs in death. In 1999,
there were 5,812 cadaveric donors and 4,627 living donors,
according to the United Network of Organ Sharing, which allocates
organs through a national registry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living transplants that happen are usually family-related,
such as sibling to sibling, but there does seem to be somewhat of a
trend toward unrelated donors coming forward,'' said UNOS spokesman
Bob Spieldenner.
</P>
<P>
   Living donor transplants more than doubled in the past decade to
4,627, outpacing cadaveric transplants, which rose only 55 percent
to 17,363, according to UNOS.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, numbers tripled on two lists: those who died
waiting for an organ and those who joined the waiting registry.
Currently, 69,227 people _ including 913 Georgians _ need one or
more organs to stay alive. More than 6,000 will die by year's end
before an organ becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   Neil and Jaclyn Damato, a father and daughter from Suwanee, Ga.,
bear a swath of staples and scars of the latest living donor
transplant wonder _ splitting a healthy donor liver in half and
inserting it into a patient with a faltering liver. The liver is
the only organ in the body with the ability to grow back.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, under the practiced scalpel of pediatric transplant
surgeon Thomas Heffron, the Damatos underwent back-to-back
next-door operations at Emory University Hospital and Children's
Health Care of Atlanta at Egleston.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery began at 8 a.m. to remove 40 percent of Neil's liver and
ended 16 hours later when doctors took out Jaclyn's diseased organ
and sewed in her father's liver. Both their livers are expected to
regenerate to full size within six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jaclyn is doing well and shows no sign of rejecting the organ,
and her father is anxiously awaiting her arrival home to share
convalescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mall of Georgia is calling wondering where she is,'' he
quipped while visiting her over the weekend at Egleston. ``Sales
are way down.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil, a 44-year-old senior vice president of sales with Keebler
Food Murray Biscuit Co., said he jumped at the chance to be his
daughter's liver donor. He and his wife, Mary Ann, agreed it held
the best hope for the oldest of their three children, who would
have had to get sicker and sicker to move up the priority list for
a cadaver liver. Jaclyn suffered from hepatitis, which led to
jaundice, anemia and extreme fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I saw it was that Mary Ann gave Jackie her first birth
15 years ago, and I wanted to give her a second birth now,'' Neil
said Sunday, sitting in a rocking chair in his daughter's
balloon-brightened hospital room. ``The only thing I got nervous
about was all the medical tests before the surgery. I kept
thinking, `If I flunk this one, it's over. Then what will happen
with Jackie?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jaclyn, a ninth-grader, said she can already see and feel the
difference of her new liver. Her eyes are no longer tinged yellow,
and she has more energy. ``It's really exciting. I knew in my heart
everything would be OK,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Success rates tend to be better using living donors than
cadaveric ones, doctors say, because living donor transplants can
be scheduled before the patient becomes extremely ill, which is the
basic criteria of being moved to the top of any transplant list.
Also, a living donor organ has not gone through the trauma of
death. It has only been out of a body for minutes, instead of the
hours that usually lapse between a fatal accident or shooting and a
hastily scheduled transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Since living donors must be healthy, and they undergo rigorous
testing for tissue compatibility, this also lessens the chances of
rejection by the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics complied by the UNOS show a four-year survival rate
of 85 percent among kidney transplant patients who underwent
cadaveric transplants, and a 94 percent survival rate for
living-related donor transplants. Four-year rates comparing
cadaveric and live liver transplants are unavailable because the
technique is relatively new, but evidence is accumulating that
living donor transplants are more successful.
</P>
<P>
   Living transplants are also cheaper than cadaveric surgery
because the recipient requires less recovery time and the operation
is elective rather than an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Kidneys are considered the least risky organ to give up while
alive as people are born with two kidneys but need only one to
function, and laparoscopic surgery has made the operation safer and
less painful.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, a public education campaign about living donor
options is about to be aimed at African-Americans, who comprise the
majority of the nearly 700 Georgians on the UNOS kidney transplant
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to get the information. The greatest fear is the
fear of the unknown,'' said Willia Jordan, a volunteer with
LifeLink of Georgia, who also sits on the board of directors for
the National Kidney Foundation of Georgia. Jordan, 49, gave a
kidney to her mother, who was in end-stage renal failure six years
ago. ``My mom is doing just great. She teaches preschool at a
Christian day care center, and she keeps up with the 2-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   But living donor transplants remain controversial within the
medical community because of the risk to the donor. Any major
surgery involves risk of death from possible hemorrhaging,
infection or complications from anesthesia. At least one and
possibly two donors have died during liver transplant surgery in
the past decade, according to the American Liver Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Another downside to living donor transplants is it produces a
much more limited ``harvest'' of parts, as opposed to the many
organs, skin, tissue and corneas that can be retrieved from one
cadaver. As many as 60 people can benefit from one deceased organ
donor.
</P>
<P>
   While doctors and ethicists continue to argue many facets of
living vs. cadaveric transplants, they agree on one point _ more
people need to give their organs away the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see living donors as solving the problem of people
waiting on the transplant list,'' said Mark Rothstein of the
University of Houston Health, Law and Policy Institute. ``Getting
more people to be organ donors (in death) is the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
