A9376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TEXAS-DEMS-2TAKES(106     05-08 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMS-2TAKES(1065)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEMOCRATS, FACING HARD TIMES, SEE NO REASON TO OPPOSE BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The once-mighty Texas Democratic Party, whose
fabled leaders Lyndon B. Johnson and Sam Rayburn once dominated not
just the state but the nation, has fallen on very hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Of today's 29 officials elected statewide in Texas, none are
Democrats. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican, faces only
token Democratic opposition in her re-election campaign this year,
which is more opposition than the party is providing in most
statewide races. And much to the chagrin of the Democratic state
chairwoman, Molly Beth Malcolm, several Democratic legislators have
been out campaigning with none other than George W. Bush, the
second-term Republican governor and soon-to-be GOP presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed they would do that,'' said Malcolm, who
returned from a vacation in Italy to discover that her party
members were consorting with the enemy. ``They are not representing
the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the most partisan Republicans, few people in Texas
would argue that Democrats are powerless or obsolete, particularly
since the party still controls the congressional delegation and the
Texas House of Representatives. But as Bush campaigns for the White
House, Democrats are consumed by a parochial, less glamorous
agenda, such as legislative races and preparing for the 2002
gubernatorial race. And few elected Democrats are willing to make
trouble for their popular governor.
</P>
<P>
   The state's most famous Democrat, former Gov. Ann Richards,
spends much of her time lobbying in Washington and has refrained
from attacking the man who beat her in 1994. The state's most
powerful Democrat, House Speaker Pete Laney, so far has stayed out
of the presidential race. Other conservative Democrats in the
Legislature either like Bush personally or are wary of antagonizing
him as their districts become increasingly Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no percentage in giving Bush a hard time,'' said
Harvey Kronberg, publisher of The Quorum Report, a widely read
online newsletter covering Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   That detente is a timely gift for Bush as he fashions himself as
a coalition builder who would foster bipartisanship in Washington.
By contrast, Arkansas Republicans tried to crush Bill Clinton in
1992. They maligned his record and his character and left little
doubt about their strategy. ``Defeating the enemy at all costs,''
recalled Richard Bearden, then the executive director of the
Arkansas Republican Party, ``and Bill Clinton was the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Arkansas, where frustrated Republicans felt little
incentive to play nice with Clinton, Texas has a tradition of
bipartisanship and chauvinism that for some Democrats outweighs any
national party loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most Texans, it's a no-brainer,'' said George Christian, a
Democrat and former press secretary to President Johnson. ``It's an
acceptable, bipartisan Texan running for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Merle Black, a political scientist at Emory University, said
testimonials from unexpected home state allies can provide
credibility for presidential candidates introducing themselves to a
national audience. Coming out of Georgia in 1976, Jimmy Carter
enlisted civil rights leader Andrew Young to help prove he was a
different sort of Southern Democrat than the race baiting governor
of Alabama, George Wallace. In the same vein, Black said, Bush is
enlisting Texas Democrats to help reassure voters that he is
different from the combative congressional Republicans of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is trying to show that he's not Newt Gingrich, he's not
Tom DeLay, he's not Dick Armey,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the Texas Democrats has roots in the 1960s, but
the unequivocal slap-in-the-face from Texas voters came in 1998,
when the party lost every statewide race, from governor to
lieutenantgovernor to land commissioner. Bush won re-election with
nearly 70 percent of the vote, the first time in 24 years that a
governor from either party had won a consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
   So when Democratic party officials announced last year that they
would not field candidates for six of the eight statewide races
this November, Republicans happily began writing obituaries.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Democratic officials were further embarrassed when a
perennial losing candidate best known for his famous name, Gene
Kelly, sought and won the party's nomination to challenge
Hutchison, an overwhelming favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats point out that the party still dominates local
politics in much of the state. The mayors of Dallas, Austin,
Houston and San Antonio are Democrats, and the party still controls
a large majority of county governments, particularly in South
Texas. But Robert Black, spokesman for the Texas Republican Party,
said that while Republicans control local government in only 57 of
the state's 254 counties, those 57 counties accounted for 56
percent of the state's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have grown so incredibly fast in such a short period of
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy of recent Democratic misfortunes would point to money
and demographics as the chief problems. Texas' huge size requires
statewide candidates to raise millions and millions of dollars in
order to compete in every media market. With corporate interests
favoring Republicans, Kronberg said Democrats often depend on
contributions from trial lawyers. But Republicans, led by Bush,
have demonized the trial bar as greedy lawyers pushing unnecessary
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats going statewide have to prove they're not pawns to
trial lawyers,'' Kronberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McClung, a Democratic political consultant in Houston, said
heavy numbers of out-of-state, Republican-leaning, white voters
have moved into the suburbs of Dallas, Austin and Houston. McClung
said these new voters were critical in the narrow 1998 defeats of
two well-known Democrats, John Sharp, who ran for lieutenant
governor, and Paul Hobby, who ran for state comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've virtually been shoved aside,'' said McClung, who worked
for Hobby.
</P>
<P>
   The result, many Democrats agree, is that a high-profile effort
to attack and embarrass Bush makes little sense as the party is
struggling to regain primacy. ``Right now, our fight is not
statewide,'' McClung said. ``George W. Bush is popular. He's
extremely well financed. And most Texans would prefer to have a
president from Texas than fight about party politics.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
