<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-DEMS-2NDTAKE-NY     05-08 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 AUSTIN, Texas: party politics.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has always been a divide between conservative, often
rural, Democrats and their more liberal urban brethren. But the
recent coziness between the conservatives and Bush does frustrate
some grass-roots party organizers. Frumencio Reyes, a Gore delegate
to the state party convention, said local voters often ask him what
is happening to the party. ``We find it difficult to answer,''
Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, who switched from Republican to Democrat in 1992, said
the party is in ``a rebuilding period.'' She said the decision not
to contest most statewide races this year was a strategic one.
Instead, Democrats hope to keep control of the House and win back
the state Senate, where Republicans hold a one-vote edge, 16-15.
Whichever party controls the Legislature will also control
congressional and legislative redistricting, and Democrats dearly
want to hold their 17-13 majority in the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the immediate future of Texas politics
depends on Bush's future. If he wins in November, his job will fall
to Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a Republican whose replacement would be
chosen by the state Senate. As the presiding officer of the Senate,
the lieutenant governor is considered the state's most powerful
office as far as influencing legislation, and a handful of
candidates in both parties are already jockeying for position.
</P>
<P>
   But neither party dominates the Senate, and no one expects a
party line vote. Instead, the ultimate winner will need to attract
votes from both sides, and the hopefuls are making certain to avoid
any partisan warfare. One of them, state Sen. Ken Armbrister, was
one of the four Democrats who campaigned with Bush in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome in November, Democrats say, they are
pointing to 2002 and beyond. The powerful statewide offices of
governor, lieutenant governor, attorney general and comptroller are
on the ballot in 2002. Bush will either be in Washington or leaving
office in Austin. Democratic officials already envision a statewide
ticket that would include Sharp, Hobby and perhaps the mayors of
Dallas, Ron Kirk, and Austin, Kirk Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Most tantalizing of all, in the eyes of many Democrats, is the
possible return of former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has been marred by scandal involving his payments to a
former mistress, party insiders believe Cisneros' star power and
fund-raising potential remains strong in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   McClung and other Democrats also believe the state's changing
demographics may turn in their favor in this decade. Hispanics are
expected to soon become the state's most populous ethnic group and
they have usually supported Democrats. Bush has aggressively
courted Hispanics, but Democrats believe their appeal is stronger.
Also, younger, college-age voters are showing renewed interest in
the party. This is the gospel Democrats are repeating to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the old lions is roaring again. Ben Barnes, a
former speaker of the House and lieutenant governor from the
Democratic glory days, gave a recent speech at the LBJ School of
Government at the University of Texas in which he warned that Texas
today ``is drifting toward mediocrity just when it should be
striving for greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   He ticked off a litany of woes from crumbling infrastructure to
underpaid teachers to substandard health care for the poor. Noting
that the state could soon have a $3 billion surplus, he warned
against more tax cuts, calling for massive reinvestment in schools
and institutions, medical research and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was a call to arms, or maybe it was just a speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
