<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-METHODIST09-COX     05-08 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODIST09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outreach plan seeks to boost black churches
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Atlanta's Cascade United Methodist Church is used to
visitors on Sunday. Visitors who have become members have built the
church's flock to about 5,000 souls.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years, the church has also hosted visitors
between Sundays: lay leaders, ministers and ministers' spouses from
other black United Methodist Churches, who are hoping to pick up
pointers to use at home.
</P>
<P>
   Cascade is one of 25 black churches chosen by the United
Methodists to be ``congregational resource centers'' for other
churches. And Monday, its pastor, the Rev. Walter Kimbrough, asked
the 1,000 delegates to the denomination's quadrennial General
Conference in Cleveland to continue the program, called
``Strengthening the Black Church for the 21st Century,'' for four
more years.
</P>
<P>
   Kimbrough has the distinction of also having pastored another of
the 25 model churches, Atlanta's Ben Hill United Methodist Church,
Georgia's largest United Methodist congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Conference delegates will vote later this week on whether to
fund the $2.3 million proposal to continue the initiative through
the 2004 conference.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kimbrough and the Rev. McCallister Hollins, pastor of the
9,500-member Ben Hill church, said funds spent on helping black
churches succeed will be an investment, bringing more members into
the denomination and more money to do ministry. Cascade and Ben
Hill together pay $600,000 per year to denominational ministries,
besides ministries sponsored by the congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for a handout,'' said Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   Having black churches learn from other black churches is
important, he said, because ``we have to continue to wrestle with
cultural things _ how do we maintain our cultural distinctiveness
and still be United Methodists. We do that very well at Ben Hill,
but it has to be a conscious decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is one of several signs at this conference that
the predominantly white United Methodist Church is becoming
increasingly diverse. Of the 9.6 million members internationally,
382,243 are African-American, 40,652 are Hispanic, 18,766 are
Native American, 56,143 are Asian American and 8,245 are Pacific
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A task force on Korean-American ministries asked for $3.2
million to provide a leadership program for clergy and lay members
in bilingual and cross-cultural ministry, establish new
congregations, strengthen existing congregations, recruit new
clergy and publish resource material. The denomination is also
developing a Korean-English hymnal.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A report on Hispanic ministries Monday evening included a
request to continue funding a 1992 plan, extended in 1996, that
provided $1 million in grants to implement ministries to Hispanics
in both Hispanic and non-Hispanic congregations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Native American delegates are asking the conference to address
a variety of concerns, including a request not to hold future
conferences in cities that have professional sports teams with
mascots they consider demeaning. Although prompted by the Cleveland
Indians' Chief Wahoo, the measure, if adopted, could also affect
Atlanta, because of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   While increasing their efforts directed to members of various
ethnic backgrounds, United Methodists still appear deeply
conflicted about how far to go in including gay and lesbian
members.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the conference committee dealing with the main church
legislation involving homosexuality voted roughly 2-1 to extend the
status quo of prohibiting ordination of sexually active homosexuals
and union ceremonies for same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also will recommend, by a 59-43 vote, that
delegates keep language that says homosexual practice is
``incompatible with Christian teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 705-210 Monday, delegates rejected a proposal to
require pastors to sign a statement promising not to practice or
promote homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
