<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTOS-ONLINE-ART-2TAK     05-08 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-ONLINE-ART-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMAKERS STRIVE TO SPEED UP ONLINE BUYING 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Order a personal computer online or over the phone,
choosing every specification, and it will be assembled and shipped
to your door in five or six days. But try to order a car from the
factory that way, and watch out.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers who place such orders face stupefyingly complex forms
asking them about sometimes obscure features like axle ratios for
towing. The few brave enough to fill out the paperwork _ most
automakers have yet to computerize the process _ then face a wait
long enough to try anyone's patience: three weeks to three months
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers have long been aware of the problem. But now they are
striving to speed things up, partly because the Internet makes it
possible and partly because their control over the sales process is
threatened by online buying services, which allow customers in
search of just the right car to check dozens or even hundreds of
dealers quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that an increasing percentage of consumers will want
to order online directly from the factory, get exactly what they
want and get it on the desired date,'' said Ronald Zarrella,
General Motors' president of North American operations. ``If we
can't do that at the factory, we can't add value compared to the
pure dot-coms.''
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford will announce particularly ambitious ventures to
accelerate production and delivery in the coming weeks, executives
familiar with their plans said. Both companies will start with one
or two models, then convert the rest of their models and factories
to faster, more flexible production and distribution. GM plans to
revamp all its factories in the United States by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   They and other automakers want to be able, within a few years,
to supply exactly the car the customer wants in as little as two
weeks. They say the changes could slow increases in car prices, by
allowing dealers to slash costs by keeping fewer cars on hand.
``Dealers should be able to reduce their inventory costs,'' said
James G. O'Connor, Ford Motor's vice president for Ford brand cars
and trucks. ``Hopefully, we should be able to pass that on to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But building cars to order is easier said than done. Automakers
hope they can fill most orders not by assembling specific vehicles
for specific customers, but by finding vehicles that they have
already built but that now sit on a train or at another dealer.
</P>
<P>
   To improve the odds of finding the right vehicle, manufacturers
plan at first to limit customer choice, not expand it. They intend
to offer models with just three to five packages of options and in
several colors. Dealers will offer accessories like bike racks and
fancy hubcaps.
</P>
<P>
   The planned new production and distribution systems will do
little to alleviate overall shortages of instant hits like the
Chrysler PT Cruiser that are hard to find in any color; assembly
plants can produce only so many vehicles each week. Even with the
new system, it will remain difficult to order obscure options on
popular models.
</P>
<P>
   James Clark, a 57-year-old management systems consultant in
Washougal, Wash., said that he tried from November through March to
order a GMC Sierra 2500 with an extended cab and a short pickup
bed, an unusual combination, but that neither he nor his dealer had
received even an estimate from GM of when the vehicle might be
built. ``I was never able to get a straight answer,'' Clark
complained, adding that he ended up buying a 1-year-old Chevrolet
Silverado pickup instead.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to GM and Ford, the Japanese and Europeans are also
experimenting, although France's Renault, which owns Japan's Nissan
Motor, is the only non-American automaker committed so far to
changing production at all its factories by next year. ``It is a
high investment,'' said Carlos Ghosn, Nissan's president. ``There
is a high return, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is allowing dealers to alter orders for Solara coupes
just five days before they are produced at its factory in
Cambridge, Ontario, instead of a month. But it may still take a
week or two to deliver the finished car.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Internet to help coordinate thousands of parts
suppliers, automakers hope to make assembly lines more flexible.
When a dealer notices that a certain color or option is in short
supply, the manufacturers want to be able to restock the showroom
within weeks, not months, so that more customers can avoid having
to place special orders.
</P>
<P>
   Speeding up car production is far more difficult than building
computers quickly. Cars require many more components: While Dell
relies on 25 main suppliers to assemble desktop computers,
DaimlerChrysler has 900 _ even after weeding out the smaller ones
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Auto parts tend to be large and expensive, so it is costly to
store inventories near assembly plants just in case they are
needed. Suppliers are often hundreds of miles away, so a factory in
Asheville, N.C., for example, ships anti-lock-brake systems all
over the Midwest, making it hard to place last-minute orders.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, distribution has actually been slowing lately.
Railroads are short of rail cars that can carry sport utility
vehicles, pickups and minivans, which can only be stacked two high,
while cars can be three high. With automobiles of virtually all
sizes selling well, the transportation problem has become so acute
that thousands of larger vehicles have stacked up in parking lots
outside factories. Sending them by truck instead is prohibitively
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   While overnight parcel services can track a packaged shipment
anywhere in the country, automakers often have little idea where
their cars are, making it hard to reroute them. ``They know the
vehicle has left the plant and they know what dealership it's going
to, but they don't know where it is during the 30 days or so in
between,'' said Daron Gifford, global automotive director at
Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the accounting and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   All automakers have been studying the problem for years. Now
they are doing something.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ford is paying particular attention to vehicle distribution and
has joined forces with the United Parcel Service to begin tracking
every car from factory to dealer to customer. It also has a
contract with the WhereNet Corp. to buy miniature radio
transmitters. These will be temporarily attached to each vehicle as
it comes off the assembly line and will continuously broadcast an
identity code, helping workers find specific cars in vast shipping
lots. ``That's where they tend to lose track of them,'' said Dan
Doles, WhereNet's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   One way GM hopes to speed production is by using the Internet to
communicate with suppliers. GM recently joined Ford and
DaimlerChrysler in setting up a business exchange for the buying
and selling of auto parts and other products. It plans to post
constant updates of its production schedules on a secure part of
the site available not only to its primary suppliers but to its
suppliers' suppliers, and on down the line, said Harold R. Kutner,
group vice president for global purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Computers at GM's factories are already linked with, for
example, dashboard makers. But if there is a sudden increase in
demand for CD players, the new system will allow GM to notify the
dashboard manufacturer and the vendor for CD players
simultaneously. ``Suppliers are going to start to get a sense of
what's happening in the marketplace,'' Kutner said.
</P>
<P>
   Like GM, Ford is planning to offer a few packages of options,
instead of allowing customers to check off dozens or even hundreds
of items. This should allow Ford to vary the proportion of these
packages at the factory, and fill many orders with cars that have
just been built, said James J. Padilla, Ford's group vice president
for global manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to have 200,000 combinations out there when the
consumer can only grapple with maybe 50,'' he said. ``We have been
prone to design and release every possible combination, into the
hundreds of thousands of combinations, which is a lot of
engineering, a lot of tooling and a lot of inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese automakers already require customers to choose among
packages of options. Toyota, Honda and Nissan managers say that
while they are also looking to shorten production and delivery
times, they believe that automakers know better than consumers what
combination of options make sense for daily use and retain their
value.
</P>
<P>
   If consumers are given too many choices, ``they'll buy a car
without an air conditioner, and they'll be sorry,'' both on warm
days and when they try to resell it, said James Press, Toyota's
executive vice president for North American sales.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler has been more cautious than GM or Ford about
accelerating production and delivery. If dealers can be assisted in
spotting local shifts in demand more quickly, it contends, they can
order the right cars in advance and have them ready when the
customer comes in the door. ``That's the way you get fast order to
delivery, and not by committing unnatural acts to get it out of the
factory quicker,'' said Jamie Jameson, DaimlerChrysler's vice
president for North American marketing operations.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, DaimlerChrysler and other automakers are trying to
improve relations with dealers. Dealers do not report a lot of
basic information back to manufacturers, like the color of vehicles
sold or the prices paid. If, for example, a model in one color is
so unpopular that dealers must offer deep discounts, it can take
months for the factory to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dealers have never wanted to share pricing information
with the manufacturer, and rightly so, because the manufacturers
use it against them'' in negotiations over the sharing of various
costs, said J. David Power III, founder of the consulting and
consumer rating company that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers, of course, try to order cars in colors that have proved
popular, and they try to order models they can sell with a minimum
of discounting. But since dealers can go months between ordering
cars, information filters back slowly to the factories.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan and Europe, where there is less land for huge
dealerships, customers have long ordered cars directly from the
factory. Japanese automakers are already able to deliver cars
within two weeks in their home market _ but customers, parts
suppliers and manufacturers all tend to be very close together.
</P>
<P>
   The European industry is more fragmented, although not quite as
much as the American industry. Renault of France manufactures half
its cars to order and delivers them in six to eight weeks, but
plans to start making three-quarters of its cars to order and
deliver them in just 15 days, at least in European cities close to
assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, said Louis Schweitzer, Renault's chief
executive, ``Inventories should be kept only for demonstration
purposes: to show the car in showrooms and to drive it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
