<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-OUTAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PAC BELL HIT BY E-MAIL GLITCHES  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pacific Bell's Internet service, which has been
plagued by glitches in its e-mail system, had problems again this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Web page warned users that e-mail was ``down'' or
``impaired'' all day Saturday, preventing some users from receiving
their messages. Pac Bell reported it fixed the problem by yesterday
morning, but it's at least the third time the company has had
problems with its e-mail system in as many months. The company has
more than 331,000 users.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' fumed one San Francisco businessman, who
had already scheduled two technicians to test his company's e-mail
system over the weekend. He complained in an e-mail to the
Chronicle that they couldn't complete the job because the Pac Bell
mail system was down. ``I'm out hundreds of dollars in wages, and
thousands more in lost opportunity costs.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pac Bell reported that users could have trouble
posting messages to some portions of an Internet message board
system known as Usenet. Pac Bell's Web site labeled the system as
``impaired'' both Saturday and yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9390 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROOKIESOFYEAR-HNS     05-08 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROOKIESOFYEAR </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Steve Francis made up some ground on the one player chosen ahead of
him in last summer's NBA draft, but he could not quite pass Elton
Brand in their race to be called the league's top rookie.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francis, the Rockets' high-speed, high-flying point guard, and
Brand, the Chicago Bulls' powerful and consistent inside force,
finished in a dead heat in the voting for the NBA Rookie of the
Year award to be announced Thursday, sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Francis and Brand will become the third pair of rookies to share
the award. Jason Kidd and Grant Hill were co-Rookies of the Year in
1994-95, and Dave Cowens and Geoff Petrie finished in a tie for the
1970-71 award.
</P>
<P>
   During workouts together before the draft, Francis and Brand
each often told the other he would be the first player chosen in
the lottery. Brand was right, and Francis was picked second by the
Vancouver Grizzlies before being dealt to the Rockets in an
11-player, three-team deal that was the largest in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Each produced one of the greatest seasons ever for NBA rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Francis became just the seventh rookie ever to average at least
15 points, five assists and five rebounds, joining Oscar Robertson,
Alvan Adams, Magic Johnson, Michael Jordan, Penny Hardaway and
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Francis was fifth in scoring among point guards, led all guards
in offensive rebounds and was third among guards in rebounding
overall.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first rookie and fourth player ever to lead the
Rockets in scoring (18 points per game), assists (6.6) and steals
(1.53). He also led the Rockets in minutes played, field goals made
and attempted, 3-pointers made and attempted, free throws made and
attempted, and offensive rebounds. He was the first Rockets player
ever to compile 400 rebounds and 500 assists in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   However, Francis' best and most telling statistical achievement
could perhaps be found in his performances against this season's
All-Defensive Team point guards. Francis averaged 26.8 points (on
56.5 percent shooting), 6.5 rebounds, 7.5 assists and 1.83 steals
against first-team defender Gary Payton of Seattle and
second-teamer Kidd of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   And Francis was the only player to be ranked among the leaders
in all nine rookie statistical categories kept by the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich often said during the season he
thought Francis could become one of the best point guards ever, a
point he made to Francis after training camp. Tomjanovich was
unavailable for comment Monday, but he has repeatedly explained why
he believes Francis has such rare potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you look at the overall impact he has on the
game, you'd see,'' Tomjanovich said. ``After a slow start reading
defenses, which is very normal, even for a guy coming into the NBA
who has played point guard, he's really been a guy who has climbed
up the ladder in the assist category. And he rebounds, he steals
the ball, and I think he's a solid defensive player for a young kid
and still has a way to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just so much that he does to impact a game. You look
at some games, and he's right up there as our leading rebounder.
And that's from the point-guard position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just beginning the process (of becoming a point guard),''
Tomjanovich said. ``I think he's just starting to get comfortable
being that guy who has the ball most of the time and just learning
some things about the fast break, the pick-and-roll, double teams
and things like that, and he's made great strides in all those
areas already. And I think that it's just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand became the 19th rookie to average at least 20 points and
10 rebounds and just the second Bulls player ever to reach those
averages in the same season (Artis Gilmore did it twice).
</P>
<P>
   Brand led NBA rookies in minutes, scoring, rebounding and
blocked shots, and he led the NBA in offensive rebounds with 4.3
per game.
</P>
<P>
   Brand's average of 20.1 points per game was second in Bulls
history for a rookie, trailing only Jordan's average of 28.2 points
in 1984-85. Brand set a Bulls record when he made 14 consecutive
field goals April 13 against the Wizards, and he led the Bulls in
scoring 51 times, including 18 of the season's final 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   So even were Brand and Francis since the days they were drafted,
both were named Rookie of the Month twice. They tied for the award
in April, the season's last month.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, unavailable for comment Monday, said during the season
he had long since gotten over the disappointment of draft night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I was upset,'' he said. ``But Elton Brand was a
good pick. I respect him. They made a good pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be No. 1,'' Francis admitted, ``to brag to
everyone I was the No. 1 pick. But it's definitely the best thing
that ever happened to me how it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
