<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-RELEASES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TWO NEW INTEL NETWORKING DEVICES FOR B2B MARKET  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp., which last year redefined its
mission as ``creating the building blocks of the Internet
economy,'' on Monday will roll out two new ones, a pair of devices
designed to speed up secure e-commerce transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The products, both part of the company's growing
``NetStructure'' line of ``intelligent networking'' devices, are
designed specifically to accelerate processing of XML, or
eXtensible Markup Language, the emerging standard for
business-to-business commerce over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Both products, the 7210 XML Accelerator and the 7280 XML
Director, will work by decoding and examining incoming XML-format
traffic before it goes to an online business' back-end servers.
They will classify each transaction by the ``dialect'' of XML it is
written in, then dispatch it to the corresponding server.
</P>
<P>
   XML creates a standard framework for e-business, but it is also
designed to be customized for the needs of specific companies and
industries. Already, several companies, including Microsoft, Ariba
and CommerceOne, have created their own dialects.
</P>
<P>
   The XML Director will feature several additional capabilities
not supported in the Accelerator. The former, for example, will be
able to prioritize orders based on information coded within the
transaction _ for example, the customer it comes from, the size of
the order or how quickly it has to be filled. E-business
administrators will be able to change priorities on the fly,
without interrupting service, according to Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The higher-end model will also check the syntax of XML traffic
and reject malformed messages so they won't tie up busy servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These products are part of a significant trend toward more
intelligent networking,'' said Meta Group analyst Peter Firstbrook.
``They move decisions that used to be done in software on the
server out to the network, before the request even reaches the
server.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else has yet announced products directly comparable to
Intel's XML devices, Firstbrook said. He added, though, that
technology Cisco Systems picked up last week with its $6 billion
acquisition of ArrowPoint Communications could enable Cisco to
enter the same category eventually.
</P>
<P>
   The new Intel offerings are scheduled to ship in July. Prices
have not been determined. Two current members of the NetStructure
family, the Commerce Accelerator and Commerce Director, are priced
at $12,995 and $39,995, respectively, and because the new XML
devices are more sophisticated, they're likely to carry somewhat
higher prices, according to Brett Helm, general manager of Intel's
network equipment division.
</P>
<P>
   Helm was CEO of iPivot, a Poway (San Diego County) company Intel
purchased in October for $500 million in cash. The new products are
based primarily on technology developed by iPivot.
</P>
<P>
   The XML devices combine Intel Pentium III microprocessors with
specialized chips and software. They'll run a customized version of
the Unix operating system, Helm said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
