<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-JAPAN-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NTT COMMUNICATIONS TO BUY VERIO FOR MAJOR MOVE INTO U.S. MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a major expansion into the United States Internet
market, NTT Communications of Japan said Monday it had agreed to
acquire Verio Inc., a Web site manager based in Englewood, Colo.,
for $5.5 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of an aggressive new strategy by NTT
Communications, a subsidiary of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, to
expand globally, particularly across Asia, America and Europe. NTT
Communications holds a 10 percent stake in Verio.
</P>
<P>
   The deal to buy the rest, worth $60 a share, represents a 67
percent premium over Verio's share price at the close of stock
trading Friday. In extremely heavy trading on the Nasdaq market
Monday, when most technology shares in the United States fell
sharply, Verio surged $22.51, or 63 percent, to $68.50. Earlier in
Tokyo, Nippon Telegraph rose 2.8 percent, to 1.46 million yen, or
about $13,518.
</P>
<P>
   NTT Communications' deal for Verio would be one of the largest
cash purchases of an Internet services company. Such acquisitions
in the Internet industry are usually settled with stock. It is also
one of the biggest Japanese purchases of an American company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts applauded the deal, saying that by acquiring Verio, NTT
Communications, a domestic and international telephone carrier,
would gain an important beachhead in the highly competitive,
fast-expanding Internet market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very positive move because Verio will gain a well
established local presence in the United States that will allow NTT
to offer higher value-added services and expand its customer
base,'' said Hironobu Sawake, a senior analyst for ING Barings
Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that NTT Communications' willingness to pay such a
high premium for Verio was an indication that the company was
serious about becoming a major player in the world
telecommunications market, though it came late to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Verio, founded in 1996, is one of the largest operators of Web
sites for businesses with an emphasis on serving small and midsize
customers. The company offers 400,000 sites in 127 countries,
including 14,000 sites for electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Satoshi Fujita, a senior vice president of NTT Communications,
said the combined Internet-telephone company would give ``U.S
dot-com companies a bridge to the Asia Pacific region and Asia
dot-com companies a reliable vertical access to the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   NTT Communications has been expanding its global network
primarily in Asia since it was created last year with the breakup
of Nippon Telegraph, which for decades was the only telephone
company in Japan and remains one of the world's largest
telecommunications businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The spin-off company has invested about $1 billion in the Asia
Pacific region on a variety of interests, including stakes in
StarHub, one of Singapore's largest Internet carriers; Philippines
Long Distance Telephone; Davnet Telecommunications, an Australian
Internet service provider; and HK Net, a Hong Kong Internet
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Fujita, asked about NTT Communications' plans for further
acquisitions, said: ``It would be correct to say that we are not
finished. Certainly we need to have more capability in the global
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive said that although NTT might have been slow in its
international expansion, the communications industry is changing so
rapidly that ``the incumbent may not necessarily be the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement to acquire Verio, a United States subsidiary
of NTT Communications will make a tender offer no later than May 17
to merge Verio with the Japanese carrier. The company said it hopes
to complete the transaction by the third quarter of this year and
that it plans no layoffs at Verio, which has 2,000 employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
