<HEADER>
A9396 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBBY-AWARDS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-08 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBBY-AWARDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEBBY AWARDS' EFFECT ON BOTTOM LINE DIFFICULT TO MEASURE  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For some Internet company executives, winning a
Webby is like winning an Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   It means giving an acceptance speech before a large crowd and
wallowing in compliments from their peers at the party afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But the parallel between being voted pre-eminent on the Internet
and best in film stops there, especially where it counts the most
in business: money. Unlike movies, Internet sites that win industry
acknowledgment usually get only a modest reward, such as a
temporary increase in visitors and a few more advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Webbys are still a coveted prize, to be
awarded Thursday at the Masonic Auditorium on Nob Hill in San
Francisco. While happy to be recognized for their work in
categories such as commerce, games and art, some Internet
executives say that the tangible benefits of winning a Webby are
difficult to measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an honor and one that we value, especially for
the people who designed the site,'' said Bill Curry, a spokesman
for online retailer Amazon.com, which won two Webbys last year.
``But whether sales go up, down, left or right because of it is
hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Media Metrix, Web sites that win a Webby are not
assured of a permanent surge in traffic. Visits to nearly half of
last year's winning sites declined the month after they were chosen
best in their category.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does a Webby victory translate into a quick boost in stock
prices. For example, the stock of Amazon.com, declined to $67.53
from $69.21 the day after the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Wrixon, president and chief executive of SeniorNet, a San
Francisco senior citizen site that won in the community category
last year, said that winning a Webby did not suddenly make her site
more popular. But it did cause other Internet executives to call
seeking advice about their own Web sites and prompt some companies
to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Webby gave us the credibility that we were able to develop
a really high-quality community, despite the fact that we had huge
competitors,'' Wrixon said. ``Before, potential partners would look
at us and say SeniorNet is nonprofit, it's probably not worth
looking at. But they don't say that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrixon did not initially know what to think of the Webby and
listed the prize on SeniorNet's awards page along with all the
other accolades the company had won. But after all the
congratulations, Wrixon reconsidered. She placed the Webby award
emblem on her site's home page next to one showing that her site
was selected as one of Yahoo's ``100 Best Sites for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Webbys, organized by the International Academy of Digital
Media Arts and Sciences in San Francisco, is hardly alone in
honoring Internet sites for excellence. One Web site,
awardsites.com, lists 2,011 different Internet award programs,
though the site's founder, David Bancroft, says even that total is
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   How much attention Internet users pay to awards like the Webbys
is unclear. Asien Shieu, a student at the University of California
at Berkeley and frequent Web surfer, said that the sheer number of
awards and the dubious provenance of some make her skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the awards look really fake,'' she said. ``I don't
usually pay attention when I see them on a site, or I wonder
whether they just made the award themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the Webbys interested mainly Internet insiders,
according to Jim Rose, co-founder of Mobshop, a San Francisco
retail site that has been nominated in this year's commerce
category. But he believes that is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Webbys are growing a bit mainstream,'' Rose said.
``A few years ago, it was a very Net-savvy audience. Now it's a
little broader.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Shlain, the Webbys' executive producer, said that her
awards program provides the public and Internet industry ``an
objective voice in distinguishing the best'' on the Web. She said
that the Webbys have a huge following, measured by the 134,000
people who cast votes this year for their favorite sites.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to generate public interest and add a veneer of
prestige, the Webbys are increasingly imitating Hollywood award
ceremonies. Celebrities scheduled to be onstage include Alan
Cummings, a Tony award-winning actor who has appeared in such films
as ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' and actress and comedian Sandra Bernhard.
</P>
<P>
   Judges include actor Robin Williams, who voted in the games
category. Rock musician David Bowie helped select the best music
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Of all Web sites that win a Webby, it is probably the smaller
ones that get the biggest boost. For example, Richard Johnson,
founder of SportsPages.com, which won in the sports category last
year, said that traffic on his site increased from about 17,000
hits a day before being nominated to about 20,000 a day, but then
declined soon after the ceremony was over.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in interest translated into a few hundred extra
dollars in subscription fees, said Johnson, who is from New York
City. But perhaps more importantly, the victory allowed him to
promote his site through the media, including television news,
which had never taken any interest in his site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I had ever won an award before in my life, so it
was nice to bask in the glory,'' said Johnson, who had never heard
of the Webbys before being nominated and was at first suspicious
that he would have to pay the award's organizers to win.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he won against other more well-funded nominees,
like Quokka Sports, gave him the confidence to go out and seek
outside investors. That effort, however, has been only moderately
successful, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Webby hasn't made a big direct difference to the
business,'' said Johnson, who now always mentions the Webby victory
when making a presentation to potential investors. ``But I don't
blame the Webbys, I blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Benjamin, who won last year in the ``Weird'' category for
his site, superbad.com, got even less out of his victory. A few
thousand more people visited his site after it was nominated for
the award.
</P>
<P>
   But because Benjamin sells nothing on superbad.com, a site
featuring animated graphics, the surge in traffic did not translate
into more money. His one-man graphic design business did get more
clients, but it had nothing to do with the award, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What it did bring him was unwanted e-mail. He said that the
International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences put his name on
a junk mail list, and he now frequently receives unwanted letters
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Benjamin said that it was an honor to win a Webby
and especially satisfying to meet some of the other winners. He
said it was more exciting, however, to have his Web site included
in this year's Whitney Biennial, one of the most prestigious
contemporary art exhibitions in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the Webbys say they are so important, people take
it at face value,'' Benjamin said. ``Winning means that five people
liked my site better than others. It's so arbitrary.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
