<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9397 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     05-08 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE: COMPANY USES BEADS TO FISH OUT `GOOD,' `BAD' GENES  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With Monday's announcement that Oakland,
Calif.'s DoubleTwist.com has produced the first rough list of human
genes, the next question is: How do they all work together?
</P>
<P>
   Enter Lynx Therapeutics, an 8-year-old Hayward, Calif., firm
whose technology may help figure out how genes interact to promote
health or cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the challenge. Each cell contains a complete set of
genes. But only some genes are switched on _ scientists say
``expressed'' _ in any given cell. The difference between a heart
cell and a skin cell boils down to which genes are expressed in
that part of your body.
</P>
<P>
   Gene expression also has medical applications. Errors in gene
expression cause some illnesses. For example, the difference
between healthy mammaries and breast cancer could be the
overexpression of a harmful gene or the underexpression of a
beneficial one.
</P>
<P>
   Lynx has a novel technology that reaches into the DNA from a
specific cell, notes which genes are expressed, and measures their
concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philosophically, it's quite simple,'' said Chief Executive
Officer Norrie Russell. ``Technically, it's a bitch to get it
working.''
</P>
<P>
   The process begins with polymer beads so tiny it would take 40
of them to equal the width of a human hair. To each microscopic
bead _ and the process requires many thousands _ Lynx attaches
short DNA tags. Think of these DNA tags as smart Velcro. Ordinary
Velcro is indiscriminate. Any two pieces will bind. But Lynx's
Velcro is particular. Each DNA tag will only bind to a specific
mate.
</P>
<P>
   Once Lynx has tagged the beads, it's only half done. It must
also append tags to the whole stew of genes being studied. There
may be thousands, or tens of thousands, of expressed genes in the
study sample. Lynx gives each gene a unique tag _ which corresponds
to a tag on one of the beads.
</P>
<P>
   So when the beads are thrown into the study sample, each gene
mates with a unique, matching bead. ``They Velcro together,''
Russell said, smacking his palms together.
</P>
<P>
   The beads provide Lynx with a way to fish genes out of the
sample. Other equipment sorts the beads and measures the prevalence
of the various genes in the sample. In a comparison of healthy and
sick breast cells, for instance, the side-by-side measurements
might reveal whether too much of one gene or too little of another
is a possible culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gives the drug companies the hints as to where to
focus their studies,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Piece of cake, right? Well, not exactly. In the official
warnings it's required to send potential investors, Lynx says its
technology is ``new and unproven'' and ``in too early a stage to
determine whether it can be successfully implemented'' to discover
potential drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But that's legal boilerplate. If investors heeded such warnings,
Wall Street would still be a fish market. Indeed, Lynx is already
selling its DNA analysis services out of its Hayward headquarters.
It has three clients so far, pharmaceutical firms willing to pay
millions of dollars a year to see whether Lynx's beads can help
sort a variety of genetic puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   Lynx production manager Keith Moon showed me through the
74,000-square-foot office and lab space where the firm's 100-person
staff juggles billions of microscopic beads. For the grand finale,
I sat at a microscope where the tiny beads are magnified 3,000
times, watching one magical step in the sorting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the money shot,'' Moon joked, the image that wows
potential clients or investors.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity more investors haven't had a chance to look through
that lens, otherwise Lynx stock might be in better shape. The
company's shares, which have been lolling around the mid to upper
20s, closed at $29.25 on Friday. Back in the heady days of spring,
when biotech ruled, Lynx nearly hit $100 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Lynx sought to capitalize on its soaring stock with a secondary
offering, but by the time it was ready, the Nasdaq had tanked. Lynx
withdrew its filing at the end of March. ``At these prices, it
wasn't worth it,'' said Chief Financial Officer Ed Albini.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is nursing some $30 million in cash, which at
its present expense rate would carry it through 2001. Russell will
presumably be out in the meantime, trying to sign up new drug
clients, while Albini keeps a lid on expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Other than proving the technology works _ Lynx must be dying to
make some stunning, money-making discovery that couldn't be done
any other way _ the only other problem is competition.
</P>
<P>
   Differential gene expression was such an obvious next step in
the discovery process that there are at least two dozen firms that
have come up with technologies to address this need. Most of them
use special computer chips that react in the presence of genes.
</P>
<P>
   These gene-chip systems have been in the field for years. Lynx
will have to prove that its beads can measure more genes than the
gene chips. But the technical pros and cons of the two technologies
are as subtle as the old debates about how many angels can sit on
the head of a pin. Mere mortals will be hard pressed to follow that
debate.
</P>
<P>
   But gene chip vendors, like Affymetrix Inc. of Santa Clara,
Calif., have one obvious advantage. They sell equipment that drug
research firms can use on their own premises for gene comparison
work _ as opposed to Lynx, which requires customers to bring the
work to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe researchers, being the very particular folks they
are, are going to want to do the experiments themselves,'' said
Affymetrix spokeswoman Anne Bowdidge.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, the Lynx chief executive officer, argued that his
technology is so powerful that potential customers won't mind
mailing their tissue samples to Hayward. That argument will be more
powerful when and if he has more than three paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who quit a plum research post at AstraZeneca
Pharmaceuticals to become Lynx's top salesman, said he has no doubt
that Lynx will win over clients, humble skeptics and make
stockholders rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology unshackled me from my golden handcuffs at the
third-largest drug company in the world,'' he said. ``This had to
be good.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
