<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-MEXICO-BANK-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH BANK WINS AUCTION FOR MEXICAN BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FINEREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A Spanish bank, Banco Santander Central Hispano,
has won a government auction for Mexico's oldest and third-largest
bank, Grupo Financiero Serfin, trumping a rival bid from the
British-based HSBC Holdings PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Santander will pay $1.56 billion to the government for all of
Serfin's stock, equivalent to 1.59 times the bank's book value, the
government bank bailout agency announced on Monday. The new bank
will have a 16 percent share of the Mexican banking market.
</P>
<P>
   With the auction, Mexico joins the quickening pace of
consolidation among banks in the hemisphere, as foreign banks
jockey for position with national banks. Last week the nation's
largest financial group, Grupo Financiero Banamex-Accival, made a
surprise bid to buy the second-largest bank, Grupo Financiero
Bancomer, challenging a merger between Bancomer and another Spanish
bank, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of Serfin increases the foreign participation in
the Mexican banking sector to nearly 50 percent, finance officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts saw the Serfin sale as a watershed for Mexico's
banks, which have had a slow recovery from the peso devaluation and
economic shock of 1995. The sale, along with new banking laws which
expedite bankruptcies and ease loan collection, ``effectively means
the banking crisis is over,'' said Brent B. Erensel at Deutsche
Bank Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Serfin employs 18,000 people in 569 branches serving 2.5 million
customers across Mexico. The Bank Savings Protection Institute took
control of Serfin in July 1999 after the bank ran into debt
problems stemming from the 1995 crisis, when spiraling interest
rates and a wave of defaults crippled the Mexican banking sector.
</P>
<P>
   In its 10 months of oversight, the agency poured $13 billion
into the bank to make it financially sound and attractive to
buyers. Serfin now has one of the lowest levels of past-due loans
of all the country's banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following the restructuring efforts, Serfin is one of the most
solid and healthy enterprises of the Mexican banking system,''
Santander directors said in a press release from Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Santander will pay for 25 percent of the stock within 20 days
and 75 percent during the following 30 days. The loser in the
Serfin bid, HSBC, will sell the 20 percent stake it already has in
Serfin to Santander for $137 million, a figure that was set by the
government agency when it took over Serfin. HSBC will receive that
payment within 10 days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the exact price offered by HSBC was not disclosed, the
bid they submitted was lower than Santander's. Still, analysts said
that HSBC had not lost interest in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Boni at Credit Lyonnais Securities said the big question
is whether Banamex and Bancomer, Mexico's two largest banks, will
complete the merger that Banamex proposed last week. The
combination could create the largest financial group in Latin
America. If that deal goes through, Boni said, Santander and other
foreign banks will likely look at other acquisitions in Mexico to
increase their market share.
</P>
</TEXT>
