<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-WIRELESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH 21: WELCOME TO MY WIRELESS WORLD  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not counting the answering machine, the VCR and
the burglar alarm, there have been three technological revolutions
in my household over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The first, of course, was getting a computer at home. The second
was instant access to the Internet _ originally with ISDN, now with
DSL. (The latter is much faster, of course, but it was the former
that brought about the qualitative change: letting us on the Web in
a blink, just by opening a browser, without having to wait for
conventional modems to perform their mating rituals.)
</P>
<P>
   Those changes involved amply publicized technologies. That's not
the case with the third epochal change, which has occurred just in
the past six months: Our laptops can now talk to each other and the
Internet from anywhere in the house, or even our modest yard,
without dragging around cables.
</P>
<P>
   They do so through a wireless local-area network. It's linked to
the wired network that connects my desktop machines and thus to the
DSL line. The net effect: We no longer have to sit at a desk to get
fast, easy access to the Internet. My wife, using her Apple iBook,
can do her e-mail from her papasan chair. Sitting on the living
room couch, with my 3-pound Compaq notebook in my lap, I can watch
the tube with one eye and surf the Web with the other.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we both sit at the kitchen table and do our online
chores simultaneously. And since the weather has warmed up, I've
begun setting up shop on the patio.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, wireless networking isn't brand new; for several
years, a variety of other technologies have promised similar
benefits. But each in its own way entailed serious compromises in
scope, speed and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   What we have now is a no-compromise solution. For an online
junkie like me, it's bliss. Even my wife, who's anything but a
techie, says she loves it.
</P>
<P>
   What made it all possible is a new standard carrying the catchy
name of IEEE 802.11b. It defines a way to move data wirelessly at
up to 11 megabits per second _ faster, in theory, than a standard
office Ethernet. In practice, it's a bit slower than a wired
network, but the difference is hardly noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Apple was first to market with this technology, which, with
characteristic cleverness, it calls AirPort. Every Mac model,
desktop and notebook now has a special slot for the AirPort add-on
card, which is priced at $99. The flying-saucer-style AirPort Base
Station, a stand-alone device that lets up to 10 card-carrying Macs
(or, as I discovered, PCs) get online without wires, is $299.
</P>
<P>
   (Anyone who thinks Apple's revival is all about colors, curves
and cutesy ads should take note _ this is real innovation. Apple
didn't invent the technology _ it gets its AirPort cards straight
from Lucent. But Steve Jobs et al deserve a lot of credit for
seeing the potential in the technology, integrating it into their
hardware and software, and bringing it to market at prices that
have competitors gasping.)
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a new Mac to enjoy the benefits of 802.11b,
though. Lucent offers a similar card for the PCMCIA slots found in
most PC notebooks as well as pre-AirPort Apple PowerBooks. It used
to be called the WaveLAN Turbo, and the Web site is still
 &LR; www.wavelan.com &LR; , but Lucent recently gave its whole wireless
family a jauntier moniker, Orinoco.
</P>
<P>
   There are two versions, called Silver and Gold, depending on the
level of encryption you want; I tried the Silver version, which
lists for $179. To add wireless capability to a desktop PC, you'll
need the PCMCIA card plus an adapter that goes in a PCI or ISA slot
($69 each).
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, two other companies that offer 802.11b products
are 3Com and Aironet, which was recently acquired by Cisco. 3Com's
AirConnect PC Card is $219; there's no desktop adapter yet.
Aironet's PC Card, which has strong encryption, lists for $249, and
its desktop cards for $349.
</P>
<P>
   The best deal I know of for PC users comes from Dell, which
sells a version of the Aironet cards with less robust encryption as
the Dell 4800LT line. I recently tried out a pair of them _ a $139
PC Card in an Inspiron 3800 notebook and a $179 PCI version in my
desktop PC _ and they worked fine.
</P>
<P>
   There are just two catches for PC users who want to get on the
wireless bandwagon:
</P>
<P>
   One is that these products are surprisingly hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   You can, however, find pointers to some dealers, online and off,
at  &LR; www.wavelan.com/contact/ &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   As for Dell, for some reason it doesn't list its 4800LT products
separately on its Web site, but I'm told they're offered as an
option if you order a new Inspiron notebook. Or you can do what I
did: Just call Dell at (800) 999-3355 and order the cards that way.
Some of the documentation makes it sound as if you need a
Dell-branded PC or notebook, but you don't _ I have the PCI card in
a non-Dell desktop, and I've used the PC Card in Windows laptops
from three vendors in addition to Dell.
</P>
<P>
   The other catch is that no one besides Apple now offers a base
station, or network access point, for less than $1,000. Unless you
want to spend that kind of money, you have to use a PC with a modem
or broadband Internet connection and an 802.11b adapter in a PCI or
ISA slot as your access point. That's a cheap solution, and it
worked as advertised in my tests; the only real downside is that it
doesn't work unless you leave your PC running.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't suit you, your best bet is probably to wait a
few weeks, when Lucent's Orinoco RG-1000, a ``residential gateway''
with a list price of $349, should hit the market.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible to use Apple's $299 base station with Windows
PCs, as I've been doing, but there are several complexities,
especially if you want your wireless traffic encrypted. The details
are too geeky to go into here, but if you really need to know,
e-mail me and I'll tell you what's worked for me and what hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: For a few hundred extra dollars, anyone with a
notebook computer can now get Internet access anywhere around the
house. It's fast (as fast as your wired Internet connection,
anyway), it's reliable and it's hugely liberating.
</P>
<P>
   Standards Soup
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about standards, tech-industry wags often joke,
is that there are so many to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more true than in the wireless
data-communications arena.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile-phone industry, of course, is the worst offender _ it
has more wide-area communications standards than I have fingers,
and lots of new ones are in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But local-area wireless developers seem to be doing their best
to catch up: Not even counting the original, slower 802.11 (no
``b'') wireless Ethernet spec, there are already two major
alternatives to 802.11b: HomeRF, which is just getting off the
ground in the consumer market, and Bluetooth, an even newer
technology that will begin appearing in cell phones, notebooks and
Palm products, among others, over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   All three of these technologies operate in the 2.4-gigahertz
portion of the spectrum. Unfortunately, that means that, at least
in their current form, they're not fully compatible. At a minimum,
experts tell me, the performance of each will suffer if one of the
others is in use nearby.
</P>
<P>
   What's really mind-boggling is that all three of these standards
have been under development for years. In some cases (notably, but
not exclusively, Intel) different groups within the very same
company have been working on each technology. Yet only recently has
the industry really started to take the compatibility problem
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the microwave-oven issue: The devices, already
installed in nearly every household likely to be interested in
wireless networking (except mine), also give off 2.4-gigahertz
signals.
</P>
<P>
   At least the industry is working on that one: The latest version
of Lucent's Orinoco configuration software includes a checkbox for
``Microwave Oven Robustness.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
