u f BC-RATES-MARKETPLACE-NYT     05-08 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATES-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: INTEREST RATE INCREASES HINT AT EVENTUAL SLOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
  By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cost of financing is on the rise for consumers
and companies.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark rate on 30-year home mortgages, at 8.65 percent,
is the highest since early 1995, and the yields on junk bonds, at
an average of 12.79 percent, are well above their levels back then.
Corporate bond yields, at 8.89 percent, are also approaching their
early 1995 marks.
</P>
<P>
   These are all signs that the Federal Reserve's interest rate
increases, five moves of a quarter point since last June, are
beginning to have an impact on the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the higher rates have not yet led to a significant drag on
the overall economy, in part because market rates have risen to
their 5-year highs very recently and in part because the stock
market has been so resilient that consumers have been unbowed.
Although growth has slowed somewhat since the fourth quarter, the
economy grew at a 5.4 percent annual rate in the first quarter. And
in the most significant data since then, 340,000 new jobs were
created last month as the unemployment rate fell to a 30-year low
of 3.9 percent, the government reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of bite in monetary policy, even more than the recent
signs of inflationary pressures in wages, has led many analysts to
predict that the Fed will push up its target for short-term
interest rates much further then its current 6 percent before the
economy will slow to an acceptable noninflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   With Fed policy makers scheduled to meet next Tuesday, the
debate has shifted to whether they will raise their target by half
a percentage point instead of just a quarter point.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rise in the yield on the futures contract of federal
funds shows that many investors expect the central bank's target
rate to be 7 percent by November.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has moved cautiously until now partly because it saw few
signs of inflationary pressures other than the spurt in crude oil
and gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence H. Meyer, a Fed governor, acknowledged in a speech last
month that ``the current episode is the smallest and most gradual
tightening'' since the late 1960s. ``So the modest effects on
aggregate demand to date perhaps only confirm the relatively modest
and extremely gradual nature of the current tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the increases in the Fed's target rate, the Federal
funds rate, seem to have had less impact than in the past. ``Some
developments,'' Meyer said, ``suggest that the recent policy moves
may have had a more limited effect on aggregate demand than would
have been expected.''
</P>
<P>
   To measure the impact of monetary policy, one has to look at
what effect a rise in the federal funds rate, which is the rate on
overnight loans between banks, has on broader financial conditions,
including interest rates, stock prices and the dollar's exchange
rate. Meyer said one gauge of the impact, the Goldman Sachs
financial conditions index, ``is not only at the very low end of
historical experience, but is nearly unchanged'' since June.
</P>
<P>
   ``So a second conclusion about the current experience,'' Meyer
said, ``is that the increase in the funds rate, to date, has had a
smaller effect than usual _ nearly zero _ on overall financial
conditions and hence on aggregate demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to the Fed's last episode of tightening help make
the point. From February 1994 to March 1995, policy makers raised
the Federal funds rate target to 6 percent from 3 percent. By
December 1994, new mortgage applications had fallen 20.3 percent
from their year-earlier level, according to John Lonski, senior
economist at Moody's Investors Service.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than slowing, the rate has actually grown recently. New
applications rose 9.2 percent in the 12 months ended in April,
despite the rise in the interest rate on a 30-year, Fannie Mae
mortgage to 8.65 percent from 6.90 percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Even though mortgage and corporate rates are rising, they have
not yet reached their peaks of the 1994-95 Fed tightening. The
Fannie Mae 30-year rate topped out at 9.29 percent in December
1994. The rate on long-term industrial bonds rated by Moody's as
Baa, its lowest investment grade rating, reached 9.37 in November
1994. (But the yields on the poorest quality corporate credits
known as junk bonds are more than three-quarters of a percentage
point higher than the 11.98 percent peak in January 1995, according
to Chase Manhattan's high-yield index.)
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most important reason the Fed's interest rate
increases have had little effect is that stocks have failed to
crumble, another factor noted by Meyer. ``Equity prices have been
unusually resilient in this episode, rising by an amount near the
maximum during the first nine months of significant tightenings
over the period studied,'' he said. While the Dow is down 3.3
percent since the end of June, the Nasdaq is up 36.6 percent, and
the Wilshire 5000, which includes all domestic stocks, is up 5.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   William Dudley, chief U.S. economist at Goldman Sachs, said
Monday the Fed would have to raise its Fed funds target to 7.5
percent next year, which means another 1.5 percentage points, to
slow the economy. Like several economists, he raised his projection
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley said the Fed's moves had had so little impact so far
because ``the bond and stock markets are so trusting'' of Alan
Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve. Investors, he said,
believe the Fed will keep inflation in check, but not push interest
rates so high as to cause a recession. ``So they are not worried
about inflation and they are not worried about a hard landing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neil M. Soss, chief U.S. economist at Credit Suisse First
Boston, said, ``we haven't seen much effect in the real economy
yet'' because consumers, who have powered much of this record
economic expansion, have not gotten a signal from financial markets
to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   But the surge in mortgage rates in the last two weeks, from 8.09
percent to 8.65 percent, may show that the Fed's message is finally
coming through, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
