<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TESTERS-GAMES-SFCHRON     05-08 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTERS-GAMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GAME TESTERS SCORE BY CATCHING BUGS  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gabrielle Brown punched a few buttons on the
handset of her Dreamcast, sending the skateboarder in the video
game up a ramp and into a gnarly, 360-degree spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is pretty clean,'' she said, as the skater attempted
another jump, then fell and injured himself. ``But sometimes his
blood comes out a little chunky.''
</P>
<P>
   Programmers at San Francisco's Sega of America probably won't
improve the fluidity of the skater's blood in Tony Hawk Pro Skater,
part of a demo that ships with the console.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't stopping Brown from looking for all sorts of
anomalies, from see-through walls and misspelled words to ``Grade
A'' bugs _ the kind that crash the game and keep programmers up
until 3 a.m. combing through thousands of lines of software code.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, and thousands more video-game testers like her, are the
last line of defense against bugs in the $7.4 billion-a-year and
growing video-game industry.
</P>
<P>
   Like word processing or spreadsheet software, games must undergo
rigorous testing before hitting retail shelves. And with game
companies now finishing up their holiday titles _ many of which
will be showcased at this week's Electronic Entertainment Expo in
Los Angeles _ it's officially testing season.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Sega and Redwood City, Calif.'s Electronic
Arts, the No. 1 video-game publisher in the United States, have
large in-house testing departments. Smaller firms often farm out
the work or rely on large publishers like EA to market, distribute
and handle the bulk of testing for a title.
</P>
<P>
   Managers at EA hired 40 game testers during one week in
mid-April. Late this summer, the EA test department will peak at
about 250.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Brown _ a rare example of a female tester _ most in the
industry are late teen and twentysomething guys with highly
developed eye-hand coordination, who decorate their desks with
``Star Wars'' action figures and play volleyball during lunch.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, they get paid to play video games.
</P>
<P>
   But if it sounds like the dream job for every 16-year-old
slacker you know, remember this: The money isn't great, and the
responsibilities are real.
</P>
<P>
   From initial conceptual drawings to final marketing blitz, a
typical game costs about $1 million and takes eight to 24 months to
develop. If it doesn't flow well or ships chock-full of glitches,
the company risks negative buzz. Although sometimes not. Grand
Turismo II, a driving game for Sony's PlayStation, doesn't allow
users to play the very last portion of the game. But that fact
hasn't kept it from becoming one of the top-selling games in the
genre.
</P>
<P>
   Testers _ whose work accounts for about $50,000 to $100,000 of
the overall cost of a game, according to EA officials _ help solve
both technical and ``gameplay'' problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In your good restaurants you have an executive chef who tastes
what everyone is doing,'' said Murray Allen, vice president of
postproduction, testing and technical support at EA. Testers ``are
the taste testers of the game. They make sure it's right, because
if a game ships and customers start taking it back to the store,
the stores don't like dealing with the company making that game
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   At most large publishers, the testing process works like this:
once a rough version of a game, or ``alpha,'' is playable, it moves
from the developers to the test department. There, testers play
through each level over and over. And over and over.
</P>
<P>
   When they find a problem (and it's always ``when,'' not ``if'')
they type up a short report that goes into the ``bug'' database.
The report details how the tester found the malfunction, how often
it popped up, and how detrimental it is to the game. Grade A bugs
are the worst: They freeze up the computer or console.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Arts has five grading levels; other companies have
fewer. At EA, an ``E'' level bug is considered fairly low priority.
Often, it's a tester's opinion on an object _ like Brown's feedback
on the blood _ or design. For example, a tester may comment that
it's too difficult to find a key that lets the player move to the
next level.
</P>
<P>
   Programmers consult the database and correct the glitches. The
fixed version goes back to the tester, who then checks that the bug
is gone and that no more have cropped up. This process continues
right up through the launch _ and sometimes afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Problematic bugs found after the launch can be fixed with a
downloadable ``patch,'' a chunk of code inserted into the program.
</P>
<P>
   If playing through a single game or battle sequence seems like a
really repetitive way to spend eight hours or more, well, it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have to run the character along the way for an
entire level to make sure it stays the same,'' said Joe Funk,
editorial director of Electronic Gaming Monthly. ``Video-game
testing sounds cool on the surface, but when you're working on the
same game and character for 120 days in a row, it gets tiresome.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, many testers swear off the games they've
tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alpha Centauri, that's a game I'll never play again,''
grumbled Dave McCormick, a 24-year-old tester at Electronic Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Right now McCormick is working on the company's Shogun Total War
title.
</P>
<P>
   In the game, players maneuver battalions of archers and
musketeers through 16th century Japan in an effort to conquer the
enemy. So far, McCormick and the other testers working on the game
have found about 1,100 bugs, ranging from raindrops that look like
black blobs to musketeers who won't fire when it's snowing.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a bug is ``like a little victory,'' said 27-year-old
Daryl Humdy, who, with 44 bugs has one of the highest ``bug
counts'' on his Shogun team. ``If something goes out you can say,
`That's my bug.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to high tolerance for endless hours in front of a
computer or TV screen, bug-hunting requires a certain amount of
creativity, according to the testers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think of the silliest things in the world to see
if it breaks the game, like driving a race car the whole time in
reverse to see what it does,'' said Chris Lovenguth, product
analyst at San Francisco's Eidos, creator of the popular Tomb
Raider game series.
</P>
<P>
   However, even the most enthusiastic game testers admit there are
drawbacks to the profession. At the end of a typical four-month
testing period, it's common for testers _ or quality assurance
analysts as they're sometimes called _ to work 70- or 80-hour
weeks. The overtime is nice, but it makes for strange sleeping
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhausting for them,'' Allen admits. ``That's why they
have futons around so that they can crash for a while. Sometimes
they just crawl under their desks for a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   The long hours can also make for some tense working conditions,
especially when testers are crammed wall to wall during crunch
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the final two weeks (of testing) and you find
another bug, you know it's going to put the project back a couple
of days, and the production department doesn't like you, marketing
doesn't like you,'' Lovenguth said. ``You're doing your job, but no
one likes you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the industry's bugaboo: piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Computer and video-game publishers say they lost $3 billion last
year worldwide to illegal copies of yet-to-be-released games. And
testers are perceived as a weak link in the chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testers come under a lot of fire because we have the game all
the time and people think that if an early version of the game gets
out, it was us,'' McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   To combat that, only testing supervisors can sign in or out
so-called ``key disks'' which let testers play the games.
</P>
<P>
   Funk estimates most testers make $20,000 to $25,000 a year; in
the Bay Area, where the cost of living is notoriously high, Funk
said it could be slightly more.
</P>
<P>
   Testers can earn more, but it takes time and persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Most start out as temporary workers. After about a year at a
fairly large company, they can move into a full-time position _ and
receive a decent bump in pay.
</P>
<P>
   After another year, it's not uncommon to be promoted into
supervisory testing positions or other departments such as
production, information technology or marketing, according to
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Abney was one of the first testers in Electronic Arts'
centralized quality assurance department in the mid-1990s. (Before
that, the company's testers were tied to development teams
scattered all over the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Abney expressed an interest in hardware and helped set up EA's
compatibility lab, where the company makes sure each game works on
an array of computers and video cards.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Abney, 27, is manager of technology development, where he
coordinates hardware purchases for EA's developers and programmers
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   EA officials estimate one tester moves up every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video-game testing isn't as glamorous as it may appear on
first sight,'' Funk said. ``At the same time, glamour is in the eye
of the beholder. You can take advantage of kids' enthusiasm _ `Wow,
I'm getting a paycheck from Nintendo.' And if they're smart, they
can parlay that into something else.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
