<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9402 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BIGDIG-FINANCING-BOS &LR;      05-08 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-FINANCING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE PRESSURED TO PRODUCE `BIG DIG' FINANCE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a two-pronged salvo with multibillion-dollar
implications, US highway officials and a powerful congressman
Monday moved independently to halt federal funding for the ``Big
Dig'' if Massachusetts fails to rapidly produce an adequate plan to
resolve the project's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Highway Administration set May 19 as the last day
the state will receive federal aid for the highway renovation
project in the absence of an acceptable plan to finish the $13.1
billion venture. The project is plagued by an overrun as large as
$2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise initiative, Representative Frank R. Wolf, a
Virginia Republican who chairs the House panel that controls
highway spending, proposed cutting all federal dollars for the Big
Dig in the next fiscal year, starting Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves increased the urgency for the state Legislature and
Governor Paul Celluci to swiftly generate a bailout plan for the
financially strapped venture. A conference committee has been
working for several weeks to try to resolve differences between
competing state House and Senate plans. Cellucci must sign the
final product.
</P>
<P>
   Either spending freeze could substantially slow the pace of
construction, if not force managers to significantly scale back the
design of the Big Dig, the largest public works project in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Big Dig officials, though clearly stunned by Wolf's plan,
expressed optimism that they can avert a potentially devastating
interruption of federal support for the project. Congress has
approved $8.55 billion for the Big Dig, of which about $3.5 billion
remains to be spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take very seriously the concerns of Congress and federal
highway officials about the credibility of the project and the
project managers,'' said Joe Landolfi, spokesman for Big Dig chief
Andrew Natsios. ``We hope that the passage of an acceptable finance
plan, which we expect in the next week or so, will help to address
most of their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said last week in Washington that he expected the state
House and Senate to produce a bill by May 19. And Alison Franklin,
a spokeswoman for Senate President Thomas Birmingham, said Monday
that the conference committee is poised to complete the bailout
plan ``in the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Massachusetts leaders fail to reach agremeent on an
acceptable plan, the Big Dig could cushion the blow of a federal
freeze after May 19 by relying temporarily on state funds. Under
the freeze proposed by the Federal Highway Administration, in a
letter Monday to Natsios, the Big Dig could spend federal dollars
that have been earmarked for current contracts but could not tap
federal aid for additional work.
</P>
<P>
   The highway agency's vow to freeze Big Dig funding was contained
in a letter formally rejecting a bailout plan that Cellucci had
proposed in March. Reiterating steps the state must take to resolve
numerous inadequacies in Cellucci's plan, the letter states,
``Documentation that these actions have been completed must be
provided to the Federal Highway Administration by May 19, 2000, or
we will freeze'' spending.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's plan could be more drastic. By halting federal funding
for the project in fiscal 2001, Congress would take away about $325
million that it previously had authorized for the project. The
money would still flow to the state as part of the annual federal
transportation subsidy, but it could be used only for road and
highway projects other than the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the state is expected to receive about $500 million in
federal highway money in fiscal 2001, of which about $175 million
normally would be set aside for non-Big Dig work. But if Wolf's
initiative succeeds, all $500 million would be used for roadwork
other than the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, one of the Big Dig's harshest congressional critics,
portrayed his move as a way to protect ``the taxpayer from waste,
fraud and abuse.'' Citing a federal task force report last month
that accused former Big Dig managers of intentionally concealing
the massive overrun and US highway officials of failing to detect
the concealment, Wolf said his plan to halt federal funds ``puts
the Congress on record to make sure that we deal effectively with
the problem of cost overruns.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's spokeswoman, Elizabeth Morra, said of his plan: ``This is
not meant to be punitive. It's meant to keep the project's
manager's feet to the fire, and if they were to come up with a new
financial plan that covers the cost increases and ensures a solid
statewide highway program, then the funds can flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative John W. Olver of Massachusetts, the second most
senior Democrat on Wolf's committee, voted for the proposal to cut
off federal funding for the Big Dig in fiscal 2001. The vote came
during a hearing on a $15 billion transportation spending package
for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is essentially saying, `Hey, this is
serious,' '' Olver said of the Big Dig's financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the federal highway agency's ultimatum, which gives the
state less than two weeks to construct an acceptable plan, Olver
said, Wolf's provision offers a five-month window for action. ``If
five months from now, they have done nothing, and if this measure
were to survive the rest of the legislative process, then they
wouldn't be able to expend any federal money on the Big Dig,''
Olver said. ``But everybody hopes we will have a finance plan in
place by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Massachusetts congressional delegation were
less receptive of Wolf's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Withholding committed federal funds is not in the interest of
any taxpayer,'' said Senator Edward M. Kennedy. ``I am confident
that we will be successful in removing this harmful provision from
the final bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry vowed to use stalling tactics, if
necessary, to kill Wolf's measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``With construction over 60 percent complete and 98.6 percent of
the design already complete, any effort to freeze federal funding
at this point is short-sighted and fiscally irresponsible,'' Kerry
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
