<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9403 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVESTING-DOMASH-SFCH     05-08 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-DOMASH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE INVESTING: INTERNET ENGINES TRACK PERFORMANCE OF
SELECTED  STOCKS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Among the many tools the Internet offers
investors, one of the most powerful is screening, the ability to
search through the entire market for stocks that meet your personal
investment needs. But how do you know what to search for?
</P>
<P>
   I ran tests to see how investors would have fared if they had
used screening criteria available at no charge on CNBC's Advanced
Search program to select stocks on May 1, 1999, and then sold them
at their closing price on April 17, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   I used ProSearch, a feature of Telescan Investor's Platform, to
run the tests. (For more information on Telescan, go to
 &LR; www.telescan.com &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   For example, let's say I wanted to find out what kind of return
I would have received by selecting stocks with the highest
price/earnings ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Using ProSearch, I would set up these parameters for this
search. I would set the program at the 255-stock maximum and then
select high price/ earnings ratio as the screening criterion.
</P>
<P>
   The program would then show me a list of 255 stocks with the
highest P/E as of May 1, 1999. It would also show each stock's
performance from then until April 17, 2000, as well as the average
return of the 255-stock portfolio over the period.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by Telescan, CNBC's Advanced Search employs a subset of
more than 60 of ProSearch's screening variables. To get to the
screening program from CNBC's homepage ( &LR; www.cnbc.com &LR; ), select
``Stocks,'' then ``Stock Screener'' and finally ``Advanced
Search.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the variables I found to be the most significant. The
name of each is shown in parentheses as it appears on CNBC's
screening page.
</P>
<P>
   -- One-Year Historical Earnings Growth (EPS Growth 1 Yr)
</P>
<P>
   The 255 companies with the highest one-year historical earnings
growth (179 percent plus), as of May 1, 1999, soared 87.8 percent
during the test period, compared to a loss of 4.3 percent for
companies with one-year earnings growth below 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- 5-Year Historical Annual Earnings Growth (EPS Growth 5 Yr)
</P>
<P>
   Companies with the highest five-year historical annual earnings
growth (68.9 percent plus) returned 30.7 percent, compared to a
loss of 4.3 percent suffered by companies with low five-year
earnings growth (0.1 to 5.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   -- Current Ratio (Current Ratio)
</P>
<P>
   Current Ratio compares a company's assets, such as cash,
inventories and accounts receivable, to its short-term debts.
Ratios above 1.0 mean the company assets exceed its debts (which is
good), and values below 1.0 indicate the company owes more than it
has (which is bad). The 255 stocks with the highest current ratios
(7.0 and higher) soared 58.4 percent during the test period, while
companies with the lowest ratios (0.1 to 0.2) rose only 7.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- Long-Term Debt (Debt/Equity Ratio)
</P>
<P>
   Long-term debt as measured by the debt/equity ratio mattered,
but less so. Companies with no long-term debt (debt/equity of 0)
rose 23.6 percent, compared to a 12.1 percent gain for high-debt
(ratios of 39.0 to 50.0) companies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gross Profit Margin (Gross Profit Margin)
</P>
<P>
   Gross Profit Margin measures the profit earned from making or
selling products before deducting for operating expenses such as
marketing, research, administration and the like. The 255 companies
with the highest GPMs (80 percent plus) returned 47.1 percent
during the year, compared to 3.6 percent for companies with low
margins (below 12.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
   -- Return on Equity (Return on Equity)
</P>
<P>
   Return on Equity is an oft-used performance measure calculated
by dividing corporate earnings by shareholders' equity. The problem
with ROE is, all things being equal, higher-debt companies have
higher ROE than companies with no debt. That shows up in the
results. The 255 companies with the highest ROEs (35 plus) returned
only 11 percent, compared to low ROE (0.1 to 2.6) companies' 19.4
percent return during the test period.
</P>
<P>
   -- Return on Assets (Return on Assets)
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Return on Assets is a better gauge than ROE,
because it measures how effectively management is using assets, a
calculation not influenced by debt levels. The results confirm that
conclusion. High ROA (18.1 plus) companies returned 32.9 percent,
compared to a loss of 4.9 percent for low ROE (0.1 to 2.6) firms.
</P>
<P>
   -- Price Earnings Ratio (P/E Ratio)
</P>
<P>
   High-priced aggressive growth stocks have outperformed
value-priced stocks in recent years. Our tests bear that out.
Companies with high price/earnings ratios (86 plus) returned 57.3
percent during the test period, compared to 2.9 percent for
companies with low P/Es (below 7.6).
</P>
<P>
   -- Price-to-Sales Ratio (Price/Sales Ratio)
</P>
<P>
   Price-to-sales ratios have become a popular valuation measure,
since many new companies do not have earnings, making it impossible
to compute P/E. Companies with high P/S (17.6 plus) returned 50.5
percent, compared to a loss of 15.6 percent for value-priced
companies with the lowest P/S (0.1 to 0.2).
</P>
<P>
   -- Relative Stock Price Performance (Rel Performance 1 Yr)
</P>
<P>
   Many successful selection strategies involve picking stocks that
have already gone up the most during the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC's Relative Performance measures a stock's price
appreciation, but the definition is a little tricky. A relative
performance of 100 means the stock price didn't change from the
beginning to the end of the year ending May 1, 1999 (in our case),
while 200 means the stock price doubled, and 50 means the price
dropped in half.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth figuring it out.
</P>
<P>
   The 255 stocks with the highest one-year relative performance
(RP values of 209 plus) rocketed 97.6 percent during the test
period, compared to a 6.3 percent return for stocks with middling
(100 to 125) relative performance, and 20.2 percent gain for the
stocks with the worst (0.3 to 34.7) relative performance over the
12 months prior to May 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to run a search once you've decided on your screening
criteria. You can require specific values, or select ``High as
Possible'' or ``Low as Possible'' for criteria of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Leave blank anything you don't care about. For instance, you can
require a minimum value for Current Ratio, but you don't have to
specify a maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Select the number of stocks you want to see listed before
clicking on Search Now to run the screen. Leave the Report Format
set to the default ``Table'' setting.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC lists the stocks meeting your requirements, sorted with the
best fits at the top. Above the list is a chart showing the returns
you would have achieved buying the stocks turned up by the screen
if you had run it on the first of each month, for 12 months back
and then sold the stocks today.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned investors know that the results of any screen, no
matter how well thought out, is simply a list of investment
candidates, not a buy list.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Harry Domash at  &LR; hdomash(AT)winninginvesting.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
