<SLUG> BC-NY-COWS-HORSES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE HORSES IN NEW YORK ARE BEING READIED FOR COW IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Md.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A city police horse has seen just about everything,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not a life-size fiberglass cow, painted in fanciful
colors.
</P>
<P>
   So, in preparation for an art exhibition of 500 such cows
scattered throughout the five boroughs, bemused mounted officers
and their equally bemused horses have some new stablemates these
days.
</P>
<P>
   At a similar exhibition in Chicago last summer, the strange
sight spooked some of the carriage horses carrying tourists along
Michigan Avenue. To avoid such problems here, sample fiberglass
cows were sent to New York's mounted police units so the horses
could get used to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These horses are used to seeing all kinds of construction,
cement trucks, crowds,'' said Deputy Inspector Peter J. Abbot, the
mounted unit commander, at the unit's headquarters on West 42nd
Street last week. ``An inanimate cow is not really going to rock
their world.''
</P>
<P>
   Right on cue, a chestnut horse nibbled on the horns of a white,
unpainted cow, apparently under the impression it was a large salt
lick.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown at the Troop A stables, next to the First Precinct
Headquarters on Varick Street, the steeds were equally blase. At
both places, people remarked that the sculptures looked more like
bulls than cows, at least in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing has big horns,'' said Arlene Greaves, a hostler at
Troop A. ``A female has thin, small horns, little short horns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it has a very masculine face,'' she added firmly.
</P>
<P>
   But Jenny Steinman, an artist who was painting two cows last
week in a work space in a former bank building behind Grand Central
Terminal, said she had been assured by Mark Varner, a bovine expert
at the University of Maryland, that the sculptures were
anatomically correct, horn-wise.
</P>
<P>
   Artists submitted 1,200 possible cow designs. They are paid
$2,000 a cow by the corporations, civic groups, cultural
institutions and other organizations that are, one might say,
ponying up to pay for the exhibition, which opens June 15. Sponsors
choose their own designs, so purple cows are not beyond the pale.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, more than 10 million people saw the exhibition,
called CowParade, generating more than $500 million in tourist
revenue. Of course, Chicago, of stockyards fame, has a long
connection with cattle. New York's relationship with cows is more
tenuous, particularly since the recent shrinkage of the bull
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
