<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GENOME-DRAFT-SFCHRON &LR;      05-08 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-DRAFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW PLAYER IN RACE TO TRACK GENOME  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A dark horse has leaped into the race to make
human genome data widely available to private and academic
researchers, which should hasten the discovery of new cures for
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, Calif.'s DoubleTwist.com will announce Monday that it
has produced a rough draft of 105,000 human genes, by doing a
computer analysis of the 85 percent of raw genome data already in
the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the genome race has been portrayed as a head-to-head
contest between the Human Genome Project _ a network of
government-funded labs that put raw genetic data on the Internet _
and Celera Genomics _ a private firm in Maryland that is
deciphering human DNA but has not yet shared its findings with the
public or the general research community.
</P>
<P>
   Celera is expected to announce any day that it has completely
deciphered the 3 billion-letter genome from end to end. At the same
time, the public genome project is expected to say that it is
nearing completion on its own rough draft of 90 percent of the
human genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   The various players are jockeying for position in advance of an
influential conference of genome scientists that will begin
Thursday at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory on Long Island, N.Y. At
stake is the ability to claim credit for a landmark scientific
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The genome is 3 billion chemical letters _ A, T, G and C _
arranged in a complex code. Understanding that code is a three-step
process of reading the raw letters, putting them in order and
picking out the genes.
</P>
<P>
   Finding genes in the genome's alphabet soup is complicated by
the fact that only 3 to 5 percent of those 3 billion letters are
thought to encode genes. The rest of the letters are called junk
DNA.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTwist Secretly Enters
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTwist secretly entered the race in August, and accelerated
its effort this spring by getting Sun Microsystems to help it build
a supercomputer network. In essence, the Oakland company has
leapfrogged steps one and two, and taken a first pass at separating
the genes from the junk in the 85 percent of the raw genome data
that is already public.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lander, a senior official of the public genome project,
praised DoubleTwist's accomplishment. ``This is fantastic,'' Lander
said. ``The reason the public project produced all this data was to
enable private companies and academics to produce the gene lists
that will fuel biomedical research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this vindicates what the public genome project was
about,'' said Fred Cohen, a professor at the University of
California at San Francisco and a member of DoubleTwist's board.
``It was about putting data into the public domain where a variety
of people could put it to a variety of uses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the hope and promise is that gene-hunting efforts
will lead to new ways to repair faulty genes that cause or
contribute to maladies such as cancer or heart disease. Although
new gene-based drugs will take years to develop and test, the
presumption is that the more researchers who focus on the task, the
faster some of the hype will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Celera President Unaware
</P>
<P>
   Celera President Craig Venter was unaware of DoubleTwist's
effort. But Venter, who is on the verge of announcing his own
milestone, complete assembly of the genome, questioned the
reliability of any gene map produced using public data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing a very quantitative analysis, and the public
database is missing about 25 percent of the genome that's in our
sequences,'' Venter said. ``Any list of genes produced from it
would be incomplete at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, DoubleTwist's chief computer scientist, Nick Tsinoremas
was reluctant to issue any gene count, knowing that subsequent
computer analyses will change the number, purpose and location of
many genes.
</P>
<P>
   Tsinoremas said 65,000 of the genes in DoubleTwist's rough draft
passed through three sets of software programs designed to identify
genes. He assigned these genes a 90 percent probability of
accuracy. The other 40,000 genes only passed one or two sets of
tests, giving them accuracy rates of 50 percent or 75 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTwist timed its announcement to precede the Cold Spring
Harbor conference. The company will explain its methodology then
but has not yet undergone the peer review process that would verify
its approach.
</P>
<P>
   But David B. Lipman, director of the National Center for
Biotechnology Information in Maryland, and the government's chief
genome database scientist, said DoubleTwist was only one of several
private and public centers designing computer programs to find the
genes in the raw public data. DoubleTwist is the first, however, to
say it has a rough draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they have some good people there and they've probably
done a good job of it, but I can't say more until I've seen the
data,'' Lipman said.
</P>
<P>
   Believing's Not Cheap
</P>
<P>
   If seeing is believing, then believing won't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Although DoubleTwist does post some free information on its
site, the company charges $10,000 for a yearly subscription to the
database that contains its gene list. DoubleTwist Chief Executive
Officer John Couch said that while this might seem expensive to the
lay person, the price puts its data within the reach of scientists
at smaller firms who can't make the sort of multimillion dollar
deals Celera has done with a few drug firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an executive I could go two ways with this information,''
Couch said, ``Hog it all, find the genes, patent them and go into
research mode, or put all this information out there in the hands
of scientists and let it explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch said the more scientists who can see gene data, the faster
this knowledge can be used to design new drugs or therapies. He
said DoubleTwist will sell ``heavily discounted'' subscriptions to
academic scientists but declined to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, a computer industry veteran from the early days of Apple
Computer, used his Silicon Valley connections to pull off this
large computing exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Although DoubleTwist started assembling its gene-hunting
software in August, it was not until January that it had ironed out
the bugs. Between January and April, the company spent some $9
million to buy more than 300 advance workstations from Sun
Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, we knew we could do it (the gene analysis) in
three months,'' Couch said.
</P>
<P>
   But given how fast Celera was moving, Couch knew that wasn't
soon enough. So he phoned Ken Okin, a former Apple associate and
now head of Sun's server business, and asked for help.
</P>
<P>
   New Supercomputers
</P>
<P>
   It turned out Sun was bringing three new supercomputers online
at a factory in Oregon. It's standard procedure to run test
programs to ``burn in'' new computers. ``Our software burned in
their supercomputers,'' said Couch, who used the extra computer
power to finish a three-month job in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, the UCSF professor and DoubleTwist board member, said Sun
seemed particularly interested in helping after being told that
Celera relied on Dell and Compaq computers. ``It was the web of
West Coast companies working together to do more than any one of
them could have accomplished,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At DoubleTwist headquarters, exhausted executives were running
on adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to the finish line first,'' said Chief Operating
Officer Robert Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
