 &UR; GENOME _ &LR;  A dark horse has leaped into the race to make human
genome data widely available to private and academic researchers,
which should hasten the discovery of new cures for disease.
Oakland, Calif.'s DoubleTwist.com will announce Monday that it has
produced a rough draft of 105,000 human genes, by doing a computer
analysis of the 85 percent of raw genome data already in the public
domain. &UR; BY TOM ABATE &LR;
