<SLUG> BC-CISCO-ACQUISITION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CISCO'S $6 BILLION DEAL IS COMPANY'S SECOND-LARGEST  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cisco Systems yesterday announced its
second-largest acquisition, snagging a fast-growing Massachusetts
company that makes switches and software to help speed access to
Web sites like Lycos and Delta Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The $6 billion stock deal for ArrowPoint Communications, which
went public five weeks ago, trails only Cisco's $6.9 billion bid
last fall for Cerent, a Petaluma, Calif., optical-networking
company. ArrowPoint helps major Web sites cope with sudden floods
of request for information, hackers and other common problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, the world's largest data networking company, agreed to
pay about $145 per share for ArrowPoint, which was trading at just
$106 per share on Wednesday. ArrowPoint shares had soared 27
percent to $134.81 on Thursday, raising suspicion that word of the
deal may have leaked out early. Shares rose another $5.38, to
$140.38, after the deal was officially announced Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose, Calif.'s Cisco passed up the chance to buy ArrowPoint
about a year ago for a fraction of the price. Executives at both
companies confirmed the companies held talks in the past. Analysts
say they probably disagreed sharply on what ArrowPoint was worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company that we have known about for a long time,''
said Ammar Hanafi, Cisco's vice president for business development.
Hanafi said it decided to approach ArrowPoint again a couple months
ago because customer interest (in the company's products) has
heated up markedly'' in the past 60 to 90 days.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, ArrowPoint's value has skyrocketed.
ArrowPoint doubled its workforce to 337 employees in the past four
months, lined up deals with major Web sites and launched one of the
hottest initial public offerings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint shares tripled in its first day as a public trading
company on March 31, giving the company a market value of $4
billion. Cisco reinitiated negotiations less than a week later,
said ArrowPoint President Lou Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO ``caused a lot of people to take notice,'' Volpi said.
Hanafi insists that Cisco actually approached ArrowPoint just
before the IPO but ArrowPoint executives waved Cisco off until the
stock offering was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the price, Wall Street liked the deal. Cisco
shares climbed $4.13 Friday to $67.75, giving it a market value of
$470 billion, the highest of any technology firm.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, analysts said the deal should help bolster Cisco's
position in a hot market for software that helps major Web sites
manage their traffic. It also helps Cisco offer one-stop-shopping
in the overall data networking market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cisco is doing what Cisco always does,'' said First Albany
analyst Matthew Barzowskas. ``Waiting for the market to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   But the deal could also be a sign that Cisco's own products,
with names like Local Director and Distributed Director, haven't
done as well as Cisco hoped, said AG Edwards analyst Peter Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   Hanafi acknowledged the products appear similar ``at a high
level,'' but insisted they have significant technical differences
and are more complementary. Hanafi added that Cisco also bought
SightPath in March and Tasmania Network Systems in October as part
of plans to broaden its product portfolio in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were expecting ArrowPoint to generate $62 million in
sales this year, though those estimates could be topped with the
help of Cisco's sales force. Cisco said the total market for Web
site management products is about $500 million this year, and
growing fast.
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint competes with firms like F5 Networks and Alteon
Websystems, whose stocks slid on the news of the its deal with
Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
