<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-3COM-PALM-ART-NYT &LR;      05-08 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-PALM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM TO SPIN OFF ITS SHARES IN PALM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   3Com Corp., whose shares have been trading as if the entire
company were worth less than the shares it owns in Palm Inc., said
Monday that it will distribute its Palm shares to its own
shareholders in late July.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which came after 3Com received a favorable tax
ruling from the IRS certifying that the spinoff would be tax-free,
sets the stage for the closing of the stock price gap that has
existed ever since Palm went public in early March. Since then,
Palm has traded at prices that appeared to be unreasonably high
relative to the price of 3Com shares.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for 3Com, Brian Johnson, said the exact number of
Palm shares to be distributed per 3Com share would not be
determined until July, because that would be affected by the number
of 3Com shares outstanding, which can vary as the company issues or
repurchases shares. But he said the company expected the ratio to
be about 1.5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Palm Monday closed at $32.25, up $1.0625, in Nasdaq
trading, and 3Com closed at $43.6875, up 56.25 cents. The
announcement of the planned spinoff came after the close of Nasdaq
trading.
</P>
<P>
   If 3Com shareholders do receive 1.5 shares of Palm for each 3Com
share, that would provide them with shares worth $48.375 at
Monday's price, $4.6875 more than the price of a 3Com share.
</P>
<P>
   While 3Com expects to report losses for the remainder of this
year as it reorganizes, it has virtually no debt and substantial
cash and is clearly worth something. The persistence of the
apparently negative value has puzzled market analysts, but while it
narrowed sharply in April it never disappeared and began to expand
again last week.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the 3Com spokesman, said the company's board had
authorized the company to spend up to $1 billion repurchasing its
shares. He said he expects most, if not all, of the share
repurchases to be made after the distribution, which will be made
July 27 to shareholders of record on July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Palm, the dominant company in the handheld organizer business,
has seen its revenue and profits grow rapidly. Judy Bruner, the
company's chief financial officer, said in an interview Monday the
company expects revenue to continue rising quickly, but that it was
possible profits would fall for a few quarters, perhaps to the
point of reporting losses, as the company spends money for improved
marketing and to expand the uses of its products.
</P>
<P>
   Palm went public on March 2, at the height of investor
enthusiasm for many technology stocks, with 3Com selling a small
part of its stake to the public. The offering price, of $38 a
share, was more than twice as high as the company had planned to
seek when it first filed to sell shares. But it was soon eclipsed
as the shares traded as high as $165, closing that day at $95.0625.
The price of 3Com ended that day at $81.8125.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent weeks, the prices of both stocks fell, and by
April 12 the Palm price had declined below the offering price. But
3Com's price always remained lower than the value of the Palm
shares it owned.
</P>
<P>
   Several reasons were offered for the persistence of the
valuation gap. One was that it was possible that the distribution
would not be completed, although most analysts thought the IRS
ruling was fairly routine. Another was that many investors did not
understand the expected distribution, or were seeking a quick
trade, in which they would sell Palm before the 3Com distribution
was made.
</P>
<P>
   To take advantage of the gap, an investor theoretically could
borrow Palm shares and sell them short while purchasing 3Com
shares. Many appear to have done that, and by early last month _
the last date for which figures are available _ more than half the
shares in public hands had been sold short. But the shares are
difficult to borrow, and anyone doing so ran the risk that they
might have to return the shares before the distribution was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a date certain for the distribution, the gap may
finally be erased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
