<SLUG> BC-VC-BOOM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VENTURE-CAPITAL INVESTING POT OVERFLOWS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Venture-capital investing went ballistic in the
first quarter, according to two new industry surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The National Venture Capital Association reports that
venture-capital firms invested a record $22.7 billion in 1,557 U.S.
companies in the first quarter _ more than triple the $6.2 billion
invested in 851 U.S. companies in the first three months of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   As dot-com companies remained Wall Street darlings through
March, VC investors directed 75 percent of their funds to
Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California companies received a stunning $7.9 billion,
more than a third of the total invested in all U.S. companies and
more than four times as much as was invested in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The figures from VentureOne Corp. are only slightly less
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco VC research organization reports that 342
local companies raised $6.3 billion from venture-capital investors
in the past quarter, 85 percent of which went to Internet-related
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Bay Area startups attracted more capital than any
other region of the country. Three local companies creating
Internet technology or Web-based services each raised $100 million
or more in private financing in the past quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's Business section, The Chronicle will run a full
report with charts on the continuing venture capital investment
boom.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
