<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Ky., La.)   (For release Sun., May 14)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tower Air, Bankrupt, Abruptly Ends Service
</P>
<P>
   Tower Air has stopped all scheduled passenger flights. The line,
which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in Delaware in
February, canceled a flight from Kennedy Airport in New York to
Israel on May 1 without warning, stranding 300 passengers, and said
it was ceasing all scheduled operations.
</P>
<P>
   A recorded message at 718-553-8500 tells ticket holders to apply
to their travel agencies for refunds. If tickets were bought
directly from the airline with a credit card, ticket holders should
request refunds from the card company on the ground that the trip
could not be made. Correspondence can be sent to Tower Air, Hangar
17, JFK International Airport, Jamaica, N.Y. 11430.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, a Show Of Chinese Equine Art
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition focusing on the role of the horse in 3,000 years
of Chinese history and culture is on display through Aug. 31 at the
Kentucky Horse Park, in the Bluegrass region. The exhibition,
``Imperial China: The Art of the Horse in Chinese History,''
features more than 300 artifacts from museums in Shaanxi Province,
including Xi'an, the ancient Chinese capital.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit explores the significance of the horse in the
unification of China, the exchange of equestrian culture with the
West through the Silk Road, significant Chinese advances in horse
accouterments and training, and the use of the horse in leisure
activities. Each dynastic period from the Western Zhou (1027-771
B.C.) through the Qing (1644-1911) will be covered.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the artifacts are gold, porcelain and jade figures, bronze
vessels, tricolored Tang dynasty ceramic statues, and a gold- and
silver-inlaid bronze Western Han Dynasty chariot, which was
restored for the exhibit. Also included are 13 life-size figures
from the famous terra-cotta army discovered about 25 years ago in
the tomb of Qin Shi Huangdi, China's first emperor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for ``Imperial China'' are $16, $11 for ages 7 to 12;
they will be issued for specific times and can be booked in
advance. A taped audio tour is included in the price, as is
admission to the 1,030-acre Kentucky Horse Park, a working farm and
educational theme park that features more than 40 breeds of horses
and two museums.
</P>
<P>
   The park is off I-75, four miles north of Lexington.
Information: 800-568-8813, or at www.kyhorsepark.com.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Satchmo Summer At a New Orleans Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Any birthday party for Louis Armstrong promises to be lively,
and a hotel in the city of his birth, New Orleans, plans a series
of parties this summer.
</P>
<P>
   From July 4, the 100th anniversary of Armstrong's birth (he was
actually born on Aug. 4, 1901, but apparently he and his manager
liked the other date more), through Labor Day, the International
House, a 119-room hotel at 221 Camp Street, two blocks from the
French Quarter, will offer a two-night package with cocktails, a
performance at the Storyville District jazz club and a sampling of
Louisiana hors d'oeuvres and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The price for this Friday-Saturday night package is $318 for a
double room. On the first Thursday of each month through August
2001, in honor of Armstrong's actual birthday, jazz musicians will
play in the lobby; an extra night's stay costs $119. Call
800-633-5770 or visit www.ihhotel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Czech VAT Refunds Available, With Catch-22
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in an effort to push the Czech Republic closer to
the European Union, the Czech government authorized the Value Added
Tax refund. But just as on Europe's map, the Czech Republic falls
somewhere between West and East in its approach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In most European Union countries, shop owners provide non-E.U.
residents a VAT refund form and help them fill it out. After a
customs officer stamps the form at your departure point, you either
take it to a cash refund office in America or elsewhere or mail it
to the address on the form. A company that deals with VAT refunds
sends you a check or credits your account. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not so in the Czech Republic. First, you need to find the refund
form, available in both Czech and English; most retailers don't
have it yet (except, perhaps, large international chains and luxury
boutiques like Moser, the crystal maker). It can be picked up at a
customs office at the airport, at 22 Sokolovska Street or the
Prague 1 Financial Bureau on 28 Stepanska. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the 22 percent VAT refund, you must spend at
least 1,000 crowns ($27) in one store on the same day, keep the
bill and have the seller stamp the form. Upon your departure _ but
no later than 30 days after the purchase _ a customs officer will
check the bought item and take a copy of the form and put it in his
files. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you must pick up the money yourself, within three
months of the purchase. So unless you return soon, you must find
someone in the Czech Republic to send the form to and to ask the
shop owner for the refund. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit awkward, I agree,'' concedes Libor Vacek, the
spokesman for the Czech Ministry of Finance. ``But we hope some
firms will soon realize it's a good business and will start
providing this service.''
</P>
<P>
   More information on VAT refunds is available from Global Refund,
a major refund provider, at 800-566-9828.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the Meurice Is Primped for a New Age
</P>
<P>
   The elegant Hotel Meurice, across from the Tuileries gardens in
Paris, is scheduled to reopen its mahogany doors in June after two
years of renovation that gutted the interior, pared 180 rooms to
160, and pushed the infrastructure toward the 21st century. The
renovation, aimed at restoring the building to its
turn-of-the-20th-century opulence, uncovered a forgotten Art
Nouveau glass dome with delicate fish-scale panels now adorning the
hotel's gilded Winter Garden tea salon. The main restaurant, Le
Meurice, is a Rococo jewel box with crystal chandeliers, antique
beveled mirrors and one Michelin star.
</P>
<P>
   A new, 2,206-square-foot rooftop suite, dubbed the Belle Etoile,
revolutionizes the idea of a room with a view. A zinc-roofed Belle
Epoque folly encased in reflective glass, this $7,000-a-night,
two-bedroom suite offers panoramic views from many points,
including a round whirlpool encased in marble.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms for business travelers, clustered on the second and third
floors, are decorated in a simpler, more streamlined style than
others and have work areas, safes big enough for laptop computers
and separate lines for computers and fax machines. A new spa
includes saunas, exercise machines and a beauty center.
</P>
<P>
   Since Augustin Meurice relocated his Paris establishment to the
chic Rue de Rivoli in 1835, the Meurice has attracted a celebrity
guest roster: the Shah of Iran was staying there when he was
overthrown, King George VI was a regular, and Salvador Dali once
filled his suite with sheep and staged a mock ovine execution.
Rates start at $425 night, at 7.1 francs to the dollar. Hotel
Meurice, 228, rue de Rivoli, 75001; 33-1-44.58.10.10, fax
33-1-44.58.10.17; www.meuricehotel.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
