<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTHCARES-TECHHELP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TEENS PROVIDE TECH SUPPORT TO SENIORS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 200 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sanel Becirovic, an 18-year-old junior at
Galileo High School in San Francisco, helps elderly people after
school.
</P>
<P>
   He plays dominoes with some and takes out the trash for others.
But more and more, the residents of the retirement homes he visits
request that he troubleshoot their Internet connections or show
them how to use Microsoft Word.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, he was figuring out why Adam Geldman's
computer wouldn't connect to CompuServe. Geldman, 78, who escaped
the Holocaust as a teenager by walking from Poland to Russia, lives
in a subsidized home for the elderly in the South of Market area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think other people are happy to play'' dominoes and other
games with the after-school volunteers, said Geldman, a slender,
serious man with glasses and a thick shock of white hair. Technical
help is the only aid he needs, he said while waiting for Becirovic
and Kelly Cheng, 16, to finish working on his computer so he could
connect to the BBC's Web site and read the news in Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Becirovic and Cheng are part of a community service program
called YouthCares, a group that fosters relationships between
teenagers and senior citizens. Because YouthCares is part of the
International Institute of San Francisco, a nonprofit group that
helps immigrants and refugees, most of the teenagers and the
seniors in the program are originally from outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Technology was not a focus of YouthCares when the program
started two years ago, said Jason Felch, program director. But over
time, Felch realized that using the Internet could help seniors
reduce their isolation when YouthCares kids couldn't be there.
</P>
<P>
   Only 14.4 percent of Americans over age 55 use the Internet,
according to the government's 1998 count. People whose first
language is not English are even less likely to be online. In 1998,
a Georgia Institute of Technology survey showed that 92.2 percent
of Internet users listed English as their primary language.
</P>
<P>
   The kids involved are not necessarily computer experts. Although
Becirovic, a Bosnian refugee, is enrolled in Cisco University's
networking class and plans a technical career, most participants
have learned all they know about computers in regular high school
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we're providing is companionship,'' Felch said.
``The biggest enemy of a lot of the seniors is isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   Loneliness is even more common for immigrant seniors, some of
whom don't speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Online, seniors can keep up on news from their home countries,
get involved with discussion groups with senior citizens, and _
most popular of all _ e-mail friends and family. As the program
progresses, Felch hopes YouthCares can introduce more seniors to
more online services, such as ordering groceries.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is the main reason neighborhood seniors show up at the
Technology and Information Empowerment Center in Chinatown, a small
computer lab downstairs from a souvenir shop. The center's
computers were donated by Microsoft, and YouthCares members provide
help.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday afternoon, Lam Shuk Kwan, 67, sat at a terminal at
the TIE Center, painstakingly entering Chinese characters in a
Hotmail e-mail message she would send to her youngest son. Next to
her mouse pad lay a printout of a photograph her son had e-mailed
her while on a business trip to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan started visiting the TIE Center more than a year ago,
because although her home had several computers _ belonging to her
children and grandchildren _ she didn't know how to turn one on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to open my eyes and send e-mail to my friends in
Vancouver, and to my sons and daughters,'' Kwan said. Now she has
her own computer at home, but she still drops into the TIE Center
to learn more and to help others learn.
</P>
<P>
   At retirement homes, the senior citizens YouthCares works with
come from a variety of countries, but because of the TIE Center's
Chinatown location, the language of instruction is usually
Cantonese, which is spoken in Southern China. As many as seven
YouthCares volunteers show up at the TIE Center each Tuesday, but
only a few speak Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
   That means students from Southern China and Hong Kong, like
Cheng, end up shuttling between computers, helping translate for
other YouthCares members. It also means that experienced seniors
like Kwan take the knowledge they've learned to help others out.
</P>
<P>
   The TIE Center also offers basic computing and Internet classes
taught in Cantonese, for about $90 a course. These are administered
by Self Help for the Elderly, the 34-year-old Chinatown nonprofit
group that runs the center.
</P>
<P>
   A class on online investing, including a speaker from discount
brokerage Charles Schwab, is being considered for this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But not all seniors can get to the center, and only a handful
that YouthCares visits in their apartments have their own
computers. To introduce the benefits of computing to more seniors,
YouthCares hopes to set up labs like the TIE Center, with donated
computers, in the common areas of the residences and community
centers it visits.
</P>
<P>
   So far, YouthCares has set up three used computers _ donated by
the International Institute _ at O'Farrell Towers, one of the
retirement homes the program visits.
</P>
<P>
   Playing games, grocery shopping and computer instruction _ all
YouthCares activities are useful in themselves, but the main goal
is to get the seniors and teens together so they can build
relationships, Felch said. The seniors in the program often find
themselves on the teaching end, telling the kids their life stories
and passing on skills they've accrued over the years.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a chance for computer-savvy high school students to
share their know-how with senior citizens, who are less likely to
be connected than any other demographic group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers are something the younger people can teach the older
people,'' Felch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the seniors are kind of in the beginning,'' Becirovic
said. ``They need to know how to open programs, save and send
e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria C.S. Diaz, a small, vivacious woman who immigrated from
Mexico when she was in her 20s, just wanted to learn how to type on
a computer. She has written dozens of poems and autobiographical
essays over the years, and she wants to preserve them for posterity
and for her descendants _ on floppy disks.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, Farahna Davis, a Lincoln High School sophomore
from South Africa, has been visiting Diaz in her two-room apartment
in a SOMA home for seniors. She has patiently helped Diaz learn to
type, save and print her work using Microsoft Word. Now, Davis is
coaching Diaz through the spell-checking process.
</P>
<P>
   Each has gained something in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Davis moved to the United States 21/2 years ago and has since
lived in three different cities with her parents. She never knew
her grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's (Diaz) made a difference in my life,'' said Davis, 16.
``She's more like my grandma now. The way she talks, I realize that
there's so much more to life. She's just opened me more.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
