<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-SUSPECT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `LOVE BUG' SUSPECT SOUGHT _ DAMAGE NEARS $3 BILLION  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The day after a seductive e-mail disguised as a
love letter devastated computer systems worldwide, authorities were
closing in on a suspected perpetrator, a 23-year-old man in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a half-dozen copycat viruses emerged as damage
estimates from the ``love-bug'' spree climbed to $2.81 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Using the nickname ``Spyder,'' the suspect used two e-mail
addresses hosted by a Manila Internet services provider, Supernet,
to send the self-replicating ``worm'' software to millions of
computer users, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   The worm, an attachment carried by e-mail titled ``I LOVE YOU,''
was able to mail itself to everyone listed in a recipient's
Microsoft Outlook address book. A huge proportion of e-mail users
received the message on Wednesday and Thursday, and many of them
clicked the attachment _ spawning enough e-mail to clog servers at
corporations and government agencies in Europe, Asia and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Supernet lets its users prepay for service using plastic cards
that work like phone cards, so there's no easy way to track them.
However, the suspect may have left traces in chat rooms and within
the message's computer code. CNN reported that the FBI is seeking a
search warrant from judges in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   A Supernet official said the company thinks the culprit is a
23-year-old man who lives in the Pandacan neighborhood of Manila,
according to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the FBI, the Philippine National Bureau of
Investigation, Interpol and the National Infrastructure Protection
Center were all working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Ayre, a spokesman for Manila ISP Sky Internet, told CNN
that one aspect of the malicious code, which would search a
recipient's hard drive for saved passwords and e-mail them to an
account in the Philippines, was discovered and eradicated early in
the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy the second part didn't reach the world,'' Ayre
said. ``It would have been extremely pathetic with 40 million
people trying to change their passwords.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual computer code of the love bug and its mutations was
relatively simple and could have been written by a bright high
school student, experts said. The virus authors' real talents lie
in the ``social engineering'' aspect _ crafting messages that
appeal to the recipients' emotions and get them to click on the
malevolent attachment.
</P>
<P>
   New variants of the love bug ricocheted around the Internet on
Friday. The slyest was an e-mail with the heading ``Mother's Day
Order Confirmation,'' whose attachment appears to be an invoice for
a $326.92 purchase of diamonds. If opened, the attachment erases
Windows systems files, making a computer difficult or impossible to
start up. That's even worse than the original love bug, which
replaces graphics and music files, as well as e-mailing itself.
</P>
<P>
   That particular ruse, coming a week before Mother's Day, played
on consumer fears about e-commerce, said Risto Siilasmaa, chief
executive of Finnish antivirus firm F-Secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recipient would know they hadn't bought anything, but
would want to check to make sure their credit card hadn't been
used,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other variants cloaked themselves as antivirus measures. One was
an e-mail titled ``Danger Virus Warning'' that claimed the
attachment would give virus-fighting tips. Another, labeled ``Virus
ALERT!!!,'' appeared to come from antivirus firm Symantec Corp.
Other versions were labeled ``Susitikim'' (Lithuanian for ``let's
meet''), ``Luck,'' ``Brainstorm'' and ``fwd: Joke.''
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the new worms were less effective because computer
professionals had mobilized antivirus defenses on Thursday and most
users were cautious about opening attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a high-end kitchen equipment company got infected
yesterday by a message labeled ``Antivirus Help'' and unwittingly
mailed it out to all the chefs in the country, said Jo Lynne
Lockley, owner of the Chefs' Professional Agency, a San Francisco
search firm for chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one's vicious _ it's out to fool people,'' said Lockley,
who had received one copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime there's a successful virus, we see a slew of
copycats,'' said Sal Viveros, director of McAfee, the antivirus
division of Santa Clara, Calif.'s Network Associates. ``People take
the existing one and change it slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Viveros had this advice for users: ``Be very wary of e-mail
attachments for the next few weeks. If you're not expecting a
document, be smart and delete that message. Don't double-click on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The original love letter has already cost $2.61 billion, largely
in lost work time, and the toll could reach $10 billion by next
week, said Samir Bhavnani, a research analyst at Computer Economics
in Carlsbad, Calif. He based the $2.61 billion figure on an
assumption that 45 million people received the e-mail and about
half of them experienced severe business delays. ``I call this
economic terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Siilasmaa suggested that users could prevent variations of the
love bug by turning off Windows scripting, the technology that
makes it possible to create simple scripts that manipulate Windows
applications. The company offers ``directions for dummies'' on how
to do this at its Web site, www.f-secure.com, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group said that
Microsoft should consider removing the feature itself.
</P>
<P>
   And in chat rooms and e-mails, a chorus of users claimed that
Microsoft should have accountability for the spread of the virus,
because it only attacked computers running Microsoft software.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
