A9417 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV14-NYT     05-08 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Alaska)   (For review Sun., May 14)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Affordable San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our group of seven women will travel to San Francisco next
month. Can you recommend any moderately priced hotels? _ Rachel
Witmer, Lake Oswego, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a number of moderately priced hotels in the city,
but remember that the 14 percent tax must be added to the rates
below.
</P>
<P>
   The Sam Wong Hotel, 615 Broadway, (415) 362-2999, fax (415)
362-1808, has 81 rooms, not far from Coit Tower, at the
Chinatown-North Beach border. After a recent renovation, the rooms
have florentine wall coverings and cherrywood furniture in a Ming
style. All have private bath and voice mail. Doubles from $119. On
the Web: www.swhotelsf.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a nicely furnished older hotel (the building dates from
1926) near Union Square, there is the Pickwick, 85 Fifth St; (415)
421-7500, fax (415) 243-8066. The 189 rooms are done in French
Provincial style and all have private bath. Standard doubles are
$99 to $189, depending on demand; discounts are often available
when booking in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Away from downtown, facing Golden Gate Park, you can try the
Stanyan Park Hotel, 750 Stanyan St., (415) 751-1000, fax (415)
668-5454. This 36-room hotel on the edge of Haight-Ashbury is in a
registered landmark building dating from 1905. The rooms have
period furniture, and some have pencil-post beds. All have private
bath. Doubles from $110; www.stanyanpark.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't mind accommodations with shared bath, you may want
to consider a bed-and-breakfast inn. The Casa Arguello, 225
Arguello Boulevard; telephone and fax (415) 752-9482, is in a large
1920s building where the Pacific Heights, Laurel Heights and
Richmond districts come together. It has four double rooms, two
with shared bath ($66) and two with private bath ($90 to $110), as
well as a large suite accommodating up to five ($135 for two
persons, $155 for three, $175 for four, $195 for five). Decor is a
mix of pastels, brass and some antiques;
www.sftravel.com/casarg.html.
</P>
<P>
   Small Ship, Big State
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am interested in small-ship cruises to Alaska. Can you give
me the names of companies offering such voyages? _ Janet Hitschler,
Commack, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. You have a number of choices. Cruise West, for example, has a
fleet of seven ships, ranging in passenger capacity from 52 to 102.
Its selection of sailings ranges from three-night trips through the
Alaskan fjords to a 15-night excursion that includes three nights
in the Denali Park Lodge. The trips have naturalists on board and
offer a good range of shore excursions. A three-night cruise on
Prince William Sound starts at $875 a person, double occupancy,
including all taxes, fees and port charges. The 15-night
cruise-land tour starts at $5,245. Call (800) 888-9378 for
brochures or visit www.cruisewest.com.
</P>
<P>
   Glacier Bay Tours and Cruises, with a fleet of four ships
carrying from 34 to 88 passengers, conducts typical port-to-port
cruises on the Inside Passage as well as cruises for the more
adventuresome, featuring sea kayaking and Zodiac excursions in
wilderness areas. The company also operates Glacier Bay Lodge, the
only hotel in Glacier Bay National Park. Prices start at $1,530 a
person, double occupancy, for a five-night cruise to $3,580 for
seven nights. Contact (800) 451-5952 or on the Web visit
www.glacierbaytours.com.
</P>
<P>
   American Safari Cruises uses vessels that carry 12 or 21
passengers, small enough to explore narrow inlets and bays. Because
of this more-intimate size, the rates are higher. An eight-night
cruise through the Inside Passage, from Juneau to Prince Rupert, or
the reverse, for $5,195 to $7,395 a person, double occupancy,
depending on cabin and date. These rates include all meals, shore
excursions, wines and drinks, taxes and port charges. In September,
a 10-night Inside Passage cruise will cost from $4,895 to $6,595.
Contact www. &QC; amsafari.com; (888) 862-8881.
</P>
<P>
   French Car Museums
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be going to the French Grand Prix auto race at the
Magny-Cours track, near Nevers, in July and then plan to meander
through Burgundy, ending up in Nice. We will visit the Ligier
Museum of racing cars at the track and have already visited the car
museum near Mougins. Do you know of any other auto museums along
our route? _ Susan Sawyer, Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a few along the way, as well as one that you may
want to make a detour for.
</P>
<P>
   Close to Vezelay in Burgundy is the Musee de Voitures des Chefs
d'Etat, in the Chateau de Montjalin in Sauvigny-le-Bois; (33-3)
86.34.46.42, fax (33-3) 86.31.66.83. This is a collection of 30
cars used by various heads of state from 1940 to 1965. Among them
are a 1939 Renault Vivistella (Marshal Petain), a Lincoln
Continental (President Kennedy), a 1959 Simca Presidence (Charles
de Gaulle) and a Pope-mobile used by Paul VI. Open daily May 1 to
Nov. 11; Admission: $4.25 at 7.1 francs to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   About three miles north of Beaune is another museum in a castle,
the Musee du Chateau de Savigny, in Savigny-les-Beaune. The
14th-century castle contains 200 motorcycles from 1903 to 1960 and
14 Abarth racing cars. Open daily; (33-3) 80.21.55.03. Admission:
$5.65.
</P>
<P>
   As you head farther south toward Nice, just north of Lyon is the
Musee Henri-Malartre, (33-4) 78.22.18.80, at the entrance to
Rochetaillee-sur-Saone. Old cars must have an affinity for castles,
because this collection of 140 cars and 40 motorcycles is in a
restored 15th-century chateau. There are 50 cars from before 1914,
and 18 were built in Lyon, an early car-manufacturing center.
There's another car here used by de Gaulle, and a Renault Espace
used by another frequent traveler, Pope John Paul II. It is open
daily. Admission: $5.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mulhouse is a considerable detour off your route, if
you can get there, you will find the Musee National de l'Automobile
_ Collection Schlumpf, the premier car collection in France and one
of the world's largest, with over 500 cars. Not all are on display
at one time, but the ones that are trace the history of motoring,
starting with an 1878 steam-driven Jacquot. The highlights are the
120 Bugattis, built in Molsheim. There are 120 racing, luxury and
sports models on display, including the enormous and extremely rare
Bugatti Royale. The museum, at 192, avenue de Colmar, Mulhouse, is
open every day (except Tuesday in winter); (33-3) 89.33.23.23, fax
(33-3) 89.32.08.90. Admission: $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   For a more extensive listing of auto museums in France, call up
www.fia.com/tourisme/museums/france.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
