<SLUG> BC-LEVI-REPORT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEVI STRAUSS REVEALS SOME INNER SECRETS  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a rare filing with government regulators,
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. put a financial face on some of the problems
that have dogged the blue-jean titan in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Profit at privately held Levi, which has eliminated 18,500 jobs
and closed 29 plants over the past several years, plummeted to $5.4
million in 1999 from $102.5 million in 1998. Revenue dipped to $5.1
billion from $6 billion during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's overarching problems described in the
documents _ including declining sales and increased competition
from the likes of Tommy Hilfiger and Calvin Klein _ aren't new. The
Chronicle reported in February that 1999 sales at the company,
which invented blue jeans during the Gold Rush, had dropped for the
third year in a row and that it didn't expect sales to rebound
until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's filing offered an uncommon look at the
147-year-old company's financial performance. Owned by the Haas
family of San Francisco, Levi is not required to disclose financial
figures to the public, although it has traditionally released
annual sales figures. This is the first time the company has
submitted a financial report to the agency since 1986, the SEC
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new details were required for the company to register $800
million in bonds the company sold privately to investors several
years ago. The move will permit the investors to sell the notes to
the public after the SEC clears the registration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us the opportunity to raise more money in the
investment bond market later on,'' Levi chief executive Philip
Marineau said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau said Levi will begin filing quarterly reports including
sales and income figures, though he said the company has no plans
to offer its shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter of 2000, the company reported income of
$65.2 million on sales of $1.1 billion, compared with the year-ago
quarter that showed a loss of $237 million on sales of $1.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The filing also described Levi's decision not to go through with
$344 million in employee bonuses after its forecasts showed that it
won't meet required financial goals for the awards to be made.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus program was initially projected to pay out as much as
$758 million, when it was formulated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, the company lowered its estimate of financial
performance through the year 2001 and determined that payment'' of
the bonus ``in 2002 is highly unlikely,'' Levi Strauss said in the
SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss disclosed that cash flow declined to $295 million
in fiscal 1999, from $479 million in 1998 and as much as $861
million in 1996. Cash flow, which is defined as earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation, amortization and certain other
items, is an important indicator of the company's ability to
service its debt.
</P>
<P>
   The company's long-term debt totaled $2.4 billion on Nov. 28,
1999, according to the SEC filing. Interest expense rose to $183
million in fiscal 1999 from $178 million in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levi's has been losing market share for many years due to lack
of innovation in its product cycle and over-distribution of the
product,'' said Todd Slater, an analyst at Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. LLC.
``I don't think they will ever be able to regain their leadership
position in the premium categories'' of jeans.
</P>
<P>
   While the overall picture painted by the documents portrays a
concern in trouble, Marineau emphasized that the layoffs and plant
closings are over and the company is making progress in rebuilding
relationships with retailers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect to turn sales around for some time, but we
have a strong fall sales line ... and our business performance is
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag  &LR; Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
