<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SKYWAY-ANNIV-COX     05-08 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKYWAY-ANNIV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Twenty years since Skyway bridge collapse
 &HT;    By Howie Paul Hartnett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every May 9, Wesley MacIntire would rouse his wife out of bed
and take her to the fishing pier overlooking the Sunshine Skyway
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   There, a safe distance from the span linking St. Petersburg and
Manatee County, the retired trucker would silently follow the
headlights of commuters or warily watch a barge approach the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Then, somewhere around 7:30 it would happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-to-Miami Greyhound bus would rumble by, taking
MacIntire back to that day in 1980 when the green and black metal
grating atop the bridge gave way, sending him to the bottom of
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago today, in a blinding rain storm, the phosphate
freighter Summit Venture plowed into a main pillar of the Skyway's
southbound span, causing more than 1,400 feet of the bridge to
cascade 150 feet into the water below.
</P>
<P>
   Seven vehicles and a Greyhound bus fell off the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five people died.
</P>
<P>
   And one survived.
</P>
<P>
   Every year after, until his death from prostate cancer in 1989,
MacIntire and his wife, Betty, made the pilgrimage from their home
just miles away to the foot of the bridge to wait for the
Greyhound.
</P>
<P>
   Bay area residents remember the crash. MacIntire remembered the
victims _ including Tuskegee University students Sharon Elaine
Dixon, Yvonne Johnson and Dwayne P. Adderly heading home to Miami
on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Or John and Doris Carlson of Pinellas Park.
</P>
<P>
   Or Horace V. Lemmons of Kings Mountain, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   They were colleagues to MacIntire.
</P>
<P>
   But the names came and quickly went in the media _ lost amid the
stories of concern about the landmark's future.
</P>
<P>
   Birth of a landmark
</P>
<P>
   The first Skyway bridge opened in 1954 as an alternative to the
Bee Line Ferry and the more lengthy route through Tampa, U.S. 41.
The 4-mile span named by the winner of a local Jaycees contest cut
the distance between St. Petersburg and the next largest city along
the coast, Bradenton, almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   The two-lane concrete bridge, with its steel truss system at the
center, quickly became a popular symbol of the area and the
preferred path for commuters and truckers.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, state Department of Transportation officials
agreed another two-lane span was needed to handle the traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1971, the new bridge mirrored its predecessor, but
repairs were common.
</P>
<P>
   Treacherous currents in the bay led ships to hit each other and
the bridge over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Until May 9, however, no one had died on the bridge from a ship
collision.
</P>
<P>
   'The Skyway bridge is down'
</P>
<P>
   Not a day goes by that former harbor pilot John E. Lerro doesn't
think about the 35 lives that ended because he guessed wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran pilot with hundreds of successful navigations under
his belt, Lerro was at the helm of the empty freighter when it
encountered an unexpected squall just south of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   With the radar out and visibility near zero, Lerro said in court
hearings, he thought he saw a course buoy. Believing he was on
track, he pushed the 609-foot-long freighter forward.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, he felt the collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayday, Mayday, Mayday, Coast Guard, Mayday, Mayday, Mayday,''
Lerro said into the radio. ``This is an ... emergency. All
emergency equipment onto the Skyway bridge. A vessel just hit the
Skyway Bridge. The Skyway Bridge is down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerro's voice remained relatively calm even until vehicles
started tumbling from the sky. Then he started screaming: ``Stop
the traffic on that Skyway bridge!''
</P>
<P>
   'It was a nightmare'
</P>
<P>
   Working in the kitchen after getting her husband off to work,
Betty MacIntire was half listening to her stereo when the first
radio bulletin came over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the southbound span and I said, 'Oh, God,''' she
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Retired from trucking after 35 years, Wesley, a World War II
POW, had taken a job inspecting vehicles at the Tropicana plant in
Bradenton _ about 20 miles south of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up immediately and called work,'' Betty said. ``He
hadn't gotten there.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the wind and the rain, Wesley MacIntire, 56 at the time,
didn't know the bridge was out until he crested the top of the
bridge and saw the words Summit Venture.
</P>
<P>
   He thought, ``Huh, now I'm gone,'' he later told his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He slammed on the brakes, but his light blue Ford Courier pickup
skidded off the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley vainly pumped the brakes for 15 stories until his truck
hit the side of the freighter and sank.
</P>
<P>
   Knocked out by the collision with the ship, Wesley awoke to find
his headlights still on and bubbles ebbing upward.
</P>
<P>
   He opened his window and started kicking up, taking two gulps of
saltwater before reaching the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The shock and saltwater were about to sink Wesley again when he
spotted a piece of the bridge floating nearby. He clung to it until
Summit Venture crewmen picked him up.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley suffered a deep cut on his head, a sprained neck, some
bumps and bruises and a sore right foot from the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went crazy waiting and waiting and waiting,'' Betty
said. ``This happened at 7:30 in the morning. I didn't hear until
12:10 p.m. that they had a survivor. It was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   When Betty met him in the hospital, Wesley said, ``I made it
again because I hit my head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of accidents with the (tractor trailer),'' Betty
explained. ``We always kidded that if he hit his head, he
survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Other nightmares
</P>
<P>
   Investigators determined the accident was a combination of
unexpected severe weather, failure of the National Weather Service
to issue a severe weather warning and failure of the pilot to
abandon the trip after the radar and visibility dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Lerro spent nearly a year trying to clear his name and restore
his pilot's license. But just as he got it back, Lerro gave up his
license again. He had multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Lerro bounced around after his diagnosis, teaching at a New York
maritime college for a while before returning to the Tampa area.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a master's degree in counseling at the University of
South Florida. When he last spoke to reporters during the Skyway's
10th anniversary, Lerro said he had begun to forgive himself.
</P>
<P>
   He could not be contacted for comment for this anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath
</P>
<P>
   Like most residents around the bay, the DOT tried to move on
from the tragedy with the construction of a new bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned by then-Gov. Bob Graham, the new span is a
steel-cable suspension bridge with two travel lanes and two
emergency lanes in each direction.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the bridge is about 50 feet taller than the
originals, but the lower grade gives drivers a more gradual ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the improved security around the bridge pillars are 36
anchored bumpers. These ``dolphins'' can withstand the impact of an
87,000-ton vessel traveling at 10 knots. The Summit Venture was
34,500 tons traveling at 8 knots.
</P>
<P>
   The travel lane beneath the bridge also was widened from 800
feet to 1,200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   And electronic message boards alert drivers to adverse
conditions at the start of the bridge and before their ascent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have decided to do is install additional cameras on
the Skyway that are wired to the Highway Patrol,'' DOT spokeswoman
Marian Pscion said. ``And within a few months, we're going to have
Highway Patrol on the Skyway 24 hours a day, seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Total cost of the concrete and canary-yellow cabled bridge was
more than $244 million. It opened April 30, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   One day prior, Wesley MacIntire and his wife got a special tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first ones to go over the new bridge,'' Betty
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the MacIntires were given one more honor. They were the
last to drive over the old bridge. After they started up the old
span, workers blocked the way to prepare for its demolition.
</P>
<P>
   At the top, Wesley stopped the car and took one last look at the
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Then he reached into his car, pulled out 35 white carnations and
dropped them in the water.
</P>
<P>
   howiehartnett(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
