<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON LONGER STAYS, ALL-SUITE HOTELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   (For release Sun., May 14)  
 By ROGER COLLIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many hotels claim to be a home away from home. But however warm
the welcome, hotel life can pall pretty quickly. It's great to be
pampered and waited on, with that fine concierge and a host of
bustling bellboys. But sometimes more privacy and independence is
preferable, as is being able to stock your own refrigerator. When
you're tired of room service and restaurants, wouldn't it be nice
to fix a chicken salad just the way you like it?
</P>
<P>
   A studio or one-bedroom apartment in a custom-built property may
have twice the space for as little as half the cost of a standard
double room in a hotel of the same quality. Apartments in the
United States and abroad range from converted town houses to modern
``aparthotels.'' There are often charming properties available in
the center of such cities as London and Paris. They typically have
grand ground- and first-floor apartments with high corniced
ceilings, with smaller, cozier accommodations above. These tend to
be smaller properties with eight to 10 apartments, compared with 40
to 100 in a newer building.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most attractive properties are hard to find because
they typically don't advertise. Travel agents are becoming better
versed as demand for these accommodations grows, but are often not
familiar with the available apartments. Leisure travelers usually
stay two weeks or less while business travelers mostly account for
longer stays.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is the best way to get information, with pictures,
maps and descriptions of facilities. Bookings can be made or
requested online. A good site is that of Worldwide Apartments, at
www.nothotels.com, (44-20) 7704 5040, which allows you to view and
book 300,000 apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apartments are a fast-growing sector of the lodging
industry,'' says Charles McCrow, managing director of the Apartment
Service, in London, which has one of the best guides, the Worldwide
Guide to Serviced Apartments; (44-20) 8944 1444,
www.apartmentservice.com. ``We call them serviced apartments,
apart-hotels or apartment suites; in the United States, where the
concept began, they're called all-suite hotels or extended-stay
hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers should be wary, he said, of hotels with apartments
attached. Those quite often charge the same prices as they do for
regular suites, so guests pay for hotel services even if they
aren't using them.
</P>
<P>
   Extra space begins to matter when you're constantly on the road
or in one place for more than a few days. Apartments are an option
that makes sense for two couples traveling together, or a family.
Such accommodations range from studios to one-to-three-bedroom
apartments with a lounge and en suite bathrooms. Most have
direct-line phone and fax, cable or satellite TV. The kitchen is
usually equipped with a toaster oven and microwave, refrigerator
and freezer, perhaps a dishwasher, and pots, pans and dishes. Maid
service is usually once a week; you pay extra for daily cleaning.
Towels are changed at least once a week. Most apartments have a
24-hour reception desk. And you may get a free grocery shopping
service.
</P>
<P>
   When booking, guests should ask about advance payment, deposits
and cancellation penalties: there is normally no charge if you give
four weeks' notice on a long-term rental. It is also wise to check
on telephone and fax charges. They may not be cheaper than
exorbitant hotel rates. But free access to phone card calls should
be offered.
</P>
<P>
   Extended-stay hotels are enjoying a boom in the United States,
with around 20 companies offering a range of apartments _ from
hotel suites to long-stay residential properties. Extended Stay
America, www.extstay.com, with more than 200 properties, is a
lower-priced, fewer-frills alternative to Residence Inn by
Marriott, www.residenceinn.com, which pioneered the idea in the
early 1990s. Homestead Village, www.stayhsd.com, plans to build
between 40 and 50 properties a year for the next three years. And
Villager Lodge, www.villager.com, (800) 328-7829, a budget brand
with weekly rates from $175 to $250, has about 125 properties now,
and has just launched a new line called Premier, with rates of $250
to $375 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Staybridge Suites by Holiday Inn, which opened its first
extended-stay hotel in Alpharetta, Ga., an Atlanta suburb, in
December 1998, now has 15 properties with another 25 under
construction _ 23 in the U.S., and one each in Toronto and in Sao
Paulo. By 2001, the company expects to have 60 to 70 properties.
</P>
<P>
   Staybridge Suites, at www.staybridge.com, (800) 238-8000, is a
kind of hybrid between a hotel and an apartment. There are two
public areas, one with two computers for the use of guests (free);
a fitness area; full front-desk service; a convenience store; and
free laundry facilities. Prices depend on length of stay, season
and location. Studios range from $89 to $109 for one to four nights
to $59 to $89 a night for a stay of 15 to 30 days; two-bedroom
two-bath suites range from $149 to $169 a night for one to four
nights to $119 to $139 for 15 to 30 nights.
</P>
<P>
   The major apartment chain in Europe is a French company,
Citadines Apart'hotels, www.citadines.com, (33-1) 41.05.79.05,
recently acquired by Houston-based Westmont Hospitality, with 49
three- and four-star properties in cities including Paris,
Marseille, Montpellier, Strasbourg, Toulouse, Lyons, Nice, London,
Brussels and Barcelona. Some, but not all, are new or recently
renovated. (The older ones tend to have more charm.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very flexible _ you can stay for one night or one
month,'' says Jan Dijksstra, development manager for Westmont in
London. ``People who stay with us tend to be younger business
travelers who know the city fairly well, and like to organize
themselves.'' Guests have their own phone line, sometimes with
voice mail; business services such as fax, e-mail and often
conference rooms are available. A studio for two at Paris Maine
Montparnasse is $105 a night ($95 a night for seven nights).
</P>
<P>
   Central Apartments, at www.central-apartments.com, (44-20) 7608
9111, is a new chain with four luxury properties in central London.
``Designer'' studios and two-bedroom apartments ($150 to $275 a
night) have pine floors and furniture and stainless-steel kitchen
equipment. Circus Apartments, (44-20) 7719 7000, in Canary Wharf,
which is set to open July 1, is a luxury property with 49
apartments $75 to $115 a night cheaper than neighboring five-star
hotels such as the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If you're chained to the desk in London waiting for Tokyo or
Hong Kong to open or you're planning a crucial tete a tete dinner,
Room Service Deliveries, (44-20) 7431 5555,
(www.roomservice.co.uk), will deliver meals from more than 150
restaurants for a $6 delivery charge. Their mobile bars offer
reasonably priced wines _ cheaper than at a restaurant but more
expensive than at a supermarket. Food is delivered piping hot in
green ``butler bags'' by a fleet of bow-tied drivers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
