<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AD-AGENCY-YOUNG-NYT &LR;      05-08 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AD-AGENCY-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG &AMP; RUBICAM POPULARIZED THE MADISON AVENUE IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with AD-AGENCY-MERGER) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The agreement by Young &AMP; Rubicam in New York to be
acquired by the WPP Group in London ends the independent life of
one of the most influential, best-known mainstream Madison Avenue
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Y&AMP;R is one of the few agencies actually on Madison
Avenue, at 285, between 40th and 41st Streets. That building has
been home to the agency since 1928.
</P>
<P>
   It was Y&AMP;R along with rivals like J. Walter Thompson; Batten,
Barton, Durstine &AMP; Osborn; Lord &AMP; Thomas; and McCann-Erickson that
helped create an image of Madison Avenue in the minds of Americans
as the home of slick specialists in a newfangled industry who tried
everything from slick slogans to earnest demonstrations to catchy
jingles to sell products with emotional as well as rational
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R was the agency that convinced consumers to sing as they
spelled out the letters ``J-E-L-L-O''; tickled funny bones with a
unconventional campaign for Piels beer featuring animated pitchmen
named Bert and Harry; convinced donors on behalf of the United
Negro College Fund that ``a mind is a terrible thing to waste'';
presented headaches by the numbers _ the tax audit, No. 1040, natch
_ for Excedrin pain reliever; rocked the New York City of the late
1960s by urging citizens to ``give a damn'' and help the Urban
Coalition; exhorted the thirsty to ``be a Pepper'' for Dr Pepper
soda; and inspired fliers to think, however briefly, of Eastern
Airlines as ``the wings of man.''
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam was a pioneer in the media of radio and
television in the days when agencies created programs for their
clients and then produced them for the networks. The comedian Jack
Benny became identified with Jell-O when Y&AMP;R brought him together
with General Foods; not long after its debut in October 1934, ``The
Jack Benny Program'' became a top-rated radio show _ and Jell-O the
best-selling gelatin dessert, a standing it has maintained to this
day.
</P>
<P>
   Other performers who came into American homes with Young &AMP;
Rubicam clients as sponsors included Arthur Godfrey, Kate Smith,
George Burns and Gracie Allen, Ronald Reagan (for ``GE Theater'')
and Fanny Brice. Series developed under the aegis of Y&AMP;R included
ratings winners like ``The Aldrich Family,'' ``The Goldbergs,''
``Schlitz Playhouse of Stars,'' ``American Bandstand'' and ``Alfred
Hitchcock Presents.''
</P>
<P>
   General Foods, now part of the Kraft Foods unit of Philip
Morris, was one of the first important clients for Y&AMP;R, which was
founded in Philadelphia in 1923 by two former employees of the NW
Ayer agency there, Raymond Rubicam and John Orr Young.
</P>
<P>
   Rubicam and Young, both copywriters, began their agency with a
$5,000 investment and one client, according to the trade
publication Advertising Age, a company that published leaflets with
instructions for making shoelaces at home. The Postum Co., a
General Foods predecessor, hired the fledgling shop in its first
year of business; in 1926, Y&AMP;R relocated to New York when Postum
agreed to award the agency the Jell-O dessert account on condition
that it move.
</P>
<P>
   As Y&AMP;R flourished with the explosive growth of radio, then
television, top management plowed profits into expansion. It formed
the first ad agency research department, opened offices in Chicago,
Hollywood, Montreal and Toronto and expanded into Europe as early
as 1943 with an office in London.
</P>
<P>
   Other firsts achieved by Y&AMP;R, according to Advertising Age,
included the first color television commercial in 1951, for Jell-O
pudding and pie filling; and the first demonstration commercial in
1954, showing a Remington razor shaving a peach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
