<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VIEQUES-PROFILE-ART-N     05-08 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCATE MAKES A STATEMENT AS THE BOMBS FALL ON VIEQUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To watch Juan A. Figueroa sit in his Manhattan office
and describe his favorite family vacation spot, where, for years,
he brought his wife, Helen, and their daughter, Taina, is to see
the sparkle of paradisaical sun on surf in his eyes:
</P>
<P>
   ``It offers Puerto Rico without the pollution, development and
the McDonald's,'' he says rhapsodically. ``It is so serene and
beautiful, tropical and green. There are scarcely 100 hotel rooms
on the whole island. And the bioluminescent bay!
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about the Seven Wonders of the World, man! You go at
night, tap your hand on the side of the boat, and the fish streak
by, lighting up the plankton. People can jump in and go swimming,
wrapped around an aura of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, every once in a while, you'd hear thud!''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the island of Vieques, Puerto Rico: lovely refuge for
tourists, ideal practice range for Navy bombers.
</P>
<P>
   As president and general counsel of the Puerto Rican Legal
Defense and Education Fund in New York, Figueroa has been a leader
in organizing much of the mainland Latino response to the Navy's
use of Vieques to train its pilots about the finer points of aerial
bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a frequent commentator on the subject, and the point
man on letters to President Clinton that have also been signed by
the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Latino leaders and politicians. And he
was the connective tissue for a Times Square rally last Friday, the
day after federal agents removed 200 demonstrators from the
military range.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: an environmental lawsuit against the Navy, now under
discussion by several groups, over the damage they say has been
wrought by more than 50 years of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa heats his rhetoric appropriately, but is careful to
keep within the boundaries of indignant discourse. His bite is
tempered with irony and affability. He is, essentially, a polite
person, a sweetheart, actually, raised not on the tough streets of
San Juan or New York but in the tobacco fields of Ciales, a
jewel-like Puerto Rican mountain town.
</P>
<P>
   The man even dreams of going to chef school.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa, 47, who has been a community organizer, an assistant
attorney general and a Connecticut state legislator, is also less a
rabble-rouser than a diplomatic, if forceful, negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   He finds his role as a legal rock-thrower _ for workers fired
for speaking Spanish, Puerto Rican political prisoners and New York
City's immigrant college students _ amusing. For Figueroa was
raised with conservative values and a pro-Washington outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up to believe that America was best,'' Figueroa
says, although he has just treat his visitor to his stump speech
about Vieques, featuring the United States as despotic colonizer.
``My grandfather would say, `The Spanish were bastards. Thank God
for the Americans!'''
</P>
<P>
   To earn money, Figueroa's father brought the family to the
mainland. Wary of city evils, he settled in Rockland County, in New
York, working as a baker. They eventually went home to Ciales, but
in the meantime, his son became bilingual, bicultural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream of every Puerto Rican at that time was to own his
own plot of land and a house of cement,'' recalls Figueroa, whose
family, for generations, had been tenant farmers. ``My parents
assumed I'd go to school here, but return to Puerto Rico.''
Twenty-five years later, he adds, abashed, ``we're still talking
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa attended Macalester College in St. Paul, Minn., which
had recruited minority students. ``They gave me a full
scholarship,'' he says, ``plus a plane ticket and a parka.''
</P>
<P>
   As a history major, his view of America lost its glow. He stayed
on in St. Paul to study organizing at a center dedicated to Saul
Alinsky, the sociologist. After marrying Helen, his college
sweetheart, who lobbies for comprehensive day care, Figueroa spent
two years in Nashua and Manchester, N.H., going door to door,
forming Latino groups around employment and educational issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the mills, there were pockets of Uruguayans and
Puerto Ricans,'' he recalls, ``and they could not be more
different.''
</P>
<P>
   After attending law school at Santa Clara University in
California, he moved to Hartford. Energetic, restless and
personable, Figueroa, who had pursued day care center abuse cases
for the attorney general's Office, started going door-to-door
again, in Hartford's gritty Third District, winning election to the
state assembly.
</P>
<P>
   He found his three terms, working within the system,
surprisingly rewarding. Figueroa helped defeat English Only
legislation and prevented deep cuts in the welfare budget. He did
little to endear himself to suburbia in pushing through bills to
help moderate-income families leave Hartford's poorer
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Since he joined the defense fund in 1993, his colleagues say,
Figueroa has significantly refocused the 28-year-old civil rights
organization. A telegenic master of the stinging sound bite, he has
raised the group's profile, expanding its work to include policy
research, a campaign urging Latinos to complete census forms, and
political advocacy, including for the clemency President Clinton
granted 16 imprisoned Puerto Rican nationalists last year.
</P>
<P>
   As an issue, he is rather fond of Vieques. ``Who wants bombing
in their backyard?'' Figueroa says. ``It's not a complicated
question. And we can use it as a way of mainstreaming the message
of who we are. Last year it was Ricky Martin. Now it's Vieques that
has captured the public's attention. And it's not just someone
dancing around!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
