<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-NYT &LR;      05-08 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASHES NEAR REBEL LEADER'S HOME LEAVE AT LEAST 4 DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SIERRA-LEONE-U.N., SIERRA-LEONE-RESCUE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Thousands of protesters, including
rival militias, marched Monday on the compound of Foday Sankoh, the
rebel leader, some throwing rocks, and his partisans responded by
firing into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the protesters were shot execution-style as they lay on
the ground, according to witnesses. Dozens of U.N. peacekeepers
assigned to the house watched helplessly, shouting, ``Cease fire!''
</P>
<P>
   At least four people died.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Freetown, rebels fired at a U.N. helicopter that had
flown with Sankoh's permission to the town of Makeni to get two
wounded U.N. soldiers. After taking off, the pilot was forced to
land and abandon the helicopter, said Lt. Col. Jaswinder Sandhu, a
U.N. spokesman. The United Nations has already been humiliated by
the taking of more than 500 of its personnel _ soldiers and
civilians _ as hostages around the country in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The violence inside the capital underlined how badly the steps
toward peace have been wiped out since the arrival of the U.N.
force late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The day began as thousands gathered at a park to march against
Sankoh, whom many hold responsible for blocking the peace process
and some consider a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people marched across the Freetown peninsula,
joined by some former soldiers and Kamajors, who are traditional
hunters, toward the house of Sankoh in western Freetown. Sankoh
lives in a two-story house inside a compound guarded by U.N.
peacekeepers and his own men.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon, the peacekeepers appeared overwhelmed by the crowd,
which pushed toward the compound and began hurling rocks and bricks
at the house. The peacekeepers, pinned against a fence, are
believed to have fired in the air. It was not clear what happened
next. But witnesses said Sankoh's own men began shooting at the
crowd and that, in turn, former government soldiers who were among
the protesters began firing at Sankoh's men.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, who at the time remained inside his house and was not
injured, told the Associated Press after the clash: ``They're
provoking us. Democracy is not about assaulting people's homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of Sankoh was not clear on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I speak to you, the exact whereabouts of Corporal Foday
Sankoh has not yet been determined,'' President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah
said on national radio Monday night, using the rank that Sankoh had
reached in the Sierra Leone army before he was cashiered years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear on Monday night how many people were killed and
wounded outside Mr. Sankoh's home.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, at Connaught Hospital and an adjoining morgue,
officials had recorded four deaths and 40 wounded, mostly from
bullet wounds. At the hospital's operating room, Dr. Sabine
Roquefort, of Doctors Without Borders, was the only surgeon
working.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Sierra Leoneans filed through the morgue, searching
for friends and relatives who had yet to be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sankoh was well protected, but the crowd was unprotected,''
said Mohammed Kallon, a member of Parliament who had helped
organize the march.
</P>
<P>
   The violence appeared to increase some Sierra Leoneans' anger at
the U.N. force, which has suffered a series of embarrassing
setbacks. Sierra Leoneans pelted some U.N. Nations trucks with
rocks on Monday after the incident outside Sankoh's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. forces have not responded as well as we had
expected,'' said Herbert Chuku, 30, who was taking part in the
march toward Sankoh's house. ``That's why we are expecting
countries like America, France and Great Britain to put an
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters criss-crossed the skies above the Freetown peninsula
all day, as foreigners, including almost all U.N. civilian
employees, continued to leave Sierra Leone. After its setbacks, the
U.N. force seemed focused on Monday night on defending western
Freetown, the headquarters of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 miles away in Port Loko, two camps where rebels
voluntarily put down their weapons were abandoned, said a Western
diplomat who flew over the area. It has become clear that many
rebels have taken up arms again, presumably with weapons stolen
from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's troops are ``better stocked now,'' said the diplomat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
