<HEADER>
A9447 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECT-ART-830(     05-08 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECT-ART-830(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO STUMBLES IN SOME OLD RUTS ON ITS WAY TO CLEAN ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM DILLON and JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ By all accounts, this year's presidential race is
the fairest and most open Mexico has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   But consider the fate of a clean-vote television campaign aimed
at persuading voters to resist coercive polling tactics, like those
that have helped the governing party win every presidential
election since the 1920s. Government officials sat passively for
weeks as pro-government media executives blocked the commercials
from the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only incident that raised concerns. Foreign
election observers, who will be traveling to Mexico to monitor the
voting, are facing delays in receiving visas. And lawmakers
monitoring campaign finance have been stymied.
</P>
<P>
   And since this is Mexico's first presidential election in which
an opposition candidate, Vicente Fox Quesada, has a credible chance
at victory, opposition leaders fear that the long-governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party may be quietly sabotaging
Mexico's costly, decade-long effort to level its electoral playing
field.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans are optimistic about the openness of the vote because
for the first time an autonomous agency, the Federal Elections
Institute, is in charge of the vote, and is lavishing $918 million
on the electoral process to prevent fraud and encourage equitable
competition.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jose Woldenberg, a former university professor who is president
of the electoral institute, makes a concise estimate of the
possibility of fraud in this year's ballot counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zero,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woldenberg is especially proud of new voting booths his agency
designed for the country's 112,500 polling stations. They are the
first Mexican booths to have a curtain so that onlookers cannot
watch a voter mark a ballot, he said in an interview. More
important, they are the first booths made to fit only one person.
</P>
<P>
   The new booths are part of sweeping electoral changes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, federal elections were controlled by the Interior
Ministry, a political arm of the president. Reforms that year put
the elections institute, which was controlled by the Interior
Ministry, under the control of a nine-member council representing a
range of political groups. For this election, the institute has
selected 700,000 Mexicans, picked solely because they were born in
April, to serve as poll officials. It has also prepared a fast,
computerized system for reporting the balloting results, to be
broadcast on live television and posted on the Internet as returns
are reported on the night of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 reforms also set limits on private donations and
earmarked hundreds of millions of public money to pay for
campaigns. The governing party, whose candidate is Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, and two opposition coalitions, one backing Fox and
another supporting Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, a leftist former
Mexico City mayor, will each receive about $100 million this year
for their campaigns. The opposition parties, which were nearly shut
out of the broadcast media in the last presidential run in 1994,
have money to buy a blizzard of ads on television and radio,
enabling them to reach backlands voters for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   However, the agency is working to level the electoral playing
field in a nation where the governing party, known as the PRI, has
held a unique grip on the levers of power for much of a century. It
remains the only political group with an organized presence
virtually everywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, old habits die hard. The broadcast media, whose
news decisions until the early 1990s were often dictated by the
government, has devoted 37 percent of campaign news coverage to the
PRI while Fox's party has received only 27 percent, according to a
survey by the electoral institute.
</P>
<P>
   Only 32 percent of Fox's coverage has been positive, in contrast
to 44 percent for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the election laws still have loopholes. For
instance, dozens of auditors scrutinizing the parties' books for
violations of campaign finance rules will not report their findings
until weeks after the election.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The laws are also vague in regulating efforts by political
parties to pressure voters. In Yucatan, the PRI mobilized brigades
to go house to house in contested districts making lists of voters'
names, according to Patricia McCarthy, a member of the elections
council in that state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't prove legally that it's coercion,'' McCarthy said.
``But in practice it is coercion in a state full of very poor
people. They say, `Look out, now the PRI has my name!' ''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo has by and large stayed above the
campaign. But problems like the block on the clean-vote TV campaign
and the visa delays experienced by the foreign election monitors
have raised suspicions among opposition leaders that his government
is working to restrain independent election monitoring in order to
help the PRI and Labastida, who was formerly interior minister,
Zedillo's chief political operator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9455 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      05-08 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE WE ALL SHOULD BUY RABBIT EARS, JUST IN CASE  
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've puzzled over the celebrated hissing match between Time
Warner and Disney for the better part of a week now, but I still
don't think I'm getting the Big Picture.
</P>
<P>
   The fuss, in case you were off reading a book or communing with
nature last week, is over how much Disney charges Time Warner to
carry Disney's ABC stations. In a technicolor snit, Time Warner
yanked ABC off the air in seven cities. Disney retaliated by
offering to reimburse Time Warner customers if they switch to
satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the dispute is media conglomerate Disney's opposition
to media conglomerate Time Warner's merger with media conglomerate
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   I know we're all supposed to work up a good froth over the fact
that this big-money spat caused folks to miss ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' but _ frankly _ I'm having a hard time keeping my
eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, I'm boycotting Reeg until he walks over to the
set of ``Wheel of Fortune'' and buys a question mark from Vanna.
Criminy, if we're going to hand out a million bucks to brainy
people, let's straighten our ties, shine our shoes and punctuate
the name of our show properly, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   My ambivalence about this cable tug-of-war is also influenced by
the cable tug-of-war in my own home. My wife and I have a
good-natured, long-running disagreement over how much TV a person
ought to have in order to get along in life.
</P>
<P>
   I think that, for optimum viewing pleasure, the screen should be
at least twice as big as my stinky feet stretched out on the sofa.
She disagrees and vetoes all my plans to knock over a liquor store
or take out a second mortgage to buy a TV set of respectable, i.e.,
wall-engulfing, size.
</P>
<P>
   This standoff resulted in our movers openly mocking my manhood
when we moved into our new home a couple of years ago.
(ITAL)``That's(END ITAL) your TV?'' one of them asked, smirking at
his co-worker as they paused to squint at the tiny screen. ``Yeesh,
you must not watch much TV, fella.'' They laughed heartily, then
resumed their delicate work of dropping boxes and nicking
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. I don't watch much TV, which brings me to the main
point of contention between my wife and me. In order to improve the
odds of finding something interesting to watch, I believe we ought
to subscribe to the widest array of channels available _ the Silver
Gold Platinum Uranium Package, or whatever it's called _ even if it
requires a periodic liquor-store heist or second mortgage to pay
for it.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, however, believes I should read a book or commune with
nature instead of watching TV. Besides, she says, the money for
upgrading the TV would be better spent on, say, our little girl's
college-education fund. At this point in the discussion, I always
relent.
</P>
<P>
   To a large degree, I brought this problem on myself. I
unwittingly short-circuited my own efforts when the smirking movers
left and I took on my first home improvement project _ signing up
for cable.
</P>
<P>
   When I called our local provider, I was startled to learn that
the basic service offered far fewer channels at nearly double the
cost of what I was accustomed to paying. In a technicolor snit, I
went off and bought a satellite dish, had it installed, turned on
the tube and _ voila! _ discovered I couldn't get network channels
with my low-budget Wet, Flimsy Cardboard Package.
</P>
<P>
   So I went out and bought rabbit ears. If I position my stinky
feet just right, I can get two identifiable stations, plus another
one that seems to offer a lot of snowstorm coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to upgrade our satellite dish to the Uranium Package
and get the networks and all other channels I'd like to receive,
we'd have to pay even more than the cable bill. And I can't
convince my wife the dish would make a nice planter.
</P>
<P>
   So I watch a lot of documentaries on the channels we do get, I
read a little, and occasionally I go outside to stand next to my
satellite dish and commune with nature.
</P>
<P>
   In time, perhaps, all of this will make me smart enough to go on
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and win big, heaping dishes of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Then we can upgrade. Provided, of course, that Time Warner and
Disney don't merge with more media conglomerates and decide to,
ahem, provide even better service at even better prices.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
