<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEAK EURO MEANS BARGAINS FOR U.S. VISITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 14)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bankers are wringing their hands; tour operators are
applauding.
</P>
<P>
   European countries are enjoying a decade-long boom in American
tourism, and the continued weakness of the new European currency,
the euro, is expected to attract even more Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as though the moment there's a strong dollar people
start packing their suitcases,'' said Giuliano Corsi, general
manager of the elegant Hotel Danieli in Venice. ``But the strong
dollar will certainly tempt people to come to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   At the luxurious Hotel Vier Jahreszeiten in Munich, capacity is
already 80 percent to 85 percent, some of which is due to American
visitors, and Gerhard Bosse, the front office manager, said,
``People are shopping and buying more, whether its simple souvenirs
or expensive items, even china.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone is so bullish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure whether a tourist from Burbank is going to come
here just because the dollar is a little stronger,'' said an
official at Euro Disney, which runs Disneyland Paris. Yet Disney
reported that park revenue had risen considerably in the first
three months of this year, though it did not say how much of that
was from Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen months ago, when the euro was introduced, the European
travel industry feared the new currency might be so strong it would
frighten visitors away. The opposite has happened.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, 11 countries _ Germany, France, Italy, Spain,
the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg, Austria, Ireland, Finland and
Portugal _ adopted the euro. Since then, any transaction not
involving cash may be done in euros. Thus, banks offer euro
accounts and credit cards, and travel agencies like Thomas Cook and
American Express euro-denominated traveler's checks; European
stores, like the Galeries Lafayette in Paris, advertise prominently
that they will accept them.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you pay for your Italian fashions or French meals in
francs or lire, you are still using euros, since the national
currencies, like French francs and Italian lire, are now mere
denominations of the euro. At the end of next year, national bills
and coins will disappear entirely. Government mints and private
contractors across Europe are busy printing 13 billion euro
banknotes and minting 56 billion coins.
</P>
<P>
   Since its introduction, the euro has lost value continuously
against other currencies. In fact, the euro has plummeted so far
that while an American buying euros a year ago got 0.85 of a euro
for every dollar, by May 5, he was getting 1.12. In local
currencies, that meant 7.3 French francs, instead of 5.5; 2.19
German marks instead of 1.65, and 2,172 Italian lire rather than
1,645.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Leu, director of the Brussels, Belgium-based European
Travel Commission, says his organization expects 12 million
American tourists this year, compared with 11.6 million last year,
continuing a string of annual increases that began in 1993. The
increases are due partly, he says, not only to the ``astonishing
fact that a cup of coffee costs 50 percent less than only a few
years ago,'' but also to America's booming economy. In the last
decade, he said, the pool of American travelers that European
tourism relies on most _ those with average annual earnings
exceeding $75,000 a year _ has doubled, to 30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Shackleford, regional director for Europe at the World
Tourism Organization in Madrid, recalls how before the euro was
introduced, European tour operators and hotel owners feared that a
powerful euro would deflect tourists to cheaper destinations, like
Turkey and Morocco. The present mix of weak euro, low European
inflation and a strong American economy, he said, `'is a tour
operator's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, airlines and cruise ship operators are cashing in. The
number of nonstop flights from American cities to Europe is
growing. In March, Air France began flying from Philadelphia to
Paris; this month, Northwest Airlines added flights from Detroit to
Rome and Milan.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Crystal Cruises of Los Angeles added several more
destinations, bringing its European cruises to 17, and lengthened
the season to mid-November, from late September; Holland America
increased its ships to three, from one. Cruise Lines International
Association, an industry group, says 1.2 million people will cruise
in Europe this year, double the number five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gavin Tollman, president and chief executive of Trafalgar Tours
in New York, said the powerful American economy and strong dollar
painted ``a jewel picture.'' Trafalgar travelers to Europe will
rise 30 percent this year over 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, not everyone in Europe is exulting. In Britain,
which decided against adopting the euro, the pound has gained in
value, making Britain more expensive for travelers from the
Continent. This month, the British Tourist Authority revised
tourism growth estimates down, from 5 percent to 3 percent. Britain
risks losing visitors to France and Italy, it warned, where prices,
measured in dollars, are as much as 20 percent lower than a year
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
