<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN TURNS IN SIGNATURES IN BID FOR PLACE ON TEXAS BALLOT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Presidential contender Patrick Buchanan turned
in an estimated 129,000 signatures to state election officials
Monday in a bid to secure his place as an independent candidate on
Texas' November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say what this guarantees is that the American people
are going to have an authentic choice this fall,'' Buchanan said.
``Not just a choice between basically one candidate of a party
establishment and another of an establishment which by and large
agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who listed as his Texas running mate Houston term
limits activist Clymer Wright, said he is still seeking the Reform
Party's presidential nomination, but sought ballot status as an
independent as an ``insurance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Wright, an old friend, agreed to be listed as a
running mate on the petitions as a ``stand-in.'' Buchanan gave no
indication whom he ultimately might pick as a vice presidential
contender. Wright was unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Reform Party, which has been critical of Buchanan's
lone wolf efforts, also is petitioning for ballot access on behalf
of numerous office-seekers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Those petitions are due to the Texas secretary of state at the
end of the month. Buchanan, as an independent candidate, was
required to submit his petitions on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Verney, founding national chairman of the Reform Party,
said Buchanan's efforts have disappointed Reform activists who have
spent years building the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money he spent on independent candidate ballot access
could have been spent on party ballot access,'' Verney said. ``Now,
without a big-name presidential candidate and a lot of money, it's
not going to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   It is likely Reform Party volunteers will be unable to secure
the 37,380 signatures required to run a full slate of candidates on
the November ballot, Verney said.
</P>
<P>
   In order to qualify as an independent, Buchanan needs about
58,000 signatures from registered voters who did not participate in
either the Democratic or Republican primaries. Election officials
must verify the signatures' authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a debate back and forth whether to try to get on as
a Reform Party or get on as an individual candidate,'' Buchanan
said. ``My understanding is that there are complexities and
problems getting a party on the ballot, and it can be disqualified
much easier than a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   With more to do securing a foothold in the 29 states where the
Reform Party is not on the ballot, Buchanan said his work in Texas
is over for now, although he plans to return to campaign in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do if he failed to get his party's
nomination, Buchanan asked, ``Who is going to beat me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Ross Perot is going to get in,'' Buchanan said
of the party's founder. To date, Perot has remained silent on
Buchanan's candidacy. The party will nominate its presidential
candidate in August.
</P>
<P>
   A former talk-show host and speechwriter for President Nixon,
Buchanan made unsuccessful presidential bids in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he bolted from the Republican Party to join the
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is good conservative country and I have always been well
-received here,'' said Buchanan, wearing a Texas-themed tie he said
was a gift from state Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Attended by about 30 supporters who greeted him with chants of,
``Go, Pat, go,'' Buchanan used the occasion to speak out against
normalizing relations with China and also against illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also took a few swipes at Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP
presidential front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Bush is a centrist, Bush RepjqjV,X7, and he comes out of
that wing of the party,'' Buchanan said. ``On the issue of right to
life, for example, the governor refuses to say he will chose
pro-life justices for the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Buchanan, a Roman Catholic, defended Bush's
handling of the Bob Jones University flap earlier this year, when
Bush came under fire for campaigning at the school whose namesake
founder is noted for anti-Catholic and racist statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the charge that Governor Bush or any member of his
family was in any way anti-Catholic is false, the charges are
without basis in fact,'' Buchanan said. ``I don't think the
governor had anything to apologize for.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his presumptive inclusion on the November ballot,
experts give Buchanan slim hope of doing much more than stealing a
few votes from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Monday when the verification process for
Buchanan's petitions would be complete.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
