<HEADER>
A9464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CRIME-RATES-ART-NYT &LR;      05-08 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-RATES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVERSAL IN MURDER RATES REACHES SMALLER TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In High Point, N.C., there has not been a drug- or gang-related
murder in the past 18 months, after a stunning upsurge in homicides
in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   In Natchez, Miss., the number of murders dropped to one in 1999,
after reaching 12 a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And in Oceanside, Calif., where there were 25 homicides in 1995,
there were seven last year.
</P>
<P>
   These drops in murder are seen as an important indication that
the decline in the nation's murder rate since 1991, long driven by
decreases in homicide in the big cities, is starting to take hold
in small cities, suburbs and rural areas across the country.
</P>
<P>
   This trend was underscored by the release Sunday of the FBI's
preliminary crime report for 1999, which showed that while homicide
dropped 2 percent in cities with a population of half a million or
more, it declined 10 percent in cities of 100,000 to 250,000, 12
percent in cities of 50,000 to 100,000 people and 14 percent in
communities of 10,000 to 25,000 people. Overall, in suburban
counties, the number of murders fell 12 percent and 14 percent in
rural counties.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the smaller the community, the bigger the decrease in
murders, according to the FBI study, known as the Uniform Crime
Report, which is based on figures supplied to the FBI by police
departments around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in big cities, officials in these smaller communities
attribute the decline to a mix of factors, including their
innovative programs, an improved economy and longer prison
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   In High Point, a city of 76,000, federal, state and local law
enforcement agencies, drawing on a program pioneered in Boston,
worked together to target drug dealers who had moved in from as far
away as Los Angeles and Mexico. In Natchez, an antebellum tourist
town of 19,000, officials say a new strategy of community policing
and four new officers financed by a Clinton administration program
helped cut crime.
</P>
<P>
   In Oceanside, a community of 160,000 just north of San Diego,
the waning of the crack cocaine epidemic, a healthy economy that
reduced unemployment and California's tough
``three-strikes-and-you're-out'' sentencing laws have kept
criminals in prison longer and all contributed to a reduction in
crime, local officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the declines in homicide began in the nation's big
cities and are spreading to smaller communities, said professor
Alfred Blumstein, a criminologist at Carnegie Mellon University, is
related to the reason the murder rate first increased in the
mid-1980s. It was the major cities that were initially hit by crack
cocaine, and then by the infestation of semiautomatic handguns and
gangs that accompanied the crack epidemic, he said. The smaller
cities and rural areas were slower to become involved in the crack
problem, and just as they lagged behind in the growth of crime,
``they are slower to come down,'' Blumstein said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some smaller cities and rural areas have been victims
of the success of larger cities in suppressing crime, which led
drug dealers and gangs to move to the small communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw in North Carolina, as law enforcement picked up
the pressure in the big cities in the mid-1990s, was that the gangs
purposely moved out to smaller places,'' said Walter Holton, the
U.S. attorney for the Middle District of North Carolina, in
Greensboro. ``We saw Mexican organized gangs literally pick up and
move from Greensboro to Randolph County,'' a rural area 30 miles to
the south, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would buy or rent property, a house or trailer, and start
selling drugs again,'' Holton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican gangs arrived at the same time as a large influx of
Hispanic families moving to North Carolina to work in the state's
rapidly expanding industries, textile mills, furniture factories
and the construction business, disguising their illicit activities,
Holton said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some gang members traveled back and forth from Los
Angeles to High Point, bringing a supply of drugs to sell. ``They
infiltrated the local market, becoming the major suppliers, and in
the process used violence for intimidation to take over the city,''
Holton added.
</P>
<P>
   But while the sharp decline in homicide in smaller communities
now is seen as a positive sign, several experts said they were
concerned that the slowing of the decrease in murder in big cities
could mean the country is nearing the end of the remarkable fall in
murder after eight consecutive years. ``The big cities are
signaling the end of the downturn is near,'' said James Allen Fox,
a professor of criminal justice at Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Blumstein said, ``The decline obviously can't
continue indefinitely.'' He has calculated that with the huge
reduction in murder in the past few years, ``If the trend
continued, we would have a negative homicide rate, and that would
occur in 2007.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally worrisome, the experts said, several big cities actually
had increases in murder in 1999 for the first time since 1991,
including San Diego, up 35.7 percent; St. Louis, up 15 percent;
Phoenix, up 14.6 percent; Milwaukee, up 11.7 percent, and New York,
up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been getting at the easy problems, so now that we've
gotten the easy gains, there should be a flattening out'' in the
overall decline, Blumstein said. Among these gains, he said, were a
shrinkage in the crack market and successful police tactics aimed
at getting young people not to carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor behind the success of smaller communities in
reducing crime has been the growing sophistication of the police in
smaller cities and towns in using many of the same tactics and
technology developed by the police in big cities like New York and
Boston. In Montclair, N.J., for example, Thomas Russo, the police
chief, said his officers now use crime mapping of past patterns of
offenses to predict where crimes will occur. They also have an
eight-member task force that targets high crime areas as well as a
juvenile unit in the city's high schools. Montclair has not had a
murder since 1997, when there were four.
</P>
<P>
   Still another factor is that smaller communities have introduced
programs, like those in big cities, to intervene early in reports
of domestic violence, trying to stop these incidents from
escalating to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington County, Va., with a population of 185,000, had only
four murders in 1999, a 50 percent reduction from eight in 1998,
though Arlington is just across the Potomac River from Washington,
a city with a high murder rate. ``I wish I could say it was my
programs,'' said Edward A. Flynn, Arlington's police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he points out that the county's few homicides are of
the traditional American kind, largely domestic killings or drunken
quarrels that turn into murder. So Flynn has stressed stopping
domestic violence early, ``to break the cycle of violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
