A9467 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BIG-GAME-MAIN-COX     05-08 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-GAME-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High rollers, rookies lining up
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Texan walked into the convenience store in Morrow,
handed over $7,000 in hundred-dollar bills and sat patiently
reading a magazine while the machine printed out lottery ticket
after lottery ticket for today's Big Game jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely any other customer will throw down a wad of
money like the big-spending Texan did Friday, not at the Citgo
Value Mart on South Main Street, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to beat him'' part-owner Balgit Singh Randhawa
said Monday. ``He said if nobody hits, he'll come back again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Texan already has plenty _ plenty _ of competition as
the biggest American lottery payoff ever grows to more than $325
million. Stores across Georgia are reporting double, triple, even
quadruple the typical daily ticket sales. Lines back up to beer
coolers. Extra cashiers and security guards are on duty.
</P>
<P>
   The virtue of patience is much in demand, especially with
unknown thousands of lottery neophytes drawn to the ticket-spitting
machines. Mary Radcliff helps first-timers mark their cards at the
Amoco she manages in Canton. Most aren't familiar with quick picks,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bustle and the potentially overwhelming drive to
turn a buck, customer service isn't lost at some stores. Bob
Langley, manager of a Speedway store in Fayetteville, Ga., turned
away possibly his biggest customer Friday afternoon when the man
said he wanted to purchase 4,000 Big Game tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Cranking out that many chits would've tied up the machine for
hours, alienating other ticket-hungry customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I could only give him 1,000,'' Langley recalled Monday.
``You've only got so much time.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is time now that is getting short for those dreaming of
riches unfathomable. Between now and 10:45 p.m., store owners,
managers and clerks expect another flurry of last-minute buying.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 18th drawing since March 7 without a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, folks were buying tickets at the rate of $350 per
second between 6 p.m. and 10:30 p.m. And, typically, 60 percent of
Big Game tickets are sold the day of the drawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold 2,600 tickets last Friday,'' said Tommy Stansel of
Tommy's Market outside Waleska. ``That's three times what I usually
sell.'' Stansel said the Big Game hasn't cut into other lottery
sales.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the Big Game that's creating the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' said Kimberly Walker, a cashier at the
Texaco station at Ga. 138 and Iris Drive in Conyers. ``We had two
people on the registers and it was still bad. It never stopped.
There was always a line. We weren't prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales normally run about 600 tickets a day. Now, though, they
jump to $2,200, virtually all of which are for the Big Game. A
third clerk will be added today, but Walker's not sure it'll help.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ``going to be terrible, too,'' Walker said. ``I just
hope someone wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
