<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-SALARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON LEADER'S PAY MAY BE TOPS AMONG NATION'S SCHOOL CHIEFS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELANIE MARKLEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Worried that other districts might lure him away,
Houston school trustees are boosting Superintendent Rod Paige's
salary to $275,000, believed the highest in the nation among school
chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Paige, who will receive a 26 percent raise on July 1, said
Monday he was caught off-guard when school trustees voted 7-0 late
last week to substantially increase his salary, now $219,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't seek this,'' said Paige, ``but I'm appreciative for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige's new salary, which tops the $260,000 paid to Dallas
Superintendent Waldemar ``Bill'' Rojas, reflects how superintendent
salaries have escalated nationwide in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod Paige, in our judgment, has been grossly underpaid,'' said
board President Larry Marshall. ``How do you justify the
superintendent of Dallas, Texas, making more money than the
superintendent of the Houston Independent School District when we
have more students? What we sought to do was to correct the
inequity.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Federation of Teachers President Gayle Fallon said she
hopes that teachers will now get an equitable pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly just raised our expectation level,'' she said.
``I expect to see the teachers the highest paid in the nation.
Hell, there are times I'd settle for the highest paid in Harris
County, which I don't think is unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige confirmed that he had been contacted by officials in
cities that are looking for new school chiefs, including Los
Angeles and New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not paid a lot of attention to that because it's almost
getting to be routine right now, where people ask me if I have an
interest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paige, whose contract expires in 2004, said he is ``committed to
Houston'' and will stay ``as long as we are accomplishing things,
as long as the board has an interest, as long as we are moving
forward and improving school performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said consistency in leadership is one of the reasons
HISD has gained a national reputation for academic improvement.
</P>
<P>
   While the average tenure of superintendents in big-city
districts is 2 1/3 years, Paige has been at the helm for more than
six years.
</P>
<P>
   National groups that monitor superintendent salaries say that a
shortage of qualified superintendents has driven salaries up.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the really quality leaders, the competition is really
fierce. And if you've got a good track record and have definitely
shown you've done a tremendous job at the helm, it sort of pushes
higher salaries,'' said Henry Duvall, spokesman for the Council of
the Great City Schools.
</P>
<P>
   According to surveys of superintendent salaries, Rojas and
Thomas Tocco, earning $249,000 in Fort Worth, Texas, are believed
to be the highest-paid superintendents in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Crew, who quit earlier this year as chancellor of New York
City schools, earned $245,000.
</P>
<P>
   New York, in particular, has had 12 superintendents in 20 years,
including seven who were fired or resigned under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Seltz, spokeswoman for the American Association of School
Administrators, said it is not surprising to see dramatically
rising salaries, particularly in urban districts that are working
hard to hire and keep good leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shortage of qualified superintendents who are
willing to take on the challenges of these large urban districts,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even smaller Houston area districts such as Cypress-Fairbanks
and Spring Branch are now paying their superintendents $200,000 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
