u w BC-ENVIRON-POLICY-NYT     05-08 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRON-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION TO PROPOSE A BAN ON NEW ROADS IN MANY NATIONAL
FORESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A draft proposal from the Clinton administration to
safeguard national forests from development would bar building
roads across nearly one-quarter of those lands but would not
immediately rule out future logging or off-road vehicle activity.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which was outlined Monday by Forest Service
officials, is intended to flesh out a pledge that President Clinton
has portrayed as a central part of his legacy. But some
environmentalists said it fell short of their hopes and warned that
it would leave some forests open to exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was described by Forest Service officials in advance of
a scheduled announcement on Tuesday. It will be reviewed within the
administration after a comment period that is to include some 300
public meetings in the next two months, and activists on both sides
of the issue said they held out hope that it would be revised.
</P>
<P>
   Among the voices that will be heard in those sessions are those
of the timber industry, which has long opposed any effort to put
broad tracts of forest off limits to roads and logging. But a top
official said in an interview Monday that the industry now
considered some form of broad protection as inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not resigned to it getting through without a fight, but
I think the odds are that it will get through,'' said the official,
W. Henson Moore, president of the American Forest &AMP; Paper
Association and a former congressman from Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who oversees the Forest
Service, called the draft plan an important step toward preserving
``among the last and best pristine lands in America.'' Glickman
said the draft was ``a balanced proposal,'' but he added, ``It's
clear to us that any good proposal can be improved upon.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of putting so much forest land off limits to roads has
been strongly opposed by powerful lawmakers from some Western
states, who contend that it would deal a heavy blow to the timber
industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration's plan would bypass those critics by
using administrative rule changes that do not require congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first outlined the initiative in a speech last fall in a
national forest in Reddish Knob, Va., and it remains the subject of
intense debate on Capitol Hill, where Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho,
dismissed it Monday as an unfair ``end run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service proposal, in the form of a draft
environmental impact statement, provides the first details on the
administration's plan. A plan that the agency named among several
alternatives as its favored approach would immediately bar road
building in virtually all of the large, unprotected roadless areas
that remain in the forest system, spanning a total of 43 million
acres in 39 states.
</P>
<P>
   The 155 national forests and grasslands that would be affected
include Lewis and Clark National Forest in Montana, Tahoe National
Forest in California, Olympic National Forest in Washington and
White Mountain National Forest in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But, in what might be a bow to political reality, the one forest
explicitly exempted from the proposal is the giant Tongass National
Forest in Alaska, the nation's largest, where conservation efforts
have been opposed by members of Alaska's congressional delegation
who see it as a vital economic resource.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Forest Service proposal, no decision about whether to
set aside roadless areas in the Tongass would be made until at
least 2004, when a plan for the future of the forest would next
come under review.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, even across the millions of acres where road
construction would be barred under the plan, any further decisions
about prohibiting logging and off-road activity would be deferred
until plans for the forests are next reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   In laying out the administration's approach last October in
Virginia, Clinton vowed ``to protect all this before it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews Monday, a number of environmentalists
criticized the administration's approach as inadequate. Ken Rait,
director of the Heritage Forests Campaign, an organization based in
Portland, Ore., that campaigns to protect forests, said he had
hoped the administration would draft a tougher policy that
``completely safeguards these forests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hopeful that the final policy will measure up to the
vision that President Clinton laid out last October,'' Rait said.
</P>
<P>
   About 34 million acres, or 18 percent, of the country's national
forest land has been set aside by Congress as wilderness areas,
which are off-limits to development and on which roads, logging and
off-road vehicles are banned. About 50 percent of national forest
land is open to logging or was long ago crisscrossed with the roads
that make development possible.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plan would cover most of the rest, which is
listed by the Forest Service as roadless areas but where road
construction has never been totally ruled out. Congressional
approval would have been required to formally designate any of the
land as wilderness, and the opposition from the Western lawmakers
has prompted the administration's effort to act on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The administration officials who outlined the draft proposal
spoke only on condition of anonymity, saying they did not want to
upstage announcements scheduled for Tuesday in Washington and
Phoenix by Glickman and Mike Dombeck, the Forest Service chief.
</P>
<P>
   In drafting the plan, the Forest Service weighed several
alternatives to protect the roadless areas, administration
officials said. They said at least one of those plans would have
gone further than the one the agency ultimately chose, by
explicitly ruling out logging as well as further road construction.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended ban on road building alone was based on the
belief that ``road construction represents the single greatest
threat to the social and ecological values of roadless areas,'' a
Forest Service official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the road ban would have a broad effect because
the prohibition would in most cases make logging and other
activities extremely difficult. One official estimated that the
approach would reduce future logging by 70 percent in what are now
roadless areas.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists said that unless logging and off-road
vehicle traffic was explicitly prohibited in the final plan, the
way would be left open for helicopter logging and other activities
that could spoil areas that deserved total protection.
</P>
<P>
   Federal procedures require the proposal to be open to comment
until July 17. The Forest Service has scheduled more than 300 open
meetings, beginning next week, to solicit public reaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
