<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9473 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AD-AGENCY-MERGER-NYT &LR;      05-08 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AD-AGENCY-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG &AMP; RUBICAM AGREES TO TAKEOVER IN BIGGEST AD DEAL EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AD-AGENCY-YOUNG) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN with STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Young &AMP; Rubicam, a Madison Avenue icon that gave the
world the Jell-O jingle and the numbered Excedrin headaches, ended
77 years of independence Monday night by agreeing to a $5.7 billion
takeover by the WPP Group, a rival based in London. It is the
largest deal in the history of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   While the boards of the two companies have yet to formally vote
on the agreement, executives close to the negotiations said they
were expected to announce an accord as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ends four months of on-again, off-again talks that
included dramatic trans-Atlantic conference calls and hand-scrawled
faxes with proposals and counterproposals, a second possible suitor
and an 11th-hour breakdown in negotiations that rivaled the
theatrics of some of the most creative commercials the companies
produce.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover would make WPP the largest advertising company in
the world measured in billings and revenue, leap-frogging the
Omnicom Group and the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would create advertising campaigns for
household brands like Ford, IBM, American Express, AT&AMP;T, Kraft
Foods and Sony. The agreement brings under one roof famous ad
agencies like Young &AMP; Rubicam, J. Walter Thompson and Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather, while making siblings of well-known public relations
agencies like Burson-Marsteller, Hill &AMP; Knowlton and Cohn &AMP; Wolfe.
Each will retain its distinctive identity within WPP.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam had been one of the last big independent agency
companies in an industry that had been consolidating relentlessly
since the mid-1980s, as Madison Avenue sought to keep pace with the
growth and international expansion of its clients seeking global
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big are getting bigger,'' said Karen R. Ficker, managing
director for advertising, publishing and new media at ING Barings.
``If you looked around out there, Y&AMP;R was probably one of the best
left for WPP.''
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam is losing its independence only 24 months after
the agency, privately held since it was founded by copywriters
Raymond Rubicam and John Orr Young in 1923, decided to sell stock
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The shares had climbed until recently and then declined, which
made Young &AMP; Rubicam vulnerable to a takeover by larger advertising
conglomerates like WPP.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the talks, WPP has agreed to
pay 0.835 of its own American depository receipt shares for each
share of Young &AMP; Rubicam. That equates to WPP paying about $63 for
each share of Y&AMP;R based on Friday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R's shares fell $4 5/16 or nearly 8 percent to $49 13/16 in
Nasdaq trading Monday. Shares of WPP dropped 65 pence, or 6.7
percent, to 910 after dropping as low as 890 in London on Monday;
its American depository receipt shares dropped 9 percent to $66
7/8.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will give WPP control of three of the world's 11
largest autonomous ad agency operations ranked by revenue: Thompson
(4), Ogilvy (10) and Y&AMP;R (11). That is the same number controlled
by WPP's principal rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom also has three: BBDO (3), DDB (7) and TBWA (15). So too
does Interpublic: McCann-Erickson (2), Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners (13)
and Draft (24).
</P>
<P>
   The goal of these new behemoth-sized agency companies is to own
or control as many of the large, multinational ad agency operations
as possible in an effort to offer the most potential services to
large, multinational clients. With each agency set up as an an
autonomous unit, the intent is to minimize conflicts that would
keep advertisers from hiring the agency company.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, agencies owned by Omnicom work for auto companies
that compete against one another, but with the agencies operating
separately, the automakers are ostensibly assured that no agency
shares proprietary data with its siblings. So BBDO and Merkley
Newman Harty work for DaimlerChrysler; DDB works for Volkswagen;
TBWA works for Nissan; and Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners works for
Isuzu.
</P>
<P>
   Some clients, however, disapprove of those arrangements and will
not agree to use an agency with a sibling that works for a rival.
That was a major issue in the talks between Young &AMP; Rubicam and its
second suitor, Publicis of France. Publicis said Monday that for
now, it was no longer interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to say no when you have such an opportunity,''
Maurice Levy, chairman and chief executive at Publicis in Paris,
said in a telephone interview. ``But there were some obstacles
regarding the nature of the deal, organizational problems and
client conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary stumbling block was Ford, which is a major Young &AMP;
Rubicam client and would probably have disapproved if Y&AMP;R were
purchased by a company that also had subsidiaries working for
rivals like BMW (Fallon McElligott in Minneapolis), General Motors
(Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney in San Francisco) and Renault (Publicis).
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the WPP deal collapses,'' Levy said, ``we would be
ready to look at Y&AMP;R once again. The phone number is in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the largest in the history of ad business, more than
twice the past record, set only in February when Havas Advertising
agreed to acquire Snyder Communications for about $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement struck between WPP and Young &AMP; Rubicam came only
after fits and starts of negotiations as each side jockeyed for
better position and leverage over the other. The main sticking
points, finally resolved over the weekend, were over price, Young &AMP;
Rubicam's ability to operate autonomously within WPP during the
integration of the company over the first year, as well as
contractual and compensation provisions for the acquired company's
senior executives. On price, Martin Sorrell, WPP's ambitious chief
executive, increased his exchange offer from 0.83 shares of WPP's
ADR to 0.835. The two companies also compromised on Young &AMP;
Rubicam's autonomy, creating a four-person board consisting of two
executives from WPP _ Sorrell and Paul Richardson, chief financial
officer _ and two executives from Young &AMP; Rubicam _ Thomas D. Bell
Jr., current chief executive, and Michael Dolan, chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also came to terms over provisions to retain Young
&AMP; Rubicam's top talent, with a non-compete clause that prevents its
employees from working for competing clients at rival agencies for
a year after leaving Y&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan is expected to become chief executive of Young &AMP; Rubicam
under WPP. Bell has been offered the position of chairman of WPP,
but it remains unclear whether he will accept. Sorrell was taking a
Concorde flight from London to New York Tuesday morning to meet
with Bell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
