u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-08 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHERE IS MARCUS CAMBY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was time Monday for the Knicks to take their medicine
for losing Game 1 to the Heat, several doses of an over-the-airways
prescription known as the classic second-guess. Much of it was
administered by reporters. Some of it was self-applied. All of it
indicated that the Knicks' playoff honeymoon concluded 10 days ago
not far from Niagara Falls, and they have come back to their
customary state of crankiness and doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Such lousy front-runners these Knicks are, which probably means
they'll be ready and raring to go in Game 2 of the Eastern
Conference semifinals Tuesday night at American Airlines Arena,
where the only missing component Monday was a pack of protesters
shouting, ``Free Marcus Camby.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the arena on a balmy afternoon, Jeff Van Gundy was
chafing at having to explain why he sat his high-octane octopus in
the final three minutes and 35 seconds of Sunday's 87-83 defeat,
after Camby had grabbed 13 rebounds in just 27 minutes. Did Van
Gundy go too long with Larry Johnson or Patrick Ewing? Should he
have pulled his point guard, and gone with Allan Houston and
Latrell Sprewell in the back court?
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's answer, delivered from the pulpit of rhetorical high
ground, was that he went with the same lineup that was 3 for 3 down
the stretch in the Toronto series, and how come no one questioned
his deployment then?
</P>
<P>
   ``When it doesn't work out, you made the wrong decisions,'' said
the coach, his lip in half smirk, before he went on to do a little
second-guessing himself, of his players' passivity in defending the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that it was much easier for the pro Camby reform
movement to fire up with the benefit of 20-20 hindsight that Larry
Johnson missed the open 3-ball this time and Patrick Ewing was
dominated by Alonzo Mourning and the Knicks could have used a
double shot of adrenaline and athleticism, of sugar-coated Camby.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, Camby pretended, relaxing his long limbs as he sat
on a table along the sideline. ``It has nothing to do with age and
size,'' he said. ``This is how we played most of our games at the
end, with old guys, short guys, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   The old guy, Patrick Ewing, was moving by game's end with the
grace of a glacier. The short guy, Johnson, was not about to
produce the game-altering energy or put-back basket the Knicks
clearly needed as they were misfiring on their last eight shots.
Throw in Latrell Sprewell being outweighed by 50 pounds by Jamal
Mashburn and what you have is a Knicks' starting and finishing
frontline that had better start spiking its spinach.
</P>
<P>
   The second-guessing was a bit overstated, given that the Knicks
several times were one shot away from winning Game 1. On the other
hand, they have now lost four of five against the Heat this season,
and if they lose again Tuesday night, expect three days in New York
of full-court panic. Van Gundy, for his part, should already have
forgotten what worked against Toronto, whose front court players
were as rooted to the floor as New York's. If the Knicks and Heat
go down the stretch again Tuesday night, he's got to start
remembering his team's most significant hour last spring, Game 5 of
the six-game takeout of the Pacers in Indianapolis in the
conference final.
</P>
<P>
   It was Camby who appeared from nowhere, changed shot patterns,
controlled the air space above the rim, spread his wingspan and
jetted the Knicks into the finals. He is the one Knick who has the
potential on any night to soar above the common Knicks-Heat playoff
scrum, but the coach apparently still has issues with commitment to
a whimsical player who has little conventional offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Larry played well,'' Van Gundy said. ``I don't know
who else you take out.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no democracy, and Sprewell said he has no idea what Van
Gundy's planning, but he had no qualms about casting his vote for
the point guard to sit in certain situations. This way, Sprewell
reasoned, Camby could get more minutes, and the Knicks could make
the injured Tim Hardaway guard himself or Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like smelling blood,'' Sprewell said. ``He's out there,
hobbling around, and I would definitely do something to make him
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Though last season is already part of a century past, the
friendship of Sprewell and Camby was, in part, a product of the way
they, as newcomers, were used by Van Gundy. They still often serve
as a window into one another's feelings, and Sprewell left no doubt
Monday that Camby was discouraged by not getting the chance to
impact Sunday's end game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I know he is,'' Sprewell said. ``I thought he should be
in the game. We talked about it but that's a coach's decision and
Marcus isn't the type at this point to pout.''
</P>
<P>
   Who has time? After three playoff games in 17 days, it is a
pleasure to have Game 2 come up before we have barely digested Game
1. With regard to a continuum and competition and context, this
finally feels like the playoffs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
