<HEADER>
A9476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     05-08 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A CHANCE TO LET REGGIE REST IN PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Could this be the end? Could this be the final chapter
of the worst Boston sports story of them all? Let's hope so.
</P>
<P>
   There's never been a good day in the Reggie Lewis story. No
closure. No healing. No catharsis. There's not been one good moment
since the night Lewis collapsed running his lane on the parquet
floor against the Charlotte Hornets. That was back in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone lost. A woman lost her husband. Children lost their
dad. A mother lost her son. The community lost a good guy. The
Celtics lost a star guard. Reggie's bosses lost faith in their own
good judgment. Fans lost a favorite player. Insurance companies
surrendered $12 million. A law firm went bankrupt after spending
three years on the first trial. A doctor lost his good reputation.
</P>
<P>
   And now Donna Harris-Lewis has lost her latest negligence
lawsuit against Dr. Gilbert Mudge, and some will lose faith in the
judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has an opinion about Harris-Lewis and her lawsuit:
She's greedy . . . The doctor thought he was smarter than everyone
else . . . Reggie damaged his heart by abusing drugs . . . There
would be no rumors about Reggie and drugs if he'd been a white
athlete . . . Donna's a publicity hound . . . Dr. Mudge lied to
cover his own butt . . . Donna is delusional and ridden with guilt
. . . She's a victim of a racist media that can't tolerate a
strong, black woman.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly everyone sympathizes with a young mother of two
children who buried her 27-year-old husband. But this isn't about
race or gender, and it isn't about medical negligence, either. Dr.
Gilbert Mudge was guilty of arrogance and certainly fell in love
with the TV cameras, but neither of two juries found him guilty of
medical negligence.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Harris-Lewis is the one who didn't like the opinion of 12
capable cardiologists who concluded that Lewis's NBA career was
over and asked about drug abuse. She's the one who had him
transferred (without medical supervision) under the cover of
darkness from New England Baptist to Brigham and Women's Hospital.
She's the one who decided not to put a headstone on Reggie's grave
at Forest Hills Cemetery in Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   She's the one who collected $12 million the Celtics owed on
Reggie's contract, then made this heinous statement to Boston
Magazine: ``I think about those firefighters in Worcester. Lots of
money is being raised for those families and I need to be taken
care of, too. Everybody has to say I'm greedy, but I do want my
money back this time around. Why should I lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Ours is a litigious society. We look to blame someone else when
something bad happens. A woman spills hot coffee on herself driving
through a fast-food window and wins a multimillion-dollar reward.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mudge made a mistake, but he didn't kill Reggie Lewis.
Sometimes we have to look at plaintiff accountability in addition
to defendant liability. Everyone feels bad that Reggie is gone, but
he is gone because he and his wife didn't listen to the opinion of
the Dream Team of physicians. They searched until they found a
doctor who would tell them what they wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after Reggie died, Harris-Lewis told WBZ-TV, ``I
personally can't blame anyone. I think everyone that was involved
with Reggie's care, they did the best that they could.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Harris-Lewis said she sued Dr. Mudge to clear Reggie's
name of drug rumors, but the first trial served only to bring more
unsubstantiated drug rumors to the surface. In the end, the drug
stuff was tossed aside, settlement discussions went nowhere, and
Harris-Lewis lost a case that was inspired by either greed, a need
for attention, or _ and this is the best case we can make _ guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Not having experienced her loss, it's easy for any of us to say
that Donna Harris-Lewis should get on with her life. It has, after
all, been seven years. She has two beautiful children, a worthy
foundation, and the legacy of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   There have been too many bad days and too many people hurt.
Donna Harris-Lewis failed to win two trials. It's time to stop
looking back, move forward, and let Reggie rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
