<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-BADDELEY-TEX     05-08 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BADDELEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH ONLY 19, BADDELEY HAS SIGHTS SET ON PRO CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Ron Baddeley, a former crew chief for legendary
driver Mario Andretti on the professional racing circuit, learned a
thing or two about world-class athletes while tuning and repairing
Indy cars in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He was struck by their single-minded focus. Years later, after
returning to his native Australia, he noticed the same trait in his
son, Aaron. Shortly after swinging his first golf club, the
teen-ager dropped off his local cricket and Australian rules
football teams, despite showing promise in both sports.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Aaron Baddeley was a 23-handicapper, smitten by a
game he could not master. Ron Baddeley, a non-golfer, questioned
the move, but put his 13-year-old son in touch with Dale Lynch, a
renowned swing teacher from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, Aaron consistently posted rounds in the 70s. By
14, he won the club championship at Croydon Golf Club. Now 19,
Baddeley's resume includes a championship at the 1999 Australian
Open, a Masters appearance and a berth in the opening round of the
GTE Byron Nelson Classic on Thursday at the Four Seasons Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad credentials for a teen-age amateur. Aaron Baddeley is
using an extended stay in the United States and Canada during the
2000 season, where he is competing primarily on sponsor's
exemptions, to determine his readiness for life as a professional
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Baddeley said he has been planning this junket for five
years. The idea surfaced after Aaron won the club championship at
Croydon and crystallized after his parents realized the most
effective way to discipline their son was to take away his golf
clubs. Even a one-day ban, Ron Baddeley said, triggered
conciliatory gestures and requests for immediate reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   It was after one such reunion of player and clubs that the
14-year-old prodigy uttered the words that struck a chord with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron told us, `I don't know what I'll do in life, but it'll
have something to do with golf,' '' Ron Baddeley said. ``I thought,
`Maybe he's got something here.' So we started that day, projecting
where he wanted to go with his golf career.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Aaron Baddeley's path has intersected with many of the
giants of the game, including the icon of Australian golf: Greg
Norman. In Baddeley, Norman envisions his successor as the poster
boy for Aussie golf in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Norman, who joined Colin Montgomerie on the
list of also-rans Baddeley dusted in November while claiming a
two-stroke victory at the 1999 Australian Open. ``Aaron has the
ability to do that mentally. Whether he wants the baton or not is
another thing. But I'd like to see that for Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a Tiger Woods, a Jack Nicklaus, a Seve Ballesteros ...
somebody with that type of charisma coming from Australia to keep
the game going and growing. It's important for us to do that. Aaron
has got the mindset to be that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has the desire. Asked about long-range goals during his
first lesson with Lynch in 1995, Baddeley responded that he wanted
to be on the PGA Tour by his 21st birthday. Five years later, he
has upped the stakes. The new target is Woods' status as the top
player on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger's the benchmark. I want to be better than the
benchmark,'' said Baddeley, who has played multiple practice rounds
with Woods at tour events this season. The youngster's performance
surprised the world's top-ranked golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits the ball better than I did at the same age, no doubt
about it,'' Woods said. ``He controls his ball flight better.
There's no denying Aaron has great talent. It's just a matter of
what he does with that talent, how dedicated he'll be as he
matures.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his track record, dedication to golf appears to be
Baddeley's long suit. Before his Masters debut, where he missed the
cut, Baddeley played nine practice rounds at Augusta National Golf
Club _ more than double the typical amount of preparation. Peers
describe him as a fixture on the practice tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I do, I want to be the best and I work hard at it,''
Baddeley said. ``My game is pretty solid, but there's room for
improvement. I'm a solid ball striker, and my \Rdriving\S accuracy
is improving as my swing gets better. I'm a pretty decent putter
from inside seven feet. If I have them outside that range, I pretty
much miss a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get to be like Tiger, where there are no
weaknesses. My goal is to get to the point where, if the ball
striking's not quite there, your short game picks it up and you
still shoot a good number. I'm not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's making strides in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   And those strides will not include time spent playing college
golf in the United States. Although he has received offers from
more than 25 schools, Baddeley nixed that idea after comparing
college curriculums to the academic load he's handling at the
Victoria Institute of Sport, where Lynch is headmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do any school work there, which is perfect,''
Baddeley said. ``All we do is just golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley did that well enough in the final round of the 1999
Australian Open to post a closing 69 while paired with Montgomerie,
the No. 3 player in the world rankings. Monty, who finished third,
answered with a 71. Baddeley said he kept himself calm during
crunch time by singing between shots with caddie Dion Kippling, a
longtime friend. Most of the tunes they crooned were by Taxi Ride,
a popular Australian rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who follow Baddeley at the Nelson should expect a similar
earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we've got a couple of new songs,'' Baddeley said. ``But
I think my parents will vouch that I have an extremely bad voice.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll also vouch that Aaron is in the final stages of his
``real-world education,'' as Ron Baddeley described it.
</P>
<P>
   Since his son emerged as a world-class amateur golfer in 1998,
Baddeley's parents have taken out loans and borrowed money against
credit cards totaling $72,500 for travel expenses to tournaments in
the United States. Included is a $28,000 bankroll for the 2000
season, which began with Baddeley finishing 57th at the Honda
Classic in his tour debut (March 9-12). After the Nelson, his next
scheduled appearance is at the Memorial Tournament (May 25-28), the
only event on the PGA Tour that offers an automatic berth to the
Australian Open champ.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Baddeley said his son will remain in North America until
September, playing events on the PGA and Canadian tours, before
deciding if he is ready to turn professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no difference in spending that money playing golf than
sending him to college,'' Ron Baddeley said. ``It's about a
career.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is Aaron's final year as an amateur, that's fine. If
not, that's fine, too. No one in the family, least of all the
prodigy, has an iron-clad timetable. Baddeley said plans to huddle
with his father and coach ``in September or October'' to review his
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't feel my game is up to scratch, I won't turn
professional,'' Baddeley said. ``If I feel my game is ready and my
coach feels the same way, there's no reason why I don't turn
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   What they want to avoid, Ron Baddeley said, is putting Aaron in
a situation similar to Justin Rose, the British teen-ager who
turned professional after finishing fourth in the 1998 British
Open. Rose, now 19, missed 21 consecutive cuts after turning
professional and competes today as a non-exempt member of the
European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley said he seeks a smoother transition to life as a
touring pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've dreamed of doing ever since I started
playing,'' Baddeley said. ``I wanted to play at Augusta, to play on
the PGA Tour. I've dreamed about it so vividly, it's not much out
of reality that I'm here. But it's probably come along a little
quicker than what I expected. I want to make sure I'm ready before
I take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Baddeley's ``real-world education'' continues
this week at the Byron Nelson Classic. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
