<SLUG> BC-SF-FAT-BIAS-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO OUTLAWS SIZE DISCRIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
  By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was a big day for people tired of living in a
small world.
</P>
<P>
   The large and tall, the pudgy and the plump _ in short, anyone
who has ever had to endure the stigma of being overweight in a
society where thin is in _ have won a battle for the bulge, at
least here in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that says a lot about this city's legendary
sensitivity, the Board of Supervisors passed an ordinance on Monday
that makes it illegal to discriminate against a person based on the
nebulous category of ``size.''
</P>
<P>
   Known throughout the city as the ``fat ordinance,'' the measure
actually applies to skinny people, too. It adds height and weight
to the same antidiscrimination codes that provide protections for
people based on race, religion, color, ancestry, age, sex, sexual
orientation, gender identity, disability and place of birth.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance, inspired by a fitness company advertisement that
was plastered on a billboard last year (``When the aliens come,
they will eat the fat ones first'') adds San Francisco to a short
list of places in the nation _ Santa Cruz, Calif., Washington,
D.C., and the state of Michigan _ with similar statutes.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance has generated a number of jokes: one local
columnist said it inspired him to form the ``California Association
of the Not So Bad, Average and Mediocre.''
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for fat acceptance say the ordinance is a
necessary remedy for all those who have ever been insulted, denied
a seat at a restaurant or rejected for a job because of their
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're convinced that this is a serious problem,'' said Larry
Brinkin of the San Francisco Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marilyn Wann, a local leader of the National Association to
Advance Fat Acceptance, and the author of ``Fat! So?'' (Ten Speed
Press, 1998), called the legislation historic and necessary,
especially when about half of all Americans are overweight and one
in four is medically obese, according to government statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need a diet,'' said Wann, who said her 270 pounds on
a 5-foot-4 frame was her natural size. ``We need an end to
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of fat-acceptance groups is evident on the Internet.
Dozens of groups have Web sites, notably the Fat Activist Task
Force (www.naafa.org/fatf), formed in 1989 to pressure Hallmark
Cards to remove products poking fun at fat people from their
merchandise list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fat people are people,'' said John Cahill, a San Francisco
writer who carries his 250 pounds on a 6-foot frame. ``From the
remarks I get on the Muni trains, you'd think I was a deaf cow.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 people of various sizes, most large, attended Monday's
board meeting to support the ordinance, which passed unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've counseled too many women and men in body-image support
groups who have had horrible experiences,'' said Melinda McBride, a
graduate student who attended the meeting to support the ordinance.
``People have gone in for medical treatment for very specific
things and they've been told to lose weight. It's important that
this law passed because it can have far-reaching implications
outside of San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ammiano, the president of the board and a former stand-up
comedian who wrote the ordinance, said he was prompted to act in
part because overweight people often become ``targets and even
scapegoats of many negative moral traits, such as laziness, low
intelligence, gluttony, bad health, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Cruz, a 1992 ordinance banning discrimination based on
height, weight, physical characteristics and sexual orientation was
invoked only once, by two women who believed they were denied
housing because they were a lesbian couple. The matter was resolved
through arbitration. That ordinance clears the way for victims of
discrimination to file a lawsuit seeking monetary redress, but none
have yet been filed.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan and Washington, D.C., where measures banning
discrimination based on height and weight or personal appearance
have been in force law since the 1970s, numerous suits have been
filed. Debbie Moss of Washington's Human Rights Commission, said
the ordinance was used by ``people being overweight, people having
their hair a certain way _ there are all kinds of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rob Morse, the San Francisco Examiner columnist who
advocated acceptance of mediocrity, said the new ordinance would
probably not change life here all that much. ``In the past, the
supes have voted to protect tropical hardwoods, the Burmese people
and San Francisco's two daily newspapers,'' he said, ``and look at
all the good that's done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
