<HEADLINE>
AMID PROTESTS, SCHWARZKOPF ACCEPTS TRUMAN GOOD NEIGHBOR AWARD  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARTELLARO Knight Ridder Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The commander of allied forces in the Persian
Gulf War on Monday praised Harry S. Truman's leadership and
criticized current American military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf, who directed the 1991
assault on Iraq, spoke after receiving the 28th annual Harry S.
Truman Good Neighbor Award in ceremonies at the Muehlebach Tower of
the Kansas City Marriott Downtown.
</P>
<P>
   At the luncheon, Schwarzkopf was heckled by about a half-dozen
protesters scattered amid the 600 guests. As the general stepped to
the podium, the protesters rose, one by one, and shouted criticisms
of U.S. economic sanctions against Iraq and continued bombing of
that country.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters said those actions hurt innocent Iraqi children,
not dictator Saddam Hussein. Several luncheon guests responded with
boos and catcalls. The protesters were escorted from the hotel by
police, who did not make any arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Neighbor Award, presented since 1973 by the Harry S.
Truman Good Neighbor Award Foundation, came on the 116th
anniversary of the birth of the president, who lived in nearby
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Festivities were to continue Monday evening with the
presentation of the annual Harry S. Truman Award for Public
Service. This year the award went to the Truman Library and the
Truman Library Institute, the library's support organization. The
presentation was to be followed by groundbreaking for the two-year,
$17 million renovation of the library.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to about 600 guests, Schwarzkopf said Truman
possessed the two key traits of effective leadership: confidence
and character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of no one who is more the epitome of leadership
than Harry S. Truman,'' Schwarzkopf said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited two difficult decisions that Truman faced: whether to
desegregate the U.S. Armed Forces in 1948; and whether to use
nuclear weapons against Japan at the close of World War II. His
mention of Truman's desegregation order drew extended applause.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf also praised Truman for keeping the American
military strong, and he urged today's political leaders to
``maintain the kind of military we can all be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have to take a hard look at what's happening with our
military. The situation is not as happy as we might want,''
Schwarzkopf said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not elaborate during his prepared remarks. After the
luncheon, he said he was referring to recent reports of widespread
dissatisfaction among junior officers and reports that the military
was not meeting its re-enlistment goals.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized substandard housing for soldiers and their
families, and he said that military families subsisting on food
stamps was ``a national disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Fixing those situations, Schwarzkopf said, ``needs to be made a
national priority.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the protesters, Schwarzkopf said that ``nobody likes
what's happening in Iraq,'' but that lifting the sanctions would
allow Hussein to rebuild his military forces and threaten his
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein could stop it tomorrow if he would comply with
U.N. resolutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hotel, about 15 to 20 persons lined up across the
street and protested the sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
