<HEADLINE>
COUPLES, ELS WITHDRAW FROM NELSON TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Two former tournament champions, Ernie Els and
Fred Couples, withdrew Monday from the GTE Byron Nelson Classic,
both citing back injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Els, who ranks seventh on the PGA Tour money list, won the 1995
Nelson. Couples won the event in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Els told tournament officials that his injury surfaced Sunday
during the final round at the Compaq Classic of New Orleans, where
Els closed with a 73 and finished in a tie for 50th. Els, who has
earned $1,292,715 at PGA Tour events this season, said he was
unsure how long he would be sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   Couples' withdrawal came three days after he joined the field in
the waning moments before Friday's commitment deadline. Couples
missed the cut in New Orleans after shooting a 76 in Friday's
second round.
</P>
<P>
   The two vacancies in the 156-player field were filled by
alternates Bobby Cochran and Emlyn Aubrey.
</P>
<P>
   With the withdrawals, the Nelson field now features seven of the
top 10 players on the money list _ as well as 39 of the top 50 _
heading into the opening round Thursday at the Four Seasons Resort.
Neither Els nor Couples had committed to compete at the MasterCard
Colonial, May 18-21 in Fort Worth. COLONIAL MOVERS, SHAKERS
</P>
<P>
   By cashing sizable checks in New Orleans, four players took
themselves off the bubble for MasterCard Colonial invitations by
climbing into the top 80 on the season money list. Deadline for
reaching the top 80, and thereby landing Colonial invitations, was
the final round of the New Orleans event.
</P>
<P>
   The latest wave of Colonial qualifiers included Flower Mound
resident Paul Stankowski (No. 80), Irving resident Joel Edwards
(No. 62), Jimmy Green (No. 74) and Stephen Ames (No. 46).
</P>
<P>
   Stankowski made the biggest move, jumping from 91st to 80th with
a $57,800 payday in New Orleans. Edwards, Green and Ames _ ranked a
respective 71st, 72nd and 79th heading into the New Orleans event _
protected their Colonial spots by collecting Sunday paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials said Monday they have not added the latest
eligible players to their commitment list because they were still
trying to contact players and gauge their plans for tournament week
(May 18-21). In addition, Colonial officials met Monday to discuss
awarding their final two sponsor's exemptions. PAST CHAMPS IN
CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   Barring last-minute changes, the field for Tuesday's Celebrity
Skins Challenge will include three past Nelson champions: Nick
Price (1991), Loren Roberts (1999) and John Cook (1998). Others
expected to participate in the seven-hole competition, which begins
at 2:30 p.m., are Flower Mound resident Paul Stankowski, former
Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach and Cowboys running back Emmitt
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Two foursomes, with team members randomly selected, will compete
in the seven-hole competition, which will begin at hole No. 1 on
the TPC course. Admission is free. YOUTH CLINIC SET
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson will join four PGA Tour competitors, as well as
trick-shot specialist Dennis Walters, on the TPC practice range at
5 p.m. Tuesday for a youth clinic. Assisting Nelson will be Dallas
residents Justin Leonard, Harrison Frazar and Hank Kuehne, along
with Plano resident D.A. Weibring.
</P>
<P>
   Walters was a collegiate golfer in the 1970s at North Texas
State before a golf cart accident left him paralyzed from the waist
down. He will showcase his golf skills along with his dog, Benji
Hogan. Admission is free. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday's opening ceremonies for the tournament will be held
at noon at the Byron Nelson statue adjacent to the first hole of
the TPC course. Among the early arriving professionals who spent
time Monday on the driving range or putting green were David Duval,
Lee Janzen, Nick Faldo and Fulton Allem.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Golf Channel will air a 90-minute documentary on Nelson's
life, titled ``Byron Nelson: A Texas Gentleman'', at 8 p.m.
tonight. James Garner will serve as narrator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Finchem, PGA Tour commissioner, is expected to visit the
TPC course Tuesday for a series of scheduled meetings. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
