<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-AID-REPORT-300&AMP;A     05-08 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-AID-REPORT-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPT. REPORT FAULTS U.S. ATTEMPTS TO GIVE EMERGENCY AID 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Note Bush and Gore comments in optional material) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the Clinton administration has made
``humanitarian intervention'' a centerpiece of its foreign policy,
it has done a poor job of delivering emergency aid to the people
who need it, an internal State Department report says.
</P>
<P>
   The ``humanitarian factor has become central to senior policy
makers' deliberations over U.S. foreign policy priorities,'' the
report states. But the officials who are responsible for easing
human suffering in foreign crises have little influence over
high-level decision making, and in some cases are deliberately shut
out, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   The report, written by a top adviser to Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, chronicles the billions of dollars in
emergency assistance that have been sent to Afghanistan, Kosovo and
Sudan to help people whose lives have been disrupted by war and to
Honduras in the aftermath of a big hurricane in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Serbian forces began expelling ethnic Albanians
from Kosovo several days after the start of the NATO bombing
campaign, senior administration officials publicly insisted that
they were prepared for Serbian actions. Despite that, there was
little food and shelter on hand as hundreds of thousands of
refugees flooded into Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The report describes the administration's main funnel for
assistance to the expelled Kosovars, the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees, as suffering from ``weak leadership'' in
the region and adds that the administration was unable to change
this.
</P>
<P>
   In Sudan, where the United States has spent more than $1 billion
in the last 10 years trying to ease suffering in longest-running
civil war in Africa, the report says the assistance has become so
routine that it now appears to act as a substitute for peacemaking
efforts to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report, initiated by Morton H. Halperin, director of policy
planning at the State Department, and based on interviews with
senior administration officials, is an unclassified document. But
it was not made public until now.
</P>
<P>
   It was obtained under the Freedom of Information Act by the
National Security Archive, a group that specializes in collecting
government documents through requests and suits. The report was
completed in January and has been submitted to Albright's office.
</P>
<P>
   In outlining options for improving response, the report suggests
that the relief programs run by the Agency for International
Development could be folded into the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   This is one step short of what Senator Jesse Helms, the North
Carolina Republican who is chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee, has been recommending since he took charge of the panel
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, who favors abolishing the agency as an independent entity
and putting it into the State Department, said he believed
``bringing AID into the State Department will mean more effective
use of the aid,'' his spokesman, Marc Thiessen said.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, the two presumptive presidential
candidates have differing views of the ``humanitarian
intervention'' policy. George W. Bush Jr. has said he would be much
more selective in deciding where and when the United States would
intervene. Vice President Al Gore supported the interventionist
policy in a recent major speech. Gore was instrumental in
preventing the agency from being melded into the State Department
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In its account of how unprepared the administration was to meet
the needs of the Kosovo refugees, the report points to shortcomings
by American intelligence officials.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of anticipating an outpouring of refugees, the
administration was expecting the opposite, that nearly a million
people would be displaced in Kosovo during the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prevailing worst-case scenario was that one million
Kosovars would be displaced internally, prohibited from exiting,
and remain largely inaccessible, in the context of an ongoing air
war and a NATO determination not to launch a ground invasion,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sudan, the report says, many in the administration
believe that too little effort has been made by top officials to
resolve the conflict. This has been partly caused by deep divisions
within the administration on how to deal with Sudan, with some
favoring total isolation of the government and even more assistance
to rebels in the south.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition, officials responsible for the large assistance
expenditures have been excluded from crucial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, officials from the Agency for International
Development and the State Department who managed the assistance
program were not consulted when the administration decided to shut
the American embassy in Khartoum in the mid-1990s because of
security concerns. The embassy closing undermined Washington's
ability to talk to Khartoum about helping civilian victims of the
war, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, Halperin said that as foreign policy
becomes more entwined with relief assistance, government agencies
responsible for such assistance may not be organized in the right
way. ``The feeling was perhaps that the institutions created during
the Cold War might not be the best ones to deal with the new
realities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One conclusion of Halperin's report appears to be that if the
United States sees itself as an increasingly important source of
assistance in foreign emergencies, including those generated by
war, then the officials responsible for delivering the assistance
ought to have a greater voice.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, this voice is so muted that it is often kept out
of top deliberations, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   During the Kosovo war, for example, when the National Security
Council took control of the daily decision-making, officials
dealing with relief issues were asked ``to excuse themselves'' from
top-level meetings once they had finished talking about their
specific areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
