<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OCONNOR-SCENE-ART-NYT     05-08 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY OF CONTRASTS: VESTMENTS AND T-SHIRTS, PRAYERS AND POLICE
RADIOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OCONNOR-NYT) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The time had come again for St. Patrick's Cathedral
to lay one of its own to rest. Deep in the cathedral's recesses, a
crypt awaited the body of Cardinal John O'Connor. But first the
rituals of a church and a city needed to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor had requested to be remembered as a simple priest, but
he was still a prince of the church. President Clinton, Vatican
emissaries and other dignitaries would need to pay their last
respects. But so would those with no bodyguards or colorful
vestments, from the schoolboy with the protruding shirttail to the
frail woman with a kerchief settled on her hair like a black mist.
</P>
<P>
   In juggling these many needs Monday, the 120-year-old cathedral
became a majestic setting for the glorious and the sad, the
frustrating and the comical. It provided a fitting last tribute to
the cardinal who had worshiped from its altar, railed against
injustices from its pulpit and enjoyed a good laugh within its
walls.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the muggy air invaded the cathedral's coolness
shortly after dawn, it was clear that good intentions would clash
with realities _ that the echoes of prayers at the front would
compete with the crackle of security radios at the back.
</P>
<P>
   As the regular Masses at 7 and 7:30 a.m. proceeded, so too did
the steady stream of people: a man in jogging clothes, another
wearing a red ironworkers T-shirt, a woman with a forehead
glistening with holy water. They lighted the votive candles in the
rows of amber-colored cups, collected their memorial cards bearing
O'Connor's portrait and sat on wooden pews.
</P>
<P>
   When the service ended, they filed past his body, then stopped
to sign one of the guest books on their way out.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she had signed her name, Beatrice Carlino, of
Flushing, Queens, shrugged and said, ``Just to leave a little bit
of myself here.''
</P>
<P>
   Security concerns _ as well as fears that the procession of
hundreds of priests, bishops and cardinals might not begin on time
_ soon persuaded church officials to cancel the rest of the
morning's Masses and to close the cathedral's doors. Shortly after
8, Chief Allan Hoehl of the Manhattan South command tucked a
memorial card into his breast pocket and told a subordinate:
``That's it. No more Masses. No more people coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   When the word spread from the police officers at the barricades
to the people waiting outside the cathedral's door _ not far from a
church banner proclaiming, ``Open Wide the Doors to Christ'' _ some
dropped to their knees and began to pray. Others complained about
the commandeering of their church by the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable _ there are very important people who want
to come _ but I don't think it's fair,'' said Madeline Zampella,
who had traveled two hours from Brooklyn only to get lost and then
blocked from her destination. She had but one conclusion, ``Money
talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, inside the nearly empty cathedral, a church official
ordered several ushers to place all the collection baskets in the
confessionals and to make sure ``there's no one sleeping'' in the
pews. Someone at the altar spoke into the microphone _ ``Testing,
testing, one, two'' _ as representatives of an Irish-American
organization posed for photographs alongside the cardinal's body.
</P>
<P>
   Then a head usher led pallbearers down the aisle to rehearse the
climactic moment of the funeral. At the last pew, the usher clicked
his heels, turned to his right and instructed his followers to
pivot sharply around the corner. After a few paces, he clicked his
heels again and turned toward the cathedral's crypt. The men who
followed seemed daunted by the task before them.
</P>
<P>
   Dignitaries and guests began to arrive about noon, as crowds of
the uninvited pressed against the metal and wooden barricades set
up near the cathedral, which faces Fifth Avenue between East 50th
and 51st Streets. Some took the sweltering scene in stride; Pamela
Montana, of Providence, R.I., distinctive in a red dress and pink
feather boa, said she had stopped on her way to the airport to pay
her respects. And when the anticipated arrival of President Clinton
forced the police to block pedestrian traffic on Madison Avenue,
those among the delayed whipped out cell phones to call waiting
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see you,'' a woman in white linen said, gazing up at an
office building across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less gracious. At various entrances to the
cathedral, dozens of people explained with increasing anxiety that
there must have been some mistake _ they were indeed among the
invited. But the security officers _ from the Secret Service, the
police department or the archdiocese, identifiable by the color of
the pins on their lapels _ adhered to the lists in their hands. Two
nuns who glided past the barricades were soon escorted back to the
street, with deference.
</P>
<P>
   And when a security officer followed the letter of his
instructions too closely, an official from the archdiocese rushed
over to say that she recognized Bishop John R. McGann, the recently
retired leader of the Diocese of Rockville Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' the officer mumbled, as the prelate smiled and walked
through.
</P>
<P>
   Across Madison Avenue from the cathedral's rear entrance, the
New York Palace Hotel was awash with clerics from around the world.
There were monks in the men's room, priests in the dining room,
bishops in the lobby. They greeted one another with great
affection, made various plans to meet after the funeral, then
followed instructions to proceed across the street.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:20, the solemn procession began to move slowly past the
huge bronze doors and up the cathedral's center aisle: cardinals,
archbishops, bishops, priests, deacons, seminarians _ so many that
those bronze doors did not close until nearly 1:55. By now the
cardinal's mahogany coffin at the foot of the altar was closed and
draped in a cloth of white to symbolize resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   The rituals of city and church continued. Outside the cathedral,
police officers sweating in blue uniforms stood watch over the
people and visitors of New York, so accustomed to paying tribute by
standing behind barricades. Inside, a ceremony resounded with the
Christian belief in rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   At the precise moment that a television reporter in the back
began to speak into her cell phone, the choir in the loft above
sang a full-throated series of amens, as if in remonstration; the
woman covered her ear and scurried for quieter ground. Then came
the traditional exchanges of peace, which included Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani's shaking hands with his opponent in this fall's Senate
race, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mass ended, it was time to take the coffin to the crypt
below. Once again, the head usher led the gray-gloved pallbearers
down the center aisle, only this time their burden was real. At the
last pew, he clicked his heels, and the procession pivoted to its
right.
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later he clicked his heels again. The sound
echoed. The coffin soon disappeared from view, and members of a
city and a church gave their cardinal one last round of applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
