<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-POLICE-545&AMP;ADD-N     05-08 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT WARNS LOS ANGELES POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adding new drama to a growing police corruption
scandal here, the nation's top civil rights enforcement officer
warned Los Angeles police and city officials Monday that they would
have to make long-sought changes in police training and procedures
or face a lawsuit that could give the federal government final say
over major policies of the department.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lann Lee, the acting assistant attorney general for civil
rights, briefed local officials on the results of the Justice
Department's four-year investigation into allegations of abusive
behavior and racial discrimination by Los Angeles officers. Lee
said the inquiry concluded that the department had enough evidence
of civil rights violations to file a so-called pattern and practice
discrimination suit contending systemic failings.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour meeting, Lee issued a statement saying the
Justice Department was ``willing to defer filing suit to allow the
city the opportunity to work toward a voluntary settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city had accepted an offer to begin discussing a
resolution of the matter and had agreed to schedule a meeting next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Such a lawsuit would be a huge political and legal black eye for
the nation's second largest city, whose police department is
already reeling from charges of brutality, corruption and evidence
fabrication that have led to the dismissal or suspension of some 30
officers and the overturning of more than 80 convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The case became public after a former police officer confessed
to handcuffing and shooting an unarmed gang member, then framing
him by planting a gun near his paralyzed body.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Lee had arrived in Los Angeles armed with a letter outlining
the department's findings. One possible outcome, the officials
said, would be for Los Angeles to promise a series of changes, in
the form of a consent decree similar to those the Justice
Department has already reached with police departments in
Pittsburgh and Steubenville, Ohio, and with the New Jersey State
Police, where the aim was to bar racial profiling in traffic stops
by troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles would be the biggest city to come under such direct
federal scrutiny, though the U.S. Attorney's office in Brooklyn has
amassed what officials call evidence of systemwide problems in the
New York Police Department's handling of brutality complaints, and
is pressing New York for changes with the threat of a similar suit.
</P>
<P>
   The action here comes as the Los Angeles police plan security
for the Democratic National Convention in August, in what has been
planned as a celebration of Southern California's rebound from the
earthquake, fires and riots of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said that Lee had informed them of the meeting
only on Friday, and that it had been arranged with such apparent
haste that Mayor Richard J. Riordan, a Republican who has staked
the success of his administration on expanding the police force and
cutting crime, was not even in town; he was in Washington on city
and convention-related business. The city attorney, the chief of
police, the president of the civilian police commission and
representatives of Riordan attended the meeting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Justice Department has conducted its inquiry since 1996,
centering on questions of excessive use of force by officers, under
a 1994 federal law that authorized federal prosecutors to go to
court to seek changes in the operations of local departments. It
was inspired by a tumultuous period here that saw the beating of a
black motorist, Rodney King, the subsequent acquittal of police
officers charged in the case and the resulting riots that tore the
city apart in 1992. In the wake of the King case, a blue-ribbon
commission recommended a host of changes in department policy,
including a new system for tracking ``problem'' officers who
amassed large numbers of misconduct complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department allocated money to help finance the
system, but in recent months it has become clear that efforts to
establish it fell victim to bureaucratic errors, infuriating
Justice officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the police and local district attorney made public
their own sweeping investigations into contentions of
evidence-tampering, false testimony and brutality among officers in
the gritty Rampart division on the western edge of downtown, in the
city's worst corruption case in half a century. As that inquiry has
grown, it has led to bitter infighting between Police Chief Bernard
Parks and District Attorney Gil Garcetti, with Riordan at one point
reduced to accusing them of behaving like children. The Justice
Department's investigation had failed to uncover the Rampart case,
which local officials here said left the federal government feeling
pressure to step up its inquiry. In March, Lee told local officials
that the department was stepping up its civil rights investigation.
But according to one city official present at that meeting, Lee
said that the federal government had ``no interest in running the
department,'' though the Justice Department had a ``role to play''
in helping introduce reforms that had worked in other police
departments around the country.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1997, the special litigation section of the
department's civil rights division obtained two consent decrees
intended to remedy misconduct in the Pittsburgh and Steubenville
police departments. The decrees required those departments to adopt
new programs for training, supervising and disciplining officers
and instituting systems to receive, investigate and respond to
civilian complaints of misconduct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
