<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      05-08 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN ADVISERS SAY SENATOR WILL FORMALLY ENDORSE BUSH TUESDAY 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Sen. John McCain, the reform-minded Republican
whose support could help rally independents to the GOP ticket, will
endorse George Bush Tuesday after a meeting with the Texas
governor, McCain advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   The aides had cautioned last week that McCain, who was Bush's
most serious challenger in the battle for the Republican
presidential nomination, was likely to withhold a formal
endorsement until later in the campaign. But they said Monday night
that the Arizona senator, after a brief telephone conversation
Sunday with Bush, wanted to take the formal step despite continued
differences with the governor, especially on the need for campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   One aide said McCain had decided to ``get the issue (of an
endorsement) behind him.'' That could change, one aide said, if
Bush irked McCain during their meeting, but neither side expected
that to occur. When aides to the two men were unable to agree on a
written statement to be issued after the meeting, Bush initiated
the phone call to McCain to again express his personal admiration
for the senator.
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, the Texas-based political consultant who was senior
adviser to McCain's campaign, called Joe Albaugh, Bush's campaign
manager, in Austin Monday night to inform him of the senator's
decision, a Republican source said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said repeatedly in recent weeks that he supports
Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee. When asked during a press
conference Monday afternoon if he might go ahead and immediately
endorse Bush if their one-on-one meeting went well, McCain said,
``Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   When an aide told Bush about the prospect of an early
endorsement from McCain, the governor smiled and said ``that's
good,'' according to Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said the Bush camp had not been planning on an
immediate endorsement from McCain but it would be ``a pleasant
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Pittsburgh on Monday afternoon, Bush was cautious
about getting formal backing from McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be up to John,'' Bush said. ``Of course I'd
like his help. He has said out loud on more than one occasion he
was looking forward to campaigning for me for president. I take him
for his word. I'm confident we're going to have a good visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said Bush's call to McCain on Sunday lasted about two
minutes and ``was cordial. The governor was reaching out before the
meeting to send a signal that `I'm looking forward to meeting with
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two men are to meet alone for about an hour over coffee and
Danish Tuesday in a Pittsburgh hotel and then hold a news
conference about 10 a.m. EDT that some cable news channels may
carry live.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting had been imperiled as recently as 10 days ago when
Bush aides were quoted as saying there was a lot of downside and
not enough upside in the session for their campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's continued strength as a force in the presidential
campaign can be measured in part by his strong showing in recent
polls. Despite the senator's repeated denials of interest in an
independent run for the White House, some national surveys show he
could get as much as a quarter of the vote as an opponent of Bush
and Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in the primaries in February and March, the surveys
show McCain draws especially strongly among voters not
traditionally aligned with either party. Some analysts believe
McCain's appeal is a personal one based on his history as a
prisoner of war in the Vietnam conflict and his penchant for
tweaking Republican orthodoxy, including his assault on the current
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain clashed repeatedly during the primary season on
the senator's call for an end to ``soft money,'' the unlimited,
largely unregulated donations flowing to the two major political
parties primarily from business and union interests.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no formal agenda for the session, McCain said
he expected to discuss a wide range of issues, including political
reform, military reform, education and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   McCain repeated his disinterest in being Bush's vice
presidential running mate but refused to rule out accepting a
Cabinet job, such as defense secretary, in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush flew to Pittsburgh from New York, where he joined President
Clinton, Gore and a host of other political figures at the funeral
of Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
