<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BIG-GAME-RICH-COX     05-08 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-GAME-RICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Game jackpot fever is getting `really wild'
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh the hunger, the churning greed, the swelling fantasies
driving the human stampede to gas stations, convenience stores _
any place selling a Big Game ticket for America's largest-ever
lottery jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   People even traveled across state lines carrying cash from
friends and family, chasing dreams of instant wealth in a game
where the chances of winning are one in more than 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 18th Big Game drawing since March 7 without a grand
prize winner, pushing the projected jackpot to more than $325
million.
</P>
<P>
   And pushing buyers and sellers into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   More than $12 million in tickets have been sold since Saturday
in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The sales pace was enough to turn a typically sedate country
store into the hottest place in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets really wild in here,'' said David Davis. The owner of
Davis Country Store in Fayette County figures he has added $600 in
profits in the past week, with people buying more gas, soda and
other things along with tickets.
</P>
<P>
   When no one won Friday night's big prize of $220 million,
lottery officials from the seven states pumped up the purse again.
</P>
<P>
   The result: A crush of customers, a bonanza of ticket sales, the
need for separate lottery lines, additional clerks and more
security.
</P>
<P>
   Some outlets are working hard for the nickel they get out of
each $1 ticket they sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' said Donnie Crownover, manager of the Pleasant
Hill BP station in Duluth, Ga, whose ticket sales have tripled to
$6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some regular shoppers have gotten angry about the congestion and
stalked out of crowded stores. ``But we're getting so many extra
customers that it's not hurting us,'' said David Gaspard, a manager
at the Circle K at Sigman Road in Rockdale County.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 percent of lottery sales revenue is channeled into
state education through pre-kindergarten programs, computer
technology and HOPE Scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Lottery Corp. president Rebecca Paul said a strong sales
year can increase bonuses for lottery workers, including herself.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers actually net about 7 percent over the course of a year
on lottery sales, because of the different games, but some store
owners say it's too much work.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring an extra hand isn't worth it, said Danny Hyde, owner of
Hickory Road Market outside Canton, who has given up selling
tickets. ``You would have to sell a hundred tickets an hour to pay
your help.''
</P>
<P>
   Merchandise sales are down at some stores. ``People don't want
products, all they want are tickets,'' said Betty Boleman, manager
of the Circle K.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
