<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9502 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     05-08 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RANGERS, THERE'S JUST NOT ANY RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ He came careening around the corner, his
helmet buckled down tight, a hockey stick twirling lightly in his
fingers and a mad glint in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Passers by in the hallway scattered to make room for John
Wetteland, the Rangers' closer, as he performed his Mike Modano
impression on in-line skates within the narrow confines of the
Rangers' clubhouse and adjacent hallways.
</P>
<P>
   It is comforting to know that some things about the Rangers'
bullpen haven't changed: Wetteland is still slightly insane.
</P>
<P>
   Almost six weeks into this tumultuous season, however, that is
about the only similarity between this year's Rangers relief corps
and last season's.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps coming back to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, injuries have decimated the team. Yes, the defense stinks.
The Rangers' youngsters _ and some of the veterans, too _ have
exasperated manager Johnny Oates by continually missing signs and
making mental errors. Juan Gonzalez's steady RBI bat _ the RBI bat
he had when he was here anyway _ has been missed.
</P>
<P>
   But you can throw all those alibis into the nearest dumpster.
The season's biggest disappointment, and the single greatest reason
for the Rangers' staggering 13-17 start , is the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were pitching like we did last year,'' setup man Tim
Crabtree admitted, ``we'd have at least _ ``at least'' _ five more
victories.''
</P>
<P>
   Five more victories, instead of losses, would mean an 18-12
record, the Rangers and Mariners would have been battling for first
place in the A.L. West when their three-game series opened last
night and you and I wouldn't be having this conversation.
</P>
<P>
   That's the difference a bad bullpen can make. How bad has this
one been? There are better numbers on toe tags at the morgue.
</P>
<P>
   At The Ballpark in Arlington, the marketing department is
thinking of changing the name to ``cowpen.'' They'll paint the
fences in black and white spots.
</P>
<P>
   When Oates goes to the mound to change pitchers, cell phones all
over the stadium speed-dial 911, so the fire department can be
standing by.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it's a veritable ``rimshot'' paradise out there.
</P>
<P>
   When the bullpen gave up just one run in Sunday's 7-6 loss to
the A's, it actually lowered the group's season ERA to 6.10, third
worst by a relief corps in the American League. As the
Rangers-Mariners series began last night, the Rangers' bullpen had
allowed at least one run in each of the team's past five games and
had given up multiple runs in 13 of the team's 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not get bogged down in mere numbers. Numbers don't
begin to encompass the sordid sorriness of the Rangers' 'pen.
Nothing disheartens a team more than to work hard for a lead, only
to see the bullpen blow it in the seventh or later.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Rangers' relievers, with the exception of Francisco
Cordero, have pitched as well as expected this season, but the real
heart of the problem lies with Crabtree and Jeff Zimmerman. They
are Oates' two right-handed setup men, which means, more often than
not, that he's entrusting them to get a lead to Wetteland in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   When the league is hitting .359 against one and .302 against the
other, that just hasn't been happening as often as anyone would
like.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, who has consistently hit 95 on the scoreboard radar
gun _ about the only thing he's done consistently _ is as baffled
as anyone after a stellar season a year ago when he was 5-1 with a
3.46 ERA. In his first 14 games this year, the ERA is 9.20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not walking people (three in 14 2/3 innings), my
strikeout-walk ratio is about 5-to-1 and the velocity on my
fastball is good,'' Crabtree said. ``It gets to the point where you
ask yourself, `What am I doing wrong?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm eating the wrong food or living the wrong lifestyle
of something. I know I'm a better pitcher now than I've ever been
in my life. I have better stuff now than I ever have. I just can't
get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a problem when you're a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree and Zimmerman have had the same trouble. They might
make just one bad pitch in an at-bat, but that's the one that's
getting ripped. They're getting away with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree grooves too many fastballs. Hitters are sitting on
Zimmerman's slider. When he makes a good one, they still can't hit
it. But if he makes a mistake with it, hangs it a little, they're
all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of low points this year,'' said
Zimmerman, who lost a game in Baltimore when he balked in the
winning run, ``like there were a lot of high points last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a prediction: It will turn around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see good health,'' pitching coach Dick Bosman said of his
two struggling right-handers. ``I see a good work ethic and I see
quality stuff. I have to think it's going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   It must, or the Rangers will never make the run for the division
title that Oates and general manager Doug Melvin expected.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, we'll let Wetteland's pregame warmup gear set the
theme for the bullpen. Just call it the ``penalty box.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0467 </DOCNO>
