u f BC-STONE-WEBSTER-BOS &LR;      05-08 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONE-WEBSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STONE &AMP; WEBSTER HAS BUYER, WILL SEEK BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Stone &AMP; Webster Inc. plans to sell most of its assets
and seek bankruptcy protection, ending a 111-year run for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1889 by a pair of young graduates from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, the firm grew on orders for
things like installing the first electric lights in the Boston's
Colonial Theatre; later its engineers build nuclear-power plants
and ski jumps for the Calgary Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, it stumbled as it tried to adjust to risky
lump-sum contracts.
</P>
<P>
   To escape a liquidity crisis, it said Monday it has signed a
letter of intent with Jacobs Engineering Group Inc. in which Jacobs
would acquire most of Stone &AMP; Webster's assets in exchange for $150
million in cash, plus a $50 million credit facility and assumption
of liabilities. The deal would make Pasadena, Calif.-based Jacobs a
powerful player in the consolidating heavy-construction industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster also said it will file a voluntary petition for
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code following a
formal sale agreement later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would provide an exit for Stone &AMP; Webster, whose shares
have fallen 74 percent this month after delays at a power-plant
project in Tiverton, R.I. forced it to take a $27.5 million charge
and begin sales negotiations. Fearing bankruptcy, customers like
the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant had already begun to cancel
the firm's contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreements are humbling for Stone &AMP; Webster, one of New
England's oldest commercial dynasties. Because of the bankruptcy
filing, Stone &AMP; Webster said it is ``not possible to determine at
the present time what value, if any, will ultimately be received by
Stone &AMP; Webster's stockholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster's problems at Tiverton surprised many, since the
gas-fired power plant is among a score of such projects going up
around New England that were supposed to shore up troubled local
construction companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the plant's developers signed up Stone &AMP; Webster under what
is known as a fixed-price or lump-sum contract: The builder agrees
to construct a project for a specific price; if it's more
expensive, the builder loses money.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, such contracts pay higher returns but are regarded as
riskier by investors. Such pacts reflect the strong competition in
the construction industry, from rivals like Morrison Knudsen Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Stone &AMP; Webster avoided such terms. According to
an authorized company history, founders Charles Stone and Edwin
Webster regarded lump-sum contracts as being ``antithetical to a
professional philosophy.'' Better, they felt, to trust engineers to
build a project properly and be paid a percentage of the total
cost.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked throughout the 1900s, when Stone &AMP; Webster
put up everything from Mississippi River dams to breweries. It also
constructed buildings for the Manhatten Project during World War
II, which positioned Stone &AMP; Webster to build nuclear power plants
after the war, including the Yankee Rowe, Maine Yankee, and
Connecticut Yankee reactors.
</P>
<P>
   But the last chief executive with ties to the company's old
guard, Bruce C. Coles, quit in 1995, amid criticism from
shareholders about the company's lagging profits and its stock
price.
</P>
<P>
   A new CEO, Kerner Smith, vowed to adjust to changes in the
industry. Developers say he failed to instill the new philosophy in
enough Stone &AMP; Webster construction managers to control spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worlds of hard-money contracting and cost-plus are
different worlds,'' one customer said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 51 percent of the company's revenue was earned through
lump-sum contracts; it has reduced that percentage since last year,
analysts say, though apparently too late.
</P>
<P>
   The shift to lump-sum contracts alone didn't doom Stone &AMP;
Webster. It also suffered with the Asian currency crisis of 1997,
which halted work on a $2.3 billion ethylene complex in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic construction was supposed to offset overseas woes,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every (engineering and construction) company that's
tried to do lump-sum work has gotten burned on it,'' said Credit
Suisse First Boston analyst Charles Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Smith hasn't been available for interviews since the company
announced its troubles last week. In a press release, Smith said
that the proposed deal, which has approvals from its directors,
``is in the best interest of all the company's constituencies,
including its employees, shareholders, clients, suppliers and
lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   John Prosser Jr., Jacobs' chief financial officer, said the
company expects to hire most of Stone &AMP; Webster's operating
employees but that more specific plans haven't be determined.
Meanwhile, Stone &AMP; Webster said it expects to continue operating
and paying its roughly 7,000 worldwide employees ``in the normal
manner.'' It will complete ongoing projects, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster exit could be a blow to New England, where the
company has about 1,700 employees. Jacobs' Prosser said the company
hasn't determined exactly what shifts it might make in the work
force. Stone &AMP; Webster has about 4,000 workers worldwide and nearly
7,000 when temporary contract workers are included. Employment
peaked at about 15,000 workers worldwide in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster's troubles mirrored those of Raytheon Co.'s
engineering and construction unit, which also built many nuclear
plants, in the 1960s and 1970s. Last month, Raytheon agreed to sell
the division to Morrison Knudsen Corp. of Boise, which also
considered buying Stone &AMP; Webster.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster had hoped to avoid a sale and some thought it
could have stumbled along for several more fiscal quarters. To save
cash, it suspended its dividend last year and has been selling
office buildings. These steps helped Stone &AMP; Webster pay down total
debt to $45 million at the end of 1999, from $131 million at the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But as problems on lump-sum projects continued to crop up, Stone
&AMP; Webster found little forbearance from banks and business
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for instance, CanFibre Group Ltd. of Toronto has
ended Stone &AMP; Webster's contract to build a $71.5 million
fiberboard plant in Lackawanna, N.Y. Stone &AMP; Webster was behind in
payments to several of its subcontractors, some of whom quit work
in protest, said CanFibre president Chris Carl.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster was signed up to work on a lump-sum basis, Carl
said, on a firm deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you finance a private facility, you finance it with the
expection that you'll be able to start earning revenue at a
specific point in time,'' Carl said.
</P>
</TEXT>
