<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-RAILROAD-KILLER-HNS &LR;      05-08 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILROAD-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATURINO RESENDIZ PLEADS INSANITY, ADMITS KILLING 9 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Accused serial killer Angel Maturino Resendiz placed
his life in the hands of jurors during the opening day of his
capital murder trial Monday by pleading insanity and admitting to
murdering nine people in three states.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz is charged in Houston with the December 1998
murder of Dr. Claudia Benton, one of the nine people he admitted
killing _ six in Texas, two in Illinois and one in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defense attorney's acknowledgment of guilt and his
graphic descriptions of each murder, the Harris County jury still
must decide whether Maturino Resendiz was insane when he broke into
Dr. Claudia Benton's West University Place home on Dec. 17, 1998,
stabbed and beat her, then raped her and robbed the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to hide anything from you,'' defense attorney
Allen Tanner told the jurors. ``We're dealing with a very, very
serious situation. ... It is a horrible case what happened to Dr.
Benton. Our hearts go out to her family. ... Evidence will show the
defendant did do that crime. He did it. No doubt he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors could still give Maturino Resendiz, 40, the death penalty
or life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County District Attorney John B. Holmes Jr. began his
case Monday by calling Benton's husband, police investigators and
technicians and colleagues of the victim from Baylor College of
Medicine, where she was a fellow in the genetics department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to ask you to convict this man of one of the most
horrible events you will ever have the misfortune of hearing,''
Holmes told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Resendiz, now wearing long, unruly sideburns and shoulder-length
hair slicked straight back, sat quietly during the eight-hour court
proceedings Monday. His face never showed emotions and he only
rarely spoke to his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said that when his client surrendered at the Texas-Mexico
border last summer, he showed no remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when we met him and talked to him, when doctors have
talked to him, the defendant has no remorse for any of his
crimes,'' Tanner said. ``The defendant in his mind thinks these
people were evil and deserved to die. ... We are pleading insanity.
The defense says he was insane when he committed each and every
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanner then read two letters Maturino Resendiz wrote while in
the Harris County Jail in which he said he was an ``angel of God.''
</P>
<P>
   In one he told of a virus that could spread faster than ebola by
spreading through the air and how the virus carriers could transmit
information ``like dolphins.'' He also said he has warned of the
impending destruction of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I have come here, I have told about the floods,
earthquakes, pestilences, famines that will come,'' he wrote.
``People will fear to go out of their houses. They will fear to
come to their houses. They will fear the night, fear the day. Many
will lose faith and kill themselves or others to get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   In another he said he surrendered because he was told he would
be treated humanely, but that authorities broke all their promises
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told at the border I was to get unrestricted visits.
That was a false promise. That I could get kosher. I never received
kosher,'' he wrote. ``The humane treatment I will get will be the
death sentence. I will go. I will not beg for my life. I was to be
sent to a mental hospital, but that will not happen. The USA will
never, never keep a promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said the letters prove how Maturino Resendiz felt his
victims had to be killed because ``something is seriously wrong up
here,'' he said touching his head.
</P>
<P>
   After Benton's colleagues testified how they had reported her
missing, her husband, George, took the stand. He was in Arizona at
the time of the murder visiting family with the couple's then
11-year-old twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   When his wife's co-workers called him, he phoned a friend to
check on the house and learned police were there. Later, he got a
call from police in Arizona, who told him his wife had been
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes produced items found in Benton's home that bore
fingerprints matching those of Maturino Resendiz.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes also said DNA and blood found at the scene would later be
shown to belong to the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   A police video of the crime scene showed how Benton's body was
found in the bedroom, sprawled face down, her head wrapped in a
plastic bag and her body covered with blankets, pillows and sheets.
</P>
<P>
   A knife from the kitchen lay near an arm, which was stretched
out from under the covers, and a bronze statuette that had been
used to bludgeon her was found near the bed. Blood spatters were
found throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said Benton was beaten and stabbed repeatedly as she
fought for her life, but the fatal blows were two stab wounds to
the back, piercing the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trial began Monday, state District Judge Bill Harmon
denied Maturino Resendiz's request for a change of venue because of
excess publicity in Houston. He polled the 13 jurors, each of whom
denied having seen newscasts or read reports that could have
affected their decision in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz was offered an interpreter, but he declined to
use one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
