<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   CUOMO SEEKS BUSH STAND ON GUN BILL: Housing Secretary Andrew
Cuomo added his voice Monday to the chorus of Democrats who have
called on Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to clarify his position on
federal legislation that would prohibit lawsuits by local
governments against gun manufacturers. Bush signed such legislation
in Texas, and suggested last week that he would do the same in
Washington. In a telephone news conference Monday, Cuomo, who has
tried to negotiate settlements between gun makers and cities that
have sued them, called Bush's remarks vague. He asserted that the
gun makers, who have broken off talks in recent months, would
return to the table if they knew Bush opposed such legislation.
Bush aides accused Cuomo of politicizing the issue. ``Instead of
spending their time distorting and misrepresenting Governor Bush's
priorities, the Clinton-Gore administration ought to spend more
time enforcing our existing gun laws,'' said Scott McClellan, a
spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   By James Dao
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION LOOMS AS PLATFORM ISSUE: Various interests groups,
especially those that support abortion rights, plan to have their
voices heard in Philadelphia this summer when the Republican
national convention assembles a platform for this year's nominee.
Over the weekend, Gov. Tommy G. Thompson of Wisconsin, the recently
selected chairman of the platform committee, offered them some
thoughts. After all the hearings are held and all the testimony is
heard, he said, the presidential candidate will have the last word,
not the committee. ``I'm certainly going to be listening to all
sectors of the party,'' Thompson told The Philadelphia Inquirer.
``But my ultimate client is George Bush, and what he feels best is
what we will do.'' On the matter of abortion, Thompson said he
would abide by Bush's promises to leave the current plank, which
strongly opposes abortion.
</P>
<P>
   By Irvin Molotsky
</P>
<P>
   THE LIBERTARIANS
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION COMMISSION SUED: The Libertarian Party sued the Federal
Elections Commission on Monday, contending that rules for
participation in presidential debates are so restrictive that they
unfairly exclude minor-party candidates and independents. The
lawsuit, the culmination of a long series of complaints about
debate regulations, argues that it is nearly impossible for less
well-known and less well-financed candidates to participate because
candidates who do not draw at least 15 percent in voter polls are
automatically excluded. In the suit, filed in federal court in
Manhattan, the Libertarians, joined by several other plaintiffs,
asserted that ``there is a common interest of the Democratic and
Republican Parties, implemented in part through organizations such
as the Commission on Presidential Debates, to lessen the stature
and legitimacy of independent and minor-party candidates.'' The
commission, a nonprofit group, has run the debates since 1987. The
suit also asserts that the debates violate federal law because
money contributed to finance them is meant to enhance voter
participation, not to support any particular party or candidate. A
commission spokesman, John Scardino, said the debate qualification
standards were fair and entirely legal.
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   RIFT GROWS AMONG ARIZONA REPUBLICANS: It is no secret among
Arizona Republicans that Gov. Jane Dee Hull's endorsement of a
fellow governor, George W. Bush, over a fellow Arizonan, Sen. John
McCain, for president left bad feelings on both sides. It was bad
enough that last month Hull agreed to give up the governor's
prerogative of leading the state's delegation to the Republican
National Convention _ after all, McCain easily won the primary, and
thus the right to control the state's 30-member delegation. Now
comes word that McCain wants his wife, Cindy, to lead the
delegation instead. That has rankled Hull supporters. The issue is
to be decided at the state party convention on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   By Todd S. Purdum
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Pittsburgh, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Washington
</P>
