<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(1300)2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLEMN RITUAL AND PAGEANTRY MARK CARDINAL O'CONNOR'S FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs for complete writethru.) (ART ADV: Photos NYT7,11,12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cardinal John Joseph O'Connor, the eighth Roman
Catholic archbishop of New York, whose wit and uncompromising
eloquence made him the Vatican's most visible leader in the United
States, was entombed beneath the altar of St. Patrick's Cathedral
Monday in an ethereal ceremony of white-robed clerics and haunting
song.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the stature that O'Connor had achieved during his 16
years running the Archdiocese of New York, political and religious
leaders from around the country and the world joined New Yorkers to
honor a man whose insistence on church teachings had defied the
secular labels of liberal and conservative politics.
</P>
<P>
   Led by acolytes bearing incense and holding high the
archbishopric cross, with its distinctive double crossbeams, a
procession of more than 2,000 deacons, priests, bishops, nuns and
cardinals marched down the central aisle of the cathedral at 1:30
p.m., passing alongside the cardinal's mahogany coffin, which was
draped in a white linen pall. As they passed, they rested their
hands on the coffin briefly, before moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made this pulpit unique in the history of the Catholic
Church in the United States,'' said Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston
in a homily that was interrupted by a long standing ovation after
he invoked O'Connor's ``constant reminder that the church must
always be unambiguously pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the audience, now on its feet, Law added, ``I see he
hasn't left the pulpit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God gifted him with a keen and subtle intellect, an uncommon
rhetorical skill, a knack for the dramatic gesture, a sharp wit and
an outrageous sense of humor, all of which he used in the service
of preaching,'' said Law, who was near O'Connor when he died last
Wednesday night at the age of 80, after a protracted battle with
cancer that began late last summer with surgery to remove a brain
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dignitaries attending the invitation-only funeral were
President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who sat beside Vice
President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper Gore. Behind the president
sat Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, the first lady's rival for the
United States Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
who was also present. Mrs. Clinton shook hands with Giuliani during
the ``kiss of peace'' that is part of the Mass.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the coffin, alongside O'Connor's two
sisters and brother, sat former President George Bush, who was a
friend of the cardinal's. Elsewhere in the audience sat Bush's son,
George W. Bush, with his wife, Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 cardinals, the highest-ranking clerics in the Roman
Catholic Church after the pope, also turned out to usher O'Connor
to his final resting place, as did an equal number of archbishops
and 300 bishops. One of them, seated prominently in the sanctuary,
was the man expected to succeed O'Connor, Bishop Edward M. Egan of
Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending were all of the others whose names have figured
prominently in speculation about a successor: Archbishops Theodore
E. McCarrick of Newark, Justin F. Rigali of St. Louis and Edwin F.
O'Brien of the military archdiocese, along with Bishops Henry
Mansell of Buffalo, Sean O'Malley of Fall River, Mass., and Donald
Wuerl of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Though few nuns attended, other than mothers superior, two
orders held prominent places. One was Mother Teresa's Missionaries
of Charity. The other was the Sisters of Life, a New York-based
order founded by O'Connor, whose 30 members devote themselves to
protecting the sanctity of life, whether by running shelters for
unwed mothers or by ministering to the sick and elderly.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,500 mourners filled the cathedral, whose walls
echoed with the hymns and speeches celebrating the eternal life on
whose threshold the faithful believe O'Connor now stands. Much of
the service, which ran nearly three hours from the procession that
opened it to the one that ended it, centered on choices the
cardinal had made as he prepared for his death _ from the selection
of Law to read the homily, to the abundance and choice of music.
</P>
<P>
   The diocesan priests and bishops wore white, in keeping with
their belief that death is not the end of life, but a time of
rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the cathedral, thousands stood in wilting temperatures
that reached the 90s, in rows 8 to 10 people deep, to hear the
service, which was broadcast over loudspeakers. Twenty-five Red
Cross workers handed out lemonade and water. Police officers
sweltered in their formal uniforms: long-sleeved shirts, ties and
woolen jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, we do not complain that you have taken him from us,''
said Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Vatican's secretary of state, who
led the Mass of Christian Burial. ``Rather we will thank you for
giving him to us.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's stands on political issues sprang from his faith in
the Gospel, making it difficult to brand him conservative or
liberal. From the start of his tenure, he preached strict adherence
to traditional church doctrines about sexuality, abjuring
homosexuality, abortion and contraception. And he assailed Catholic
politicians, like Gov. Mario M. Cuomo and Geraldine A. Ferraro, who
he felt strayed from those views.
</P>
<P>
   But in later years, the cardinal's image as a conservative
blurred somewhat as he he spoke out for the rights of workers and
the dispossessed, and opposed capital punishment and euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was the cardinal's untiring efforts to outlaw
abortion that perhaps drew the greatest attention to him, and that
Monday sparked an unscripted show of devotion: a sustained,
standing ovation, which began when one of the Sisters of Life rose
to her feet.
</P>
<P>
   And it was his unabashed use of the news media to assert church
doctrine, whether in the secular or religious arena, that marked
the cardinal. In opening remarks Monday, Bishop Anthony Brucato,
one of O'Connor's two vicar generals, his top lieutenants, made a
special point of welcoming the millions of Catholics watching the
cardinal's funeral on television.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief talk about O'Connor early in the service, Cardinal
William Baum noted that O'Connor's patron saint was St. John
Fisher, who was beheaded for treason in 1535 by King Henry VIII of
England after refusing to renounce the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardinal O'Connor wasn't decapitated,'' Baum said. ``He didn't
die for his faith, but he did proclaim it, and he suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Baum recalled that O'Connor had asked Catholics to pray for his
soul after his death.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:35, after many in the cathedral, including Giuliani, had
lined the aisles to receive holy communion, Sodano sprinkled
O'Connor's coffin with holy water, as incense rose toward the
cathedral's vaulted ceilings. There hung the traditional red hats
of the New York archbishops before Cardinal Francis Spellman, who
was installed in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   In solemn procession, Sodano led the coffin up the center aisle
and down the side, as hymns filled the church. Behind him walked
other cardinals and a few members of O'Connor's family, including
his two sisters, Mary Ward and Dorothy Hamilton, and his brother
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller group, consisting only of Sodano, a few other church
officials and O'Connor's family, actually entered the crypt to see
the burial.
</P>
<P>
   On the stone that sealed his crypt is a simple inscription
bearing his name and age, and the years he served as archbishop of
New York. Also carved in the stone is his coat of arms, emblazoned
with the words he chose to give meaning to his mission: ``There can
be no love without justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HANFORD-NUKE-200&AMP;ADD-     05-08 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANFORD-NUKE-200&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPT. CANCELS NUCLEAR CLEANUP CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Washington)  By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department said on Monday that it had
failed in its attempt to save money on nuclear waste cleanup by
privatizing the task of solidifying highly radioactive liquid
wastes at the Hanford nuclear reservation in Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   The department said that it was canceling its contract with BNFL
Inc., which was supposed to finance and build a waste-processing
factory and run it for almost 20 years, receiving most of its pay
only when it produced a product.
</P>
<P>
   By dismissing the contractor, the department risks missing
court-sanctioned deadlines that it had agreed on with Washington
State and the federal Environmental Protection Agency for the
cleanup of the Hanford plant.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said in a statement that
``BNFL's proposal was outrageously expensive and inadequate in many
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said the company, whose budget estimates for the
job had more than doubled in less than two years, will be kept on
to do some design work; it will be paid $200 million to $300
million for the design work and for its glass-melting technology.
But the job of finishing the design, building the plant and running
it will be opened up for bidding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The plant is supposed to produce liquid wastes encased in a
radiation-absorbing glass and wrapped in stainless steel for
long-term storage. The Energy Department chose BNFL, an American
subsidiary of British Nuclear Fuels PLC, because the British parent
had done similar work in England.
</P>
<P>
   When the initial contract was signed in August 1998, BNFL said
it could do the job for $6.9 billion. More recently, it said the
cost would be $15.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington attorney general, Christine O. Gregoire, who
negotiated cleanup deadlines, said in an interview that delays had
been predictable because of ``bad business decisions'' by the
Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   The original concept, she pointed out, was for two private
companies to compete, but the department had narrowed the field to
just BNFL, which allowed that company to ``commit highway
robbery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, BNFL said that ``while disappointed that the
Department of Energy has decided to recompete the entirety of the
contract, we are pleased that they have determined that the design
and technical solution is sound and will be the basis for
proceeding with the cleanup.''
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Glauthier, the deputy secretary of energy, acknowledged in
a telephone interview with reporters that the department had a
history of delays and cost overruns and was still looking for a way
to give contractors an incentive to do their work on time and on
budget. He said the department might try privatizing another task,
but one with fewer uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty unhappy with the performance this contractor has
had,'' he said. ``We're taking an unusual step, terminating this
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the department's experience in the glass-making
technology, called vitrification, has been poor. A plant built
under a traditional contract at the Savannah River nuclear
reservation, near Aiken, S.C., opened late, and engineers still
have not determined how to stop the wastes from producing benzene,
a gas that can burn or explode at the proper concentration. The
waste at Hanford, in south central Washington State, is stored in
underground tanks, some of which are leaking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
