A9528 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EXCITE-BRAINDRAIN-SFC     05-08 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-BRAINDRAIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SENIOR EXECUTIVES FLEEING FROM EXCITEATHOME  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ExciteAtHome, whose stock has fallen 59 percent
this year, is also suffering a brain drain.
</P>
<P>
   At least three senior executives have left the Redwood City,
Calif., Internet company in recent weeks, and at least one more is
rumored to have a foot out the door.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the company said Tom Jermoluk, who stepped down as
chief executive in January, will also hand the chairman's title to
Chief Executive Officer George Bell. Jermoluk, who will remain on
the board of directors, is reportedly negotiating to become a
partner of the Palo Alto, Calif., venture capital firm Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, which has ties to ExciteAtHome. He
already has investments in some other Kleiner companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Adam Grosser, president of subscriber networks,
quit two weeks ago. Senior vice president and general counsel David
Pine is leaving in June to join Handspring, which makes handheld
computers that compete with Palm.
</P>
<P>
   And others could be leaving soon, observers say. ExciteAtHome,
which runs the fifth-most-popular network of Internet sites and is
the largest provider of cable modem service, just completed a
corporate reorganization last week. Shares have slid 78 percent
over the past 12 months, worse than many other Internet
powerhouses. By comparison, Lycos is up 7 percent, Yahoo is up 64
percent and America Online is down 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a bunch of resumes on the street,'' said Sean
Doherty, an AtHome co-founder who now runs Urban Media
Communications, a Palo Alto startup.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty pointed out that all three executives who are leaving
originally worked for AtHome, which provides superfast Internet
service over cable television lines. The company became
ExciteAtHome when it bought Excite, an Internet portal that
competes with Yahoo and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ExciteAtHome just launched television commercials in
four cities yesterday, including San Francisco, that solely promote
the ``Excite'' brand _ rather than ExciteAtHome. The campaign is
expected to cost $5 million to $10 million, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company ``is kind of turning into Excite,'` Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   But ExciteAtHome spokeswoman Melissa Walia says the company
simply prefers to use the Excite name for national branding
campaigns to promote all its services.
</P>
<P>
   She said the company only promotes the AtHome name to promote
the cable modem service where it is available. However,
ExciteAtHome is still focused heavily on attracting more cable
modem customers, she added. It hopes to reach 3 million subscribers
by year end, up from 1.5 million at the end of March, and 10
million by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, financial analyst Abhishek Gami said he thinks
several Excite executives could leave the company as well as the
company refocuses its business.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome already has announced plans to throttle down
efforts to keep up with Yahoo and Lycos. The company recently
overhauled the Internet gateway for its cable modem customers but
isn't sure when it will do the same for its public Internet site.
Gami estimates it could be a year away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to hear about more management defections,'' said
Gami, who works for William Blair. ``Ultimately, George (Bell) is
going to assemble his own team.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
