<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS DISCOMFORTED BY HOMILETIC PRAISE OF `PRO LIFE' STAND
</HEADLINE>
  (With OCONNOR) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the politicians crowded into the pews at the
front of St. Patrick's Cathedral on Monday, from Democrats like
President Clinton to Republicans like Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, it
was a difficult moment. At the pulpit, Cardinal Bernard Law gave a
homily for Cardinal John O'Connor that included a sharp reminder of
one issue with which the cardinal famously sparred with national
and New York government leaders. ``What a great legacy he has left
us in his constant reminder that the church must always be
unambiguously pro life,'' Law said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment's pause. Then, rising from the pews, came an
unbroken roar of applause that lasted for one minute and 50
seconds. Most of the political leaders at the front, almost all
supporters of legalized abortion, rustled in obvious discomfort as
television cameras focused in on the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The mourners applauded as Law tried to quiet them with a gesture
of his hands. Then they rose to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   And with the audience rose the politicians, if not quite as
quickly: Gov. George Pataki, Giuliani, Clinton, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, Sens. Charles Schumer and Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, both New York Democrats, among them. Giuliani,
after tugging at his jacket, even joined in the applause, though
unenergetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro life'' is shorthand for opposition to abortion, and most
of the politicians in the front pews favor abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But as Law described it, O'Connor meant the ``defense of life''
to include much more: opposing capital punishment, euthanasia and
physician-assisted suicide, and defending the rights of workers and
``a just peace in the Middle East and in Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and his father, the former president,
applauded. They oppose abortion, but they vigorously support the
death penalty and are not friendly to organized labor, as O'Connor
was. Few major American politicians are fully in tune with the
Roman Catholic teachings that brought those in the cathedral to
their feet.
</P>
<P>
   As the applause went on, the president could be seen whispering
to Mrs. Clinton, who has moved to New York and is running for
senator against Giuliani. They stood in what aides later described
as a gesture of respect to the church and the cardinal, though they
did not applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, said he applauded out of
respect. ``This was done out of a show of respect for the
cardinal,'' Mindel said. ``As is known, the mayor is pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who also favors abortion rights, applauded too, ``out of
respect for the cardinal and the principals of the Catholic
Church,'' said his senior adviser, Zenia Mucha.
</P>
<P>
   Law seemed startled by the display that his remark about
O'Connor's teachings evoked. ``I see he hasn't left the pulpit,''
Law said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
