<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-SENATE-DEBATE-ART-     05-08 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-DEBATE-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY SENATE CONTENDERS TRY SOFTER TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ After languishing for months in the shadow of
their better-known, better-financed Democratic rivals, New Jersey's
four Republican candidates for the United States Senate had their
first debate on Monday, with all four brandishing their
conservative credentials while avoiding the harsh attacks they had
leveled at each other in recent campaign mailings.
</P>
<P>
   With only regional political bases and limited name recognition,
the four used the forum to make broad appeals to the 300,000 voters
expected to decide the June 6 primary, describing their views in
favor of tax cuts, free trade and severely limiting the use of
American military troops abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The format did not allow for give-and-take during what was
largely a genial debate, with the candidates mentioning each
other's names only when they agreed on various issues. Their only
critical words were aimed at Democrats, specifically President
Clinton and New Jersey's two Democratic Senate contenders, Jim
Florio and Jon S. Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert D. Franks, a four-term congressman from Union
County, called himself a common-sense conservative and said that he
and fellow Republicans in Congress deserved credit for the robust
economy because they had helped ``to drag Bill Clinton kicking and
screaming down the path to fiscal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   James W. Treffinger, the Essex County executive, described
himself as an ``unabashed conservative'' and proposed replacing the
income tax code with a flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   William L. Gormley, a state senator from Ocean County, said he
was a fiscal conservative because he had voted for 37 tax cuts
since Gov. Christine Todd Whitman took office in 1994. In an
unusual move for a contestant in a Republican primary, however,
Gormley also said he had become a target for the National Rifle
Association because he was the only Republican state legislator to
vote for New Jersey's assault weapons ban in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The most conservative candidate in the race is Murray Sabrin, a
college finance professor who ran for governor as a Libertarian in
1993. Sabrin called for the abolition of affirmative action, the
Departments of Education, Energy, and Housing and Urban
Development, the capital gains tax and the estate tax. When asked
whether his platform might be too extreme for New Jersey's
historically moderate Republican voters, he beamed. ``That's what
they said about Ronald Wilson Reagan in 1980,'' Sabrin said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, sponsored jointly by The New York Times and The New
Jersey Network, was taped at 1 p.m. and broadcast at 9 p.m. The
Democratic candidates are scheduled to hold their first debate on
Thursday, and both debates will be broadcast back-to-back on Sunday
at 2 p.m. The Democrats have agreed to four debates before the
primary. The Republicans are scheduled to hold two more.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The tranquil tone of Monday's debate was a departure from the
increasingly heated campaign. In recent weeks, Gormley's campaign
has called Franks a ``Clinton Republican,'' saying that the
congressman voted to impeach the president but days later urged the
Senate not to remove him from office. Franks has branded Gormley a
``Florio Republican,'' and accused him of cooperating too closely
with Florio during his four years as governor.
</P>
<P>
   As if bracing for such a criticism, Gormley began the debate
with a one-minute opening statement in which he described his votes
against Florio's tax increase. But an attack from Franks never
came. Instead, Franks talked of his own efforts, when he was a
state legislator and Republican state chairman, to block Florio's
1990 income tax increase and deny his re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger predicted that Corzine's programs would bankrupt the
country. Referring to Florio's $2.8-billion tax increase, he said,
``There are at least 2.8 billion reasons not to vote for Jim
Florio.''
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the debate emphasized the similarities between
Treffinger, Gormley and Franks. All three said they favored limited
gun control, campaign finance reform, expanding trade relations
with China and federal tax credits to help working families afford
health care and higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Franks and Gormley described issues in which they broke ranks
with their party leadership. Franks said he defied Republican
leaders in the House of Representatives when he voted to support
campaign finance and the patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley described his vote for Florio's assault weapon ban as an
act of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the opportunity as a United States marine to fire an
M-16, and I know what damage they can do,'' Gormley said. ``We need
to send a message to the NRA, and the special interest groups who
don't care about our children and don't care about the future of
our state, to tell them we're not going to stand for it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
