<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-JOCKS-INTERNET-SFCHRO     05-08 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOCKS-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ATHLETES SCORING ON THE INTERNET  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ These days, it's easy for sports fans to get
``up close and personal'' with their favorite athletes on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Steve Young of the San Francisco 49ers, for example,
shared exclusive details and photos on his Web site from his
invitation-only wedding in March in Hawaii. Young said his wedding
reception was ``like a fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, tennis teen queen Anna Kournikova used her site to
deny rumors that she was planning to marry Pavel Bure, Sergi
Federov or any other hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   And Oakland Athletics slugger Jason Giambi revealed in a
poignant note on his site that his 1999 season, a stellar one for
him on the field, was painful off the field because of his divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest names in sports, from current superstars like Barry
Bonds and Shaquille O'Neal to retired Hall of Fame legends like Joe
Montana and Reggie Jackson, now compete for eyeballs on the Web
with ``exclusive'' columns and personal tidbits not available
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give them a reason to go back every day,'' said
Montana in an interview about his game plan for a new online
venture project, SportsHabitat.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be news, there'll be advice,'' Montana said. ``This
area is going to be interactive.''
</P>
<P>
   In pre-Web days, sports celebrities made extra cash off the
field by holding up a can of beer or shaving cream and smiling into
a TV camera.
</P>
<P>
   But now, big-name athletes of all sports are joining the rush
for Web e-commerce revenues and stock options. The athletes
themselves have become entertainment content that the sites use to
draw Web users into buying all manner of sports shoes, gloves,
bats, balls, golf clubs, T-shirts and other collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a recent phenomenon, within the last year, where
it's become commonplace for athletes to ask `What's my Web site
strategy?' '' said Ross Schaufelberger,, president and founder of
AthletesDirect.com, which has aggregated more than 275 athlete Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a golden opportunity to create revenue and exposure
under their control in a new medium,'' Schaufelberger said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, sports-related sites have become popular and
potentially lucrative Web attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Online research firm Jupiter Communications Inc. noted in a
recent report that sports was the fifth-most-popular channel on
America Online, behind news, entertainment, shopping and personal
finance.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter said that popularity should translate into about $3
billion in online sales of sporting goods, clothing, shoes and game
tickets by 2003, up from about $600,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   And according to a report last year by Forrester Research Inc.,
the Internet is causing a radical power shift of sports-related
programming away from the traditional radio and television media.
That shift should generate about $2.4 billion in advertising
revenue for sports-related sites by 2004, with e-commerce sales of
sports-related products climbing to about $4.7 billion in that same
time.
</P>
<P>
   So it's natural that professional athletes are lining up to
shoot for the Net as well.
</P>
<P>
   One example is Dunk.net, an Internet e-commerce site co-founded
by Los Angeles Lakers superstar center O'Neal and his agent,
Leonard Armato.
</P>
<P>
   The company has lined up two other notable partners: New York
Mets all-star catcher Mike Piazza and forward Rebecca Lobo of the
New York Liberty _ a Women's National Basketball Association team.
</P>
<P>
   Dunk.net offers customized athletic shoes and clothing, such as
the $84 Chromz basketball shoe, a style Shaq wore during this
year's NBA All-Star Game in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes and other apparel sold on Dunk.net are not available
in retail stores. Because it is made to order, like a computer
system sold on the Web, the shoes can be custom tailored to fit the
customer's choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a really tight Web site,'' O'Neal said during
an interview. ``Dunk is going to give the consumer a chance to feel
important.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep those customers coming back, O'Neal answers e-mailed
questions on ``ShaqTV,'' a streaming video program available only
on Dunk.net.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who said he likes to download free MP3s, said he also
hopes the site helps youth grasp the future power of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At first, ``I didn't understand the Internet language,'' O'Neal
said. ``I thought it was geeky. Now I know that it's cool. Now it's
my job to get the kids to say this is cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana, the legendary 49ers quarterback, has a new part-time
job as a business adviser for SportsHabitat.com Inc. of Orange
County, Calif., a new Web site whose co-founder and chief
communications officer is Jackson, the former Oakland Athletics and
New York Yankees slugger.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which will fully launch in June, will offer sports
buffs news, information and sporting equipment. Montana will also
wear the title ``magazine editor-in-chief'' for the site's ``Joe
Montana's in the Red Zone'' section.
</P>
<P>
   Montana said he was encouraged that SportsHabitat.com was also
going to try to appeal to women and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to find a way to get people to come to your store,''
Montana said. ``With names like Reggie, Chris Evert and Freddie
Couples, it's tough not to know those names.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, three of the biggest names in sports, Michael Jordan,
Wayne Gretzky and John Elway are partners in a sports apparel and
memorabilia site called MVP.com. Gretzky, meanwhile, is also a
partner in Faceoff.com, a hockey portal that features a column
written by the retired NHL great.
</P>
<P>
   AthletesDirect, now a unit of Broadband Sports Inc. of Santa
Monica, Calif., started in 1996 operating sites on America Online
for Steve Young and Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   The company now has the largest collection of Web jock sites,
with more than 275 stars from 15 sports - including Bonds,
Kournikova, Cincinnati Reds outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. and Los
Angeles Lakers forward Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The Web allows athletes to bypass the filter of traditional
media like newspapers, radio and television to give their fans
direct ``scoops'' they wouldn't get anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Young, for example, went to great lengths to keep all reporters
away from his wedding but posted his own photos and wedding account
on his AthletesDirect site.
</P>
<P>
   And in February, NFL tight end Shannon Sharpe scooped the media
by reporting on his Web site that he has agreed to a four-year deal
with the Baltimore Ravens. Olympic gold medalist Sheryl Swoopes
used her site to announce she would not play for the USA National
women's basketball team to spend more time with her 2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the press puts a stamp on certain players,'' wrote
Giants star Bonds on his site. ``Once they've stamped you as a bad
person. That's what they feed on and there's nothing you can do
about it. I know in my heart the type of ballplayer I am and the
type of person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   In another post, Bonds commented on Ken Griffey's trade to the
Reds and hinted about his future with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'd like to play with Kenny. We were teammates on a
(1996) tour of Japan, and we had a good time. I'm signed with the
Giants through next season (2001), but you never know what can
happen in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans can also tap into other minutia as well. Atlanta Falcons
running back Jamal Anderson wrote that earlier this month in San
Francisco he sat on a panel with supermodel Cindy Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly packed the house ... at least Cindy did!''
Anderson wrote. ``I think I was just as entertaining as Cindy ...
and maybe even a little cuter! You know I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Bryant's site, the young forward has kept his fans abreast of
his team's progress in the current NBA playoffs and answering
e-mails from fans, such as one fan who asked about his pregame
rituals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eat a good breakfast, go to shoot-around and I have a light
afternoon meal,'' Bryant wrote. ``I sleep when I'm tired. If not, I
watch a movie or something. I like old movies, like `The Ten
Commandments' or sometimes a Disney movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Orioles slugger Albert Belle, who refuses to talk to
the media, last month responded testily to an e-mail from a fan who
called him unprofessional.
</P>
<P>
   ``When have I not been professional on the baseball field? ...
Do I play everyday? Have I ever shown up a pitcher, or umpire? Do I
ever say anything negative or criticize? How about you walk in my
footsteps for a week and you see if can do the job that I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Belle then took a sarcastic shot at fans of his former team, the
Cleveland Indians, whom he once dubbed ``village idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am assuming you are a Cleveland fan, are you? It is nice to
know that you visit my Web site, please come back and bring some
buddies with you.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, basketball star Lobo said she enjoys how the
Web gives her personal interaction with fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my Web site, they can vote on what hairstyle they want me
to have. When I got hurt, I was inundated with e-mails from
well-wishers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still unclear whether the athletes have the kind of draw to
make the sites financially successful. AthletesDirect, in fact,
lost $203.8 million in 1999, according to its SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   And traffic to the sites, so far, is small. According to the
Nielsen/NetRatings Internet audience rating service,
AthletesDirect.com had 444,914 unique visitors for March, the
latest month for which data is available, while MVP.com had 172,178
unique visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Another research company, Media Metrix, tracked 372,000 unique
visitors to MVP.com in March.
</P>
<P>
   But both companies said many of the sites fall below their
radars because they don't generate enough traffic to meet their
services' minimum reporting standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain pretty dubious of athletes' Web sites,'' said Patrick
Keane, senior Internet analyst for Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   According to Keane's report on Internet sports commerce, a
survey of sports-minded Web surfers showed 35 percent looked for
scores and statistics, 27 percent wanted to read about the games
and 25 percent wanted event information. Only 1 percent wanted to
chat with stars and 2 percent liked chatting with other fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the very young fans gravitate toward celebrity or
star-driven sites,'' Keane said. ``Finding out what Ken Griffey Jr.
eats for breakfast is interesting to a very limited subset of
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
