 MONEYBAG: MEASURING VALUE OF INFORMATION  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Our investment club has been using the Value Line Investment
Survey as a research resource. The subscription is up for renewal,
and we wonder whether there is a different survey, weekly
newsletter, or whatever, that you would recommend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: I would rather not recommend any stock-touting letters. I am not
convinced that any of them will do you much good over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   However, based on the advertisements it places in financial
publications, Value Line's powers of prognostication look pretty
remarkable. It says that the stocks that it gave the highest
rankings over the years appreciated by 18,037 percent between 1965
and 1999. Meanwhile, the Dow Jones industrial average grew by only
1,161 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Can Value Line keep it up? You don't necessarily have to worry
about that, because its publication provides a vast amount of
useful, quantitative information about many hundreds of stocks. You
can ignore Value Line's opinions, if you choose, while using its
data to make your own decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If you want an objective assessment of some 160 prominent
stock-market newsletters, go to the Hulbert Financial Digest Web
site at  &LR; www.hulbertdigest.com.  &LR; The editor, Mark Hulbert, has been
tracking the stock-picking performances of leading market letters
for nearly two decades and is considered the dean of his field.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the Hulbert Web site provides links to the
sites of many of the market letters it surveys.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you want to know how Hulbert rates those market
letters, you will have to take out a paid subscription to the
digest. That normally costs $200 per year, but a $59 introductory
offer is currently available. You can apply electronically on the
Web site, or call toll-free at (888) 485-2378.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Equal Compensation
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do online discount brokers charge the same low commissions no
matter how large the trade? Also, could you tell me the Web
addresses of some reliable brokers?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: Most online brokers charge a low, fixed commission for
relatively small trades and considerably more for very large
trades.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Brown &AMP; Co. ( &LR; www.brownco.com &LR; ) is renowned for its
trifling $5 commission on market orders and $10 on limit orders of
5,000 shares or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   But if you trade more shares than that, the commission rises
steeply. On a 5,001-share market order you would pay the basic $5
plus a penny per share _ including the first 5,000 shares. Your
commission would jump to $55.01.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the Web addresses of the five online brokers that
received the highest ratings in a recent customer-satisfaction
survey by J.D. Power &AMP; Associates:
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity ( &LR; www.fidelity.com &LR; );
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab ( &LR; www.schwab.com &LR; );
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch ( &LR; www.ml.com &LR; );
</P>
<P>
   Datek Online ( &LR; www.datek.com &LR; );
</P>
<P>
   DLJdirect ( &LR; www.dljdirect.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Getting Fair Share
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was a small shareholder of 3Com Corp. before it spun off
Palm Inc. in the recent initial public offering. Why wasn't I given
a chance to buy some IPO shares? And now that Palm has been carved
out of the 3Com assets, how am I, as a 3Com shareholder, to be
compensated?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: As you seem to infer, the little guy usually doesn't get
to participate in the hottest IPOs. Institutional investors _ and
individuals who are among the most-favored customers of brokerage
firms _ stand the best chance.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you had bought Palm shares at the $38 IPO
price two months ago, you would be sitting on a substantial paper
loss today. Yes, the stock soared way above $100 on March 2, the
first day of trading, but it has since sold in the mid-20s, and it
closed yesterday at $32.25.
</P>
<P>
   You also should bear in mind that 3Com sold only a bit more than
4 percent of Palm's shares to the public, while retaining ownership
of the rest. It plans to distribute the remaining 96 percent to you
and other shareholders sometime in the next several months, in
proportion to your stake in 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   As to how you were compensated for the IPO: 3Com received more
than $800 million in cash for the 23 million shares it sold at $38
apiece. That money was added to the company's cash hoard, of which
you are a part-owner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
 &LR; moneybag(AT)sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column,
901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
