<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-MUTUAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCHWAB THINK TANK FOCUSES ON MUTUAL FUNDS  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., ``advice'' used to be a
dirty word.
</P>
<P>
   The leading discount broker's original, self-imposed mandate was
to provide bare-bones securities trading at a bargain price _
period.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted someone to hold your hand and tell you how to
invest or if you needed to see the latest high-powered investment
research, you had to take your business to full-service brokers,
such as Merrill Lynch, which charged commissions several times
greater than Schwab's.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the brokerage business crowded to the bursting point
and competitive as a snake pit, the line between full-service and
discount brokers has blurred. In the struggle to attract and keep
customers, every broker is striving to be everything to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   At Schwab, much of this effort is being spearheaded by a small,
low-profile think tank called the Schwab Center for Investment
Research. It is what one Schwab publicist calls the ``brains''
behind the advice that Schwab dispenses to customers these days.
</P>
<P>
   Opening in November 1997, it consists of 13 staffers _ primarily
statistics nerds with doctoral degrees _ who grind out a succession
of original reports and studies designed to help Schwab customers
make the right investment choices.
</P>
<P>
   The center also produces course material for investment seminars
at Schwab branches. And it masterminds some of Schwab's Web-based
analytical tools, such as the Stock Analyzer, which allows
investors to compare a company with the rest of the market and the
rest of its industry.
</P>
<P>
   The center was the brainchild of Schwab co-chief executive David
Pottruck and other top managers. They reasoned that if Schwab was
going to begin offering advice to customers, it needed to back up
that advice with independent, objective, high-quality research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers want to be informed and educated,'' says Chip Roame,
a former Schwab strategist who now runs his own consulting firm in
Tiburon, Calif. ``Customers appreciate that, and as a result, more
of their investment dollars will wind up at Schwab.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the center's reports focus on mutual-fund investing,
reflecting the fact that funds have become the investment of choice
for most rank-and-file customers.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on funds appears to make the Schwab Center unique
among brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full-service brokers do a boatload of equity research,'' says
John Rekenthaler, research director of Morningstar Inc., ``but to
my knowledge, they do almost nothing in the way of mutual-fund
studies.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's reports bear such titles as:
</P>
<P>
   ``How Many Funds Should You Own?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do New Funds Offer Better Performance?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which Publicly Available Variables Explain Future Mutual Fund
Performance?''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Riepe, 36, the Schwab vice president who manages the
center, says the titles usually end with question marks because the
reports are ``customer driven,'' and Schwab customers ask those
kinds of questions.
</P>
<P>
   The questions, posed mainly by people who visit Schwab's
branches, are passed along to Riepe and his colleagues by service
representatives, executives and marketing people.
</P>
<P>
   If a frequently asked question is intriguing enough, the Schwab
Center will tackle it. The center has generated 15 reports so far,
an average of one every other month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of folklore surrounding investing,'' Riepe
remarks. ``People say things must be a certain way, and that
becomes the commonsense belief. We look deeper _ at the empirical
data.''
</P>
<P>
   Riepe recalls that last summer, when the stock market hit a
severe downdraft, ``a lot of people wanted some fixed-income
exposure. You can do that two ways: go directly into bonds or into
bond mutual funds. Our firm didn't have a policy as to which was
best.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's analysts assumed that it was more cost-efficient to
invest large sums of money directly in bonds. People with small
sums to invest, on the other hand, would do better to put their
money in bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   But how small and how large?
</P>
<P>
   The center's staff examined the facts and crunched the numbers
and concluded that the cutoff was $50,000. You need a bond
portfolio at least that large to justify buying bonds on your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy individual bonds, there is the commission and the
spread between the bid price and the offering price,'' Riepe
observes. ``On the other hand, a bond mutual fund charges a
management fee. We built models and strategies for different types
of bond portfolios, and found that if you've got $50,000 and buy
investment-grade, highly liquid bonds and hold them to maturity,
the costs are comparable to those of a low-cost bond fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Riepe says another common question posed by customers is whether
they should periodically weed out the worst-performing mutual funds
in their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   One school of thought maintained that you should do it, because
poor performers tend to continue to perform poorly. But others
insisted that poor performers tend to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knew, however, so the Schwab Center delved into
the question.
</P>
<P>
   It found that you can enhance your portfolio by selling off the
worst performers ``within their peer groups'' _ that is, among
funds with the same investment styles, such as small
capitalization/growth or large capitalization/technology.
</P>
<P>
   `'The key is the peer group,'' Riepe says. ``Mutual fund
customers may see a fund with a 180 percent one-year return and
another with a 20 percent return. But your criterion should be:
What are they doing to get that track record?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the best-performing fund is heavily tilted toward tech
stocks and the other isn't. On the other hand, if you are
evaluating within a peer group and find your fund is consistently
at the bottom, that tells you something _ that the management team
may not be doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The center turns out multiple versions of each report. The
shortest versions _ summaries running 250 words _ are printed in
``Schwab Investor,'' a newsletter inserted with the monthly
brokerage statements the firm sends to its account holders.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat longer versions _ 500 to 700 words _ get printed in On
Investing, a magazine sent to customers who trade a lot, or have
large accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Still longer versions _ four printed pages _ are shipped to the
branches and distributed free to visitors who want them. They also
are posted indefinitely on the Schwab Web site at  &LR; www.schwab.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Full-blown, scholarly versions, running to thousands of words,
replete with arcane formulas and charts, are sent to customers of
Schwab's institutional branch _ mainly financial planners and
investment advisers.
</P>
<P>
   To a great extent, those mailings get ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Several investment professionals interviewed by The Chronicle
said they are too busy to give the center's reports careful
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do all our own research,'' says Craig Litman of
Litman/Gregory in Larkspur. ``Most of what comes across our desks
from other sources doesn't provide much added value for us.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the center does have some fans among the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great information,'' says Richard DelMonte, a Danville
retirement planner. ``I get it in the mail, take it home and read
it in bed. They really are good at gathering a lot of statistical
information. They pick really good topics that sometimes surprise
you with the results.''
</P>
<P>
   DelMonte says he was impressed with a study entitled ``How Tax
Efficient Are Tax-Managed Funds?'' The title refers to mutual funds
that try to minimize capital-gains distributions so their
shareholders won't get hit with big tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded that tax-managed funds generally were more
tax-efficient than other types of funds but noted that there were
very few of them. It suggested that investors who are concerned
about their tax burden, but want a broad fund selection, might find
it worthwhile to buy index funds, which tend to be nearly as
tax-efficient as tax-managed funds.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
