<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Balk costs Braves 3rd loss in row
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami _ Five games removed from their 15-game winning streak,
the Braves are in danger of beginning to look not all that good,
just streaky. John Rocker balked home the winning run in the bottom
of the ninth inning Monday night as the Braves lost their third in
a row and fourth in their last five games, 3-2 to the Florida
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   With the winning run at third base, Rocker dropped the ball
while his foot was on the pitching rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bako singled off Rudy Seanez to start the ninth, his third
hit of the game. Danny Bautista, who pinch ran for him, advanced to
second on an Andres Galarraga error on a pickoff throw and reached
third on a groundout. Rocker relieved Seanez, and his intentional
walk to Mark Smith brought up Cliff Floyd, who didn't have to take
the bat off his shoulder as Bautista scored on the balk. The only
hit the Braves managed with runners in scoring position was an
infield hit by Chipper Jones in the eighth inning. Seven other
opportunities were wasted, including two with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux was making his first start since the modern
franchise-record winning streak ended in Los Angeles, when he gave
up a season-high six runs and took his first loss.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux returned to form against the Marlins, though a Rafael
Furcal error wound up costing him two runs in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was the logical choice to feel immediate effects from the
Braves' recent injury problems, mainly the loss of catcher Eddie
Perez. Called up from AA Greenville, 22-year-old catcher Fernando
Lunar made his major-league debut in place of Perez, who was at
Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta recovering from season-ending shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A bad case of the bobbles on the infield hurt Maddux the most.
Rafael Furcal booted a Preston Wilson grounder near second base
trying to start a double play, and the Marlins scored the first of
two unearned runs for a 2-0 lead in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux worked around a Chipper Jones error and a grounder off
Furcal's glove for a hit to send the Braves into the last third of
the game with a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had stranded 21 runners in the last two games of the
Phillies series, and they continued to struggle against Marlins
starter Vladimir Nunez. The Braves managed nothing over the first
four innings against a pitcher who hadn't won yet in six starts
this season, going 0-3 with a 10.48 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   They used a Furcal walk and a Maddux single down the first base
line to cut the lead to 2-1. With a chance to do serious damage in
the sixth, they came away with only the game-tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
