<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHR     05-08 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: RATE INCREASE MEANS I-BONDS OFFER HEALTHY RETURN,
LOW  RISK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S. government's inflation savings bonds
haven't gotten much attention since they were introduced in
September 1998, but that may change soon.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, the government raised the current rate, guaranteed for
six months, on its so-called I-bonds to 7.49 percent from 6.98
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That beats the yield on all other Treasury securities and
money-market funds and most certificates of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Like all U.S. government securities, I-bonds are free from state
taxes. That gives them an edge over CDs, which are fully taxable.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's increase in the I-bond rate was bigger than expected
and reflects a couple of energy-induced inflationary spikes in
February and March.
</P>
<P>
   Ed White, a money manager in Fredricksburg, Texas, who has
always favored I-bonds, likes them even more now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a tax-deferred money-market account in your
safe deposit box with an exceptionally high real rate of return,
and it's the safest instrument in the world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I-bonds work like this: Every six months, in May and November,
the government sets a new rate on the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The rate has two parts: a ``core'' rate that is fixed and
guaranteed for the life of the bond and a floating rate that
changes every six months. The floating rate is based on the
Consumer Price Index for urban consumers for the previous six
months (ending the month before the adjustment date).
</P>
<P>
   The floating rate was raised last week to 3.82 percent from 3.58
percent, reflecting an unusually large 1.91 percent increase in the
CPI-U between October 1999 and March 2000. (That works out to 3.82
percent on an annual basis.)
</P>
<P>
   But what really surprised experts is that the government also
raised the core rate to 3.6 percent from 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Sudderth, a spokesman for the Bureau of the Public Debt,
says the core rate increase was based on market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But ``marketing'' may be more like it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when the government tries to get
workers at about 40,000 companies to buy bonds through payroll
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Savings bond expert Dan Pederson suspects the nearly 7.5 percent
rate ``was designed to draw attention to the I-bond.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he adds, ``the attention is warranted right now, if you can
lock in a 3.6 percent spread over inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   The spread between an investment's return and the inflation rate
is known as the ``real rate of return.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 50 years, the real rate of return has been 6 to 7
percent for stocks and 1 to 1.5 percent for short- to
intermediate-term Treasuries, according to White.
</P>
<P>
   That makes 7.49 percent pretty attractive, but remember that the
full rate is only in effect for six months. Bonds purchased between
May 1 and October 31 will earn 3.6 percent plus whatever the
floating rate is for every six-month period until the bonds are
sold.
</P>
<P>
   I-bonds should not be confused with the government's
inflation-indexed Treasury bonds, which can be traded through a
brokerage firm in the secondary market, like regular Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   I-bonds, like the government's older cousins EE bonds, can only
be purchased directly from the Bureau of the Public Debt or through
most banks. Unlike EE bonds, which are purchased at half of face
value, I-bonds are bought at face value. The I-bonds are available
in eight denominations ranging from $50 to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The interest rate on EE bonds is also changed every six months.
It equals 90 percent of the average yield on five-year Treasuries.
The rate on EE bonds purchased today is 5.73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While I-bonds appear to be far superior, if the Federal Reserve
continues to raise interest rates and that causes inflation to turn
back down, then EE bonds could end up being the better deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we run at 2 percent (annual) inflation over the next six
months, it would drop the I-bond rate down to 5.6 percent,'' says
Pederson, author of ``Savings Bonds: When to Hold, When to Fold.''
</P>
<P>
   Although nobody knows what will happen in the future, Pederson
says he went back about 15 years to see which would have been the
better bond _ the I-bond or the EE bond.
</P>
<P>
   His conclusion: ``If the fixed (core) rate is 3.25 percent or
higher, the I-bond is a better deal. With 3.6 percent, it makes the
I-bonds even a better deal.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more facts: I-bonds must be held for at least six months.
They can be held for up to 30 years. However, if you cash in the
bonds before five years, you'll lose three months' worth of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Interest is added to the value of the bond and is paid out,
along with principal, when the bond is redeemed. Taxes are not owed
until the bond is cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the Bureau of the Public Debt at
(510) 337 5039 or visit  &LR; www.savingsbonds.gov  &LR; (the government's
site) or  &LR; www.bondhelp.com &LR;  (Pederson's site).
</P>
<P>
   NOT HUNGRY FOR WEBVAN: Here's a good piece of advice: Never go
grocery shopping on an empty stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another good piece of advice: Never ask a crowd of
investors if they'd buy an online grocery store right after they've
eaten a big Mediterranean chicken lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Alsop, the noted journalist-turned-venture capitalist,
learned that the hard way Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Alsop was on a luncheon panel at the big Chase H&AMP;Q technology
investment conference at the Westin St. Francis in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   First he explained why he thought business-to-consumer Internet
companies (a.k.a. e-tailers) are not dead.
</P>
<P>
   He proceeded to disclose that he bought 3,000 shares of Webvan,
the online grocery store, at an average price of just under $10.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, he continued, is now trading around $6.25 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Then he asked the audience _ about a thousand institutional
investors and stock analysts _ how many people would buy Webvan at
$6.25 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single hand went up. (Well, Alsop thought he saw one.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first buy sign I've seen on Webvan,'' quipped
fellow panelist David Bonderman, founder of buyout firm Texas
Pacific Group. (Often, the best time to buy a stock is when nobody
else wants to own it.)
</P>
<P>
   The most delicious part of the lunch, however, was seeing Sandy
Robertson on the dais along with Alsop, Bonderman and Dan Case, CEO
of Chase H&AMP;Q.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson and Case were rivals for many years until the former
sold his investment bank, Robertson, Stephens, to Bank of America.
The firm was sold several times after that, and Robertson is no
longer affiliated with his old company.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's starting a new firm, Francisco Partners, that will
do leveraged buyouts of tech firms _ including many his old company
took public.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
