<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 05/08/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- OCONNOR-4 -- St. Patrick's
Cathedral was the scene of majesty and bathos, sadness and some
comedy Monday as dignitaries and ordinary worshipers paid respects
to Cardinal John O'Connor, who was buried under the altar. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- TEXAS-DEMS-B&AMP;W -- Texas
Democrats - namely Lyndon B. Johnson as Senate majority leader and
Sam Rayburn as speaker - once all but ran the country. Now at least
some are out stumping for George W. Bush. (George Tames/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- NY-AUCTION -- Caillebotte's
``Man on the Balcony,'' sold for $14.3 million at Christie's Monday
night. All but five of the 47 works on offer found buyers in a sale
which totaled $104.5 million. (Christie's/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TRENTON, N.J. -- May 8, 2000 -- NJ-SENATE-DEBATE -- The
four Republican candidates for the United States Senate in New
Jersey relaxed after their first debate Monday. From left, James W.
Treffinger, Robert D. Franks, Murray Sabrin and William L. Gormley.
(Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) SAN FRANCISCO -- May 8, 2000 -- SF-FAT-BIAS -- Marilyn
Wann, left, Jason Fisher and Nancy Gold are supporters of San
Francisco's anti-bias ``fat ordinance,'' which was approved Monday.
The measure actually applies to skinny people, too. It adds height
and weight to the same antidiscrimination codes that provide
protections for people based on race, religion, color, ancestry,
age, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, disability and place
of birth. (Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- MEXICO-ELECT -- In a Mexican
public service television campaign against coercive polling
tactics, the woman in white is pressured by three people to vote
for one party. An announcer tells viewers that their vote is ``free
and secret.'' (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- HAT-FASHION-2 -- Though the
formal custom of wearing hats has been in decline since the Kennedy
administration, last week there were actually two occasions in New
York where one could wear a hat without feeling like a raving
idiot. Above, at Joan Rivers' party: from left, Blaine Trump, in
striped hat; Ghislaine Maxwell; and Princess Firyal of Jordan. At
the Conservatory Gardens, below, Noriko Maeda, left, and Hiroko
Rodriguez in Philip Treacy hats. (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- HAT-FASHION-1 -- Though the
formal custom of wearing hats has been in decline since the Kennedy
administration, last week there were actually two occasions in New
York where one could wear a hat without feeling like a raving
idiot. Somers White, left, arrived for the 18th annual Central Park
Conservancy luncheon. At Joan Rivers' party, Lizzie Spender
Humphries, the wife of Barry Humphries (Dame Edna), said, ``He
liked this one'' (Barbara Alper/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- NY-POT-ARRESTS -- Under the
Giuliani administration's continuing crackdown intended to improve
quality of life, crackdown, minor offenses ranging from smoking
marijuana in public to jumping a turnstile typically result in a
night in a sweltering, overcrowded and urine-soaked holding cell.
Police arrested 312 protesters, many of them young people from
outside the city, during a marijuana legalization rally in Lower
Manhattan on Saturday. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- VIEQUES-PROFILE -- As
president and general counsel of the Puerto Rican Legal Defense and
Education Fund in New York, Juan A. Figueroa has been a leader in
organizing much of the mainland Latino response to the Navy's use
of Vieques to train its pilots about the finer points of aerial
bombardment. ``Who wants bombing in their backyard?'' said
Figueroa. ``Last year it was Ricky Martin. Now it's Vieques that
has captured the public's attention.'' (Dith Pran/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- OBIT-TURNER-B&AMP;W -- Ruth D.
Turner, a Harvard professor, author, curator and diver who became
one of the world's leading experts in the species of mollusks that
devour wooden piers and sunken ships, died on April 30 at a nursing
home in Waltham, Mass. She was 85. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) OAKLAND, Calif. -- May 8, 2000 -- GENE-SALE --
DoubleTwist Inc., a small biotechnology company in California, said
Monday that it had identified as many as 105,000 human genes by
performing the first comprehensive computer analysis of the
publicly available data from the Human Genome Project. ``The real
key is knowing where the human genes lie on this immense string of
base pairs,'' said John Couch, the president of DoubleTwist. (Thor
Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- TOTES-COX -- As product
development director for the Totes-Isotoner Corp., Jean Silverstein
designs and supervises all of the company's rainwear, oversees
graphic design, and supervises the new children's division, which
will debut this fall. Among the new items are licensed products
from Fisher Price and a line of Harry Potter items that will be
introduced next spring. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- SOUTHERN-STEW-2-COX -- The
ingredients vary by location, but the tradition of slowly simmering
large batches of stew for community gatherings is a shared one
captured in a new exhibit at the University of South Carolina's
McKissick Museum in Columbia. The classic ingredients of a St.
Helena Stew (or Lowcountry boil) include sweet corn, potatoes,
sausage and shrimp. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ALBERTA, Va. -- May 8, 2000 -- SOUTHERN-STEW-1-COX --
The ingredients vary by location, but the tradition of slowly
simmering large batches of stew for community gatherings is a
shared one captured in a new exhibit at the University of South
Carolina's McKissick Museum in Columbia. Champion stewmaster Jeff
Daniel, left, coordinated the cooking of a Brunswick Stew at a
community auction in Alberta. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- TONY-NOMINEES -- When the
Tony Award nominations were announced Monday, Rosemary Harris,
left, and her daughter, Jennifer Ehle, shown with her co-star,
Stephen Dillane, were pitted against each other in a
leading-actress category. Harris was nominated for her work in
``Waiting in the Wings''; Ehle was nominated for ``The Real
Thing.'' (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LONDON -- May 8, 2000 -- SUB-INTERNET-BATTLEGROUND --
Ian Clarke, a 23-year-old Irish programmer, is finishing a program
called Freenet that is intended to make it possible to share any
kind of information anonymously while rendering it virtually
impossible to remove the information from the Internet once it is
placed there. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) L'ANSE AIX MEADOWS, Newfoundland -- May 8, 2000 --
SCI-VINLAND -- The remains of a Viking settlement near the village
of L'Anse aux Meadows, rediscovered in 1960, have inspired new
research that has caused experts to revise their views of the
explorers. These new interpretations of the Vikings and their Norse
descendants are illustrated in an exhibition, ``Vikings: The North
Atlantic Saga,'' at the National Museum of Natural History in
Washington through Aug. 13. (John Noble Wilford/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- OCONNOR-3 -- Hailed by
friends and followers at a touching funeral Mass, Cardinal John
O'Connor arrived at his final resting place beneath St. Patrick's
Cathedral on Monday completing his journey from local priest to the
nation's most prominent Roman Catholic. Dignitaries taking part in
the Mass near the coffin of Cardinal O'Connor were, from left,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Libby Pataki, wife of New York Gov. George
Pataki, Gov. George Bush of Texas, President Clinton, first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Gore and his wife Tipper.
The cardinal's coffin is in the background. (Keith Meyers/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- OCONNOR-2 -- Hailed by
friends and followers at a touching funeral Mass, Cardinal John
O'Connor arrived at his final resting place beneath St. Patrick's
Cathedral on Monday completing his journey from local priest to the
nation's most prominent Roman Catholic. Dignitaries taking part in
the Mass near the coffin of Cardinal O'Connor were, from left,
former President Bush, Sen. Daniel Moynihan, Sen. Charles Schumer,
Peter Valone, New York City Council speaker, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, New York Gov. George Pataki, his wife Libby, President
Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Gore and
his wife Tipper. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- EBAY-AUCTION -- On April 28, a
California man who uses the handle ``golfpoorly'' put a half dozen
items up for sale on eBay, the online auction company. Along with
an unopened roll of twine, a never inflated basketball and several
other items, he offered this ``great big wild abstract painting.''
Bids started at a quarter. On Monday bids for this painting, which
may be a 1952 work by Richard Diebenkorn, are up to a $135,605.
(The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CHEROKEE COUNTY, Ga. -- May 8, 2000 --
TRUCK-HOUSE-CRASH-COX -- Zachary Williams, 6, stands outside his
home after being woken when a tractor trailer truck slammed into
the porch at 5:20 a.m. Monday morning. Workers, rear, prepare to
right the rig. The truck was involved in an accident with a pickup
truck before turning sideways and skidding into the home. ``It
sounded like the house falling down,'' said Zachary's mom, Sarah
Williams. The driver of the truck emerged relatively unscathed; the
driver of the pickup was taken to the hospital. (John Spink/The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- May 8, 2000 -- SCI-MILKYWAY-COLLIDE -- A
collision of galaxies in the constellation Canis Major, captured by
the Hubble Space Telescope, may be a prelude to what happens three
billion years from now if the Milky Way and the Great Andromeda
galaxies cross paths. Astronomers have known for decades that
Andromeda is headed this way, though they still cannot say whether
the two are destined to collide or merely to speed past, narrowly
missing each other. (Hubble Heritage Project/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- OCONNOR-1 -- J. Roger Watkins
holds a photo of John Cardinal O'Connor while weeping outside St.
Patrick's Cathedral on Monday during O'Connor's funeral Mass.
Watkins, a builder, said the cardinal had helped him after his
daughter was injured and considered O'Connor a friend. (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- May 8, 2000 -- WEATHER-FEATURE -- With
temperatures in the nation's capital in the unseasonable 90's on
Monday, many people around the city were looking for some sort of
relief. Students from Hillsboro High School in Nashville, Tenn.,
cooled off in the Dupont Cirlcle fountain. (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 8, 2000 -- NY-COWS-HORSES -- When an
exhibit of fiberglass cows was spread throughout Chicago last
summer, the strange sight spooked some of the carriage horses along
Michigan Avenue. In order to avoid such problems here, sample
fiberglass cows have been sent to the city's mounted police units
so the horses can can get used to them. Deputy Inspector Peter
Abbott sees how a seven-year-old horse, yet to be named, reacts to
one of the cows. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PASEDENA, Calif. -- May 8, 2000 -- SCI-NASA -- As 300
space scientists and engineers gathered recently for the fourth
International Conference on Low-Cost Planetary Missions,
conversations turned to last year's failures of two American Mars
probes and how lessons learned might apply to other projects now
under way or being planned. One of the studies, conducted by Tony
Spear, the retired project manager of NASA's popular 1997 Mars
Pathfinder mission, said senior managers expected too much of
projects that followed his successful one. Spears in his Pasadena
office. (Michael Tweed/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- May 8, 2000 -- SCI-ULTRASOUND-2 -- Since
the 70's, ultrasound has grown up. Rather than simply glancing at
the fetus, doctors today can take measurements as well as check
vital organs. The latest gadgets, though far from standard use,
create three-dimensional images of the fetus allowing for the
identifcation of finer points of the developing anatomy. A screen
shot of a three-dimentional picture of a healthy 34Qweek old fetus
sucking its thumb. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- May 8, 2000 -- SCI-ULTRASOUND-1 -- Since
the 70's, ultrasound has grown up. Rather than simply glancing at
the fetus, doctors today can take measurements as well as check
vital organs. The latest gadgets, though far from standard use,
create three-dimensional images of the fetus allowing for the
identifcation of finer points of the developing anatomy. Dr.
Lawrence Platt administers a fetal ultrasound to Sandra Socza. Her
healty baby is seen at right. ( Edward Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- May 8, 2000 -- SCI-BRODY-HEALTH --
Forty years ago on Tuesday, a social and medical revolution was set
off: the Pill was born. Since its introduction, an estimated 468
million American women have taken it. Today more than 16 million
American women are on it, making it the most popular contraceptive
technique outside of sterilization. Dr. John Rock, the pioneer of
the birth control pill, in his laboratory in 1966. (Sam Falk/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
