</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACHING EWING IS GUIDED BY SPIRIT  

</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ About a half-hour before the team bus pulled away Sunday
morning, Patrick Ewing folded his 7-foot frame into the back of a
taxi and rode off with a rehabilitation specialist by his side.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was on his way to American Airlines Arena, early en route
to Game 1 against the Miami Heat, to receive yet another treatment
for the back spasms that left him nearly unable to walk when they
first occurred on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to a long list of things Ewing is not afraid of _ like
Chicago and Michael Jordan, heights and tight spaces _ he does not
have a fear of needles, either. He had an acupuncture session two
hours before tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes to play. If necessary, he will go through the
same process before the Knicks try to even the four-of-seven-game,
second-round series in Game 2 on Tuesday night in Miami. Today,
Ewing sat on the sideline after practice, his body parts packed as
deep as Champagne bottles in ice, and answered the question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Why put himself through all this?
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy playing,'' Ewing said just before he asked a Knicks
trainer to wrap his back with a bigger bandage. ``When I finish
playing, I want to leave with a ring. The most important thing is I
enjoy doing it. I enjoy waking up and practicing. I enjoy playing
against the best players in the world. It feels good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who in this league doesn't play with any pain or nagging
nicks? We all play with it. The question is: Can you go out and
perform at a high level like that? I think that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the state of his scratch-and-dent-sale body, he did
remarkably well in Game 1. He played 40 minutes, scored 17 points,
grabbed 9 rebounds and blocked a shot. But the issue isn't his
statistics; it's his mobility. It's how the Heat drove fearlessly
into the paint for uncontested layups, how languid Ewing was in
transition, how difficult it was for him to prevent Alonzo Mourning
from taking over the game at the end.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, Mourning, who scored 10 of 26 points in
the final eight minutes of the game, was able to get position deep
in the post against Ewing for an easy layup. And he was able to
bolt outside of a late-arriving Ewing for a key jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alonzo had a great game, especially down the stretch,'' Ewing
said. ``He got the ball deep and was able to make plays. I have to
do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ewing was not the root of the Knicks' problems on Sunday.
Even if he is more mobile in Game 2, he won't be the cure-all,
either. There were other issues _ some relating to Ewing and some
not _ that led to the loss on Sunday. Monday, Coach Jeff Van Gundy
outlined the three areas that need most improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we didn't start the game with the intensity we'd talked
about all week,'' Van Gundy said. ``There was a discernible
difference between Toronto in the first quarter and the first
quarter Sunday. They shot 60 percent, and outrebounded us, 16-7.
They were 8 for 8 on layups, and we never fouled them once. Two, we
didn't fight for the ball as much as we need to. And three, we
didn't pass the ball like we had to pass to shoot the percent we
need to shoot to win down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, the Knicks totaled only four assists.
Even though they had the Heat in the penalty with seven minutes
left in the game, the Knicks didn't drive but instead launched
quick jumpers early in the shot clock. And they didn't work the
ball into Ewing. After Ewing made his first two shots in the fourth
quarter, he didn't touch the ball for the last nine minutes of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Knicks' problem was the way the Heat sealed off
Ewing. Part of it was the sloppy ball-handling by the Knicks. Allan
Houston tried to whip a pass into Ewing, but threw it right into
the hands of P.J. Brown with 28.3 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take care of the ball,'' Van Gundy said. ``Eight of
their 19 fourth-quarter points came off our five turnovers. And
they didn't turn it over once in the fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the ball in his hands, Ewing could make a difference
only with his defense. But with his body weighed down with
injuries, with Van Gundy choosing to leave him one-on-one in
coverage, Ewing couldn't prevent Mourning's run. He will try again
on Tuesday. Whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing, I'm playing,'' Ewing said. ``I've always had
bangs and bumps. I've always had ice on my knees and other parts of
my body. That's part of basketball. That's part of life. I don't
even concern myself with it. The only thing I'm concerned about is
that tomorrow, at 8 p.m., I feel good. I'll go out and play to the
best of my abilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
