<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-SKILES-SUNS-LADN     05-08 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SKILES-SUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS' SKILES IS SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Scott Skiles was being serious, which is like
saying Shaquille O'Neal is big. O'Neal is big all the time.
</P>
<P>
   So as Skiles stood somewhat uncomfortably against the wall
outside the Suns locker room moments before his Suns would open
their playoff series against the top-seeded Lakers, the NBA's
newest coaching Boy Wonder didn't hesitate in his response.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't Skiles, all of 36 and leading his first postseason team,
feel just a tad more under the microscope coaching in the playoffs
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said flatly. ``That doesn't even cross my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bet he meant it, too. Skiles is what you might call focused.
This is a very serious young man, but then, Skiles can't remember a
time when he wasn't intense.
</P>
<P>
   Intense, serious, focused, competitive, tough, a throwback
</P>
<P>
   those are the terms used to describe Skiles since he first
started garnering national attention from a small Indiana high
school in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a man who smiles a lot, though he has plenty to be
happy about these days. He was supposed to be Danny Ainge's
third-year assistant, and when the season began, he was. Then 20
games into it, Ainge decided he had to spend more time with his
wife and six children, and wanted out of coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock,'' said Suns chairman Jerry Colangelo. `It was
really a surprise when he called to tell us he wanted to meet. It
was after a loss Saturday in San Antonio. On Sunday morning, I got
a call in church that Danny wanted to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the locker room, and just as I sat down he said,
`I've made a decision. I'm going to quit.' It wasn't like he wanted
to talk about options. As soon as he explained why, I didn't even
raise a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `I feel really good about the fact that Scott
Skiles is here. I don't know what your plans are, but I wouldn't
hesitate to give him the job.'''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles was young but felt sure he was ready. He had always
wanted to be a coach, and since he first began his 10-year career
as an NBA point guard, wanted to coach in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   He had spent a year as a head coach for PAOK in Greece when
Ainge first got the Phoenix job, remembered the tenacious Orlando
Magic guard and asked that he be made an Suns assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember in our first conversation, Danny saying, `I don't
think he's going to be here very long. He's going to be a head
coach in this league and it won't take him long to get there
because he's really good,''' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out it wouldn't take him long, but he wasn't going
anywhere. When Ainge made his decision to walk away, Colangelo said
he didn't hesitate to give Skiles the job and not on an interim
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott was kind of made for this,'' he said. ``I mean, this was
something he dreamed about, something he always wanted. He saw
himself as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, you never know how it's going to happen or if
it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles directed the Suns to a 40-22 mark. He stressed teamwork.
He stressed hard work. And as uncharacteristic as it sounded to
those used to their wild shoot-'em-up offense, he stressed defense.
</P>
<P>
   Showing confidence and intelligence, he asked Colangelo to bring
back John MacLeod as an assistant coach. MacLeod had been a head
coach in the NBA for 18 years _ and for all or parts of 14 seasons
with Phoenix _ and ranks 10th on the league's all-time win list
(707 victories).
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches who look in the mirror know themselves pretty well,''
Colangelo said. ``Know their own strengths and weaknesses. And the
kind of people you should have assisting are those that kind of
fill in the blanks. What John brought was experience. And that was
indication that Scott's not intimidated by anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said MacLeod: ``I think that says something about Scotty. He
wasn't threatened. He wasn't looking at it from that perspective.
He was looking at it from having a veteran, experienced coach who's
been in the playoffs, who's coached 1300-some games, who could help
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The players already knew Skiles, and responded quickly to his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Despite not having a dominant big man, the Suns allowed just
93.7 points per game. Over a full season, that would have been the
second-fewest points allowed in team history. Opponents shot a
team-record-low .424 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles had built his own career through hard work and attitude
and he didn't have to say much to get his message across.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's doing his job, he's more a reserved type of guy,''
said Suns veteran Cliff Robinson. ``He's not really the type to be
out there laughing and joking. He's serious. That's what we've come
to expect from him. But at the same time, when he's away from this,
he's a cool guy to hang out with.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles said that's the way he was even as a youth growing up in
Plymouth, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just very, very intense even at a young age,'' Skiles
said earlier this year. ``I was cognizant then that some people
were kind of against me. If a Little League game was rained out, I
was hard to handle. I was not an easy child to raise by anybody's
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles wasn't just aware of the movie ``Hoosiers,'' he lived it.
He led the state in scoring in 1982. He hit a 25-foot shot in the
closing seconds to send the state championship game into overtime,
scoring 39 points in the double-OT victory. Plymouth became the
smallest school to win the Indiana state title since Milan in 1954
_ Milan was the school made famous by ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   At Michigan State he was the nation's second-leading scorer
(27.4) before being taken with the 22nd overall pick by Milwaukee.
In Orlando, he played with O'Neal, Brian Shaw and current Suns
guard Penny Hardaway. His 30 assists against Denver on Dec. 30,
1990 is an NBA record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great player and from the look of things, he's going
to be a great coach in this league,'' O'Neal said. ``He's pretty
good right now, but in a couple years, he's going to be one of the
dominant coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo rewarded Skiles with a five-year contract last month.
Rumor has it, Skiles smiled. His unexpected opening could be
leading to a lengthy run. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
