<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ COULD SEE DOUBLE-TEAM FROM SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ As Shaquille O'Neal awaits the FedEx
package delivering his MVP trophy today, he also awaits a different
kind of honor from the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The double team. The triple team. And perhaps, the brass-plated
kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   Against mostly single coverage, O'Neal scored 37 points in Game
1 of the Lakers' second-round series against the Suns. So now it's
Phoenix's move, and the Lakers anticipate more double-teams of the
MVP-in-waiting (a news conference for the coronation will be held
this afternoon).
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll happen. They just have to figure out a way to do it,''
coach Phil Jackson said. ``Right now they're just hoping that Luc
(Longley) can stem the tide. And he did the first (quarter). His
body and presence on Shaquille was the difference ... to at least
contend with Shaq's thrust, his first, initial shot. And he started
off very poorly, 1 for 7, but found some second shots and found
some extra energy and then Luc got in foul trouble and he got a
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, Phoenix doesn't do much double-teaming, and they have
just two days to adopt a strategy for Game 2, Wednesday at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be tough,'' Jackson said. ``They'll have some problems.
What they did well against San Antonio (in the first round) is they
fronted and then they had a person coming from the backside on the
lob passes to David Robinson and then crowd him with that player
from the back, or block shots with (Corie) Blount or (Shawn)
Marion. And they're very athletic and can do that. Against David,
it worked OK, although he scored very well against them. But with
Shaq, his size and ability to overload the floor, and get the ball
to him anyway when he's fronted, will be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who struggled at times against the Sacramento Kings'
double teams in the first round, said he's ready for whatever the
Suns do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to hope my reaction skills are up and ready, so
whatever they do, we just have to react,'' he said. ``They're
probably going to do something different, but we have a lot of
weapons on this team, and as long as I do all the other stuff, like
rebound and defend, my team will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   How would O'Neal stop O'Neal?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the unexplained question,'' he said. ``That's an
`X-Files' question.''
</P>
<P>
   TROPHY TIME: O'Neal was reserved when the subject of winning MVP
came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I get it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That much is a given. The only question is whether he'll be the
first player in history to win unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a nice accolade,'' he said. ``I'm having a
pretty good year. It'd be nice to be appreciated by you guys (in
the media).''
</P>
<P>
   REST TIME: After playing four playoff games in eight days,
Jackson gave his regulars the day off Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my standpoint, today is a day that we needed to have
off,'' he said. ``I thought we needed just some time to get live
legs again, so we could play that kind of speed ball that is
required against Phoenix. ... The second thing is the mental
attitude. They have to get the mental attitude to play aggressive
enough, so that we don't get complacent or lackadaisical.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG HEADS: Having routed the Sacramento Kings twice only to see
them tie the series, the Lakers are trying to avoid another bout
with overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we had that problem playing against Sacramento,'' John
Salley said. ``We blew them out and we came in relaxed, and they
taxed us for that overconfidence, for that ego thrust that we did
when we went up to Sacramento. So I don't think we're going to run
into that trap again. We know what it's like to embarrass
ourselves. We know it takes 11 more (victories) to win a
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   OUCH REPORT: Suns All-Star Jason Kidd had to skip practice
Monday and probably will sit today as well to rest his sore left
ankle, which he broke March 22. He is questionable for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the game wore on, I could tell that he wasn't doing the
things he really is capable of doing,'' said Lakers guard Derek
Fisher, who has a bone spur in his right ankle. ``I was kind of
joking with him there at the end of the game that we're both out
here hobbling on one foot, trying to do everything we can to help
our teams.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
