<HEADER>
A9552 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX     05-08 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN AND CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers first base coach Ed Napoleon
announced his retirement yesterday, ending a 45-year baseball
career. Napoleon, 62, wants to be with his wife Marcy, who has not
been in good health at their home in Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making the right decision,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon's career began in 1956 as an outfielder for Dothan,
Ala., in the St. Louis Cardinals organization. That was the same
year Mickey Mantle won the Triple Crown and Don Larsen pitched his
perfect game in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon played 15 seasons in the minors, spent 17 years as a
minor-league manager or coach (he managed and played one year) and
another 14 years as a big-league coach with the New York Yankees,
Cleveland Indians, Kansas City Royals, Houston Astros and the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank Doug Melvin, Johnny Oates, the players and
everybody in the Texas Rangers organization for an outstanding 51/2
years,'' Napoleon said. ``The people here made it even more
difficult to retire at this time. However, it is very important to
me to be home in Florida, and this is the right decision for me and
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon's primary assignment was working with the Rangers
outfielders and, Rusty Greer said, ``He knows as much about playing
the outfield as anybody. More importantly, he's a good person. It's
going to be sad to see him go but I think he's making the right
decision.''  &QL; 
No successor named
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have yet to name a successor for Ed Napoleon but
Oates said the No. 1 priority is to find a someone who can work
with their young outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some ideas, but that will be the No. 1 need,'' Oates
said. ``It's not imperative we stay within the organization but I
would like to.''
</P>
<P>
   One candidate would be Dick McLaughlin, their minor-league
outfield and base-running instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon's departure leaves an opening in the Rangers coaching
staff for the first time since Oates was hired in 1994. He has had
the same six original coaches until Napoleon retired.  &QL; 
Useful acquisition
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners signed free-agent second baseman Mark McLemore from
Texas because he can play in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries have forced the team to use him at second base more
than planned, Mariners manager Lou Piniella said. Last night,
McLemore started at second and led off as the Mariners began a
three-game series against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Going in, he led the Mariners in at-bats (104) and stolen bases
(six) and was their fourth-leading run scorer (19) despite a .221
batting average. He also had 19 walks, third best on the team.
Saturday, he delivered the game-winning hit in the ninth inning a
1-0 victory against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stabilizes things,'' Piniella said. ``He's had a slow start
with the bat, but he's taken a lot of pitches at the plate. He's
been getting walks and some key hits.''
</P>
<P>
   McLemore hasn't lost confidence despite not being invited back
by Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't listen to what anybody says,'' McLemore said. ``If I
listened to what everybody said, I would have never lasted 14 days,
much less 14 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners pitcher Aaron Sele, a teammate of McLemore's in Texas
for two seasons, said McLemore hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same-old, same-old,'' Sele said. ``He's having fun.
That's the way he is.''  &QL; 
Sele's value increases
</P>
<P>
   With Freddy Garcia and Jamie Moyer on the disabled list, former
Rangers starter Aaron Sele has become the Mariners' No. 1 starter,
Mariners manager Lou Piniella said. Sele, who will start against
the Rangers tomorrow, is 2-2 with a 4.50 earned-run average. He
leads the Mariners in innings with 38.
</P>
<P>
   Sele has contributed in other ways. Moyer said the team's
younger pitchers have found it easy to turn to the seven-year
veteran for his thoughts about pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the younger guys on the team have a lot of potential
but not a lot of experience,'' Moyer said. ``It's good seeing that
veteran kind of guy. He's been able to add to this clubhouse.''  &QL; 
Former teammates
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele and Mark McLemore said they'll enjoy seeing their
former teammates this week, but the Rangers don't resemble the team
they played for last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've pulled off some trades and let some free agents go _
they're definitely a different team,'' Sele said. ``But they're
still leading the league in hitting. They've put another good team
on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores such as Friday's 17-16 final don't go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team can score some runs,'' McLemore said. ``Trust me _ I
know. I used my legs to score those runs many times.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
