<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH TO COMPLAIN ABOUT IN LAKERLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is Sunday afternoon, and the eternal spring rite known as the
NBA playoffs is set to unfold again at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the Game 1 tipoff between the Lakers and Phoenix
Suns, Jerry West is a picture of calm.
</P>
<P>
   He is in luxury box suite 10B, private sanctuary of Laker owner
Jerry Buss and his colorful entourage that includes some of the
most resilient hangers-on in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He is standing and gazing down at the magnificent new structure,
and he begins reflecting on the arenas he played in during his Hall
of Fame career in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We once played on the stage at the Shrine Auditorium,'' he
says. ``We once played at the L.A. State gym. This place is so
awesome. There was nothing even close to this when I played. I
played in a lot of old convention halls and civic auditoriums and
cow barns.''
</P>
<P>
   West smiles softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this luxury suite is bigger than most of our locker
rooms were in those days,'' he cracks.
</P>
<P>
   The match begins.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Friday night's raucous atmosphere for the Lakers' Game 5
wipeout of the Sacramento Kings ``My ears still are ringing,'' says
West the crowd is subdued.
</P>
<P>
   So are the Lakers in the early stages.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows who's going to win this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are a nice, little feisty team with athletic players
that eliminated the San Antonio Spurs, but Luc Longley, Cliff
Robinson, Corie Blount and Oliver Miller won't be able to handle
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal misses 6 of his first 7 shots, but you know eventually he
will start dominating the proceedings as the Phoenix coach, Scott
Skiles, curiously chooses to guard him with only one defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of what poison you want to choose,'' Skiles will
say afterward. ``If you double team Shaq, he passes out to
teammates for open jump shots. So you concede the 30 to 40 points
to Shaq, and try to put the clamps down on the rest of his
teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one of O'Neal's teammates, Kobe Bryant, is as
superb as O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are up by only five (46-41) at halftime, but you get
the feeling that they have matters under their control.
</P>
<P>
   As I repair to the Chick Hearn press room, I run into that
well-known fight patron, Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have done as well against Lennox Lewis as that
basketball player (Michael Grant) did,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson nods with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was embarrassing,'' he says, referring to Lewis' second
round devastation of Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The final half follows the expected script, as O'Neal's lurking
presence in the middle forces the Suns into taking mostly outside
shots which they keep missing and as O'Neal and Bryant attack
relentlessly on offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers pull away to a 15-point edge (75-60) at the end of
three quarters, and soon it gets even larger as the bored audience
contents itself watching cheering fans caught on the huge Staples
Center video scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, as I head for the interview room, I run into an old
acquaintance, Jerry Colangelo, the owner of the Suns and Arizona
Diamondbacks whom I've known since 1968 when he was a mere general
manager of the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew you when you couldn't rub two nickels together,'' I say
to the most powerful man in Arizona athletics, now a millionaire
many, many times over.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs, and we reminisce about old times when, as an interim
coach, he nearly led the Suns to colossal upset of the Lakers
during the 1970 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the Lakers down 3-1, but we just couldn't stop Wilt
Chamberlain,'' he recalls wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem as though this Sun team can stop Shaquille
O'Neal, either,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither has any other team been able to stop O'Neal this
season,'' says Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you here Wednesday night,'' I say in my good-bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``No you won't,'' says Colangelo. ``My wife and I are going to
Europe. I'm going to be out of the country for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, even Jerry Colangelo knows the destiny that
inevitably awaits the Suns against a Laker team they've failed to
beat in five attempts this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview room, the coaches, Phil Jackson and Scott
Skiles, recite what you expect coaches to recite after a 105-77
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We committed too many turnovers (23) to win,'' says Skiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to play with good energy at both ends of the court
after a slow start,'' says Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Etc., etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal appears, and says his slow start against the
Suns might be traced to a dramatic change in his evening sleeping
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to bed last night at 11 o'clock, and I haven't gone to
bed that early in eight years,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I ask O'Neal how he feels when he hears the crowd start
chanting, ``MVP! MVP! MVP!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel good,'' he says. ``It makes me feel as though
I've been doing a good job. It's a nice accolade to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerry Buss' private lounge later, Bill Bertka, the venerable
assistant coach, is waxing poetic about Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Shaq continues to improve, he's going to become the best
big man ever,'' he says. ``I think he has the potential to do more
things better than all the other great big men.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson is seated at a table nearby, conversing with a
friend as he carefully nurses a glass of red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson tells me he's living in Playa del Rey, and I ask him how
he likes Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great,'' he says. ``The weather's been great. The
people have been great. The team's been great. What's there to
complain about?''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
