<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-AUCTION-ART-NYT &LR;      05-08 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONET AND CAILLEBOTTE, NOT SCANDAL, STAR IN SEASON'S FIRST BIG
AUCTION
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was an air of curiosity at Christie's on Monday
night as the first big evening sale of the spring got under way.
Not only was it the first sale since the federal antitrust
investigation of Christie's and Sotheby's heated up, but it was
also the first auction since both companies raised the fees they
charge buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Many works sold for far less than their low estimates, but sell
they did. All but five of the 47 works on offer found buyers. The
sale totaled $104.5 million, just above its low estimate of $101
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockefeller Center salesroom was packed with the usual
faces: dealers and collectors who gather twice a year to watch
which way the art market will go. While the sale had moments when
prices soared far above anybody's expectations, many works sold for
far below their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, experts said, had little to do with either the
investigation or the new buyer's premium. When Christie's put the
sale together month ago, there were no major estates, and as a
result they had to convince sellers that now was the right time to
get top dollar for their art. Christie's also had what dealers call
``the Phillips factor.'' With Bernard Arnault, the new owner of
Phillips, offering sellers large sums to compete with Sotheby's and
Christie's, estimates became more aggressive than they might have
otherwise been.
</P>
<P>
   By the day of the auction, however, Christie's had a good idea
of where prices were going and cleverly persuaded sellers to drop
their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   By far the evening's biggest success was for Caillebotte's ``Man
on the Balcony, Boulevard Haussmann'' (1880), which depicts a man
who experts think was the artist's lawyer, Albert Courtier, shaded
by a red-and-white awning, looking out at the boulevard from the
balcony of Caillebotte's Paris apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Seven bidders tried to buy the painting, which had been
estimated at $6 million to $8 million. It eventually sold for $14.3
million to Simon de Pury, the former chairman of Sotheby's in
Europe, who is now a private dealer and was bidding on behalf of a
collector. The price was a record for Caillebotte, seven times his
previous record of $2 million, set at Christie's in London in 1989
at the height of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department investigation, which came to wide
attention when two top officials at Sotheby's resigned in February,
centers on whether the leadership of Sotheby's Christie's colluded
to set commissions they charge buyers and sellers. While those
allegations had certainly registered in the minds of those present
at the auction, most drew a firm distinction between the
behind-the-scenes scandal and the art on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pictures that people are interested in,'' said Rodney
Hawes, a 40-something retiree who arrived early to scout the field.
``The antitrust stuff has nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another buyer was even more adamant. A 47-year-old bidder from
London, who spoke on condition on anonymity, said, ``Anybody who
doesn't bid or bids less on a painting they love and want for their
collection because of some investigation is insane.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening's most expensive painting was one of the greatest
examples of Monet's ``Waterlily'' series, painted by the lily pond
behind the artist's house in Giverny, outside Paris. This one, from
1906, has been in the same unidentified private collection for more
than 85 years and is in pristine condition. Estimated at $20
million to $25 million, it sold to an unidentified telephone bidder
for $20.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include Christie's commission, 17.5 percent of the
first $80,000 plus 10 percent of any amount above that. Estimates
do not reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   Another Monet that received considerable attention was
``Windmills in Holland,'' an 1871 landscape that captured the
artist's talent for capturing flickering reflections of light on
water. It sold for $3 million, its low estimate, to an unidentified
telephone bidder. The painting came from the estate of Guy
Bjorkman, a businessman who divided his time between Manhattan and
Geneva before his death last year. Also being sold from his estate
was an 1890 Toulouse-Lautrec portrait of a woman known only as
Berthe the Deaf. This was one of the evening's biggest casualties.
Estimated at $6 million to $8 million, nobody raised a paddle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
