<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEILS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST DEVILS, IT IS SIX AND OUT FOR THE LEAFS  

</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils ignored failures of the past
in dominating the Toronto Maple Leafs, 3-0, Monday night to win
their second-round series in six games and reach the Eastern
Conference finals for the first time since capturing the Stanley
Cup in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The last three times the Devils had led a four-of-seven-game
series, 3-2, they had lost twice, including last season against the
Penguins and in 1994 to the Rangers. Judging by the way they Devils
played at Continental Arena Monday night, they didn't forget those
failures. They allowed just six shots on goal _ the fewest allowed
in the playoffs or regular season since expansion in 1967 _ and
took the lead just 18 seconds into the game. With Scott Stevens
leading the way, they were more physical and dominated all parts of
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' hits on Tomas Kaberle and Kevyn Adams Saturday night in
Toronto most likely reverberated in Monday night's encounter. Those
two crunching open-ice hits by the Devils' captain were reminiscent
of his thunderous hit on Detroit's Slava Kozlov in the second game
of the Stanley Cup finals in 1995, when the Devils swept the Red
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's our captain,'' said John Madden, a rookie
center, who has been playing with a high level of intensity in the
playoffs. ``He's always given us a lift, whether scoring goals or
making hits like that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Martin Brodeur earned his second shutout of the playoffs
and eighth of his playoff career, the defense and the physical
players did their part. In addition, Petr Sykora and Jason Arnott
scored against Curtis Joseph in the early stages of the first and
second periods. Madden's empty-net goal with six seconds left iced
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs failed to convert on their two power plays
Monday night, leaving them 0 for 20 in this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils will face the winner of the Philadelphia-Pittsburgh
series, which the Flyers are leading, 3-2. Game 6 is in Pittsburgh
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora put the Devils on the right track 18 seconds into the
game when he dug out the puck in a crowd in front of Joseph for his
fourth goal of these playoffs. The goal came after Patrik Elias
kicked the puck from behind the goal to the right of Joseph on a
play that started with Arnott keeping the puck near Joseph the
first time the Devils entered Toronto's zone.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott scored the Devils' second goal 25 seconds into the second
period. This time it was Sykora who made the pass from behind the
goal.Arnott, who was in the slot to take the pass, scored his
second goal of the playoffs. The sequence started with Ken Daneyko
keeping the puck in Toronto's zone.
</P>
<P>
   Sarcastic chants of ``Cu-jo, Cu-jo'' for Toronto's goaltender
and patriotic chants of ``U.S.A., U.S.A.'' shortly after Arnott's
goal echoed throughout Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd gave Stevens and the Devils a standing ovation
midway through the third period when Stevens crushed Tie Domi,
Toronto's main policeman, with an open-ice hit midway as the Maple
Leaf entered the Devils' zone.
</P>
<P>
   With the privilege of making the last change, Robinson
maintained the line of Bobby Holik, Sergei Brylin and Randy McKay
for almost the entire game. Holik was so effective against Mats
Sundin that the captain of the Maple Leafs even took a roughing
penalty against Holik.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive pairing against Sundin's line was Stevens and
Brian Rafalski. And for the sixth time in the series, they played
so well it inspired the rest of the Devils to raise their game to a
higher level.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who took 27 shots on goal, were so effective
defensively in the first two periods that they allowed five shots
in the 40 minutes, including just two in the second period. The
defensive play of Madden and Jay Pandolfo was particularly
inspiring for the Devils; it bordered on brilliance in shutting
down the Maple Leafs' second manpower advantage.
</P>
<P>
   After a team meeting Monday, Daneyko, the defenseman who has
played in all of the Devils' 118 playoff games, recalled the
Devils' previous postseason failures. ``You don't forget those
things,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
