<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DISCIPLINE STARTS BEHIND THE BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It's not quite seven weeks since Larry
Robinson took command as their coach, but in the Devils' sudden
success, it seems like seven years.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23 the Devils still had the best overall record in the
Eastern Conference of the National Hockey League, but they were in
a 5-10-2 slump. Lou Lamoriello, their prescient president and
general manager, judged that the team had lost what he called its
``ice discipline.'' So he sacked Robbie Ftorek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we were playing,'' Lamoriello said at the time, ``I
didn't see the light at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Devils now halfway through the long dark Stanley
Cup tunnel, Lamoriello can see the light.
</P>
<P>
   In playing a virtually perfect game Tuesday night, the Devils
moved into the conference finals with a 3-0 shutout that limited
the Toronto Maple Leafs to only six shots on net _ the lowest
one-game total in either the regular schedule or the playoffs since
the NHL began to keep that statistic in its 1967-1968 expansion
season.
</P>
<P>
   Only six shots on net. That's now the symbol of how Larry
Robinson, in his firm and fatherly manner over the last seven
weeks, has restored the Devils' ``ice discipline'' established by
Coach Jacques Lemaire in the 1995 Stanley Cup triumph when Robinson
was an assistant coach. And maybe even improved on Lemaire's
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry keeps reminding us,'' said Scott Stevens, the Devils'
captain, ``that once we stop and play a simple game, we're a much
better hockey team. He's got our forwards doing a fantastic job of
checking. That's how Dallas won the cup last year; their forwards
were unbelievable. And that's how we've been able to limit the
opposing shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Daneyko, who has seen eight coaches come and go in his 15
seasons as a Devils defenseman, appreciated the way Robinson
simplifies strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an honest guy, a straight shooter,'' Daneyko said. ``Some
coaches go on and on for half an hour with Xs and Os, but the
players' attention span is never that long. Larry can get it done
in three minutes. He's a great translator. He can explain it and
simplify it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daneyko thought Robinson has a ``toughness'' he didn't possess
in four frustrating seasons as the Los Angeles Kings coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us a kick in the butt when we need it,'' Daneyko
said. ``He did it in the Florida series and he did it after the
opener in Toronto when we thought we had played well even though we
didn't win. He reminded us that if we didn't win, we didn't play
well enough.''
</P>
<P>
   During a game, you'll see Robinson talking quietly to a player,
sometimes patting a shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discipline starts behind the bench and Larry is very cool back
there,'' Stevens said. ``If you see your coach jumping around, you
tend to get excited too. I've always liked a coach who stays calm,
who coaches the game and stays off the refs. Larry's calm and he
keeps the players the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long before Ftorek was fired, he was suspended for one game
for throwing part of the Devils' bench on the ice to protest a
referee's call.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is different. When a scrum broke out between goaltender
Martin Brodeur and Maple Leaf forward Darcy Tucker as the Devils'
4-3 victory ended Saturday night in Toronto, the Devils coach made
sure none of his players on the bench left the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want any of our people being suspended,'' he
explained, ``over something silly like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 20 solid seasons with the Montreal Canadiens as a Hall of
Fame defenseman, Robinson was considered hockey's heavyweight
champion when a fight developed, but he was never a goon. He earned
six Stanley Cup rings, including four in a row from 1976 to 1979,
but for all his glory, he was always humble. And he's humble now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about me,'' he said. ``It's about those 24 guys
that have been here since September. They're the guys out there
sweating and bleeding. All I do is point them in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   That direction is toward the other end of the long dark Stanley
Cup tunnel. Only time will tell if the Devils can get through that
tunnel to a Summer of partying with Lord Stanley's silver chalice,
but at least Lou Lamoriello can see the light. So can the Devils
and so can their seven-week miracle-worker, Larry Robinson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
