<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODEN FALTERS AGAINST YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Veteran baseball people called him the greatest young
pitcher they had ever seen when he was 19 years old. But at 35,
Dwight Gooden is hanging on, accepting opportunity from any team
willing to extend it to him.
</P>
<P>
   He signed a minor league deal with the Houston Astros before
spring training _ National Association, not National League _ and
after one start of four innings for the pitching-starved Astros, he
was sold to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. Now Gooden is pitching for
his hometown team and is 10 victories short of 200.
</P>
<P>
   But those 10 might seem like 10,000 to Gooden when he has games
like Monday night's, in which he was pasted in a 6-3 loss to the
Yankees, his first regular-season start against the team he pitched
a no-hitter for in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, Clay Bellinger and Paul O'Neill hit home runs for
the Yankees. Andy Pettitte (2-1) threw six and one-third impressive
innings, and Mariano Rivera bounced back from his worst outing of
the season to earn his 12th save in a seven-pitch ninth inning. The
Yankees have 9 victories in their last 11 games and are 21-9.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, who won a Cy Young award with the Mets 15 years ago,
pitched for the Cleveland Indians the last two years but never
pitched against the Yankees during the regular season, because the
rotation didn't fall right, because he was injured or because
Manager Mike Hargrove was afraid of pitching him against the
Yankees, believing Gooden's emotions might overcome him.
</P>
<P>
   But Gooden probably needed as much emotion as possible Monday
night to overcome his lack of raw stuff. He threw 33 pitches in the
first inning, and the Yankee hitters did not swing and miss one
time. They swung with gusto, windmill hacks, as if they knew the
precise identity and location of the next pitch. Bernie Williams
crushed a high drive down the right-field line in the inning, a
ball hit so hard that even if you had your eyes closed, you would
have known it was going to travel a very long way.
</P>
<P>
   That drive hooked foul, barely, Williams running all the way to
first base, thinking it would stay fair, before he jerked his head
in dismay. Gooden's fate appeared all but assured, even with the
game scoreless. He had nothing with which to combat the Yankee
hitters, no good fastball or curve, not much control. He was going
to take a beating.
</P>
<P>
   Williams drew a walk, with Ricky Ledee already standing on
second base, and Gooden fell behind Martinez three balls and no
strikes. Martinez took one strike before blistering the next pitch
into the upper deck in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte gave the lead back over the second and third innings,
while falling into the pattern of trying to throw almost every
pitch inside to right-handed hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays' batters adjusted, Jose Canseco and Bubba
Trammell and others moving backward in the batter's box as they
swung and pulling Pettitte's pitches. Canseco stepped back and
slammed a double with two out in the third, driving home Gerald
Williams with the tying run. But Pettitte started pitching to both
sides of the plate in the fourth, fanning Kevin Stocker on a
fastball over the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough time for the Yankees to finish Gooden once and
for all. Gooden tried blowing a high fastball past Bellinger, but
Bellinger measured it perfectly, hammering it straight back over
Gooden's head, over the head of Gerald Williams in center field,
over the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden retreated behind the mound to rub a new baseball, his
mouth pursed, sweat pouring down his cheeks and forehead.
</P>
<P>
   He climbed back up the mound, and after issuing another walk, he
attempted to spin a curve low to O'Neill. But O'Neill bent over,
like someone playing croquet on a warm spring evening, and lined
the ball into the right-field stands, a two-run homer. Gooden won
two of his first three starts for the Devil Rays, the 189th and
190th victories of his career, but his night was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Rothschild took the ball from him, and as Gooden
reached the Devil Ray dugout, teammates reached out to shake his
hand and slap him on the back, an unusual reaction, considering
that the Yankees had just pounded him for six runs on six hits and
four walks over four and a third innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
