<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-HARDAWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORE FOOT MAY MAKE HARDAWAY AN EASY MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One shoe was off, temporarily easing the discomfort in
Tim Hardaway's sprained left foot after the Miami Heat's 90-minute
practice Monday. The pressure on Hardaway, though, is expected to
be more intense on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Like a boxer targeting an opponent's bleeding wound, Hardaway
believes the Knicks will force him to defend more often against
penetration by the point guards in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway almost rolled over on his ankle trying to defend the
Knicks' Charlie Ward, who blew by him on a nifty fake and crossover
move in the third quarter of Game 1 on Sunday. Hardaway left the
court immediately and missed seven minutes while having his ankle
retaped in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll put the ball on the floor and drive more to see if I'm
able to stay with it,'' Hardaway said. ``I'd do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who said he was 80 to 85 percent, had 6 points, 7
assists and 1 rebound in 30 minutes in Game 1. In four
regular-season meetings against the Knicks, he averaged 15.3
points, 7.8 assists, 3.8 rebounds and 37.5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need to make any adjustments against me,'' Hardaway
said. ``I really didn't do anything. Hopefully, I'll be able to
play the same minutes I did Sunday and make a few more shots.
Mostly, I just want to be out there and be aggressive and lead my
team. I know I won't be able to do certain moves. But I know I'm
helping because I'm still a threat out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway's presence kept the Knicks' attention on the perimeter
and away from double-teaming Alonzo Mourning down low. Defensively,
Hardaway will be a liability if either Chris Childs or Ward
exploits his injured foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``One leg or arm, I still want him out there,'' Mourning said.
``He still has a huge effect on our play.'' Riley's Viewpoint
</P>
<P>
   After spending 90 minutes reviewing videotapes of Game 1, Heat
Coach Pat Riley offered the same analysis he did Sunday: the Heat's
defense was strong, but the Knicks, particularly Larry Johnson (4
of 9) and Latrell Sprewell (4 of 12), did not shoot well in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson scored 6 of his 8 points in the first four minutes, but
disappeared in the fourth, missing the one shot he took _ an open
24-footer _ with 1 minute 11 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell sank two free throws in final minute, but clanked his
only two field-goal attempts. Neither player seemed in sync with
the offense down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major adjustment we've got to make is in some certain
situations where they had open shots and just didn't make them,''
Riley said. ``We can't expect that to happen again. Even though we
won, it was still very unclear. We can't sit idly by and think we
caused them to miss those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley also seemed more concerned about containing Sprewell,
Johnson and Allan Houston than he did about stopping Patrick Ewing,
who had 17 points and 9 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked a little stiff when he fell down a few times,''
Riley said. ``But he had a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley also pointed to turnovers and the Heat's shot selection in
the fourth quarter. ``We only took three or four bad shots and had
zero turnovers,'' Riley said. ``For us, that's rare. We took care
of the ball when it mattered most.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had one fewer turnover than the Heat (13-12), but
committed five turnovers in the fourth quarter. The Camby Factor
</P>
<P>
   The Heat's P.J. Brown wondered why the Knicks did not play
Marcus Camby as much as _ or more than _ Larry Johnson in Game 1.
In 27 minutes, Camby scored 11 points on 4-of-5 shooting and
grabbed 13 rebounds. In 39 minutes, Johnson had 8 points and 6
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different story if they play Camby more,'' Brown said.
``It means a lot more work for me. If you can get a body on him and
hurt his activeness, you can contain him. But it's not that
easy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
