<SLUG> BC-NY-MONOXIDE-DEATHS-264-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURNACE'S LINK TO AIR CONDITIONER KILLED 6 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSLYN HEIGHTS, N.Y. _ A Long Island doctor who returned home
Sunday morning after working the late shift knew right away that he
had made a ghastly mistake, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   When Dr. Andrei Kranz, 42, opened his door, he found six family
members and friends dead in bed, all in their nightclothes. Among
them were his parents and his 3-year-old daughter. He tried to
resuscitate them and failed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the moment the doctor saw the bodies he
suspected carbon monoxide poisoning. He told the police that he had
disconnected a carbon monoxide detector last summer because the
alarm was constantly going off, keeping him and his family from
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was indeed accidental carbon monoxide
intoxication, said Diane Makunas, a spokeswoman for the county
medical examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The furnace and the air-conditioning system are both in a closed
basement room of Kranz's home. The exhaust vent for the
air-conditioner was closed and its intake filter was clogged. As
the heat turned oppressive on Friday afternoon, someone in the
house turned on the air-conditioning without turning off the
furnace, the police said. With no other source of air, the
conditioner pulled in the furnace fumes, cooled them and sent the
fumes throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were Kranz's parents, Marcus Kranz, 85, and Victoria
Kranz, 74; his daughter; a live-in nanny, Emelia Dumtru, 58; and
two house guests, Dr. Emil Campeanu, 75, and his wife, Maria, 68,
of Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Kranz's wife, Anka, and stepdaughter were in Romania, family
friends said.
</P>
</TEXT>
