<HEADER>
A9669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-STRATEGY-N     05-08 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY'S STRATEGY LACKED ONLY A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It only took one game for Jeff Van Gundy to go from the
genius who produced the blueprint to stop Vince Carter to the
second-guessed coach who left Marcus Camby on the bench at the end
of Sunday's Game 1 loss in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, Marcus, I thought, played very well,'' Van Gundy said
Monday, put in a position to defend himself after Camby had 11
points and 13 rebounds but did not play the last four minutes of
the game. ``But I really do believe we went down the stretch in
those three games against Toronto the same way and got the same
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Larry Johnson did not hit the open 3-pointer to win
the game. On Sunday, with 1 minute 11 seconds remaining, Johnson
was left open but rushed his shot and left it well off the side of
the rim. If he had made the 3-pointer, the Knicks would have had a
1-point lead and the outcome might have been different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset every time something doesn't work, and it didn't
work,'' Van Gundy said. ``So believe me, you guys aren't the first
to evaluate me, I do it for myself. When it doesn't work, you made
the wrong decision as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about Marcus being on a roll. I thought that was our
best unit to finish with in Game 1. I thought Marcus played well. I
thought Larry played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players, like Latrell Sprewell, wondered about Van Gundy's
strategy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Marcus is playing like that, he definitely needs to play,
but it's up to Jeff to decide that, though,'' said Sprewell, who
noted that he talked to Camby after the game and found his teammate
discouraged. ``We talked. But Marcus isn't the type, at this point,
to pout or anything like that. We're all about winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just understands that Jeff wants him to come off
the bench. Obviously, I think Marcus probably would rather start.
And like I've said, we all want to play as many minutes as
possible. But we have so much talent, that's a difficult thing for
Jeff to go back and forth with. I think Marcus understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Camby was very accepting of his role in Game 1. He
didn't complain or question his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just play in the concept of the team and within my game,''
he said. ``If it is coming out in the last five minutes, so be it.
The guys who are out there on the court are definitely money
players. Larry is a proven big-time player, as we saw last
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Toronto, an open 3-pointer for Johnson sealed Van Gundy
from the second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that ball swings to Larry and he makes it, everyone is
talking about something else today,'' Van Gundy said. ``People want
to make it out to be a complicated issue. But if you make your
shots, like we did in Toronto, it covers up the mistakes. If you
miss down the stretch, they aren't covered up as much.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
