<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BUILDING A RESUME ON PERSEVERANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ He was cut by Pat Riley, renounced by Rick
Pitino and traded by Larry Brown. On perseverance alone, you have
to love Bruce Bowen's resume.
</P>
<P>
   His last pit stop before his current tour of duty, his third,
with the Miami Heat? Bowen spent two days with the worst team in
the Eastern Conference. Then the Chicago Bulls released him.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to be told by three of the game's alleged
miracle workers that they like your talent and desire but you no
longer fit into their salary cap or roster plans.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls? As if they can't give you a decent run before the
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   You expect Bowen to nod his head with I-told-you-so
satisfaction, take a thinly veiled shot at everyone who served him
his walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the player who appeared on the New York sports radar on
Sunday in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference semifinals against the
Knicks _ the rangy 6-foot-7-inch swingman who put a hand in Allan
Houston's face, steered Latrell Sprewell toward the Heat front line
and made an important 3-pointer in Miami's victory _ folded his
arms and allowed a half-smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the business,'' he said Monday in the LaSalle High
School gymnasium, where the Heat prepared for Game 2 on Tuesday
night. ``I felt like I would play somewhere. It was just a matter
of when.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your perspective, Bowen either arrived at the right
place at the right time for Miami or else the Knicks were literally
in the wrong place at the wrong time when he became available.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy wanted Bowen badly for his ability
to come off the bench to defend big guards aggressively. But the
Heat claimed Bowen off waivers on Feb. 23 because of a quirk of
timing. Under National Basketball Association rules, teams with
inferior records get to claim players before those with better
records. Feb. 23 happened to be one of only two days all season
that the Knicks were in sole possession of first place in the
Atlantic Division, ahead of the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of good fortune that goes into this,'' Van Gundy
said. ``Everyone knows we wanted him, but it's just how it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen is not a franchise player, but he is one of those
athletic, long-limbed guys who make defenses better. He played 12
of the most efficient minutes off the Miami bench on Sunday, coming
in to guard Houston and switching to Sprewell when Marcus Camby
replaced Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Released by Riley after spending one week in training camp with
Miami in 1995, Bowen was brought back for a month at the close of
the 1996-97 season. He played in one game, and Riley did not
re-sign him. Bowen also played for Pitino in Boston for two seasons
before moving to Philadelphia last season.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers, who liked him, shipped Bowen to Chicago to make
financial room for Toni Kukoc in the three-team trade with the
Golden State Warriors on Feb. 16. Bowen made it out of Chicago and
into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God is moving in my life,'' he said. ``I'm a faithful
person. It's not the peaches and cream in this league that a lot of
people feel. It takes a lot of prayer and a lot of faith just to
get by.''
</P>
<P>
   His big-picture perspective and likable demeanor helped his
cause. There is more to Bowen than merely Cut by Riley and Traded
by Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in a tough neighborhood in Fresno, Calif., and turned
down many opportunities to join the gang life, which claimed three
of his cousins. Bowen went on to star at Cal State-Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen was not drafted by the NBA, but he never got down about
his journeyman plight. He viewed his playing for five teams in
three years as valuable experience and tried not to focus on the
rejections. When Riley first released him, Bowen thought it was
cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed,'' he said. ``It was my first actual league
experience. Coming out of college, you don't ever think about the
business side of everything. But I called and told him I
appreciated the opportunity. I think that kind of caught him off
guard, because so many guys leave without saying anything.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, with so many tall shooting guards carving up his
team, Riley was happy to rehire Bowen. ``He basically said, `We
like your defense on the big guards in this league,''' Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said after Game 1: ``When Allan and Latrell Sprewell stare
you in the eyes, some players get pretty defensive. Bruce is the
opposite. He and Dan Majerle get after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen is unsure how he will try to help contain Sprewell and
Houston for the rest of the series, but he already has a fairly
comprehensive scouting report laid out.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he needs is a little space to get up,'' Bowen said of
Houston. ``He can penetrate and kick, penetrate and pull up. You
have to try and limit him with his air space and hopefully force
him to beat you with the drive, if that's what you're trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``And with Spree, he's great driving the ball, and he can shoot
the ball as well. But he likes to take the ball to the basket more.
When I move over to Spree, I have to think about the tendencies
Spree may have and try to disrupt those a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen is not likely to put up big numbers this week. But he will
flail his arms and move his feet as fast as he can, trying to
defuse the grand arsenal of Houston and Sprewell, building his
resume one stop at a time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
