<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEW ERA BRINGS MORE OFFENSE AND FANS TO BALLPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop. Just stop. Cease and desist. Enough already. Let the
concern and consternation over the increase in home runs and runs
end here and now. Instead of tearing out the hair and gnashing the
teeth, sit back and relax and enjoy what we have. It's a new era
for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened before. The advent of Babe Ruth marked the
beginning of an era that made baseball the country's sport of
choice. Without Ruth and the home runs he produced, baseball would
have withered and died eons ago. If an escalation of the Ruthian
experience is occurring now, let it be. Don't look for ways to
stifle it.
</P>
<P>
   Fans evidently don't find fault with the outbreak of scoring.
They may attend games this season in record numbers. That possible
development is what Major League Baseball anticipates, at least, so
why would anyone want to do anything to take away from the fans
something they appear to like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans are enjoying it,'' Commissioner Bud Selig said
Monday. ``Did we design this? No. We aren't that smart. We ought to
watch it and analyze it, but is it necessarily bad? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday night about 39,000 fans sat at The Ballpark in
Arlington and watched a game that could become the signature event
of the new era. Oakland led Texas, 15-7, after six and a half
innings, but the Rangers won the game, 17-16, scoring 10 runs in
the last three innings. The fans who were there were ecstatic and
will talk about the game for months, if not years, to come. No one
asked for his money back. It was 4 hours 1 minute of great
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The purists, of course, cringed. The purists, however, are not
paying the players' inflated salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Teams played 457 games in the first five weeks of the season.
They averaged 10.76 runs and 2.59 home runs a game. Pitchers
compiled a 4.96 earned run average in that period.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists suspect that the ball has been doctored to
make it easier for batters to hit it out of the park. The fact is
home runs and runs have increased nearly every year since the first
of two expansions that added four teams in the 1990s. In 1992, the
year before the first expansion, teams averaged 8.39 runs and 1.45
home runs a game, and pitchers compiled a 3.80 ERA in the first 457
games.
</P>
<P>
   With the postexpansion proliferation of scoring and home run
hitting, new standards have to be established. The new era, for
example, needs a new ERA. A 3.00 earned run average used to be
considered good for a pitcher. With the average ERA up by about a
third, that standard has to be raised to 4.00. Last season the
American League had only eight starting pitchers at 4.00 or lower.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers are the players who are affected most adversely in the
new era. For the most part, they are fodder for hitters who have
become stronger and in parks that have become smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Halladay is supposed to be a good young pitcher for Toronto,
but in seven starts this season he has an 11.53 ERA Jose Lima, a
21-game winner for Houston last year, has a 9.53 ERA in seven
starts and has been battered for a major league-high 16 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   It is middle relief pitchers, though, who deserve hazard pay for
their efforts. With pitching staffs short on talent generally, if
the starter is knocked out early, his departure triggers a parade
of ineffective relievers who should still be learning their craft
in the minor leagues or who never demonstrated enough ability to
pitch in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Tanyon Sturtze is a reliever for the White Sox whose
professional career spanned the 1990's. In that decade, he spent
all but 110 playing days in the minors. Relieving for the White Sox
this season, he has a 13.03 ERA in eight appearances covering nine
and two-thirds innings &UR; . &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR;  Home run standards, too, must be raised because of inflation.
From 1976 until 1995, excluding the strike seasons of 1981 and
1994, the American and National League home run champions averaged
42 home runs. In the last five seasons, their successors have hit
an average of 53 home runs a year. Using that 26 percent inflation
rate, if 30 home runs had been considered a benchmark for sluggers,
that number should now be at least 38, if not 40.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's new era, however, has not eliminated low-scoring
games. This season has already produced seven 1-0 games and 14 2-1
games. Boston has lost a pair of 1-0 decisions; Los Angeles
suffered two 1-0 losses in consecutive games with different teams.
Cleveland lost two consecutive 2-1 games to different teams. The
Mets have won three 2-1 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Each day or set of days can still produce vastly different
results. Colorado scored 43 runs in three games against Montreal
last week, then went to San Francisco and was shut out twice in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   A premium is placed on good pitching more than ever in the new
era. But the success of Pedro Martinez (1.22), Randy Johnson
(0.93), Tom Glavine (1.73) and some others shows that hitters
haven't assumed command completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are Pedro Martinez and Randy Johnson using a different ball?''
Selig asked. ``Of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials are nevertheless studying developments in the
new era. They are having the balls tested, they will go to Costa
Rica and tour the Rawlings factory where the balls are made, they
will study bats, they are considering raising the mound in a couple
of rookie minor leagues to see what effect such a change could have
on hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Officials met Monday with Rawlings people, who for the 972nd
time vowed that they had made no change in the balls. If that is
so, let the new era continue and take baseball wherever Mark
McGwire and friends lead it. Just leave a few 1-0 games around for
old times' sake. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
