<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-ASSESS-820(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A SINGULAR FUNERAL FOR A SINGULAR MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ The funeral fit the man. And of course the city too.
It was majestic, sacramental, solemn, prayerful. That was
uppermost. But it didn't lack a touch of the ticker-tape parade
either, and more than a touch of in-your-face political
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has so much political, moral and cultural explosiveness
been put into such proximity as in the first few pews of St.
Patrick's Cathedral on Monday, where President Clinton and Hillary
Rodham Clinton knelt with Vice President Gore, the Bush dynasty,
father and son, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Gov. George Pataki,
Secretary General Kofi Annan of the United Nations and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright. There were two former mayors, Edward Koch
and David Dinkins, and _ well, the idea is clear. Draw all the
lines of alliance, rivalry, anger and affection among those
individuals and the results would be as messy as a child's
scribble.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cardinal John O'Connor, along with the importance of New
York City, who brought all those leaders there. One suspects that
he would have been delighted and his mischievous sense of humor set
working overtime.
</P>
<P>
   If this was a national event for a national religious leader, it
was also an international event for a major figure in an
international church. There were five Roman Catholic cardinals from
overseas plus the two Americans, Cardinal William Baum and Cardinal
Edmund Szoka, who work in Rome. No less than Cardinal Angelo
Sodano, the Vatican secretary of state, celebrated the Mass. To go
any higher it would have had to be the pope himself.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a personal event, reflecting O'Connor himself. There
was his signature emphasis on what the church calls its defense of
life, with opposition to abortion and euthanasia at its core, but
fleshed out to include international peacemaking, the rights of
workers, the poor and the sick, and the condemnation of capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In O'Connor's style, Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston was utterly
direct with this message _ no matter how uncomfortable he might be
making a group of political leaders, virtually none of whom could
qualify as ``unambiguously pro life'' by the standards spelled out
in the Boston prelate's homily.
</P>
<P>
   Very visible at the funeral and frequently mentioned was another
of O'Connor's typically personal initiatives, the founding of the
Sisters of Life, an order of nuns who devote themselves to the
cause largely through prayer but also service to women in need.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cardinal's request that the Mass not be a tribute to
him, his profile and personality loomed so large as to put all else
in the shadows; the other nuns and priests, the lay workers and
active parishioners, the vast New York Catholic church of parishes
and neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago died in November 1996,
his funeral had gospel music and singing in Polish and Spanish
along with Gregorian chant. It had brief prayers offered by lay
people in many of the archdiocese's languages. The homily was
delivered not by a high official but a local priest, the cardinal's
longtime aide.
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple fact of geography, not of anyone's planning,
that Bernardin was buried with his predecessors in a cemetery 15
miles from his cathedral. The cortege drove through the
archdiocese's city streets, far from downtown and past churches and
schools and saloons and used car lots, too, and past clusters of
construction workers doffing their hard hats, elderly folks braving
the November drizzle and schoolchildren waving signs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, by contrast, was buried within his own cathedral,
smack in the middle of Manhattan. The journey was entirely within
the cathedral and surrounded by men in vestments. It was a moving
moment when the magnificent choir had completed its Latin chant of
``May the angels escort you into paradise,'' and then the
worshipers gave the cardinal a final volley of applause before the
coffin was carried down to the crypt.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some who belong to the New York church of parish bazaars and
religious education classes and Altar and Rosary Societies were
pressing against the police barriers across Fifth Avenue, but most,
one supposed, had to watch on television.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yet the funeral did not always seem to float above and beyond
this New York church in a realm of Vatican influence, national
politics and the New York's leader's very special concerns. The
service could come suddenly down to earth in the way that O'Connor
often did, the way so frequently mentioned during the last week,
with personal attention to a specific individual.
</P>
<P>
   When, at the very end of the service, Baum thanked several
people who had helped O'Connor to the end, he did not stop with
family and aides but went on to one of the most faithful but least
known of the workers, Maura O'Kelly, who oversaw the cardinal's
residence as she had for his two predecessors. O'Connor would have
been delighted with that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
