<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LAND OF SOUND BITES, EMRICK IS A MOUTHFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For five years, Mike Emrick enriched Fox's coverage of the
National Hockey League. But for its NHL games this season, and the
next four, ABC chose to use ESPN's voices, and not to employ
Emrick.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Emrick out was expected because of the ABC-ESPN
corporate connection. But not having Emrick means that ABC's No. 1
hockey voice is not the absolute best.
</P>
<P>
   Emrick's skills remain on display during Devils games on Fox
Sports New York. His play-by-play is smooth, clear, linguistically
absorbing and as grammatically sharp as it is possible to be at
hockey's pace.
</P>
<P>
   In one 22-second sound bite late in Game 5 of the Devils-Toronto
playoff series Saturday night, Emrick showed his vocal dexterity.
With the Devils leading, 3-2, with 6 minutes 15 seconds left in the
game, Emrick said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a shot fought off by Niedermayer. Niedermayer hugs the
boards. It's Thomas. The pass behind is cut off by Stevens and
dumped along for Claude Lemieux. Shoots it along. Kaberle tried to
play it further. Niedermayer's stick knocked out of his hand, so
it's shillelaghed back out again by Stevens. Brought on by
Pandolfo. To Madden. Madden, cruising in, fires! Score!''
</P>
<P>
   Emrick calls radio on TV, and unintrusive camera work is the
best way to illustrate that. In a telecast with action as ferocious
as Saturday's was in its final minutes, the FSNY director Joe
O'Rourke rarely strayed from the game camera mounted high at center
ice.
</P>
<P>
   To bring viewers closer to the game, it has become fashionable
in live hockey for directors to jump to close-ups, low-angle corner
shots or the cameras from above the goals. Each option holds
potential rewards to jazz up the telecast but risks losing sight of
the puck, a developing three-on-two rush or linear perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, if I feel I'm winning the gambles, I do it, but if
I'm losing, I back off,'' O'Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the right conservative direction was needed, Emrick's
words found almost perfect accompaniment. Four quick cuts were made
from four minutes left in the third period until 2:50 remained.
From that point until 17 seconds were left _ a patch with
relentless action and no stoppages _ FSNY never shifted live from
the center-ice roost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game dictated that,'' O'Rourke said. ``When it's flying
like that, all you can do is make people mad by cutting away. I
couldn't see the sense in guessing where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, however, FSNY's center-ice perch at Continental
Arena seemed like the worst way to watch the Devils-Toronto series.
ESPN, CBC, the Canadian network, and SRC, the French-language
broadcaster, got preferred space in the traditional center-ice
position on the arena's first tier, pushing FSNY up a level, which
brought vertigo to hockey viewing. By the next game in New Jersey,
two nights later, FSNY had reclaimed a lower position. &QL; 
Missed Shots, Cheap Shots
</P>
<P>
   The last few minutes of Game 1 of the Knicks-Miami National
Basketball Association playoff series on Sunday on NBC offered less
verbal clarity than FSNY provided during the Devils-Maple Leafs
game.
</P>
<P>
   You had to wonder what Bill Walton, an NBC analyst, meant in
labeling Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy a prophet for saying the
series would come down to ``one play, one shot, one tipped ball, a
long 3 or an offensive rebound.'' Not many options left, are there?
You, too, can be a seer if you foresee every possibility but an
84-foot shot.
</P>
<P>
   Walton and Steve Jones, the co-analyst, also provided a safe
haven for Allan Houston, who too often evades criticism for his
inadequate ballhandling.
</P>
<P>
   Jones praised Houston for ``playing with control'' after hitting
the second of two jumpers, which put the Knicks ahead, 81-79. But
neither announcer said a word _ not even a ``horrible'' from Walton
_ when Houston made two turnovers, one on an ill-advised pass to
Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Walton criticized Chris Childs for flinging 3-point
shots when he should have been setting up Houston, Larry Johnson or
Latrell Sprewell, he seemed not to care enough to comment when
Childs faked a 3-pointer, then traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the NBC announcers found it easier to criticize questionable
3-point shots missed by Miami's Tim Hardaway, who is hampered by an
ankle injury. After the first of the shots, an air ball, Tom
Hammond, the play-by-play announcer asked, ``What in the world was
that about?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
