<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLSOUTH SAID TO BE IN DEAL WITH GE SATELLITE DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bidding to offer digital television service throughout the
Southeast, the BellSouth Corp. intends to announce Tuesday that it
has signed a long-term contract to purchase satellite services from
the General Electric Co., an executive close to the deal said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth had been rumored to be in discussions with Loral Space
and Communications Ltd., one of GE's rivals in the satellite
industry.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday exactly why BellSouth, the Southeast's
dominant local telephone carrier, instead choose General Electric's
Americom division. Americom, however, claims to operate North
America's biggest satellite fleet, with at least a dozen
satellites. The executive close to the deal said that GE had
committed to launching a new satellite to be used primarily by
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   While BellSouth and GE do not expect to announce financial terms
or the specific length of the contract Tuesday, BellSouth does
intend to announce plans to offer satellite television service to
the 14 million households it already serves by the first half of
2002, the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   A BellSouth spokesman and a GE spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, which recently agreed to fold its wireless telephone
unit into a joint venture with SBC Communications Inc., currently
sells television service to about 120,000 households in 11
Southeastern markets. That operation uses a combination of wired
and ground-based wireless systems, but the company apparently
believed that only satellite technology would allow BellSouth to
compete against cable television operators across the company's
region.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, SBC announced a wide-ranging marketing partnership
with DirecTV Inc., which is a subsidiary of the General Motors
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But while that deal merely allowed SBC to distribute DirecTV's
services, BellSouth seems to be taking a more hands-on approach. GE
does not currently market satellite television directly to United
States consumers. The new service will bear only the BellSouth
brand, said an executive close to the deal, adding that BellSouth
has not yet selected a contractor to manufacture the necessary
satellite dishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-CAPRI-KAN &LR;      05-08 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPRI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLE OF CAPRI CASINOS AGREES TO FINE 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven Mississippi casinos have agreed to fines totaling $1.05
million for multiple violations of anti-money-laundering reporting
requirements under federal banking laws.
</P>
<P>
   Isle of Capri Casinos Inc., which is seeking regulatory approval
to buy the Flamingo Hilton Casino in Kansas City, was among the
gambling operations cited by the U.S. Treasury Department's
Financial Crimes Enforcement Network, also known as FinCEN.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gaming Commission officials said Monday that they would
review the federal government's case against Isle of Capri in
connection with the sale, which company officials have said they
hope to close by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   According to settlement documents, all the violations were for
the casinos' failure to properly report cash transactions in excess
of $10,000 during various periods between 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A 1986 law added cash-intensive casinos to the Treasury
Department's widespread monitoring of financial institutions to
detect money laundering activities. Missouri casinos are less
vulnerable to laundering because of the state's $500 wagering loss
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Allan B. Solomon, Isle of Capri vice president and general
counsel, brushed off the fines as a minor infraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big deal,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of it was intentional. A lot of it is inadvertent
failures or not checking the right box (on forms) due to the
inexperience of employees when we first opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Isle's Biloxi casino opened in 1992 and was fined $227,500 for
44 violations during 1993. Isle's Vicksburg casino opened in 1993
and was fined $150,000 for 31 violations in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury spokeswoman said the lag time of several years from
offense to prosecution was not unusual in such cases, which
typically are uncovered during Internal Revenue Service audits.
</P>
<P>
   During the mid to late '90s, FinCEN collected more than $2
million in fines for similar reporting violations by a dozen
Atlantic City casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mississippi casinos in Gulfport, Biloxi, Natchez and
Vicksburg also were fined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9683 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SMALL-BUSINESS2TAKES-     05-08 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BUSINESS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC LEADERS WORK TO COUNTER FALL IN SMALL-BUSINESS RANKING 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JOYCE SMITH KNIGHT-RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Stung by recent research that Kansas City has
slacked off in entrepreneurial support, area business groups are
battling back.
</P>
<P>
   Cognetics Inc., a Cambridge, Mass., company that tracks
activities of 10 million businesses, recently downgraded Kansas
City's ranking as a place to start and grow a small business. The
company said its criteria for ranking the top 50 metropolitan areas
_ Kansas City fell from 14th in 1999 to 23rd _ were subjective and
difficult to measure.
</P>
<P>
   That's not good enough for the Metropolitan Entrepreneurs
Council of the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, the council has formed a task force to
examine Kansas City's entrepreneurial environment. It wants to know
what Kansas City can brag about in terms of small-business
development and define what barriers local entrepreneurs face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to say their rankings aren't any good, but in
many ways Kansas City would top the list,'' said Becky Blades,
chairwoman of the entrepreneurs council. ``We want to explore what
things make a city good for entrepreneurs, the resources that
entrepreneurs say helped them. The Kauffman Center alone represents
a resource that no other city can come close to.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Kayne, director for community initiative at the Kauffman
Center for Entrepreneurial Leadership, said Cognetics looked at
things such as quality of life, but needed to broaden its
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to look at is: What would be the measures for
Kansas City, and how can we bring those measures up?'' Kayne said.
``We're never going to have skiing in Kansas City. And yes, I miss
sailing on Chesapeake Bay. But where else can I have a
3,000-square-foot house for under $200,000?''
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 68,000 businesses in Kansas City, 98 percent are
small businesses employing fewer than 250 people. They contribute
$124 billion annually to the Kansas City economy and employ nearly
640,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has more than 80 organizations to assist those small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of people just going out and hanging up a shingle, we
are educating entrepreneurs and improving their success rate,''
Blades said. ``The challenge is to coordinate those efforts and to
let the entrepreneurs know what organizations are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's successful entrepreneurs have given back to the
business community through programs such as the Helzberg
Entrepreneurial Mentoring Program and the Kauffman Center.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 people recently attended the Energizing
Entrepreneurs 2000 small-business expo at Bartle Hall, one of the
largest such expos in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber's annual small-business luncheon Friday is among the
nation's largest and will attract 1,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just been a lot of focus on trying to serve
entrepreneurs,'' said Bill Reisler, managing director of Kansas
City Equity Partners, a venture capital firm. ``As a result, we're
getting more business starts; we're getting more activity. Out of
that, you are getting more quality teams that deserve venture
investment. Out of that, you get more successful, nationally
noticed businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Before opening Plaza Personnel Ltd. in 1997, Sharon McInerney
took the Women's Entrepreneurial Training Program at Avila College
and researched her plan for nine months at the Small Business
Administration's One Stop Capital Shop.
</P>
<P>
   She found she needed more working capital, and obtained a loan
backed by the SBA.
</P>
<P>
   McInerney continues to receive business counseling through
Johnson County Community College's Small Business Development
Center and mentoring through the SBA's Office of Women Business
Ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the business you want to start really well and are
confident about how things are going to work,'' McInerney said.
``But you need that to make a good presentation and sell that to
the banker. Some people hastily come up with an idea and expect to
put it in place in a couple of months, and it doesn't happen that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Fish, president of 4-year-old FishNet Security, took the
Kauffman Center's FastTrac entrepreneurship training program. The
global network security solutions company had 1999 revenue of $5.3
million and expects to triple that this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The class really generates a lot of thinking,'' Fish said.
``It also introduces you to business strategies of other
entrepreneurs. I recommend the program to anyone that is wanting to
start their own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Area small businesses historically have faced a lack of capital.
But that, too, is changing.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists reportedly invested a record $157 million in
area companies during the first three months of the year,
surpassing the record $143 million for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kansas City has a bit of its own inferiority
complex,'' Reisler said. ``I hear it from entrepreneurs all the
time: `You can't raise money here.' But $160 million, that's not
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Reisler said the real question was whether it's harder to get
venture capital in Kansas City than elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, with the exception of the Silicon Valley, Denver,
Austin and the Boston area, Kansas City fares pretty well,''
Reisler said. ``The amount of money vs. the amount of entrepreneurs
is a pretty good balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kayne would like to see lawyers, accountants and consultants
trading services for equity positions in start-ups, a popular
concept in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to build that culture here,'' Kayne said. ``Cash is
the most valuable asset new entrepreneurs have.''
</P>
<P>
   Area small-business experts also are concerned about the lack of
skilled labor, the availability of health insurance and the ability
to get companies up to speed in technology.
</P>
<P>
   With a low unemployment rate, area companies are having trouble
finding any workers, let alone skilled ones.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
