<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer Virus Is Traced To Apartment in Philippines
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen law enforcement agents raided a Manila
apartment from which they said a malicious computer program was
unleashed last week, disrupting computer systems around the world.
They took one resident into custody and ordered his roommate, a
woman, to turn herself in.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, including two representing the FBI, apparently
expected to find the computer from which the attack was started. A
local official said that no computer was found, but that a box
containing 17 items including telephones, wires, computer disks and
computer magazines was seized. The officials would not say what had
led them to the apartment and did not characterize the moves as
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Names Top Financial Officer
</P>
<P>
   Boeing named Michael Sears as its chief financial officer,
replacing Deborah C. Hopkins, who left after only 16 months for the
same position at Lucent Technologies. Sears, 52, has been president
of Boeing's military aircraft and missile systems unit. He came to
Boeing from McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Falls, but Dow Up 25 Points
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks sank on Monday after a bearish report on Cisco
Systems rekindled doubts on the value of technology shares. The
Nasdaq composite index dropped 147.44 points, or 3.9 percent, to
3,669.38. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 25.77 points, or
0.2 percent, to 10,603.63, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index dropped 8.46 points, or 0.6 percent, to 1,424.17.
</P>
<P>
   Painting on Ebay Creates a Frenzy
</P>
<P>
   Bidding for a painting on eBay, the online auction site, soared
from a quarter to $135,805. A six-figure sale would not only be one
of the highest prices paid online for art, it would also be a
powerful testimony to the ability of the Internet to ignite a sales
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge Rules Against Napster
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has decided not to dismiss a lawsuit filed by
the recording industry against Napster, which offers a service that
allows consumers to share and trade music over the Internet. The
judge also suggested that Napster might face an uphill battle as
the case proceeded to trial.
</P>
<P>
   First Analysis of Genome Project
</P>
<P>
   The biotechnology company DoubleTwist said it had identified as
many as 105,000 human genes by performing the first comprehensive
computer analysis of the publicly available data from the Human
Genome Project.
</P>
<P>
   NTT Communications to Buy Verio
</P>
<P>
   NTT Communications of Japan agreed to buy Verio, a Web site
manager, for $5.5 billion in cash. The move is part of an
aggressive new strategy by the Nippon Telegraph and Telephone unit,
to expand globally. NTT Communications currently holds a 10 percent
stake in Verio. Shares of Verio jumped 62 percent, up $22.375, to
$58.3125.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth to Add Digital Offerings
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth intends to announce on Tuesday that it has signed a
long-term contract to purchase satellite services from General
Electric so that it can offer digital television service throughout
the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford to Offer Medical Data
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University is establishing a company to provide medical
information online to doctors, while they meet with patients.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Bank Is Sold at Auction
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish bank Banco Santander Central Hispano won a
government auction for Mexico's oldest and third-largest bank,
Grupo Financiero Serfin, trumping a rival bid from the
British-based HSBC Holdings.
</P>
</TEXT>
