r f BC-SMALL-BUSINESS2NDTAKE     05-08 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BUSINESS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC LEADERS WORK TO COUNTER FALL IN SMALL-BUSINESS RANKING 
</HEADLINE>
 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JOYCE SMITH KNIGHT-RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Virtually everybody is employed that can be
employed,'' said Brad Douglas, acting regional administrator for
the SBA in Kansas City. ``Small businesses are looking at creative
ways to address the problem. If they want to keep people, they have
to pay more than minimum wage.''
</P>
<P>
   GeoAccess Inc., an Overland Park-based Internet and software
solutions provider for the managed health care industry, provides
free lunches and snacks to its 225 employees. Other companies let
employees bring their dogs to work or provide an area for employee
naps.
</P>
<P>
   More companies also will need information technology workers to
manage and constantly innovate systems, said Susan Catts, president
of Silicon Prairie Technology Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure we have a critical mass of people here to
support the companies that are choosing to be in this region,''
Catts said. ``Particularly small companies that get founded here,
you want to hold on to them. You don't want to put them in a
situation where they grow only so much, and then they have to leave
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brass Ross Vending of Kansas City grew steadily for six years,
but revenue has been stagnant the past three. John Ross, owner of
the vending company, blames the minority ``glass ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an African-American male who has been in business for
nine years, and I've consistently seen the rules change when we are
on the edge of a lucrative contract,'' Ross said. ``When we get
close to big money, a lot of people don't want to see us advance.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Marie Young, executive director of the Black Chamber of
Commerce of Greater Kansas City, said several established
minority-owned businesses had closed in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only grow so far; that's what's happening to these 15-
to 20-year-old companies,'' Young said. ``There's such a tight,
closed circle, we're not able to get east of Troost, so to speak.
We spend so much of our time just trying to fight to get in the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks and other service providers often develop programs aimed
at the minority community but rarely ask minorities what they need,
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were sick and you were the doctor, could you help me
without asking me what my problems are? That does not happen,''
Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Paul Chaurand, executive director of the Hispanic Economic
Development Corp., said service providers needed to understand the
cultural differences involved when working with Hispanics. Recent
immigrants are often distrustful of banks and prefer to borrow from
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they need to build credit with a lender,'' Chaurand said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Luciani of the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce said
the chamber worked with many area minority organizations to ensure
that its programs are meeting their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a great effort so we don't exclude people,'' said
Luciani, senior vice president for economic growth and development
at the chamber. ``We are geographically sensitive, racially
sensitive and ethnically sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber's new Minority Business Alliance Partnership will
link mentors with small-business owners to help the operations
continue to grow through subcontractors, prime contracts and better
access to capital. Other programs are open to all entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   But while resources are important, Young said, minorities still
need the opportunity to use what they've learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I was a college student with numerous degrees and I
can't get a job, I'm not working, I'm not able to do the things
I've been trained to do,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City can point to a diverse group of businesses that have
experienced rapid growth _ Three Dog Bakery, LaserCycle, Peripheral
Vision InfoSystems, Birch Telecom and GeoAccess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're attracting attention, and that's a good thing for
entrepreneurs,'' Reisler said. ``So by most of the tests that we
can see, the environment continues to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Cognetics said Kansas City lost points in its annual rankings
because of its industrial flavor _ an image that may fade as the
city gears up for a knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique point in time for the Kansas City region,''
Kayne said. ``We're going to be a powerful biotech community in the
next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stowers Institute can help raise Kansas City's reputation as
a research center, and a task force of area businesspeople is
looking at ways to expand research and support commercial
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Cognetics also based its results on employee and sales growth.
But Blades said researchers needed to consider micro and home-based
businesses of five employees or fewer. Some of those ``lifestyle
companies'' may not want to grow any larger and Kansas City has the
support systems, such as the Home Business Connection, to help them
succeed at that level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is a place where people come together and give of
themselves to help each other. People gave to me and helped me when
there was nothing I could give back to them,'' Blades said of her
public relations and marketing company, Blades &AMP; Associates. ``Now
I'm trying to give back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0517 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SENIORAOL-AZR &LR;      05-08 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORAOL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX SENIORS MOST WIRED IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MAUREEN WEST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Senior citizens in Phoenix are surfing the Net more
than their peers anywhere else in the country, according to America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix-area seniors - those 55 and older - stay online an
average of 22 hours a week, compared with an average of 18 hours
for seniors in other high-use cities. The national average for all
ages is 7 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's seniors may be more computer savvy because of many
local computer classes and the computer centers at many retirement
communities. Education and income also are higher for seniors here,
Vincent C. Huffman of Scottsdale Community College said.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors are the fastest-growing group of Internet users, making
up 13 percent of the online population, AOL's Kathie Lentz said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 3,200 seniors surveyed nationwide said they go
online to e-mail children, grandchildren and friends. Others use it
to do research, check financial investments, find medical news or
search travel options.
</P>
<P>
   Like Phoenix's Bettie Brenner, 74, many seniors are finding that
computers keep them active and involved.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner is a birder and follows the migration patterns on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens that I can't go on a birding trip, then I can go
online,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the top 10 are Boston; Tampa; Los Angeles; Orlando;
West Palm Beach, Fla.; Ft. Myers, Fla.; Cleveland; San Francisco
area; and New York City. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-08-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000508.0518 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-08 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9690 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-SENIORAOL-AZR &LR;      05-08 0262
